Plot: Nick is a struggling dentist in Canada. A new neighbor moves in, and he discovers that it is Jimmy "The Tulip" Teduski. His wife convinces him to go to Chicago and inform the mob boss who wants Jimmy dead.
Title: The Whole Nine Yards
Actors: Bruce Willis, Matthew Perry, Rosanna Arquette, Michael Clarke Duncan
tomatoConsensus: Despite a charming cast, The Whole Nine Yards could only tickle half of the critics' funny bones. The other half thought it an underwelming, depressing sitcom.

Plot: Three egotistical swingers, who think they're God's gift to women, end up having their friendships tested when all three of them pick up and start dating the same woman.
Title: Whipped
Actors: Amanda Peet, Brian Van Holt, Jonathan Abrahams, Zorie Barber
tomatoConsensus: The sex jokes in Whipped are tiresomely vulgar and unfunny. Critics also condemn the movie as cynical and mean-spirited, with no likable characters.

Plot: An orphaned dinosaur raised by lemurs joins an arduous trek to a sancturary after a meteorite shower destroys his family home.
Title: Dinosaur
Writer: Thom Enriquez (story), John Harrison (story), Robert Nelson Jacobs (story), Ralph Zondag (story), John Harrison (screenplay), Robert Nelson Jacobs (screenplay), Walon Green (based on an earlier screenplay by), Gregory Gunter (creative development), Shirley Pierce (screenplay), Jonathan Roberts (additional story material), Rhett Reese (additional story material), Tamara Lusher (additional story)
Actors: D.B. Sweeney, Alfre Woodard, Ossie Davis, Max Casella
tomatoConsensus: While Dinosaur's plot is generic and dull, its stunning computer animation and detailed backgrounds are enough to make it worth a look.

Plot: In order to protect a beautiful woman and her son from a robber, a male FBI agent disguises himself as a large grandmother.
Title: Big Momma's House
Writer: Darryl Quarles (story), Darryl Quarles (screenplay), Don Rhymer (screenplay)
Actors: Martin Lawrence, Nia Long, Paul Giamatti, Jascha Washington
tomatoConsensus: Big Momma's House is funny in some parts, but it is essentially a one-joke movie.

Plot: A retired master car thief must come back to the industry and steal 50 cars with his crew in one night to save his brother's life.
Title: Gone in Sixty Seconds
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Giovanni Ribisi, Angelina Jolie, T.J. Cross
tomatoConsensus: Even though Oscar-bearers Nicolas Cage, Angelina Jolie, and Robert Duval came aboard for this project, the quality of Gone in 60 Seconds is disappointingly low. The plot line is nonsensical, and even the promised car-chase scenes are boring.

Plot: New York City police detective John Shaft (nephew of the original 1970s detective) goes on a personal mission to make sure the son of a real estate tycoon is brought to justice after a racially-motivated murder.
Title: Shaft
Writer: Ernest Tidyman (novel), John Singleton (story), Shane Salerno (story), Richard Price (screenplay), John Singleton (screenplay), Shane Salerno (screenplay)
Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Vanessa Williams, Jeffrey Wright, Christian Bale
tomatoConsensus: With a charismatic lead, this new Shaft knows how to push the right buttons.

Plot: When a bird "flies" into a chicken farm, the fellow chickens see him as an opportunity to escape their evil owners.
Title: Chicken Run
Writer: Peter Lord (original story), Nick Park (original story), Karey Kirkpatrick (screenplay), Mark Burton (additional dialogue), John O'Farrell (additional dialogue)
Actors: Phil Daniels, Lynn Ferguson, Mel Gibson, Tony Haygarth
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 23 wins & 26 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Chicken Run has all the charm of Nick Park's Wallace & Gromit, and something for everybody. The voice acting is fabulous, the slapstick is brilliant, and the action sequences are spectacular.

Plot: A nice-guy cop with dissociative identity disorder must protect a woman on the run from a corrupt ex-boyfriend and his associates.
Title: Me, Myself & Irene
Writer: Peter Farrelly, Mike Cerrone, Bobby Farrelly
Actors: Jim Carrey, Renée Zellweger, Anthony Anderson, Mongo Brownlee
tomatoConsensus: While Jim Carrey's comedic skills earn some laughs, Me, Myself and Irene sports a tired, unsatisfying plot.

Plot: Peaceful farmer Benjamin Martin is driven to lead the Colonial Militia during the American Revolution when a sadistic British officer murders his son.
Title: The Patriot
Actors: Mel Gibson, Heath Ledger, Joely Richardson, Jason Isaacs
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 8 wins & 18 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Patriot can be entertaining to watch, but it relies too much on formula and melodrama.

Plot: When enemies Boris, Natasha and Fearless leader escape into the real world with a nefarious scheme, Rocky & Bullwinkle do the same and team up with a young F.B.I. agent to stop the trio.
Title: The Adventures of Rocky & Bullwinkle
Actors: Rene Russo, Jason Alexander, Piper Perabo, Randy Quaid
tomatoConsensus: Though the film stays true to the nature of the original cartoon, the script is disappointing and not funny.

Plot: A man marries an heiress for her money even though he is actually in love with her friend.
Title: The Golden Bowl
Actors: Kate Beckinsale, James Fox, Anjelica Huston, Nick Nolte
tomatoConsensus: Coming from the Merchant-Ivory team, The Golden Bowl is visually stunning, but the filmmakers have difficulty in transporting the characterizations of the Henry James novel to the screen.

Plot: An unhappy and disliked image consultant gets a second shot at life when an eight year old version of himself mysteriously appears.
Title: The Kid
Actors: Bruce Willis, Spencer Breslin, Emily Mortimer, Lily Tomlin
tomatoConsensus: Critics find The Kid to be too sweet and the movie's message to be annoyingly simplistic.

Plot: Two mutants come to a private academy for their kind whose resident superhero team must oppose a terrorist organization with similar powers.
Title: X-Men
Writer: Tom DeSanto (story), Bryan Singer (story), David Hayter (screenplay)
Actors: Hugh Jackman, Patrick Stewart, Ian McKellen, Famke Janssen
tomatoConsensus: Faithful to the comics and filled with action, X-Men brings a crowded slate of classic Marvel characters to the screen with a talented ensemble cast and surprisingly sharp narrative focus.

Plot: The wife of a university research scientist believes that her lakeside Vermont home is haunted by a ghost - or that she is losing her mind.
Title: What Lies Beneath
Writer: Clark Gregg (screenplay), Sarah Kernochan (story), Clark Gregg (story)
Actors: Michelle Pfeiffer, Katharine Towne, Miranda Otto, James Remar
tomatoConsensus: Robert Zemeckis is unable to salvage an uncompelling and unoriginal film.

Plot: Mr. Conductor's supply of magic gold dust, which allows him to travel between Shining Time and Thomas's island, is critically low. Unfortunately, he doesn't know how to get more. Meanwhile,...
Title: Thomas and the Magic Railroad
Actors: Alec Baldwin, Cody McMains, Russell Means, Peter Fonda
tomatoConsensus: Kids these days demand cutting edge special effects or at least a clever plot with cute charectors. This movie has neither, having lost in its Americanization what the British original did so right.

Plot: Scientist Sherman Klump's inventions, his upcoming marriage to his pretty colleague Denise Gaines and his reputation are threatened by his evil clone Buddy Love.
Title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
Writer: Jerry Lewis (characters), Steve Oedekerk (story), Barry W. Blaustein (story), David Sheffield (story), Barry W. Blaustein (screenplay), David Sheffield (screenplay), Paul Weitz (screenplay), Chris Weitz (screenplay)
Actors: Eddie Murphy, Janet Jackson, Larry Miller, John Ales
tomatoConsensus: While Eddie Murphy is still hilarious as the entire Klump family, the movie falls apart because of uneven pacing, a poor script, and skits that rely on being gross rather than funny.

Plot: Scientists discover how to make people invisible, but their test subject becomes an insane killer who stalks them.
Title: Hollow Man
Writer: Gary Scott Thompson (story), Andrew W. Marlowe (story), Andrew W. Marlowe (screenplay)
Actors: Elisabeth Shue, Kevin Bacon, Josh Brolin, Kim Dickens
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 9 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despite awesome special effects, Hollow Man falls short of other films directed by Paul Verhoeven. This flick over time degenerates into a typical horror film.

Plot: A small-town English widow, facing financial troubles after her husband's suicide, turns to agriculture of an illegal kind.
Title: Saving Grace
Writer: Mark Crowdy (story), Craig Ferguson (screenplay), Mark Crowdy (screenplay)
Actors: Brenda Blethyn, Craig Ferguson, Martin Clunes, Tchéky Karyo
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 8 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The plot and basis for jokes are slight, but Saving Grace is indeed saved by some charming performances, most notably Brenda Blethyn's.

Plot: Omens and concepts of good vs. evil have no place in Maggie O'Connor's well-ordered, practical universe. Her life revolves around her job as a nurse at a busy New York hospital, until one ...
Title: Bless the Child
Writer: Cathy Cash Spellman (novel), Thomas Rickman (screenplay), Clifford Green (screenplay), Ellen Green (screenplay)
Actors: Kim Basinger, Jimmy Smits, Holliston Coleman, Rufus Sewell
tomatoConsensus: Bless the Child squanders its talented cast on a plot that's more likely to inspire unintentional laughs than shivers.

Title: The Replacements
Actors: Keanu Reeves, Gene Hackman, Brooke Langton, Orlando Jones
tomatoConsensus: The cliched characters and obvious outcome make all the fun and excitement amount to nothing.

Plot: A concert film featuring four major African American stand up comedians.
Title: The Original Kings of Comedy
Writer: Cedric the Entertainer, Steve Harvey, D.L. Hughley, Bernie Mac
Actors: Steve Harvey, D.L. Hughley, Cedric the Entertainer, Bernie Mac
tomatoConsensus: If you want lots of laughs and don't mind some profanity, The Original Kings of Comedy can deliver.

Plot: Shaw is an operative for the United Nations' covert dirty-tricks squad, using espionage and quasi-ethical tactics to secure peace and cooperation. When a shipping container full of dead ...
Title: The Art of War
Writer: Wayne Beach (story), Wayne Beach (screenplay), Simon Barry (screenplay)
Actors: Wesley Snipes, Anne Archer, Maury Chaykin, Marie Matiko
tomatoConsensus: Excessively noisy and overly reliant on genre clichés, The Art of War wastes its star's charisma on a ridiculous, convoluted plot and poorly edited action sequences.

Plot: A champion high school cheerleading squad discovers its previous captain stole all their best routines from an inner-city school and must scramble to compete at this year's championships.
Title: Bring It On
Actors: Kirsten Dunst, Eliza Dushku, Jesse Bradford, Gabrielle Union
tomatoConsensus: Despite the formulaic, fluffy storyline, this movie is surprisingly fun to watch, mostly due to its high energy and how it humorously spoofs cheerleading instead of taking itself too seriously.

Plot: Four retired mobsters plan one last crime to save their retirement home.
Title: The Crew
Actors: Richard Dreyfuss, Burt Reynolds, Dan Hedaya, Seymour Cassel
tomatoConsensus: Though the four actors are good together, the jokes are stale and not funny.

Plot: Trying to bootstrap his way out of Brooklyn's mean streets is Diamond, a rap musician. With his long-time pal Gage acting as his manager, he's trying to lay down a demo tape with cut-rate ...
Title: Turn It Up
Writer: Ray 'Cory' Daniels (story), Chris Hudson (story), Kelly Hilaire (story), Robert Adetuyi (screenplay)
Actors: Pras Michel, Ja Rule, Jason Statham, Vondie Curtis-Hall
tomatoConsensus: Reviewers say Turn It Up has a derivative feel, running through too many urban movie cliches.

Plot: David Allen Griffin is a cool killer- time and time again, he chooses a female victim, studies her for weeks till he knows her routine to the smallest detail, makes meticulous preparations ...
Title: The Watcher
Writer: Darcy Meyers (story), David Elliot (story), David Elliot (screenplay), Clay Ayers (screenplay)
Actors: James Spader, Marisa Tomei, Keanu Reeves, Ernie Hudson
tomatoConsensus: The Watcher has Keanu Reeves cast against type, but the movie is short on thrills, suspense, and believability.

Plot: Two criminal drifters without sympathy get more than they bargained for after kidnapping and holding for ransom the surrogate mother of a powerful and shady man.
Title: The Way of the Gun
Actors: Ryan Phillippe, Benicio Del Toro, Juliette Lewis, Taye Diggs
tomatoConsensus: The Way of the Gun has some good parts, but overall, the movie is derivative, sloppy, and sluggish.

Plot: A high-school boy is given the chance to write a story for Rolling Stone Magazine about an up-and-coming rock band as he accompanies it on their concert tour.
Title: Almost Famous
Actors: Billy Crudup, Frances McDormand, Kate Hudson, Jason Lee
tomatoConsensus: Almost Famous, with its great ensemble performances and story, is a well-crafted, warm-hearted movie that successfully draws you into its era.

Plot: An ex-con is used by police to lure a criminal out of hiding.
Title: Bait
Writer: Andrew Scheinman, Adam Scheinman, Tony Gilroy
Actors: Jamie Foxx, David Morse, Robert Pastorelli, Doug Hutchison
tomatoConsensus: Even though Jamie Foxx shines in Bait, the movie suffers from music video roots and a formulaic script that strains credibility.

Plot: A professional karaoke hustler reconnects with his daughter and a bored suburban businessman turns outlaw karaoke singer, among other plotlines.
Title: Duets
Actors: Lochlyn Munro, Carol Alexander, Michael Rogers, Huey Lewis
tomatoConsensus: Duets suffers from sloppy direction and stretches credibility. Also, the characters are uninteresting and it's hard to care about what happens to them.

Plot: A film school is the center of a fresh spate of killings based on urban legends.
Title: Urban Legends: Final Cut
Writer: Silvio Horta (characters), Paul Harris Boardman, Scott Derrickson
Actors: Jennifer Morrison, Matthew Davis, Hart Bochner, Loretta Devine
tomatoConsensus: This teen horror movie brings nothing new to an already exhausted genre. And it's bad. Really bad.

Plot: Brazilian chef Isabella Oliveira moves to San Francisco when her husband, frustrated by her motion sickness, cheats on her.
Title: Woman on Top
Actors: Penélope Cruz, Murilo Benício, Harold Perrineau, Mark Feuerstein
tomatoConsensus: Despite Penelope Cruz's beauty and charm, the movie is too tepid to be a romance and too silly to be believable. And the movie is too eager to please with an ending that seems more like a cop out.

Plot: An east European girl goes to America with her young son, expecting it to be like a Hollywood film.
Title: Dancer in the Dark
Country: Denmark, Spain, Germany, Netherlands, Italy, USA, UK, France, Sweden, Finland, Iceland, Norway
Actors: Björk, Catherine Deneuve, David Morse, Peter Stormare
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 33 wins & 45 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Dancer in Dark can be grim, dull, and difficult to watch, but even so, it has a powerful and moving performance from Bjork and is something quite new and visionary.

Plot: Diana, without her father knowing it, trains as a boxer and achieves impressive success, blazing new trails for female boxers.
Title: Girlfight
Actors: Michelle Rodriguez, Jaime Tirelli, Paul Calderon, Santiago Douglas
tomatoConsensus: Michelle Rodriguez gives a compelling performance, despite lack of a boxing background; Karyn Kusama packs a punch with this directorial debut.

Plot: The true story of a newly appointed African-American coach and his high school team on their first season as a racially integrated unit.
Title: Remember the Titans
Actors: Denzel Washington, Will Patton, Wood Harris, Ryan Hurst
tomatoConsensus: An inspirational crowd-pleaser with a healthy dose of social commentary, Remember the Titans may be predictable, but it's also well-crafted and features terrific performances.

Plot: A frustrated African-American TV writer proposes a blackface minstrel show in protest, but to his chagrin it becomes a hit.
Title: Bamboozled
Actors: Damon Wayans, Savion Glover, Jada Pinkett Smith, Tommy Davidson
tomatoConsensus: Bamboozled is too heavy-handed in its satire and comes across as more messy and overwrought than biting.

Plot: Years ago, Jack Carter left his Seattle home to become a Las Vegas mob casino financial enforcer. He returns for the funeral of his brother Richard 'Richie' after a car crash during a storm...
Title: Get Carter
Actors: Sylvester Stallone, Miranda Richardson, Rachael Leigh Cook, Rhona Mitra
tomatoConsensus: A remake that doesn't approach the standard of the original, Get Carter will likely leave viewers confused and unsatisfied. Also, reviews are mixed concerning Stallone's acting.

Plot: Male nurse Greg Focker meets his girlfriend's parents before proposing, but her suspicious father is every date's worst nightmare.
Title: Meet the Parents
Writer: Greg Glienna, Mary Ruth Clarke, Greg Glienna (story), Mary Ruth Clarke (story), Jim Herzfeld (screenplay), John Hamburg (screenplay)
Actors: Robert De Niro, Ben Stiller, Teri Polo, Blythe Danner
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 14 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despite sometimes sitcom-like execution, Meet the Parents is a hilarious look at familial relationships that works mostly because the chemistry between its two leads is so effective.

Plot: The drug-induced utopias of four Coney Island people are shattered when their addictions run deep.
Title: Requiem for a Dream
Writer: Hubert Selby Jr. (based on the book by), Hubert Selby Jr. (screenplay), Darren Aronofsky (screenplay)
Actors: Ellen Burstyn, Jared Leto, Jennifer Connelly, Marlon Wayans
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 32 wins & 61 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though the movie may be too intense for some to stomach, the wonderful performances and the bleak imagery are hard to forget.

Plot: Senator Laine Hanson is a contender for US Vice President, but information and disinformation about her past surfaces that threatens to de-rail her confirmation.
Title: The Contender
Actors: Gary Oldman, Joan Allen, Jeff Bridges, Christian Slater
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 20 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Critics say this political thriller is solidly made, with top-notch performances, screenplay, and direction for about two third of the film. Unfortunately, the ending almost tank the whole movie.

Plot: Dr. Sullivan Travis "Dr. T." is a wealthy Dallas gynecologist for some of the wealthiest women in Texas who finds his idealist life beginning to fall apart starting when his wife, Kate, ...
Title: Dr. T & the Women
Actors: Richard Gere, Helen Hunt, Farrah Fawcett, Laura Dern
tomatoConsensus: In terms of quality, Dr. T and the Women is one of Altman's good-but-not-great films. In typical Altman style, it features some great ensemble acting, including a wonderful performance by Richard Gere.

Plot: The Saturday Night Live character gets a big screen treatment.
Title: The Ladies Man
Writer: Tim Meadows, Dennis McNicholas, Andrew Steele
Actors: Tim Meadows, Karyn Parsons, Billy Dee Williams, John Witherspoon
tomatoConsensus: The Ladies Man joins the growing list of mediocre movies based on SNL skits. It just doesn't have enough material to last the length of the movie.

Title: Pay It Forward
Actors: Kevin Spacey, Helen Hunt, Haley Joel Osment, Jay Mohr
tomatoConsensus: Pay It Forward has strong performances from Spacey, Hunt, and Osment, but the movie itself is too emotionally manipulative and the ending is bad.

Plot: A television weatherman scams a local lottery.
Title: Lucky Numbers
Actors: John Travolta, Lisa Kudrow, Tim Roth, Ed O'Neill
tomatoConsensus: Nora Ephron's attempt at dark comedy is an uneven product, both in terms of the direction and the acting. The characters are unlikable to the point where you don't care what happens to them, and Ephron condescends to the material.

Plot: Three women, detectives with a mysterious boss, retrieve stolen voice-ID software, using martial arts, tech skills, and sex appeal.
Title: Charlie's Angels
Writer: Ryan Rowe, Ed Solomon, John August, Ivan Goff (TV series), Ben Roberts (TV series)
Actors: Cameron Diaz, Drew Barrymore, Lucy Liu, Bill Murray
tomatoConsensus: Mixing tongue-in-cheek cheesecake with glossy action set pieces, Charlie's Angels is slick and resonably fun despite its lack of originality.

Plot: A down-and-out golfer attempts to recover his game and his life with help from a mystical caddy.
Title: The Legend of Bagger Vance
Actors: Will Smith, Matt Damon, Charlize Theron, Bruce McGill
tomatoConsensus: Despite the talent involved in The Legend of Bagger Vance, performances are hindered by an inadequate screenplay full of flat characters and bad dialogue. Also, not much happens, and some critics are offended by how the film glosses over issues of racism.

Plot: After two of the devil's three sons escape Hell to wreak havoc on Earth, the devil must send his third son, the mild-mannered Nicky, to bring them back before it's too late.
Title: Little Nicky
Writer: Tim Herlihy, Adam Sandler, Steven Brill
Actors: Adam Sandler, Patricia Arquette, Harvey Keitel, Rhys Ifans
tomatoConsensus: Despite the presence of a large, talented cast, the jokes in Little Nicky are dumb, tasteless, and not that funny, and Adam Sandler's character is grating to watch.

Plot: In LA's Fairfax district, where ethnic groups abound, four households celebrate Thanksgiving amidst family tensions. In the Nguyen family, the children's acculturation and immigrant parents...
Title: What's Cooking?
Actors: Mercedes Ruehl, Victor Rivers, Douglas Spain, Maria Carmen
tomatoConsensus: What's Cooking? is well-acted, but the scenes sometimes sink into melodrama as characters scream at each other, and the movie as a whole is too lightweight and forgettable.

Plot: Futuristic action about a man who meets a clone of himself and stumbles into a grand conspiracy about clones taking over the world.
Title: The 6th Day
Actors: Arnold Schwarzenegger, Michael Rapaport, Tony Goldwyn, Michael Rooker
tomatoConsensus: This offering from Arnold Schwarzenegger contains an intriguing, disturbing premise, but the film's execution is too routine and formulaic to make good use of it.

Plot: On the outskirts of Whoville, there lives a green, revenge-seeking Grinch who plans on ruining the Christmas holiday for all of the citizens of the town.
Title: How the Grinch Stole Christmas
Writer: Dr. Seuss (book), Jeffrey Price (screenplay), Peter S. Seaman (screenplay)
Actors: Jim Carrey, Taylor Momsen, Kelley, Jeffrey Tambor
tomatoConsensus: Jim Carrey shines as the Grinch. Unfortunately, it's not enough to save this movie. You'd be better off watching the TV cartoon.

Plot: Cruella DeVil gets out of prison and goes after them darned puppies once more.
Title: 102 Dalmatians
Writer: Dodie Smith (novel), Kristen Buckley (story), Brian Regan (story), Kristen Buckley (screenplay), Brian Regan (screenplay), Bob Tzudiker (screenplay), Noni White (screenplay)
Actors: Glenn Close, Gérard Depardieu, Ioan Gruffudd, Alice Evans
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This sequel to the live-action 101 Dalmatians is simply more of the same. Critics say it also drags in parts, potentially boring children, and that it's too violent for a G-rated movie.

Plot: In a Napoleonic era insane asylum, an inmate, the irrepressible Marquis De Sade, fights a battle of wills against a tyrannically prudish doctor.
Title: Quills
Actors: Geoffrey Rush, Kate Winslet, Joaquin Phoenix, Michael Caine
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 18 wins & 41 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though hard to watch, this film's disturbing exploration of freedom of expression is both seductive and thought-provoking.

Plot: Profion, a tyrant, attempts to overthrow a peaceful kingdom ruled by a tough empress.
Title: Dungeons & Dragons
Actors: Jeremy Irons, Bruce Payne, Justin Whalin, Marlon Wayans
tomatoConsensus: Critics say this movie has a cheap look and is badly directed. Despite the presence of talented actors, the performances are really bad, and additionally, some people are offended at Marlon Wayans' character, calling it a racist throwback to black stereotypes.

Plot: Alice hires a professional negotiator to obtain the release of her engineer husband, who has been kidnapped by anti-government guerrillas in South America.
Title: Proof of Life
Writer: Tony Gilroy, William Prochnau (article), Thomas Hargrove (book)
Actors: Meg Ryan, Russell Crowe, David Morse, Pamela Reed
tomatoConsensus: Despite its promising premise and superstar cast, Proof of Life is just a routine thriller that doesn't offer anything new.

Plot: A climber must rescue his sister on top of K2, one of the world's biggest mountains.
Title: Vertical Limit
Writer: Robert King (story), Robert King (screenplay), Terry Hayes (screenplay)
Actors: Chris O'Donnell, Robin Tunney, Stuart Wilson, Augie Davis
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The plot in Vertical Limit is ludicrously contrived and cliched. Meanwhile, the action sequences are so over-the-top and piled one on top of another, they lessen the impact on the viewer.

Plot: Unscrupulous boxing promoters, violent bookmakers, a Russian gangster, incompetent amateur robbers, and supposedly Jewish jewelers fight to track down a priceless stolen diamond.
Title: Snatch
Actors: Benicio Del Toro, Dennis Farina, Vinnie Jones, Brad Pitt
tomatoConsensus: Though perhaps a case of style over substance, Guy Ritchie's second crime caper is full of snappy dialogue, dark comedy, and interesting characters.

Plot: Two potheads wake up after a night of partying and cannot remember where they parked their car.
Title: Dude, Where's My Car?
Actors: Ashton Kutcher, Seann William Scott, Jennifer Garner, Marla Sokoloff
tomatoConsensus: The movie isn't funny, the plot is too thin, and the production values feel more like a TV sitcom than a movie.

Plot: Emperor Kuzco is turned into a llama by his ex-administrator Yzma, and must now regain his throne with the help of Pacha, the gentle llama herder.
Title: The Emperor's New Groove
Writer: Chris Williams (story by), Mark Dindal (story by), David Reynolds (screenplay), Roger Allers (based on an original story by), Matthew Jacobs (based on an original story by), Stephen J. Anderson (additional story material), Don Hall (additional story material), John Norton (additional story material), Doug Frankel (additional story), Mark Kennedy (additional story), Mark Walton (additional story)
Actors: David Spade, John Goodman, Eartha Kitt, Patrick Warburton
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 27 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Emperor's New Groove isn't the most ambitious animated film, but its brisk pace, fresh characters, and big laughs make for a great time for the whole family.

Title: Pollock
Writer: Steven Naifeh (book), Gregory White Smith (book), Barbara Turner (screenplay), Susan Emshwiller (screenplay)
Actors: Ed Harris, Robert Knott, Molly Regan, Marcia Gay Harden
tomatoConsensus: Though Pollock does not really allow audiences a glimpse of the painter as a person, it does powerfully depict the creative process. Harris throws himself into the role and turns in a compelling performance.

Plot: A young writing prodigy finds a mentor in a reclusive author.
Title: Finding Forrester
Actors: Sean Connery, Rob Brown, F. Murray Abraham, Anna Paquin
tomatoConsensus: Despite the predictability of its plot and its similarity to Good Will Hunting, Finding Forrester has an honest, solid feel to it and good rapport between Connery and Brown.

Plot: A woman with extrasensory perception is asked to help find a young woman who has disappeared.
Title: The Gift
Actors: Cate Blanchett, Giovanni Ribisi, Keanu Reeves, Katie Holmes
tomatoConsensus: With a reported budget of around 10 million, The Gift is obviously a labor of love for those involved. Unfortunately, the A-list cast can't prevent the movie from becoming a by-the-numbers whodunit with an ending that's all but unsatisfactory.

Plot: Episodic look at the life of Cuban poet and novelist, Reinaldo Arenas (1943-1990), from his childhood in Oriente province to his death in New York City. He joins Castro's rebels. By 1964, ...
Title: Before Night Falls
Writer: Cunningham O'Keefe, Lázaro Gómez Carriles, Julian Schnabel, Reynaldo Arenas (memoir "Before Night Falls"), Jana Bokova (documentary "Havana")
Actors: Olatz López Garmendia, Giovanni Florido, Loló Navarro, Batan Silva
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 15 wins & 20 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: An impressionistic, fragmented look at Reinaldo Arenas, Before Night Falls' imagery manages to evoke a sense of the writer's artistry, and Bardem's strong performance holds the film together. Finally, a biopic done well.

Plot: In the deep south during the 1930s, three escaped convicts search for hidden treasure while a relentless lawman pursues them.
Title: O Brother, Where Art Thou?
Writer: Homer (epic poem "The Odyssey"), Ethan Coen, Joel Coen
Actors: George Clooney, John Turturro, Tim Blake Nelson, John Goodman
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 7 wins & 35 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though not as good as Coen brothers' classics such as Blood Simple, the delightfully loopy O Brother, Where Art Thou? is still a lot of fun.

Plot: A movie crew invades a small town whose residents are all too ready to give up their values for showbiz glitz.
Title: State and Main
Actors: Michael Higgins, Michael Bradshaw, Morris Lamore, Allen Soule
tomatoConsensus: State and Main offers plenty of wit and laughs in its lampoons of the movie industry.

Plot: Two Texas cowboys head to Mexico in search of work, but soon find themselves in trouble with the law after one of them falls in love with a wealthy rancher's daughter.
Title: All the Pretty Horses
Actors: Matt Damon, Henry Thomas, Penélope Cruz, Angelina Torres
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 13 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This adaptation of Cormac McCarthy's novel comes off as rather flat and uninvolving. Scenes feel rushed and done in shorthand, and the romance between Damon and Cruz has no sparks.

Plot: A conservative judge is appointed by the President to spearhead America's escalating war against drugs, only to discover that his teenage daughter is a crack addict. Two DEA agents protect an informant. A jailed drug baron's wife attempts to carry on the family business.
Title: Traffic
Actors: Benicio Del Toro, Jacob Vargas, Andrew Chavez, Michael Saucedo
tomatoConsensus: Soderbergh successfully pulls off the highly ambitious Traffic, a movie with three different stories and a very large cast. The issues of ethics are gray rather than black-and-white, with no clear-cut good guys. Terrific acting all around.

Plot: A man juggles searching for his wife's murderer and keeping his short-term memory loss from being an obstacle.
Title: Memento
Writer: Christopher Nolan (screenplay), Jonathan Nolan (short story "Memento Mori")
Actors: Guy Pearce, Carrie-Anne Moss, Joe Pantoliano, Mark Boone Junior
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 54 wins & 55 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Christopher Nolan skillfully guides the audience through Memento's fractured narrative, seeping his film in existential dread.

Plot: The Pokemon master Ash must rescue his mother from the encasement of a crystal tower.
Title: #DUPE#
Writer: Norman J. Grossfeld (english version), Michael Haigney (english version), Takeshi Shudo
Actors: Rica Matsumoto, Veronica Taylor, Rachael Lillis, Ikue Ôtani
tomatoConsensus: Critics say that the third Pokemon movie has a better plot than its two predecessors. This is not enough, however, to recommend it to those not already fans of the franchise.

Plot: Brutal gangster Don Logan recruits "retired" safecracker Gal for one last job, but it goes badly for both of them.
Title: Sexy Beast
Actors: Ray Winstone, Ben Kingsley, Ian McShane, Amanda Redman
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 21 wins & 20 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Sexy Beast rises above other movies in the British gangster genre due to its performances -- particularly an electrifying one by Ben Kingsley -- and the script's attention to character development.

Plot: A retelling of Sir Ernest Shackleton 's ill-fated expedition to Antarctica in 1914-1916, featuring new footage of the actual locations and interviews with surviving relatives of key ...
Title: The Endurance
Writer: Caroline Alexander (book), Caroline Alexander, Joseph Dorman
Actors: Liam Neeson, Julian Ayer, John Blackborow, David Cale
tomatoConsensus: The Endurance presents exciting footage of an amazing real-life story of survival.

Plot: Several lonely hearts in a semi-provincial suburb of a town in Denmark use a beginner's course in Italian as the platform to meet the romance of their lives.
Title: Italian for Beginners
Actors: Anders W. Berthelsen, Anette Støvelbæk, Ann Eleonora Jørgensen, Peter Gantzler
tomatoConsensus: Unlike many romantic comedies, the charming Italian for Beginners feels natural and genuinely heart-warming.

Plot: When a Newsweek photojournalist disappears in war-torn Yugoslavia, his wife travels to Europe to find him.
Title: Harrison's Flowers
Writer: Isabel Ellsen (book), Élie Chouraqui (screenplay), Didier Le Pêcheur (screenplay), Isabel Ellsen (screenplay), Michael Katims (screenplay)
Actors: Andie MacDowell, Elias Koteas, Brendan Gleeson, Adrien Brody
tomatoConsensus: Though it presents the war in shockingly gritty, realistic terms, Harrison's Flowers uses such scenes as background for a trite love story.

Plot: Coming-of-age story about a 15-year-old boy, Oscar, who falls in love with his stepmother, Eve.
Title: Tadpole
Writer: Heather McGowan (story), Niels Mueller (story), Gary Winick (story), Heather McGowan, Niels Mueller
Actors: Aaron Stanford, Kate Mara, Robert Iler, Peter Appel
tomatoConsensus: Slight, but good-natured and witty.

Plot: A computer programmer's dream job at a hot Portland-based firm turns nightmarish when he discovers his boss has a secret and ruthless means of dispatching anti-trust problems.
Title: Antitrust
Actors: Ryan Phillippe, Rachael Leigh Cook, Claire Forlani, Tim Robbins
tomatoConsensus: Due to its use of cliched and ludicrous plot devices, this thriller is more predictable than suspenseful. Also, the acting is bad.

Plot: A retiring police chief pledges to catch the killer of a young child.
Title: The Pledge
Writer: Friedrich Dürrenmatt (book), Jerzy Kromolowski (screenplay), Mary Olson-Kromolowski (screenplay)
Actors: Patricia Clarkson, Beau Daniels, Benicio Del Toro, Dale Dickey
tomatoConsensus: Though its subject matter is grim and may make viewers queasy, The Pledge features an excellent, subtle performance by Jack Nicholson.

Plot: A popular high school cheerleader becomes pregnant with the star quarterback's child, only to find herself turning to crime to support the lifestyle she wants to live.
Title: Sugar & Spice
Actors: Marla Sokoloff, Marley Shelton, Melissa George, Mena Suvari
tomatoConsensus: Though this cheerleader comedy has an intriguing premise, it's too empty-headed and saddled with too many lame jokes to live up to it. Also, some critics say the movie is irresponsible in its depiction of teens and guns.

Plot: Five women are stalked by an unknown assailant while preparing for Valentine's Day.
Title: Valentine
Writer: Tom Savage (novel), Donna Powers (screenplay), Wayne Powers (screenplay), Gretchen J. Berg (screenplay), Aaron Harberts (screenplay)
Actors: Denise Richards, David Boreanaz, Marley Shelton, Jessica Capshaw
tomatoConsensus: Valentine is basically a formulaic throwback to conventional pre-Scream slasher flicks. Critics say it doesn't offer enough suspense or scares to justify its addition to the genre.

Plot: Living in exile, Hannibal Lecter tries to reconnect with now disgraced FBI agent Clarice Starling and finds himself a target for revenge from a powerful victim.
Title: Hannibal
Writer: Thomas Harris (novel), David Mamet (screenplay), Steven Zaillian (screenplay)
Actors: Anthony Hopkins, Julianne Moore, Gary Oldman, Ray Liotta
tomatoConsensus: While superbly acted and stylishly filmed, Hannibal lacks the character interaction between the two leads which made the first movie so engrossing.

Plot: A pair of buddies conspire to save their best friend from marrying the wrong woman.
Title: Saving Silverman
Actors: Steve Zahn, Jack Black, Jason Biggs, Amanda Peet
tomatoConsensus: Dragged down by a plot lacking any sense of logic and obnoxious, unsympathetic characters, this comedy is more crude and mean-spirited than funny.

Plot: After dying before his time, an aspiring black comic gets a second shot at life - by being placed in the body of a wealthy white businessman.
Title: Down to Earth
Writer: Elaine May, Warren Beatty, Chris Rock (screenplay), Lance Crouther (screenplay), Ali LeRoi (screenplay), Louis C.K. (screenplay)
Actors: Chris Rock, Regina King, Chazz Palminteri, Eugene Levy
tomatoConsensus: A toned down Chris Rock fails to bring a limp script to life as the movie moves from one gag to the next.

Plot: TJ and company must save summer vacation from disappearing forever.
Title: Recess: School's Out
Writer: Paul Germain (television series Recess), Joe Ansolabehere (television series Recess), Paul Germain (story), Joe Ansolabehere (story), Jonathan Greenberg (story), Jonathan Greenberg (screenplay)
Actors: Rickey D'Shon Collins, Jason Davis, Ashley Johnson, Andrew Lawrence
tomatoConsensus: Though basically a TV cartoon stretched out to movie-length, Recess has enough successful jokes and smart writing to make it a worthwhile view.

Plot: In a coma, a cartoonist finds himself trapped within his own underground creation and must find a way to get back, while racing against his popular but treacherous character, Monkeybone.
Title: Monkeybone
Writer: Kaja Blackley (graphic novel "Dark Town"), Sam Hamm
Actors: Brendan Fraser, Bridget Fonda, John Turturro, Chris Kattan
tomatoConsensus: Though original and full of bizarre visuals, Monkeybone is too shapeless a movie, with unengaging characters and random situations that fail to build up laughs.

Plot: A gang of ex-cons rob a casino during Elvis convention week.
Title: 3000 Miles to Graceland
Actors: Kurt Russell, Kevin Costner, Courteney Cox, Christian Slater
tomatoConsensus: While the premise sounds promising, the movie turns out to be a tedious and unnecessarily violent heist movie that's low on laughs and leaves no cliche unturned.

Plot: A man tries to transport an ancient gun called The Mexican, believed to carry a curse, back across the border, while his girlfriend pressures him to give up his criminal ways.
Title: The Mexican
Actors: Brad Pitt, Julia Roberts, James Gandolfini, J.K. Simmons
tomatoConsensus: Though The Mexican makes a good attempt at originality, its ponderous length makes it wear out its welcome. Also, those looking forward to seeing Roberts and Pitt paired up may end up disappointed, as they are kept apart for most of the movie.

Plot: A mailman takes care of a dog that, unbeknownst to him, is an FBI drug-sniffing superdog that has escaped from the witness protection program after becoming the target of an assassination.
Title: See Spot Run
Writer: George Gallo (screenplay), Gregory Poirier (screenplay), Dan Baron (screenplay), Chris Faber (screenplay), Andrew Deane (story), Michael Alexander Miller (story), George Gallo (story), Stuart Gibbs (adaptation), Craig Titley (adaptation)
Actors: David Arquette, Michael Clarke Duncan, Leslie Bibb, Joe Viterelli
tomatoConsensus: See Spot Run has all the elements chidren enjoy in a movie: a lovable dog, bad things happening to stupid adults, and lots of dog poop. For adults, it's either hit-or-miss.

Plot: A homicide detective and a fire marshall must stop a pair of murderers who commit videotaped crimes to become media darlings.
Title: 15 Minutes
Actors: Robert De Niro, Edward Burns, Kelsey Grammer, Avery Brooks
tomatoConsensus: As critical as it is about sensationalism in the media, 15 Minutes itself indulges in lurid violence, and its satire is too heavy-handed to be effective.

Plot: When Berke Landers, a popular high school basketball star, gets dumped by his life-long girlfriend, Allison, he soon begins to lose it. But with the help of his best friend Felix's sister ...
Title: Get Over It
Actors: Kirsten Dunst, Ben Foster, Melissa Sagemiller, Sisqó
tomatoConsensus: As with most teen movies, Get Over It is entirely predictable, and there's not enough plot to sustain the length of the movie. However, it is not without its charms.

Plot: A Russian and a German sniper play a game of cat-and-mouse during the Battle of Stalingrad.
Title: Enemy at the Gates
Actors: Jude Law, Ed Harris, Rachel Weisz, Joseph Fiennes
tomatoConsensus: Atmospheric and thrilling, Enemy at the Gates gets the look and feel of war right. However, the love story seems out of place.

Plot: Four friends begin to question women and relationships when one of them announces impending nuptials.
Title: The Brothers
Actors: Morris Chestnut, D.L. Hughley, Bill Bellamy, Shemar Moore
tomatoConsensus: Often seen as a Waiting to Exhale with men, The Brothers is amiable. However, it feels superficial and somewhat of a retread.

Plot: After being jilted by her boyfriend, a talk show talent scout writes a column on the relationship habits of men which gains her national fame.
Title: Someone Like You...
Actors: Ashley Judd, Greg Kinnear, Hugh Jackman, Marisa Tomei
tomatoConsensus: A light and predictable, if somewhat shallow, romantic comedy that's easy to sit through because of the charming leads.

Plot: Seven years ago, a bunch of friends make a bet that'll give the last remaining bachelor a ton of money. Now, after losing a ton of money at a Vegas Casino, Michael Delaney has to quickly ...
Title: Tomcats
Actors: Jerry O'Connell, Shannon Elizabeth, Jake Busey, Horatio Sanz
tomatoConsensus: Why even bother? You already know if you're going to see it or not.

Plot: A tailor living in Panama reluctantly becomes a spy for a British agent.
Title: The Tailor of Panama
Writer: John le Carré (novel), Andrew Davies (screenplay), John le Carré (screenplay), John Boorman (screenplay)
Actors: Pierce Brosnan, Geoffrey Rush, Jamie Lee Curtis, Leonor Varela
tomatoConsensus: The Tailor of Panama is a smart, darkly satirical thriller with exuberant performances from Pierce Brosnan and Geoffrey Rush.

Plot: A congressman's daughter under Secret Service protection is kidnapped from a private school by an insider who calls Det. Alex Cross, sucking him into the case even though he's recovering from the loss of his partner.
Title: Along Came a Spider
Actors: Morgan Freeman, Monica Potter, Michael Wincott, Dylan Baker
tomatoConsensus: Derivative and contains too many implausible situations.

Plot: After being abandoned by his parents at the Grand Canyon, Joe Dirt tells the story of his journey to find his parents.
Title: Joe Dirt
Actors: David Spade, Brittany Daniel, Dennis Miller, Adam Beach
tomatoConsensus: If you fall within the target audience of Joe Dirt, you may find it funny. Otherwise, the jokes will seem like a tired retread.

Plot: A girl group find themselves in the middle of a conspiracy to deliver subliminal messages through popular music in this send up of the music industry and pop culture.
Title: Josie and the Pussycats
Writer: Deborah Kaplan, Harry Elfont, Richard Goldwater (characters), Dan DeCarlo (characters), John L. Goldwater (characters)
Actors: Rachael Leigh Cook, Rosario Dawson, Tara Reid, Gabriel Mann
tomatoConsensus: This live-action update of Josie and the Pussycats offers up bubbly, fluffy fun, but the constant appearance of product placements seems rather hypocritical.

Plot: A group of old family members bands together when a despicable family member thankfully expires.
Title: Kingdom Come
Writer: David Dean Bottrell (play), Jessie Jones (play), David Dean Bottrell (screenplay), Jessie Jones (screenplay)
Actors: LL Cool J, Jada Pinkett Smith, Vivica A. Fox, Loretta Devine
tomatoConsensus: While it has its moments, Kingdom Come is marred by a script that's low on laughs and uneven in tone.

Plot: An unemployed cartoonist moves back in with his parents and younger brother Freddy. When his parents demand he leave, he begins to spread rumors that his father is sexually abusing Freddy.
Title: Freddy Got Fingered
Actors: Tom Green, Rip Torn, Marisa Coughlan, Eddie Kaye Thomas
tomatoConsensus: Unfavorably comparing it with such infamously bad titles as Battlefield Earth, a significant number of critics are calling Tom Green's extreme gross-out comedy the worst movie they have ever seen.

Plot: A young man gets embroiled in a war against vampires.
Title: The Forsaken
Actors: Kerr Smith, Brendan Fehr, Izabella Miko, Johnathon Schaech
tomatoConsensus: It's all been done before, and done better.

Plot: Every man has a different recollection of the beautiful young woman who wreaked havoc on their lives during one heated night.
Title: One Night at McCool's
Actors: Matt Dillon, Mary Jo Smith, Michael Douglas, Paul Reiser
tomatoConsensus: Critics say this blend of film noir and screwball comedy seems to think itself more clever and hip than it actually is. Also, the crucial femme fatale role needs a better, more mature actress than Tyler.

Plot: Porter Stoddard is a well-known New York architect who is at a crossroads... a nexus where twists and turns lead to myriad missteps, some with his wife Ellie, others with longtime friends ...
Title: Town & Country
Actors: Warren Beatty, Nastassja Kinski, Diane Keaton, Goldie Hawn
tomatoConsensus: Afflicted with extensive re-editing and re-writing, this sex comedy feels confusingly choppy. Also, the main characters are so wealthy and privileged that it's difficult to feel sympathy for their problems.

Plot: The mummified body of Imhotep is shipped to a museum in London, where he once again wakes and begins his campaign of rage and terror.
Title: The Mummy Returns
Actors: Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz, John Hannah, Arnold Vosloo
tomatoConsensus: In The Mummy Returns, the special effects are impressive, but the characters seem secondary to the computer generated imagery.

Plot: After his master dies, a peasant squire, fueled by his desire for food and glory, creates a new identity for himself as a knight.
Title: A Knight's Tale
Actors: Heath Ledger, Rufus Sewell, Shannyn Sossamon, Paul Bettany
tomatoConsensus: Once you get past the anachronism, A Knight's Tale becomes a predictable, if spirited, Rocky on horseback.

Plot: Traces the birth and failure of new media company govWorks.com.
Title: Startup.com
Actors: Kaleil Isaza Tuzman, Tom Herman, Kenneth Austin, Tricia Burke
tomatoConsensus: Startup.com is more than just a look at the rise and fall of the new economy. At its center is a friendship being tested to the limit, and that's what makes it worth viewing.

Plot: After his swamp is filled with magical creatures, an ogre agrees to rescue a princess for a villainous lord in order to get his land back.
Title: Shrek
Writer: William Steig (book), Ted Elliott, Terry Rossio, Joe Stillman, Roger S.H. Schulman, Cody Cameron (additional dialogue), Chris Miller (additional dialogue), Conrad Vernon (additional dialogue)
Actors: Mike Myers, Eddie Murphy, Cameron Diaz, John Lithgow
tomatoConsensus: While simultaneously embracing and subverting fairy tales, the irreverent Shrek also manages to tweak Disney's nose, provide a moral message to children, and offer viewers a funny, fast-paced ride.

Plot: A poet falls for a beautiful courtesan whom a jealous duke covets.
Title: Moulin Rouge!
Actors: Nicole Kidman, Ewan McGregor, John Leguizamo, Jim Broadbent
tomatoConsensus: A love-it-or-hate-it experience, Moulin Rouge is all style, all giddy, over-the-top spectacle. But it's also daring in its vision and wildly original.

Plot: Pearl Harbor follows the story of two best friends, Rafe and Danny, and their love lives as they go off to join the war.
Title: Pearl Harbor
Actors: Ben Affleck, Josh Hartnett, Kate Beckinsale, William Lee Scott
tomatoConsensus: Pearl Harbor tries to be the Titanic of war movies, but it's just a tedious romance filled with laughably bad dialogue. The 40 minute action sequence is spectacular though.

Plot: A rich man catches a thief burglarizing his home and steals the thief's lucky ring, who then tries to get it back.
Title: What's the Worst That Could Happen?
Actors: Martin Lawrence, Danny DeVito, John Leguizamo, Glenne Headly
tomatoConsensus: Talented cast is squandered by an uninvolving script filled with unfunny gags.

Plot: A fire-fighting cadet, two college professors, and a geeky but sexy government scientist work against an alien organism that has been rapidly evolving since its arrival on Earth inside a meteor.
Title: Evolution
Writer: Don Jakoby (story), David Diamond (screenplay), David Weissman (screenplay), Don Jakoby (screenplay)
Actors: David Duchovny, Julianne Moore, Orlando Jones, Seann William Scott
tomatoConsensus: Director Reitman tries to remake Ghostbusters, but his efforts are largely unsuccessful because the movie has too many comedic misfires.

Plot: Love is complex and relationships deteriorate.
Title: The Anniversary Party
Actors: Alan Cumming, Jennifer Jason Leigh, Otis, Steven Freedman
tomatoConsensus: This Party features a killer cast and many funny scenes, but the movie feels like nothing more than an excuse for the actors to emote.

Plot: A young adventurer named Milo Thatch joins an intrepid group of explorers to find the mysterious lost continent of Atlantis.
Title: Atlantis: The Lost Empire
Writer: Tab Murphy (screenplay), Kirk Wise (story by), Gary Trousdale (story by), Joss Whedon (story by), Bryce Zabel (story by), Jackie Zabel (story by), Tab Murphy (story by), David Reynolds (additional screenplay material)
Actors: Michael J. Fox, Corey Burton, James Garner, Claudia Christian
tomatoConsensus: Atlantis provides a fast-paced spectacle, but stints on such things as character development and a coherent plot.

Plot: Video game adventuress Lara Croft comes to life in a movie where she races against time and villains to recover powerful ancient artifacts.
Title: Lara Croft: Tomb Raider
Writer: Sara B. Cooper (story), Mike Werb (story), Michael Colleary (story), Simon West (adaptation), Patrick Massett (screenplay), John Zinman (screenplay)
Actors: Angelina Jolie, Jon Voight, Iain Glen, Noah Taylor
tomatoConsensus: Angelina Jolie is perfect for the role of Lara Croft, but even she can't save the movie from a senseless plot and action sequences with no emotional impact.

Plot: Dolittle must save a forest and a bear's life.
Title: Dr. Dolittle 2
Writer: Hugh Lofting (Doctor Dolittle stories), Larry Levin
Actors: Eddie Murphy, Kristen Wilson, Raven-Symoné, Kyla Pratt
tomatoConsensus: Although there are laughs to be had in Dr. Dolittle 2, its preoccupation with toilet humor and Murphy's restrained performance makes this a missed opportunity.

Plot: Los Angeles police officer Brian O'Connor must decide where his loyalty really lies when he becomes enamored with the street racing world he has been sent undercover to destroy.
Title: The Fast and the Furious
Writer: Ken Li (magazine article "Racer X"), Gary Scott Thompson (screen story), Gary Scott Thompson (screenplay), Erik Bergquist (screenplay), David Ayer (screenplay)
Actors: Paul Walker, Vin Diesel, Michelle Rodriguez, Jordana Brewster
tomatoConsensus: Sleek and shiny on the surface, The Fast and the Furious recalls those cheesy teenage exploitation flicks of the 1950s.

Plot: This is the story of Jody, an unemployed young black man, who's been living with his mother for several years, even though he's got a child of his own. Romantically, he's having ...
Title: Baby Boy
Actors: Tyrese Gibson, Taraji P. Henson, Omar Gooding, Tamara LaSeon Bass
tomatoConsensus: Preachy and repetitive in parts, Baby Boy still manages to exude authenticity, thanks to its competent cast.

Plot: At Pacific Palisades High, a poor Latino falls hard for a troubled girl from the affluent neighborhood.
Title: Crazy/Beautiful
Actors: Kirsten Dunst, Jay Hernandez, Bruce Davison, Herman Osorio
tomatoConsensus: The story is not new, but the film gets credit for trying to move away from the genre's cliches. Kirsten Dunst and newcomer Jay Hernandez give believable performances.

Plot: A betrayed intelligence officer enlists the aid of a prostitute to prove his innocence from a deadly conspiracy while returning a favor to her.
Title: Kiss of the Dragon
Writer: Jet Li (story), Luc Besson (screenplay), Robert Mark Kamen (screenplay)
Actors: Jet Li, Bridget Fonda, Tchéky Karyo, Max Ryan
tomatoConsensus: A formulaic actioner that's sure to please action fans. Those looking for plot, believability, or character development will have difficulty finding them.

Plot: Two aspiring boxers, lifelong friends, get involved in a money-laundering scheme through a low-level organized crime group.
Title: Made
Actors: Jon Favreau, Vince Vaughn, Joe Goossen, Famke Janssen
tomatoConsensus: Not as good as Swingers, but it's still witty and goofy enough for some laughs.

Plot: A movie publicist deals with the messy public split of his movie's co-stars while keeping reporters at bay while a reclusive director holds the film's print hostage.
Title: America's Sweethearts
Actors: Julia Roberts, Billy Crystal, Catherine Zeta-Jones, John Cusack
tomatoConsensus: Despite its famous cast, the movie lacks sympathetic characters and is only funny in spurts.

Plot: A transgender punk-rock girl from East Berlin tours the U.S. with her band as she tells her life story and follows the former lover/band-mate who stole her songs.
Title: Hedwig and the Angry Inch
Writer: John Cameron Mitchell (book), Stephen Trask (book), John Cameron Mitchell (screenplay)
Actors: John Cameron Mitchell, Miriam Shor, Stephen Trask, Theodore Liscinski
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 28 wins & 32 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Hedwig and the Angry Inch may very well be the next Rocky Horror midnight movie. It not only knows how to rock, but Hedwig's story has an emotional poignancy.

Plot: An Air Force astronaut crash lands on a mysterious planet where evolved, talking apes dominate a race of primitive humans.
Title: Planet of the Apes
Writer: Pierre Boulle (novel), William Broyles Jr. (screenplay), Lawrence Konner (screenplay), Mark Rosenthal (screenplay)
Actors: Mark Wahlberg, Tim Roth, Helena Bonham Carter, Michael Clarke Duncan
Awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 10 wins & 25 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This remake of Planet of the Apes can't compare to the original in some critics' mind, but the striking visuals and B-movie charms may win you over.

Plot: A woman along with her lover, plan to con a rich man by marrying him and on earning his trust running away with all his money. Everything goes as planned until she actually begins to fall in love with him.
Title: Original Sin
Actors: Antonio Banderas, Angelina Jolie, Thomas Jane, Jack Thompson
tomatoConsensus: Laughably melodramatic, Original Sin features bad acting, bad dialogue, and bad plotting.

Plot: Mia Thermopolis has just found out that she is the heir apparent to the throne of Genovia. With her friends Lilly and Michael Moscovitz in tow, she tries to navigate through the rest of her 16th year.
Title: The Princess Diaries
Actors: Julie Andrews, Anne Hathaway, Hector Elizondo, Heather Matarazzo
tomatoConsensus: A charming, if familiar, makeover movie for young teenage girls.

Plot: In this sequel to the hit comedy American Pie (1999), the high school students are now in college. These close friends decide to meet up at the beach house for some fun.
Title: American Pie 2
Writer: Adam Herz (characters), David H. Steinberg (story), Adam Herz (story), Adam Herz (screenplay)
Actors: Jason Biggs, Shannon Elizabeth, Alyson Hannigan, Chris Klein
tomatoConsensus: Being a sequel, American Pie 2 doesn't retain the freshness of the original, nor is it as funny.

Plot: A policeman white blood cell, with the help of a cold pill, must stop a deadly virus from destroying the human they live in, Frank.
Title: Osmosis Jones
Actors: Chris Rock, Laurence Fishburne, David Hyde Pierce, Brandy Norwood
tomatoConsensus: The animated portion of Osmosis is zippy and fun, but the live-action portion is lethargic.

Plot: A woman who lives in a darkened old house with her two photosensitive children becomes convinced that her family home is haunted.
Title: The Others
Actors: Nicole Kidman, Fionnula Flanagan, Christopher Eccleston, Alakina Mann
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 28 wins & 50 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Others is a spooky thriller that reminds us that a movie doesn't need expensive special effects to be creepy.

Plot: When a Midwest town learns that a corrupt railroad baron has captured the deeds to their homesteads without their knowledge, a group of young ranchers join forces to take back what is ...
Title: American Outlaws
Writer: Roderick Taylor (story), Roderick Taylor (screenplay), John Rogers (screenplay)
Actors: Colin Farrell, Scott Caan, Ali Larter, Gabriel Macht
tomatoConsensus: With corny dialogue, revisionist history, anachronistic music, and a generically attractive cast, American Outlaws is a sanitized, teenybopper version of Jesse James.

Plot: A woman spirals out of control while trying to keep her son from being found culpable in a murder investigation.
Title: The Deep End
Writer: Elisabeth Sanxay Holding (novel), Scott McGehee, David Siegel
Actors: Tilda Swinton, Goran Visnjic, Jonathan Tucker, Peter Donat
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 18 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A well-acted film noir with arresting visuals.

Plot: When a fisherman leaves to fight with the Greek army during WWII, his fiancee falls in love with the local Italian commander.
Title: Captain Corelli's Mandolin
Actors: Penélope Cruz, John Hurt, Christian Bale, Irene Papas
tomatoConsensus: The cinematography is gorgeous, but the movie plays it fast and loose with history and the novel it was adapted from. Mostly, the movie fails because the romance between the leads strains credulity and the story is largely uninvolving.

Plot: A Las Vegas casino magnate, determined to find a new avenue for wagering, sets up a race for money.
Title: Rat Race
Actors: Breckin Meyer, Jenica Bergere, Cuba Gooding Jr., Carrie Diamond
tomatoConsensus: Rat Race moves from one sight gag to another, but only a handful of them are genuinely funny.

Plot: An insurance investigator and an efficency expert who hate each other are both hypnotized by a crooked hypnotist with a jade scorpion into stealing jewels.
Title: The Curse of the Jade Scorpion
Actors: John Tormey, John Schuck, Woody Allen, Elizabeth Berkley
tomatoConsensus: The writing for Scorpion is not as sharp as Woody Allen's previous movies as most of the jokes fall flat.

Plot: The comic 'Bluntman and Chronic' is based on real-life stoners Jay and Silent Bob, so when they get no profit from a big-screen adaptation they set out to wreck the movie.
Title: Jay and Silent Bob Strike Back
Actors: Jason Mewes, Kevin Smith, Ben Affleck, Jeff Anderson
tomatoConsensus: Fans can expect a good laugh as the cast from Smith's previous films reunite for Jay and Silent Bob's last bow. The loose plotting and crude language may be too much for others though.

Plot: Years in the future, a Martian police unit is sent to pick up a highly dangerous criminal at a remote mining post. Upon arrival, the cops find that the post has become a charnel house.
Title: Ghosts of Mars
Actors: Natasha Henstridge, Ice Cube, Jason Statham, Clea DuVall
tomatoConsensus: John Carpenter's Ghosts of Mars is not one of Carpenter's better movies, filled as it is with bad dialogue, bad acting, confusing flashbacks, and scenes that are more campy than scary.

Plot: A rich girl whose family summers on Cape Cod has a romance with a local poor boy who hopes to become a major league baseball player.
Title: Summer Catch
Writer: Kevin Falls (story), Kevin Falls (screenplay), John Gatins (screenplay)
Actors: Freddie Prinze Jr., Jessica Biel, Fred Ward, Matthew Lillard
tomatoConsensus: A cliched and predictable sports comedy that's mostly devoid of excitement or laughs, Summer Catch is strictly bush-league.

Plot: A Mexican-American master chef and father to three daughters has lost his taste for food but not for life.
Title: Tortilla Soup
Writer: Hui-Ling Wang (earlier screenplay), Ang Lee (earlier screenplay), James Schamus (earlier screenplay), Ramón Menéndez (screenplay), Tom Musca (screenplay), Vera Blasi (screenplay)
Actors: Jacqueline Obradors, Tamara Mello, Judy Herrera, Nikolai Kinski
tomatoConsensus: An English remake of Ang Lee's Eat Drink Man Woman, Tortilla Soup is as charming and flavorful as the dishes it features.

Plot: An update of Shakespeare's 'Othello' with a young cast, set in an upper class prep school, & centered around basketball player Odin.
Title: O
Actors: Mekhi Phifer, Martin Sheen, Josh Hartnett, Andrew Keegan
tomatoConsensus: Though well-intentioned and serious in its exploration of teen violence, O is an uneven experiment that doesn't quite succeed.

Plot: Alexander Dumas' novel is updated with an eastern influence as D'Artagnan attempts to join the king's elite guards, the Royal Musketeers, and find the man who killed his parents.
Title: The Musketeer
Actors: Catherine Deneuve, Mena Suvari, Stephen Rea, Tim Roth
tomatoConsensus: Hong Kong inspired action sequences take center stage in this latest Three Musketeers adaptation. Unfortunately, the oversimplification of the story and an uncharismatic lead character leave the movie flat.

Plot: A co-ed is caught between the world of the living and the dead.
Title: Soul Survivors
Actors: Melissa Sagemiller, Wes Bentley, Casey Affleck, Eliza Dushku
tomatoConsensus: Soul Survivors' stock characters and utter lack of suspense gives viewers little reason to attempt deciphering the confusing plot.

Plot: An arrogant career woman plays a series of heartless mind-games with her boyfriend to "put him in line," only to discover that he has a few tricks up his own sleeve.
Title: Two Can Play That Game
Actors: Vivica A. Fox, Morris Chestnut, Anthony Anderson, Gabrielle Union
tomatoConsensus: As a romantic comedy, Two Can Play That Game is more mean-spirited than romantic. Also, some critics say the movie is misogynistic in its attitudes and has too many blatant product placements.

Plot: An orphaned teenager is taken in by a Malibu couple but discovers they aren't the caring friends they seemed to be.
Title: The Glass House
Actors: Leelee Sobieski, Diane Lane, Stellan Skarsgård, Bruce Dern
tomatoConsensus: Due to obvious plot twists and foreshadowing, The Glass House fails to thrill. By the end, it degenerates into ludicrousness.

Plot: An aimless young man who is scalping tickets, gambling and drinking, agrees to coach a Little League team from the Cabrini Green housing project in Chicago as a condition of getting a loan from a friend.
Title: Hardball
Actors: Keanu Reeves, Diane Lane, John Hawkes, Bryan Hearne
tomatoConsensus: Although Hardball contains some touching moments, they are not enough to transcend the sports formula.

Plot: A young singer dates a disc jockey who helps her get into the music business, but their relationship become complicated as she ascends to super stardom.
Title: Glitter
Actors: Mariah Carey, Max Beesley, Da Brat, Tia Texada
tomatoConsensus: Glitter is a hodgepodge of movie cliches and bad acting that's sure to generate unintentional laughs. Unfortunately, the movie is not bad enough to be good.

Plot: The interlocking lives and loves of six New Yorkers.
Title: Sidewalks of New York
Actors: Penny Balfour, Edward Burns, Michael Leydon Campbell, Nadia Dajani
tomatoConsensus: Though well-acted, Sidewalks of New York generally comes off as a second-rate Woody Allen film. The characters seem self-absorbed, the problems trite.

Plot: When the daughter of a psychiatrist is kidnapped, he's horrified to discover that the abductors' demand is that he break through to a post traumatic stress disorder suffering young woman who knows a secret...
Title: Don't Say a Word
Writer: Andrew Klavan (novel), Anthony Peckham (screenplay), Patrick Smith Kelly (screenplay)
Actors: Michael Douglas, Sean Bean, Brittany Murphy, Skye McCole Bartusiak
tomatoConsensus: Don't Say A Word is slick and competently made, but the movie is routine and stretches believability with many eye rolling moments.

Plot: A widowed mother and her son change when a mysterious stranger enters their lives.
Title: Hearts in Atlantis
Actors: Anthony Hopkins, Anton Yelchin, Hope Davis, Mika Boorem
tomatoConsensus: Hearts in Atlantis is well-acted and beautiful to look at, but the movie is nothing more than a mood piece.

Plot: At the end of his career, a clueless fashion model is brainwashed to kill the Prime Minister of Malaysia.
Title: Zoolander
Writer: Drake Sather (character Derek Zoolander), Ben Stiller (character Derek Zoolander), Drake Sather (story), Ben Stiller (story), Drake Sather (screenplay), Ben Stiller (screenplay), John Hamburg (screenplay)
Actors: Ben Stiller, Owen Wilson, Christine Taylor, Will Ferrell
tomatoConsensus: A wacky satire on the fashion industry, Zoolander is one of those deliberately dumb comedies that can deliver genuine laughs.

Plot: Three young people on a road trip from Colorado to New Jersey talk to a trucker on their CB radio, then must escape when he turns out to be a psychotic killer.
Title: Joy Ride
Actors: Steve Zahn, Paul Walker, Leelee Sobieski, Jessica Bowman
tomatoConsensus: A well-constructed B-movie thriller, Joy Ride keeps up the necessary level of tension and chills. Critics also liked Zahn's performance as the goofball older brother.

Plot: Max Keeble, the victim of his 7th grade class, plots revenge when he learns he's moving; it backfires when he doesn't move after all.
Title: Max Keeble's Big Move
Writer: David L. Watts (story), Jonathan Bernstein (story), Mark Blackwell (story), James Greer (story), Jonathan Bernstein (screenplay), Mark Blackwell (screenplay), James Greer (screenplay)
Actors: Alex D. Linz, Larry Miller, Jamie Kennedy, Zena Grey
tomatoConsensus: Max Keeble may be fun for kids, but bland and unoriginal for adults.

Plot: A couple reunite years after the night they first met, fell in love, and separated, convinced that one day they'd end up together.
Title: Serendipity
Actors: John Cusack, Kate Beckinsale, Jeremy Piven, Bridget Moynahan
tomatoConsensus: Light and charming, Serendipity could benefit from less contrivances.

Plot: Two bank robbers fall in love with the girl they've kidnapped.
Title: Bandits
Actors: Bruce Willis, Billy Bob Thornton, Cate Blanchett, Troy Garity
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 4 wins & 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The story may not warrant its lengthy running time, but the cast of Bandits makes it an enjoyable ride.

Plot: After a car wreck on the winding Mulholland Drive renders a woman amnesiac, she and a perky Hollywood-hopeful search for clues and answers across Los Angeles in a twisting venture beyond dreams and reality.
Title: Mulholland Drive
Actors: Naomi Watts, Jeanne Bates, Dan Birnbaum, Laura Harring
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 46 wins & 56 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: David Lynch's dreamlike and mysterious Mulholland Drive is a twisty neo-noir with an unconventional structure that features a mesmirizing performance from Naomi Watts as a woman on the dark fringes of Hollywood.

Plot: Over 20 years after his death by a gunshot, Jimmy Bones comes back as a ghost to wreak revenge on those who killed him and to clean up his neighborhood.
Title: Bones
Actors: Snoop Dogg, Pam Grier, Michael T. Weiss, Clifton Powell
tomatoConsensus: Slow to start, the sleek looking Bones is more silly than scary.

Plot: In Victorian Era London, a troubled clairvoyant police detective investigates the murders by Jack The Ripper.
Title: From Hell
Writer: Alan Moore (graphic novel), Eddie Campbell (graphic novel), Terry Hayes (screenplay), Rafael Yglesias (screenplay)
Actors: Johnny Depp, Heather Graham, Ian Holm, Robbie Coltrane
tomatoConsensus: Visually impressive, but this latest Ripper tale is dull and far from scary.

Plot: A court-martialed general rallies together 1200 inmates to rise against the corrupt system that put him away.
Title: The Last Castle
Writer: David Scarpa (story), David Scarpa (screenplay), Graham Yost (screenplay)
Actors: Robert Redford, James Gandolfini, Mark Ruffalo, Steve Burton
tomatoConsensus: The Last Castle is well acted and rousing for the most part, but the story can't stand up to close scrutiny.

Plot: A single mother, with dreams of becoming a writer, has a son at the age of 15 in 1965, and goes through a failed marriage with the drug-addicted father.
Title: Riding in Cars with Boys
Actors: Drew Barrymore, Steve Zahn, Adam Garcia, Brittany Murphy
tomatoConsensus: Riding in Cars With Boys suffers from mixing grit and pathos with cuteness and comedy. Ironically, many critics found Zahn's character more compelling and three-dimensional than Barrymore's.

Plot: A man shuffles through a dream meeting various people and discussing the meanings and purposes of the universe.
Title: Waking Life
Actors: Trevor Jack Brooks, Lorelei Linklater, Wiley Wiggins, Glover Gill
tomatoConsensus: Waking Life's inventive animated aesthetic adds a distinctive visual component to a film that could easily have rested on its smart screenplay and talented ensemble cast.

Plot: PROT is a patient at a mental hospital who claims to be from a far away planet. His psychiatrist tries to help him, only to begin to doubt his own explanations.
Title: K-PAX
Actors: Kevin Spacey, Jeff Bridges, Mary McCormack, Alfre Woodard
tomatoConsensus: For those who have seen One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest or Starman, K-Pax may not hold anything new. The movie works best as a showcase for Kevin Spacey and Jeff Bridges.

Plot: When Cyrus Kriticos, a very rich collector of unique things dies, he leaves it all to his nephew and his family. All including his house, his fortune, and his malicious collection of ghosts!
Title: Thir13en Ghosts
Writer: Robb White (story), Neal Marshall Stevens (screenplay), Richard D'Ovidio (screenplay)
Actors: Tony Shalhoub, Embeth Davidtz, Matthew Lillard, Shannon Elizabeth
tomatoConsensus: The production design is first rate, but 13 Ghosts is distinctly lacking in scares.

Plot: When a man is diagnosed with terminal cancer, he takes custody of his misanthropic teenage son, for whom quality time means getting high, engaging in small-time prostitution, and avoiding his father.
Title: Life as a House
Actors: Kevin Kline, Kristin Scott Thomas, Hayden Christensen, Jena Malone
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 8 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A manipulative tearjerker, Life as a House benefits from fine performances from the cast.

Plot: A laconic, chain-smoking barber blackmails his wife's boss and lover for money to invest in dry cleaning, but his plan goes terribly wrong.
Title: The Man Who Wasn't There
Actors: Billy Bob Thornton, Frances McDormand, Michael Badalucco, James Gandolfini
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 24 wins & 41 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Stylish but emotionally distant, The Man Who Wasn't There is a clever tribute to the film noir genre.

Plot: A divorced father discovers that his 12-year-old son's new stepfather is not what he made himself out to be.
Title: Domestic Disturbance
Writer: Lewis Colick (story), William S. Comanor (story), Gary Drucker (story), Lewis Colick (screenplay)
Actors: John Travolta, James Lashly, Rebecca Tilney, Debra Mooney
tomatoConsensus: Well-made but extremely predictable, Domestic Disturbance is an average thriller that may work better on TV.

Plot: In order to power the city, monsters have to scare children so that they scream. However, the children are toxic to the monsters, and after a child gets through, two monsters realize things may not be what they think.
Title: Monsters, Inc.
Writer: Pete Docter (original story by), Jill Culton (original story by), Jeff Pidgeon (original story by), Ralph Eggleston (original story by), Andrew Stanton (screenplay), Daniel Gerson (screenplay)
Director: Pete Docter, David Silverman, Lee Unkrich
Actors: John Goodman, Billy Crystal, Mary Gibbs, Steve Buscemi
tomatoConsensus: Clever, funny, and delightful to look at, Monsters, Inc. delivers another resounding example of how Pixar elevated the bar for modern all-ages animation.

Plot: A career jewel thief finds himself at tense odds with his longtime partner, a crime boss who sends his nephew to keep watch.
Title: Heist
Actors: Gene Hackman, Danny DeVito, Delroy Lindo, Sam Rockwell
tomatoConsensus: Heist didn't cover any new ground, but the cast and Mamet's expertise with witty banter make it worthwhile.

Plot: A shallow man falls in love with a 300 pound woman because of her "inner beauty".
Title: Shallow Hal
Writer: Sean Moynihan, Peter Farrelly, Bobby Farrelly
Actors: Gwyneth Paltrow, Jack Black, Jason Alexander, Joe Viterelli
tomatoConsensus: While surprisingly sweeter and warm-hearted than previous Farrelly outings, Shallow Hal is also less funny and more bland.

Plot: With the rent due and his car booted, Sean (Dr. Dre) has to come up with some ends...and fast. When his best buddy and roommate Dee Loc (Snoop Dogg), suggests that Sean get a job busting ...
Title: The Wash
Actors: Anthony Albano, Dr. Dre, Tic, Lamont Bentley
tomatoConsensus: Sloppily-made, amateurish, and scarce on laughs, The Wash can't compare to Richard Pryor's 1976 Car Wash.

Plot: Rescued from the outrageous neglect of his aunt and uncle, a young boy with a great destiny proves his worth while attending Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry.
Title: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone
Actors: Richard Harris, Maggie Smith, Robbie Coltrane, Saunders Triplets
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 17 wins & 60 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone adapts its source material faithfully while condensing the novel's overstuffed narrative into an involving -- and often downright exciting -- big-screen magical caper.

Title: Novocaine
Writer: Paul Felopulos (story), David Atkins (story), David Atkins (screenplay)
Actors: Chelcie Ross, Steve Martin, Laura Dern, Lynne Thigpen
tomatoConsensus: The quirky Novocaine flirts with both dark comedy and noir suspense, but the result is a jarring mix of tones which never quite mesh.

Plot: Martin Lawrence plays Jamal, an employee in Medieval World amusement park. After sustaining a blow to the head, he awakens to find himself in 14th century England.
Title: Black Knight
Writer: Darryl Quarles, Peter Gaulke, Gerry Swallow
Actors: Martin Lawrence, Marsha Thomason, Tom Wilkinson, Vincent Regan
tomatoConsensus: Black Knight feels like a lazily constructed movie, filled with lame gags and constant mugging from Lawrence.

Plot: A snowboarder's plans for his own snowboard park go awry when an ex-girlfriend returns to town.
Title: Out Cold
Actors: Flex Alexander, A.J. Cook, David Denman, Caroline Dhavernas
tomatoConsensus: A party movie that substitutes surfs for snow, Out Cold will leave viewers just that with its gross-out humor and sophomoric plot.

Plot: Retiring CIA agent Nathan Muir recalls his training of Tom Bishop while working against agency politics to free him from his Chinese captors.
Title: Spy Game
Writer: Michael Frost Beckner (story), Michael Frost Beckner (screenplay), David Arata (screenplay)
Actors: Robert Redford, Brad Pitt, Catherine McCormack, Stephen Dillane
tomatoConsensus: The outcome of the kinetic Spy Game is never in doubt, but it is fun watching Robert Redford and Brad Pitt work.

Plot: A New England couple's college-aged son dates an older woman who has two small children and an unwelcome ex-husband.
Title: In the Bedroom
Writer: Robert Festinger (screenplay), Todd Field (screenplay), Andre Dubus (story "Killings")
Actors: Tom Wilkinson, Sissy Spacek, Nick Stahl, Marisa Tomei
Awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 38 wins & 69 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Expertly crafted and performed, In the Bedroom is a quietly wrenching portrayal of grief.

Plot: A Navy navigator is shot down over enemy territory and is ruthlessly pursued by a secret police enforcer and the opposing troops. Meanwhile his commanding officer goes against orders in an attempt to rescue him.
Title: Behind Enemy Lines
Writer: Jim Thomas (story), John Thomas (story), David Veloz (screenplay), Zak Penn (screenplay)
Actors: Owen Wilson, Gene Hackman, Gabriel Macht, Charles Malik Whitfield
tomatoConsensus: The plot for Behind Enemy Lines is more jingoistic than credible, and the overload of flashy visual tricks makes the action sequences resemble a video game.

Plot: Danny Ocean and his eleven accomplices plan to rob three Las Vegas casinos simultaneously.
Title: Ocean's Eleven
Writer: George Clayton Johnson, Jack Golden Russell, Harry Brown, Charles Lederer, Ted Griffin (screenplay)
Actors: George Clooney, Cecelia Ann Birt, Paul L. Nolan, Carol Florence
tomatoConsensus: As fast-paced, witty, and entertaining as it is star-studded and coolly stylish, Ocean's Eleven offers a well-seasoned serving of popcorn entertainment.

Title: The Business of Strangers
Actors: Stockard Channing, Julia Stiles, Frederick Weller, Mary Testa
tomatoConsensus: The Business of Strangers showcases a complex, compelling performance by Channing. Her interactions and clashes with Stiles make for riveting viewing.

Plot: Bosnia and Herzegovina during 1993 at the time of the heaviest fighting between the two warring sides. Two soldiers from opposing sides in the conflict, Nino and Ciki, become trapped in no man's land, whilst a third soldier becomes a living booby trap.
Title: No Man's Land
Country: Bosnia and Herzegovina, France, Slovenia, Italy, UK, Belgium
Actors: Branko Djuric, Rene Bitorajac, Filip Sovagovic, Georges Siatidis
tomatoConsensus: Bleak and darkly humorous, No Man's Land vividly illustrates the absurdity of war.

Plot: "Piñero" tells the story of the explosive life of a Latino icon, the poet-playwright-actor Miguel Piñero, whose urban poetry is recognized as a pre-cursor to rap and hip-hop. After doing ...
Title: Piñero
Actors: Benjamin Bratt, Giancarlo Esposito, Talisa Soto, Nelson Vasquez
tomatoConsensus: Though Bratt is great in the title role, the biopic itself is messy and Piñero grows tiresome.

Plot: A sendup of all the teen movies that have accumulated in the past two decades.
Title: Not Another Teen Movie
Writer: Mike Bender, Adam Jay Epstein, Andrew Jacobson, Phil Beauman, Buddy Johnson
Actors: Chyler Leigh, Chris Evans, Jaime Pressly, Eric Christian Olsen
tomatoConsensus: NATM has some funny moments, but the movie requires the audience to have familiarity with the movies being spoofed and a tolerance for toilet and sexual humor to be truly effective.

Plot: True story of the lifelong romance between novelist Iris Murdoch and her husband John Bayley, from their student days through her battle with Alzheimer's disease.
Title: Iris
Writer: John Bayley (books), Richard Eyre (screenplay), Charles Wood (screenplay)
Actors: Kate Winslet, Hugh Bonneville, Judi Dench, Jim Broadbent
