tomatoConsensus: A solidly constructed drama, Iris is greatly elevated by the strength of its four lead performances.

Plot: The relationships of four couples unravel after the discovery of a young woman's body in Lantana bush in suburban Sydney.
Title: Lantana
Actors: Anthony LaPaglia, Geoffrey Rush, Barbara Hershey, Kerry Armstrong
tomatoConsensus: Lantana is an intricately plotted character study that quietly shines with authenticity.

Plot: An estranged family of former child prodigies reunites when their father announces he is terminally ill.
Title: The Royal Tenenbaums
Actors: Gene Hackman, Anjelica Huston, Ben Stiller, Gwyneth Paltrow
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 45 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Royal Tenenbaums is a delightful adult comedy with many quirks and a sense of poignancy. Many critics especially praised Hackman's performance.

Plot: Two guys by the name of Silas and Jamal decided to one day smoke something magical, which eventually helps them to ace their college entrance exam.
Title: How High
Actors: Method Man, Redman, Obba Babatundé, Mike Epps
tomatoConsensus: How High is a sloppily constructed stoner movie filled with lame, vulgar jokes.

Plot: An eight year-old boy genius and his friends must rescue their parents after the adults are abducted by aliens.
Title: Jimmy Neutron: Boy Genius
Writer: John A. Davis (story), Steve Oedekerk (story), John A. Davis (screenplay), David N. Weiss (screenplay), J. David Stem (screenplay), Steve Oedekerk (screenplay), Dan Schneider (contributing writer)
Actors: Megan Cavanagh, Mark DeCarlo, Debi Derryberry, Jeffrey Garcia
tomatoConsensus: What Jimmy Neutron lacks in computer animation, it makes up for in charm and cleverness.

Plot: Kate and her actor brother live in N.Y. in the 21st Century. Her ex-boyfriend, Stuart, lives above her apartment. Stuart finds a space near the Brooklyn Bridge where there is a gap in time....
Title: Kate & Leopold
Writer: Steven Rogers (story), James Mangold (screenplay), Steven Rogers (screenplay)
Actors: Meg Ryan, Hugh Jackman, Liev Schreiber, Breckin Meyer
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though Jackman charms, Kate and Leopold is bland and predictable, and the time travel scenario lacks inner logic.

Plot: A meek Hobbit from the Shire and eight companions set out on a journey to destroy the powerful One Ring and save Middle Earth from the Dark Lord Sauron.
Title: The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring
Writer: J.R.R. Tolkien (novel), Fran Walsh (screenplay), Philippa Boyens (screenplay), Peter Jackson (screenplay)
Actors: Alan Howard, Noel Appleby, Sean Astin, Sala Baker
tomatoConsensus: Full of eye-popping special effects, and featuring a pitch-perfect cast, The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring brings J.R.R. Tolkien's classic to vivid life.

Plot: A biography of sports legend Muhammad Ali, focusing on his triumphs and controversies between 1964 and 1974.
Title: Ali
Writer: Gregory Allen Howard (story), Stephen J. Rivele (screenplay), Christopher Wilkinson (screenplay), Eric Roth (screenplay), Michael Mann (screenplay)
Actors: Will Smith, Jamie Foxx, Jon Voight, Mario Van Peebles
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 25 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though perhaps no film could fully do justice to the fascinating life and personality of Muhammad Ali, Mann's direction and Smith's performance combine to pack a solid punch.

Plot: 123 elite U.S. soldiers drop into Somalia to capture two top lieutenants of a renegade warlord and find themselves in a desperate battle with a large force of heavily-armed Somalis.
Title: Black Hawk Down
Actors: Josh Hartnett, Ewan McGregor, Tom Sizemore, Eric Bana
tomatoConsensus: Though it's light on character development and cultural empathy, Black Hawk Down is a visceral, pulse-pounding portrait of war, elevated by Ridley Scott's superb technical skill.

Plot: The lives of upstairs guests and downstairs servants at a party in 1932 in a country house in England as they investigate a murder involving one of them.
Title: Gosford Park
Writer: Julian Fellowes, Robert Altman (based upon an idea by), Bob Balaban (based upon an idea by)
Actors: Maggie Smith, Michael Gambon, Kristin Scott Thomas, Camilla Rutherford
tomatoConsensus: A mixture of Upstairs, Downstairs, Clue, and perceptive social commentary, Gosford Park ranks among director Altman's best.

Plot: A mentally handicapped man fights for custody of his 7-year-old daughter, and in the process teaches his cold hearted lawyer the value of love and family.
Title: I Am Sam
Actors: Sean Penn, Michelle Pfeiffer, Dakota Fanning, Dianne Wiest
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 10 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Not only does the manipulative I Am Sam oversimplify a complex issue, it drowns it in treacle.

Plot: After a family tragedy, a racist prison guard reexamines his attitudes while falling in love with the African American wife of the last prisoner he executed.
Title: Monster's Ball
Actors: Billy Bob Thornton, Taylor Simpson, Gabrielle Witcher, Heath Ledger
tomatoConsensus: Somber and thought provoking, Monster's Ball has great performances all around.

Plot: An emotionally-beaten man with his young daughter moves to his ancestral home in Newfoundland to reclaim his life.
Title: The Shipping News
Writer: Annie Proulx (based on the novel by), Robert Nelson Jacobs (screenplay)
Actors: Kevin Spacey, Julianne Moore, Judi Dench, Cate Blanchett
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 2 wins & 10 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though solidly made and acted, The Shipping News is rather heavy-handed and dull, especially given the nature of its protagonist.

Plot: In the future, an alien race uses androids as bombs to attack Earth. A government weapons specialist is accused of being one such android and sets out to prove his innocence.
Title: Impostor
Writer: Philip K. Dick (short story "The Impostor"), Scott Rosenberg (adaptation), Caroline Case (screenplay), Ehren Kruger (screenplay), David Twohy (screenplay)
Actors: Gary Sinise, Madeleine Stowe, Vincent D'Onofrio, Tony Shalhoub
tomatoConsensus: With its low production value and uninspired direction, Impostor comes off as a mixture of The Fugitive and Blade Runner, only not as good or as involving.

Title: American Adobo
Actors: Christopher De Leon, Dina Bonnevie, Ricky Davao, Cherry Pie Picache
tomatoConsensus: The characters and situations seem borrowed from overwrought sitcoms.

Plot: Kenichi and his uncle Shunsaku Ban must find the mystery behind robot girl Tima.
Language: Japanese, French, German, Italian, Spanish, English, Russian
Title: Metropolis
Writer: Osamu Tezuka (comic book), Katsuhiro Ôtomo (screenplay), Marc Handler (English version)
Actors: Yuka Imoto, Kei Kobayashi, Kôki Okada, Tarô Ishida
tomatoConsensus: A remarkable technical achievement, Metropolis' eye-popping visuals more than compensate for its relatively routine story.

Plot: A thirtysomething bank clerk from St Albans has his small-town life exploded by the arrival of his Russian mail-order bride.
Title: Birthday Girl
Actors: Nicole Kidman, Ben Chaplin, Vincent Cassel, Mathieu Kassovitz
tomatoConsensus: Kidman shows her range in this quirky movie, but the shift in tone from romantic comedy to thriller may leave viewers unsatisfied.

Plot: A modernized retelling of "MacBeth" set in 1970s suburban Pennsylvania. Joe McBeth, an unambitious hamburger stand employee, is driven to success by his scheming wife.
Title: Scotland, Pa.
Actors: James Le Gros, Maura Tierney, Christopher Walken, Kevin Corrigan
tomatoConsensus: Though it's not as good as it could have been, Scotland PA shows cleverness at utilizing its premise.

Plot: Five Vermont state troopers, avid pranksters with a knack for screwing up, try to save their jobs and out-do the local police department by solving a crime.
Title: Super Troopers
Writer: Jay Chandrasekhar, Kevin Heffernan, Steve Lemme, Paul Soter, Erik Stolhanske
Actors: André Vippolis, Joey Kern, Geoffrey Arend, Erik Stolhanske
tomatoConsensus: A more-miss -than-hit affair, Super Troopers will most likely appeal to those looking for something silly.

Plot: A group of old friends reminisce about their lives over the years after the death of one of their crew.
Title: Last Orders
Actors: Michael Caine, Tom Courtenay, David Hemmings, Bob Hoskins
tomatoConsensus: With a cast that includes some of the best acting talent in Britain, Last Orders is a rewarding character-driven ensemble piece.

Plot: Vietnam veteran Leon Barlow is struggling as a writer, and his personal life isn't much better. His unsympathetic ex-wife Marilyn doesn't approve of his visits with his two children, and he...
Title: Big Bad Love
Writer: Larry Brown (stories), James Howard (screenplay), Arliss Howard (screenplay)
Actors: Arliss Howard, Debra Winger, Paul Le Mat, Rosanna Arquette
tomatoConsensus: A boozy depiction of a struggling writer, Big Bad Love is too messy and self-indulgent.

Plot: A stressed father, a bride-to-be with a secret, a smitten event planner, and relatives from around the world create much ado about the preparations for an arranged marriage in India.
Title: Monsoon Wedding
Actors: Naseeruddin Shah, Lillete Dubey, Shefali Shetty, Vijay Raaz
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 6 wins & 11 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: An insightful, energetic blend of Hollywood and Bollywood styles, Monsoon Wedding is a colorful, exuberant celebration of modern-day India, family, love, and life.

Plot: Shane and June Brown are an American couple honeymooning in Paris in an effort to nurture their new life together, a life complicated by Shane's mysterious and frequent visits to a medical ...
Title: Trouble Every Day
Actors: Vincent Gallo, Tricia Vessey, Béatrice Dalle, Alex Descas
tomatoConsensus: An erotic thriller dulled by a messy narrative.

Plot: A woman searching for the perfect man instead discovers the perfect woman.
Title: Kissing Jessica Stein
Actors: Jennifer Westfeldt, Tovah Feldshuh, Esther Wurmfeld, Hillel Friedman
tomatoConsensus: A trite but refreshing and comical spin on nature of love.

Plot: A man confesses to an FBI agent his family's story of how his religious fanatic father's visions lead to a series of murders to destroy supposed "demons."
Title: Frailty
Actors: Bill Paxton, Matthew McConaughey, Powers Boothe, Matt O'Leary
tomatoConsensus: Creepy and disturbing, Frailty is well-crafted, low-key horror.

Plot: Semi-true story of the Hollywood murder that occurred at a star-studded gathering aboard William Randolph Hearst's yacht in 1924.
Title: The Cat's Meow
Actors: Kirsten Dunst, Edward Herrmann, Eddie Izzard, Cary Elwes
tomatoConsensus: The Cat's Meow is a deliciously evoked period piece and whodunit.

Plot: A woman is in love with a man in love with another woman, and all three have designs on a young man raised as an ape.
Title: Human Nature
Actors: Patricia Arquette, Rhys Ifans, Tim Robbins, Ken Magee
tomatoConsensus: As quirky as Being John Malkovich but not as funny, Human Nature feels too forced and unengaging.

Plot: A princess is determined to restore her homeland's throne to its rightful heir, a young prince with whom she falls in love.
Title: The Triumph of Love
Writer: Marivaux (play), Clare Peploe, Marilyn Goldin, Bernardo Bertolucci
Actors: Mira Sorvino, Rachael Stirling, Ben Kingsley, Jay Rodan
tomatoConsensus: Not as charming as it could have been, Triumph of Love plays too broadly and amounts to little more than a trifle.

Plot: Jason Voorhees returns with a new look, a new machete, and his same murderous attitude as he is awakened on a spaceship in the 25th century.
Title: Jason X
Actors: Kane Hodder, Jeff Geddis, Lexa Doig, David Cronenberg
tomatoConsensus: Jason goes to the future, but the story is still stuck in the past.

Plot: Documentary about the pioneering 1970s Zephyr skating team.
Title: Dogtown and Z-Boys
Actors: Sean Penn, Jay Adams, Tony Alva, Jeff Ament
tomatoConsensus: Dogtown and Z-Boys is a colorful, exhilarating look at the skateboarding subculture.

Plot: In 1950s Trinidad, a frustrated writer supports himself as a masseur--and soon becomes a revered mystic and politico.
Title: The Mystic Masseur
Actors: Om Puri, Aasif Mandvi, Ayesha Dharker, Jimi Mistry
tomatoConsensus: Though pretty to look at, The Mystic Masseur is too slow-paced and lacks narrative tension.

Plot: A young filmmaker in 1960s Paris juggles directing a cheesy sci-fi debacle, directing his own personal art film, coping with his crumbling relationship with his girlfriend, and a new-found infatuation with the sci-fi film's starlet.
Title: CQ
Actors: Jeremy Davies, Angela Lindvall, Élodie Bouchez, Gérard Depardieu
tomatoConsensus: CQ is a stylish and fun homage to campy 1960s flicks.

Plot: In New York City, the lives of a lawyer, an actuary, a house-cleaner, a professor and the people around them intersect as they ponder order and happiness in the face of life's cold unpredictability.
Title: Thirteen Conversations About One Thing
Actors: Matthew McConaughey, David Connolly, Joseph Siravo, A.D. Miles
tomatoConsensus: Thirteen Conversations About One Thing is an intelligent and poignant look at lives intersecting.

Actors: Ian Holm, Iben Hjejle, Tim McInnerny, Tom Watson

Plot: Self-esteem and insecurity are at the heart of this comedy about the relationship between a mother and her three confused daughters.
Title: Lovely & Amazing
Actors: Troy Ruptash, Emily Mortimer, Brenda Blethyn, Raven Goodwin

Plot: Two best friends grow up on the Isle of Wight and in Brighton in the 1970s and 1980s.
Title: Me Without You

Plot: A "normal" guy who is married to a hot actress gets worried that she is involved with her costar. This worry turns into jealousy and causes problems in their relationship. This is a story about trust and a comedy about the actions between men and women.
Title: My Wife Is an Actress

tomatoConsensus: My Wife is an Actress is a delightful, snappy romantic comedy.

Plot: Two people who have pledged never to fall in love again then discover each other in a gay bar.
Title: Never Again
Actors: Jeffrey Tambor, Jill Clayburgh, Caroline Aaron, Bill Duke
tomatoConsensus: The performances are excellent, but much of the story rings false.

Plot: Various lives converge on an isolated island, all connected by an author whose novel has become inextricably entwined with his own life.
Title: Sex and Lucia

tomatoConsensus: Beneath the gratuitous nudity lies a complex and visually striking movie.

Plot: Cletis Tout is a comedy about mistaken identities, a hit man who sees everything in terms of the movies and a twenty year old diamond heist.
Title: Who Is Cletis Tout?

tomatoConsensus: Cliched and endlessly self-referential, Who Is Cletis Tout? doesn't add anything original to the crime genre.

Plot: A failed novelist's inability to pay the bills strains relations with his wife and leads him to work at an escort service where he becomes entwined with a wealthy woman whose husband is a successful writer.

tomatoConsensus: This story about a gigolo isn't plausible or compelling enough.

tomatoConsensus: One of Jaglom's better films, Festival in Cannes is an enjoyable insider's take on the movie industry.

Plot: The wannabe sons of mobsters go to a remote town in the Midwest, and get themselves into more trouble than anyone could anticipate.
Title: Knockaround Guys

Plot: Ash must stop a hunter who forces the legendary Pokémon Celebi to help him destroy a forest.
Title: Pokémon 4: The Movie

Plot: An American master chemist plans to score big on a once in a lifetime drug deal. All does not go as planned and he is soon entangled in a web of deceit.
Title: Formula 51

tomatoConsensus: Filled with profanities, Formula 51 is a stylized and incoherent mess that doesn't add up to much.

Plot: An enigmatic tale of four incredibly lucky people whose lives are intertwined by destiny are subject to the laws of fate. They discover that they cannot afford to be without luck as they ...
Title: Intacto
Writer: Juan Carlos Fresnadillo, Andrés M. Koppel
Actors: Leonardo Sbaraglia, Eusebio Poncela, Mónica López, Antonio Dechent
tomatoConsensus: The plot gimmick is original, bolstered by stylishly intriguing setpieces.

Plot: A German Jewish refugee family moves to and adjusts to a farm life in 1930s Kenya.
Title: Nowhere in Africa

tomatoConsensus: A visually lovely epic with compelling, three-dimensional characters.

Plot: A series of overlapping stories about four suburban families dealing with different maladies. Esther Gold's life is consumed by caring for her comatose son; Jim Train is sent into a ...
Title: The Safety of Objects

Plot: A clueless boss has no idea what to do with his mundane office worker whose refusal of duties only gets worse each passing minute.
Title: Bartleby
Writer: Herman Melville (story "Bartleby the Scrivener"), Jonathan Parker (screenplay), Catherine DiNapoli (screenplay)
Actors: David Paymer, Crispin Glover, Glenne Headly, Maury Chaykin

Plot: A story about a man's personal struggle to victory in the 1971 Madison, Indiana hydro-plane regatta.
Title: Madison
Actors: Jim Caviezel, Jake Lloyd, Mary McCormack, Bruce Dern
tomatoConsensus: A pedictable and heavy-handed sports drama.

Plot: Emily Lindstrom, 14, is an aspiring concert violinist; she's spending the summer practicing for a big audition while her girlfriends are at camp. She's also got a thriving neighborhood ...
Title: Little Secrets
Actors: Evan Rachel Wood, Michael Angarano, David Gallagher, Vivica A. Fox
tomatoConsensus: Little Secrets is wholesome entertainment for the kids, but also rather bland.

Plot: A guidance counselor mistakenly sends out the wrong transcripts to Stanford University under the name of an over-achieving high schooler.
Title: Orange County
Actors: Colin Hanks, Jack Black, Schuyler Fisk, Bret Harrison

Plot: A rough-around-the-edges martial arts master seeks revenge for his parent's death.
Title: Kung Pow: Enter the Fist

tomatoConsensus: A short sketch's worth of jokes stretched into a full-length feature.

Plot: When a Miami dentist inherits a team of sled dogs, he's got to learn the trade or lose his pack to a crusty mountain man.

Plot: A young man, falsely imprisoned by his jealous "friend," escapes and uses a hidden treasure to exact his revenge.
Title: The Count of Monte Cristo
Actors: Jim Caviezel, Guy Pearce, Richard Harris, James Frain
tomatoConsensus: Though it may not reach for any new artistic heights, The Count of Monte Cristo is an old-fashioned yet enjoyable swashbuckler.

Title: The Mothman Prophecies
Actors: Richard Gere, David Eigenberg, Bob Tracey, Ron Emanuel
tomatoConsensus: A creepy thriller that poses more questions than it answers.

Plot: The story of two North Carolina teens, Landon Carter and Jamie Sullivan, who are thrown together after Landon gets into trouble and is made to do community service.

Plot: When geeky Ethan discovers three fellow students scamming the examination system, he blackmails them to win over the college's most popular girl.

tomatoConsensus: Another teen comedy with little on its mind but moving to the next gross-out gag, Slackers strains for laughs and features grating characters.

Plot: After a young boy's school essay erroneously finds its way into the hands of a Hollywood producer who turns the idea into a hit film, the boy travels to Los Angeles to claim his credit.

Plot: After his family is killed by a terrorist act, a firefighter goes in search of the one responsible.

Plot: The big thing in 2005 is a violent sport which can have some pretty serious consequences... like dying.

Title: Rollerball

Plot: Three childhood best friends, and a guy they just met, take a road trip across the country, finding themselves and their friendship in the process.

tomatoConsensus: A cliched and silly pop star vanity project, Crossroads is strictly for Britney fans only.

Plot: A law student becomes a lieutenant during World War II, is captured and asked to defend a black prisoner of war falsely accused of murder.

tomatoConsensus: Well-made and solidly acted, Hart's War is modestly compelling. However, the movie suffers from having too many subplots.

Plot: John Quincy Archibald takes a hospital emergency room hostage when his insurance won't cover his son's heart transplant.
Title: John Q

Plot: In London during World War II, this is the story of Wendy's daughter, Jane, who is kidnapped by Captain Hook and Peter Pan must come to the rescue.

Plot: A grieving doctor is being contacted by his late wife through his patients near death experiences.

Writer: Brandon Camp (story), Mike Thompson (story), David Seltzer (screenplay), Brandon Camp (screenplay), Mike Thompson (screenplay)
Actors: Kevin Costner, Susanna Thompson, Joe Morton, Ron Rifkin

Plot: The vampire Lestat becomes a rock star whose music wakes up the queen of all vampires.

Actors: Aaliyah, Stuart Townsend, Marguerite Moreau, Vincent Perez

Plot: The story of the first major battle of the American phase of the Vietnam War and the soldiers on both sides that fought it.

tomatoConsensus: The war cliches are laid on a bit thick, but the movie succeeds at putting a human face on soldiers of both sides in the Vietnam War.

Plot: A bounty hunter chases and catches suspects all over Miami . He ends up getting shot at and start to second guess his job as a bounty hunter . While he feels he need to be making more and ...

tomatoConsensus: A sloppy, poorly directed action-comedy, All About the Benjamins is too derivative and gratuitously violent.

Plot: Hoping to alter the events of the past, a 19th century inventor instead travels 800,000 years into the future, where he finds humankind divided into two warring races.

Plot: Set during the Ice Age, a sabertooth tiger, a sloth, and a wooly mammoth find a lost human infant, and they try to return him to his tribe.
Title: Ice Age
Writer: Michael J. Wilson (story), Michael Berg (screenplay), Michael J. Wilson (screenplay), Peter Ackerman (screenplay), James Bresnahan (additional story), Doug Compton (additional story), Mike Thurmeier (additional story), Jeff Siergey (additional story), Galen T. Chu (additional story), Xeth Feinberg (additional story)

tomatoConsensus: Even though Ice Age is treading over the same grounds as Monsters, Inc. and Shrek, it has enough wit and laughs to stand on its own.

Plot: A divorced woman and her diabetic daughter take refuge in their newly-purchased house's safe room, when three men break-in, searching for a missing fortune.

Plot: A Texas baseball coach makes the major league after agreeing to try out if his high school team made the playoffs.
Title: The Rookie

tomatoConsensus: A heart-warming sports flick, The Rookie greatly benefits from understated direction and the emotional honesty Dennis Quaid brings to the role of Jim Morris.

Plot: A young Greek woman falls in love with a non-Greek and struggles to get her family to accept him while she comes to terms with her heritage and cultural identity.

Plot: After a tragic incident, a man drifts into a world populated by thugs and speed junkies.

Plot: Bobby (one of the deuces gang) and the sister of a rival gang member fall in love.

Plot: A director is forced to work with his ex-wife, who left him for the boss of the studio bankrolling his new film. But the night before the first day of shooting, he develops a case of psychosomatic blindness.

Actors: Téa Leoni, Bob Dorian, Ivan Martin, Gregg Edelman
tomatoConsensus: Although Hollywood Ending contains some zany one-liners, its promising premise is far from developed.

Plot: When bitten by a genetically modified spider, a nerdy, shy, and awkward high school student gains spider-like abilities that he eventually must use to fight evil as a superhero after tragedy befalls his family.

Plot: A cynical, immature young man is taught how to act like a grown-up by a little boy.

Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 28 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: About a Boy benefits tremendously from Hugh Grant's layered performance, as well as a funny, moving story that tugs at the heartstrings without tilting into treacle.

Plot: Ten years after initially meeting, Anakin Skywalker shares a forbidden romance with Padmé, while Obi-Wan investigates an assassination attempt on the Senator and discovers a secret clone army crafted for the Jedi.

Actors: Ewan McGregor, Natalie Portman, Hayden Christensen, Christopher Lee
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 16 wins & 53 nominations.

Plot: After running away fails, a terrified woman (Jennifer Lopez) empowers herself in order to battle her abusive husband (Billy Campbell).

Plot: Two Los Angeles homicide detectives are dispatched to a northern town where the sun doesn't set to investigate the methodical murder of a local teen.

Writer: Hillary Seitz (screenplay), Nikolaj Frobenius, Erik Skjoldbjærg
Actors: Al Pacino, Martin Donovan, Oliver 'Ole' Zemen, Hilary Swank
tomatoConsensus: Driven by Pacino's performance, Insomnia is a smart and riveting psychological drama.

Plot: A wild stallion is captured by humans and slowly loses the will to resist training. Yet throughout his struggles for freedom, the stallion refuses to let go of the hope of one day returning home to his herd.
Title: Spirit: Stallion of the Cimarron
Actors: Matt Damon, James Cromwell, Daniel Studi, Chopper Bernet
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 19 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A visually stunning film that may be too predictable and politically correct for adults, but should serve children well.

Plot: CIA analyst Jack Ryan must thwart the plans of a terrorist faction that threatens to induce a catastrophic conflict between the United States and Russia's newly elected president by detonating a nuclear weapon at a football game in Baltimore.
Title: The Sum of All Fears

Actors: Ian Mongrain, Russell Bobbitt, James Cromwell, Ken Jenkins
tomatoConsensus: A slick and well-made thriller that takes on new weight due to the current political climate.

Plot: When "The Man" tries to derail a black candidate's presidential campaign, Undercover Brother and his fellow secret agents come to the rescue.

Actors: Eddie Griffin, Chris Kattan, Denise Richards, Aunjanue Ellis

Plot: When a Harvard-educated CIA agent is killed during an operation, the secret agency recruits his twin brother.

Plot: After years of mother-daughter tension, Siddalee receives a scrapbook detailing the wild adventures of the "Ya-Yas", her mother's girlhood friends.
Title: Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood

tomatoConsensus: Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood is more melodramatic than emotionally truthful, and uneven in its mixture of time periods, actresses, laughter and tears.

Plot: After a martini-induced rampage, a fantasy-prone young woman is placed under house arrest.
Title: Cherish
Actors: Brad Hunt, Robin Tunney, Liz Phair, Lindsay Crouse
tomatoConsensus: The different genres in Cherish don't mesh well, and the quirkiness sometimes feels too forced.

Plot: A man is picked up by a fishing boat, bullet-riddled and suffering from amnesia, before racing to elude assassins and regain his memory.
Title: The Bourne Identity
Writer: Tony Gilroy (screenplay), W. Blake Herron (screenplay), Robert Ludlum (novel)
Actors: Matt Damon, Franka Potente, Chris Cooper, Clive Owen
tomatoConsensus: Expertly blending genre formula with bursts of unexpected wit, The Bourne Identity is an action thriller that delivers -- and then some.

Plot: After an acrimonious break up, the Mystery Inc. gang are individually brought to an island resort to investigate strange goings on.
Title: Scooby-Doo

Plot: Two U.S. Marines in WWII are assigned to protect Navajo Marines who use their native language as an unbreakable radio cypher.
Title: Windtalkers

tomatoConsensus: The action sequences are expertly staged. Windtalkers, however, sinks under too many clichés and only superficially touches upon the story of the code talkers.

Plot: A basketball star is booted out of the NBA when his on-court antics go too far, so he poses as a woman and joins the WUBA.
Title: Juwanna Mann

tomatoConsensus: With its tired premise, Juwanna Mann's jokes fall flat.

Plot: A Hawaiian girl adopts an unusual pet who is actually a notorious extra-terrestrial fugitive from the law.
Title: Lilo & Stitch

Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 27 nominations.

Plot: In a future where a special police unit is able to arrest murderers before they commit their crimes, an officer from that unit is himself accused of a future murder.
Title: Minority Report
Writer: Philip K. Dick (short story), Scott Frank (screenplay), Jon Cohen (screenplay)

Plot: An idealistic prep school teacher attempts to redeem an incorrigible student.

Actors: Kevin Kline, Emile Hirsch, Embeth Davidtz, Rob Morrow

Actors: Ice Cube, Mike Epps, John Witherspoon, Don 'D.C.' Curry
tomatoConsensus: This Friday installment is more shapeless and stale than its predecessors.

Plot: While filming an advertisement, some extreme sports enthusiasts unwittingly stop a group of terrorists.

tomatoConsensus: The various stunts in Extreme Ops don't compensate for the inane storyline and bad dialogue.

Plot: A troubled psychologist is sent to investigate the crew of an isolated research station orbiting a bizarre planet.
Title: Solaris
Actors: George Clooney, Natascha McElhone, Viola Davis, Jeremy Davies
tomatoConsensus: Slow-moving, cerebral, and ambiguous, Solaris is not a movie for everyone, but it offers intriguing issues to ponder.

Plot: A Disney animated version of "Treasure Island". The only difference is that the film is set in outer space with alien worlds and other galactic wonders.
Title: Treasure Planet

Plot: A psychology student finds all her childhood fears and phobias becoming real after a traumatic event.

Plot: Mobster Paul Vitti is released into Dr. Ben Sobol's care, where only more chaos ensues.

Plot: A band director recruits a Harlem street drummer to play at a Southern university.

Plot: The Enterprise is diverted to the Romulan homeworld Romulus, supposedly because they want to negotiate a peace treaty.

Plot: A man upon retirement embarks on a journey to his estranged daughter's wedding only to discover more about himself and life than he ever expected.

Plot: While Frodo and Sam edge closer to Mordor with the help of the shifty Gollum, the divided fellowship makes a stand against Sauron's new ally, Saruman, and his hordes of Isengard.

Plot: Antwone Fisher, a young navy man, is forced to see a psychiatrist after a violent outburst against a fellow crewman. During the course of treatment a painful past is revealed and a new hope begins.

Plot: In 1863, Amsterdam Vallon returns to the Five Points area of New York City seeking revenge against Bill the Butcher, his father's killer.

Plot: The story of how the novel "Mrs. Dalloway" affects three generations of women, all of whom, in one way or another, have had to deal with suicide in their lives.

Plot: A Polish Jewish musician struggles to survive the destruction of the Warsaw ghetto of World War II.

Plot: A con man (Dillon) travels to Cambodia (also on the run from law enforcement in the U.S.) to collect his share in an insurance scam, but discovers more than he bargained for...

Plot: Three fraternal bank robbers languishing in jail, discover a profitable (if not dodgy) way to spend their time. Crime can most certainly pay, if you "know wot I mean?" However when sex and ...

Plot: A man blinded by toxic waste which also enhanced his remaining senses fights crime as an acrobatic martial arts superhero.
