tomatoConsensus: Tries to be high-minded, but in the end, it's just a stylish action movie.

Plot: An FBI deep-woods tracker captures a trained assassin who has made a sport of hunting humans.
Title: The Hunted
Writer: David Griffiths, Peter Griffiths, Art Monterastelli
Actors: Tommy Lee Jones, Benicio Del Toro, Connie Nielsen, Leslie Stefanson
tomatoConsensus: An all too familiar chase movie that's not worth the talents involved.

Plot: A young man with an unusual connection to rats uses them at his own sociopathic will.
Title: Willard
Writer: Glen Morgan (screenplay), Gilbert Ralston, Stephen Gilbert (book)
Actors: Crispin Glover, R. Lee Ermey, Laura Harring, Jackie Burroughs
tomatoConsensus: In this creepy story of a man and his rodents, Glover seems born to play the oddball title character.

Plot: Friends on a camping trip discover that the town they're vacationing in is being plagued in an unusual fashion by parasitic aliens from outer space.
Title: Dreamcatcher
Writer: Stephen King (novel), William Goldman (screenplay), Lawrence Kasdan (screenplay)
Actors: Morgan Freeman, Thomas Jane, Jason Lee, Damian Lewis
tomatoConsensus: An incoherent and overly long creature feature.

Plot: When Piglet comes up missing his Hundred Acre Wood friends use Piglet's own Book of Memories to find him, discovering along the way just how big a role he's played in their lives.
Title: Piglet's Big Movie
Writer: Brian Hohlfeld (screenplay), A.A. Milne (books), Ted Henning (additional screenplay material)
Actors: John Fiedler, Jim Cummings, Andre Stojka, Kath Soucie
tomatoConsensus: Wholesome and charming entertainment for young children.

Plot: A small-town woman tries to achieve her goal of becoming a flight attendant.
Title: View from the Top
Actors: Gwyneth Paltrow, Christina Applegate, Mark Ruffalo, Candice Bergen
tomatoConsensus: Uneven in tone and badly edited, A View From the Top wastes the talents of its cast and condescends to its characters.

Plot: A DEA agent investigates the disappearance of a legendary Army ranger drill sergeant and several of his cadets during a training exercise gone severely awry.
Title: Basic
Actors: John Travolta, Connie Nielsen, Samuel L. Jackson, Tim Daly
tomatoConsensus: Basic gets so needlessly convoluted in its plot twists that the viewer eventually loses interest.

Plot: The only way to save Earth from catastrophe is to drill down to the core and set it spinning again.
Title: The Core
Actors: Christopher Shyer, Ray Galletti, Eileen Pedde, Rekha Sharma
tomatoConsensus: A B-movie with its tongue planted firmly in cheek, The Core is so unintentionally (intentionally?) bad that it's a hoot.

Plot: When a presidential candidate dies unexpectedly in the middle of the campaign, Washington, D.C. alderman, Mays Gilliam is unexpectedly picked as his replacement.
Title: Head of State
Actors: Chris Rock, Bernie Mac, Dylan Baker, Nick Searcy
tomatoConsensus: Head of State squanders its potentially ripe premise with watered-down satire and formulaic gags.

Plot: An American teenager learns that her father is a wealthy British politician running for office. Although she is eager to find him, she realizes it could cause a scandal and cost him the election.
Title: What a Girl Wants
Writer: William Douglas-Home (play), William Douglas-Home, Jenny Bicks (screenplay), Elizabeth Chandler (screenplay)
Actors: Amanda Bynes, Colin Firth, Kelly Preston, Eileen Atkins
tomatoConsensus: Little girls will definitely enjoy it, but it's too syrupy and predictable for adults.

Plot: A man known as Diablo emerges to head a drug cartel after the previous leader is imprisoned.
Title: A Man Apart
Actors: Vin Diesel, Larenz Tate, Timothy Olyphant, Geno Silva
tomatoConsensus: Action and drama elements don't mix well in this clichéd actioner.

Plot: Documentary on comedian Eddie Griffin who heads back home to a family reunion, which includes two uncles - one a porn director and the other an ex-pimp.
Title: DysFunktional Family
Actors: Eddie Griffin, Joe Howard, Matthew Brent, Robert Noble
tomatoConsensus: The humor is more profane and offensive than funny.

Plot: Dave Buznik is a businessman who is wrongly sentenced to an anger-management program, where he meets an aggressive instructor.
Title: Anger Management
Actors: Adam Sandler, Jack Nicholson, Marisa Tomei, Luis Guzmán
tomatoConsensus: Thought not without its funny moments, Anger Management is ultimately stale and disappointingly one-note, especially considering its capable cast.

Plot: James Cameron and Bill Paxton, director and actor of the 1997 film Titanic, travel to the final undersea resting place of the ill-fated ship of dreams.
Title: Ghosts of the Abyss
Actors: Bill Paxton, John Broadwater, Lori Johnston, Charles Pellegrino
tomatoConsensus: The underwater footage is both beautiful and awe-inspiring.

Plot: Two teenage couples traveling across the backwoods of Texas searching for urban legends of murder end up as prisoners of a bizarre and sadistic backwater family of serial killers.
Title: House of 1000 Corpses
Actors: Sid Haig, William Bassett, Karen Black, Erin Daniels
tomatoConsensus: There's an abundance of gore in this derivative horror movie, but little sense or wit.

Plot: Based on the very underground comic book, a Tibetan monk becomes a mentor to a young street kid whom he can teach to protect a scroll.
Title: Bulletproof Monk
Actors: Yun-Fat Chow, Seann William Scott, Jaime King, Karel Roden
tomatoConsensus: Venerable action star Chow Yun-Fat is the only saving grace in this silly action flick that more often than not resembles a commercial in style.

Plot: Mockumentary captures the reunion of 1960s folk trio the Folksmen as they prepare for a show at The Town Hall to memorialize a recently deceased concert promoter.
Title: A Mighty Wind
Actors: Jim Moret, Stuart Luce, Mary Gross, Marty Belafsky
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 24 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though not as uproariously funny as Guest's previous movies, A Mighty Wind is also more heartfelt.

Plot: A wrongfully convicted boy is sent to a brutal desert detention camp where he joins the job of digging holes for some mysterious reason.
Title: Holes
Actors: Sigourney Weaver, Jon Voight, Tim Blake Nelson, Shia LaBeouf
tomatoConsensus: Faithful to its literary source, this is imaginative, intelligent family entertainment.

Plot: A senator arranges for his son, a rich white kid who fancies himself black, to be kidnapped by a couple of black actors pretending to be murderers to try and shock him out of his plans to become a rapper.
Title: Malibu's Most Wanted
Writer: Fax Bahr, Adam Small, Jamie Kennedy, Nick Swardson
Actors: Jamie Kennedy, Taye Diggs, Anthony Anderson, Regina Hall
tomatoConsensus: There are some laughs, but not enough to sustain the running time.

Plot: Jake Vig (Burns) is a consummate grifter about to pull his biggest con yet, one set to avenge his friend's murder. But his last scam backfired, leaving him indebted to a mob boss (Hoffman) and his enforcer.
Title: Confidence
Actors: Edward Burns, Rachel Weisz, Morris Chestnut, Leland Orser
tomatoConsensus: While it may not be the best con in town, the movie still manages to entertain with its colorful cast.

Plot: Stranded at a desolate Nevada motel during a nasty rain-storm, ten strangers become acquainted with each other when they realize that they're being killed off one by one.
Title: Identity
Actors: John Cusack, Ray Liotta, Amanda Peet, John Hawkes
tomatoConsensus: Identity is a film that will divide audiences -- the twists of its plot will either impress or exasperate you.

Plot: This is the story of a dysfunctional New York family, and their attempts to reconcile.
Title: It Runs in the Family
Actors: Michael Douglas, Kirk Douglas, Rory Culkin, Cameron Douglas
tomatoConsensus: Despite its gimmick casting, the movie ultimately goes nowhere.

Plot: Sixteen American college students drink, flirt, fight and canoodle during their Spring Break vacation in Cancun, Mexico.
Title: The Real Cancun
Actors: Benjamin Fletcher, Nicole Frilot, Roxanne Frilot, David Ingber
tomatoConsensus: The footage is predictable and rather tame, and most of the people are uninteresting.

Plot: Lizzie McGuire has graduated from middle school and takes a trip to Rome, Italy with her class. And what was supposed to be only a normal trip, becomes a teenager's dream come true.
Title: The Lizzie McGuire Movie
Writer: Susan Estelle Jansen, Ed Decter, John J. Strauss, Terri Minsky (characters)
Actors: Hilary Duff, Adam Lamberg, Hallie Todd, Robert Carradine
tomatoConsensus: Harmless piece of fluff that ought to satisfy fans of the TV show.

Plot: The X-Men band together to find a mutant assassin who has made an attempt on the President's life, while the Mutant Academy is attacked by military forces.
Title: X-Men 2
Writer: Zak Penn (story), David Hayter (story), Bryan Singer (story), Michael Dougherty (screenplay), Dan Harris (screenplay), David Hayter (screenplay)
Actors: Patrick Stewart, Hugh Jackman, Ian McKellen, Halle Berry
tomatoConsensus: Tightly scripted, solidly acted, and impressively ambitious, X2: X-Men United is bigger and better than its predecessor -- and a benchmark for comic sequels in general.

Plot: A bank manager with: (a) a gambling problem and (b) access to a multimillion dollar account gets into a messy situation. Based on the story of the largest one-man bank fraud in Canadian history.
Title: Owning Mahowny
Actors: Philip Seymour Hoffman, Minnie Driver, John Hurt, Maury Chaykin
tomatoConsensus: This story of addiction may lack the typical flash and glamour, but Hoffman makes Mahowny compelling.

Plot: Two men get laid off and have to become stay-at-home dads when they can't find jobs. This inspires them to open their own day-care center.
Title: Daddy Day Care
Actors: Eddie Murphy, Jeff Garlin, Steve Zahn, Regina King
tomatoConsensus: Daddy Day Care does its job of babysitting the tots. Anyone older will probably be bored.

Plot: Quiet, unassuming Adam is changing in a major way, thanks to his new girlfriend, art student Evelyn. Adam's friends are a little freaked by the transformation.
Title: The Shape of Things
Actors: Gretchen Mol, Paul Rudd, Rachel Weisz, Frederick Weller
tomatoConsensus: LaBute returns to his earlier themes of cruelty in relationships, and the results hit hard.

Plot: Neo and the rebel leaders estimate that they have 72 hours until 250,000 probes discover Zion and destroy it and its inhabitants. During this, Neo must decide how he can save Trinity from a dark fate in his dreams.
Title: The Matrix Reloaded
Writer: Lilly Wachowski, Lana Wachowski, Lilly Wachowski (characters), Lana Wachowski (characters)
Actors: Ray Anthony, Christine Anu, Andy Arness, Alima Ashton-Sheibu
tomatoConsensus: Though its heady themes are a departure from its predecessor, The Matrix Reloaded is a worthy sequel packed with popcorn-friendly thrills.

Plot: A guy who complains about God too often is given almighty powers to teach him how difficult it is to run the world.
Title: Bruce Almighty
Writer: Steve Koren (story), Mark O'Keefe (story), Steve Koren (screenplay), Mark O'Keefe (screenplay), Steve Oedekerk (screenplay)
Actors: Jim Carrey, Morgan Freeman, Jennifer Aniston, Philip Baker Hall
tomatoConsensus: Carrey is hilarious in the slapstick scenes, but Bruce Almighty gets bogged down in treacle.

Plot: Right before his daughter's wedding, a mild-mannered foot doctor discovers that his future son-in-law's father is a free-wheeling international spy.
Title: The In-Laws
Writer: Andrew Bergman (screenplay), Nat Mauldin (screenplay), Ed Solomon (screenplay)
Actors: Michael Douglas, Michael Bodnar, Vladimir Radian, Robin Tunney
tomatoConsensus: Bigger and slicker than the original, but not necessarily better.

Plot: After his son is captured in the Great Barrier Reef and taken to Sydney, a timid clownfish sets out on a journey to bring him home.
Title: Finding Nemo
Writer: Andrew Stanton (original story by), Andrew Stanton (screenplay), Bob Peterson (screenplay), David Reynolds (screenplay)
Actors: Albert Brooks, Ellen DeGeneres, Alexander Gould, Willem Dafoe
tomatoConsensus: Breathtakingly lovely and grounded by the stellar efforts of a well-chosen cast, Finding Nemo adds another beautifully crafted gem to Pixar's crown.

Plot: After being betrayed and left for dead in Italy, Charlie Croker and his team plan an elaborate gold heist against their former ally.
Title: The Italian Job
Writer: Troy Kennedy-Martin, Donna Powers (screenplay), Wayne Powers (screenplay)
Actors: Mark Wahlberg, Charlize Theron, Donald Sutherland, Jason Statham
tomatoConsensus: Despite some iffy plot elements, The Italian Job succeeds in delivering an entertaining modern take on the original 1969 heist film, thanks to a charismatic cast.

Plot: Six people find themselves trapped in the woods of West Virginia, hunted down by "cannibalistic mountain men grossly disfigured through generations of in-breeding."
Title: Wrong Turn
Actors: Desmond Harrington, Eliza Dushku, Emmanuelle Chriqui, Jeremy Sisto
tomatoConsensus: An unremarkable slasher flick that fails to distinguished itself from others of its ilk.

Plot: Former cop Brian O'Conner is called upon to bust a dangerous criminal and he recruits the help of a former childhood friend and street racer who has a chance to redeem himself.
Title: 2 Fast 2 Furious
Writer: Gary Scott Thompson (characters), Michael Brandt (story), Derek Haas (story), Gary Scott Thompson (story), Michael Brandt (screenplay), Derek Haas (screenplay)
Actors: Paul Walker, Tyrese Gibson, Eva Mendes, Cole Hauser
tomatoConsensus: Beautiful people and beautiful cars in a movie that won't tax the brain cells.

Plot: Set back in the 80s when Harry met Lloyd in high school where they cross paths with a mean principal and a bunch of other outcasts much like themselves.
Title: Dumb and Dumberer: When Harry Met Lloyd
Writer: Peter Farrelly (characters), Bennett Yellin (characters), Bobby Farrelly (characters), Robert Brener (story), Robert Brener (screenplay), Troy Miller (screenplay)
Actors: Timothy Stack, Mimi Rogers, Wayne Federman, Lucas Gregory
tomatoConsensus: This lame prequel induces more groans than laughs. Rent the original instead.

Plot: A waitress from Texas and a college student from Pennsylvania meet during spring break in Fort Lauderdale, Florida and come together through their shared love of singing.
Title: From Justin to Kelly
Actors: Kelly Clarkson, Justin Guarini, Katherine Bailess, Anika Noni Rose
tomatoConsensus: A notorious stinker, From Justin To Kelly features banal songs, a witless plot, and non-existent chemistry between its American Idol-sanctioned leads.

Plot: Two LAPD detectives who moonlight in other fields investigate the murder of an up-and-coming rap group.
Title: Hollywood Homicide
Actors: Harrison Ford, Josh Hartnett, Lena Olin, Bruce Greenwood
tomatoConsensus: Hollywood Homicide suffers from too many subplots and not enough laughs.

Plot: The Rugrats get tangled in an exotic adventure, where they're helped by the Thornberrys, a family that travels the world making nature documentaries.
Title: Rugrats Go Wild
Actors: Elizabeth Daily, Nancy Cartwright, Kath Soucie, Dionne Quan
tomatoConsensus: The Rugrats franchise has gone from fresh to formulaic.

Plot: A writer must turn out a novel in thirty days or face the wrath of loan sharks.
Title: Alex & Emma
Actors: Luke Wilson, Derek Barbosa, Lobo Sebastian, Rob Reiner
tomatoConsensus: A dull and unfunny comedy where the leads fail to generate any sparks.

Plot: The Angels investigate a series of murders which occur after the theft of a witness protection profile database.
Title: Charlie's Angels: Full Throttle
Writer: Ivan Goff (television series), Ben Roberts (television series), John August (story), John August (screenplay), Cormac Wibberley (screenplay), Marianne Wibberley (screenplay)
Actors: Cameron Diaz, Drew Barrymore, Lucy Liu, Bernie Mac
tomatoConsensus: Eye candy for those who don't require a movie to have a plot or for it to make sense.

Plot: Bruce Banner, a genetics researcher with a tragic past, suffers an accident that causes him to transform into a raging green monster when he gets angry.
Title: Hulk
Writer: Stan Lee (Marvel comic book character), Jack Kirby (Marvel comic book character), James Schamus (story), John Turman (screenplay), Michael France (screenplay), James Schamus (screenplay)
Actors: Eric Bana, Jennifer Connelly, Sam Elliott, Josh Lucas
tomatoConsensus: While Ang Lee's ambitious film earns marks for style and an attempt at dramatic depth, there's ultimately too much talking and not enough smashing.

Plot: Elle Woods heads to Washington D.C. to join the staff of a congresswoman in order to pass a bill to ban animal testing.
Title: Legally Blonde 2: Red, White & Blonde
Writer: Amanda Brown (characters), Eve Ahlert (story), Dennis Drake (story), Kate Kondell (story), Kate Kondell (screenplay)
Actors: Reese Witherspoon, Sally Field, Regina King, Jennifer Coolidge
tomatoConsensus: This blonde joke is less funny the second time around.

Plot: The sailor of legend is framed by the goddess Eris for the theft of the Book of Peace, and must travel to her realm at the end of the world to retrieve it and save the life of his childhood friend Prince Proteus.
Title: Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas
Actors: Brad Pitt, Catherine Zeta-Jones, Michelle Pfeiffer, Joseph Fiennes
tomatoConsensus: Competent, but not magical.

Plot: A cybernetic warrior from a post-apocalyptic future travels back in time to protect a 19-year old drifter and his future wife from a most advanced robotic assassin and to ensure they both survive a nuclear attack.
Title: Terminator 3: Rise of the Machines
Writer: James Cameron (characters), Gale Anne Hurd (characters), John Brancato (story), Michael Ferris (story), Tedi Sarafian (story), John Brancato (screenplay), Michael Ferris (screenplay)
Actors: Arnold Schwarzenegger, Nick Stahl, Claire Danes, Kristanna Loken
tomatoConsensus: Although T3 never reaches the heights of the second movie, it is a welcome addition to the Terminator franchise.

Plot: A British mystery author visits her publisher's home in the South of France, where her interaction with his unusual daughter sets off some touchy dynamics.
Title: Swimming Pool
Writer: François Ozon (screenplay), Emmanuèle Bernheim, Sionann O'Neill (translation: English)
Actors: Charlotte Rampling, Ludivine Sagnier, Charles Dance, Jean-Marie Lamour
tomatoConsensus: A sensual thriller with two engaging performers demanding our undivided attention.

Plot: Blacksmith Will Turner teams up with eccentric pirate "Captain" Jack Sparrow to save his love, the governor's daughter, from Jack's former pirate allies, who are now undead.
Title: Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl
Writer: Ted Elliott (screen story), Terry Rossio (screen story), Stuart Beattie (screen story), Jay Wolpert (screen story), Ted Elliott (screenplay), Terry Rossio (screenplay)
Actors: Johnny Depp, Geoffrey Rush, Orlando Bloom, Keira Knightley
Awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 31 wins & 88 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: May leave you exhausted like the theme park ride that inspired it; however, you'll have a good time when it's over.

Plot: In an alternate Victorian Age world, a group of famous contemporary fantasy, SF and adventure characters team up on a secret mission.
Title: The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen
Writer: Alan Moore (comic books), Kevin O'Neill (comic books), James Robinson (screenplay)
Actors: Sean Connery, Naseeruddin Shah, Peta Wilson, Tony Curran
tomatoConsensus: Just ordinary. LXG is a great premise ruined by poor execution.

Plot: A love story set in 1930s England that follows 17-year-old Cassandra Mortmain, and the fortunes of her eccentric family, struggling to survive in a decaying English castle.
Title: I Capture the Castle
Actors: Romola Garai, Sophie Stuckey, Bill Nighy, Helena Little
tomatoConsensus: A handsome and charming adaptation of the novel.

Plot: Set in 1955, the residents of a small Montana community are forced to move their homes to make way for a new dam.
Title: Northfork
Actors: James Woods, Nick Nolte, Douglas Sebern, Claire Forlani
tomatoConsensus: Visually poetic, but may be too dramatically inert for some.

Plot: Two loose-cannon narcotics cops investigate the flow of Ecstasy into Florida.
Title: Bad Boys II
Writer: George Gallo (characters), Marianne Wibberley (story), Cormac Wibberley (story), Ron Shelton (story), Ron Shelton (screenplay), Jerry Stahl (screenplay)
Actors: Martin Lawrence, Will Smith, Jordi Mollà, Gabrielle Union
tomatoConsensus: Two and a half hours of explosions and witless banter.

Plot: A teenager (Moore), disillusioned by too many examples of love gone wrong, refuses to believe that true love exists. Then this new guy (Ford) comes along...
Title: How to Deal
Actors: Mandy Moore, Allison Janney, Trent Ford, Alexandra Holden
tomatoConsensus: Soap opera for teens.

Plot: After a sudden attack on the MI5, Johnny English, Britain's most confident yet unintelligent spy, becomes Britain's only spy.
Title: Johnny English
Writer: Neal Purvis, Robert Wade, William Davies
Actors: Rowan Atkinson, Tasha de Vasconcelos, Ben Miller, Greg Wise
tomatoConsensus: A tame spy spoof that elicits infrequent chuckles.

Plot: A singer, whose career has gone on a downward spiral, is forced to make a comeback to the performance stage for a benefit concert.
Title: Masked and Anonymous
Actors: Bob Dylan, Jeff Bridges, Penélope Cruz, John Goodman
tomatoConsensus: Unintelligible and self-indulgent Bob Dylan vehicle.

Plot: Adventuress Lara Croft goes on a quest to save the mythical Pandora's Box before an evil scientist and recruits a former Marine turned mercenary to assist her.
Title: Lara Croft Tomb Raider: The Cradle of Life
Writer: Dean Georgaris (screenplay), Steven E. de Souza (story), James V. Hart (story)
Actors: Angelina Jolie, Gerard Butler, Ciarán Hinds, Chris Barrie
tomatoConsensus: Though the sequel is an improvement over the first movie, it's still lacking in thrills.

Title: Seabiscuit
Actors: David McCullough, Jeff Bridges, Paul Vincent O'Connor, Chris Cooper
Awards: Nominated for 7 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 36 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A life-affirming, if saccharine, epic treatment of a spirit-lifting figure in sports history.

Plot: After a series of Broadway flops, songwriter Bert Hanley (Dixon) goes to work at a musical camp for young performers. Inspired by the kids, he finds an opportunity to regain success by staging an altogether new production.
Title: Camp
Actors: Daniel Letterle, Joanna Chilcoat, Robin de Jesus, Steven Cutts
tomatoConsensus: Campy comedy that squeaks by on its charms.

Plot: It's the wedding of Jim and Michelle and the gathering of their families and friends, including Jim's old friends from high school and Michelle's little sister.
Title: American Wedding
Actors: Jason Biggs, Seann William Scott, Alyson Hannigan, Eddie Kaye Thomas
tomatoConsensus: Raunchier and even more gross than the first two American Pies, American Wedding ought to please fans of the series.

Plot: An overworked mother and her daughter do not get along. When they switch bodies, each is forced to adapt to the other's life for one freaky Friday.
Title: Freaky Friday
Writer: Mary Rodgers (novel), Heather Hach (screenplay), Leslie Dixon (screenplay)
Actors: Jamie Lee Curtis, Lindsay Lohan, Mark Harmon, Harold Gould
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 9 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Jamie Lee Curtis and Lindsay Lohan charm in Mark Waters' nicely pitched -- and Disney's second -- remake of the 1976 hit.

Plot: An imprisoned drug kingpin offers a huge cash reward to anyone that can break him out of police custody and only the LAPD's Special Weapons and Tactics team can prevent it.
Title: S.W.A.T.
Writer: Robert Hamner (characters), Ron Mita (story), Jim McClain (story), David Ayer (screenplay), David McKenna (screenplay)
Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Colin Farrell, Michelle Rodriguez, LL Cool J
tomatoConsensus: A competent, but routine police thriller.

Title: The Divorce
Writer: Diane Johnson (novel), Ruth Prawer Jhabvala (screenplay), James Ivory (screenplay)
Actors: Kate Hudson, Jean-Marie Lhomme, Naomi Watts, Esmée Buchet-Deàk
tomatoConsensus: A mixed bag of uneven tones that feels flat.

Plot: Surfers and secret spots from around the world are profiled in this documentary.
Title: Step Into Liquid
Actors: Robert August, Rochelle Ballard, Shawn Barron, Layne Beachley
tomatoConsensus: A perfect companion piece to The Endless Summer.

Plot: Freddy Krueger and Jason Voorhees return to terrorize the teenage population. Except this time, they're out to get each other, too.
Title: Freddy vs. Jason
Writer: Wes Craven (characters), Victor Miller (characters), Damian Shannon, Mark Swift
Actors: Robert Englund, Ken Kirzinger, Monica Keena, Jason Ritter
tomatoConsensus: Fans of the two horror franchises will enjoy this showdown. But for everyone else, it's the same old slice and dice.

Plot: Four skaters follow their idol on his summer tour in an attempt to get noticed, get sponsored, and become stars themselves.
Title: Grind
Actors: Mike Vogel, Vince Vieluf, Adam Brody, Joey Kern
tomatoConsensus: Mediocre skateboard stunts are padded by a half-baked plot and one-dimensional characters.

Plot: A former gunslinger is forced to take up arms again when he and his cattle crew are threatened by a corrupt lawman.
Title: Open Range
Actors: Robert Duvall, Kevin Costner, Annette Bening, Michael Gambon
tomatoConsensus: Greatly benefiting from the tremendous chemistry between Kevin Costner and Robert Duvall, Open Range is a sturdy modern Western with classic roots.

Plot: A grown-up woman, who kept her childish instincts and behavior, starts working as a nanny of a 8-year-old girl, who actually acts like an adult. But in the end everything turns to its right places.
Title: Uptown Girls
Writer: Julia Dahl (screenplay), Mo Ogrodnik (screenplay), Lisa Davidowitz (screenplay), Allison Jacobs (story)
Actors: Brittany Murphy, Dakota Fanning, Marley Shelton, Donald Faison
tomatoConsensus: With two obnoxious lead characters and an uneven screenplay, Uptown Girls fails to charm.

Plot: An original mix of fiction and reality illuminates the life of comic book hero everyman Harvey Pekar.
Title: American Splendor
Writer: Harvey Pekar (comic book series American Splendor), Joyce Brabner (comic book series Our Cancer Year), Shari Springer Berman, Robert Pulcini
Actors: Chris Ambrose, Joey Krajcar, Josh Hutcherson, Cameron Carter
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 31 wins & 47 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Exhilarating both stylistically and for its entertaining, moving portrayal of an everyman, American Splendor is a portrait of a true underground original.

Plot: A government agent trains Cody Banks in the ways of covert operations that require younger participants.
Title: Agent Cody Banks
Writer: Ashley Miller (screenplay), Zack Stentz (screenplay), Scott Alexander (screenplay), Larry Karaszewski (screenplay), Jeffrey Jurgensen (story)
Actors: Frankie Muniz, Hilary Duff, Angie Harmon, Keith David
tomatoConsensus: Should satisfy young teens, but offers nothing new for those who are familiar with the formula.

Plot: A Jewish-American Princess is forced to take control of a hard-core hip-hop record label and tries to rein the one of the label's most controversial rappers.
Title: Marci X
Actors: Lisa Kudrow, Damon Wayans, Richard Benjamin, Jane Krakowski
tomatoConsensus: The material is too thin for feature-length and the jokes are socially outdated and clueless.

Plot: A Hong Kong detective suffers a fatal accident involving a mysterious medallion and is transformed into an immortal warrior with superhuman powers.
Title: The Medallion
Writer: Alfred Cheung (story and original characters), Bennett Davlin, Alfred Cheung, Gordon Chan, Paul Wheeler, Bey Logan
Actors: Jackie Chan, Lee Evans, Claire Forlani, Julian Sands
tomatoConsensus: The use of special effects diminishes some of Chan's appeal in this disposable picture.

Plot: Set a few days after the original, a championship basketball team's bus is attacked by The Creeper, the winged, flesh-eating terror, on the last day of his 23-day feeding frenzy.
Title: Jeepers Creepers II
Actors: Ray Wise, Jonathan Breck, Garikayi Mutambirwa, Eric Nenninger
tomatoConsensus: Jeepers Creepers 2 is competently made, but it doesn't have the scares of the original.

Plot: A thirty-something former child star hires a foster family to re-create the childhood he never had.
Title: Dickie Roberts: Former Child Star
Actors: David Spade, Mary McCormack, Craig Bierko, Scott Terra
tomatoConsensus: A so-so David Spade comedy with a few laughs.

Plot: A young priest is sent to Rome to investigate the troubling death of the head of his order.
Title: The Order
Actors: Heath Ledger, Shannyn Sossamon, Benno Fürmann, Mark Addy
tomatoConsensus: A religious thriller that's more lethargic and silly than thrilling.

Plot: Based on the true story of Michael Alig, a Club Kid party organizer whose life was sent spiraling down when he bragged on television about killing his drug dealer and roommate.
Title: Party Monster
Writer: Fenton Bailey, Randy Barbato, James St. James (book)
Actors: Seth Green, Macaulay Culkin, Diana Scarwid, Dillon Woolley
tomatoConsensus: The lurid display of camp soon turns tedious.

Plot: A phobic con artist and his protégé are on the verge of pulling off a lucrative swindle when the former's teenage daughter arrives unexpectedly.
Title: Matchstick Men
Writer: Eric Garcia (book), Nicholas Griffin (screenplay), Ted Griffin (screenplay)
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Sam Rockwell, Alison Lohman, Bruce Altman
tomatoConsensus: Breezy and well-acted, Matchstick Men focuses more on the characters than on the con.

Plot: Hitman "El Mariachi" becomes involved in international espionage involving a psychotic CIA agent and a corrupt Mexican general.
Title: Once Upon a Time in Mexico
Actors: Antonio Banderas, Salma Hayek, Johnny Depp, Mickey Rourke
tomatoConsensus: Violent, pulpy, loopy fun, with Depp stealing the show.

Plot: A faded movie star and a neglected young woman form an unlikely bond after crossing paths in Tokyo.
Title: Lost in Translation
Actors: Scarlett Johansson, Bill Murray, Akiko Takeshita, Kazuyoshi Minamimagoe
tomatoConsensus: Effectively balancing humor and subtle pathos, Sofia Coppola crafts a moving, melancholy story that serves as a showcase for both Bill Murray and Scarlett Johansson.

Plot: Jerry Falk learns a lesson the hard way when he falls head over heels in love with a beautiful but flighty girl, Amanda.
Title: Anything Else
Actors: Woody Allen, Jason Biggs, Fisher Stevens, Anthony Arkin
tomatoConsensus: Too many elements from better Woody Allen films are being recycled here.

Plot: A New York advertising executive travels to a small Southern town to collect an inheritance but finds he must create a gospel choir and lead it to success before he can collect.
Title: The Fighting Temptations
Writer: Elizabeth Hunter (story), Elizabeth Hunter (screenplay), Saladin K. Patterson (screenplay)
Actors: Nigel Washington, Chloe Bailey, Demetress Long, Ann Nesby
tomatoConsensus: The music is the only saving grace in this predictable and eager-to-please comedy.

Plot: A coming-of-age story about a shy, young boy sent by his irresponsible mother to spend the summer with his wealthy, eccentric uncles in Texas.
Title: Secondhand Lions
Actors: Michael Caine, Robert Duvall, Haley Joel Osment, Kyra Sedgwick
tomatoConsensus: A wholesome but schmaltzy movie.

Plot: Selene, a beautiful warrior, is entrenched in a war between the vampire and werewolf races. Although she is aligned with the vampires, she falls in love with Michael, a human who is sought by werewolves for unknown reasons.
Title: Underworld
Writer: Kevin Grevioux (story), Len Wiseman (story), Danny McBride (story), Danny McBride (screenplay)
Actors: Kate Beckinsale, Scott Speedman, Michael Sheen, Shane Brolly
tomatoConsensus: Though stylish to look at, Underworld is tedious and derivative.

Plot: Six American women who planned on travelling to South America to adopt babies are forced, by law, to live there.
Title: Casa de los babys
Actors: Angelina Peláez, Lizzie Curry Martinez, Vanessa Martinez, Amanda Álvarez
tomatoConsensus: Well-acted and thought provoking, if not completely satisfying.

Plot: A tough aspiring chef is hired to bring home a mobster's son from the Amazon but becomes involved in the fight against an oppressive town operator and the search for a legendary treasure.
Title: The Rundown
Writer: R.J. Stewart (story), R.J. Stewart (screenplay), James Vanderbilt (screenplay)
Actors: Dwayne Johnson, Seann William Scott, Rosario Dawson, Christopher Walken
tomatoConsensus: The Rundown doesn't break any new ground, but it's a smart, funny buddy action picture with terrific comic chemistry between Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson and Seann William Scott.

Plot: A writer impulsively buys a villa in Tuscany in order to change her life.
Language: English, Italian, Polish, French, Spanish, German
Title: Under the Tuscan Sun
Writer: Frances Mayes (book), Audrey Wells (screen story), Audrey Wells (screenplay)
Actors: Diane Lane, Sandra Oh, Lindsay Duncan, Raoul Bova
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though formulaic and superficial, Under the Tuscan Sun is redeemed by Lane's vibrant performance.

Plot: During the early 16th Century idealistic German monk Martin Luther, disgusted by the materialism in the church, begins the dialogue that will lead to the Protestant Reformation.
Title: Luther
Actors: Joseph Fiennes, Alfred Molina, Jonathan Firth, Claire Cox
tomatoConsensus: This cinematic treatment of Martin Luther's life is more dull than inspiring.

Plot: The son of Italian immigrants to Canada struggles to find the best way to reveal to his parents that he's gay.
Title: Mambo Italiano
Writer: Steve Galluccio (play), Steve Galluccio (screenplay), Émile Gaudreault (screenplay)
Actors: Luke Kirby, Ginette Reno, Paul Sorvino, Mary Walsh
tomatoConsensus: A broad, shrill comedy that plays like a sitcom.

Plot: After being kicked out of a rock band, Dewey Finn becomes a substitute teacher of a strict elementary private school, only to try and turn it into a rock band.
Title: School of Rock
Actors: Jack Black, Adam Pascal, Lucas Papaelias, Chris Stack
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 7 wins & 18 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Black's exuberant, gleeful performance turns School of Rock into a hilarious, rocking good time.

Plot: With a childhood tragedy that overshadowed their lives, three men are reunited by circumstance when one has a family tragedy.
Title: Mystic River
Actors: Sean Penn, Tim Robbins, Kevin Bacon, Laurence Fishburne
tomatoConsensus: Anchored by the exceptional acting of its strong cast, Mystic River is a somber drama that unfolds in layers and conveys the tragedy of its story with visceral power.

Plot: An intergalactic dog pilot from Sirius (the dog star), visits Earth to verify the rumors that dogs have failed to take over the planet.
Title: Good Boy!
Writer: Zeke Richardson (story "Dogs from Outer Space"), Zeke Richardson (screen story), John Hoffman (screen story), John Hoffman (screenplay)
Actors: Molly Shannon, Liam Aiken, Kevin Nealon, Brittany Moldowan
tomatoConsensus: Good Boy! should appeal to kids. Adults, however, might consider it a dog.

Plot: A group of college students travel to a mysterious island to attend a rave, and end up getting trapped there because it's been taken over by bloodthirsty zombies.
Title: House of the Dead
Writer: Mark A. Altman (story), Dan Bates (story), Dave Parker (screenplay), Mark A. Altman (screenplay)
Actors: Jonathan Cherry, Tyron Leitso, Clint Howard, Ona Grauer
tomatoConsensus: A grungy, disjointed, mostly brainless mess of a film, House of the Dead is nonetheless loaded with unintentional laughs.

Plot: A beautiful gold digger matches wits with a shrewd Beverly Hills divorce lawyer who is increasingly attracted to her.
Title: Intolerable Cruelty
Writer: Robert Ramsey (story), Matthew Stone (story), John Romano (story), Robert Ramsey (screenplay), Matthew Stone (screenplay), Ethan Coen (screenplay), Joel Coen (screenplay)
Actors: George Clooney, Catherine Zeta-Jones, Geoffrey Rush, Cedric the Entertainer
tomatoConsensus: Though more mainstream than other Coen films, there are still funny oddball touches, and Clooney and Zeta-Jones sizzle like old-time movie stars.

Plot: A juror on the inside and a woman on the outside manipulate a court trial involving a major gun manufacturer.
Title: Runaway Jury
Writer: John Grisham (novel), Brian Koppelman (screenplay), David Levien (screenplay), Rick Cleveland (screenplay), Matthew Chapman (screenplay)
Actors: John Cusack, Gene Hackman, Dustin Hoffman, Rachel Weisz
tomatoConsensus: An implausible but entertaining legal thriller.

Plot: After picking up a traumatized young hitchhiker, five friends find themselves stalked and hunted by a deformed chainsaw-wielding killer and his family of equally psychopathic killers.
Title: The Texas Chainsaw Massacre
Writer: Kim Henkel, Tobe Hooper, Scott Kosar (screenplay)
Actors: Jessica Biel, Jonathan Tucker, Erica Leerhsen, Mike Vogel
tomatoConsensus: An unnecessary remake that's more gory and less scary than the original.

Plot: A wayward daughter invites her dying mother and the rest of her estranged family to her apartment for Thanksgiving dinner.
Title: Pieces of April
Actors: Katie Holmes, Derek Luke, Oliver Platt, Alison Pill
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 15 wins & 21 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Pieces of April transcends its small-scale setting and budget with endearing performances, playful humor, and genuine sweetness, resulting in a touching holiday treat.

Plot: Story of the relationship between the poets Ted Hughes and Sylvia Plath.
Title: Sylvia
Actors: David Birkin, Alison Bruce, Amira Casar, Daniel Craig
tomatoConsensus: This biopic about Sylvia Plath doesn't rise above the level of highbrow melodrama.

Plot: New York writing professor, Frannie Avery, has an affair with a police detective who is investigating the murder of a beautiful young woman in her neighborhood.
Title: In the Cut
Writer: Jane Campion (screenplay), Susanna Moore (screenplay), Susanna Moore (novel), Stavros Kazantzidis (additional writer)
Actors: Jennifer Jason Leigh, Meg Ryan, Michael Nuccio, Allison Nega
tomatoConsensus: Ryan is very good playing against type, but Campion's good-looking thriller is far from thrilling.

Plot: Beyond Borders is an epic tale of the turbulent romance between two star-crossed lovers set against the backdrop of the world's most dangerous hot spots. Academy Award winner Angelina Jolie...
Title: Beyond Borders
Actors: Angelina Jolie, Clive Owen, Teri Polo, Linus Roache
tomatoConsensus: Beyond Borders is good-intentioned, but the use of human suffering as a backdrop for a romance comes across as sanctimonious and exploitative.

Plot: The story of a high school coach and the developmentally challenged man who he took under his wing.
Title: Radio
Actors: Cuba Gooding Jr., Ed Harris, Alfre Woodard, S. Epatha Merkerson
tomatoConsensus: The story is heavy on syrupy uplift and turns Radio into a saint/cuddly pet.

Title: Brother Bear
Writer: Tab Murphy (screenplay), Lorne Cameron (screenplay), David Hoselton (screenplay), Steve Bencich (screenplay), Ron J. Friedman (screenplay), Stephen J. Anderson (story supervisor), Stevie Wermers (story), Kevin Deters (story), Woody Woodman (story), Thom Enriquez (story), Kevin Harkey (story), Broose Johnson (story), John Norton (story), John Puglisi (story), Tim Hodge (additional story), Tom LaBaff (additional story), Ray Shenusay (additional story), Brian Pimental (additional story), Jim Story (additional story), Don Dougherty (additional story), Don Hall (additional story), Samuel Levine (additional story), Aurian Redson (additional story), Chris Williams (additional story), Jeff Hand (additional story material)
Actors: Joaquin Phoenix, Jeremy Suarez, Jason Raize, Rick Moranis
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 19 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Brother Bear is gentle and pleasant if unremarkable Disney fare, with so-so animation and generic plotting.

Title: Elephant
Actors: Alex Frost, Eric Deulen, John Robinson, Elias McConnell
tomatoConsensus: The movie's spare and unconventional style will divide viewers.

Plot: From his hospital bed, a writer suffering from a skin disease hallucinates musical numbers and paranoid plots.
Title: The Singing Detective
Actors: Robert Downey Jr., Robin Wright, Mel Gibson, Jeremy Northam
tomatoConsensus: Delightful performance from Robert Downey Jr. can't save The Singing Detective's transition from TV to the big screen.

Plot: The true story of a young journalist who fell from grace when it was found he had fabricated over half of his articles.
Title: Shattered Glass
Actors: Hayden Christensen, Peter Sarsgaard, Chloë Sevigny, Rosario Dawson
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 11 wins & 27 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A compelling look at Stephen Glass' fall from grace.

Plot: The human city of Zion defends itself against the massive invasion of the machines as Neo fights to end the war at another front while also opposing the rogue Agent Smith.
Title: The Matrix Revolutions
Writer: Lilly Wachowski, Lana Wachowski, Lilly Wachowski (characters), Lana Wachowski (characters)
Actors: Mary Alice, Tanveer K. Atwal, Helmut Bakaitis, Kate Beahan
tomatoConsensus: A disappointing conclusion to the Matrix trilogy as characters and ideas take a back seat to the special effects.

Plot: After inadvertently wreaking havoc on the elf community due to his ungainly size, a man raised as an elf at the North Pole is sent to the U.S. in search of his true identity.
Title: Elf
Actors: Will Ferrell, James Caan, Bob Newhart, Edward Asner
tomatoConsensus: A movie full of Yuletide cheer, Elf is a spirited, good-natured family comedy, and it benefits greatly from Will Ferrell's funny and charming performance as one of Santa's biggest helpers.

Plot: Follows the lives of eight very different couples in dealing with their love lives in various loosely interrelated tales all set during a frantic month before Christmas in London, England.
Title: Love Actually
Actors: Bill Nighy, Gregor Fisher, Rory MacGregor, Colin Firth
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 10 wins & 26 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A sugary tale overstuffed with too many stories. Still, the cast charms.

Plot: Director Nathaniel Kahn searches to understand his father, noted architect Louis Kahn, who died bankrupt and alone in 1974.
Title: My Architect
Actors: Edmund Bacon, Edwina Pattison Daniels, Balkrishna Doshi, Frank Gehry
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 3 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A moving and enlightening documentary about architect Louis Kahn.

Plot: The Looney Tunes search for a man's missing father and the mythical Blue Monkey diamond.
Title: Looney Tunes: Back in Action
Actors: Brendan Fraser, Jenna Elfman, Steve Martin, Timothy Dalton
tomatoConsensus: The plot is a nonsensical, hyperactive jumble and the gags are relatively uninspired compared to the classic Looney Tunes cartoons.

Plot: During the Napoleonic Wars, a brash British captain pushes his ship and crew to their limits in pursuit of a formidable French war vessel around South America.
Title: Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World
Writer: Patrick O'Brian (novels), Peter Weir (screenplay), John Collee (screenplay)
Actors: Russell Crowe, Paul Bettany, James D'Arcy, Edward Woodall
tomatoConsensus: Russell Crowe's rough charm is put to good use in this masterful adaptation of Patrick O'Brian's novel.

Plot: Home movies, photographs, and recited poetry illustrate the life of Tupac Shakur, one of the most beloved, revolutionary, and volatile hip-hop M.Cs. of all time.
Title: Tupac: Resurrection
Actors: Tupac Shakur, Rappin' 4-Tay, Conrad Bain, Bill Bellamy
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: There's no question where the director's loyalty lies in this one-sided tribute; however, Tupac's charisma makes this doc an engaging sit.

Plot: In 1885 New Mexico, a frontier medicine woman forms an uneasy alliance with her estranged father when her daughter is kidnapped by an Apache brujo.
Title: The Missing
Actors: Tommy Lee Jones, Cate Blanchett, Evan Rachel Wood, Jenna Boyd
tomatoConsensus: An expertly acted and directed Western. But like other Ron Howard features, the movie is hardly subtle.

Plot: Two bored children have their lives turned upside down when a talking cat comes to visit them.
Title: The Cat in the Hat
Writer: Dr. Seuss (book), Alec Berg (screenplay), David Mandel (screenplay), Jeff Schaffer (screenplay)
Actors: Mike Myers, Alec Baldwin, Kelly Preston, Dakota Fanning
tomatoConsensus: Filled with double entendres and potty humor, this Cat falls flat.

Plot: A repressed female psychiatrist wakes up as a patient in the asylum where she worked, with no memory of why she is there or what she has done.
Title: Gothika
Actors: Halle Berry, Robert Downey Jr., Charles S. Dutton, John Carroll Lynch
tomatoConsensus: Berry's acting talents can't save Gothika from its preposterous plot and bad dialogue.

Plot: A freak accident brings together a critically ill mathematician, a grieving mother, and a born-again ex-con.
Title: 21 Grams
Actors: Sean Penn, Naomi Watts, Danny Huston, Carly Nahon
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 29 wins & 71 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Alejandro González Iñárritu deftly weaves an uncommonly structured narrative with panache in 21 Grams, a stylish, haunting drama full of fine performances.

Plot: A realtor and his wife and children are summoned to a mansion, which they soon discover is haunted, and while they attempt to escape, he learns an important lesson about the family he has neglected.
Title: The Haunted Mansion
Actors: Eddie Murphy, Terence Stamp, Nathaniel Parker, Marsha Thomason
tomatoConsensus: Neither scary nor funny, The Haunted Mansion is as lifeless as the ghosts in the movie.

Plot: A group of archaeological students become trapped in the past when they go there to retrieve their professor. The group must survive in 14th century France long enough to be rescued.
Title: Timeline
Writer: Michael Crichton (novel), Jeff Maguire (screenplay), George Nolfi (screenplay)
Actors: Paul Walker, Frances O'Connor, Gerard Butler, Billy Connolly
tomatoConsensus: This incoherently plotted addition to the time-travel genre looks and sounds cheesy.

Plot: In an old school Las Vegas casino, its top gambling jinx breaks his curse when he falls in love, much to his boss' consternation.
Title: The Cooler
Actors: William H. Macy, Alec Baldwin, Maria Bello, Shawn Hatosy
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 25 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A small movie elevated by superb performances.

Plot: Honey is a sexy, tough music video choreographer who shakes up her life after her mentor gives her an ultimatum: sleep with him or be blacklisted within their industry.
Title: Honey
Actors: Jessica Alba, Mekhi Phifer, Romeo Miller, Joy Bryant
tomatoConsensus: An attractive Jessica Alba and energetic dance numbers provide some lift to this corny and formulaic movie.

Plot: An American military advisor embraces the Samurai culture he was hired to destroy after he is captured in battle.
Title: The Last Samurai
Writer: John Logan (story), John Logan (screenplay), Edward Zwick (screenplay), Marshall Herskovitz (screenplay)
Actors: Ken Watanabe, Tom Cruise, William Atherton, Chad Lindberg
Awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 19 wins & 54 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: With high production values and thrilling battle scenes, The Last Samurai is a satisfying epic.

Plot: A frustrated son tries to determine the fact from fiction in his dying father's life.
Title: Big Fish
Actors: Ewan McGregor, Albert Finney, Billy Crudup, Jessica Lange
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 62 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A charming father-and-son tale filled with typical Tim Burton flourishes.

Plot: Highschool loser (Cannon) pays a cheerleader (Milian) to pose as his girlfriend so he can be considered cool. Remake of 1987' Can't Buy Me Love, starring Patrick Dempsey.
Title: Love Don't Cost a Thing
Writer: Michael Swerdlick (screenplay), Troy Byer (screenplay), Michael Swerdlick (screenplay)
Actors: Nick Cannon, Jordan Burg, Jackie Benoit, George Cedar
tomatoConsensus: A stale, unnecessary remake of Can't Buy Me Love.

Plot: A swinger on the cusp of being a senior citizen with a taste for young women falls in love with an accomplished woman closer to his age.
Title: Something's Gotta Give
Actors: Jack Nicholson, Diane Keaton, Keanu Reeves, Frances McDormand
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 12 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though it occasionally stumbles into sitcom territory, Something's Gotta Give is mostly a smart, funny romantic comedy, with sharp performances from Jack Nicholson, Diane Keaton, and Keanu Reeves.

Plot: A young peasant maid working in the house of painter Johannes Vermeer becomes his talented assistant and the model for one of his most famous works.
Title: Girl with a Pearl Earring
Actors: Colin Firth, Scarlett Johansson, Tom Wilkinson, Judy Parfitt
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 17 wins & 41 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Visually arresting, but the story could be told with a bit more energy.

Plot: Tale of a former Nazi executioner who becomes a target of hit men and Police investigators.
Title: The Statement
Actors: Michael Caine, Tilda Swinton, Jeremy Northam, Alan Bates
tomatoConsensus: The movie bores despite a splendid performance by Michael Caine.

Plot: Gandalf and Aragorn lead the World of Men against Sauron's army to draw his gaze from Frodo and Sam as they approach Mount Doom with the One Ring.
Title: The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King
Writer: J.R.R. Tolkien (novel), Fran Walsh (screenplay), Philippa Boyens (screenplay), Peter Jackson (screenplay)
Actors: Noel Appleby, Ali Astin, Sean Astin, David Aston
tomatoConsensus: Visually breathtaking and emotionally powerful,  The Lord of the Rings - The Return of the King is a moving and satisfying conclusion to a great trilogy.

Plot: A free-thinking art professor teaches conservative 1950s Wellesley girls to question their traditional social roles.
Title: Mona Lisa Smile
Actors: Julia Roberts, Kirsten Dunst, Julia Stiles, Maggie Gyllenhaal
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though Mona Lisa Smile espouses the value of breaking barriers, the movie itself is predictable and safe.

Plot: A Women's Institute chapter's fundraising effort for a local hospital by posing nude for a calendar becomes a media sensation.
Title: Calendar Girls
Actors: Helen Mirren, Julie Walters, John Alderton, Linda Bassett
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 14 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A charming, but cliched comedy reminiscent of The Full Monty.

Plot: An abandoned wife is evicted from her house and starts a tragic conflict with her home's new owners.
Title: House of Sand and Fog
Writer: Andre Dubus III (novel), Vadim Perelman (screenplay), Shawn Lawrence Otto (screenplay)
Actors: Jennifer Connelly, Ben Kingsley, Ron Eldard, Frances Fisher
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 12 wins & 37 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Powerful and thought provoking film.

Plot: Based on the life of Aileen Wuornos, a Daytona Beach prostitute who became a serial killer.
Title: Monster
Actors: Charlize Theron, Christina Ricci, Bruce Dern, Lee Tergesen
tomatoConsensus: Charlize Theron gives a searing, deglamorized performance as real life serial killer Aileen Wuornos in Monster, an intense, disquieting portrait of a profoundly damaged soul.

Plot: With his wife doing a book tour, a father of twelve must handle a new job and his unstable brood.
Title: Cheaper by the Dozen
Writer: Frank B. Gilbreth Jr. (novel), Ernestine Gilbreth Carey (novel), Craig Titley (screen story), Sam Harper (screenplay), Joel Cohen (screenplay), Alec Sokolow (screenplay)
Actors: Steve Martin, Bonnie Hunt, Piper Perabo, Tom Welling
tomatoConsensus: In this family of twelve children, much chaos ensues, but little hilarity.

Plot: What seemed like a breezy idea for an engineer to net him millions of dollars, leaves him on the run for his life and piecing together why he's being chased.
Title: Paycheck
Writer: Philip K. Dick (short story), Dean Georgaris (screenplay)
Actors: Ben Affleck, Aaron Eckhart, Uma Thurman, Paul Giamatti
tomatoConsensus: Though Dick's short story has an intriguing premise, Woo reduces it to a lot of meaningless chases, shoot-outs, and explosions.

Title: Peter Pan
Writer: J.M. Barrie (play), P.J. Hogan (screenplay), Michael Goldenberg (screenplay)
Actors: Jason Isaacs, Jeremy Sumpter, Rachel Hurd-Wood, Lynn Redgrave
tomatoConsensus: Solid if far from definitive, this version of Peter Pan is visually impressive, psychologically complex and faithful to its original source.

Plot: Against the background of an Australian desert, Sandy, a geologist, and Hiromitsu, a Japanese businessman, play out a story of human inconsequence in the face of the blistering universe. ...
Title: Japanese Story
Actors: Toni Collette, Gotaro Tsunashima, Matthew Dyktynski, Lynette Curran
tomatoConsensus: An emotional film where Toni Collette gets to show her impressive range.

Plot: The true story of two climbers and their perilous journey up the west face of Siula Grande in the Peruvian Andes in 1985.
Title: Touching the Void
Actors: Brendan Mackey, Nicholas Aaron, Richard Hawking, Joe Simpson
tomatoConsensus: Gripping even though the outcome is known.

Plot: A young American studying in Paris in 1968 strikes up a friendship with a French brother and sister. Set against the background of the '68 Paris student riots.
Title: The Dreamers
Writer: Gilbert Adair (screenplay), Gilbert Adair (based on the novel)
Actors: Michael Pitt, Eva Green, Louis Garrel, Anna Chancellor
tomatoConsensus: Though lushly atmospheric, The Dreamers doesn't engage or provoke as much as it should.

Plot: A thirteen-year-old girl's relationship with her mother is put to the test as she discovers drugs, sex, and petty crime in the company of her cool but troubled best friend.
Title: Thirteen
Actors: Nikki Reed, Evan Rachel Wood, Vanessa Hudgens, Holly Hunter
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 45 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: An emotionally wrenching, not to mention terrifying, film about the perils of being a teenager.

Plot: In 1990, to protect his fragile mother from a fatal shock after a long coma, a young man must keep her from learning that her beloved nation of East Germany as she knew it has disappeared.
Title: Good Bye Lenin!
Writer: Bernd Lichtenberg, Wolfgang Becker (author), Achim von Borries (collaborator on screenplay), Hendrik Handloegten (collaborator on screenplay), Christoph Silber (collaborator on screenplay)
Actors: Daniel Brühl, Katrin Saß, Chulpan Khamatova, Maria Simon
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 32 wins & 17 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Funny and poignant social critique of German reunification.

Plot: A variety of losers in Dublin have harrowingly farcical intersecting stories of love, greed and violence.
Title: Intermission
Actors: Colin Farrell, Kerry Condon, Johnny Thompson, Emma Bolger
tomatoConsensus: An edgy and energetic ensemble story.

Plot: A woman on the run from the mob is reluctantly accepted in a small Colorado town. In exchange, she agrees to work for them. As a search visits town, she finds out that their support has a price. Yet her dangerous secret is never far away...
Title: Dogville
Country: Denmark, Sweden, UK, France, Germany, Netherlands, Norway, Finland, Italy
Actors: Nicole Kidman, Harriet Andersson, Lauren Bacall, Jean-Marc Barr
tomatoConsensus: A challenging piece of experimental filmmaking.

Plot: A young man's experience in a juvenile detention center that touches on the tumultuous changes that befall his family and the community in which he lives.
Title: The United States of Leland
Actors: Don Cheadle, Ryan Gosling, Chris Klein, Jena Malone
tomatoConsensus: The United States of Leland has its moments, but they're undermined by a muddled plot, unsympathetic characters, and frustratingly uneven performances.

Plot: A young drifter working on a river barge disrupts his employers' lives while hiding the fact that he knows more about a dead woman found in the river than he admits.
Title: Young Adam
Actors: Ewan McGregor, Tilda Swinton, Peter Mullan, Emily Mortimer
tomatoConsensus: A grim mood piece with good performances from the leads.

Plot: A series of vignettes that all have coffee and cigarettes in common.
Title: Coffee and Cigarettes
Actors: Roberto Benigni, Steven Wright, Joie Lee, Cinqué Lee
tomatoConsensus: Episodes vary in quality, but overall this talky film is quirkily engaging.

Plot: Mario Van Peebles's half documentary/half homage to his father Melvin's 1971 film, Sweet Sweetback's Baadasssss Song.
Title: Baadasssss!
Writer: Melvin Van Peebles (book), Mario Van Peebles (screenplay), Dennis Haggerty (screenplay)
Actors: Mario Van Peebles, Joy Bryant, T.K. Carter, Terry Crews
tomatoConsensus: An entertaining and intriguing tribute to a father from his son.

Plot: A woman has a passionate affair with a man half her age, who is also sleeping with her daughter.
Title: The Mother
Actors: Anne Reid, Peter Vaughan, Anna Wilson-Jones, Daniel Craig
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 11 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Reid gives a fearless, realistic performance in depicting an older woman's sexual blossoming.

Plot: An actress, a writer, a student, and a government worker band together in an effort to escape Paris as the Nazis move into the city.
Title: Bon voyage
Writer: Jean-Paul Rappeneau (scenario), Patrick Modiano (scenario), Jérôme Tonnerre (adaptation), Jean-Paul Rappeneau (adaptation), Gilles Marchand (adaptation), Julien Rappeneau (adaptation)
Actors: Isabelle Adjani, Gérard Depardieu, Virginie Ledoyen, Yvan Attal
tomatoConsensus: It's froth, but stylish and giddily entertaining.

Plot: Filmmaker Jonathan Caouette's documentary on growing up with his schizophrenic mother -- a mixture of snapshots, Super-8, answering machine messages, video diaries, early short films, and more -- culled from 19 years of his life.
Title: Tarnation
Actors: Renee Leblanc, Jonathan Caouette, Adolph Davis, Rosemary Davis
tomatoConsensus: Using music and home video footage to great effect, Jonathan Caouette has made a very personal and moving film.

Plot: An adaptation of Evelyn Waugh's novel "Vile Bodies," is a look into the lives of a young novelist, his would-be lover, and a host of young people who beautified London in the 1930s.
Title: Bright Young Things
Actors: Simon McBurney, Michael Sheen, Emily Mortimer, James McAvoy
tomatoConsensus: Colored with witty performances and a camp sense of satire, Stephen Fry's version of Evelyn Waugh's novel may only be fitfully successful but it does mark a promising debut for the British comic.

Plot: Documentary on Charles Bukowski, author of 'Notes of a Dirty Old Man', 'Love Is a Dog from Hell', and the autobiographical novels, 'Women', 'Hollywood', and 'Post Office'.
Title: Bukowski: Born into This
Actors: Charles Bukowski, Bono, John Bryan, Linda Lee Bukowski
tomatoConsensus: A thoroughly engrossing documentary examining the life of talented but troubled writer Charles Bukowski.

Plot: A musical of sorts set in Winnipeg during the Great Depression, where a beer baroness organizes a contest to find the saddest music in the world. Musicians from around the world descend on the city to try and win the $25,000 prize.
Title: The Saddest Music in the World
Writer: Kazuo Ishiguro (original screenplay), George Toles, Guy Maddin
Actors: Mark McKinney, Isabella Rossellini, Maria de Medeiros, David Fox
tomatoConsensus: Guy Maddin perfectly recreates the look and feel of a 1930s in this bizarre picture.

Plot: When the head of a statue sacred to a village is stolen, a young martial artist goes to the big city and finds himself taking on the underworld to retrieve it.
Title: Ong-Bak: The Thai Warrior
Writer: Panna Rittikrai (story), Prachya Pinkaew (story), Suphachai Sittiaumponpan (screenplay)
Actors: Tony Jaa, Petchtai Wongkamlao, Pumwaree Yodkamol, Suchao Pongwilai
tomatoConsensus: While Ong-Bak: The Thai Warrior may be no great shakes as a movie, critics are hailing the emergence of a new star in Tony Jaa, whose athletic performance is drawing comparisons with Bruce Lee, Jackie Chan, and Jet Li.

Plot: The filmed account of a large Canadian rock festival train tour.
Title: Festival Express
Actors: Rick Danko, Levon Helm, Garth Hudson, Richard Manuel
tomatoConsensus: Festival Express is a spellbinding documentary that nostalgically chronicles five days in the summer of 1970, when a train full of now- legendary rock perfomers jammed its way across Canada.

Plot: Divided into three "kingdoms" -- Enfer (Hell), Purgatoire (Purgatory) and Paradis (Paradise) -- Notre Musique is an indictment of modern times.
Language: French, Arabic, English, Hebrew, Serbo-Croatian, Spanish
Title: Notre musique
Actors: Sarah Adler, Nade Dieu, Rony Kramer, Simon Eine
tomatoConsensus: A dense, but thoughtful meditation about war by Jean-Luc Godard.

Plot: The relationships of two couples become complicated and deceitful when the man from one couple meets the woman of the other.
Title: Closer
Actors: Julia Roberts, Jude Law, Natalie Portman, Clive Owen
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 19 wins & 45 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Closer's talented cast and Mike Nichols' typically assured direction help smooth a bumpy journey from stage to screen.

Plot: Daniel Ocean recruits one more team member so he can pull off three major European heists in this sequel to Ocean's 11.
Title: Ocean's Twelve
Writer: George Nolfi, George Clayton Johnson (characters), Jack Golden Russell (characters)
Actors: Brad Pitt, Catherine Zeta-Jones, George Clooney, Ed Kross
tomatoConsensus: While some have found the latest star-studded heist flick to be a fun, glossy star vehicle, others declare it's lazy, self-satisfied and illogical.

Plot: Blade, now a wanted man by the FBI, must join forces with the Nightstalkers to face his most challenging enemy yet: Dracula.
Title: Blade: Trinity
Writer: David S. Goyer, Marv Wolfman (character), Gene Colan (character)
Actors: Wesley Snipes, Kris Kristofferson, Dominic Purcell, Jessica Biel
tomatoConsensus: Louder, campier, and more incoherent than its predecessors, Blade: Trinity seems content to emphasize style over substance and rehash familiar themes.

Plot: The film follows a rebellious teenager on leave from the Marines who falls in love with a female musician. The relationship is threatened when she develops a mental illness...
Title: Stateside
Actors: Rachael Leigh Cook, Jonathan Tucker, Agnes Bruckner, Val Kilmer
tomatoConsensus: An inept drama that rings false.

Plot: A documentary on perception of the United States's war with Iraq, with an emphasis on Al Jazeera's coverage.
Title: Control Room
Actors: Samir Khader, Josh Rushing, George W. Bush, Hassan Ibrahim
tomatoConsensus: A fascinating, enlightening behind-the-scenes look at the Al Jazeera network.

Plot: When a massive fire kills their parents, three children are delivered to the custody of cousin and stage actor Count Olaf, who is secretly plotting to steal their parents' vast fortune.
Title: A Series of Unfortunate Events
Actors: Jim Carrey, Liam Aiken, Emily Browning, Kara Hoffman
tomatoConsensus: Although it softens the nasty edges of its source material, Lemony Snicket's A Series of Unfortunate Events is a gothic visual treat, and it features a hilariously manic turn from Jim Carrey as the evil Count Olaf.

Plot: In the year 2032, Batô, a cyborg detective for the anti-terrorist unit Public Security Section 9, investigates the case of a female robot--one created solely for sexual pleasure--who slaughtered her owner.
Title: Ghost in the Shell 2: Innocence

Actors: Akio Ôtsuka, Atsuko Tanaka, Kôichi Yamadera, Tamio Ôki
tomatoConsensus: The animation is lovely, but the plot is complex to the point of inscrutability, leaving Ghost in the Shell 2: Innocence both original and numbing.

Plot: Antoine and Helene drive to South France to return their kids from a holiday camp. The traffic is dense and the atmosphere growingly tense; he is an alcoholic and becomes increasingly drunk...
Title: Red Lights
Writer: Georges Simenon (novel), Laurence Ferreira Barbosa, Cédric Kahn, Gilles Marchand
Actors: Jean-Pierre Darroussin, Carole Bouquet, Vincent Deniard, Alain Dion
tomatoConsensus: Red Lights is a taut, character-driven thriller, set against the debris-strewn battleground of a failing marriage.

Plot: Ethics, being human and the soul come to the fore when a 7-year old finds a bag of Pounds just days before the currency is switched to Euros and learns what we are really made of.
Title: Millions
Actors: Alex Etel, Lewis McGibbon, James Nesbitt, Daisy Donovan
tomatoConsensus: A charming children fable even adults can enjoy.

Plot: A woman and her daughter emigrate from Mexico for a better life in America, where they start working for a family where the patriarch is a newly celebrated chef with an insecure wife.
Title: Spanglish
Actors: Adam Sandler, Téa Leoni, Paz Vega, Cloris Leachman
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 10 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Paz Vega shines, and Adam Sandler gives a performance of thoughtfulness and depth, but Spanglish is ultimately undermined by sitcommy plotting and unearned uplift.

Plot: A gay Canadian living in London has his perfectly crafted life upset when his devoutly Muslim mother comes to visit.
Title: Touch of Pink
Writer: Ian Iqbal Rashid, Ken Chubb (story editor)
Actors: Jimi Mistry, Kyle MacLachlan, Suleka Mathew, Kris Holden-Ried
tomatoConsensus: Kyle MacLachlan does a very good imitation Cary Grant in this forced and contrived tale.

Plot: Jim Caviezel stars as golf legend Bobby Jones, the icon who retired from competition at the tender age of 28.
Title: Bobby Jones: Stroke of Genius
Writer: Rowdy Herrington (story), Kim Dawson (story), Rowdy Herrington (screenplay), Bill Pryor (screenplay), Tony De Paul (screenplay)
Actors: Jim Caviezel, Claire Forlani, Jeremy Northam, Malcolm McDowell
tomatoConsensus: This earnest, monotonous biopic lacks dramatic tension and simplifies Jones' life.

Plot: A successful cocaine dealer gets two tough assignments from his boss on the eve of his planned early retirement.
Title: Layer Cake
Actors: Daniel Craig, Tom Hardy, Jamie Foreman, Sally Hawkins
tomatoConsensus: A stylized, electric British crime thriller.

Plot: The discovery of a corpse threatens to unravel a bumbling local politician's campaign for governor of Colorado.
Title: Silver City
Actors: Chris Cooper, Richard Dreyfuss, Cajardo Lindsey, John C. Ashton
tomatoConsensus: Heavy-handed and often dull.

Plot: Survivors of a plane crash in the Mongolian desert work together to build a new plane.
Title: Flight of the Phoenix
Writer: Lukas Heller, Scott Frank (screenplay), Edward Burns (screenplay)
Actors: Dennis Quaid, Tyrese Gibson, Giovanni Ribisi, Miranda Otto
tomatoConsensus: What this update lacks in tension, it makes up for with generic action.

Plot: When a teen is bullied, his brother and friends lure the bully into the woods to seek revenge.
Title: Mean Creek
Actors: Rory Culkin, Ryan Kelley, Scott Mechlowicz, Trevor Morgan
tomatoConsensus: Mean Creek is an uncomfortably riveting glimpse into the casual cruelty of youth.

Plot: Fired from his job for exposing corrupt business practices, a former biotech executive turns to impregnating wealthy lesbians for profit.
Title: She Hate Me
Writer: Michael Genet (story), Michael Genet (screenplay), Spike Lee (screenplay)
Actors: Anthony Mackie, Kerry Washington, Ellen Barkin, Monica Bellucci
tomatoConsensus: She Hate Me can't decide if it wants to be a commentary on corporate greed or a sex farce.

Plot: A documentary crew followed Metallica for the better part of 2001-2003, a time of tension and release for the rock band, as they recorded their album St. Anger, fought bitterly, and sought the counsel of their on-call shrink.
Title: Metallica: Some Kind of Monster
Actors: James Hetfield, Lars Ulrich, Kirk Hammett, Robert Trujillo
tomatoConsensus: Fascinating behind-the-scenes look at how Metallica survives one of their more turbulent periods.

Plot: Two documentary filmmakers chronicle their time in Sonagchi, Calcutta and the relationships they developed with children of prostitutes who work the city's notorious red light district.
Title: Born Into Brothels: Calcutta's Red Light Kids
Actors: Kochi, Avijit Halder, Shanti Das, Manik
tomatoConsensus: A powerful and uplifting documentary.

Plot: Documentary detailing the origins and history of surf culture.
Title: Riding Giants
Actors: Jeff Clark, Darrick Doerner, Sarah Gerhardt, Laird John Hamilton
tomatoConsensus: A great addition to the existing surfing documentaries.

Plot: "WHAT THE #$*! DO WE KNOW?!" is a radical departure from convention. It demands a freedom of view and greatness of thought so far unknown, indeed, not even dreamed of since Copernicus. It's...
Title: What the #$*! Do We (K)now!?
Writer: William Arntz, Betsy Chasse, Matthew Hoffman, Mark Vicente
Director: William Arntz, Betsy Chasse, Mark Vicente
Actors: Marlee Matlin, Elaine Hendrix, John Ross Bowie, Robert Bailey Jr.
tomatoConsensus: Educational, but as entertainment, it'll have viewers asking, 'What the bleep?'

Plot: Documentary on reported Conservative bias of the Rupert Murdoch-owned Fox News Channel (FNC), which promotes itself as "Fair and Balanced". Material includes interviews with former FNC employees and the inter-office memos they provided.
Title: Outfoxed: Rupert Murdoch's War on Journalism
Actors: Roger Ailes, Eric Alterman, Christiane Amanpour, Harry Belafonte
tomatoConsensus: Neither fair nor balanced itself, Outfoxed offers an often entertaining indictment of the Fox News Channel.

Plot: A determined woman works with a hardened boxing trainer to become a professional.
Title: Million Dollar Baby
Actors: Clint Eastwood, Hilary Swank, Morgan Freeman, Jay Baruchel
tomatoConsensus: Clint Eastwood's assured direction - combined with knockout performances from Hilary Swank and Morgan Freeman - help Million Dollar Baby to transcend its clichés, and the result is deeply heartfelt and moving.

Plot: Paul Rusesabagina was a hotel manager who housed over a thousand Tutsi refugees during their struggle against the Hutu militia in Rwanda.
Title: Hotel Rwanda
Actors: Xolani Mali, Don Cheadle, Desmond Dube, Hakeem Kae-Kazim
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 16 wins & 42 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A sobering and heartfelt tale about massacre that took place in Rwanda while most of the world looked away.

Plot: A biopic depicting the early years of legendary director and aviator Howard Hughes' career from the late 1920s to the mid-1940s.
Title: The Aviator
Actors: Leonardo DiCaprio, Cate Blanchett, Kate Beckinsale, John C. Reilly
tomatoConsensus: With a rich sense of period detail, The Aviator succeeds thanks to typically assured direction from Martin Scorsese and a strong performance from Leonardo DiCaprio, who charts Howard Hughes' descent from eccentric billionaire to reclusive madman.

Plot: A young soprano becomes the obsession of a disfigured musical genius who lives beneath the Paris Opéra House.
Title: The Phantom of the Opera

Actors: Gerard Butler, Emmy Rossum, Patrick Wilson, Miranda Richardson
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 35 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The music of the night has hit something of a sour note: Critics are calling the screen adaptation of Andrew Lloyd Webber's popular musical histrionic, boring, and lacking in both romance and danger. Still, some have praised the film for its sheer spectacle.

Plot: A swooning study of "Mack the Knife" singer Bobby Darin (Spacey) specifically, and his relationship with his wife Sandra Dee (Bosworth).
Title: Beyond the Sea
Actors: Kevin Spacey, Kate Bosworth, John Goodman, Bob Hoskins
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Kevin Spacey's bio of singer Bobby Darin is either a fearless piece of showmanship or an embarrassing vanity project, according to critics.

Plot: A child molester returns to his hometown after 12 years in prison and attempts to start a new life.
Title: The Woodsman
Writer: Steven Fechter (play), Nicole Kassell (screenplay), Steven Fechter (screenplay)
Actors: Kevin Bacon, David Alan Grier, Eve, Kyra Sedgwick
tomatoConsensus: Kevin Bacon's performance as a pedophile who is trying to start fresh has drawn raves from critics, who have praised the Woodsman as compelling, creepy, complex and well-crafted.

Plot: A middle-aged ad exec is faced with a new boss who's nearly half his age... and who also happens to be sleeping with his daughter.
Title: In Good Company
Actors: Dennis Quaid, Topher Grace, Scarlett Johansson, Marg Helgenberger
tomatoConsensus: The witty and charming In Good Company offers laughs at the expense of corporate culture.

Plot: All hell breaks loose when the Byrnes family meets the Focker family for the first time.

tomatoConsensus: Talented cast is wasted as the movie is content with recycling jokes from its predecessor, Meet the Parents.

Plot: In 16th century Venice, when a merchant must default on a large loan from an abused Jewish moneylender for a friend with romantic ambitions, the bitterly vengeful creditor demands a gruesome payment instead.
Title: The Merchant of Venice

Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 6 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A respectable if uneven take on the Bard's The Merchant of Venice.

Plot: Fat Albert and the Cosby Kids come to life and step out of their animated, inner-city Philadelphia world.
Title: Fat Albert

tomatoConsensus: A bland but good-natured adaptation of the cartoon show.

Plot: A documentary on Henry Darger, visionary artist, janitor, and novelist.
Title: In the Realms of the Unreal
Actors: Larry Pine, Dakota Fanning, Frier McCollister, Wally Wingert
Awards: Nominated for 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A fascinating treatment on the life of a reclusive man.

Plot: In 1860s Britain, a boy inventor finds himself caught in the middle of a deadly conflict over a revolutionary advance in steam power.
Title: Steamboy
Actors: Anne Suzuki, Masane Tsukayama, Katsuo Nakamura, Manami Konishi
tomatoConsensus: The story isn't the greatest, but there's an abundance of sci-fi eye candy to compensate.

Plot: Jane Austen's Pride and Prejudice gets a Bollywood treatment.
Title: Bride & Prejudice
Writer: Jane Austen (novel), Paul Mayeda Berges, Gurinder Chadha
Actors: Aishwarya Rai Bachchan, Martin Henderson, Nadira Babbar, Anupam Kher

Plot: Near the Iraqi-Turkish border on the eve of an American invasion, refugee children like 13-year-old Kak (Ebrahim), gauge and await their fate.

tomatoConsensus: Set in Iraq after the fall of Saddam, Turtles Can Fly is being hailed as extraordinary, moving, and lyrical.

Plot: Five stages in the romance between a woman and a man.
Title: 5x2
Actors: Valeria Bruni Tedeschi, Stéphane Freiss, Françoise Fabian, Michael Lonsdale
tomatoConsensus: Five scenes from a marriage, deftly and poignantly presented.

Plot: American soldiers of the 2/3 Field Artillery, a group known as the "Gunners," tell of their experiences in Baghdad during the Iraq War. Holed up in a bombed out pleasure palace built by Sadaam Hussein, the soldiers endured hostile situations some four months after President George W. Bush declared the end of major combat operations in the country.
Title: Gunner Palace
Actors: Bryant Davis, Devon Dixon, Javorn Drummond, Elliot Lovett
tomatoConsensus: A shapeless documentary, but shows what's it like for the soldiers on the ground.

Plot: Following the suicide of his wife, an Israeli intelligence agent is assigned to befriend the grandchildren of a Nazi war criminal.

Title: Walk on Water
Actors: Lior Ashkenazi, Knut Berger, Caroline Peters, Gideon Shemer
tomatoConsensus: Politically complex and ambitious, Walk on Water delivers a memorable story of guilt, revenge, and human connectivity.

Plot: A suspense thriller about a reporter from Miami who travels to Ecuador in pursuit of a serial killer known as the "Monster of Babahoyo."

Plot: Two alternating stories, one comedy and the other tragedy, about Melinda's attempts to straighten out her life.
Title: Melinda and Melinda

Title: Woman Thou Art Loosed
Writer: T.D. Jakes (novel), Stan Foster (screenplay), Christine Swanson (revised screenplay)

Plot: Three short films -- one each from directors Michelangelo Antonioni, Steven Soderbergh and Wong Kar Wai -- address the themes of love and sex.

Plot: In this suburban drama, a widower (played by Anthony LaPaglia) confronts his older son's (played by Aaron Stanford) decision to leave home and his younger son's self-destructive behavior.
Title: Winter Solstice

tomatoConsensus: A deliberately paced, realistic portrait of a family's grief and healing.

Plot: By working through problems stemming from his past, Tom Warshaw, an American artist living in Paris, begins to discover who he really is, and returns to his home to reconcile with his family and friends.

tomatoConsensus: A sincere but inept coming of age story.

Plot: Aviva is thirteen, awkward and sensitive. Her mother Joyce is warm and loving, as is her father, Steve, a regular guy who does have a fierce temper from time to time. The film revolves around her family, friends and neighbors.

Plot: Los Angeles citizens with vastly separate lives collide in interweaving stories of race, loss and redemption.

Plot: A teenage hustler and a young man obsessed with alien abductions cross paths, together discovering a horrible, liberating truth.

Plot: A Chinese-American lesbian and her traditionalist mother are reluctant to go public with secret loves that clash against cultural expectations.

Plot: Parallel storylines tell the current state of affairs for two ex-lovers: Nora's a single mother who comes to care for her terminally ill father; holed in up in mental ward, Ismael, a brilliant musician, plots his escape.
Title: Kings & Queen

Plot: In the Yorkshire countryside, working-class tomboy Mona meets the exotic, pampered Tamsin. Over the summer season, the two young women discover they have much to teach one another, and much to explore together.

Plot: Saint Ralph is the unlikely story of Ralph Walker, a ninth grader who outran everyone's expectations except his own in his bold quest of trying to win the 1954 Boston Marathon.
Title: Saint Ralph

Plot: In this film, told almost entirely in iambic pentameter, She is a scientist in a loveless marriage to Anthony, a devious politician. He is a Lebanese doctor in self-imposed exile, working ...
Title: Yes
Actors: Shirley Henderson, Joan Allen, Sam Neill, Simon Abkarian
tomatoConsensus: Emotional performances/ Can't stop the curse/ Of ever-present pretensions/ Writ in heavy-handed verse.

Plot: Is the love compatible with coupledom? And what of freedom and fidelity? These are some of the questions facing two married men.
Title: ...And They Lived Happily Ever After
