tomatoConsensus: Though this French film features good acting, it lacks the wit and charm one would expect to see.

Actors: Drew Barrymore, John August, Stephanie Bedell, Allison Burnett

Plot: Through the eyes of a British "documentary", this film takes a satirically humorous, and sometimes frightening, look at the history of an America where the South won the Civil War.
Title: C.S.A.: The Confederate States of America
Actors: Greg Kirsch, Renee Patrick, Molly Graham, William Willmott
tomatoConsensus: Through the eyes of a British "documentary", this film takes a satirically humorous, and sometimes frightening, look at the history of an America where the South won the Civil War.

Plot: The story of John Wilmot, a.k.a. the Earl of Rochester, a 17th century poet who famously drank and debauched his way to an early grave, only to earn posthumous critical acclaim for his life's work.
Title: The Libertine
Actors: Johnny Depp, Paul Ritter, John Malkovich, Stanley Townsend
tomatoConsensus: Despite Johnny Depp's zealous performance, muddled direction and murky cinematography hinder The Libertine.

Plot: While retaining her secret identity, the illustrious Mrs. Erlynne (Hunt) saves Lady Windemere (Johansson) from making a grand social faux-pas with the scoundrelly Lord Darlington (Moore).
Title: A Good Woman
Actors: Helen Hunt, Scarlett Johansson, Milena Vukotic, Stephen Campbell Moore
tomatoConsensus: This adaptation of Wilde's Lady Windermere's Fan lacks bite due to liberties taken with the source material, coupled with uneven performances.

Title: The Intruder
Writer: Claire Denis, Jean-Pol Fargeau, Jean-Luc Nancy (novel)
Actors: Michel Subor, Grégoire Colin, Yekaterina Golubeva, Bambou
tomatoConsensus: The impressionistic narrative may confound the viewer, but Denis crafts wonderfully poetic, dreamlike imagery.

Plot: When a scientist sent back to the prehistoric era strays off the path he causes a chain of events that alters history in disastrous ways.
Title: A Sound of Thunder

Actors: Armin Rohde, Heike Makatsch, Jemima Rooper, David Oyelowo
tomatoConsensus: Choppy logic and uneven performances are overshadowed by not-so-special effects that makes the suspension of disbelief a nearly impossible task.

Plot: A Gulf war veteran is wrongly sent to a mental institution for insane criminals, where he becomes the object of a Doctor's experiments, and his life is completely affected by them.
Title: The Jacket
Writer: Tom Bleecker (story), Marc Rocco (story), Massy Tadjedin (screenplay)
Actors: Adrien Brody, Keira Knightley, Kris Kristofferson, Jennifer Jason Leigh
tomatoConsensus: The Jacket is a case of creepy style over substance.

Plot: Political intrigue and deception unfold inside the United Nations, where a U.S. Secret Service agent is assigned to investigate an interpreter who overhears an assassination plot.
Title: The Interpreter
Writer: Martin Stellman (story), Brian Ward (story), Charles Randolph (screenplay), Scott Frank (screenplay), Steven Zaillian (screenplay)
Actors: Nicole Kidman, Sean Penn, Catherine Keener, Jesper Christensen

Plot: Six months after the incidents involving the lethal videotape, new clues prove that there is a new evil lurking in the darkness.
Title: The Ring Two
Writer: Ehren Kruger, Kôji Suzuki (novel), Hiroshi Takahashi
Actors: Naomi Watts, Simon Baker, David Dorfman, Elizabeth Perkins
tomatoConsensus: Ring Two serves up horror cliches, and not even Hideo Nakata, the director of the movies from which this one is based, can save the movie from a dull screenplay full of absurdities.

Plot: A young boy wins a tour through the most magnificent chocolate factory in the world, led by the world's most unusual candy maker.
Title: Charlie and the Chocolate Factory

Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 15 wins & 46 nominations.

Plot: An architect's desire to speak with his wife from beyond the grave, becomes an obsession with supernatural repercussions.
Title: White Noise

Plot: A young detective goes undercover at an elite private school to destroy an international stolen car ring.

Writer: Brent Goldberg (story), David Wagner (story), Nick Cannon (story), David Wagner (screenplay), Brent Goldberg (screenplay)
Actors: Nick Cannon, Adrian Young, Art Bonilla, Bart McCarthy

Plot: When her husband unexpectedly disappears, a sharp-witted suburban wife and her daughters juggle their mom's romantic dilemmas and family dynamics.
Title: The Upside of Anger

Plot: Elektra the warrior survives a near-death experience, becomes an assassin-for-hire, and tries to protect her two latest targets, a single father and his young daughter, from a group of supernatural assassins.

Plot: An abandoned zebra grows up believing he is a racehorse, and, with the help of his barnyard friends and a teenage girl, sets out to achieve his dream of racing with thoroughbreds.
Title: Racing Stripes

Plot: Controversy surrounds high school basketball coach Ken Carter after he benches his entire team for breaking their academic contract with him.

Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Rob Brown, Robert Ri'chard, Rick Gonzalez
tomatoConsensus: Even though it's based on a true story, Coach Carter is pretty formulaic stuff, but it's effective and energetic, thanks to a strong central performance from Samuel L. Jackson.

Plot: A police sergeant must rally the cops and prisoners together to protect themselves on New Year's Eve, just as corrupt policeman surround the station with the intent of killing all to keep their deception in the ranks.
Title: Assault on Precinct 13
Actors: Ethan Hawke, Laurence Fishburne, Gabriel Byrne, Maria Bello
tomatoConsensus: This remake has been praised by some as an expertly made B-movie, and dismissed by others as formulaic.

Plot: Nick Persons is a selfish player who owns a collectables sports shop in Vancouver. Everything in his life is perfect until he meets Suzanne Kingston, a business woman who has something Nick...
Title: Are We There Yet?
Writer: Steven Gary Banks (story), Claudia Grazioso (story), Steven Gary Banks (screenplay), Claudia Grazioso (screenplay), J. David Stem (screenplay), David N. Weiss (screenplay)
Actors: Ice Cube, Nia Long, Aleisha Allen, Philip Bolden
tomatoConsensus: This supposed family comedy staring the usually blameless Ice Cube and Nia Long has provoked most critics to write, "Is it over yet?"

Plot: Based on the video game, Alone in the Dark focuses on Edward Carnby, a detective of the paranormal, who slowly unravels mysterious events with deadly results.
Title: Alone in the Dark
Writer: Elan Mastai, Michael Roesch, Peter Scheerer
Actors: Christian Slater, Tara Reid, Stephen Dorff, Frank C. Turner
tomatoConsensus: Inept on almost every level, Alone in the Dark may not work as a thriller, but it's good for some head-slapping, incredulous laughter.

Plot: As a widower tries to piece together his life in the wake of his wife's suicide, his daughter finds solace -- at first -- in her imaginary friend.
Title: Hide and Seek
Actors: Robert De Niro, Dakota Fanning, Famke Janssen, Elisabeth Shue
tomatoConsensus: Robert De Niro and especially Dakota Fanning have earned some praise for their work in Hide and Seek, but critics have called the rest of the film derivative, illogical and somewhat silly.

Plot: James Cameron teams up with NASA scientists to explore the Mid-Ocean Ridge, a submerged chain of mountains that band the Earth and are home to some of the planet's most unique life forms.
Title: Aliens of the Deep
Actors: Anatoly M. Sagalevitch, Genya Chernaiev, Victor Nischeta, Pamela Conrad
tomatoConsensus: An amazing array of images from beneath the sea.

Plot: A young man tries to deal with the childhood terror that has affected his life.
Title: Boogeyman
Writer: Eric Kripke (story), Eric Kripke (screenplay), Juliet Snowden (screenplay), Stiles White (screenplay)
Actors: Barry Watson, Emily Deschanel, Skye McCole Bartusiak, Tory Mussett
tomatoConsensus: The plot is been-there done-that generic, and none of the shock effects can do anything to build up suspense.

Plot: Single-girl anxiety causes Kat Ellis (Messing) to hire a male escort (Mulroney) to pose as her boyfriend at her sister's wedding. Her plan, an attempt to dupe her ex-fiancé, who dumped her a couple years prior, proves to be her undoing.
Title: The Wedding Date
Actors: Debra Messing, Dermot Mulroney, Amy Adams, Jack Davenport
tomatoConsensus: Critics are leaving The Wedding Date at the alter, calling it shopworn, bland, and lightweight.

Plot: While helping his latest client woo the fine lady of his dreams, a professional "date doctor" finds that his game doesn't quite work on the gossip columnist with whom he's smitten.
Title: Hitch
Actors: Will Smith, Eva Mendes, Kevin James, Amber Valletta
tomatoConsensus: Despite Hitch's predictability, Will Smith and Kevin James win praise for their solid, warmhearted performances.

Plot: A heffalump is heard trumpeting in the hundred acre woods. Winnie the Pooh, Tigger, and Piglet are scared and rush to Rabbit's house for advice. Roo joins them and they all agree that ...
Title: Pooh's Heffalump Movie
Writer: Brian Hohlfeld (screenplay), Evan Spiliotopoulos (screenplay), A.A. Milne (characters)
Actors: Jim Cummings, John Fiedler, Nikita Hopkins, Kath Soucie
tomatoConsensus: A charming and delightful walk through the Hundred Acres Woods for young viewers.

Plot: An examination of the infamous pornographic film Deep Throat (1972), covering aspects from the film's creation to its cultural impact.
Title: Inside Deep Throat
Actors: Dennis Hopper, Gerard Damiano, John Waters, Larry Flynt
tomatoConsensus: A documentary on the film that brought smut mainstream, Inside Deep Throat is gaining praise as an entertaining look at a pop culture milestone. However, some critics say the film could have gone a little deeper into the people involved.

Plot: Supernatural detective John Constantine helps a detective prove her sisters death was not a suicide, but something more.
Title: Constantine
Writer: Jamie Delano (comic book "Hellblazer"), Garth Ennis (comic book "Hellblazer"), Kevin Brodbin (story), Kevin Brodbin (screenplay), Frank A. Cappello (screenplay)
Actors: Keanu Reeves, Rachel Weisz, Shia LaBeouf, Djimon Hounsou
tomatoConsensus: Despite solid production values and an intriguing premise, Constantine lacks the focus of another spiritual shoot-em-up, The Matrix.

Plot: Tim Avery, an aspiring cartoonist, finds himself in a predicament when his dog stumbles upon the mask of Loki. Then after conceiving an infant son "born of the mask", he discovers just how looney child raising can be.
Title: Son of the Mask
Actors: Jamie Kennedy, Alan Cumming, Liam Falconer, Ryan Falconer
tomatoConsensus: Overly frantic, painfully unfunny, and sorely missing the presence of Jim Carrey.

Plot: A mischievous dog befriends a lonely young girl in a new town and helps her make new friends.
Title: Because of Winn-Dixie
Actors: AnnaSophia Robb, Jeff Daniels, Cicely Tyson, Dave Matthews
tomatoConsensus: An old-fashioned, if bland, adaptation of Kate DiCamillo's novel.

Title: Man of the House
Writer: John J. McLaughlin (story), Scott Lobdell (story), Robert Ramsey (screenplay), Matthew Stone (screenplay), John J. McLaughlin (screenplay)
Actors: Tommy Lee Jones, Cedric the Entertainer, Christina Milian, Paula Garcés
tomatoConsensus: A high-concept movie that plays out like a mediocre TV sitcom.

Plot: A couple's seemingly solid marriage begins to crumble when the wife discovers that her husband intends to divorce her.
Title: Diary of a Mad Black Woman
Actors: Kimberly Elise, Steve Harris, Tyler Perry, Shemar Moore
tomatoConsensus: Tyler Perry's successful play can't make the move to the screen; this mix of slapstick, melodrama and spirituality lacks a consistent tone.

Plot: Disgraced Navy SEAL Shane Wolfe is handed a new assignment: Protect the five Plummer kids from enemies of their recently deceased father -- a government scientist whose top-secret experiment remains in the kids' house.
Title: The Pacifier
Actors: Vin Diesel, Lauren Graham, Faith Ford, Brittany Snow
tomatoConsensus: Vin Diesel parodies his tough guy image for the family audience, but the result is only moderately amusing.

Plot: Disenchanted with the movie industry, Chili Palmer tries the music industry, meeting and romancing a widow of a music executive on the way.
Title: Be Cool
Actors: John Travolta, Uma Thurman, Vince Vaughn, Cedric the Entertainer
tomatoConsensus: Be Cool is tepid, square, and lukewarm; as a parody of the music business, it has two left feet.

Plot: A failed police negotiator turned small-town cop, must save the lives of a family held hostage, which draws him into a much more dangerous situation.
Title: Hostage
Actors: Bruce Willis, Kevin Pollak, Jimmy Bennett, Michelle Horn
tomatoConsensus: Grisly and cliched, audiences may feel they're being held Hostage.

Plot: In a robot world, a young idealistic inventor travels to the big city to join his inspiration's company, only to find himself opposing its sinister new management.
Title: Robots
Writer: Ron Mita (story), Jim McClain (story), David Lindsay-Abaire (story), David Lindsay-Abaire (screenplay), Lowell Ganz (screenplay), Babaloo Mandel (screenplay)
Actors: Paula Abdul, Halle Berry, Lucille Bliss, Terry Bradshaw
tomatoConsensus: Robots delights on a visual level, but the story feels like it came off an assembly line.

Plot: With the help of her coach, her mum, and the boy who drives the Zamboni machine, nothing can stop Casey (Trachtenberg) from realizing her dream to be a champion figure skater.
Title: Ice Princess
Writer: Meg Cabot (story), Hadley Davis (story), Hadley Davis (screenplay)
Actors: Michelle Trachtenberg, Joan Cusack, Amy Stewart, Steve Ross
tomatoConsensus: This likable Disney film gets points for effort, but can't stick the landing when it comes to originality.

Plot: After Cheryl Frasier and Stan Fields are kidnapped, Gracie goes undercover in Las Vegas to find them.
Title: Miss Congeniality 2: Armed and Fabulous
Writer: Marc Lawrence (characters), Katie Ford (characters), Caryn Lucas (characters), Marc Lawrence
Actors: Sandra Bullock, Regina King, Enrique Murciano, William Shatner
tomatoConsensus: Sandra Bullock is still as appealing as ever; too bad the movie is not pageant material.

Plot: A young woman, Theresa, brings her boyfriend, Simon, home to meet her parents and surprise them with the news of their engagement. Another surprise: Simon is white.
Title: Guess Who
Writer: William Rose (motion picture "Guess Who's Coming to Dinner"), David Ronn (story), Jay Scherick (story), David Ronn (screenplay), Jay Scherick (screenplay), Peter Tolan (screenplay)
Actors: Bernie Mac, Ashton Kutcher, Zoe Saldana, Judith Scott
tomatoConsensus: Despite the chemistry of its stars, Guess Who, a loose remake of Guess Who's Coming to Dinner, lacks the political relevance of the original.

Plot: A father and daughter isolated on an island off the East Coast and living on a once-thriving commune grapple with the limits of family and sexuality.
Title: The Ballad of Jack and Rose
Actors: Camilla Belle, Daniel Day-Lewis, Catherine Keener, Ryan McDonald
tomatoConsensus: Heavy on the symbolism and overly contrived.

Plot: A determined hairstylist (Queen Latifah) competes with her former boss (Kevin Bacon) after opening her own business in Atlanta.
Title: Beauty Shop
Writer: Elizabeth Hunter (story), Kate Lanier (screenplay), Norman Vance Jr. (screenplay)
Actors: Queen Latifah, Alicia Silverstone, Andie MacDowell, Alfre Woodard
tomatoConsensus: Despite a strong performance by Queen Latifah, Beauty Shop is in need of some style pointers.

Plot: A documentary on the Baja 1000, an annual off-road race held in Baja, Mexico that attracts hundreds of racers, their souped-up machines, and thousands of fans.
Title: Dust to Glory
Actors: Mario Andretti, Sal Fish, James Garner, Robby Gordon
tomatoConsensus: Amazing footage from the Baja off-road race will give viewers an adrenaline rush.

Plot: Master explorer Dirk Pitt goes on the adventure of a lifetime of seeking out a lost Civil War battleship known as the "Ship of Death" in the deserts of West Africa while helping a WHO doctor being hounded by a ruthless dictator.
Title: Sahara
Writer: Clive Cussler (novel), Thomas Dean Donnelly (screenplay), Joshua Oppenheimer (screenplay), John C. Richards (screenplay), James V. Hart (screenplay)
Actors: Matthew McConaughey, Steve Zahn, Penélope Cruz, William H. Macy
tomatoConsensus: A mindless adventure flick with a preposterous plot.

Plot: Lindsay is stuck in the middle of her relationship with Ben and his passion for the Boston Red Sox.
Title: Fever Pitch
Writer: Lowell Ganz (screenplay), Babaloo Mandel (screenplay), Nick Hornby (novel)
Actors: Drew Barrymore, Jimmy Fallon, Jason Spevack, Jack Kehler
tomatoConsensus: While not a home run, Fever Pitch has enough charm and on-screen chemistry between the two leads to make it a solid hit.

Plot: Newlyweds are terrorized by demonic forces after moving into a large house that was the site of a grisly mass murder a year before.
Title: The Amityville Horror
Writer: Scott Kosar (screenplay), Jay Anson (novel), Sandor Stern (earlier screenplay), George Lutz (material), Kathy Lutz (material)
Actors: Ryan Reynolds, Melissa George, Jesse James, Jimmy Bennett
tomatoConsensus: A so-so remake of a so-so original.

Plot: A small town Pinewood Derby competition transforms an average group of dads into an awkward bunch of competitors.
Title: Down and Derby
Actors: Greg Germann, Lauren Holly, Adam Hicks, Perry Anzilotti
tomatoConsensus: Dull, predictable family fare.

Plot: On a flight from Los Angeles to New York, Oliver and Emily make a connection, only to decide that they are poorly suited to be together. Over the next seven years, however, they are ...
Title: A Lot Like Love
Actors: Amanda Peet, Ashton Kutcher, Taryn Manning, Aimee Garcia
tomatoConsensus: A tiresome rom-com.

Plot: Hoping to foil his own gold-digging wife's plan, a loathsome businessman arranges his own kidnapping, only to realize that there are plenty of other people interested in his wealth as well.
Title: King's Ransom
Actors: Anthony Anderson, Jay Mohr, Kellita Smith, Nicole Ari Parker
tomatoConsensus: Filled with crass dialogue, unlikable characters, and overdone slapstick gags, King's Ransom is an utterly inept would-be comedy.

Plot: Based on a true story, this film tells the tale of the 1950 US soccer team who, against all odds, beat England 1 - 0 in the city of Belo Horizonte, Brazil. Although no US team has ever won a World Cup title, this story is about the family traditions and passions which shaped the lives of the players who made up this team of underdogs.
Title: The Game of Their Lives
Actors: Gerard Butler, Wes Bentley, Jay Rodan, Gavin Rossdale
tomatoConsensus: An enthusiastic but ultimately uninspired soccer film.

Plot: Corporate audio and videotapes tell the inside story of the scandal involving one company's manipulation of California's energy supply and its, and how its executives wrung a billion dollars out of the resulting crisis.
Title: Enron: The Smartest Guys in the Room
Writer: Bethany McLean (book), Peter Elkind (book), Alex Gibney
Actors: Peter Coyote, John Beard, Barbara Boxer, George W. Bush
tomatoConsensus: A concise, entertaining documentary about the spectacular failure of Enron.

Plot: Darius Stone, a new agent in the XXX program, is sent to Washington, DC to defuse a power struggle amongst national leaders.
Title: xXx: State of the Union
Actors: Willem Dafoe, Samuel L. Jackson, Ice Cube, Scott Speedman
tomatoConsensus: Even more absurd and implausible than the first XXX movie, State of the Union is less inspired and technically competent than its predecessor.

Plot: Balian of Ibelin travels to Jerusalem during the crusades of the 12th century, and there he finds himself as the defender of the city and its people.
Title: Kingdom of Heaven
Actors: Martin Hancock, Michael Sheen, Nathalie Cox, Eriq Ebouaney
tomatoConsensus: Although it's an objective and handsomely presented take on the Crusades, Kingdom of Heaven lacks depth.

Plot: A group of unwitting teens are stranded near a strange wax museum and soon must fight to survive and keep from becoming the next exhibit.
Title: House of Wax
Writer: Charles Belden (story), Chad Hayes (screenplay), Carey Hayes (screenplay)
Actors: Elisha Cuthbert, Chad Michael Murray, Brian Van Holt, Paris Hilton
tomatoConsensus: Bearing little resemblance to the 1953 original, House of Wax is a formulaic but better-than-average teen slasher flick.

Plot: A man enslaved by the mob since childhood and raised into behaving like a human attack dog escapes his captors and attempts to start a new life.
Title: Unleashed
Actors: Jet Li, Morgan Freeman, Bob Hoskins, Kerry Condon
tomatoConsensus: Jet Li gets to emote in some emotionally awkward scenes, but the gritty fight sequences come through in what is Li's best English language film.

Plot: Family man Phil Weston, a lifelong victim of his father's competitive nature, takes on the coaching duties of a kids' soccer team, and soon finds that he's also taking on his father's dysfunctional way of relating...
Title: Kicking & Screaming
Actors: Will Ferrell, Robert Duvall, Mike Ditka, Kate Walsh
tomatoConsensus: The script is mediocre and fails to give Ferrell a proper comedic showcase.

Plot: The love life of Charlotte is reduced to an endless string of disastrous blind dates, until she meets the perfect man, Kevin. Unfortunately, his merciless mother will do anything to destroy their relationship.
Title: Monster-in-Law
Actors: Jennifer Lopez, Jane Fonda, Michael Vartan, Wanda Sykes
tomatoConsensus: While Jane Fonda steals the movie in her return to the screen, a tired script and flimsy performances make this borderline comedy fall flat.

Plot: Spoiled by their upbringing with no idea what wild life is really like, four animals from New York Central Zoo escape, unwittingly assisted by four absconding penguins, and find themselves in Madagascar, among a bunch of merry lemurs
Title: Madagascar
Writer: Mark Burton, Billy Frolick, Eric Darnell, Tom McGrath
Actors: Ben Stiller, Chris Rock, David Schwimmer, Jada Pinkett Smith
tomatoConsensus: Though its story is problematic in spots and its humor is hit-or-miss for the adult crowd, Madagascar boasts impressive visuals and enough spunky charm to keep children entertained.

Plot: The students of several New York City elementary schools learn ballroom dancing and compete in a city wide dance competition.
Title: Mad Hot Ballroom
Actors: Heather Berman, Emma Therese Biegacki, Eva Carrozza, Evangelina Carrozzo
tomatoConsensus: This heartwarming documentary will win audiences over, as the sheer charm of precocious, enthusiastic children learning to dance resonates from the screen.

Title: The Longest Yard
Writer: Albert S. Ruddy (story), Tracy Keenan Wynn, Sheldon Turner (screenplay)
Actors: Adam Sandler, Chris Rock, Burt Reynolds, Nelly
tomatoConsensus: This Yard has some laughs but missing from this remake is the edginess of the original.

Plot: The story of James Braddock, a supposedly washed-up boxer who came back to become a champion and an inspiration in the 1930s.
Title: Cinderella Man
Writer: Cliff Hollingsworth (screenplay), Akiva Goldsman (screenplay), Cliff Hollingsworth (story)
Actors: Russell Crowe, Renée Zellweger, Paul Giamatti, Craig Bierko
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 16 wins & 40 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: With grittiness and an evocative sense of time and place, Cinderella Man is a powerful underdog story. And Ron Howard and Russell Crowe prove to be a solid combination.

Plot: Four best girlfriends hatch a plan to stay connected with one another as their lives start off in different directions: they pass around a pair of secondhand jeans that fits each of their bodies perfectly.
Title: The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants
Writer: Ann Brashares (novel), Delia Ephron (screenplay), Elizabeth Chandler (screenplay)
Actors: Amber Tamblyn, Alexis Bledel, America Ferrera, Blake Lively
tomatoConsensus: This adaptation of a beloved novel charms with its heartwarming tale of friendship and young adulthood; realistic portrayals of the lives of teenage girls lend the comedy-drama sincerity, and may capture hearts outside the female-centric demographic.

Plot: The film follows the surf and skateboarding trends that originated in Venice, California during the 1970's.
Title: Lords of Dogtown
Actors: John Robinson, Emile Hirsch, Rebecca De Mornay, William Mapother
tomatoConsensus: Lords of Dogtown, while slickly made and edited, lacks the depth and entertaining value of the far superior documentary on the same subject, Dogtown and Z-Boys.

Plot: A bored married couple is surprised to learn that they are both assassins hired by competing agencies to kill each other.
Title: Mr. & Mrs. Smith
Actors: Brad Pitt, Angelina Jolie, Vince Vaughn, Adam Brody
tomatoConsensus: Although this action-romance suffers from weak writing and one too many explosions, the chemistry generated by onscreen couple Pitt and Jolie is palpable enough to make this a thoroughly enjoyable summer action flick.

Plot: Working class New York bus driver Ralph Kramden is always coming up with get-rich-quick schemes for him and his best friend, Ed Norton, who's always around to help him get in (and out of) trouble.
Title: The Honeymooners
Writer: Danny Jacobson, David Sheffield, Barry W. Blaustein, Don Rhymer
Actors: Cedric the Entertainer, Mike Epps, Gabrielle Union, Regina Hall
tomatoConsensus: This pointless remake of the classic TV series only offers generic characters and gags.

Plot: After training with his mentor, Batman begins his fight to free crime-ridden Gotham City from the corruption that Scarecrow and the League of Shadows have cast upon it.
Title: Batman Begins
Writer: Bob Kane (characters), David S. Goyer (story), Christopher Nolan (screenplay), David S. Goyer (screenplay)
Actors: Christian Bale, Michael Caine, Liam Neeson, Katie Holmes
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 66 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Brooding and dark, but also exciting and smart, Batman Begins is a film that understands the essence of one of the definitive superheroes.

Plot: Teenager Holly Hamilton is tired of moving every time her single mom Jean has another personal meltdown involving yet another second-rate guy. To distract her mother from her latest bad ...
Title: The Perfect Man
Writer: Michael McQuown (story), Heather Robinson (story), Katherine Torpey (story), Gina Wendkos (screenplay)
Actors: Hilary Duff, Heather Locklear, Chris Noth, Mike O'Malley
tomatoConsensus: Preposterous and predictable, The Perfect Man manages few laughs with its poorly paced sitcom script, cookie-cutter characters and contrived plotting.

Plot: Spanning twenty-four hours, Heights follows five New Yorkers challenged to choose their destiny before the sun comes up the next day.
Title: Heights
Writer: Amy Fox (screenplay), Amy Fox (play), Chris Terrio (additional screenplay material)
Actors: Chandler Williams, Bess Wohl, Glenn Close, Elizabeth Banks
tomatoConsensus: Yet another movie about relationships in the Big Apple, Heights is never dull thanks to a competent cast.

Plot: Maggie Peyton, the new owner of Number 53 - the free-wheelin' Volkswagen bug with a mind of its own - puts the car through its paces on the road to becoming a NASCAR competitor.
Title: Herbie Fully Loaded
Writer: Thomas Lennon (screenplay), Robert Ben Garant (screenplay), Alfred Gough (screenplay), Miles Millar (screenplay), Thomas Lennon (story), Robert Ben Garant (story), Mark Perez (story), Gordon Buford (characters)
Actors: Lindsay Lohan, Michael Keaton, Matt Dillon, Breckin Meyer
tomatoConsensus: Herbie: Fully Loaded is a decent kids movie that is pretty undemanding for adult viewers.

Plot: The living dead have taken over the world, and the last humans live in a walled city to protect themselves as they come to grips with the situation.
Title: Land of the Dead
Actors: Simon Baker, John Leguizamo, Dennis Hopper, Asia Argento
tomatoConsensus: George A. Romero's latest entry in his much-vaunted Dead series is not as fresh as his genre-inventing original, Night of the Living Dead. But Land of the Dead does deliver on the gore and zombies-feasting-on-flesh action.

Plot: Thinking he can overshadow an unknown actress in the part, an egocentric actor unknowingly gets a witch cast in an upcoming television remake of the classic sitcom Bewitched (1964).
Title: Bewitched
Writer: Nora Ephron, Delia Ephron, Sol Saks (television series)
Actors: Nicole Kidman, Will Ferrell, Shirley MacLaine, Michael Caine
tomatoConsensus: Bewitched is haunted by scattered laughs and a lack of direction.

Title: Rize
Actors: Larry Berry, Tommy the Clown, Dragon, Jassy Marie
tomatoConsensus: The dances in Rize are electric even if the documentary doesn't go that deeply into the performers' lives.

Plot: A lonely shoe salesman and an eccentric performance artist struggle to connect in this unique take on contemporary life.
Title: Me and You and Everyone We Know
Actors: John Hawkes, Miranda July, Miles Thompson, Brandon Ratcliff
tomatoConsensus: Miranda July's debut feature is a charmingly offbeat and observant film about people looking for love.

Plot: As Earth is invaded by alien tripod fighting machines, one family fights for survival.
Title: War of the Worlds
Writer: Josh Friedman (screenplay), David Koepp (screenplay), H.G. Wells (novel)
Actors: Tom Cruise, Dakota Fanning, Miranda Otto, Justin Chatwin
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 13 wins & 40 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Steven Spielberg's adaptation of War of the Worlds delivers on the thrill and paranoia of H.G. Wells' classic novel while impressively updating the action and effects for modern audiences.

Plot: In the Antarctic, every March since the beginning of time, the quest begins to find the perfect mate and start a family.
Title: March of the Penguins
Writer: Luc Jacquet (scenario), Luc Jacquet (adaptation), Michel Fessler (adaptation), Jordan Roberts (narration: US edited version)
Actors: Charles Berling, Romane Bohringer, Jules Sitruk, Morgan Freeman
tomatoConsensus: Only the most hardened soul won't be moved by this heartwarming doc.

Plot: An acclaimed college basketball coach is demoted to a junior varsity team after a public meltdown.
Title: Rebound
Writer: William Wolff (story), Ed Decter (story), John J. Strauss (story), Jon Lucas (screenplay), Scott Moore (screenplay)
Actors: Martin Lawrence, Wendy Raquel Robinson, Breckin Meyer, Horatio Sanz
tomatoConsensus: Rebound ought to entertain its target audience, but there's nothing here for those who've seen The Bad News Bears or its countless derivatives.

Plot: A mother and daughter, still wounded from a bitter custody dispute, hole up in a run-down apartment building. Adding further drama to their plight, they are targeted by the ghost of former resident.
Title: Dark Water
Writer: Kôji Suzuki (novel), Hideo Nakata (film Honogurai mizu no soko kara), Takashige Ichise (film Honogurai mizu no soko kara), Rafael Yglesias (screenplay)
Actors: Jennifer Connelly, John C. Reilly, Tim Roth, Dougray Scott
tomatoConsensus: All the atmospherics in Dark Water can't make up for the lack of genuine scares.

Plot: Will Thomas still lead a life of crime and cruelty, just like his thuggish father, or will he pursue his dream of becoming a pianist?
Title: The Beat That My Heart Skipped
Writer: Jacques Audiard (scenario), Tonino Benacquista (scenario), James Toback (earlier screenplay: d'après le film "Fingers" écrit et réalisé par)
Actors: Romain Duris, Niels Arestrup, Jonathan Zaccaï, Gilles Cohen
Awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 20 wins & 12 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Stylish and visceral, this able remake is infused with realism, grit, and a taut performance by star Romain Duris.

Plot: A group of astronauts gain superpowers after a cosmic radiation exposure and must use them to oppose the plans of their enemy, Doctor Victor Von Doom.
Title: Fantastic Four
Writer: Mark Frost, Michael France, Stan Lee (Marvel comic book), Jack Kirby (Marvel comic book)
Actors: Ioan Gruffudd, Jessica Alba, Chris Evans, Michael Chiklis
tomatoConsensus: Marred by goofy attempts at wit, subpar acting, and bland storytelling, Fantastic Four is a mediocre attempt to bring Marvel's oldest hero team to the big screen.

Plot: Quadriplegics, who play full-contact rugby in wheelchairs, overcome unimaginable obstacles to compete in the Paralympic Games in Athens, Greece.
Title: Murderball
Director: Henry Alex Rubin, Dana Adam Shapiro
Actors: Joe Bishop, Keith Cavill, Andy Cohn, Scott Hogsett
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 17 wins & 12 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: An entertaining and gripping documentary that shows being confined to a wheelchair doesn't mean the fun has to end.

Plot: John Beckwith and Jeremy Grey, a pair of committed womanizers who sneak into weddings to take advantage of the romantic tinge in the air, find themselves at odds with one another when John meets and falls for Claire Cleary.
Title: Wedding Crashers
Actors: Owen Wilson, Vince Vaughn, Christopher Walken, Rachel McAdams
tomatoConsensus: Wedding Crashers is both raunchy and sweet, and features top-notch comic performances from Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson.

Plot: Happy Endings weaves multiple stories to create a witty look at love, family and the sheer unpredictablity of life itself.
Title: Happy Endings
Actors: Lisa Kudrow, Steve Coogan, Jesse Bradford, Bobby Cannavale
tomatoConsensus: Despite strong individual performances, the overlong, disjointed plot of Happy Endings self-indulgently rambles.

Plot: With help from his friends, a Memphis pimp in a mid-life crisis attempts to become a successful hip-hop emcee.
Title: Hustle & Flow
Actors: Terrence Howard, Anthony Anderson, Taryn Manning, Taraji P. Henson
tomatoConsensus: Hustle & Flow is gritty and redemptive, with a profound sense of place and exciting music.

Plot: Lincoln Six Echo is just like everyone else - he's waiting to go to the Island, the only place left in the world to actually live a life. Thousands of people stay at a facility waiting to ...
Title: The Island
Writer: Caspian Tredwell-Owen (screenplay), Alex Kurtzman (screenplay), Roberto Orci (screenplay), Caspian Tredwell-Owen (story)
Actors: Ewan McGregor, Scarlett Johansson, Djimon Hounsou, Sean Bean
tomatoConsensus: A clone of THX 1183, Coma, and Logan's Run, The Island is another loud and bombastic Michael Bay movie where explosions and chases matter more than characters, dialogue, or plot.

Plot: The murderous, backwoods Firefly family take to the road to escape a vengeful police force which is not afraid of being as ruthless as their target.
Title: The Devil's Rejects
Actors: Sid Haig, Bill Moseley, Sheri Moon Zombie, William Forsythe
tomatoConsensus: Zombie has improved as a filmmaker since "House of 1000 Corpses" and will please fans of the genre, but beware -- the horror is nasty, relentless, and sadistic.

Plot: A Seattle musician's life and career are reminiscent to those of Kurt Cobain.
Title: Last Days
Actors: Michael Pitt, Lukas Haas, Asia Argento, Scott Patrick Green
tomatoConsensus: While the minimalist style is not for all viewers, those who prefer experimentalism will find Last Days hypnotic.

Plot: Set in an era where superheroes are commonly known and accepted, young William Stronghold, the son of the Commander and Jetstream, tries to find a balance between being a normal teenager and an extraordinary being.
Title: Sky High
Writer: Paul Hernandez, Robert Schooley, Mark McCorkle
Actors: Michael Angarano, Kurt Russell, Kelly Preston, Danielle Panabaker
tomatoConsensus: This highly derivative superhero coming-of-age flick is moderately entertaining, family-friendly fluff.

Plot: Deeply ensconced in a top-secret military program, three pilots struggle to bring an artificial intelligence program under control before it initiates the next world war.
Title: Stealth
Actors: Josh Lucas, Jessica Biel, Jamie Foxx, Sam Shepard
tomatoConsensus: Loud, preposterous, and predictable, Stealth borrows heavily and unsucessfully from Top Gun and 2001.

Plot: A forty-something preschool teacher looks to the personals for a change of pace and a relationship, with hilarious results.
Title: Must Love Dogs
Actors: Diane Lane, John Cusack, Elizabeth Perkins, Christopher Plummer
tomatoConsensus: Despite good work from its likable leads, the romantic comedy Must Love Dogs is too predictable.

Plot: The crew of the ship Serenity try to evade an assassin sent to recapture one of their numbers who is telepathic.
Title: Serenity
Actors: Nathan Fillion, Gina Torres, Alan Tudyk, Morena Baccarin
tomatoConsensus: Snappy dialogue and goofy characters make this Wild Wild West soap opera in space fun and adventurous.

Plot: As the extremely withdrawn Don Johnston is dumped by his latest woman, he receives an anonymous letter from a former lover informing him that he has a son who may be looking for him. A freelance sleuth neighbor moves Don to embark on a cross-country search for his old flames in search of answers.
Title: Broken Flowers
Writer: Jim Jarmusch, Bill Raden (inspired by an idea from), Sara Driver (inspired by an idea from)
Actors: Bill Murray, Julie Delpy, Heather Simms, Brea Frazier
tomatoConsensus: Bill Murray's subtle and understated style complements director Jim Jarmusch's minimalist storytelling in this quirky, but deadpan comedy.

Plot: Cousins Bo, Luke, and Daisy Duke, and their uncle Jesse, egg on the authorities of Hazzard County, Boss Hogg and Sheriff Coltrane.
Title: The Dukes of Hazzard
Writer: John O'Brien (screenplay), John O'Brien (story), Jonathan L. Davis (story), Gy Waldron (characters)
Actors: Johnny Knoxville, Seann William Scott, Alice Greczyn, Steve Lemme
tomatoConsensus: A dumb, goofy, and vacuous adaptation of a TV show where plot is simply an excuse to string together the car chases.

Plot: A dealer in "outsider" art travels from Chicago to North Carolina to meet her new in-laws, challenging the equilibrium of this middle class Southern home.
Title: Junebug
Actors: Embeth Davidtz, David Kuhn, Alessandro Nivola, Alicia Van Couvering
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 21 wins & 25 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Aided and abetted by a wonderful cast, director Phil Morrison transforms familiar material into an understated and resonant comedy.

Plot: Deuce is tricked again into man-whoring by T.J., only in Amsterdam while other man-whores are being murdered in his midst.
Title: Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo
Writer: Harris Goldberg (characters), Rob Schneider (characters), Rob Schneider (story), Rob Schneider (screenplay), David Garrett (screenplay), Jason Ward (screenplay)
Actors: Rob Schneider, Eddie Griffin, Jeroen Krabbé, Til Schweiger
tomatoConsensus: A witless follow-up to the surprise 1999 hit, Deuce Bigalow: European Gigolo is raunchy, politically incorrect, and not particularly funny.

Plot: A hospice nurse working at a spooky New Orleans plantation home finds herself entangled in a mystery involving the house's dark past.
Title: The Skeleton Key
Actors: Kate Hudson, Gena Rowlands, John Hurt, Peter Sarsgaard
tomatoConsensus: Thanks to its creaky and formulaic script, The Skeleton Key is more mumbo-jumbo than hoodoo and more dull than scary.

Plot: Taking place towards the end of WWII, 500 American Soldiers have been entrapped in a camp for 3 years. Beginning to give up hope they will ever be rescued, a group of Rangers goes on a dangerous mission to try and save them.
Title: The Great Raid
Writer: William B. Breuer (book), Hampton Sides (book), Carlo Bernard (screenplay), Doug Miro (screenplay)
Actors: Benjamin Bratt, James Franco, Robert Mammone, Max Martini
tomatoConsensus: Though the climax of the film -- the actual raid -- is exciting, the rest of it is bogged down in too many subplots and runs on for too long.

Plot: A 15-year-old girl incites chaos among her friends and a media frenzy when she accuses her drama teacher of sexual harassment.
Title: Pretty Persuasion
Actors: Evan Rachel Wood, David Wagner, Brent Goldberg, Adi Schnall
tomatoConsensus: Pretty Persuasion aims for high satire but falls short of poignancy by depending on too much black humor, with too little redeeming humanity to provide balance.

Plot: A devastating and heartrending take on grizzly bear activists Timothy Treadwell and Amie Huguenard, who were killed in October of 2003 while living among grizzlies in Alaska.
Title: Grizzly Man
Actors: Werner Herzog, Carol Dexter, Val Dexter, Sam Egli
tomatoConsensus: Whatever opinion you come to have of the obsessive Treadwell, Herzog has once again found a fascinating subject.

Plot: An orphaned cheetah becomes the best friend and pet of a young boy living in South Africa.
Title: Duma
Writer: Carol Cawthra Hopcraft (book), Xan Hopcraft (book), Carol Flint (story), Karen Janszen (story), Karen Janszen (screenplay), Mark St. Germain (screenplay)
Actors: Alex Michaeletos, Campbell Scott, Mary Makhatho, Nthabiseng Kenoshi
tomatoConsensus: This is an old-fashioned, richly textured family film that will appeal to children and adults alike.

Plot: Goaded by his buddies, a nerdy guy who's never "done the deed" only finds the pressure mounting when he meets a single mother.
Title: The 40-Year-Old Virgin
Actors: Steve Carell, Catherine Keener, Paul Rudd, Romany Malco
tomatoConsensus: Steve Carell's first star turn scores big with a tender treatment of its titular underdog, using raunchy but realistically funny comedy to connect with adult audiences.

Plot: A woman is kidnapped by a stranger on a routine flight. Threatened by the potential murder of her father, she is pulled into a plot to assist her captor in offing a politician.
Title: Red Eye
Writer: Carl Ellsworth (screenplay), Carl Ellsworth (story), Dan Foos (story)
Actors: Rachel McAdams, Cillian Murphy, Brian Cox, Laura Johnson
tomatoConsensus: With solid performances and tight direction from Wes Craven, Red Eye is a brisk, economic thriller.

Plot: Faced with the suspicious death of their father, two brothers must motivate one another to get back on their bikes and take the Las Vegas Motocross Championships by storm.
Title: Supercross
Writer: Ken Solarz (screenplay), Bart Baker (screenplay), Bart Baker (story), Keith Alan Bernstein (story)
Actors: Steve Howey, Mike Vogel, Cameron Richardson, Sophia Bush
tomatoConsensus: While it showcases some cool stunts, Supercross feels like an infomercial for its titular sport, with undeveloped characters and a shopworn plot.

Plot: Set in 1944, Valiant is a woodland pigeon who wants to become a great hero someday. When he hears they are hiring recruits for the Royal Homing Pigeon Service, he immediately sets out for ...
Title: Valiant
Writer: George Webster (story), Jordan Katz (screenplay), George Webster (screenplay), George Melrod (screenplay)
Actors: Ewan McGregor, Ricky Gervais, Tim Curry, Jim Broadbent
tomatoConsensus: Valiant has a good collection of voice talents, but the story is strictly by-the-numbers.

Plot: Bloodthirsty creatures await a pack of divers who become trapped in an underwater cave network.
Title: The Cave
Actors: Cole Hauser, Eddie Cibrian, Morris Chestnut, Lena Headey
tomatoConsensus: Despite its stylized and impressive sets, this horror-monster movie mish-mash suffers from endless cliches and wildly implausible plotlines.

Plot: A group of aspiring entertainers try to establish careers for themselves in the city of Los Angeles.
Title: Undiscovered
Actors: Pell James, Steven Strait, Kip Pardue, Carrie Fisher
tomatoConsensus: Undiscovered, a film about aspiring actresses and musicians, lacks originality and a convincing plot.

Plot: A widower is determined to get to the bottom of a potentially explosive secret involving his wife's murder, big business, and corporate corruption.
Title: The Constant Gardener
Writer: Jeffrey Caine (screenplay), John le Carré (based on the novel by)
Actors: Ralph Fiennes, Rachel Weisz, Hubert Koundé, Danny Huston
tomatoConsensus: The Constant Gardener is a smart, gripping, and suspenseful thriller with rich performances from the leads.

Plot: A lonely landscape architect falls for the spirit of the beautiful woman who used to live in his new apartment.
Title: Just Like Heaven
Writer: Peter Tolan (screenplay), Leslie Dixon (screenplay), Marc Lévy (novel)
Actors: Reese Witherspoon, Mark Ruffalo, Donal Logue, Dina Spybey-Waters
tomatoConsensus: Delightfully sweet like a lollipop, Just Like Heaven is a dreamy romantic comedy that may give you a toothache when it attempts to broach difficult end of life issues by throwing a cherry on top.

Plot: The daughter of a brilliant but mentally disturbed mathematician, recently deceased, tries to come to grips with her possible inheritance: his insanity. Complicating matters are one of her father's ex-students, who wants to search through his papers, and her estranged sister, who shows up to help settle his affairs.
Title: Proof
Writer: David Auburn (play), David Auburn (screenplay), Rebecca Miller (screenplay)
Actors: Gwyneth Paltrow, Anthony Hopkins, Jake Gyllenhaal, Danny McCarthy
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Gwyneth Paltrow and Anthony Hopkins give exceptional performances in a film that intelligently tackles the territory between madness and genius.

Plot: An arms dealer confronts the morality of his work as he is being chased by an Interpol agent.
Language: English, Ukrainian, German, Spanish, Russian, French, Arabic, Turkish
Title: Lord of War
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Bridget Moynahan, Jared Leto, Shake Tukhmanyan
tomatoConsensus: While Lord of War is an intelligent examination of the gun trade, it is too scattershot in its plotting to connect.

Plot: A group of teenagers run for their lives through the swamps of Louisiana, chased by Mr. Jangles, a man possessed by 13 evil souls, and now relentless in his pursuit of new victims.
Title: Venom
Writer: Flint Dille (screenplay), John Zuur Platten (screenplay), Brandon Boyce (screenplay), Flint Dille (story), John Zuur Platten (story)
Actors: Agnes Bruckner, Jonathan Jackson, Laura Ramsey, D.J. Cotrona
tomatoConsensus: A voodoo horror flick without the mojo, Venom is chock full of gory impalings of interchangeable teenage girls and hunky guys by an unstoppable zombie whose unimaginative rampage quickly lulls us to sleep.

Plot: A young Jewish American man endeavors to find the woman who saved his grandfather during World War II in a Ukrainian village, that was ultimately razed by the Nazis, with the help of an eccentric local.
Title: Everything Is Illuminated
Actors: Eugene Hutz, Elijah Wood, Jonathan Safran Foer, Jana Hrabetova
tomatoConsensus: Although it excises much from its famously dense source material, Everything is Illuminated is a quirky, ambitious debut film from Liev Schreiber.

Plot: Justin throws himself and everyone around him into chaos when he attempts to break free from his addiction to his thumb.
Title: Thumbsucker
Actors: Ted Beckman, Benjamin Bratt, Vincent D'Onofrio, Arvin V. Entena
tomatoConsensus: Though quirky coming-of-age themes are common in indie films, this one boasts a smart script and a great cast.

Plot: Ben's dad Sam shows up one night with a note from Ben's mother (Sam's wife of 46 years), that she has left. While Ben's wife and his three sisters try to find her, Ben takes Sam on a day ...
Title: The Thing About My Folks
Actors: Peter Falk, Paul Reiser, Olympia Dukakis, Elizabeth Perkins
tomatoConsensus: The Thing About My Folks lacks cohesiveness, and the cloying tone makes the talkiness grating.

Plot: Is American foreign policy dominated by the idea of military supremacy? Has the military become too important in American life? Jarecki's shrewd and intelligent polemic would seem to give an affirmative answer to each of these questions.
Title: Why We Fight
Actors: Ken Adelman, John Ashcroft, Osama bin Laden, George Bush
tomatoConsensus: A provocative and timely film that explores the military/industrial complex and the motivating forces that lead us to war.

Plot: Space Marines are sent to investigate strange events at a research facility on Mars but find themselves at the mercy of genetically enhanced killing machines.
Title: Doom
Writer: Dave Callaham (screenplay), Wesley Strick (screenplay), Dave Callaham (story)
Actors: Karl Urban, Rosamund Pike, Deobia Oparei, Ben Daniels
tomatoConsensus: Sure to please fans of the video game, but lacking in plot and originality to please other moviegoers.

Plot: Young employees at Shenaniganz restaurant collectively stave off boredom and adulthood with their antics.
Title: Waiting...
Actors: Ryan Reynolds, Anna Faris, Justin Long, David Koechner
tomatoConsensus: Waiting... is a gross-out comedy that is more gross than comic.

Plot: Aeon Flux is a mysterious assassin working for the Monicans, a group of rebels trying to overthrow the government. When she is sent on a mission to kill the Chairman, a whole new mystery is found.
Title: Æon Flux
Writer: Phil Hay, Matt Manfredi, Peter Chung (characters)
Actors: Charlize Theron, Marton Csokas, Jonny Lee Miller, Sophie Okonedo
tomatoConsensus: Aeon Flux lacks the gravity-defying pace of its animated predecessor, and, despite some flash, is largely a dull affair.

Plot: Desperate to provide care for her daughter, down-on-her-luck Jean moves in with her father in-law from whom she is estranged. Through time, they learn to forgive each other and heal old wounds.
Title: An Unfinished Life
Actors: Robert Redford, Jennifer Lopez, Morgan Freeman, Josh Lucas
tomatoConsensus: A story of disjointed family members yearning for true emotional depth, An Unfinished Life teeters between overtly saccharine sentiments and moments of real intimacy.

Plot: Special Agent Derrick Vann is a man out to get the man who killed his partner but a case of mistaken identity leads him to Andy Fidler, a salesman with too many questions and a knack of getting in Vanns way.
Title: The Man
Writer: Jim Piddock (screenplay), Margaret Oberman (screenplay), Stephen Carpenter (screenplay), Jim Piddock (story), Margaret Oberman (story)
Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Eugene Levy, Miguel Ferrer, Luke Goss
tomatoConsensus: Despite the steely presence of Samuel L. Jackson and the comic timing of Eugene Levy, The Man's plot is pointless and its jokes rehashed, as it ends up playing out like the Odd Couple with gas.

Plot: A bereaved woman and her daughter are flying home from Berlin to America. At 30,000 feet, the child vanishes, and nobody will admit she was ever on the plane.
Language: English, French, German, Arabic, Italian, Japanese
Title: Flightplan
Actors: Jodie Foster, Peter Sarsgaard, Sean Bean, Kate Beahan
tomatoConsensus: The actors are all on key here, but as the movie progress, tension deflates as the far-fetched plot kicks in.

Plot: When a shy groom practices his wedding vows in the inadvertent presence of a deceased young woman, she rises from the grave assuming he has married her.
Title: Corpse Bride
Writer: Tim Burton (characters), Carlos Grangel (characters), John August (screenplay), Caroline Thompson (screenplay), Pamela Pettler (screenplay)
Actors: Johnny Depp, Helena Bonham Carter, Emily Watson, Tracey Ullman
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 26 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: As can be expected from a Tim Burton movie, Corpse Bride is whimsically macabre, visually imaginative, and emotionally bittersweet.

Plot: A wrongfully expelled Harvard undergrad moves to London, where he is introduced to the violent underworld of football hooliganism.
Title: Green Street Hooligans
Writer: Lexi Alexander (story), Dougie Brimson (story), Dougie Brimson (screenplay), Josh Shelov (screenplay), Lexi Alexander (screenplay)
Actors: Elijah Wood, Charlie Hunnam, Claire Forlani, Marc Warren
tomatoConsensus: When it comes to the subculture of soccer thugs, Green Street Hooligans lacks sufficient insight, and instead comes off as a Fight Club knock-off.

Plot: A mild-mannered man becomes a local hero through an act of violence, which sets off repercussions that will shake his family to its very core.
Title: A History of Violence
Writer: John Wagner (graphic novel), Vince Locke (graphic novel), Josh Olson (screenplay)
Actors: Viggo Mortensen, Maria Bello, Ed Harris, William Hurt
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 35 wins & 72 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A History of Violence raises compelling and thoughtful questions about the nature of violence, while representing a return to form for director David Cronenberg in one of his more uncharacteristic pieces.

Plot: In the 1913 US Open, 20-year-old Francis Ouimet played against his idol, 1900 US Open champion, Englishman Harry Vardon.
Title: The Greatest Game Ever Played
Actors: James Paxton, Tom Rack, Armand Laroche, Peter Hurley
tomatoConsensus: Despite all the underdog sports movie conventions, the likable cast and lush production values make The Greatest Game Ever Played a solid and uplifting tale.

Plot: In 1959, Truman Capote learns of the murder of a Kansas family and decides to write a book about the case. While researching for his novel In Cold Blood, Capote forms a relationship with one of the killers, Perry Smith, who is on death row.
Title: Capote
Actors: Allie Mickelson, Kelci Stephenson, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Craig Archibald
tomatoConsensus: Philip Seymour Hoffman's riveting central performance guides a well-constructed retelling of the most sensational and significant period in author Truman Capote's life.

Plot: A group of divers find themselves in deep trouble with a drug lord after they come upon the illicit cargo of a sunken airplane.
Title: Into the Blue
Actors: Paul Walker, Jessica Alba, Scott Caan, Ashley Scott
tomatoConsensus: Even the endless shots of bronzed beach babes and buffed dudes can't keep this soggy scuba flick's plot from drowning.

Plot: In order to support her ten children, Evelyn Ryan (Moore) enters a commercial jingle-writing contest. Based on a true story.
Title: The Prize Winner of Defiance, Ohio
Actors: Julianne Moore, Woody Harrelson, Laura Dern, Trevor Morgan
tomatoConsensus: Noteworthy for Julianne Moore's performance, Prize Winner is nonetheless a largely indistinct and tentative film that fails to convey the true power of its bittersweet tale.

Plot: In a fantasy world of opposing kingdoms, a 15-year old girl must find the fabled MirrorMask in order to save the kingdom and get home.
Title: Mirrormask
Writer: Neil Gaiman (story), Dave McKean (story), Neil Gaiman (teleplay)
Actors: Stephanie Leonidas, Jason Barry, Rob Brydon, Gina McKee
tomatoConsensus: While visually dazzling, there isn't enough story to hang all the fancy effects on.

Plot: Wallace and his loyal dog, Gromit, set out to discover the mystery behind the garden sabotage that plagues their village and threatens the annual giant vegetable growing contest.
Title: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit
Writer: Steve Box (screenplay), Nick Park (screenplay), Mark Burton (screenplay), Bob Baker (screenplay), Nick Park (based on characters by)
Actors: Peter Sallis, Ralph Fiennes, Helena Bonham Carter, Peter Kay
tomatoConsensus: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit is a subtly touching and wonderfully eccentric adventure featuring Wallace and Gromit.

Plot: A murder mystery brings together a private eye, a struggling actress, and a thief masquerading as an actor.
Title: Kiss Kiss Bang Bang
Writer: Brett Halliday (novel), Shane Black (screen story), Shane Black (screenplay)
Actors: Robert Downey Jr., Val Kilmer, Michelle Monaghan, Corbin Bernsen
tomatoConsensus: Tongue-in-cheek satire blends well with entertaining action and spot-on performances in this dark, eclectic neo-noir homage.

Plot: The extremely talented Santiago Munez is given a chance at professional football, after being spotted by a scout who has ties with Newcastle United.
Title: Goal! The Dream Begins
Writer: Mike Jefferies (story), Adrian Butchart (screenplay), Dick Clement (screenplay), Ian La Frenais (screenplay), Mike Jefferies (screenplay)
Actors: Leonardo Guerra, Tony Plana, Miriam Colon, Kuno Becker
tomatoConsensus: Impressive sports action sequences are the highlight, as the run-of the-mill story invokes every known sports movie cliche.

Plot: This drama centers on Hank Chinaski, the fictional alter-ego of "Factotum" author Charles Bukowski, who wanders around Los Angeles, CA trying to live off jobs which don't interfere with his primary interest, which is writing. Along the way, he fends off the distractions offered by women, drinking and gambling.
Title: Factotum
Writer: Charles Bukowski (novel), Bent Hamer, Jim Stark
Actors: Matt Dillon, Lili Taylor, Didier Flamand, Fisher Stevens
tomatoConsensus: Matt Dillon's performance is the highlight of this somewhat slow but fascinating portrayal of Charles Bukowski's alter-ego.

Plot: Howard Spence (Sam Shepard) has seen better days. Once a big Western movie star, he now drowns his disgust for his selfish and failed life with alcohol, drugs and young women. If he were to...
Title: Don't Come Knocking
Writer: Sam Shepard (screenplay), Sam Shepard (story), Wim Wenders (story)
Actors: James Roday, Jeffrey Vincent Parise, Majandra Delfino, Marieh Delfino
tomatoConsensus: The cinematography conjures beautifully evocative landscapes, but aside from that, the film is meandering and pointless.

Plot: Strait-laced Rose breaks off relations with her party girl sister, Maggie, over an indiscretion involving Rose's boyfriend. The chilly atmosphere is broken with the arrival of Ella, the grandmother neither sister knew existed.
Title: In Her Shoes
Writer: Jennifer Weiner (based on the novel by), Susannah Grant (screenplay)
Actors: Cameron Diaz, Anson Mount, Toni Collette, Richard Burgi
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 6 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Honesty and solid performances make In Her Shoes a solid fit for all audiences.

Plot: Follows two young boys dealing with their parents' divorce in Brooklyn in the 1980s.
Title: The Squid and the Whale
Actors: Owen Kline, Jeff Daniels, Laura Linney, Jesse Eisenberg
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 23 wins & 47 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This is a piercingly honest, acidly witty look at divorce and its impact on a family.

Plot: After suffering a career-ending injury, a former college football star aligns himself with one of the most renowned touts in the sports-gambling business.
Title: Two for the Money
Actors: Al Pacino, Matthew McConaughey, Rene Russo, Armand Assante
tomatoConsensus: Despite its sportsmanlike swagger, Two for the Money's aimless plot isn't worth betting on.

Plot: A couple's marriage is complicated by the introduction of a third party.
Title: Separate Lies
Writer: Nigel Balchin (based on the novel by "A Way Through the Wood"), Julian Fellowes
Actors: Tom Wilkinson, Emily Watson, Hermione Norris, John Warnaby
tomatoConsensus: Though the characters in this tasteful adult drama keep a stiff upper lip, the moral dilemmas are nuanced and the emotional pain feels real.

Plot: The story of a forbidden and secretive relationship between two cowboys, and their lives over the years.
Title: Brokeback Mountain
Writer: Annie Proulx (short story), Larry McMurtry (screenplay), Diana Ossana (screenplay)
Actors: Heath Ledger, Jake Gyllenhaal, Randy Quaid, Valerie Planche
tomatoConsensus: A beautiful, epic Western, Brokeback Mountain's love story is imbued with heartbreaking universality thanks to moving performances by Heath Ledger and Jake Gyllenhaal.

Title: Elizabethtown
Actors: Orlando Bloom, Kirsten Dunst, Susan Sarandon, Alec Baldwin
tomatoConsensus: This story of a floundering shoe designer who returns home for a family tragedy gets lost in undeveloped plot lines and lackluster performances.

Plot: A fictionalized account of the first major successful sexual harassment case in the United States -- Jenson vs. Eveleth Mines, where a woman who endured a range of abuse while working as a miner filed and won the landmark 1984 lawsuit.
Title: North Country
Writer: Michael Seitzman (screenplay), Clara Bingham (book), Laura Leedy (book)
Actors: Charlize Theron, Thomas Curtis, Elle Peterson, Frances McDormand
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 17 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though sometimes melodramatic and formulaic, North Country is nonetheless a rousing, powerful story of courage and humanity.

Plot: Broadcast journalist Edward R. Murrow looks to bring down Senator Joseph McCarthy.
Title: Good Night, and Good Luck.
Actors: Jeff Daniels, David Strathairn, Alex Borstein, Rose Abdoo
Awards: Nominated for 6 Oscars. Another 38 wins & 119 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A passionate and concise cinematic civics lesson, Good Night, And Good Luck has plenty to say about today's political and cultural climate, and its ensemble cast is stellar.

Plot: Cale Crane catalyzes the rescue and rehabilitation of Sonador, a race horse with a broken leg.
Title: Dreamer: Inspired by a True Story
Actors: Kurt Russell, Dakota Fanning, Kris Kristofferson, Elisabeth Shue
tomatoConsensus: Though formulaic, this horse story's saving grace is its strong performances.

Plot: A lawman apprehends a notorious outlaw and gives him nine days to kill his older brother, or else they'll execute his younger brother.
Title: The Proposition
Actors: Richard Wilson, Noah Taylor, Jeremy Madrona, Jae Mamuyac
tomatoConsensus: Brutal, unflinching, and violent, but thought-provoking and with excellent performances, this Australian western is the one of the best examples of the genre to come along in recent times.

Plot: This is a story about a successful young R&B; singer that has an unlikely homecoming when his father, the bishop, becomes ill.
Title: The Gospel
Actors: Boris Kodjoe, Idris Elba, Nona Gaye, Clifton Powell
tomatoConsensus: While it features outstanding musical numbers, The Gospel reduces a series of worthy themes -- faith, family, forgiveness -- to soapy, banal clichés.

Plot: The inhabitants of Antonio Island, off the coast of Oregon, are about to unveil a statue honoring the four men (Castle, Wayne, Williams and Malone) who founded their town in 1871. Nick ...
Title: The Fog
Writer: Cooper Layne (screenplay), John Carpenter, Debra Hill
Actors: Tom Welling, Maggie Grace, Selma Blair, DeRay Davis
tomatoConsensus: The Fog is a so-so remake of a so-so movie, lacking scares, suspense or originality.

Plot: A film adaptation of Steve Martin's novel about a complex love triangle between a bored salesgirl, a wealthy businessman and an aimless young man.
Title: Shopgirl
Actors: Steve Martin, Claire Danes, Jason Schwartzman, Bridgette Wilson-Sampras
tomatoConsensus: Shopgirl is precariously slight, but it has some intriguing moments, and Danes is luminous.

Plot: This movie focuses on the attempts of a psychiatrist to prevent one of his patients from committing suicide while trying to maintain his own grip on reality.
Title: Stay
Actors: Ewan McGregor, Ryan Gosling, Kate Burton, Naomi Watts
tomatoConsensus: A muddled brain-teaser, Stay has a solid cast and innovative visuals but little beneath the surface.

Plot: Despite trying to keep his swashbuckling to a minimum, a threat to California's pending statehood causes the adventure-loving Alejandro de la Vega (Banderas) -- and his wife, Elena (Zeta-Jones) -- to take action.
Title: The Legend of Zorro
Writer: Roberto Orci (screenplay), Alex Kurtzman (screenplay), Roberto Orci (story), Alex Kurtzman (story), Ted Elliott (story), Terry Rossio (story), Johnston McCulley (character)
Actors: Alberto Reyes, Julio Oscar Mechoso, Gustavo Sánchez Parra, Adrian Alonso
tomatoConsensus: Zorro can survive a lot of things, but it looks like he can't survive marriage.

Plot: A Chicago weather man, separated from his wife and children, debates whether professional and personal success are mutually exclusive.
Title: The Weather Man
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Michael Caine, Hope Davis, Gemmenne de la Peña
tomatoConsensus: With fine performances and a dark, dry sense of humor, The Weather Man is mostly cloudy with occasional rays of sunshine.

Plot: A detective and his team must rescue eight people trapped in a factory by the twisted serial killer known as Jigsaw.
Title: Saw II
Actors: Tobin Bell, Shawnee Smith, Donnie Wahlberg, Erik Knudsen
tomatoConsensus: Saw II is likely to please the gore-happy fans of the original, though it may be too gruesome for those not familiar with first film's premise.

Plot: A career driven professional from Manhattan is wooed by a young painter, who also happens to be the son of her psychoanalyst.
Title: Prime
Actors: Uma Thurman, Meryl Streep, Bryan Greenberg, Jon Abrahams
tomatoConsensus: Though Streep is dependably terrific in her role, the rest of the movie is too sitcom-ish, and the romance itself is dull.

Plot: Captives of the very relationships that define and sustain them, nine women resiliently meet the travails and disappointments of life.
Title: Nine Lives
Actors: Elpidia Carrillo, Aomawa Baker, Miguel Sandoval, Mary Pat Dowhy
tomatoConsensus: Nine Lives is bolstered by a strong cast and features many insightful glimpses into the lives of women.

Plot: Gambler Jake Green enters into a game with potentially deadly consequences.
Title: Revolver
Actors: Jason Statham, Ray Liotta, Vincent Pastore, André Benjamin
tomatoConsensus: In attempting to meld his successful previous formulas with philosophical musings, Guy Ritchie has produced an incoherent misfire.

Plot: A psychological study of operations desert shield and desert storm during the gulf war; through the eyes of a U.S marine sniper who struggles to cope with the possibility his girlfriend may be cheating on him back home.
Title: Jarhead
Actors: Jake Gyllenhaal, Scott MacDonald, Peter Sarsgaard, Jamie Foxx
tomatoConsensus: This first person account of the first Gulf War scores with its performances and cinematography but lacks an emotional thrust.

Plot: After ruining his reputation with the town, a courageous chicken must come to the rescue of his fellow citizens when aliens start an invasion.
Title: Chicken Little
Writer: Mark Dindal (story by), Mark Kennedy (story by), Steve Bencich (screenplay), Ron J. Friedman (screenplay), Ron Anderson (screenplay), Robert L. Baird (additional story material), Daniel Gerson (additional story material), Sara Parriott (additional screenplay material), Josann McGibbon (additional screenplay material), David Reynolds (additional dialogue), Sandra Tsing Loh (additional dialogue)
Actors: Zach Braff, Garry Marshall, Don Knotts, Patrick Stewart
tomatoConsensus: In its first non-Pixar CGI venture, Disney expends more effort in the technical presentation than in crafting an original storyline.

Plot: A down-and-dirty musical set in the world of working-class New York, tells a story of a husband's journey into infidelity and redemption when he must choose between his seductive mistress and his beleaguered wife.
Title: Romance & Cigarettes
Actors: James Gandolfini, Susan Sarandon, Kate Winslet, Steve Buscemi
tomatoConsensus: This movie musical aims for fun and modern, but Romance and Cigarettes is too scattered and uneven to achieve either.

Plot: In December 1914, an unofficial Christmas truce on the Western Front allows soldiers from opposing sides of the First World War to gain insight into each other's way of life.
Title: Joyeux Noel
Country: France, Germany, UK, Belgium, Romania, Norway, Japan
Actors: Diane Kruger, Natalie Dessay, Benno Fürmann, Rolando Villazón
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 11 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The poignant humanity on display in Joyeux Noel makes its sentimentality forgivable.

Plot: A tale of an inner city drug dealer who turns away from crime to pursue his passion, rap music.
Title: Get Rich or Die Tryin'
Actors: 50 Cent, Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje, Joy Bryant, Omar Benson Miller
tomatoConsensus: While it may be based upon 50 Cent's own life experiences, Get Rich Or Die Tryin' is too similar to many other rags-to-riches stories to resonate.

Plot: While visiting his hometown during Christmas, a man comes face-to-face with his old high school crush whom he was best friends with -- a woman whose rejection of him turned him into a ferocious womanizer.
Title: Just Friends
Actors: Ryan Reynolds, Amy Smart, Anna Faris, Chris Klein
tomatoConsensus: There are moments of mirth in this overly broad comedy, but mostly, Just Friends is just not that funny.

Plot: A politically-charged epic about the state of the oil industry in the hands of those personally involved and affected by it.
Language: English, Urdu, Arabic, Persian, French, Mandarin
Title: Syriana
Actors: Kayvan Novak, George Clooney, Amr Waked, Christopher Plummer
tomatoConsensus: Ambitious, complicated, intellectual, and demanding of its audience, Syriana is both a gripping geopolitical thriller and wake-up call to the complacent.

Plot: When two married business executives having an affair are blackmailed by a violent criminal, the two must turn the tables on him to save their families.
Title: Derailed
Actors: Vincent Cassel, Clive Owen, Addison Timlin, Melissa George
tomatoConsensus: With miscast stars, a ludicrous plot and an obvious twist, Derailed embodies its name all too aptly.

Plot: Sparks fly when spirited Elizabeth Bennet meets single, rich, and proud Mr. Darcy. But Mr. Darcy reluctantly finds himself falling in love with a woman beneath his class. Can each overcome their own pride and prejudice?
Title: Pride & Prejudice
Actors: Keira Knightley, Talulah Riley, Rosamund Pike, Jena Malone
Awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 13 wins & 52 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Sure, it's another adaptation of cinema's fave Jane Austen novel, but key performances and a modern filmmaking sensibility make this familiar period piece fresh and enjoyable.

Plot: Three backpackers stranded in the Australian outback are befriended by a local who turns out to be a sadistic psychopath and will plunge them into a hellish nightmare of insufferable torture.
Title: Wolf Creek
Actors: John Jarratt, Cassandra Magrath, Kestie Morassi, Nathan Phillips
tomatoConsensus: Though Wolf Creek is effectively horrific, it is still tasteless exploitation.

Plot: A caving expedition goes horribly wrong, as the explorers become trapped and ultimately pursued by a strange breed of predators.
Title: The Descent
Actors: Shauna Macdonald, Natalie Mendoza, Alex Reid, Saskia Mulder
tomatoConsensus: Deft direction and strong performances from its all-female cast guide The Descent, a riveting, claustrophobic horror film.

Plot: Harry finds himself mysteriously selected as an under-aged competitor in a dangerous tournament between three schools of magic.
Title: Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire
Actors: Eric Sykes, Timothy Spall, David Tennant, Daniel Radcliffe
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 13 wins & 41 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The main characters are maturing, and the filmmakers are likewise improving on their craft; vibrant special effects and assured performances add up to what is the most complex yet of the Harry Potter films.

Plot: A chronicle of country music legend Johnny Cash's life, from his early days on an Arkansas cotton farm to his rise to fame with Sun Records in Memphis, where he recorded alongside Elvis Presley, Jerry Lee Lewis, and Carl Perkins.
Title: Walk the Line
Writer: Johnny Cash (book), Johnny Cash (book), Gill Dennis, James Mangold
Actors: Joaquin Phoenix, Reese Witherspoon, Ginnifer Goodwin, Robert Patrick
tomatoConsensus: Superior acting and authentic crooning capture the emotional subtleties of the legend of Johnny Cash with a freshness that is a pleasure to watch.

Plot: This is the film version of the Pulitzer and Tony Award winning musical about Bohemians in the East Village of New York City struggling with life, love and AIDS, and the impacts they have on America.
Title: Rent
Actors: Anthony Rapp, Adam Pascal, Rosario Dawson, Jesse L. Martin
tomatoConsensus: Fans of the stage musical may forgive Rent its flaws, but weak direction, inescapable staginess and an irritating faux-boho pretension prevent the film from connecting on screen.

Plot: Two young brothers are drawn into an intergalactic adventure when their house is hurled through the depths of space by the magical board game they are playing.
Title: Zathura: A Space Adventure
Writer: Chris Van Allsburg (book), David Koepp (screenplay), John Kamps (screenplay)
Actors: Jonah Bobo, Josh Hutcherson, Dax Shepard, Kristen Stewart
tomatoConsensus: Dazzling special effects for the kids + well-crafted storytelling for the 'rents = cinematic satisfaction for the whole family.

Plot: Narrative digressions on sex, race, politics, and more from comedienne Sarah Silverman.
Title: Sarah Silverman: Jesus Is Magic
Actors: Sarah Silverman, Brian Posehn, Laura Silverman, Bob Odenkirk
tomatoConsensus: Silverman's brand of humor is dirty, offensive, and, judging from this film, very, very funny.

Plot: A wife and mother begins a downward emotional spiral, as her husband avoids their collapsing marriage by immersing himself in his 11 year-old daughter's quest to become a spelling bee champion.
Title: Bee Season
Actors: Richard Gere, Juliette Binoche, Flora Cross, Max Minghella
tomatoConsensus: Bee Season is an intelligent, but frustratingly distant and diffuse drama about family dysfunction.

Plot: In the 1970s, a young trans woman, Patrick "Kitten" Braden, comes of age by leaving her Irish town for London, in part to look for her mother and in part because her gender identity is beyond the town's understanding.
Title: Breakfast on Pluto
Writer: Neil Jordan, Pat McCabe, Pat McCabe (book)
Actors: Cillian Murphy, Morgan Jones, Eva Birthistle, Liam Neeson
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 6 wins & 15 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Well-acted if monotonous drama about a transvestite prostitute in London during the 1970s.

Plot: A widowed Coast Guard Admiral and a widow handbag designer fall in love and marry, much to the dismay of her 10 and his 8 children.
Title: Yours, Mine & Ours
Writer: Ron Burch (screenplay), David Kidd (screenplay), Melville Shavelson, Mort Lachman, Madelyn Davis, Bob Carroll Jr.
Actors: Dennis Quaid, Rene Russo, Sean Faris, Katija Pevec
tomatoConsensus: The initial set-up is unbelievable, the plotting is predictable and stale, and the comedy depends on repetitive pratfalls that soon get old.

Plot: A successful DJ manages to rescue a powerful mobster one night. In order to repay him, the mobster gives him the task of protecting his daughter.
Title: In the Mix
Writer: Jacqueline Zambrano (screenplay), Chanel Capra (story), Cara Dellaverson (story), Brian Rubenstein (story)
Actors: Usher Raymond, Chazz Palminteri, Emmanuelle Chriqui, Robert Costanzo
tomatoConsensus: Fans may get a kick out of seeing Usher showcasing his charm on screen, but the movie itself is tone deaf and inconsequential, even by rom-com standards.

Plot: Five of the world's best snowboarders are taken to the mountains of Alaska for some outrageous "Big Mountain" rides.
Title: First Descent
Actors: Shawn Farmer, Terje Håkonsen, Nick Perata, Travis Rice
tomatoConsensus: This snowboarding doc scores with its dazzling array of snowboarding stunts and beautiful scenery, but loses points with shameless product placement and an overlong runtime.

Title: Match Point
Actors: Jonathan Rhys Meyers, Alexander Armstrong, Paul Kaye, Matthew Goode
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 28 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Woody Allen's sharpest film in years, Match Point is a taut, philosophical thriller about class and infidelity.

Plot: A grief-stricken screenwriter unknowingly enters a three-way relationship with a woman and her film executive husband - to chilling results.
Title: The Dying Gaul
Actors: Patricia Clarkson, Campbell Scott, Peter Sarsgaard, Ryan Miller
tomatoConsensus: Though it has a fine cast, The Dying Gaul's plot feels calculated and too intellectualized.

Plot: Two childhood friends are recruited for a suicide bombing in Tel Aviv.
Title: Paradise Now
Writer: Hany Abu-Assad, Bero Beyer, Pierre Hodgson
Actors: Lubna Azabal, Hamza Abu-Aiaash, Kais Nashif, Lutuf Nouasser
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 13 wins & 15 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This film delves deeply into the minds of suicide bombers, and the result is unsettling.

Plot: Four kids travel through a wardrobe to the land of Narnia and learn of their destiny to free it with the guidance of a mystical lion.
Title: The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe
Writer: Ann Peacock (screenplay), Andrew Adamson (screenplay), Christopher Markus (screenplay), Stephen McFeely (screenplay), C.S. Lewis (book)
Actors: Georgie Henley, Skandar Keynes, William Moseley, Anna Popplewell
tomatoConsensus: With first-rate special effects and compelling storytelling, this adaptation stays faithful to its source material and will please moviegoers of all ages.

Plot: In 1933 New York, an overly ambitious movie producer coerces his cast and hired ship crew to travel to the mysterious Skull Island, where they encounter Kong, a giant ape who is immediately smitten with leading lady Ann Darrow.
Title: King Kong
Writer: Fran Walsh (screenplay), Philippa Boyens (screenplay), Peter Jackson (screenplay), Merian C. Cooper (based on a story by), Edgar Wallace (based on a story by)
Actors: Naomi Watts, Jack Black, Adrien Brody, Thomas Kretschmann
tomatoConsensus: Featuring state-of-the-art special effects, terrific performances, and a majestic sense of spectacle, Peter Jackson's remake of King Kong is a potent epic that's faithful to the spirit of the 1933 original.

Plot: Nitta Sayuri reveals how she transcended her fishing-village roots and became one of Japan's most celebrated geisha.
Title: Memoirs of a Geisha
Actors: Suzuka Ohgo, Togo Igawa, Mako, Samantha Futerman
tomatoConsensus: Less nuanced than its source material, Memoirs of a Geisha may be a lavish production, but it still carries the simplistic air of a soap opera.

Plot: An uptight, conservative businesswoman accompanies her boyfriend to his eccentric and outgoing family's annual Christmas celebration and finds that she's a fish out of water in their free-spirited way of life.
Title: The Family Stone
Actors: Claire Danes, Diane Keaton, Rachel McAdams, Dermot Mulroney
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 7 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This family holiday dramedy features fine performances but awkward shifts of tone.

Plot: A globetrotting hitman and a crestfallen businessman meet in a hotel bar in Mexico City in an encounter that draws them together in a way neither expected.
Title: The Matador
Actors: Pierce Brosnan, Arlin Miller, Azucena Medina, Jonah Meyerson
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This humorously amoral, oddball comic thriller features strong performances by Pierce Brosnan and Greg Kinnear as a flamboyant, aging hit-man and an out of work suburban businessman, respectively.

Plot: Ranch hand Pete Perkins looks to fulfill the promise to his recently deceased best friend by burying him in his hometown in Mexico.
Title: Three Burials
Actors: Tommy Lee Jones, Barry Pepper, Julio Cedillo, Dwight Yoakam
tomatoConsensus: Tommy Lee Jones' directorial debut is both a potent western and a powerful morality tale.

Plot: Based on the true story of the Black September aftermath, about the five men chosen to eliminate the ones responsible for that fateful day.
Language: English, German, French, Hebrew, Arabic, Italian, Greek, Russian
Title: Munich
