Writer: Tony Kushner (screenplay), Eric Roth (screenplay), George Jonas (book)
Actors: Eric Bana, Daniel Craig, Ciarán Hinds, Mathieu Kassovitz
Awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 12 wins & 62 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Munich can't quite achieve its lofty goals, but this thrilling, politically even-handed look at the fallout from an intractable political conflict is still well worth watching.

Plot: After putting together another Broadway flop, down-on-his-luck producer Max Bialystock teams up with timid accountant Leo Bloom in a get-rich-quick scheme to put on the world's worst show.
Title: The Producers
Writer: Mel Brooks (screenplay), Thomas Meehan (screenplay), Mel Brooks, Mel Brooks, Thomas Meehan, Mel Brooks
Actors: Nathan Lane, Matthew Broderick, Uma Thurman, Will Ferrell
Awards: Nominated for 4 Golden Globes. Another 1 win & 13 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despite the rich source material, The Producers has a stale, stagy feel more suited to the theater than the big screen.

Plot: A pre-operative male-to-female transgender takes an unexpected journey when she learns that she fathered a son, now a teenage runaway hustling on the streets of New York.
Title: Transamerica
Actors: Andrea James, Felicity Huffman, Danny Burstein, Maurice Orozco
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 31 wins & 22 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A terrific performance by Felicity Huffman carries this unconventional but touching transgender road movie.

Plot: Sarah Huttinger is a woman who learns that her family was the inspiration for the book and film "The Graduate" -- and that she just might be the offspring of the well-documented event.
Title: Rumor Has It...
Actors: Jennifer Aniston, Kevin Costner, Shirley MacLaine, Mark Ruffalo
tomatoConsensus: This riff on The Graduate has a solid cast, but is too lightweight to fully register.

Plot: The Bakers, while on vacation, find themselves competing with a rival family of eight children.
Title: Cheaper by the Dozen 2
Writer: Sam Harper, Craig Titley (characters), Frank B. Gilbreth Jr. (novel), Ernestine Gilbreth Carey (novel)
Actors: Steve Martin, Eugene Levy, Bonnie Hunt, Tom Welling
tomatoConsensus: A sequel to a remake, Cheaper 2 wastes its solid cast in scenes of over-the-top, predictable humor.

Plot: When an affluent couple lose all their money following a series of blunders, they turn to a life of crime to make ends meet.
Title: Fun with Dick and Jane
Writer: Judd Apatow (screenplay), Nicholas Stoller (screenplay), Gerald Gaiser (story), Judd Apatow (story), Nicholas Stoller (story), Gerald Gaiser (novel), David Giler, Jerry Belson, Mordecai Richler
Actors: Jim Carrey, Téa Leoni, Alec Baldwin, Richard Jenkins
tomatoConsensus: This muddled comedy has a few laughs, but never sustains a consistent tone.

Plot: A young guy's only option to erase a really bad debt is to rig the Special Olympics by posing as a contestant.
Title: The Ringer
Actors: Johnny Knoxville, Brian Cox, Katherine Heigl, Jed Rees
tomatoConsensus: Despite a few laughs and good intentions, The Ringer is too predictable to really score the points it aims for.

Plot: Heath Ledger plays the fabled romantic as a man who, after failing to win the affection of a particular Venetian woman, strives to discover the real meaning of love.
Title: Casanova
Writer: Jeffrey Hatcher (screenplay), Kimberly Simi (screenplay), Kimberly Simi (story), Michael Cristofer (story)
Actors: Heath Ledger, Sienna Miller, Jeremy Irons, Oliver Platt
tomatoConsensus: This frothy, oddly bloodless film does a disservice to the colorful life of the real Casanova.

Plot: Laura Henderson buys an old London theater and opens it up as the Windmill, a performance hall which goes down in history for, among other things, its all-nude revues.
Title: Mrs Henderson Presents
Writer: David Rose (idea), Kathy Rose (idea), Martin Sherman, Sheila van Damm (book)
Actors: Judi Dench, Bob Hoskins, Will Young, Christopher Guest
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 31 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Judi Dench and Bob Hoskins shine in this warm, witty period piece.

Plot: Set in 1930s Shanghai, where a blind American diplomat develops a curious relationship with a young Russian refugee who works odd -- and sometimes illicit -- jobs to support members of her dead husband's aristocratic family.
Title: The White Countess
Actors: Natasha Richardson, Lynn Redgrave, Madeleine Potter, Madeleine Daly
tomatoConsensus: High production values and fine performances get bogged down by a lifeless story that fails to engage the viewer.

Plot: A pastor preoccupied with writing the perfect sermon fails to realize that his wife is having an affair and his children are up to no good.
Title: Keeping Mum
Writer: Richard Russo (screenplay), Niall Johnson (screenplay), Richard Russo (story)
Actors: Rowan Atkinson, Kristin Scott Thomas, Maggie Smith, Patrick Swayze
tomatoConsensus: The stellar cast, including Kristin Scott Thomas and Dame Maggie Smith, is certainly an asset, but this black comedy is too uneven.

Plot: The story of the English exploration of Virginia, and of the changing world and loves of Pocahontas.
Title: The New World
Actors: Colin Farrell, Q'orianka Kilcher, Christopher Plummer, Christian Bale
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 25 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despite arresting visuals and strong lead performances, The New World suffers from an unfocused narrative that will challenge viewers' attention spans over its 2 1/2 hours.

Plot: In the 18th century, a vampire escapes from the freak show she once participated in and teams up with a group of vampire slayers to kill the man who raped her mother.
Title: BloodRayne
Actors: Kristanna Loken, Michael Madsen, Matthew Davis, Will Sanderson
tomatoConsensus: BloodRayne is an absurd sword-and-sorcery vid-game adaptation from schlock-maestro Uwe Boll, featuring a distinguished (and slumming) cast.

Plot: Three backpackers head to a Slovak city that promises to meet their hedonistic expectations, with no idea of the hell that awaits them.
Language: English, Czech, German, Dutch, Slovak, Japanese, Icelandic, Russian, Spanish
Title: Hostel
Country: USA, Germany, Czech Republic, Slovakia, Iceland
Actors: Jay Hernandez, Derek Richardson, Eythor Gudjonsson, Barbara Nedeljakova
tomatoConsensus: Featuring lots of guts and gore, Hostel is a wildly entertaining corpse-filled journey -- assuming one is entertained by corpses, guts, and gore, that is.

Plot: Little Red Riding Hood, the Wolf, the Woodsman, and Granny all tell the police the events that lead up to their encounter.
Title: Hoodwinked!
Writer: Cory Edwards (screenplay), Todd Edwards (screenplay), Tony Leech (screenplay), Todd Edwards (story), Cory Edwards (story)
Director: Cory Edwards, Todd Edwards, Tony Leech
Actors: Anne Hathaway, Glenn Close, Jim Belushi, Patrick Warburton
tomatoConsensus: This fractured fairytale doesn't have the wit or animation quality to compete with the likes of the Shrek franchise.

Plot: To improve its relations with Muslim countries, the United States government sends comedian Albert Brooks to south Asia to write a report on what makes followers of Islam laugh.
Title: Looking for Comedy in the Muslim World
Actors: Penny Marshall, Victoria Burrows, Paul Jerome, Albert Brooks
tomatoConsensus: Although the premise seems ripe for laughs, Albert Brooks isn't ruthless or clever enough to pull it off.

Plot: A 10-year-old and an 11-year-old find love in New York City.
Title: Little Manhattan
Actors: Josh Hutcherson, Charlie Ray, Bradley Whitford, Cynthia Nixon
tomatoConsensus: Little Manhattan is a sweet story of young love that provides an enlightening if pragmatic view on love and courtship.

Plot: The story of New Zealander Burt Munro, who spent years rebuilding a 1920 Indian motorcycle, which helped him set the land speed world record at Utah's Bonneville Salt Flats in 1967.
Title: The World's Fastest Indian
Actors: Anthony Hopkins, Iain Rea, Tessa Mitchell, Aaron Murphy
tomatoConsensus: Overcomes its formulaic storyline thanks to Anthony Hopkins' warm and endearing portrayal of an age-defying thrill seeker.

Plot: Director Michael Winterbottom (Northam) attempts to shoot the adaptation of Laurence Sterne's essentially unfilmable novel, "The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman."
Title: Tristram Shandy: A Cock and Bull Story
Actors: Steve Coogan, Rob Brydon, Keeley Hawes, Shirley Henderson
tomatoConsensus: Though Laurence Sterne's novel was considered more or less impossible to successfully adapt to film, director Michael Winterbottom has done it in Tristram Shandy: A Cock and Bull Story, by making movie about the making of the movie. Stars Steve Coogan and Rob Brydon add madcap, knowing performances to the mix, and the result is a fun, postmodern romp, before there was any modern romp to post.

Plot: A governess uses magic to rein in the behavior of seven ne'er-do-well children in her charge.
Title: Nanny McPhee
Writer: Emma Thompson (screenplay), Christianna Brand ("Nurse Matilda" books)
Actors: Emma Thompson, Colin Firth, Kelly Macdonald, Thomas Brodie-Sangster
tomatoConsensus: A bit alarming at first, Nanny McPhee has a hard edge to counter Mary Poppins-style sweetness, but it still charms us and teaches some valuable lessons.

Plot: A mix of Dave Chappelle's sketch comedy and musical interludes, inspired in part by the 1973 documentary Wattstax.
Title: Dave Chappelle's Block Party
Actors: Dave Chappelle, Erykah Badu, Isaac ben Ayala, Yasiin Bey
tomatoConsensus: Dave Chappelle's Block Party is a raucous return to the spotlight for the comic, buoyed by witty, infectious humor and outstanding musical performances.

Plot: A newlywed bride becomes infatuated with another woman, who questions her sexual orientation, promoting a stir among the bride's family and friends.
Title: Imagine Me & You
Actors: Piper Perabo, Lena Headey, Matthew Goode, Celia Imrie
tomatoConsensus: Aside from its lesbian theme, Imagine Me & You can only offer more of the same generic rom-com cliches.

Plot: In a future British tyranny, a shadowy freedom fighter, known only by the alias of "V", plots to overthrow it with the help of a young woman.
Title: V for Vendetta
Writer: Lilly Wachowski (screenplay), Lana Wachowski (screenplay), David Lloyd (graphic novel art)
Actors: Natalie Portman, Hugo Weaving, Stephen Rea, Stephen Fry
tomatoConsensus: Visually stunning and thought-provoking, V For Vendetta's political pronouncements may rile some, but its story and impressive set pieces will nevertheless entertain.

Plot: Satirical comedy follows the machinations of Big Tobacco's chief spokesman, Nick Naylor, who spins on behalf of cigarettes while trying to remain a role model for his twelve-year-old son.
Title: Thank You for Smoking
Actors: Joan Lunden, Eric Haberman, Aaron Eckhart, Mary Jo Smith
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 12 wins & 30 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Loaded with delightfully unscrupulous characters and and a witty, cynical script, Thank You For Smoking is a sharp satire with a brilliantly smarmy lead performance from Aaron Eckhart.

Plot: Six days in the violent life of a young Johannesburg gang leader.
Title: Tsotsi
Actors: Presley Chweneyagae, Terry Pheto, Kenneth Nkosi, Mothusi Magano
tomatoConsensus: Chweneyagae's powerful performance carries this simple yet searing tale of a shantytown teenager's redemption.

Plot: A teenage loner pushes his way into the underworld of a high school crime ring to investigate the disappearance of his ex-girlfriend.
Title: Brick
Actors: Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Nora Zehetner, Lukas Haas, Noah Fleiss
tomatoConsensus: This entertaining homage to noirs past has been slickly and compellingly updated to a contemporary high school setting.

Plot: A teenage girl raids a man's home in order to expose him under suspicion that he is a sex offender with pedophilia.
Title: Hard Candy
Actors: Patrick Wilson, Ellen Page, Sandra Oh, Odessa Rae
tomatoConsensus: Disturbing, controversial, but entirely engrossing, Hard Candy is well written with strong lead performances, especially that of newcomer Ellen Page. A movie that stays with the viewer long after leaving the theater.

Plot: A drag queen comes to the rescue of a man who, after inheriting his father's shoe factory, needs to diversify his product if he wants to keep the business afloat.
Title: Kinky Boots
Actors: Joel Edgerton, Chiwetel Ejiofor, Sarah-Jane Potts, Nick Frost
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 6 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Kinky Boots relies heavily on the Full Monty formula of Britcoms, while playing it too safe in a desperate attempt not to offend. Ejiofor's performance is its redeeming virtue.

Plot: A young fighter named Kham must go to Australia to retrieve his stolen elephant. With the help of a Thai-born Australian detective, Kham must take on all comers, including a gang led by an evil woman and her two deadly bodyguards.
Title: The Protector
Writer: Napalee, Piyaros Thongdee, Joe Wannapin, Kongdej Jaturanrasamee, Prachya Pinkaew (story)
Actors: Tony Jaa, Petchtai Wongkamlao, Bongkoj Khongmalai, Xing Jin
tomatoConsensus: Despite some impressive fight scenes, this trimmed-down version of the Thai action pic is an off-putting mix of scant plot, choppy editing, and confusing subtitles and dubbing.

Plot: Based on the true events of the only case in US History where a spirit caused the death of a man.
Title: An American Haunting
Actors: Donald Sutherland, Sissy Spacek, James D'Arcy, Rachel Hurd-Wood
tomatoConsensus: Well, it looks good. But wasn't it supposed to be scary?

Plot: Set in the present-day San Fernando Valley, the project revolves around a delusional man who believes he's a cowboy and the relationship that he starts with a rebellious young woman.
Title: Down in the Valley
Actors: Edward Norton, Evan Rachel Wood, David Morse, Rory Culkin
tomatoConsensus: The premise of Old West clashing with modern suburbia is fresh and initially intriguing, but the second act degenerates into a clumsy jumble of events which strain credibility.

Plot: Set at the end of the '60s, as Swaziland is about to receive independence from Great Britain, the film follows the young Ralph Compton, at 12, through his parents' traumatic separation, ...
Title: Wah-Wah
Actors: Gabriel Byrne, Emily Watson, Julie Walters, Nicholas Hoult
tomatoConsensus: The ensemble cast is strong, but they get overpowered by the muddled stew of melodrama.

Plot: Instead of adhering to the norms of their South Central neighborhood, a group of skater boys opt to bus into Hollywood and Beverly Hills, where they attract local rich girls - and plenty of...
Title: Wassup Rockers
Writer: Larry Clark (screenplay), Larry Clark (story), Matthew Frost (story)
Actors: Jonathan Velasquez, Francisco Pedrasa, Milton Velasquez, Usvaldo Panameno
tomatoConsensus: As usual with Clark's films, the fixation on kids is rather creepy, plus the plot eventually runs off the rails into camp.

Title: The Lost City
Actors: Alfredo Armenteros, Danny Pino, Richard Marquez, Franklin Dominguez
tomatoConsensus: Its heart is in the right place, but what starts as a promising exercise devolves into an overlong, unevenly directed disappointment.

Plot: The life of Bettie Page, a 1950s pin-up model and one of the first sex icons in America, who became the target of a Senate investigation due to her risqué bondage photos.
Title: The Notorious Bettie Page
Writer: Mary Harron, Guinevere Turner, Richard Foster (based on the book by)
Actors: Gretchen Mol, Chris Bauer, Jared Harris, Sarah Paulson
tomatoConsensus: This biopic only skims the surface of Bettie Page's life, leaving her as a cipher, and additionally fails to place her iconic status in historical context.

Plot: A widowed man's life turns upside down when he embarks on a journey to find a dying man's long lost love.
Title: Marilyn Hotchkiss' Ballroom Dancing & Charm School
Writer: Randall Miller (short film "Marilyn Hotchkiss Ballroom Dancing and Charm School"), Randall Miller (screenplay), Jody Savin (screenplay)
Actors: John Goodman, Elden Henson, Robert Carlyle, Sean Astin
tomatoConsensus: Clumsily staged and brimming with melodrama and trite self-help cliches, this dance movie stays stuck at amateur level.

Plot: Frank determines to salvage his self-esteem and tackle his demons by attempting the ultimate test of endurance - swimming the English Channel.
Title: On a Clear Day
Actors: Peter Mullan, Brenda Blethyn, Sean McGinley, Jamie Sives
tomatoConsensus: Another blue-collar inspirational feel-good British dramedy, On A Clear Day succeeds on the strength of lead actor Peter Mullan's performance and Gaby Dellal's competent direction.

Plot: Follows two New York city couples -- one heterosexual and one gay who explore the peaks and the valleys of their respective relationships.
Title: Adam & Steve
Actors: Malcolm Gets, Cary Curran, Craig Chester, Parker Posey
tomatoConsensus: Gross-out comedy and true love make for an awkward mix in this clunky romance.

Plot: A documentary on the legendary singer-songwriter, with performances by those musicians he has influenced.
Title: Leonard Cohen: I'm Your Man
Actors: Leonard Cohen, Martha Wainwright, Beth Orton, Jarvis Cocker
tomatoConsensus: A moving, if somewhat uneven, look at the legendary singer-songwriter, I'm Your Man treats Cohen's body of work with the reverence it deserves.

Plot: A prequel to the critically acclaimed series featuring Jerri Blank, a 46-year-old ex-junkie, ex-con who returns to high school in a bid to start her life over.
Title: Strangers with Candy
Writer: Stephen Colbert (series Strangers with Candy), Paul Dinello (series Strangers with Candy), Amy Sedaris (series Strangers with Candy), Mitch Rouse (series Strangers with Candy), Stephen Colbert, Paul Dinello, Amy Sedaris
Actors: Amy Sedaris, Paul Sedaris, Chandra Wilson, Kristy Thomas
tomatoConsensus: Occasionally funny, but little more than a jumbled, overextended episode of the TV show. Still, Candy devotees won't be disappointed.

Plot: Two people come to the end of a spear in order to realize that the divisions between them are not real.
Title: End of the Spear
Writer: Bill Ewing, Bart Gavigan, Jim Hanon
Actors: Louie Leonardo, Chad Allen, Jack Guzman, Christina Souza
tomatoConsensus: Shoddy filmmaking and a lack of character development derail what could be a potentially compelling tale.

Plot: The true story of a man who posed as director Stanley Kubrick during the production of Kubrick's last film, Eyes Wide Shut, despite knowing very little about his work and looking nothing like him.
Title: Color Me Kubrick
Actors: Tom Allen, Scott Baker, Nick Barber, Angus Barnett
tomatoConsensus: Colour Me Kubrick has a fascinating premise, but provides little insight into Kubrick and the man who impersonated him.

Plot: When an assassin is diagnosed with terminal cancer, she decides to carry out one final killing, assisted by her lover and stepson, Mikey.
Title: Shadowboxer
Actors: Cuba Gooding Jr., Helen Mirren, Vanessa Ferlito, Macy Gray
tomatoConsensus: With random characters and a preposterous plot, this bizarre thriller might leave you with your mouth hanging open in disbelief.

Plot: A family in financial crisis is forced to sell Lassie, their beloved dog. Hundreds of miles away from her true family, Lassie escapes and sets out on a journey home.
Title: Lassie
Actors: Peter O'Toole, Samantha Morton, John Lynch, Peter Dinklage
tomatoConsensus: A beautifully-made retelling of the classic collie tale, one need not be a dog-lover to fall for Lassie.

Plot: Dot (Belle), a young deaf and mute woman, is sent to live with her godparents (Falco and Donovan) and their daughter (Cuthbert). The new addition to the household realizes that everything is not copacetic in the home, and the family's dark come to light.
Title: The Quiet
Actors: Elisha Cuthbert, Camilla Belle, Edie Falco, Martin Donovan
tomatoConsensus: This psychological thriller's talented cast is undercut by leaden pacing and a problematic plot.

Plot: A look at the life and work of the renown architect.
Title: Sketches of Frank Gehry
Actors: Charles Arnoldi, Barry Diller, Michael Eisner, Rolf Fehlbaum
tomatoConsensus: This affectionate, casually framed portrait of the acclaimed architect reveals him to be an engaging, likeable subject.

Plot: After much drama, cheating, and trial separations, two men fight to save their respective relationships.
Title: Trust the Man
Actors: David Duchovny, Julianne Moore, Sascha Gillen, Brianna Gillen
tomatoConsensus: What aspires to be a sophisticated, unconventional romantic comedy turns out to be a contrivance-filled pretender to other, better films of its genre.

Plot: A romantic comedy about our amazing capacity to rebound and fall in love at any age. Lois, Harry, Marilyn ,Sandy and Jack live in an "Active Adult" community in Boynton Beach, Florida. ...
Title: Boynton Beach Club
Writer: Florence Seidelman (story), David Cramer (story), Susan Seidelman, Shelly Gitlow
Actors: Brenda Vaccaro, Dyan Cannon, Len Cariou, Joseph Bologna
tomatoConsensus: While the movie has been praised for showcasing a cinematically underused and disrespected age group, it also has the small-screen feel of a silly sitcom.

Plot: A tough-minded drama about two friends in South Central Los Angeles and the violence that comes between them.
Title: Harsh Times
Actors: Christian Bale, Freddy Rodríguez, Eva Longoria, Chaka Forman
tomatoConsensus: Despite a dedicated performance by Christian Bale, Harsh Times suffers from a heavy-handed and overly bleak plot.

Plot: In 1920, Inge, a German national, travels from Norway to rural Minnesota for her arranged marriage to Olaf, a Norwegian farmer; bureaucracy and prejudice cause major complications.
Title: Sweet Land
Writer: Will Weaver (short story "A Gravestone Made of Wheat"), Ali Selim
Actors: Elizabeth Reaser, Lois Smith, Patrick Heusinger, Stephen Pelinski
tomatoConsensus: Finding the right balance between subtle and sentimental, Sweet Land moves beyond other similarly-themed dramas with evocative cinematography that plays an equal role to the talented cast.

Plot: An examination of life inside the Grande Chartreuse, the head monastery of the reclusive Carthusian Order in France.
Title: Into Great Silence
tomatoConsensus: A meditative, deliberately paced doc capable of absorbing patient viewers into a whole different world.

Plot: Luke Wilson plays a good-hearted ex-con who gets a job in a retirement hotel. Three elderly residents help him win back his girlfriend as he lends them a hand in fighting hotel corruption.
Title: The Wendell Baker Story
Actors: Luke Wilson, Eva Mendes, Jacob Vargas, Owen Wilson
tomatoConsensus: The Wendell Baker Story is a lackadaisical comedy of quirky characters and situations, but ultimately the lazy narrative bores instead of charms.

Plot: A district attorney is involved in a 24-hour showdown with a gang leader and is, at the same time, being manipulated by an attractive assistant district attorney and a cryptic stranger.
Title: Slow Burn
Writer: Wayne Beach (screenplay), Wayne Beach (story), Anthony Walton (story)
Actors: Ray Liotta, LL Cool J, Mekhi Phifer, Jolene Blalock
tomatoConsensus: With wooden acting and hammy, overheated dialogue, Slow Burn isn't so much a noir as it is a mediocre parody of one.

Plot: Third part in Aleksandr Sokurov's quadrilogy of Power, following Moloch (1999) and Taurus (2001), focuses on Japanese Emperor Hirohito and Japan's defeat in World War II when he is finally confronted by General Douglas MacArthur who offers him to accept a diplomatic defeat for survival.
Title: The Sun
Actors: Issei Ogata, Robert Dawson, Kaori Momoi, Shirô Sano
tomatoConsensus: Certainly not for the impatient, Aleksandr Sokurov's deliberately paced look at Hirohito in the waning days of World War II is both enlightening and admirable in its restraint.

Plot: A modern-day pirate plans a massive attack on North and South Korea.
Title: Typhoon
Actors: Dong-gun Jang, Jung-jae Lee, Mi-yeon Lee, David Lee McInnis
tomatoConsensus: A pseudo-political thriller on the fritz, Typhoon drowns in its own heavy handedness and silly acting.

Plot: An undercover cop in a not-too-distant future becomes involved with a dangerous new drug and begins to lose his own identity as a result.
Title: A Scanner Darkly
Actors: Rory Cochrane, Robert Downey Jr., Mitch Baker, Keanu Reeves
tomatoConsensus: A faithful adaptation of Philip K. Dick's novel, A Scanner Darkly takes the viewer on a visual and mind-blowing journey into the author's conception of a drug-addled and politically unstable world.

Plot: A 35 year old video game tester has to move in with his grandma and her two old lady roommates.
Title: Grandma's Boy
Writer: Barry Wernick, Allen Covert, Nick Swardson
Actors: Linda Cardellini, Allen Covert, Peter Dante, Shirley Jones
tomatoConsensus: A gross-out comedy that's more gross than comedic, Grandma's Boy is lazy and unrewarding.

Plot: An affair between the second in line to Britain's throne (Franco) and the princess of the feuding Irish (Myles) spells doom for the young lovers.
Title: Tristan + Isolde
Actors: James Franco, Sophia Myles, Rufus Sewell, David O'Hara
tomatoConsensus: Competent but somewhat static, Tristan & Isolde doesn't achieve the sweeping romanticism that it aims for.

Plot: Upon learning of a terminal illness, a shy woman (Queen Latifah) decides to sell off all her possessions and live it up at a posh European hotel.
Title: Last Holiday
Writer: Jeffrey Price (screenplay), Peter S. Seaman (screenplay), J.B. Priestley
Actors: Queen Latifah, LL Cool J, Timothy Hutton, Giancarlo Esposito
tomatoConsensus: Although Queen Latifah's bountiful life-affirming spirit permeates the film, director Wayne Wang is unable to revive this remake with any real flair.

Plot: Picking up directly from the previous film, vampire warrior Selene and the half werewolf Michael hunt for clues to reveal the history of their races and the war between them.
Title: Underworld: Evolution
Writer: Danny McBride (screenplay), Len Wiseman (story), Danny McBride (story), Kevin Grevioux (characters), Len Wiseman (characters), Danny McBride (characters)
Actors: Kate Beckinsale, Scott Speedman, Tony Curran, Derek Jacobi
tomatoConsensus: A visual and aural assault on the senses, this vampire-werewolf sequel makes a lot of noise and features a heavy-handed, overly convoluted story.

Plot: Set against the backdrop of boxing at the Naval Academy, centers on a young man from the wrong side of the tracks whose dream of attending Annapolis becomes a reality.
Title: Annapolis
Actors: James Franco, Macka Foley, Jim Parrack, Donnie Wahlberg
tomatoConsensus: Stocked with leading men who look the part but lacking an iota of original plot, Annapolis is merely a watery shadow of superior seafaring military dramas.

Plot: An FBI agent reprises his disguise as a corpulent old lady and takes a job as a nanny in a crime suspect's house.
Title: Big Momma's House 2
Actors: Martin Lawrence, Nia Long, Emily Procter, Zachary Levi
tomatoConsensus: Unfunny and unoriginal. In other words, a perfect piece of evidence for opponents of pointless movie sequels.

Plot: In this third installment of the Final Destination series, a student's premonition of a deadly rollercoaster ride saves her life and a lucky few, but not from death itself which seeks out those who escaped their fate.
Title: Final Destination 3
Writer: Glen Morgan, James Wong, Jeffrey Reddick (characters)
Actors: Mary Elizabeth Winstead, Ryan Merriman, Kris Lemche, Alexz Johnson
tomatoConsensus: Final Destination 3 is more of the same: gory and pointless, with nowhere new to go.

Plot: Kenya McQueen, an accountant finds love in the most unexpected place when she agrees to go on a blind date with Brian Kelly, a sexy and free-spirited landscaper.
Title: Something New
Actors: Sanaa Lathan, Fuzzy Fantabulous, Katharine Towne, Stanley DeSantis
tomatoConsensus: Something New tackles serious questions about race and interracial relationships with genuine appeal and an alluring romance that develops as naturally as the plot.

Plot: Bumbling Inspector Clouseau must solve the murder of a famous soccer coach and find out who stole the infamous Pink Panther diamond.
Title: The Pink Panther
Writer: Len Blum (screenplay), Steve Martin (screenplay), Len Blum (story), Michael Saltzman (story), Maurice Richlin (characters), Blake Edwards (characters)
Actors: Steve Martin, Kevin Kline, Jean Reno, Emily Mortimer
tomatoConsensus: Though Steve Martin is game, the particulars of the Inspector Clouseau character elude him in this middling update.

Plot: The Man in the Yellow Hat is an oddball museum employee who looks after his pet monkey - an inquisitive and wonderful creature whose enthusiasm often gets the best of him.
Title: Curious George
Writer: Ken Kaufman (screenplay), Ken Kaufman (story), Mike Werb (story), Margret Rey (books), H.A. Rey (books)
Actors: Frank Welker, Will Ferrell, Shane Baumel, Timyra-Joi Beatty
tomatoConsensus: Curious George is a bright, sweet, faithful adaptation of the beloved children's books.

Plot: A security specialist is forced into robbing the bank that he's protecting, as a bid to pay off his family's ransom.
Title: Firewall
Actors: Harrison Ford, Virginia Madsen, Carly Schroeder, Jimmy Bennett
tomatoConsensus: Harrison Ford's rote performance brings little to this uninspired techno-heist film whose formulaic plot is befuddled with tedious and improbable twists.

Plot: During a babysitting gig, a high-school student is harassed by an increasingly threatening prank caller.
Title: When a Stranger Calls
Writer: Jake Wade Wall (screenplay), Steve Feke, Fred Walton
Actors: Camilla Belle, Tommy Flanagan, Katie Cassidy, Tessa Thompson
tomatoConsensus: What's fitting punishment for running up the phone bill? Why have that person baby sit; that'll teach them. Or better yet, make that person through this poorly acted, fright-free remake of the 1979 movie of the same name. Camilla Belle is a looker, but she got nothing on Carol Kane, the actress who originally played the part, when it comes to range. The final straw is that the payoff isn't worth the tedium that comes before. Just hang up on this one.

Plot: A black police detective must solve a strange case of a kidnapped boy and deal with a big racial protest.
Title: Freedomland
Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Julianne Moore, Edie Falco, Ron Eldard
tomatoConsensus: Poorly directed and overacted, Freedomland attempts to address sensitive race and class issues but its overzealousness misses the mark.

Plot: Brutal cold forces two Antarctic explorers to leave their team of sled dogs behind as they fend for their survival.
Title: Eight Below
Writer: David DiGilio (screenplay), Toshirô Ishidô (film Nankyoku Monogatari), Koreyoshi Kurahara (film Nankyoku Monogatari), Tatsuo Nogami (film Nankyoku Monogatari), Susumu Saji (film Nankyoku Monogatari)
Actors: Paul Walker, Bruce Greenwood, Moon Bloodgood, Wendy Crewson
tomatoConsensus: Featuring a stellar cast of marooned mutts, who deftly display emotion, tenderness, loyalty and resolve, Eight Below is a heartwarming and exhilarating adventure film.

Plot: Spoof of romantic comedies which focuses on a man, his crush, his parents, and her father.
Title: Date Movie
Actors: Alyson Hannigan, Adam Campbell, Sophie Monk, Eddie Griffin
tomatoConsensus: In an attempt to parody rom-com cliches, Date Movie ultimately makes a mockery of itself, with juvenile toilet humor and empty pop culture references.

Plot: A low-ranking thug is entrusted by his crime boss to dispose of a gun that killed corrupt cops, but things get out of control when the gun ends up in wrong hands.
Title: Running Scared
Actors: Paul Walker, Cameron Bright, Vera Farmiga, Chazz Palminteri
tomatoConsensus: This film runs with frenetic energy punctuated by gratuitous violence but sorely lacks in plot, character development and stylistic flair.

Plot: While planning her family reunion, a pistol-packing grandma must contend with the other dramas on her plate, including the runaway who has been placed under her care, and her love-troubled nieces.
Title: Madea's Family Reunion
Actors: Tyler Perry, Blair Underwood, Lynn Whitfield, Boris Kodjoe
tomatoConsensus: Tyler Perry's Madea's Family Reunion is sincere in its positive intentions, but leaves something to be desired as a film.

Plot: This is the story of Doogal, an adorable candy-loving mutt who goes on a mission to save the world. Doogal must prevent the evil sorcerer Zeebad from freezing the earth forever with the ...
Title: Doogal
Writer: Paul Bassett (screenplay), Martine Danot (characters), Serge Danot (characters), Serge Danot (creator), Serge Danot (screenplay), Butch Hartman (screenplay), Tad Safran (screenplay), Raolf Sanoussi (screenplay), Stephane Sanoussi (screenplay)
Director: Dave Borthwick, Jean Duval, Frank Passingham
Actors: Daniel Tay, Jimmy Fallon, Jon Stewart, Whoopi Goldberg
tomatoConsensus: Overloaded with pop culture references, but lacking in compelling characters and plot, Doogal is too simpleminded even for the kiddies.

Plot: A beautiful hemophage infected with a virus that gives her superhuman powers has to protect a boy in a futuristic world, who is thought to be carrying antigens that would destroy all hemophages.
Title: Ultraviolet
Actors: Milla Jovovich, Cameron Bright, Nick Chinlund, Sebastien Andrieu
tomatoConsensus: An incomprehensible and forgettable sci-fi thriller, Ultraviolet is inept in every regard.

Plot: Manhattanite Ashley is known to many as the luckiest woman around. After a chance encounter with a down-and-out young man, however, she realizes that she's swapped her fortune for his.
Title: Just My Luck
Writer: I. Marlene King (screenplay), Amy Harris (screenplay), Jonathan Bernstein (story), Mark Blackwell (story), James Greer (story), I. Marlene King (story)
Actors: Lindsay Lohan, Chris Pine, Samaire Armstrong, Bree Turner
tomatoConsensus: Just My Luck is a screwball rom-com that fails to take advantage of Lindsay Lohan's considerable charm. The film (along with Robert Altman's A Prairie Home Companion) marks the end of Lohan's teen queen phase as she begins playing characters that are older, but not necessarily wiser. Lohan's character is supposedly cursed with bad luck, though the movie confuses misfortune with plain stupidity, leading Lohan into a long series of silly and senseless physical gags.

Plot: When their computer hacker friend accidentally channels a mysterious wireless signal, a group of co-eds rally to stop a terrifying evil from taking over the world.
Title: Pulse
Writer: Wes Craven (screenplay), Ray Wright (screenplay), Kiyoshi Kurosawa
Actors: Kristen Bell, Ian Somerhalder, Christina Milian, Rick Gonzalez
tomatoConsensus: Another stale American remake of a successful Japanese horror film, Pulse bypasses the emotional substance of the original and overcompensates with pumped-up visuals and every known horror cliche.

Plot: A 3-D digital exploration of the ocean's depths and its creatures.
Title: Deep Sea
Actors: Johnny Depp, Kate Winslet
tomatoConsensus: Viewers will welcome being whisked away to this magical world of exotic sea life.

Plot: An aging alcoholic cop is assigned the task of escorting a witness from police custody to a courthouse 16 blocks away. There are, however, chaotic forces at work that prevent them from making it in one piece.
Title: 16 Blocks
Actors: Bruce Willis, Yasiin Bey, David Morse, Jenna Stern
tomatoConsensus: Despite strong performances from Bruce Willis and Mos Def, 16 Blocks is a shopworn entry in the buddy-action genre.

Plot: A thirty-something, is still living at home until his parents hire an interventionist to help him graduate out of the house. That's when the fun begins.
Title: Failure to Launch
Actors: Matthew McConaughey, Sarah Jessica Parker, Zooey Deschanel, Justin Bartha
tomatoConsensus: The few comic gags sprinkled throughout the movie fail to spice up this formulaic rom-com.

Plot: Manny, Sid, and Diego discover that the ice age is coming to an end, and join everybody for a journey to higher ground. On the trip, they discover that Manny, in fact, is not the last of the woolly mammoths.
Title: Ice Age: The Meltdown
Writer: Peter Gaulke (screenplay), Gerry Swallow (screenplay), Jim Hecht (screenplay), Peter Gaulke (story), Gerry Swallow (story)
Actors: Ray Romano, John Leguizamo, Denis Leary, Seann William Scott
tomatoConsensus: Despite its impressive animation and the hilarious antics of the saber-toothed squirrel Scrat, Ice Age 2: The Meltdown comes up short on the storytelling front.

Plot: Mexican beauty Camilla hopes to rise above her station by marrying a wealthy American. That is complicated by meeting Arturo Bandini, a first-generation Italian hoping to land a writing career and a blue-eyed blonde on his arm.
Title: Ask the Dust
Actors: Colin Farrell, Salma Hayek, Donald Sutherland, Eileen Atkins
tomatoConsensus: Though Hayek is luminous, Farrell seems miscast, and the film fails to capture the gritty, lively edginess of the book upon which it's based.

Plot: When her brother decides to ditch for a couple weeks in London, Viola heads over to his elite boarding school, disguises herself as him, and proceeds to fall for one of her soccer teammates. Little does she realize she's not the only one with romantic troubles, as she, as he, gets in the middle of a series of intermingled love affairs.
Title: She's the Man
Writer: Ewan Leslie (screenplay), Karen McCullah (screenplay), Kirsten Smith (screenplay), Ewan Leslie (story)
Actors: Amanda Bynes, Channing Tatum, Laura Ramsey, Vinnie Jones
tomatoConsensus: Shakespeare's wit gets lost in translation with She's the Man's broad slapstick, predictable jokes, and unconvincing plotline.

Plot: Based on the true story of Jack DiNorscio, a mobster who defended himself in court for what would be the longest mafia trial in U.S. history.
Title: Find Me Guilty
Writer: Sidney Lumet, T.J. Mancini, Robert J. McCrea
Actors: Vin Diesel, Alex Rocco, Frank Pietrangolare, Richard DeDomenico
tomatoConsensus: Find Me Guilty's excessive length and heavy-handed narrative keep it from reaching its full potential, but Vin Diesel's performance is well worth watching.

Plot: A police detective, a bank robber, and a high-power broker enter high-stakes negotiations after the criminal's brilliant heist spirals into a hostage situation.
Title: Inside Man
Actors: Denzel Washington, Clive Owen, Jodie Foster, Christopher Plummer
tomatoConsensus: Spike Lee's energetic and clever bank-heist thriller is a smart genre film that is not only rewarding on its own terms, but manages to subvert its pulpy trappings with wit and skill.

Plot: Two teenage girls discover a mermaid in their beach club's swimming pool.
Title: Aquamarine
Writer: John Quaintance (screenplay), Jessica Bendinger (screenplay), Alice Hoffman (novel)
Actors: Emma Roberts, Joanna 'JoJo' Levesque, Sara Paxton, Jake McDorman
tomatoConsensus: A lighthearted, gum-smacking, boy-crazy film with a hopeful message for young girls.

Plot: A suburban American family is being stalked by a group of psychotic people who live in the desert, far away from civilization.
Title: The Hills Have Eyes
Writer: Alexandre Aja (screenplay), Grégory Levasseur (screenplay), Wes Craven
Actors: Aaron Stanford, Kathleen Quinlan, Vinessa Shaw, Emilie de Ravin
tomatoConsensus: Faster paced for today's audiences, this Hills remake ratchets up the gore for the hardcore horror fans, but will turn away casual audiences.

Plot: A man tries to live a normal life despite the fact that he sometimes turns into a sheepdog.
Title: The Shaggy Dog
Writer: Cormac Wibberley (screenplay), Marianne Wibberley (screenplay), Geoff Rodkey (screenplay), Jack Amiel (screenplay), Michael Begler (screenplay), Bill Walsh (earlier screenplay "The Shaggy Dog"), Lillie Hayward (earlier screenplay "The Shaggy Dog"), Don Tait (earlier screenplay "The Shaggy D.A.")
Actors: Tim Allen, Kristin Davis, Zena Grey, Spencer Breslin
tomatoConsensus: This Disney retread has neither inspiration nor originality, but may please moviegoers under the age of ten.

Plot: The real story of a dance teacher who believed in the talent of a group of problem kids.
Title: Take the Lead
Actors: Antonio Banderas, Rob Brown, Yaya DaCosta, Alfre Woodard
tomatoConsensus: Banderas is charismatic in the lead, and the dance sequences are captivating, but the story is too familiar and predictable.

Plot: A young girl from South Los Angeles tries to make it to the National Spelling Bee.
Title: Akeelah and the Bee
Actors: Keke Palmer, Laurence Fishburne, Angela Bassett, Curtis Armstrong
tomatoConsensus: A warm, family-friendly underdog story, featuring terrific supporting performances from Keke Palmer, Laurence Fishburne, and Angela Bassett.

Plot: A slovenly cable repairman becomes a big-city health inspector and is tasked with uncovering the source of a food poisoning epidemic.
Title: Larry the Cable Guy: Health Inspector
Actors: Larry the Cable Guy, David Koechner, Michael Papajohn, Phyllis Alexion
tomatoConsensus: An aggressively lowbrow vehicle for its titular star, this gross-out comedy fails to "git-r-done."

Plot: For a group of teens, the answer to the mysterious death of their old friend lies within the world of an online video game based on the true story of an ancient noblewoman known as the Blood Countess.
Title: Stay Alive
Actors: Jon Foster, Samaire Armstrong, Frankie Muniz, Jimmi Simpson
tomatoConsensus: A by-the-numbers teen horror flick, Stay Alive fails to exploit its premise for any real scares.

Plot: Novelist Catherine Tramell is once again in trouble with the law, and Scotland Yard appoints psychiatrist Dr. Michael Glass to evaluate her. Though, like Detective Nick Curran before him, Glass is entranced by Tramell and lured into a seductive game.
Title: Basic Instinct 2
Writer: Leora Barish, Henry Bean, Joe Eszterhas (characters)
Actors: Stan Collymore, Sharon Stone, Neil Maskell, David Thewlis
tomatoConsensus: Unable to match the suspense and titilation of its predecessor, Basic Instinct 2 boasts a plot so ludicrous and predictable it borders on "so-bad-it's-good."

Plot: As four friends prepare for life after high school, different challenges bring about turning points in each of their lives. The dramas unfold and resolve at their local rollerskating rink, Cascade.
Title: ATL
Actors: Greg Andrews, Monica Arnold, Brandon Bernard Benton, Adam Boyer
tomatoConsensus: Strong lead performances and catchy musical interludes rescue this coming-of-age story from its formulaic script and uneven direction.

Plot: A small town is taken over by an alien plague, turning residents into zombies and all forms of mutant monsters.
Title: Slither
Actors: Don Thompson, Nathan Fillion, Gregg Henry, Xantha Radley
tomatoConsensus: A slimy, B-movie homage oozing with affection for low-budget horror films, Slither is creepy and funny -- if you've got the stomach for it.

Plot: A trio of guys try and make up for missed opportunities in childhood by forming a three-player baseball team to compete against standard children baseball squads.
Title: The Benchwarmers
Actors: Rob Schneider, David Spade, Jon Heder, Jon Lovitz
tomatoConsensus: A gross-out comedy that is more sophomoric than funny, The Benchwarmers goes down swinging.

Plot: Two plus-sized ladies meet the men of their dreams in the most unexpected of ways.
Title: Phat Girlz
Actors: Mo'Nique, Jimmy Jean-Louis, Godfrey, Kendra C. Johnson
tomatoConsensus: Although Phat Girlz has good intentions, it is sloppily made and thin on laughs.

Plot: A young man (Lerman) moves from Montana to Florida with his family, where he's compelled to engage in a fight to protect a population of endangered owls.
Title: Hoot
Actors: Luke Wilson, Logan Lerman, Brie Larson, Tim Blake Nelson
tomatoConsensus: Lacking energy and humor, Hoot is a ho-hum story of eco-awareness that falls flat as a pancake.

Plot: Cindy finds out the house she lives in is haunted by a little boy and goes on a quest to find out who killed him and why. Also, Alien "Tr-iPods" are invading the world and she has to uncover the secret in order to stop them.
Title: Scary Movie 4
Writer: Craig Mazin (screenplay), Jim Abrahams (screenplay), Pat Proft (screenplay), Craig Mazin (story), Shawn Wayans (characters), Marlon Wayans (characters), Buddy Johnson (characters), Phil Beauman (characters), Jason Friedberg (characters), Aaron Seltzer (characters)
Actors: Anna Faris, Regina Hall, Craig Bierko, Bill Pullman
tomatoConsensus: Sure to inspire a few chuckles, but not enough to compensate for the recycled material from its predecessors.

Plot: A Secret Service agent is framed as the mole in an assassination attempt on the President. He must clear his name and foil another assassination attempt while on the run from a Secret Service Protective Intelligence Division agent.
Title: The Sentinel
Actors: Michael Douglas, Kiefer Sutherland, Eva Longoria, Martin Donovan
tomatoConsensus: The Sentinel starts off well enough but quickly wears thin with too many plot holes and conventional action sequences.

Plot: An adolescent lion is accidentally shipped from the New York Zoo to Africa. Now running free, his zoo pals must put aside their differences to help bring him back.
Title: The Wild
Writer: Ed Decter (screenplay), John J. Strauss (screenplay), Mark Gibson (screenplay), Philip Halprin (screenplay), Mark Gibson (story), Philip Halprin (story), Bill Wolkoff (additional story material), David Collard (additional story material), Matt Lopez (additional story material), Lloyd Taylor (additional story material), Steve 'Spaz' Williams (additional story material)
Actors: Kiefer Sutherland, Jim Belushi, Eddie Izzard, Janeane Garofalo
tomatoConsensus: With a rehashed plot and unimpressive animation, there's nothing wild about The Wild.

Plot: A woman, Rose, goes in search for her adopted daughter within the confines of a strange, desolate town called Silent Hill.
Title: Silent Hill
Actors: Radha Mitchell, Sean Bean, Laurie Holden, Deborah Kara Unger
tomatoConsensus: Silent Hill is visually impressive, but as with many video game adaptations, it's plagued by inane dialogue, a muddled plot, and an overlong runtime.

Plot: The new season of "American Dreamz," the wildly popular television singing contest, has captured the country's attention, as the competition looks to be between a young Midwestern gal (Moore) and a showtunes-loving young man from Orange County (Golzari). Recently awakened President Staton (Quaid) even wants in on the craze, as he signs up for the potential explosive season finale.
Title: American Dreamz
Actors: Hugh Grant, Dennis Quaid, Mandy Moore, Willem Dafoe
tomatoConsensus: This overly silly satire aims at too many targets with arrows too dull to make relevant social commentary.

Plot: Agent Ethan Hunt comes into conflict with a dangerous and sadistic arms dealer who threatens his life and his fianceé in response .
Language: English, Italian, Mandarin, Cantonese, German, Czech
Title: Mission: Impossible III
Writer: Alex Kurtzman, Roberto Orci, J.J. Abrams, Bruce Geller (television series)
Actors: Tom Cruise, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Ving Rhames, Billy Crudup
tomatoConsensus: Fast-paced, with eye-popping stunts and special effects, the latest Mission: Impossible installment delivers everything an action fan could ask for. A thrilling summer popcorn flick.

Plot: Bob Munro and his dysfunctional family rent an RV for a road trip to the Colorado Rockies, where they ultimately have to contend with a bizarre community of campers.
Title: RV
Actors: Robin Williams, Cheryl Hines, Joanna 'JoJo' Levesque, Josh Hutcherson
tomatoConsensus: An unoriginal and only occasionally funny family road-trip movie, RV is a mediocre effort that not even the charisma of Robin Williams can save.

Plot: A real-time account of the events on United Flight 93, one of the planes hijacked on September 11th, 2001 that crashed near Shanksville, Pennsylvania when passengers foiled the terrorist plot.
Title: United 93
Actors: J.J. Johnson, Gary Commock, Polly Adams, Opal Alladin
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 27 wins & 46 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Potent and sobering, United 93 treats the subject matter with respect, never resorting to Hollywood aggrandizement.

Plot: After a run-in with the law, Haley Graham (Missy Peregrym) is forced to return to the world from which she fled some years ago. Enrolled in an elite gymnastics program run by the legendary Burt Vickerman (Jeff Bridges), Haley's rebellious attitude gives way to something that just might be called team spirit.
Title: Stick It
Actors: Jeff Bridges, Missy Peregrym, Vanessa Lengies, Nikki SooHoo
tomatoConsensus: Director Jessica Bendinger is unable to transfer her winning Bring It On formula to the world of gymnastics, despite Missy Peregrym's strong lead performance.

Plot: A scheming raccoon fools a mismatched family of forest creatures into helping him repay a debt of food, by invading the new suburban sprawl that popped up while they were hibernating...and learns a lesson about family himself.
Title: Over the Hedge
Writer: Len Blum (screenplay), Lorne Cameron (screenplay), David Hoselton (screenplay), Karey Kirkpatrick (screenplay), Michael Fry (comic strip characters), T. Lewis (comic strip characters), Chris Poche (additional dialogue), Mike de Seve (story consultant), Eric Forsberg (additional dialogue)
Actors: Bruce Willis, Garry Shandling, Steve Carell, Wanda Sykes
tomatoConsensus: Even if it's not an animation classic, Over the Hedge is clever and fun, and the jokes cater to family members of all ages.

Plot: Starting from childhood attempts at illustration, the protagonist pursues his true obsession to art school. But as he learns how the art world really works, he finds that he must adapt his vision to the reality that confronts him.
Title: Art School Confidential
Actors: Max Minghella, Sophia Myles, John Malkovich, Jim Broadbent
tomatoConsensus: Art School's misanthropy is too sour, its targets too flat and cliched, and Clowes and Zwigoff stumble when trying to build a story around the premise.

Plot: On New Year's Eve, the luxury ocean liner Poseidon capsizes after being swamped by a rogue wave. The survivors are left to fight for their lives as they attempt to escape the sinking ship.
Title: Poseidon
Actors: Josh Lucas, Kurt Russell, Jacinda Barrett, Richard Dreyfuss
tomatoConsensus: This remake of The Poseidon Adventure delivers dazzling special effects. Unfortunately, it doesn't seem that any of the budget was left over to devote to the script.

Plot: A murder inside the Louvre and clues in Da Vinci paintings lead to the discovery of a religious mystery protected by a secret society for two thousand years -- which could shake the foundations of Christianity.
Title: The Da Vinci Code
Actors: Tom Hanks, Audrey Tautou, Ian McKellen, Jean Reno
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 6 wins & 21 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: What makes Dan Brown's novel a best seller is evidently not present in this dull and bloated movie adaptation of The Da Vinci Code.

Plot: When a cure is found to treat mutations, lines are drawn amongst the X-Men, led by Professor Charles Xavier, and the Brotherhood, a band of powerful mutants organized under Xavier's former ally, Magneto.
Title: X-Men: The Last Stand
Actors: Hugh Jackman, Halle Berry, Ian McKellen, Patrick Stewart
tomatoConsensus: X-Men: The Last Stand provides plenty of mutant action for fans of the franchise, even if it does so at the expense of its predecessors' deeper character moments.

Plot: In a bid to keep their luxurious condo from their significant other, a couple's break-up proceeds to get uglier and nastier by the moment.
Title: The Break-Up
Writer: Jeremy Garelick (screenplay), Jay Lavender (screenplay), Vince Vaughn (story), Jeremy Garelick (story), Jay Lavender (story)
Actors: Vince Vaughn, Jennifer Aniston, Joey Lauren Adams, Cole Hauser
tomatoConsensus: This anti-romantic comedy lacks both laughs and insight, resulting in an odd and unsatisfying experience.

Plot: A chance encounter with a stranger changes the life of a college gymnast.
Title: Peaceful Warrior
Actors: Scott Mechlowicz, Nick Nolte, Amy Smart, Tim DeKay
tomatoConsensus: Based on a best-selling memoir, Peaceful Warrior loses something in the transition from page to screen. It hits the viewer over the head with philosophical jargon, and ultimately fails to live up to its source material.

Plot: A 13-year-old boy uses his upcoming bar mitzvah to reconcile the strained relationship between his father and grandfather.
Title: Keeping Up with the Steins
Actors: Daryl Sabara, Jami Gertz, Jeremy Piven, Cheryl Hines
tomatoConsensus: Keeping Up With the Steins is one of those comedies that play more like a corny sitcom than a theatrical movie.

Plot: A hot-shot race-car named Lightning McQueen gets waylaid in Radiator Springs, where he finds the true meaning of friendship and family.
Title: Cars
Writer: John Lasseter (original story by), Joe Ranft (original story by), Jorgen Klubien (original story by), Dan Fogelman (screenplay), John Lasseter (screenplay), Joe Ranft (screenplay), Kiel Murray (screenplay), Phil Lorin (screenplay), Jorgen Klubien (screenplay)
Actors: Owen Wilson, Paul Newman, Bonnie Hunt, Larry the Cable Guy
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 27 wins & 28 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Cars offers visual treats that more than compensate for its somewhat thinly written story, adding up to a satisfying diversion for younger viewers.

Title: The Omen
Actors: Predrag Bjelac, Carlo Sabatini, Bohumil Svarc, Liev Schreiber
tomatoConsensus: Even with the force of a "classic" behind it, remake fever can't hold up the hollowness of this style-drenched Omen.

Plot: Berated all his life by those around him, a monk follows his dream and dons a mask to moonlight as a Luchador (Mexican wrestler).
Title: Nacho Libre
Writer: Jared Hess, Jerusha Hess, Mike White
Actors: Jack Black, Ana de la Reguera, Héctor Jiménez, Darius Rose
tomatoConsensus: At times hilarious, but other times offensive, Director Jared Hess is unable to recapture the collective charisma of his Napoleon characters, instead relying on a one-joke concept that runs out of steam. Sure to entertain the adolescents, however.

Plot: A lonely doctor who once occupied an unusual lakeside home begins exchanging love letters with its former resident, a frustrated architect. They must try to unravel the mystery behind their extraordinary romance before it's too late.
Title: The Lake House
Writer: David Auburn (screenplay), Eun-Jeong Kim (motion picture "Siworae"), Ji-na Yeo (motion picture "Siworae")
Actors: Keanu Reeves, Sandra Bullock, Christopher Plummer, Ebon Moss-Bachrach
tomatoConsensus: The plot of The Lake House is a little too convoluted, and the film fails to pull off the sweeping romance it aims for.

Plot: A workaholic architect finds a universal remote that allows him to fast-forward and rewind to different parts of his life. Complications arise when the remote starts to overrule his choices.
Title: Click
Actors: Adam Sandler, Kate Beckinsale, Christopher Walken, David Hasselhoff
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 11 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This latest Adam Sandler vehicle borrows shamelessly from It's A Wonderful Life and Back To The Future, and fails to produce the necessary laughs that would forgive such imitation.

Plot: A smart but sensible new graduate lands a job as an assistant to Miranda Priestly, the demanding editor-in-chief of a high fashion magazine.
Title: The Devil Wears Prada
Actors: Meryl Streep, Anne Hathaway, Emily Blunt, Stanley Tucci
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 16 wins & 48 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A rare film that surpasses the quality of its source novel, this Devil is a witty expose of New York's fashion scene, with Meryl Streep in top form and Anne Hathaway more than holding her own.

Plot: Jack Sparrow races to recover the heart of Davy Jones to avoid enslaving his soul to Jones' service, as other friends and foes seek the heart for their own agenda as well.
Title: Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest
Writer: Ted Elliott, Terry Rossio, Ted Elliott (characters), Terry Rossio (characters), Stuart Beattie (characters), Jay Wolpert (characters)
Actors: Johnny Depp, Orlando Bloom, Keira Knightley, Jack Davenport
tomatoConsensus: Gone is Depp's unpredictability and much of the humor and originality of the first movie.

Plot: A best man (Wilson) stays on as a houseguest with the newlyweds, much to the couple's annoyance.
Title: You, Me and Dupree
Actors: Owen Wilson, Kate Hudson, Matt Dillon, Michael Douglas
tomatoConsensus: A rather generic entry into the arrested development subgenre, with themes borrowed from other more successful and funnier films. Dupree wears out its welcome.

Plot: A calamity at Dante and Randal's shops sends them looking for new horizons - but they ultimately settle at the fast food empire Mooby's.
Title: Clerks II
Actors: Brian O'Halloran, Jeff Anderson, Jason Mewes, Kevin Smith
tomatoConsensus: Clerks II dishes up much of the graphic humor and some of the insight that made the 1994 original a cult hit.

Plot: Apartment building superintendent Cleveland Heep rescues what he thinks is a young woman from the pool he maintains. When he discovers that she is actually a character from a bedtime story who is trying to make the journey back to her home, he works with his tenants to protect his new friend from the creatures that are determined to keep her in our world.
Title: Lady in the Water
Actors: Paul Giamatti, Bryce Dallas Howard, Jeffrey Wright, Bob Balaban
tomatoConsensus: A far-fetched story with little suspense and unconvincing scenarios, Lady In The Water feels contrived, pretentious, and rather silly.

Plot: When a regular guy dumps a superhero for her neediness, she uses her powers to make his life a living hell.
Title: My Super Ex-Girlfriend
Actors: Uma Thurman, Luke Wilson, Anna Faris, Rainn Wilson
tomatoConsensus: My Super Ex=Girlfriend is an only sporadically amusing spoof on the superhero genre that misses the mark with a nerd-turned-superwoman who embodies sexist clichés.

Plot: A group of delinquents are sent to clean the Blackwell Hotel. Little do they know reclusive psychopath Jacob Goodnight has holed away in the rotting hotel. When one of the teens is captured, those who remain - a group that includes the cop who put a bullet in Goodnight's head four years ago - band together to survive against the brutal killer.
Title: See No Evil
Actors: Glenn Jacobs, Christina Vidal, Michael J. Pagan, Samantha Noble
tomatoConsensus: See No Evil is packed with cliches from countless other teen slasher films, making for a predictable, scare-free waste of time.

Plot: The retelling of France's iconic but ill-fated queen, Marie Antoinette. From her betrothal and marriage to Louis XVI at 15 to her reign as queen at 19 and to the end of her reign as queen and ultimately the fall of Versailles.
Title: Marie Antoinette
Actors: Kirsten Dunst, Jason Schwartzman, Judy Davis, Rip Torn
tomatoConsensus: Lavish imagery and a daring soundtrack set this film apart from most period dramas; in fact, style complete takes precedence over plot and character development in Coppola's vision of the doomed queen.

Plot: A documentary that investigates the birth and death of the electric car, as well as the role of renewable energy and sustainable living in the future.
Title: Who Killed the Electric Car?
Actors: Martin Sheen, Reverend Gadget, Dave Barthmuss, Ed Begley Jr.
tomatoConsensus: A searing indictment of big business and greed, Who Killed The Electric Car? is a well-tuned doc that simultaneously entertains and enrages.

Plot: Filmmaker Davis Guggenheim follows Al Gore on the lecture circuit, as the former presidential candidate campaigns to raise public awareness of the dangers of global warming and calls for immediate action to curb its destructive effects on the environment.
Title: An Inconvenient Truth
Actors: Al Gore, Billy West
tomatoConsensus: This candid, powerful and informative documentary illuminates some of the myths surrounding its dual subjects: global warming and Al Gore.

Plot: A teenager becomes a major competitor in the world of drift racing after moving in with his father in Tokyo to avoid a jail sentence in America.
Title: The Fast and the Furious: Tokyo Drift
Actors: Lucas Black, Damien Marzette, Trula M. Marcus, Zachery Ty Bryan
tomatoConsensus: Eye-popping driving sequences coupled with a limp story and flat performances make this Drift an adequate follow-up to the previous Fast and Furious installments. Strictly for the racing crowd and fans of the first two films.

Plot: Jon and Garfield visit the United Kingdom, where a case of mistaken cat identity finds Garfield ruling over a castle. His reign is soon jeopardized by the nefarious Lord Dargis, who has designs on the estate.
Title: Garfield 2
Writer: Joel Cohen, Alec Sokolow, Jim Davis (comic strip "Garfield")
Actors: Breckin Meyer, Jennifer Love Hewitt, Billy Connolly, Bill Murray
tomatoConsensus: Strictly for (very) little kids, A Tale of Two Kitties features skilled voice actors but a plot that holds little interest.

Plot: An ex-convict (Tyrese) gets tangled up with a gang after his car is hijacked with his son inside.
Title: Waist Deep
Writer: Vondie Curtis-Hall (screenplay), Darin Scott (screenplay), Michael Mahern (story)
Actors: Tyrese Gibson, Shawn Parr, Henry Hunter Hall, Johnny C. Pruitt
tomatoConsensus: A well-meaning B-movie that suffers from a cliche-ridden script and poorly drawn characters that fail to inspire much sympathy.

Plot: Superman reappears after a long absence, but is challenged by an old foe who uses Kryptonian technology for world domination.
Title: Superman Returns
Writer: Michael Dougherty (screenplay), Dan Harris (screenplay), Bryan Singer (story), Michael Dougherty (story), Dan Harris (story), Jerry Siegel (characters), Joe Shuster (characters)
Actors: Brandon Routh, Kate Bosworth, Kevin Spacey, James Marsden
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 12 wins & 38 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Bryan Singer's reverent and visually decadent adaptation gives the Man of Steel welcome emotional complexity. The result: a satisfying stick-to-your-ribs adaptation.

Plot: Part drama, part documentary, The Road to Guantánamo focuses on the Tipton Three, a trio of British Muslims who were held in Guantanamo Bay for two years until they were released without charge.
Title: The Road to Guantanamo
Actors: Riz Ahmed, Farhad Harun, Waqar Siddiqui, Arfan Usman
tomatoConsensus: A gut-wrenching and riveting docu-drama that serves as a stinging indictment of U.S. military justice in an era of ever-increasing scrutiny.

Plot: A family determined to get their young daughter into the finals of a beauty pageant take a cross-country trip in their VW bus.
Title: Little Miss Sunshine
Actors: Abigail Breslin, Greg Kinnear, Paul Dano, Alan Arkin
tomatoConsensus: Little Miss Sunshine succeeds thanks to a strong ensemble cast that includes Greg Kinnear, Steve Carell, Toni Collette, Alan Arkin, and Abigail Breslin, as well as a delightfully funny script.

Plot: Tragedy strikes a married couple on vacation in the Moroccan desert, touching off an interlocking story involving four different families.
Language: English, Arabic, Spanish, Japanese, Berber languages, French, Russian, Japanese Sign Language
Title: Babel
Writer: Guillermo Arriaga, Guillermo Arriaga (idea), Alejandro G. Iñárritu (idea)
Actors: Brad Pitt, Cate Blanchett, Mohamed Akhzam, Peter Wight
tomatoConsensus: In Babel, there are no villains, only victims of fate and circumstance. Director Alejandro Gonzalez Iñarritu weaves four of their woeful stories into this mature and multidimensional film.

Plot: An in-depth look at The New York Times' long-time crossword puzzle editor Will Shortz and his loyal fan base.
Title: Wordplay
Actors: Will Shortz, Merl Reagle, Tyler Hinman, Trip Payne
tomatoConsensus: You see them hunched over with their brows furrowed, folded newspaper in hand as they attempt to complete the crossword puzzle. This may even describe you. This ingeniously edited documentary introduces viewers to some of the more dedicated fans of this solitary pastime, none more well-known the puzzle editor for the New York Times, Will Shortz. This underground world provides a surprising amount of crowd-pleasing entertainment and suspense, especially at the annual crossword tournament. Didn't know there was one, did you?

Plot: A wannabe dad mistakes a vertically challenged criminal on the lam as his newly adopted son.
Title: Littleman
Writer: Keenen Ivory Wayans, Shawn Wayans, Marlon Wayans
Actors: Marlon Wayans, Shawn Wayans, Kerry Washington, John Witherspoon
tomatoConsensus: Another gimmicky comedy from the Wayans brothers, Little Man comes with the requisite raunchiness, but forgot to bring the laughs.

Plot: Three teens discover that their neighbor's house is really a living, breathing, scary monster.
Title: Monster House
Writer: Dan Harmon (screenplay), Rob Schrab (screenplay), Pamela Pettler (screenplay), Dan Harmon (story), Rob Schrab (story)
Actors: Ryan Newman, Steve Buscemi, Mitchel Musso, Catherine O'Hara
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 23 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Monster House welcoms kids and adults alike into a household full of smart, monstrous fun.

Plot: An FBI agent takes on a plane full of deadly and venomous snakes, deliberately released to kill a witness being flown from Honolulu to Los Angeles to testify against a mob boss.
Title: Snakes on a Plane
Writer: John Heffernan (screenplay), Sebastian Gutierrez (screenplay), David Dalessandro (story), John Heffernan (story)
Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Julianna Margulies, Nathan Phillips, Rachel Blanchard
tomatoConsensus: Snakes on a Plane lives up to its title, featuring snakes on a plane. It isn't perfect, but then again, it doesn't need to be.

Title: Scoop
Actors: Jim Dunk, Robert Bathurst, Geoff Bell, Christopher Fulford
tomatoConsensus: Rehashing old plot lines and characters, Scoop is a tiresome dipper and another disappointing addition to Woody Allen's repertoire.

Plot: #1 NASCAR driver Ricky Bobby stays atop the heap thanks to a pact with his best friend and teammate, Cal Naughton, Jr. But when a French Formula One driver, makes his way up the ladder, Ricky Bobby's talent and devotion are put to the test.
Title: Talladega Nights: The Ballad of Ricky Bobby
Actors: Will Ferrell, John C. Reilly, Sacha Baron Cohen, Gary Cole
tomatoConsensus: Though it occasionally stalls, Talladega Nights' mix of satire, clever gags, and excellent ensemble performances put it squarely in the winner's circle.

Plot: A newly recruited night security guard at the Museum of Natural History discovers that an ancient curse causes the animals and exhibits on display to come to life and wreak havoc.
Title: Night at the Museum
Writer: Robert Ben Garant (screenplay), Thomas Lennon (screenplay), Robert Ben Garant (screen story), Thomas Lennon (screen story), Milan Trenc (book)
Actors: Ben Stiller, Carla Gugino, Dick Van Dyke, Mickey Rooney
tomatoConsensus: Parents might call this either a spectacle-filled adventure or a shallow and vapid CG-fest, depending on whether they choose to embrace this on the same level as their kids.

Plot: Two Port Authority police officers become trapped under the rubble of the World Trade Center.
Title: World Trade Center
Writer: Andrea Berloff, John McLoughlin (true story), Donna McLoughlin (true story), William Jimeno (true story), Allison Jimeno (true story)
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Maria Bello, Connor Paolo, Anthony Piccininni
tomatoConsensus: As a visually stunning tribute to lives lost in tragedy, World Trade Center succeeds unequivocally, and it is more politically muted than many of Stone's other works.

Plot: An IRS auditor suddenly finds himself the subject of narration only he can hear: narration that begins to affect his entire life, from his work, to his love-interest, to his death.
Title: Stranger Than Fiction
Actors: Will Ferrell, William Dick, Guy Massey, Martha Espinoza
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 14 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A fun, whimsical tale about an office drone trying to save his life from his narrator, Stranger Than Fiction features a subdued performances from Will Ferrell that contributes mightily to its quirky, mind-bending affect.

Plot: Based on the 1980s TV action/drama, this update focuses on vice detectives Crockett and Tubbs as their respective personal and professional lives become dangerously intertwined.
Title: Miami Vice
Actors: Colin Farrell, Jamie Foxx, Li Gong, Naomie Harris
tomatoConsensus: Miami Vice is beautifully shot but the lead characters lack the charisma of their TV series counterparts, and the underdeveloped story is well below the standards of Michael Mann's better films.

Plot: A struggling salesman takes custody of his son as he's poised to begin a life-changing professional endeavor.
Title: The Pursuit of Happyness
Actors: Will Smith, Jaden Smith, Thandie Newton, Brian Howe
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 24 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Will Smith's heartfelt performance elevates The Pursuit of Happyness above mere melodrama.

Plot: Three ex-girlfriends of a serial cheater set up their former lover to fall for the new girl in town so they can watch him get his heart broken.
Title: John Tucker Must Die
Actors: Jesse Metcalfe, Brittany Snow, Ashanti, Sophia Bush
tomatoConsensus: This derivitive teen comedy tries to go for cute when it could use more bite.

Plot: After Lucas Nickle floods an ant colony with his watergun, he's magically shrunken down to insect size and sentenced to hard labor in the ruins.
Title: The Ant Bully
Actors: Julia Roberts, Nicolas Cage, Meryl Streep, Paul Giamatti
tomatoConsensus: Sometimes inventive and witty, this animated adventure into an ant-sized world is a pleasant diversion.

Plot: Professional assassin Chev Chelios learns his rival has injected him with a poison that will kill him if his heart rate drops.
Title: Crank
Actors: Jason Statham, Amy Smart, Jose Pablo Cantillo, Efren Ramirez
tomatoConsensus: It's a film about a guy injected with Speed... wait, there's no bus. It's a film about a guy who has to kick a bunch of squirmy butt to stay alive... wait, no snakes or planes here. But it is a film about doing lots of drugs and pulling lots of punches, and it entertains accordingly.

Plot: In the midst of his crumbling relationship, a radio show host begins speaking to his biggest fan, a young boy, via the telephone. But when questions about the boy's identity come up, the host's life is thrown into chaos.
Title: The Night Listener
Writer: Armistead Maupin (screenplay), Terry Anderson (screenplay), Patrick Stettner (screenplay), Armistead Maupin (novel)
Actors: Robin Williams, Toni Collette, Joe Morton, Bobby Cannavale
tomatoConsensus: This psychological thriller compels by blurring the line between truth and fiction; unfortunately, the film itself gets muddled in a hazy account of Maupin's original novel.

Plot: When the farmer's away, all the animals play ... and sing, and dance. Eventually, though, someone has to step in and run things, a responsibility that ends up going to Otis, a carefree cow.
Title: Barnyard
Actors: Kevin James, Courteney Cox, Sam Elliott, Danny Glover
tomatoConsensus: Unimaginative and unfunny, this tale of barnyard mischief borders on 'udder' creepiness and adds little to this summer's repertoire of animated films.

Plot: Tyler Gage receives the opportunity of a lifetime after vandalizing a performing arts school, gaining him the chance to earn a scholarship and dance with an up and coming dancer, Nora.
Title: Step Up
Writer: Duane Adler (screenplay), Melissa Rosenberg (screenplay), Duane Adler (story)
Actors: Channing Tatum, Jenna Dewan Tatum, Damaine Radcliff, De'Shawn Washington
tomatoConsensus: This trite teen romance has too little plot and not enough dancing.

Plot: Former superhero Jack is called back to work to transform an unlikely group of ragtag kids into superheroes at a private Academy.
Title: Zoom
Writer: Adam Rifkin (screenplay), David Berenbaum (screenplay), Adam Rifkin (screen story), Jason Lethcoe (novel)
Actors: Tim Allen, Courteney Cox, Chevy Chase, Spencer Breslin
tomatoConsensus: Lacking the punch and good cheer of The Incredibles and Sky High, Zoom is a dull and laugh-free affair.

Plot: An inner-city junior high school teacher with a drug habit forms an unlikely friendship with one of his students after she discovers his secret.
Title: Half Nelson
Actors: Ryan Gosling, Jeff Lima, Shareeka Epps, Nathan Corbett
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 27 wins & 45 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Half Nelson features powerful performances from Ryan Gosling and Shareeka Epps. It's a wise, unsentimental portrait of lonely people at the crossroads.

Plot: Two wealthy sisters, both heiresses to their family's cosmetics fortune, are given a wake-up call when a scandal and ensuing investigation strip them of their wealth.
Title: Material Girls
Writer: John Quaintance, Jessica O'Toole, Amy Rardin
Actors: Hilary Duff, Haylie Duff, Maria Conchita Alonso, Anjelica Huston
tomatoConsensus: Plagued by paper-thin characterizations and a hackneyed script, Material Girls fails to live up to even the minimum standards of its genre.

Plot: A high school slacker who's rejected by every school he applies to opts to create his own institution of higher learning, the South Harmon Institute of Technology, on a rundown piece of property near his hometown.
Title: Accepted
Writer: Adam Cooper (screenplay), Bill Collage (screenplay), Mark Perez (screenplay), Mark Perez (story)
Actors: Justin Long, Jonah Hill, Adam Herschman, Columbus Short
tomatoConsensus: Like its characters who aren't able to meet their potential, Accepted's inconsistent and ridiculous plot gets annoying, despite a few laughs.

Plot: In turn-of-the-century Vienna, a magician uses his abilities to secure the love of a woman far above his social standing.
Title: The Illusionist
Writer: Neil Burger (screenplay), Steven Millhauser (short story "Eisenheim the Illusionist")
Actors: Edward Norton, Paul Giamatti, Jessica Biel, Rufus Sewell
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 9 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Illusionist is an engrossing, well-crafted story of mystery, magic and intrigue that is certain to enchant, if not hypnotize, audiences.

Plot: After the death of Princess Diana, Queen Elizabeth II struggles with her reaction to a sequence of events nobody could have predicted.
Title: The Queen
Actors: Helen Mirren, James Cromwell, Alex Jennings, Roger Allam
tomatoConsensus: Full of wit, humor, and pathos, Stephen Frears' moving portrait looks at life of the British royals during the period after Princess Diana's death.

Plot: Two brothers travel to Germany for Oktoberfest, only to stumble upon a secret, centuries-old competition described as a "Fight Club" with beer games.
Title: Beerfest
Writer: Jay Chandrasekhar, Kevin Heffernan, Steve Lemme, Paul Soter, Erik Stolhanske
Actors: M.C. Gainey, Paul Soter, Erik Stolhanske, Cloris Leachman
tomatoConsensus: Beerfest features some laugh-inducing gags, but is too long and the pacing too uneven to form a coherent, functioning comedy.

Plot: During the first day of his new school year, a fifth grade boy squares off against a bully and winds up accepting a dare that could change the balance of power within the class.
Title: How to Eat Fried Worms
Actors: Luke Benward, Hallie Kate Eisenberg, Adam Hicks, Austin Rogers
tomatoConsensus: This Fear Factor for kids is good-natured and tasty enough.

Plot: Based on the story of Vince Papale, a 30-year-old bartender from South Philadelphia who overcame long odds to play for the NFL's Philadelphia Eagles in 1976.
Title: Invincible
Actors: Mark Wahlberg, Greg Kinnear, Elizabeth Banks, Kevin Conway
tomatoConsensus: As simple and authentic as the gritty South Philly invirons in which it's set in, Invincible sends a uplifting and heartfelt message packed with an athletic enthusiasm that shouldn't be missed.

Plot: A musical set in the Prohibition-era American South, where a speakeasy performer and club manager Rooster must contend with gangsters who have their eyes on the club while his piano player ...
Title: Idlewild
Actors: André Benjamin, Big Boi, Paula Patton, Terrence Howard
tomatoConsensus: Idlewild has some truly breathtaking moments, but borrows too heavily from other similar movies, and the disjointed script is not worthy of talents involved.

Plot: As Magdalena's 15th birthday approaches, her simple, blissful life is complicated by the discovery that she's pregnant. Kicked out of her house, she finds a new family with her great-granduncle and gay cousin.
Title: Quinceañera
Actors: Jesus Castanos, Araceli Guzman-Rico, Emily Rios, J.R. Cruz
tomatoConsensus: This slice-of-life story of a teenage girl in Echo Park is both a sweet crowd-pleaser and a perceptive look at socioeconomic community issues.

Plot: A naturally talented basketball player, Noah Cruise is determined to become a doctor using his basketball scholarship to UCLA pre-med, rather than succumb to the lure of former sports agent...
Title: Crossover
Actors: Anthony Mackie, Wesley Jonathan, Eva Marcille, Wayne Brady
tomatoConsensus: This heartfelt but incompetent, cliche-ridden sports picture is the cinematic equivalent of an airball.

Plot: Against the backdrop of the Irish War of Independence, two brothers fight a guerrilla war against British forces.
Title: The Wind That Shakes the Barley
Country: Ireland, UK, Germany, Italy, Spain, France, Belgium, Switzerland
Actors: Cillian Murphy, Pádraic Delaney, Liam Cunningham, Orla Fitzgerald
tomatoConsensus: Bleak and uncompromising, but director Ken Loach brightens his film with gorgeous cinematography and tight pacing, and features a fine performance from Cillian Murphy.

Plot: During a team-building retreat in the mountains a group of sales representatives are hunted down one by one.
Title: Severance
Writer: James Moran (screenplay), Christopher Smith (screenplay), James Moran (story)
Actors: Toby Stephens, Claudie Blakley, Andy Nyman, Babou Ceesay
tomatoConsensus: A twisted and bloody spoof on office life, Severance nicely balances comedy and nasty horror.

Plot: A detective examines the mysterious death of George Reeves, the star of the television series Adventures of Superman (1952).
Title: Hollywoodland
Actors: Adrien Brody, Diane Lane, Ben Affleck, Bob Hoskins
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 7 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: More than a movie star murder mystery, Hollywoodland takes it slow in order to reveal the intriguing details of the rise and fall of superstar fame.

Plot: Four young men who belong to a New England supernatural legacy are forced to battle a fifth power long thought to have died out. Meanwhile, jealousy and suspicion threaten to tear them apart.
Title: The Covenant
Actors: Steven Strait, Laura Ramsey, Sebastian Stan, Taylor Kitsch
tomatoConsensus: The Covenant plays out like a teen soap opera, full of pretty faces, wooden acting, laughable dialogue, and little suspense.

Plot: Michael and Jenna, having been a couple for three years, want to get married and start a family. These plans seem to be well on their way when Jenna announces that she's pregnant. But ...
Title: The Last Kiss
Writer: Paul Haggis (screenplay), Gabriele Muccino (motion picture "L'ultimo bacio")
