Actors: Zach Braff, Jacinda Barrett, Casey Affleck, Rachel Bilson
tomatoConsensus: You'll either find the The Last Kiss to be a phony bore or a refreshing take about young 20-somethings at the crossroads between their carefree lifestyle and responsibility. Zach Braff and the rest of the appealing cast make the case for the latter.

Plot: Private Joe Bauers, the definition of "average American", is selected by the Pentagon to be the guinea pig for a top-secret hibernation program. Forgotten, he awakes five centuries in the future. He discovers a society so incredibly dumbed down that he's easily the most intelligent person alive.
Title: Idiocracy
Writer: Mike Judge (story), Mike Judge (screenplay), Etan Cohen (screenplay)
Actors: Luke Wilson, Maya Rudolph, Dax Shepard, Terry Crews
tomatoConsensus: Idiocracy delivers the hilarity and biting satire that could only come from Mike Judge.

Plot: A documentary on kids who attend a summer camp hoping to become the next Billy Graham.
Title: Jesus Camp
Actors: Lou Engle, Becky Fischer, Ted Haggard, Mike Papantonio
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 6 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Evangelical indoctrination is given an unflinching, even-handed look in this utterly worthwhile documentary.

Plot: As a modern-day scientist, Tommy is struggling with mortality, desperately searching for the medical breakthrough that will save the life of his cancer-stricken wife, Izzi.
Title: The Fountain
Writer: Darren Aronofsky (screenplay), Darren Aronofsky (story), Ari Handel (story)
Actors: Hugh Jackman, Rachel Weisz, Ellen Burstyn, Mark Margolis
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 9 wins & 31 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Fountain -- a movie about metaphysics, universal patterns, Biblical symbolism, and boundless love spread across one thousand years -- is visually rich but suffers from its own unfocused ambitions.

Plot: A man entranced by his dreams and imagination is love-struck with a French woman and feels he can show her his world.
Title: The Science of Sleep
Actors: Gael García Bernal, Charlotte Gainsbourg, Alain Chabat, Miou-Miou
tomatoConsensus: Lovely and diffuse, Sleep isn't as immediately absorbing as Gondry's previous work, but its messy beauty is its own reward.

Plot: Two policemen see their personal and professional lives fall apart in the wake of the "Black Dahlia" murder investigation.
Title: The Black Dahlia
Actors: Josh Hartnett, Scarlett Johansson, Aaron Eckhart, Hilary Swank
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 12 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though this ambitious noir crime-drama captures the atmosphere of its era, it suffers from subpar performances, a convoluted story, and the inevitable comparisons to other, more successful films of its genre.

Plot: A boy (Jake T. Austin) begins a grand journey to return Babe Ruth's baseball bat before the deciding game of the 1932 World Series comes to a close.
Title: Everyone's Hero
Writer: Robert Kurtz (screenplay), Jeff Hand (screenplay), Howard Jonas (story)
Director: Colin Brady, Christopher Reeve, Dan St. Pierre
Actors: Ritchie Allen, Jake T. Austin, Cherise Boothe, Jesse Bronstein
tomatoConsensus: Everyone's Hero is such a predictable and bland tale that it'll appeal mostly to little kids; others seeking something in Pixar's league are looking in the wrong ballpark.

Plot: Teenagers at a juvenile detention center, under the leadership of their counselor, gain self-esteem by playing football together.
Title: Gridiron Gang
Actors: Dwayne Johnson, Xzibit, L. Scott Caldwell, Leon Rippy
tomatoConsensus: The role of probation officer Sean Porter fits Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson like a glove; however, the execution is so cliched, the youths' stories (based on real events), fail to inspire.

Plot: People suffer largely unnoticed while the rest of the world goes about its business. This is a documentary exploration of the mythic beauty of the Golden Gate Bridge, the most popular ...
Title: The Bridge
Actors: Eric Geleynse, Chris Brown, Susan Ginwalla, Caroline Pressley
tomatoConsensus: Tactlessly morbid or remarkably sensitive? Deeply disturbing or viscerally fascinating? Critics are divided on Eric Steele's unique documentary on the Golden Gate Bridge, wonder of the modern world and notorious suicide destination.

Plot: The adventures of the Lafayette Escadrille, young Americans who volunteered for the French military before the U.S. entered World War I, and became the country's first fighter pilots.
Title: Flyboys
Writer: Phil Sears (screenplay), Blake T. Evans (screenplay), David S. Ward (screenplay), Blake T. Evans (story)
Actors: James Franco, Scott Hazell, Mac McDonald, Philip Winchester
tomatoConsensus: A poorly scripted history-rewriting exercise with mediocre acting and unconvincing CGI battle scenes.

Plot: Chris Pontius, Johnny Knoxville, Steve-O, Bam Margera, and the whole crew return to the screen to raise the stakes higher than ever before.
Title: Jackass Number Two
Writer: Jeff Tremaine (television series "Jackass"), Spike Jonze (television series "Jackass"), Johnny Knoxville (television series "Jackass"), Preston Lacy (additional scenes)
Actors: Johnny Knoxville, Bam Margera, Steve-O, Chris Pontius
tomatoConsensus: Better than any sequel to a movie of a television show has a right to be, Jackass: Number Two dares you not to laugh.

Plot: Kazakh TV talking head Borat is dispatched to the United States to report on the greatest country in the world. With a documentary crew in tow, Borat becomes more interested in locating and marrying Pamela Anderson.
Title: Borat: Cultural Learnings of America for Make Benefit Glorious Nation of Kazakhstan
Writer: Sacha Baron Cohen (screenplay), Anthony Hines (screenplay), Peter Baynham (screenplay), Dan Mazer (screenplay), Sacha Baron Cohen (story), Peter Baynham (story), Anthony Hines (story), Todd Phillips (story), Sacha Baron Cohen (based on a character created by)
Actors: Sacha Baron Cohen, Ken Davitian, Luenell, Chester
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 20 wins & 29 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Part satire, part shockumentary,Borat gets high-fives almost all-around for being offensive in the funniest possible way. Jagshemash!

Plot: A high school swim champion with a troubled past enrolls in the U.S. Coast Guard's "A" School, where legendary rescue swimmer Ben Randall teaches him some hard lessons about loss, love, and self-sacrifice.
Title: The Guardian
Actors: Kevin Costner, Ashton Kutcher, Sela Ward, Melissa Sagemiller
tomatoConsensus: The Coast Guard gets its chance for a heroic movie tribute, but The Guardian does it no justice, borrowing cliche after cliche from other (and better) military branch movies.

Plot: Boog, a domesticated 900lb. Grizzly bear, finds himself stranded in the woods 3 days before Open Season. Forced to rely on Elliot, a fast-talking mule deer, the two form an unlikely friendship and must quickly rally other forest animals if they are to form a rag-tag army against the hunters.
Title: Open Season
Writer: Steve Bencich (screenplay), Ron J. Friedman (screenplay), Nat Mauldin (screenplay), Jill Culton (screen story by), Anthony Stacchi (screen story by), Steve Moore (from an original story by), John B. Carls (from an original story by), Sam Harper (additional story material), Dan Wilson (additional story material), David Gilbreth (additional story material)
Director: Roger Allers, Jill Culton, Anthony Stacchi
Actors: Martin Lawrence, Ashton Kutcher, Gary Sinise, Debra Messing
tomatoConsensus: Open Season is a cliched palette of tired jokes and CG animal shenanigans that have been seen multiple times this cinematic year.

Plot: A young guy short on luck, enrolls in a class to build confidence to help win over the girl of his dreams, which becomes complicated when his teacher has the same agenda.
Title: School for Scoundrels
Actors: Billy Bob Thornton, Jon Heder, Jacinda Barrett, Michael Clarke Duncan
tomatoConsensus: School for Scoundrels squanders its talented cast with a formulaic, unfocused attempt at a romantic comedy that's neither romantic nor funny.

Plot: An undercover cop and a mole in the police attempt to identify each other while infiltrating an Irish gang in South Boston.
Title: The Departed
Writer: William Monahan (screenplay), Alan Mak, Felix Chong
Actors: Leonardo DiCaprio, Matt Damon, Jack Nicholson, Mark Wahlberg
tomatoConsensus: Featuring outstanding work from an excellent cast, The Departed is a thoroughly engrossing gangster drama with the gritty authenticity and soupy morality we come to expect from Martin Scorsese.

Plot: On one last road trip before they're sent to serve in Vietnam, two brothers and their girlfriends get into an accident that calls their local sheriff to the scene. Thus begins a terrifying experience where the teens are taken to a secluded house of horrors, where a young, would-be killer is being nurtured.
Title: The Texas Chainsaw Massacre: The Beginning
Writer: Sheldon Turner (screenplay), Sheldon Turner (story), David J. Schow (story)
Actors: Jordana Brewster, Taylor Handley, Diora Baird, Matt Bomer
tomatoConsensus: The Texas Chainsaw Massacre: The Beginning is full of blood and gore, but not enough scares or a coherent story to make for a successful horror film.

Plot: A slacker competes with a repeat winner for the "Employee of the Month" title at work, in order to gain the affections of a new female employee.
Title: Employee of the Month
Writer: Don Calame (screenplay), Chris Conroy (screenplay), Greg Coolidge (screenplay), Don Calame (story), Chris Conroy (story)
Actors: Dane Cook, Jessica Simpson, Dax Shepard, Andy Dick
tomatoConsensus: Employee of the Month features mediocre performances, few laughs, and a lack of satiric bite.

Plot: After the death of his uncle, the 14-year-old schoolboy Alex Rider is forced by the Special OperationsDivision of Britain's secret intelligence service, MI6, for a mission which will save millions of lives.
Title: Alex Rider: Operation Stormbreaker
Actors: Sarah Bolger, Robbie Coltrane, Stephen Fry, Damian Lewis
tomatoConsensus: Alex Rider: Operation Stormbreaker is strictly children's fare, as it lacks originality, excitement, and believabiltity.

Plot: Young Augusten Burroughs absorbs experiences that could make for a shocking memoir: the son of an alcoholic father and an unstable mother, he's handed off to his mother's therapist, Dr. Finch, and spends his adolescent years as a member of Finch's bizarre extended family.
Title: Running with Scissors
Actors: Annette Bening, Brian Cox, Joseph Fiennes, Evan Rachel Wood
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 6 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despite a few great performances, the film lacks the sincerity and emotional edge of Burroughs' well-loved memoir.

Plot: Three interwoven stories about a terrible curse. A young woman encounters a malevolent supernatural force while searching for her missing sister in Tokyo; a mean high school prank goes horribly wrong; a woman with a deadly secret moves into a Chicago apartment building.
Title: The Grudge 2
Writer: Stephen Susco, Takashi Shimizu (film "Ju-On: The Grudge")
Actors: Sarah Michelle Gellar, Amber Tamblyn, Arielle Kebbel, Takako Fuji
tomatoConsensus: A diminished sequel that makes even less sense than The Grudge 1.

Plot: A comedian who hosts a news satire program decides to run for president, and a computerized voting machine malfunction gets him elected.
Title: Man of the Year
Actors: Robin Williams, Christopher Walken, Laura Linney, Lewis Black
tomatoConsensus: Weakened by second-half attempts at thriller and romance, this presidential comedy also fails to hit any sharp political notes, resulting in a confused and unsatisfying mess.

Plot: A group of diamond thieves on the run kidnap the wife of a recently discharged marine who goes on a chase through the South Carolinian wilderness to retrieve her.
Title: The Marine
Writer: Michelle Gallagher (story), Michelle Gallagher (screenplay), Alan B. McElroy (screenplay)
Actors: John Cena, Robert Patrick, Kelly Carlson, Anthony Ray Parker
tomatoConsensus: Overblown in every possible way, The Marine is either so bad it's good or just really, really bad.

Title: Infamous
Actors: Sigourney Weaver, Toby Jones, Gwyneth Paltrow, Sandra Bullock
tomatoConsensus: Though comparisons with last year's Capote may be inevitable, Infamous takes a different angle in its depiction of the author, and stands up well enough on its own.

Plot: The young Jewish girl, Hadassah, goes on to become the Biblical Esther, the Queen of Persia, who saves the Jewish nation from annihilation at the hands of its arch enemy.
Title: One Night with the King
Writer: Stephan Blinn (screenplay), Mark Andrew Olsen (novel), Tommy Tenney (novel)
Actors: Tiffany Dupont, Luke Goss, John Noble, Omar Sharif
tomatoConsensus: Despite its epic source matierial, One Night With the King is held back by dull storytelling and a clumsy script.

Plot: The lives of two lovelorn spouses from separate marriages, a registered sex offender, and a disgraced ex-police officer intersect as they struggle to resist their vulnerabilities and temptations in suburban Massachusetts.
Title: Little Children
Writer: Todd Field (screenplay), Tom Perrotta (screenplay), Tom Perrotta (based on the novel by)
Actors: Kate Winslet, Jennifer Connelly, Patrick Wilson, Jackie Earle Haley
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 18 wins & 54 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Little Children takes a penetrating look at suburbia and its flawed individuals with an unflinching yet humane eye.

Plot: A losing coach with an underdog football team faces their giants of fear and failure on and off the field to surprising results.
Title: Facing the Giants
Actors: Erin Bethea, James Blackwell, Bailey Cave, Shannen Fields
tomatoConsensus: The tropes of both football and evangelical movies are gracelessly on parade in this banal, insipid drama.

Plot: Based on the events of the brutal Ugandan dictator Idi Amin's regime as seen by his personal physician during the 1970's.
Title: The Last King of Scotland
Writer: Peter Morgan (screenplay), Jeremy Brock (screenplay), Giles Foden (novel)
Actors: Forest Whitaker, James McAvoy, Kerry Washington, Gillian Anderson
tomatoConsensus: Forest Whitaker's performance as real-life megalomaniac dictator Idi Amin powers this fictionalized political thriller, a blunt and brutal tale about power and corruption.

Plot: A documentary on the life of John Lennon, with a focus on the time in his life when he transformed from a musician into an antiwar activist.
Title: The U.S. vs. John Lennon
Actors: John Lennon, Stew Albert, Tariq Ali, Carl Bernstein
tomatoConsensus: Though it glosses over anything negative about Lennon, this documentary offers a lot of fascinating archival footage, plus its political issues still have relevance for today.

Plot: A group of New Yorkers caught up in their romantic-sexual milieu converge at an underground salon infamous for its blend of art, music, politics, and carnality.
Title: Shortbus
Actors: Sook-Yin Lee, Paul Dawson, Lindsay Beamish, PJ DeBoy
tomatoConsensus: The sex may be explicit, but Mitchell integrates it into the characters' lives and serves the whole story up with a generous dose of sweetness and wit.

Plot: In 2027, in a chaotic world in which women have become somehow infertile, a former activist agrees to help transport a miraculously pregnant woman to a sanctuary at sea.
Language: English, German, Italian, Romanian, Spanish, Arabic, Georgian, Russian, Serbian
Title: Children of Men
Writer: Alfonso Cuarón (screenplay), Timothy J. Sexton (screenplay), David Arata (screenplay), Mark Fergus (screenplay), Hawk Ostby (screenplay), P.D. James (novel)
Actors: Clive Owen, Juan Gabriel Yacuzzi, Michael Caine, Mishal Husain
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 41 wins & 71 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Children of Men works on every level: as a violent chase thriller, a fantastical cautionary tale, and a sophisticated human drama about societies struggling to live.

Plot: Two stage magicians engage in competitive one-upmanship in an attempt to create the ultimate stage illusion.
Title: The Prestige
Writer: Jonathan Nolan (screenplay), Christopher Nolan (screenplay), Christopher Priest (novel)
Actors: Hugh Jackman, Christian Bale, Michael Caine, Piper Perabo
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 32 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Full of twists and turns, The Prestige is a dazzling period piece that never stops challenging the audience.

Plot: The life stories of the six men who raised the flag at The Battle of Iwo Jima, a turning point in WWII.
Title: Flags of Our Fathers
Writer: William Broyles Jr. (screenplay), Paul Haggis (screenplay), James Bradley (book), Ron Powers (book)
Actors: Ryan Phillippe, Jesse Bradford, Adam Beach, John Benjamin Hickey
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 15 wins & 24 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Flags of Our Fathers is both a fascinating look at heroism, both earned and manufactured, and a well-filmed salute to the men who fought at the battle of Iwo Jima.

Plot: Young Katy claims a wild horse as her own -- an effort to prove to her father that she is capable of one day taking over the family ranch.
Title: Flicka
Writer: Mark Rosenthal (screenplay), Lawrence Konner (screenplay), Mary O'Hara (novel)
Actors: Tim McGraw, Maria Bello, Alison Lohman, Ryan Kwanten
tomatoConsensus: The rebellious protagonist will rally girls and children, but adults may find Flicka saddled with thin characters, over-the-top dialogue, and a plot that wanders into the countryside and never comes back.

Plot: The movie is a coming-of-age drama about a boy growing up in Astoria, N.Y., during the 1980s. As his friends end up dead, on drugs or in prison, he comes to believe he has been saved from their fate by various so-called saints.
Title: A Guide to Recognizing Your Saints
Actors: Dianne Wiest, Robert Downey Jr., Shia LaBeouf, Melonie Diaz
tomatoConsensus: A Guide to Recognizing Your Saints is a lively, powerful coming-of-age tale with winning performances and sharp direction from first-timer Dito Montiel.

Plot: Jigsaw kidnaps a doctor to keep him alive while he watches his new apprentice put an unlucky citizen through a brutal test.
Title: Saw III
Writer: Leigh Whannell (story), James Wan (story), Leigh Whannell (screenplay)
Actors: Tobin Bell, Shawnee Smith, Angus Macfadyen, Bahar Soomekh
tomatoConsensus: Saw III does little beyond repeating its predecessor's tropes on a gorier level.

Plot: A drama about terrorism in Apartheid-era South Africa, revolving around a policeman and a young man who carries out solo attacks against the regime.
Title: Catch a Fire
Actors: Tim Robbins, Derek Luke, Bonnie Henna, Mncedisi Shabangu
tomatoConsensus: No stranger to the political thriller, director Phillip Noyce tackles apartheid and terrorism with experienced gusto, while Derek Luke and Tim Robbins hand in nuanced performances.

Plot: Years after the assassination of President George W. Bush in Chicago, an investigative documentary examines that as-yet-unsolved crime.
Title: Death of a President
Actors: Hend Ayoub, Becky Ann Baker, Brian Boland, Michael Reilly Burke
tomatoConsensus: In this unconvincing fictional documentary, the tense 30 minutes that lead into the title event is outweighed by the boring, melodramatic hour preceding it.

Plot: The story of an uptown rat that gets flushed down the toilet from his penthouse apartment, ending in the sewers of London, where he has to learn a whole new and different way of life.
Title: Flushed Away
Writer: Dick Clement (screenplay), Ian La Frenais (screenplay), Christopher Lloyd (screenplay), Joe Keenan (screenplay), William Davies (screenplay), Sam Fell (story by), Peter Lord (story by), Dick Clement (story by), Ian La Frenais (story by)
Actors: Hugh Jackman, Kate Winslet, Ian McKellen, Jean Reno
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 6 wins & 13 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Clever and appealing for both children and adults, Flushed Away marks a successful entry into digital animated features for Aardman Animations.

Plot: Jean-Baptiste Grenouille, born with a superior olfactory sense, creates the world's finest perfume. His work, however, takes a dark turn as he searches for the ultimate scent.
Title: Perfume: The Story of a Murderer
Writer: Andrew Birkin (screenplay), Bernd Eichinger (screenplay), Tom Tykwer (screenplay), Patrick Süskind (novel)
Actors: Ben Whishaw, Francesc Albiol, Gonzalo Cunill, Roger Salvany
tomatoConsensus: Perfume is what you'd expect from a Tom Twyker-directed movie glamorizing a serial killer: a kinetic visual feast, with a dark antihero that's impossible to feel sympathy for.

Plot: Santa, aka Scott Calvin, is faced with double-duty: how to keep his new family happy, and how to stop Jack Frost from taking over Christmas.
Title: The Santa Clause 3: The Escape Clause
Writer: Ed Decter, John J. Strauss, Leo Benvenuti (characters), Steve Rudnick (characters)
Actors: Tim Allen, Elizabeth Mitchell, Eric Lloyd, Judge Reinhold
tomatoConsensus: Playing Jack Frost as an evil cross between Liza Minnelli and Liberace, Martin Short is a welcome presence, but this tired series continues drawing from its bag of bland gags and dumb slapstick.

Plot: A British investment broker inherits his uncle's chateau and vineyard in Provence, where he spent much of his childhood. He discovers a new laid-back lifestyle as he tries to renovate the estate to be sold.
Title: A Good Year
Actors: Freddie Highmore, Albert Finney, Russell Crowe, Rafe Spall
tomatoConsensus: A Good Year is a fine example of a top-notch director and actor out of their elements, in a sappy romantic comedy lacking in charm and humor.

Plot: Joanna Mills, a traveling business woman, begins having nightmares of a murder that occurred 15 years ago. Soon she is drawn to an old farmhouse, where the murder took place.
Title: The Return
Actors: Sarah Michelle Gellar, Peter O'Brien, Adam Scott, Kate Beahan
tomatoConsensus: Unoriginality may be an acceptable risk in the Horror genre, but boredom is never okay.

Plot: Three actors learn that their respective performances in the film "Home for Purim," a drama set in the mid-1940s American South, are generating award-season buzz.
Title: For Your Consideration
Actors: Catherine O'Hara, Stephen Rannazzisi, Ed Begley Jr., Eugene Levy
tomatoConsensus: As the object of satire gets bigger the jokes become thinner, and Christopher Guest isn't as droll or insightful here than when he was lampooning smaller subjects.

Plot: Armed with a licence to kill, Secret Agent James Bond sets out on his first mission as 007 and must defeat a weapons dealer in a high stakes game of poker at Casino Royale, but things are not what they seem.
Title: Casino Royale
Country: UK, Czech Republic, USA, Germany, Bahamas
Writer: Neal Purvis (screenplay), Robert Wade (screenplay), Paul Haggis (screenplay), Ian Fleming (novel)
Actors: Daniel Craig, Eva Green, Mads Mikkelsen, Judi Dench
Awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 25 wins & 39 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Casino Royale disposes of the silliness and gadgetry that plagued recent James Bond outings, and Daniel Craig delivers what fans and critics have been waiting for: a caustic, haunted, intense reinvention of 007.

Plot: Into the world of the Emperor Penguins, who find their soul mates through song, a penguin is born who cannot sing. But he can tap dance something fierce!
Title: Happy Feet
Writer: George Miller, John Collee, Judy Morris, Warren Coleman
Director: George Miller, Warren Coleman, Judy Morris
Actors: Carlos Alazraqui, Lombardo Boyar, Jeffrey Garcia, Johnny A. Sanchez
tomatoConsensus: Visually dazzling, with a thoughtful storyline and catchy musical numbers, Happy Feet marks a successful animated debut from the makers of Babe.

Plot: When a career criminal's plan for revenge is thwarted by unlikely circumstances, he puts his intended victim's son in his place by putting him in prison...and then joining him.
Title: Let's Go to Prison
Writer: Robert Ben Garant, Thomas Lennon, Michael Patrick Jann, Jim Hogshire (book)
Actors: Dax Shepard, Will Arnett, Chi McBride, David Koechner
tomatoConsensus: Let's Go to Prison is guilty on all counts of cliched setups, base humor, and failure to ellicit laughs.

Plot: After a ferry is bombed in New Orleans, an A.T.F. agent joins a unique investigation using experimental surveillance technology to find the bomber, but soon finds himself becoming obsessed with one of the victims.
Title: Deja Vu
Actors: Denzel Washington, Paula Patton, Val Kilmer, Jim Caviezel
tomatoConsensus: Tony Scott tries to combine action, science fiction, romance, and explosions into one movie, but the time travel conceit might be too preposterous and the action falls apart under scrutiny.

Plot: The story of the assassination of U.S. Senator Robert F. Kennedy who was shot in the early morning hours of June 5, 1968 in the Ambassador Hotel in Los Angeles, and 22 people in the hotel whose lives were never the same.
Title: Bobby
Actors: Harry Belafonte, Joy Bryant, Nick Cannon, Emilio Estevez
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 7 wins & 15 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despite best intentions from director Emilio Estevez and his ensemble cast, they succumb to a script filled with pointless subplots and awkward moments working too hard to parallel contemporary times.

Plot: Two neighbors have it out after one of them decorates his house for the holidays so brightly that it can be seen from space.
Title: Deck the Halls
Writer: Matt Corman, Chris Ord, Don Rhymer
Actors: Danny DeVito, Matthew Broderick, Kristin Davis, Kristin Chenoweth
tomatoConsensus: Relying on flat humor and a preposterous plot, Deck the Halls is an unnecessarily mean-spirited holiday movie that does little to put viewers in a holiday mood.

Plot: An actor (Freeman) prepping for an upcoming role meets a quirky grocery clerk (Vega), and the pair hit the road to show one another their respective worlds.
Title: 10 Items or Less
Actors: Morgan Freeman, Paz Vega, Jonah Hill, Anne Dudek
tomatoConsensus: A small film that relies too heavily on the charm of its big actors.

Plot: Two women troubled with guy-problems swap homes in each other's countries, where they each meet a local guy and fall in love.
Title: The Holiday
Actors: Cameron Diaz, Kate Winslet, Jude Law, Jack Black
tomatoConsensus: The Holiday, while sweet and somewhat touching, lacks any surprises and eventually overstays its welcome.

Plot: An ensemble piece examining the health risks involved in the fast food industry and its environmental and social consequences as well.
Title: Fast Food Nation
Writer: Eric Schlosser, Richard Linklater, Eric Schlosser (book)
Actors: Wilmer Valderrama, Catalina Sandino Moreno, Ana Claudia Talancón, Juan Carlos Serrán
tomatoConsensus: Despite some fine performances and memorable scenes, Fast Food Nation is more effective as Eric Schlosser's eye-opening non-fiction book than as Richard Linklater's fictionalized, mostly punchless movie.

Plot: In Venice Beach, naive Midwesterner JB bonds with local slacker KG and they form the rock band Tenacious D. Setting out to become the world's greatest band is no easy feat, so they set out to steal what could be the answer to their prayers -- a magical guitar pick housed in a rock-and-roll museum some 300 miles away.
Title: Tenacious D in The Pick of Destiny
Writer: Jack Black, Kyle Gass, Liam Lynch
Actors: Jack Black, Kyle Gass, JR Reed, Ronnie James Dio
tomatoConsensus: Tenacious D fan will find this movie hilarious; everybody else will see only a low-brow concept movie and a small assembly of jokes stretched past the 100 minute mark.

Plot: A drama that focuses on the period in Mary and Joseph's life where they journeyed to Bethlehem for the birth of Jesus.
Title: The Nativity Story
Actors: Keisha Castle-Hughes, Oscar Isaac, Hiam Abbass, Shaun Toub
tomatoConsensus: The Nativity Story is a dull retelling of a well-worn tale with the look and feel of a high-school production.

Plot: Taj Mahal Badalandabad leaves Coolidge College behind for the halls of Camford University in England, where he looks to continue his education, and teach an uptight student how to make the most out of her academic career.
Title: Van Wilder 2: The Rise of Taj
Writer: David Drew Gallagher, Brent Goldberg (characters), David Wagner (characters)
Actors: Kal Penn, Lauren Cohan, Daniel Percival, Glen Barry
tomatoConsensus: A low-brow comedy, minus the comedy.

Plot: A group of young backpackers' vacation turns sour when a bus accident leaves them marooned in a remote Brazilian rural area that holds an ominous secret.
Title: Turistas
Actors: Josh Duhamel, Melissa George, Olivia Wilde, Desmond Askew
tomatoConsensus: Beautiful scenery and cinematography can't save Turistas from its wooden acting and stale and predictable plot.

Plot: A fisherman, a smuggler, and a syndicate of businessmen match wits over the possession of a priceless diamond.
Title: Blood Diamond
Writer: Charles Leavitt (screenplay), Charles Leavitt (story), C. Gaby Mitchell (story)
Actors: Leonardo DiCaprio, Djimon Hounsou, Jennifer Connelly, Kagiso Kuypers
Awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 8 wins & 26 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Blood Diamond overcomes poor storytelling with its biting commentary and fine performances.

Plot: A group of unaccompanied minors bond while snowed in at the midwestern Hoover International Airport during the holiday season and ultimately create a makeshift holiday themselves.
Title: Unaccompanied Minors
Actors: Lewis Black, Wilmer Valderrama, Tyler James Williams, Dyllan Christopher
tomatoConsensus: Unaccompanied Minors, while featuring credible performances by its mostly young cast, is simply a rehash of other, funnier movies.

Plot: Wilbur the pig is scared of the end of the season, because he knows that come that time, he will end up on the dinner table. He hatches a plan with Charlotte, a spider that lives in his pen, to ensure that this will never happen.
Title: Charlotte's Web
Writer: Susannah Grant (screenplay), Karey Kirkpatrick (screenplay), Earl Hamner Jr. (film story), E.B. White (book)
Actors: Julia Roberts, Steve Buscemi, John Cleese, Oprah Winfrey
tomatoConsensus: Kids will be entertained by the straightforward plot and cute animals, and adults will be charmed by how quiet and humble the production is, a fine translation of E.B. White's genteel prose.

Plot: Thirty years after the ring of the first bell, Rocky Balboa comes out of retirement and dons his gloves for his final fight; against the reigning heavyweight champ Mason 'The Line' Dixon.
Title: Rocky Balboa
Actors: Sylvester Stallone, Burt Young, Antonio Tarver, Geraldine Hughes
tomatoConsensus: Implausible but entertaining and poignant, Rocky Balboa finds the champ in fighting form for the first time in years.

Plot: Turning her back on her wealthy, established family, Diane Arbus falls in love with Lionel Sweeney, an enigmatic mentor who introduces Arbus to the marginalized people who help her become one of the most revered photographers of the twentieth century.
Title: Fur: An Imaginary Portrait of Diane Arbus
Actors: Nicole Kidman, Robert Downey Jr., Ty Burrell, Harris Yulin
tomatoConsensus: This portrait of a groundbreaking photographer lacks the daring of its subject.

Plot: A British medical doctor fights a cholera epidemic in a small Chinese village, while being trapped at home in a loveless marriage to an unfaithful wife.
Title: The Painted Veil
Actors: Catherine An, Bin Li, Bin Wu, Alan David
Awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 8 wins & 11 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Visually, The Painted Veil has all the trappings of a stuffy period drama, but Norton's and Watts's deft portrayals of imperfect, complicated characters give the film a modern-day spark.

Plot: When a plane crash claims the lives of members of the Marshall University football team and some of its fans, the team's new coach and his surviving players try to keep the football program alive.
Title: We Are Marshall
Writer: Jamie Linden (screenplay), Cory Helms (story), Jamie Linden (story)
Actors: Matthew McConaughey, Matthew Fox, Anthony Mackie, David Strathairn
tomatoConsensus: Matthew McConaughey almost runs We Are Marshall to the end zone, but can't stop it from taking the easy, feel-good route in memorializing this historic event in American sports.

Plot: The tumultuous early history of the Central Intelligence Agency is viewed through the prism of one man's life.
Title: The Good Shepherd
Actors: Matt Damon, Angelina Jolie, Alec Baldwin, Tammy Blanchard
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 11 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though ambitious and confidently directed by Robert De Niro, The Good Shepherd is ultimately a tedious drama that holds few surprises and succumbs to self-seriousness.

Plot: A trio of black female soul singers cross over to the pop charts in the early 1960s, facing their own personal struggles along the way.
Title: Dreamgirls
Actors: Jamie Foxx, Beyoncé Knowles, Eddie Murphy, Danny Glover
tomatoConsensus: Dreamgirls' simple characters and plot hardly detract from the movie's real feats: the electrifying performances and the dazzling musical numbers.

Plot: An unruly class of gifted and charming teenage boys are taught by two eccentric and innovative teachers, as their headmaster pushes for them all to get accepted into Oxford or Cambridge.
Title: The History Boys
Writer: Alan Bennett (screenplay), Alan Bennett (play), Gilles Coiffard (french dialogue writer)
Actors: Samuel Anderson, James Corden, Stephen Campbell Moore, Richard Griffiths
Awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 2 wins & 12 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: While not quite having the impact of its original stage version, The History Boys nevertheless is a witty and involving school drama.

Plot: A veteran high school teacher befriends a younger art teacher, who is having an affair with one of her 15-year-old students. However, her intentions with this new "friend" also go well beyond platonic friendship.
Title: Notes on a Scandal
Actors: Judi Dench, Cate Blanchett, Tom Georgeson, Michael Maloney
Awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 65 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: In this sharp psychological thriller, Judi Dench and Cate Blanchett give fierce, memorable performances as two schoolteachers locked in a battle of wits.

Plot: The movie adaptation of the best selling video game series Dead or Alive.
Title: DOA: Dead or Alive
Writer: J.F. Lawton (screenplay), Adam Gross (screenplay), Seth Gross (screenplay), J.F. Lawton (story)
Actors: Jaime Pressly, Devon Aoki, Holly Valance, Sarah Carter
tomatoConsensus: With a ridiculous plot and comical acting, checking one's brain at the door is required before watching DOA: Dead or Alive.

Plot: While in post-war Berlin to cover the Potsdam Conference, an American military journalist is drawn into a murder investigation which involves his former mistress and his driver.
Title: The Good German
Actors: George Clooney, Cate Blanchett, Tobey Maguire, Beau Bridges
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though Steven Soderbergh succeeds in emulating the glossy look of 1940s noirs, The Good German ultimately ends up as a self-conscious exercise in style that forgets to develop compelling characters.

Plot: The story of the battle of Iwo Jima between the United States and Imperial Japan during World War II, as told from the perspective of the Japanese who fought it.
Title: Letters from Iwo Jima
Writer: Iris Yamashita (screenplay), Iris Yamashita (story), Paul Haggis (story), Tadamichi Kuribayashi (book), Tsuyoko Yoshido (book)
Actors: Ken Watanabe, Kazunari Ninomiya, Tsuyoshi Ihara, Ryô Kase
tomatoConsensus: A powerfully humanistic portrayal of the perils of war, this companion piece to Flags of our Fathers is potent and thought-provoking, and it demonstrates Clint Eastwood's maturity as a director.

Plot: An alliance of evil-doers, led by Frieda, looks to take over Fairy Tale Land. But when Ella realizes her stepmother is out to ruin her storybook existence, she takes a dramatic turn and blossoms into the leader of the resistance effort.
Title: Happily N'Ever After
Actors: George Carlin, John DiMaggio, Andy Dick, Sarah Michelle Gellar
tomatoConsensus: Happily N'Ever After has none of the moxy, edge, or postmodern wit of the other fairy-tales-gone-haywire CG movie it so blatantly rips off.

Plot: The story of Beatrix Potter, the author of the beloved and best-selling children's book, "The Tale of Peter Rabbit", and her struggle for love, happiness and success.
Title: Miss Potter
Actors: Renée Zellweger, Ewan McGregor, Emily Watson, Barbara Flynn
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A charming biopic that maintains its sweetness even in sadder moments.

Plot: Ten-year-old Arthur, in a bid to save his grandfather's house from being demolished, goes looking for some much-fabled hidden treasure in the land of the Minimoys, a tiny people living in harmony with nature.
Title: Arthur and the Invisibles
Writer: Céline Garcia, Luc Besson, Luc Besson (book), Patrice Garcia (creator: characters and settings), Georges Bouchelagem (creator: characters and settings), Philippe Rouchier (creator: characters and settings), Nicolas Fructus (creator: characters and settings)
Actors: Freddie Highmore, Mia Farrow, Ron Crawford, Penny Balfour
tomatoConsensus: Arthur wastes its big-name voice talent on a predictable script and substandard CG animation.

Plot: Life for a pair of veteran actors gets turned upside down after they meet a brash teenager.
Title: Venus
Actors: Peter O'Toole, Leslie Phillips, Beatrice Savoretti, Philip Fox
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 20 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Audiences may attend to witness Peter O'Toole's Oscar-worthy performance, but they'll also be treated to a humane, tender exploration of maturing with both dignity and irreverence.

Plot: A drama based on the life of Jesse James Hollywood, a drug dealer who became one of the youngest men ever to be on the FBI's most wanted list.
Title: Alpha Dog
Actors: Bruce Willis, Matthew Barry, Emile Hirsch, Fernando Vargas
tomatoConsensus: A glossy yet unflinching portrait of violent, hedonistic teenagers. Bruce Willis and Sharon Stone chew the scenery, while Justin Timberlake gives a noteworthy performance.

Plot: A manager of an orphanage in India is sent to Copenhagen, Denmark, where he discovers a life-altering family secret.
Title: After the Wedding
Writer: Susanne Bier (story), Anders Thomas Jensen (story), Anders Thomas Jensen (screenplay)
Actors: Mads Mikkelsen, Neeral Mulchandani, Tanya Sharma, Swini Khara
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 16 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The cast brings After the Wedding's melodramatic script to life, creating a movie that is emotionally raw and satisfying.

Title: Catch and Release
Actors: Jennifer Garner, Timothy Olyphant, Sam Jaeger, Kevin Smith
tomatoConsensus: A romantic dramedy with boring, stock characters and contrived situations.

Plot: When a Las Vegas performer-turned-snitch named Buddy Israel decides to turn state's evidence and testify against the mob, it seems that a whole lot of people would like to make sure he's no longer breathing.
Title: Smokin' Aces
Actors: Ryan Reynolds, Ray Liotta, Joseph Ruskin, Alex Rocco
tomatoConsensus: A violent mess of a movie, Smokin' Aces has some Quentin Tarantino's style but not much of his wit or humor.

Plot: Based on the true story, two homicide detectives track Martha Beck and Raymond Martinez Fernandez, a murderous pair known as the "Lonely Hearts Killers" who lured their victims through the personals.
Title: Lonely Hearts
Actors: John Travolta, James Gandolfini, Jared Leto, Salma Hayek
tomatoConsensus: Several genres and plotlines intertwine in Lonely Hearts but don't connect, creating an uneven and unsatisfying film.

Plot: Through the neighborhoods of Paris, love is veiled, revealed, imitated, sucked dry, reinvented and awakened.
Title: Paris, je t'aime
Writer: Tristan Carné (original idea), Emmanuel Benbihy (concept), Emmanuel Benbihy (transitions), Bruno Podalydès (segment), Paul Mayeda Berges (segment), Gurinder Chadha (segment), Gus Van Sant (segment), Joel Coen (segment), Ethan Coen (segment), Walter Salles (segment), Daniela Thomas (segment), Christopher Doyle (segment), Rain Li (in collaboration with), Gabrielle Keng (in collaboration with), Isabel Coixet (segment), Nobuhiro Suwa (segment), Sylvain Chomet (segment), Alfonso Cuarón (segment), Olivier Assayas (segment), Oliver Schmitz (segment), Richard LaGravenese (segment), Vincenzo Natali (segment), Wes Craven (segment), Tom Tykwer (segment), Gena Rowlands (segment), Alexander Payne (segment), Nadine Eïd (segment), Frédéric Auburtin (transitions), Jean-Pierre Ronssin (transitions), Jane Hawksley (transitions), Vincent Poymiro (transitions), Paul Mayeda Berges (screenplay), Nadine Eïd (screenplay)
Director: Olivier Assayas, Frédéric Auburtin, Emmanuel Benbihy, Gurinder Chadha, Sylvain Chomet, Ethan Coen, Joel Coen, Isabel Coixet, Wes Craven, Alfonso Cuarón, Gérard Depardieu, Christopher Doyle, Richard LaGravenese, Vincenzo Natali, Alexander Payne, Bruno Podalydès, Walter Salles, Oliver Schmitz, Nobuhiro Suwa, Daniela Thomas, Tom Tykwer, Gus Van Sant
Actors: Fanny Ardant, Julie Bataille, Leïla Bekhti, Melchior Derouet
tomatoConsensus: Paris Je T'aime is uneven, but there are more than enough delightful moments in this omnibus tribute to the City of Lights to tip the scale in its favor.

Plot: A NASA astronaut (Thornton), forced to retire years earlier so he could save his family farm, has never given up his dream of space travel and looks to build his own rocket, despite the government's threats to stop him.
Title: The Astronaut Farmer
Actors: Billy Bob Thornton, Virginia Madsen, Max Thieriot, Jasper Polish
tomatoConsensus: The Astronaut Farmer is a charming, inspirational drama that successfully avoids modern cinematic cliches while appealing to the optimistic dreamer in all of us.

Plot: A God-fearing bluesman takes to a wild young woman who, as a victim of childhood sexual abuse, looks everywhere for love, never quite finding it.
Title: Black Snake Moan
Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Christina Ricci, Justin Timberlake, S. Epatha Merkerson
tomatoConsensus: Uninhibited performances, skillful direction, and a killer blues soundtrack elevate Black Snake Moan beyond its outlandish premise.

Plot: Based on the rise and fall of socialite Edie Sedgwick, concentrating on her relationships with Andy Warhol and a folk singer.
Title: Factory Girl
Writer: Captain Mauzner (screenplay), Simon Monjack (story), Aaron Richard Golub (story), Captain Mauzner (story)
Actors: Sienna Miller, Guy Pearce, Hayden Christensen, Jimmy Fallon
tomatoConsensus: Despite a dedicated performance by Sienna Miller, Factory Girl delves only superficially into her character, and ultimately fails to tell a coherent story.

Plot: The story is set at the beginning of the 20th century in Sicily. Salvatore, a very poor farmer, and a widower, decides to emigrate to the US with all his family, including his old mother. ...
Title: Golden Door
Actors: Charlotte Gainsbourg, Vincenzo Amato, Vincent Schiavelli, Aurora Quattrocchi
tomatoConsensus: Slow-moving but ultimately rewarding, Golden Door is a profound drama with scenes of fantastical magical realism, lively humor, and stunning images.

Plot: A landscape architect's dealings with a young thief cause him to re-evaluate his life.
Title: Breaking and Entering
Actors: Jude Law, Robin Wright, Martin Freeman, Juliette Binoche
tomatoConsensus: This class warfare drama feels contrived and superficial: characters don't act logically as the movie manipulates them towards deconstructing various social issues.

Plot: Four boys from Sudan embark on a journey to America after years of wandering Sub-Saharan Africa in search of safety.
Title: God Grew Tired of Us
Actors: Panther Bior, John Bul Dau, Nicole Kidman, Daniel Abol Pach
tomatoConsensus: Not just a powerful telling of the journey of exiled Sudanese boys, God Grew Tired of Us is also a poignant account of the determination of the human spirit.

Plot: The idealist William Wilberforce maneuvers his way through Parliament, endeavoring to end the British transatlantic slave trade.
Title: Amazing Grace
Actors: Ioan Gruffudd, Romola Garai, Benedict Cumberbatch, Albert Finney
tomatoConsensus: Amazing Grace is your quintessential historical biopic: stately, noble, and with plenty of electrifying performances.

Plot: A deceased billionaire leaves his spoiled adult grandson a series of odd tasks to perform in order to receive "the ultimate gift," with the resentful grandson having no idea what that might be.
Title: The Ultimate Gift
Actors: James Garner, Bill Cobbs, Lee Meriwether, George Lee
tomatoConsensus: Though The Ultimate Gift avoids religious speechifying like other Fox Faith films, it's dramatically inert with flat direction.

Plot: King Leonidas of Sparta and a force of 300 men fight the Persians at Thermopylae in 480 B.C.
Writer: Zack Snyder (screenplay), Kurt Johnstad (screenplay), Michael Gordon (screenplay), Frank Miller (graphic novel), Lynn Varley (graphic novel)
Actors: Gerard Butler, Lena Headey, Dominic West, David Wenham
tomatoConsensus: A simple-minded but visually exciting experience, full of blood, violence, and ready-made movie quotes.

Plot: An adopted woman returns to her home country and the family home that she never knew and must face the mystery that lies there.
Title: The Abandoned
Writer: Karim Hussain (screenplay), Nacho Cerdà (screenplay), Richard Stanley (screenplay)
Actors: Anastasia Hille, Karel Roden, Valentin Ganev, Paraskeva Djukelova
tomatoConsensus: The Abandoned spends so much time setting up the creepy atmosphere, that it forgets to inhabit it with genuine spooks or scares.

Plot: Set in 1985, working-class student Brian Jackson (McAvoy) navigates his first year at Bristol University.
Title: Starter for 10
Actors: Joseph Friend, James Gaddas, Catherine Tate, Mark Gatiss
tomatoConsensus: Starter For 10 is a spirited coming-of-age tale that remains charming and witty even as it veers into darker teritory. The unique setting of a quiz show makes the film wittier than your average romantic comedy.

Plot: Through a set of wacky circumstances, a young gold digger mistakenly woos a mild-mannered bartender thinking he's a wealthy suitor.
Title: Priceless
Writer: Pierre Salvadori (scenario), Benoît Graffin (scenario), Pierre Salvadori (dialogue)
Actors: Audrey Tautou, Gad Elmaleh, Marie-Christine Adam, Vernon Dobtcheff
tomatoConsensus: Priceless is a light, farcical rom-com that features sharp performances from Audrey Tautou and Gad Elmaleh.

Plot: A monster emerges from Seoul's Han River and focuses its attention on attacking people. One victim's loving family does what it can to rescue her from its clutches.
Title: The Host
Writer: Joon-ho Bong (screenplay), Won-jun Ha (screenplay), Chul-hyun Baek (screenplay)
Actors: Kang-ho Song, Hie-bong Byeon, Hae-il Park, Doona Bae
tomatoConsensus: As populace pleasing as it is intellectually satisfying, The Host combines scares, laughs, and satire into a riveting, monster movie.

Plot: American-born Gogol, the son of Indian immigrants, wants to fit in among his fellow New Yorkers, despite his family's unwillingness to let go of their traditional ways.
Title: The Namesake
Actors: Kal Penn, Tabu, Irrfan Khan, Jacinda Barrett
tomatoConsensus: An ambitious exploration of the immigrant experience with a talented cast that serves the material well.

Plot: Stewart Kane, an Irishman living in the Australian town of Jindabyne, is on a fishing trip in isolated hill country with three other men when they discover the body of a murdered girl in ...
Title: Jindabyne
Writer: Raymond Carver (short story "So Much Water So Close to Home"), Beatrix Christian
Actors: Chris Haywood, Tatea Reilly, Laura Linney, Sean Rees-Wemyss
tomatoConsensus: Jindabyne's disparate themes may not quite cohere, but the film features fine performances from Linney and Byrne.

Title: Avenue Montaigne
Writer: Danièle Thompson (screenplay), Christopher Thompson (screenplay), Danièle Thompson (dialogue)
Actors: Valérie Lemercier, Cécile De France, Albert Dupontel, Claude Brasseur
tomatoConsensus: A cute and bubbly French comedy that carries no deeper lessons or agendas than to have a little fun for 90 minutes.

Plot: In the Nazi-occupied Netherlands during World War II, a Jewish singer infiltrates the regional Gestapo headquarters for the Dutch resistance.
Title: Black Book
Actors: Carice van Houten, Sebastian Koch, Thom Hoffman, Halina Reijn
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 13 wins & 21 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A furious mix of sex, violence, and moral relativism, Black Book is shamelessly entertaining melodrama.

Plot: At the end of the Civil War, a colonel hunts down a man with whom he has a grudge.
Title: Seraphim Falls
Writer: David Von Ancken, Abby Everett Jaques
Actors: Liam Neeson, Pierce Brosnan, Michael Wincott, Xander Berkeley
tomatoConsensus: A brutal, slow-moving drama that unfolds among some great-looking scenery.

Plot: A fictionalized account of the last year of Beethoven's life.
Title: Copying Beethoven
Actors: Diane Kruger, Ralph Riach, Matyelok Gibbs, Ed Harris
tomatoConsensus: A pretentious historical drama that's ultimately a drag, despite Ed Harris' powerful performance.

Plot: Painter Francisco Goya faces a scandal involving his muse, who is labeled a heretic by a monk.
Title: Goya's Ghosts
Actors: Javier Bardem, Natalie Portman, Stellan Skarsgård, Randy Quaid
tomatoConsensus: Ornate costumes and a talented cast can't make up for Ghosts' glacial pace and confused plot.

Plot: A mockumentary that follows three couples as they battle it out to win the coveted title of 'Most Original Wedding of the Year'.
Title: Confetti
Actors: Martin Freeman, Jessica Hynes, Stephen Mangan, Meredith MacNeill
tomatoConsensus: This improvised mockumentary has its funny and even sweet moments, but it's not as witty or sharp as Christopher Guest's offerings.

Plot: Innocent lives hang on the whim of an elusive psychopathic murderer whose strange riddles and impossible timelines force three people into a mission to end the game before one or all of them die.
Title: Thr3e
Actors: Marc Blucas, Justine Waddell, Laura Jordan, Max Ryan
tomatoConsensus: Thr3e is a shoddily made, thrill-free thriller that isn't half as good as the several movies it borrows from (Adaptation, Saw, Se7en).

Plot: A slacker is forced to work for his father-in-law after his pregnant wife steps away from her high-paying job.
Title: The Ex
Actors: Zach Braff, Amanda Peet, Jason Bateman, Charles Grodin
tomatoConsensus: The Ex suffers from inept direction and characters that are either unsympathetic or plain unpleasant to watch.

Plot: When a machine that allows therapists to enter their patients' dreams is stolen, all Hell breaks loose. Only a young female therapist, Paprika, can stop it.
Title: Paprika
Writer: Yasutaka Tsutsui (novel), Seishi Minakami (screenplay), Satoshi Kon (screenplay)
Actors: Megumi Hayashibara, Tôru Furuya, Kôichi Yamadera, Katsunosuke Hori
tomatoConsensus: Following its own brand of logic, Paprika is an eye-opening mind trip that is difficult to follow but never fails to dazzle.

Plot: The true story of Graeme Obree, the Champion cyclist who built his bicycle from old bits of washing machines who won his championship only to have his title stripped from him and his mental health problems which he has suffered since.
Title: The Flying Scotsman
Writer: John Brown, Simon Rose, Declan Hughes
Actors: Jonny Lee Miller, Sean Brown, Joseph Carney, Crawford McInally-Kier
tomatoConsensus: The Flying Scotsman's too-brisk pacing reduces the scale of cyclist Graham Obree's accomplishments while not uncovering what makes him tick.

Plot: A young boy becomes friends with a gang of skinheads. Friends soon become like family, and relationships will be pushed to the very limit.
Title: This Is England
Actors: Thomas Turgoose, Stephen Graham, Jo Hartley, Andrew Shim
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 13 wins & 15 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A moving coming-of-age tale that captures the despair among England's working-class youth in the 1980s.

Plot: A man coping with the institutionalization of his wife because of Alzheimer's disease faces an epiphany when she transfers her affections to another man, Aubrey, a wheelchair-bound mute who also is a patient at the nursing home.
Title: Away from Her
Writer: Sarah Polley, Alice Munro (short story "The Bear Came Over the Mountain")
Actors: Gordon Pinsent, Stacey LaBerge, Julie Christie, Olympia Dukakis
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 62 wins & 37 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: An accomplished directorial debut by Sarah Polley, Away From Her is a touching exploration of the effects of Alzheimer's, in which the tender wisdom of Polley's script is beautifully complemented by a wonderful performance from Julie Christie.

Plot: An unhinged war veteran holes up with a lonely woman in a spooky Oklahoma motel room. The line between reality and delusion is blurred as they discover a bug infestation.
Title: Bug
Actors: Ashley Judd, Michael Shannon, Harry Connick Jr., Lynn Collins
tomatoConsensus: Disappointing resolution aside, Bug uses its claustrophobic setting and cinéma vérité camerawork to tense, impressive effect.

Plot: A ten-years-later continuation of Hal Hartley's "Henry Fool", where Fay Grim (Posey) is coerced by a CIA agent (Goldblum) to try and locate notebooks that belonged to her fugitive ex-husband (Ryan). Published in them is information that could compromises the security of the U.S., causing Fay to first head to Paris to fetch them ...
Title: Fay Grim
Actors: Parker Posey, D.J. Mendel, Liam Aiken, Megan Gay
tomatoConsensus: Fay Grim is too concerned with its own farcical premise to present a coherent, involving story.

Plot: A U.S. fighter pilot's epic struggle of survival after being shot down on a mission over Laos during the Vietnam War.
Title: Rescue Dawn
Actors: Zach Grenier, Marshall Bell, Christian Bale, Toby Huss
tomatoConsensus: Director Werner Herzog has once again made a compelling tale of man versus nature, and Christian Bale completely immerses himself in the role of fighter pilot (and prisoner of war) Dieter Dengler.

Plot: The story of a TV pilot as it goes through the Network TV process of casting, production and finally airing.
Title: The TV Set
Actors: David Duchovny, Sigourney Weaver, Ioan Gruffudd, Judy Greer
tomatoConsensus: Offering both broad and insider jokes, The TV Set is a sharp satire that will please both the average moviegoers and pop culture aficionados.

Plot: A psychic's ominous reading sends a man into a tailspin.
Title: First Snow
Actors: Guy Pearce, Steven Michael Quezada, J.K. Simmons, Nicholas Ballas
tomatoConsensus: In First Snow, an interesting premise gives way to a slow and tedious noir that adds little to the genre.

Plot: Guy Maddin reluctantly returns to his childhood home, an abandoned Canadian island, where his parents ran an orphanage. As Guy fulfills his dying mother's request to paint the lighthouse ...
Title: Brand Upon the Brain!
Writer: Guy Maddin, Louis Negin (narration), George Toles
Actors: Gretchen Krich, Sullivan Brown, Maya Lawson, Katherine E. Scharhon
tomatoConsensus: A bizarre, compelling spectacle that invests its absurd plot with heartfelt sincerety, Brand Upon the Brain! is a unique cinematic experience.

Plot: A 30-something southern woman searches for love, despite the burdens she carries with her.
Title: Come Early Morning
Actors: Ashley Judd, Jason T. Davis, Richard Lee Crow, Laura Prepon
tomatoConsensus: A quiet but moving film anchored by the unexpected depth of Ashley Judd's performance.

Plot: A 12 year old boy and his mother become the targets of two warring werewolf packs, each with different intentions and motives.
Title: Skinwalkers
Writer: James DeMonaco, Todd Harthan, James Roday
Actors: Jason Behr, Elias Koteas, Rhona Mitra, Natassia Malthe
tomatoConsensus: Skinwalkers is an atrociously-acted project whose unoriginal and ineptly-staged action sequences remind viewers of far better werewolf and action movies.

Title: El cantante
Writer: Leon Ichaso (screenplay), David Darmstaeder (screenplay), Todd Bello (screenplay), David Darmstaeder (story), Todd Bello (story)
Actors: Marc Anthony, Jennifer Lopez, John Ortiz, Manny Perez
tomatoConsensus: El Cantante adheres to the most basic conventions of the musical biopic, rendering it indistinguishable from others of its ilk.

Plot: An American accountant bombarded with cable news and the media's obsession with terrorist plots in the post 9-11 world, receives a jolt when an unattached Islamic graduate student moves in next door.
Title: Civic Duty
Actors: Peter Krause, Kari Matchett, Richard Schiff, Khaled Abol Naga
tomatoConsensus: At times a tense and provocative thriller, Civic Duty struggles to move beyond its one-note premise.

Plot: During a three day heat wave just before a huge 4th of July celebration, an action star stricken with amnesia meets up with a porn star who is developing her own reality TV project, and a policeman who holds the key to a vast conspiracy.
Title: Southland Tales
Actors: Carlos Amezcua, Curtis Armstrong, Robert Benz, Todd Berger
tomatoConsensus: Southland Tales, while offering an intriguing vision of the future, remains frustratingly incoherent and unpolished.

Plot: A look at the glamorous life at an old-world Prague hotel.
Language: Czech, German, French, English, Italian, Korean
Title: I Served the King of England
Actors: Ivan Barnev, Oldrich Kaiser, Julia Jentsch, Marián Labuda
tomatoConsensus: With charm and an eye for life's bittersweet moments, Czech New Wave master Jiri Menzel paints a picaresque story with whimsy and intellect.

Plot: Thirteen years after the end of the Vietnam War, a family who was tragically affected by the war are forced to emigrate to America.
Title: Journey from the Fall
Writer: Ham Tran (story), Lam Nguyen (story), Ham Tran
Actors: Kieu Chinh, Long Nguyen, Diem Lien, Jayvee Mai The Hiep
tomatoConsensus: Ham Tran's ambitious film proves to be extremely powerful due to stunning photography and passionate performances.

Plot: The film tells the story of a highly-gifted boy whose parents have demanding and ambitious plans for him - they want him to become a pianist. However, one day the boy, Vitus, is no longer ...
Title: Vitus
Writer: Peter Luisi, Fredi M. Murer, Lukas B. Suter
Actors: Fabrizio Borsani, Teo Gheorghiu, Julika Jenkins, Urs Jucker
tomatoConsensus: Though not highly original, Vitus is slightly redeemed by its charm and compelling performances.

Plot: A modern romantic tale about a young aristocratic heiress born under a curse that can only be broken when she finds true love with "one who will love her faithfully."
Title: Penelope
Actors: Richard E. Grant, Catherine O'Hara, Nick Prideaux, Michael Feast
tomatoConsensus: Though Penelope has a charming cast and an appealing message, it ultimately suffers from faulty narrative and sloppy direction.

Plot: In a hospital on the outskirts of 1920s Los Angeles, an injured stuntman begins to tell a fellow patient, a little girl with a broken arm, a fantastic story of five mythical heroes. Thanks to his fractured state of mind and her vivid imagination, the line between fiction and reality blurs as the tale advances.
Title: The Fall
Writer: Dan Gilroy (screenplay), Nico Soultanakis (screenplay), Tarsem Singh (screenplay), Valeri Petrov
Actors: Catinca Untaru, Justine Waddell, Lee Pace, Kim Uylenbroek
tomatoConsensus: More visually elaborate than the fragmented story can sometimes support, The Fall walks the line between labor of love and filmmaker self-indulgence.

Plot: One day in New York City changes three people forever.
Title: Bella
Writer: Alejandro Monteverde, Patrick Million, Leo Severino
Actors: Eduardo Verástegui, Tammy Blanchard, Manny Perez, Angélica Aragón
tomatoConsensus: Critics labeled Bella as a simplistic and mostly pedestrian, but positive word of mouth gave this tiny indie surprising theatrical legs.

Plot: In this documentary, the show's emcee, Vince Vaughn, and four stand-up comedians hand-picked by Vaughn, travel the country and perform in 30 cities. This film documents the interactions on and off stage along the way.
Title: Wild West Comedy Show: 30 Days & 30 Nights - Hollywood to the Heartland
Actors: Vince Vaughn, Ahmed Ahmed, John Caparulo, Bret Ernst
tomatoConsensus: Vince Vaughn's Wild West Comedy Show has some entertaining moments, but is a mostly hit-and-miss documentary.

Plot: Three women take a road trip to Santa Barbara in order to deliver the ashes of one of their dead husbands to his resentful daughter.
Title: Bonneville
Writer: Daniel D. Davis (screenplay), Daniel D. Davis (story), Christopher N. Rowley (story)
Actors: Jessica Lange, Robert Conder, Kathy Bates, Joan Allen
tomatoConsensus: The amazing cast of Bonneville is paired up with a basic, predictable script and lackluster direction.

Plot: An inept tae kwon do instructor struggles with marital troubles and an unhealthy obsession with fellow tae kwon do enthusiast Chuck "The Truck" Wallace.
Title: The Foot Fist Way
Writer: Ben Best, Jody Hill, Danny McBride
Actors: Danny McBride, Mary Jane Bostic, Ben Best, Spencer Moreno
tomatoConsensus: The rough edges and biting humor of this martial arts comedy will keep audiences laughing and cringing in turns.

Plot: A brief look into Romani culture and Rom (Gypsies) from around the globe as five famous Romani groups tour the USA. The film visits their families at home in Spain, India, Macedonia and Romania.
Language: Romany, Hindi, English, Romanian, Spanish, Macedonian
Title: When the Road Bends... Tales of a Gypsy Caravan
Actors: Maharaja, Esma Redzepova, Taraf de Haidouks, Antonio El Pipa
tomatoConsensus: A dynamic doc following five Romani bands is a pleasure for the senses thanks to vibrant colors and eclectic music.

Plot: A fading country music star (Keith) returns to his hometown, where he reunites with his childhood sweetheart and also meets his 16-year-old daughter for the first time.
Title: Broken Bridges
Actors: Brian F. Durkin, Jason Leith, Richard Tillman, Toby Keith
tomatoConsensus: A cliched attempt at a feel-good drama, Broken Bridges is schmaltzy, predictable, and stiffly acted.

Plot: A young teacher inspires her class of at-risk students to learn tolerance, apply themselves, and pursue education beyond high school.
Title: Freedom Writers
Writer: Richard LaGravenese (screenplay), Freedom Writers (book), Erin Gruwell (book)
Actors: Hilary Swank, Patrick Dempsey, Scott Glenn, Imelda Staunton
tomatoConsensus: Freedom Writers is a frank, formulaic entry in the inspirational inner-city teacher genre, with an energetic Hilary Swank leading the appealing cast of unknowns.

Plot: Cedric the Entertainer plays Jake, a seemingly regular guy who has no idea who he is after being hit over the head by mysterious assailants; when he finds himself entangled in a government ...
Title: Code Name: The Cleaner
Actors: Cedric the Entertainer, Lucy Liu, Nicollette Sheridan, Mark Dacascos
tomatoConsensus: Code Name: The Cleaner is a limp action/comedy flick that alternates between lame, worn-out jokes and cheesy martial arts.

Plot: After the death of his brother, An expert street dancer goes to Georgia to attend Truth University. But his efforts to get an education and woo the girl he likes are sidelined when he joins...
Title: Stomp the Yard
Writer: Robert Adetuyi (screenplay), Gregory Ramon Anderson (earlier screenplay)
Actors: Columbus Short, Meagan Good, Ne-Yo, Darrin Dewitt Henson
tomatoConsensus: While Stomp the Yard contains impressive musical and dance numbers, it loses its momentum during the intervening soap opera-style subplots.

Plot: A news team is sent to Burundi to capture and bring home a legendary 25-foot crocodile. Their difficult task turns potentially deadly when a warlord targets them for death.
Title: Primeval
Actors: Dominic Purcell, Brooke Langton, Orlando Jones, Jürgen Prochnow
tomatoConsensus: Primeval is a low-quality horror film, which due to the inane political messages does not even qualify as campy fun.

Plot: A serial killer pins his crimes on two college students who gave him a ride.
Title: The Hitcher
Writer: Eric Red (screenplay), Jake Wade Wall (screenplay), Eric Bernt (screenplay), Eric Red
Actors: Sean Bean, Sophia Bush, Zachary Knighton, Neal McDonough
tomatoConsensus: Sean Bean tries giving motive and emotion to the hitcher, but director Dave Meyers is more interested in cheap shocks, and gratuitious gore and torture.

Plot: A preteen's life turns upside down when he befriends the new girl in school and they imagine a whole new fantasy world to escape reality.
Title: Bridge to Terabithia
Writer: Jeff Stockwell (screenplay), David Paterson (screenplay), Katherine Paterson (book)
Actors: Josh Hutcherson, AnnaSophia Robb, Zooey Deschanel, Robert Patrick
tomatoConsensus: Bridge to Terabithia is a faithful adaptation of a beloved children's novel and a powerful portrayal of love, loss, and imagination through children's eyes.

Plot: Jenna is a pregnant, unhappily married waitress in the deep south. She meets a newcomer to her town and falls into an unlikely relationship as a last attempt at happiness.
Title: Waitress
Actors: Keri Russell, Nathan Fillion, Cheryl Hines, Jeremy Sisto
tomatoConsensus: Sweet, smart, and quirky, Waitress hits the right, bittersweet notes through this romantic comedy through its witty script and a superb performance by Keri Russell.

Plot: A young teenage werewolf (Bruckner) is torn between honoring her family's secret and her love for a man (Dancy).
Title: Blood and Chocolate
Writer: Ehren Kruger (screenplay), Christopher Landon (screenplay), Annette Curtis Klause (book)
Actors: Agnes Bruckner, Hugh Dancy, Olivier Martinez, Katja Riemann
tomatoConsensus: Cheap CG effects and laughable dialogue make Blood and Chocolate worse than the usual werewolf flick.

Plot: A comedic satire of films that are large in scope, reputation and popularity.
Title: Epic Movie
Actors: Kal Penn, Adam Campbell, Jennifer Coolidge, Jayma Mays
tomatoConsensus: A crude comedy with nothing new or insightful to say about the subjects it satirizes.

Plot: An ominous darkness invades a seemingly serene sunflower farm in North Dakota, and the Solomon family is torn apart by suspicion, mayhem and murder.
Title: The Messengers
Actors: Kristen Stewart, Dylan McDermott, Penelope Ann Miller, John Corbett
tomatoConsensus: The Messengers is an atmospheric but derivative rip-off of countless other horror movies.

Plot: A meddling mother tries to set her daughter up with the right man so her kid won't follow in her footsteps.
Title: Because I Said So
Actors: Diane Keaton, Mandy Moore, Gabriel Macht, Tom Everett Scott
tomatoConsensus: Overly reliant on caricatures and lacking any human insight, Because I Said So is an unfunny, cliche-ridden mess.

Plot: After the death of his parents during World War II, young Hannibal Lecter moves in with his beautiful aunt and begins plotting revenge on the barbarians responsible for his sister's death.
Title: Hannibal Rising
Actors: Aaran Thomas, Gaspard Ulliel, Li Gong, Helena-Lia Tachovská
tomatoConsensus: Hannibal Rising reduces the horror icon to a collection of dime-store psychological traits.

Plot: A mild-mannered guy, who is engaged to a monstrous woman, meets the woman of his dreams, and schemes to find a way to be with her.
Title: Norbit
Writer: Eddie Murphy (screenplay), Charlie Murphy (screenplay), Jay Scherick (screenplay), David Ronn (screenplay), Eddie Murphy (story), Charlie Murphy (story)
Actors: Eddie Murphy, Thandie Newton, Terry Crews, Clifton Powell
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 8 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Coming off his Oscar-nominated performance in Dreamgirls, the talented-but-inconsistent Eddie Murphy plays three roles in Norbit, a cruel, crass, stereotype-filled comedy that's more depressing than funny.

Plot: Stunt motorcyclist Johnny Blaze gives up his soul to become a hellblazing vigilante, to fight against power hungry Blackheart, the son of the devil himself.
Title: Ghost Rider
Writer: Mark Steven Johnson (screenplay), Mark Steven Johnson (screen story)
Actors: Matt Long, Raquel Alessi, Brett Cullen, Peter Fonda
tomatoConsensus: Ghost Rider is a sour mix of morose, glum histrionics amidst jokey puns and hammy dialogue.

Plot: FBI upstart Eric O'Neill enters into a power game with his boss, Robert Hanssen, an agent who was put on trial for selling secrets to the Soviet Union.
Title: Breach
Writer: Adam Mazer (screenplay), William Rotko (screenplay), Billy Ray (screenplay), Adam Mazer (story), William Rotko (story)
Actors: Chris Cooper, Ryan Phillippe, Laura Linney, Caroline Dhavernas
tomatoConsensus: Powered by Chris Cooper's masterful performance, Breach is a tense and engaging portrayal of the FBI's infamous turncoat.

Plot: A mechanic (Elba) enlists the help of a successful-but-lonely attorney (Union) while trying to wrest custody of his three daughters from his treacherous ex-wife and her larcenous boy friend...
Title: Daddy's Little Girls
Actors: Gabrielle Union, Idris Elba, Louis Gossett Jr., Tasha Smith
tomatoConsensus: Daddy's Little Girls boasts fine performances and a poignant message, but is ultimately let down by amateurish filmmaking.

Plot: A washed up singer is given a couple days to compose a chart-topping hit for an aspiring teen sensation. Though he's never written a decent lyric in his life, he sparks with an offbeat younger woman with a flair for words.
Title: Music and Lyrics
Actors: Hugh Grant, Scott Porter, Nick Bacon, Andrew Wyatt
tomatoConsensus: Music & Lyrics is a light and pleasant romantic comedy that succeeds because of the considerable charm of its co-stars. The music segments featuring Hugh Grant are worth the price of admission.

Plot: Walter Sparrow becomes obsessed with a novel that he believes was written about him. As his obsession increases, more and more similarities seem to arise.
Title: The Number 23
Actors: Jim Carrey, Virginia Madsen, Logan Lerman, Danny Huston
tomatoConsensus: Jim Carrey has been sharp in a number of non-comedic roles, but this lurid, overheated, and self-serious potboiler is not one of them. The Number 23 is clumsy, unengaging, and mostly confusing.

Plot: A rag-tag team of Reno cops are called in to save the day after a terrorist attack disrupts a national police convention in Miami Beach during spring break. Based on the Comedy Central series.
Title: Reno 911!: Miami
Writer: Robert Ben Garant, Thomas Lennon, Kerri Kenney, Robert Ben Garant (TV series), Thomas Lennon (TV series), Kerri Kenney (TV series)
Actors: Lennie Loftin, Danny DeVito, Robert Ben Garant, Niecy Nash
tomatoConsensus: Reno 911!'s anarchic brand of comedy loses much in translation to the big screen where it feels slapdash and shallow.

Plot: Exceptional London cop Nicholas Angel is involuntarily transferred to a quaint English village and paired with a witless new partner. While on the beat, Nicholas suspects a sinister conspiracy is afoot with the residents.
Title: Hot Fuzz
Actors: Simon Pegg, Martin Freeman, Bill Nighy, Robert Popper
tomatoConsensus: The brilliant minds behind Shaun of the Dead successfully take a shot at the buddy cop genre with Hot Fuzz. The result is a bitingly satiric and hugely entertaining parody.

Plot: A Las Vegas magician who can see into the future is pursued by FBI agents seeking to use his abilities to prevent a nuclear terrorist attack.
Title: Next
Writer: Gary Goldman (screenplay), Jonathan Hensleigh (screenplay), Paul Bernbaum (screenplay), Gary Goldman (screen story), Philip K. Dick (novel)
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Julianne Moore, Jessica Biel, Thomas Kretschmann
tomatoConsensus: Numerous plot holes and poorly motivated characters prevent Next from being the thought-provoking sci-fi flick it could've been.

Plot: A San Francisco cartoonist becomes an amateur detective obsessed with tracking down the Zodiac killer.
Title: Zodiac
Actors: Jake Gyllenhaal, Mark Ruffalo, Anthony Edwards, Robert Downey Jr.
tomatoConsensus: A quiet, dialogue-driven thriller that delivers with scene after scene of gut-wrenching anxiety. David Fincher also spends more time illustrating nuances of his characters and recreating the mood of the 70s than he does on gory details of murder.

Plot: A group of suburban biker wannabes looking for adventure hit the open road, but get more than they bargained for when they encounter a New Mexico gang called the Del Fuegos.
Title: Wild Hogs
Actors: Tim Allen, John Travolta, Martin Lawrence, William H. Macy
tomatoConsensus: Wild Hogs is a dreadful combination of fish-out-of-water jokes, slapstick, and lazy stereotypes.

Plot: Two siblings begin to develop special talents after they find a mysterious box of toys. Soon the kids, their parents, and even their teacher are drawn into a strange new world and find a task ahead of them that is far more important than any of them could imagine!
Title: The Last Mimzy
Writer: Bruce Joel Rubin (screenplay), Toby Emmerich (screenplay), James V. Hart (screen story), Carol Skilken (screen story), Henry Kuttner (short story "Mimsy Were the Borogoves"), C.L. Moore (short story "Mimsy Were the Borogoves")
Actors: Chris O'Neil, Rhiannon Leigh Wryn, Joely Richardson, Timothy Hutton
tomatoConsensus: The Last Mimzy makes efforts to be a fun children's movie, but unsuccessfully juggles too many genres and subplots -- eventually settling as an unfocused, slightly dull affair.

Plot: A biographical portrait of a pre-fame Jane Austen and her romance with a young Irishman.
Title: Becoming Jane
Writer: Jane Austen (letters), Kevin Hood, Sarah Williams
Actors: Anne Hathaway, James McAvoy, Julie Walters, James Cromwell
tomatoConsensus: Although Becoming Jane is a well-crafted period piece, it lacks fresh insight into the life and works of Jane Austen. The film focuses too much on wardrobe and not enough on Austen's achievements.

Plot: Depressed housewife learns her husband was killed in a car accident the day previously, awakens the next morning to find him alive and well at home, and then awakens the next day after to a world in which he is still dead.
Title: Premonition
Actors: Sandra Bullock, Julian McMahon, Shyann McClure, Courtney Taylor Burness
tomatoConsensus: Overdosing on flashbacks, and more portentous than profound, the overly obtuse Premonition weakly echoes such twisty classics as Memento, The Sixth Sense, and Groundhog Day.

Plot: A young widower returns to his hometown to search for answers to his wife's murder, which may be linked to the ghost of a murdered ventriloquist.
Title: Dead Silence
Writer: Leigh Whannell (screenplay), James Wan (story), Leigh Whannell (story)
Actors: Ryan Kwanten, Amber Valletta, Donnie Wahlberg, Michael Fairman
tomatoConsensus: More tasteful than recent slasher flicks, but Dead Silence is undone by boring characters, bland dialogue, and an unnecessary and obvious twist ending.

Plot: A man who lost his family in the September 11 attack on New York City runs into his old college roommate. Rekindling the friendship is the one thing that appears able to help the man recover from his grief.
Title: Reign Over Me
Actors: Adam Sandler, Don Cheadle, Jada Pinkett Smith, Liv Tyler
tomatoConsensus: Reign Over Me is a charming, affecting tale of friendship and loss, with solid performances from Adam Sandler as a broken, grief-stricken man and Don Cheadle as his old friend and savior.

Plot: The determined Jim Ellis starts a swim team for troubled teens at the Philadelphia Department of Recreation.
Title: Pride
Writer: Kevin Michael Smith (screenplay), Michael Gozzard (screenplay), J. Mills Goodloe (screenplay), Norman Vance Jr. (screenplay), Kevin Michael Smith (story), Michael Gozzard (story)
Actors: Terrence Howard, Bernie Mac, Kimberly Elise, Tom Arnold
tomatoConsensus: Pride features a typically stellar performance from Terrence Howard, but ultimately falls victim to its over usage of sports movie clichés.

Plot: A marksman living in exile is coaxed back into action after learning of a plot to kill the President. Ultimately double-crossed and framed for the attempt, he goes on the run to find the real killer and the reason he was set up.
Title: Shooter
Actors: Mark Wahlberg, Michael Peña, Danny Glover, Kate Mara
tomatoConsensus: With an implausible story and numerous plot holes, Shooter fails to distinguish itself from other mindless action-thrillers.

Plot: A group of National Guard trainees find themselves battling against a vicious group of mutants on their last day of training in the desert.
Title: The Hills Have Eyes II
Writer: Wes Craven, Jonathan Craven, Wes Craven (characters)
Actors: Cécile Breccia, Michael Bailey Smith, Archie Kao, Jay Acovone
tomatoConsensus: The Hills Have Eyes 2 is a completely unoriginal sequel offers plenty of gore and clichés, but few scares.

Plot: When the world is threatened by an ancient evil, the four adolescent turtles must reunite and overcome their faults in order to stand against it.
Title: TMNT
Writer: Kevin Munroe, Peter Laird (characters), Kevin Eastman (characters)
Actors: Chris Evans, Sarah Michelle Gellar, Mako, Kevin Smith
tomatoConsensus: TMNT's art direction is splendid, but the plot is non-existent and the dialogue lacks the irony and goofy wit of the earlier TMNT movies.

Plot: Chris is a once promising high school athlete whose life is turned upside down following a tragic accident. As he tries to maintain a normal life, he takes a job as a janitor at a bank, where he ultimately finds himself caught up in a planned heist.
Title: The Lookout
Actors: Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Jeff Daniels, Matthew Goode, Isla Fisher
tomatoConsensus: The Lookout is a genuinely suspenseful and affecting noir due to the great ensemble cast and their complex, realistic characters.

Plot: In 2002, two rival Olympic ice skaters were stripped of their gold medals and permanently banned from men's single competition. Presently, however, they've found a loophole that will allow them to qualify as a pairs team.
Title: Blades of Glory
Writer: Jeff Cox (screenplay), Craig Cox (screenplay), John Altschuler (screenplay), Dave Krinsky (screenplay), Craig Cox (story), Jeff Cox (story), Busy Philipps (story)
Actors: Will Ferrell, Jon Heder, Will Arnett, Amy Poehler
tomatoConsensus: Thanks to the spirited performances of a talented cast - particularly Will Ferrell and Jon Heder as rivals-turned-teammates -- Blades of Glory successfully spoofs inspirational sports dramas with inspired abandon.

Plot: Newlyweds Nick and Suzanne decide to move to the suburbs to provide a better life for their two kids. But their idea of a dream home is disturbed by a contractor with a bizarre approach to business.
Title: Are We Done Yet?
Writer: Hank Nelken (screenplay), Hank Nelken (screen story), Steven Gary Banks (characters), Claudia Grazioso (characters), Norman Panama (screenplay), Melvin Frank (screenplay)
Actors: Ice Cube, Nia Long, John C. McGinley, Aleisha Allen
tomatoConsensus: Are We Done Yet? plays it way too safe with generic slapstick and uninspired domestic foibles.

Plot: Quentin Tarantino and Robert Rodriguez's homage to exploitation double features in the 60s and 70s with two back-to-back cult films that include previews of coming attractions between them.
Title: Grindhouse
