Writer: Robert Rodriguez, Rob Zombie, Edgar Wright, Jeff Rendell, Eli Roth, Quentin Tarantino, Rob Cotterill (story), Jason Eisener (story), John Davies (fake trailer segment "Hobo with a Shotgun")
Director: Robert Rodriguez, Eli Roth, Quentin Tarantino, Edgar Wright, Rob Zombie
Actors: Kurt Russell, Zoë Bell, Rosario Dawson, Vanessa Ferlito
tomatoConsensus: Grindhouse delivers exhilarating exploitation fare with wit and panache, improving upon its source material with feral intelligence.

Plot: A former Christian missionary, who specializes in debunking religious phenomena, investigates a small town which seems to be suffering from the 10 biblical plagues.
Title: The Reaping
Writer: Carey Hayes (screenplay), Chad Hayes (screenplay), Brian Rousso (story)
Actors: Hilary Swank, David Morrissey, Idris Elba, AnnaSophia Robb
tomatoConsensus: It may feature such accomplished actors as Hilary Swank and Stephen Rea, but The Reaping also boasts the apropos tagline "What hath God wrought?" It's schlocky, spiritually shallow, and scare-free.

Plot: Rexxx, Hollywood's top canine star, gets lost and is adopted into a shabby firehouse. He teams up with a young kid to get the station back on its feet.
Title: Firehouse Dog
Writer: Claire-Dee Lim, Mike Werb, Michael Colleary
Actors: Josh Hutcherson, Bruce Greenwood, Bill Nunn, Scotch Ellis Loring
tomatoConsensus: Firehouse Dog's cute premise is ruined with endless fart and poop jokes, and an overlong run time.

Plot: Lewis is a brilliant inventor who meets mysterious stranger named Wilbur Robinson, whisking Lewis away in a time machine and together they team up to track down Bowler Hat Guy in a showdown that ends with an unexpected twist of fate.
Title: Meet the Robinsons
Writer: Jon Bernstein (screenplay), Michelle Bochner Spitz (screenplay), Don Hall (screenplay), Nathan Greno (screenplay), Aurian Redson (screenplay), Joseph Mateo (screenplay), Stephen J. Anderson (screenplay), William Joyce (based upon the book "A Day with Wilbur Robinson" by)
Actors: Angela Bassett, Daniel Hansen, Jordan Fry, Matthew Josten
tomatoConsensus: Meet the Robinsons is a visually impressive children's animated film marked by a story of considerable depth.

Title: Perfect Stranger
Actors: Halle Berry, Bruce Willis, Giovanni Ribisi, Richard Portnow
tomatoConsensus: Despite the presence of Halle Berry and Bruce Willis, Perfect Stranger is too convoluted to work, and features a twist ending that's irritating and superfluous. It's a techno-thriller without thrills.

Plot: A teen living under house arrest becomes convinced his neighbor is a serial killer.
Title: Disturbia
Writer: Christopher Landon (screenplay), Carl Ellsworth (screenplay), Christopher Landon (story)
Actors: Shia LaBeouf, Sarah Roemer, Carrie-Anne Moss, David Morse
tomatoConsensus: Aside from its clichéd resolution, Disturbia is a tense, subtle thriller with a noteworthy performance from Shia LaBeouf.

Plot: A Viking boy is left behind after his clan battles a Native American tribe. Raised within the tribe, he ultimately becomes their savior in a fight against the Norsemen.
Title: Pathfinder
Actors: Karl Urban, Moon Bloodgood, Russell Means, Clancy Brown
tomatoConsensus: A few rousing action sequences can't make up for Pathfinder's non-existent plot and silly dialogue.

Plot: An action epic that explores the origins of Master Shake, Frylock, and Meatwad, better known as the Aqua Teen Hunger Force, who somehow become pitted in a battle over an immortal piece of exercise equipment.
Title: Aqua Teen Hunger Force Colon Movie Film for Theaters
Actors: Dana Snyder, Carey Means, Dave Willis, Andy Merrill
tomatoConsensus: The non sequitur humor of Aqua Teen Hunger Force will surely appeal to its built-in fanbase, but for the uninitiated, the premise wears thin.

Plot: A gorgeous young automobile fanatic--and front to the hottest unsigned band on the West coast--finds herself caught up in illegal drag-racing competitions organized by exotic car fanatics.
Title: Redline
Actors: Nathan Phillips, Nadia Bjorlin, Angus Macfadyen, Eddie Griffin
tomatoConsensus: Redline has plenty of bad acting, laughable dialogue, and luxury cars.

Plot: An attorney, intent on climbing the career ladder toward success, finds an unlikely opponent in a manipulative criminal he is trying to prosecute.
Title: Fracture
Writer: Daniel Pyne (screenplay), Glenn Gers (screenplay), Daniel Pyne (story)
Actors: Anthony Hopkins, Ryan Gosling, David Strathairn, Rosamund Pike
tomatoConsensus: Though Fracture's plot is somewhat implausible, the onscreen face-off between Gosling and Hopkins overshadows any faults.

Plot: A married couple becomes stranded at an isolated motel and finds hidden video cameras in their room. They soon realize that unless they escape, they'll be the next victims of a snuff film.
Title: Vacancy
Actors: Kate Beckinsale, Luke Wilson, Frank Whaley, Ethan Embry
tomatoConsensus: Vacancy's restraint with gore is commendable, the thin characters and B-movie cliches less so.

Title: In the Land of Women
Actors: Adam Brody, Kelsey Keel, Danielle Savre, Gia Mantegna
tomatoConsensus: While pleasantly acted, In the Land of Women is a dramatically stilted film with underdeveloped characters.

Plot: Mr. Bean wins a trip to Cannes where he unwittingly separates a young boy from his father and must help the two come back together. On the way he discovers France, bicycling, and true love, among other things.
Title: Mr. Bean's Holiday
Writer: Rowan Atkinson (character), Richard Curtis (character), Simon McBurney (story), Hamish McColl (screenplay), Robin Driscoll (screenplay)
Actors: Rowan Atkinson, Steve Pemberton, Lily Atkinson, Preston Nyman
tomatoConsensus: Mr. Bean's Holiday means well, but good intentions can't withstand the 90 minutes of monotonous slapstick and tired, obvious gags.

Plot: A teenager is left invisible to the living after an attack.
Title: The Invisible
Writer: Mick Davis (screenplay), Christine Roum (screenplay), Mats Wahl (novel)
Actors: Justin Chatwin, Margarita Levieva, Marcia Gay Harden, Chris Marquette
tomatoConsensus: Dull and confusing execution makes this ghost story utterly forgettable and unintentionally funny.

Plot: Jack Conrad is awaiting the death penalty in a corrupt Central American prison. He is "purchased" by a wealthy television producer and taken to a desolate island where he must fight to the death against nine other condemned killers from all corners of the world, with freedom going to the sole survivor.
Title: The Condemned
Writer: Scott Wiper (screenplay), Rob Hedden (screenplay), Rob Hedden (story), Andy Hedden (story), Scott Wiper (story)
Actors: Steve Austin, Vinnie Jones, Robert Mammone, Tory Mussett
tomatoConsensus: The Condemned is a morally ambiguous, exceedingly violent and mostly forgettable action film.

Plot: A strange black entity from another world bonds with Peter Parker and causes inner turmoil as he contends with new villains, temptations, and revenge.
Title: Spider-Man 3
Writer: Sam Raimi (screenplay), Ivan Raimi (screenplay), Alvin Sargent (screenplay), Sam Raimi (screen story), Ivan Raimi (screen story), Stan Lee (Marvel comic book), Steve Ditko (Marvel comic book)
Actors: Tobey Maguire, Kirsten Dunst, James Franco, Thomas Haden Church
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 3 wins & 31 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though there are more characters and plotlines, and the action sequences still dazzle, Spider-Man 3 nonetheless isn't quite as refined as the first two.

Plot: A hotshot poker player tries to win a tournament in Vegas, but is fighting a losing battle with his personal problems.
Title: Lucky You
Writer: Eric Roth (screenplay), Curtis Hanson (screenplay), Eric Roth (story)
Actors: Phyllis Somerville, Eric Bana, Horatio Sanz, Drew Barrymore
tomatoConsensus: Lucky You tries to combine a romantic story with the high-stakes world of poker, but comes up with an empty hand.

Plot: A secretary's life changes in unexpected ways after her dog dies.
Title: Year of the Dog
Actors: Molly Shannon, Laura Dern, Regina King, Tom McCarthy
tomatoConsensus: Year of the Dog is a warm and quirky comedy that never condescends to its eccentric characters.

Plot: Pleasantly plump teenager Tracy Turnblad teaches 1962 Baltimore a thing or two about integration after landing a spot on a local TV dance show.
Title: Hairspray
Writer: Leslie Dixon (screenplay), John Waters, Mark O'Donnell (musical play), Thomas Meehan (musical play)
Actors: John Travolta, Michelle Pfeiffer, Christopher Walken, Amanda Bynes
Awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 19 wins & 39 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Hairspray is an energetic, wholly entertaining musical romp; a fun Summer movie with plenty of heart. Its contagious songs will make you want to get up and start dancing.

Plot: Six months after the rage virus was inflicted on the population of Great Britain, the US Army helps to secure a small area of London for the survivors to repopulate and start again. But not everything goes to plan.
Title: 28 Weeks Later
Writer: Rowan Joffe (screenplay), Juan Carlos Fresnadillo (screenplay), Enrique López Lavigne (screenplay), Jesús Olmo (screenplay)
Actors: Robert Carlyle, Rose Byrne, Jeremy Renner, Harold Perrineau
tomatoConsensus: While 28 Weeks Later lacks the humanism that made 28 Days Later a classic, it's made up with fantastic atmosphere and punchy direction.

Plot: A troubled young woman is sent to live with her grandmother for the summer, while hiding a secret that could potentially tear her family apart.
Title: Georgia Rule
Actors: Jane Fonda, Lindsay Lohan, Felicity Huffman, Dermot Mulroney
tomatoConsensus: Comedic and dramatic in all the wrong places, Georgia Rule is a confused dramedy that wastes the talents of its fine cast.

Plot: Three bumbling Army reservists bound for Iraq are accidentally dropped at Mexican village besieged by hostile forces.
Title: Delta Farce
Actors: Michael Rose, Glenn Morshower, Larry the Cable Guy, Christina Moore
tomatoConsensus: Too afraid to be a real satire of the Iraq War, Delta Farce instead devolves into a reprehensible, unfunny mix of slapstick, gay panic, and flatulence jokes.

Plot: When his new father-in-law, King Harold falls ill, Shrek is looked at as the heir to the land of Far, Far Away. Not one to give up his beloved swamp, Shrek recruits his friends Donkey and Puss in Boots to install the rebellious Artie as the new king. Princess Fiona, however, rallies a band of royal girlfriends to fend off a coup d'etat by the jilted Prince Charming.
Title: Shrek the Third
Writer: William Steig (book), Andrew Adamson (story), Jeffrey Price (screenplay), Peter S. Seaman (screenplay), Chris Miller (screenplay), Aron Warner (screenplay), Jeff Snow (story)
Actors: Mike Myers, Eddie Murphy, Cameron Diaz, Antonio Banderas
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 5 wins & 14 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Shrek the Third has pop culture potshots galore, but at the expense of the heart, charm, and wit that made the first two Shreks classics.

Plot: A modern-day musical about a busker and an immigrant and their eventful week in Dublin, as they write, rehearse and record songs that tell their love story.
Title: Once
Actors: Glen Hansard, Markéta Irglová, Hugh Walsh, Gerard Hendrick
tomatoConsensus: A charming, captivating tale of love and music, Once sets the standard for the modern musical. And with Dublin as its backdrop, Once is fun and fresh.

Plot: Captain Barbossa, Will Turner and Elizabeth Swann must sail off the edge of the map, navigate treachery and betrayal, find Jack Sparrow, and make their final alliances for one last decisive battle.
Title: Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End
Writer: Ted Elliott, Terry Rossio, Ted Elliott (characters), Terry Rossio (characters), Stuart Beattie (characters), Jay Wolpert (characters)
Actors: Johnny Depp, Geoffrey Rush, Orlando Bloom, Keira Knightley
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 20 wins & 41 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: POTC: AWE provides the thrilling action scenes, but mixes in too many characters with too many incomprehensible plot threads.

Plot: A psychological thriller about a man who is sometimes controlled by his murder-and-mayhem-loving alter ego.
Title: Mr. Brooks
Actors: Kevin Costner, Demi Moore, Dane Cook, William Hurt
tomatoConsensus: The setup is intriguing, but Mr. Brooks overstuffs itself with twists and subplots, becoming more preposterous as it goes along.

Plot: A teenager faces an uphill battle when she fights to give women the opportunity to play competitive soccer.
Title: Gracie
Writer: Lisa Marie Petersen (screenplay), Karen Janszen (screenplay), Andrew Shue (story), Ken Himmelman (story), Davis Guggenheim (story)
Actors: Jesse Lee Soffer, Christopher Shand, Carly Schroeder, Karl Girolamo
tomatoConsensus: Gracie can be rousing and touching in spots, but is ultimately undone by its predictable story arc and a lack of nuance.

Plot: Eagle vs Shark is the tale of two socially awkward misfits and the strange ways they try to find love; through revenge on high-school bullies, burgers, and video games.
Title: Eagle vs Shark
Writer: Loren Taylor (story), Taika Waititi (story), Taika Waititi
Actors: Loren Taylor, Jemaine Clement, Joel Tobeck, Brian Sergent
tomatoConsensus: Though there are frequent moments of wit and mordant humor, Eagle vs Shark needs more to distinguish itself from other precious, Napoleon Dynamite-ish comedies.

Plot: On the day that a serial killer that he helped put away is supposed to be executed, a noted forensic psychologist and college professor receives a call informing him that he has 88 minutes left to live.
Title: 88 Minutes
Actors: Al Pacino, Alicia Witt, Leelee Sobieski, Amy Brenneman
tomatoConsensus: 88 Minutes is a shockingly inept psychological thriller that expertly squanders the talent at hand.

Plot: Three American college students studying abroad are lured to a Slovakian hostel, and discover the grim reality behind it.
Title: Hostel: Part II
Country: USA, Czech Republic, Italy, Iceland, Slovakia
Actors: Lauren German, Roger Bart, Heather Matarazzo, Bijou Phillips
tomatoConsensus: Offering up more of the familiar sadism and gore, Hostel: Part II will surely thrill horror fans.

Plot: A teenage skateboarder's life begins to fray after he is involved in the accidental death of a security guard.
Title: Paranoid Park
Actors: Gabe Nevins, Daniel Liu, Jake Miller, Taylor Momsen
tomatoConsensus: Director Gus Van Sant once again superbly captures the ins and outs of teenage life in Paranoid Park, a quietly devastating portrait of a young man living with guilt and anxiety.

Plot: A behind-the-scenes look at the annual Penguin World Surfing Championship, and its newest participant, up-and-comer Cody Maverick.
Title: Surf's Up
Writer: Don Rhymer (screenplay), Ash Brannon (screenplay), Chris Buck (screenplay), Christopher Jenkins (screenplay), Christopher Jenkins (story by), Christian Darren (story by)
Actors: Shia LaBeouf, Jeff Bridges, Zooey Deschanel, Jon Heder
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 18 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Surf's Up is a laid back, visually stunning animated movie that brings a fresh twist to some familiar conventions. Its witty mockumentary format is fun and inventive, and the CGI is breathtakingly realistic.

Plot: The Fantastic Four learn that they aren't the only super-powered beings in the universe when they square off against the powerful Silver Surfer and the planet-eating Galactus.
Title: Fantastic 4: Rise of the Silver Surfer
Writer: Don Payne (screenplay), Mark Frost (screenplay), John Turman (story), Mark Frost (story), Stan Lee (characters), Jack Kirby (characters)
Actors: Ioan Gruffudd, Jessica Alba, Chris Evans, Michael Chiklis
tomatoConsensus: While an improvement on its predecessor, Fantastic Four: Rise of the Silver Surfer is nevertheless a juvenile, simplistic picture that has little benefit beyond its special effects.

Plot: Teen detective Nancy Drew accompanies her father on a business trip to Los Angeles, where she happens upon clues to a murder mystery involving a movie star.
Title: Nancy Drew
Writer: Andrew Fleming (screenplay), Tiffany Paulsen (screenplay), Tiffany Paulsen (story), Mildred Wirt Benson (characters)
Actors: Emma Roberts, Craig Gellis, Rich Cooper, Max Thieriot
tomatoConsensus: Emma Roberts is bubbly and charming as Nancy Drew, the junior detective. But despite her best efforts, Nancy Drew still lacks excitement, surprise, and compelling secondary characters.

Plot: A documentary comparing the highly profitable American health care industry to other nations, and HMO horror stories including shotgun deaths.
Title: Sicko
Actors: Michael Moore, Tucker Albrizzi, Tony Benn, George W. Bush
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 14 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Driven by Michael Moore's sincere humanism, Sicko is a devastating, convincing, and very entertaining documentary about the state of America's health care.

Plot: Mariane Pearl embarks on a frantic search to locate her journalist husband, Daniel, when he goes missing in Pakistan.
Title: A Mighty Heart
Actors: Dan Futterman, Angelina Jolie, Archie Panjabi, Mohammed Afzal
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 17 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Angelina Jolie conveys the full emotional range of a woman in a desperate situation in A Mighty Heart, an urgent yet tactful film about a difficult subject.

Plot: A man who specializes in debunking paranormal occurrences checks into the fabled room 1408 in the Dolphin Hotel. Soon after settling in, he confronts genuine terror.
Writer: Matt Greenberg (screenplay), Scott Alexander (screenplay), Larry Karaszewski (screenplay), Stephen King (short story)
Actors: John Cusack, Paul Birchard, Margot Leicester, Walter Lewis
tomatoConsensus: Relying on psychological tension rather than overt violence and gore, 1408 is a genuinely creepy thriller with a strong lead performance by John Cusack.

Plot: The shy son of an aging comedienne tries to find a balance between his demanding home life, his new girlfriend, and his mother's second chance at fame.
Title: Introducing the Dwights
Writer: Brenda Blethyn, Jo Brand, Keith Thompson
Actors: Brenda Blethyn, Rebecca Gibney, Khan Chittenden, Richard Wilson
tomatoConsensus: Despite a predictable storyline, Introducing the Dwights succeeds on the strength of its sweet and earnest portrayal of family dysfunction.

Plot: John McClane and a young hacker join forces to take down master cyber-terrorist Thomas Gabriel in Washington D.C.
Title: Live Free or Die Hard
Writer: Mark Bomback (screenplay), Mark Bomback (story), David Marconi (story), John Carlin (article), Roderick Thorp (certain original characters)
Actors: Bruce Willis, Timothy Olyphant, Justin Long, Maggie Q
tomatoConsensus: Live Free or Die Hard may be preposterous, but it's an efficient, action-packed summer popcorn flick with thrilling stunts and a commanding performance by Bruce Willis. Fans of the previous Die Hard films will not be disappointed.

Plot: A reverend puts an engaged couple through a grueling marriage preparation course to see if they are meant to be married in his church.
Title: License to Wed
Writer: Kim Barker (screenplay), Tim Rasmussen (screenplay), Vince Di Meglio (screenplay), Kim Barker (story), Wayne Lloyd (story)
Actors: Robin Williams, Mandy Moore, John Krasinski, Eric Christian Olsen
tomatoConsensus: Featuring one of Robin Williams' most shtick-heavy performances, the broad and formulaic License to Wed wrings little out of its slightly creepy, unappealing premise.

Plot: A drama exploring the romantic past and emotional present of Ann Grant and her daughters, Constance and Nina. As Ann lays dying, she remembers, and is moved to convey to her daughters, the defining moments in her life 50 years prior, when she was a young woman. Harris is the man Ann loves in the 1950s and never forgets.
Title: Evening
Writer: Susan Minot (screenplay), Michael Cunningham (screenplay), Susan Minot (novel)
Actors: Claire Danes, Toni Collette, Vanessa Redgrave, Patrick Wilson
tomatoConsensus: Beautifully filmed, but decidedly dull, Evening is a collossal waste of a talented cast.

Plot: God contacts Congressman Evan Baxter and tells him to build an ark in preparation for a great flood.
Title: Evan Almighty
Writer: Steve Oedekerk (screenplay), Steve Oedekerk (story), Joel Cohen (story), Alec Sokolow (story), Steve Koren (characters), Mark O'Keefe (characters)
Actors: Steve Carell, Morgan Freeman, Lauren Graham, Johnny Simmons
tomatoConsensus: Big on special effects but short on laughs, Evan Almighty underutilizes a star-studded cast that includes Steve Carell and Morgan Freeman.

Plot: A man and a woman awaken to find themselves trapped in a cellar. As their kidnapper drives them mad, the truth about their horrific abduction is revealed.
Title: Captivity
Writer: Larry Cohen (screenplay), Joseph Tura (screenplay), Larry Cohen (story)
Actors: Elisha Cuthbert, Daniel Gillies, Pruitt Taylor Vince, Michael Harney
tomatoConsensus: Lacking scares or psychological insight, Captivity is a distasteful entry in the 'torture porn' subgenre.

Plot: With their warning about Lord Voldemort's return scoffed at, Harry and Dumbledore are targeted by the Wizard authorities as an authoritarian bureaucrat slowly seizes power at Hogwarts.
Title: Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix
Actors: Daniel Radcliffe, Harry Melling, Jason Boyd, Richard Macklin
Awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 14 wins & 38 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It's not easy to take the longest Harry Potter book and streamline it into the shortest HP movie, but director David Yates does a bang up job of it, creating an Order of the Phoenix that's entertaining and action-packed.

Plot: Two straight, single Brooklyn firefighters pretend to be a gay couple in order to receive domestic partner benefits.
Title: I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry
Writer: Barry Fanaro (screenplay), Alexander Payne (screenplay), Jim Taylor (screenplay), Lew Gallo (treatment)
Actors: Adam Sandler, Kevin James, Jessica Biel, Dan Aykroyd
tomatoConsensus: Whether by way of inept comedy or tasteless stereotypes, I Now Pronounce You Chuck And Larry falters on both levels.

Plot: The music of the Beatles and the Vietnam War form the backdrop for the romance between an upper-class American girl and a poor Liverpudlian artist.
Title: Across the Universe
Writer: Dick Clement (screenplay), Ian La Frenais (screenplay), Julie Taymor (story), Dick Clement (story), Ian La Frenais (story)
Actors: Evan Rachel Wood, Jim Sturgess, Joe Anderson, Dana Fuchs
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 16 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Psychedelic musical numbers can't mask Across the Universe's clichéd love story and uninteresting characters.

Plot: Nora Wilder is freaking out. Everyone around her is in a relationship, is married, or has children. Nora is in her thirties, alone with job she's outgrown and a mother who constantly ...
Title: Broken English
Actors: Parker Posey, Drea de Matteo, Tim Guinee, Gena Rowlands
tomatoConsensus: Though Broken English eventually settles into basic rom-com territory, it's pleasant and good-natured, and Parker Posey is spellbinding throughout the movie.

Plot: Self-proclaimed stuntman Rod Kimble is preparing for the jump of his life - to clear fifteen buses to raise money for his abusive stepfather Frank's life-saving heart operation.
Title: Hot Rod
Actors: Andy Samberg, Jorma Taccone, Bill Hader, Danny McBride
tomatoConsensus: A few funny scenes can't save the disjointed Hot Rod, which is too silly and sloppy to hold up.

Plot: In a countryside town bordering on a magical land, a young man makes a promise to his beloved that he'll retrieve a fallen star by venturing into the magical realm.
Title: Stardust
Writer: Jane Goldman (screenplay), Matthew Vaughn (screenplay), Neil Gaiman (novel)
Actors: Ian McKellen, Bimbo Hart, Alastair MacIntosh, David Kelly
tomatoConsensus: A faithful interpretation that captures the spirit of whimsy, action, and off-kilter humor of Neil Gaiman, Stardust juggles multiple genres and tones to create a fantastical experience.

Plot: When a rap mogul from Atlanta tries to join a conservative country club in the Carolinas he runs into fierce opposition from the board President- but it's nothing that he and his entourage can't handle.
Title: Who's Your Caddy?
Writer: Don Michael Paul, Bradley Allenstein, Robert Henny
Actors: Mick Partridge, Big Boi, Faizon Love, Sherri Shepherd
tomatoConsensus: A juvenile, uninspired retread of Caddyshack, Who's Your Caddy? is unoriginal, unfunny, and just plain forgettable.

Plot: After Homer accidentally pollutes the town's water supply, Springfield is encased in a gigantic dome by the EPA and the Simpson family are declared fugitives.
Title: The Simpsons Movie
Writer: James L. Brooks (screenplay), Matt Groening (screenplay), Al Jean (screenplay), Ian Maxtone-Graham (screenplay), George Meyer (screenplay), David Mirkin (screenplay), Mike Reiss (screenplay), Mike Scully (screenplay), Matt Selman (screenplay), John Swartzwelder (screenplay), Jon Vitti (screenplay), Joel H. Cohen (consultant writer), John Frink (consultant writer), Tim Long (consultant writer), Michael Price (consultant writer)
Actors: Dan Castellaneta, Julie Kavner, Nancy Cartwright, Yeardley Smith
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 32 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Simpsons Movie contains the hearty laughs, biting satire, and honest portrayal of an American family that makes the show so popular. And it boasts slicker animation and polished writing that hearkens back to the show's glory days.

Plot: A young woman who was missing reappears, but she claims to be someone else entirely.
Title: I Know Who Killed Me
Actors: Bonnie Aarons, Lindsay Lohan, Michael Adler, Julia Ormond
tomatoConsensus: Distasteful and ludicrously plotted, I Know Who Killed Me is a career nadir for all involved -- particularly Lindsay Lohan in a dual role.

Plot: The life of a top chef changes when she becomes the guardian of her young niece.
Title: No Reservations
Actors: Catherine Zeta-Jones, Aaron Eckhart, Abigail Breslin, Patricia Clarkson
tomatoConsensus: This romantic comedy may look good on paper, but it's too predictable and melancholy for the genre.

Plot: A Beagle must use his newly-bestowed superpowers to defend Capitol City from mad scientist Simon Barsinister.
Title: Underdog
Writer: Adam Rifkin (screenplay), Joe Piscatella (screenplay), Craig A. Williams (screenplay), Joe Piscatella (story), Craig A. Williams (story), Adam Rifkin (story), W. Watts Biggers (television series)
Actors: Jason Lee, Peter Dinklage, Jim Belushi, Patrick Warburton
tomatoConsensus: Underdog is a mostly forgettable adaptation that relies far too heavily on recycled material and sloppy production.

Plot: A rich kid becomes the self-appointed psychiatrist to the student body of his new high school.
Title: Charlie Bartlett
Actors: Anton Yelchin, Robert Downey Jr., Hope Davis, Kat Dennings
tomatoConsensus: With engaging performances marked by an inconsistent tone, Charlie Bartlett is a mixed bag of clever teen angst comedy and muddled storytelling.

Plot: Jason Bourne dodges a ruthless CIA official and his agents from a new assassination program while searching for the origins of his life as a trained killer.
Title: The Bourne Ultimatum
Writer: Tony Gilroy (screenplay), Scott Z. Burns (screenplay), George Nolfi (screenplay), Tony Gilroy (screen story), Robert Ludlum (novel)
Actors: Matt Damon, Julia Stiles, David Strathairn, Scott Glenn
tomatoConsensus: The Bourne Ultimatum is an intelligent, finely tuned non-stop thrill ride. Another strong performance from Matt Damon and sharp camerawork from Paul Greengrass make this the finest installment of the Bourne trilogy.

Plot: During their first year of high school, four best girlfriends face off against the domineering student body president who wants to split them up into different social cliques.
Title: Bratz
Writer: Susan Estelle Jansen (screenplay), Adam De La Peña (story), David Eilenberg (story)
Actors: Logan Browning, Janel Parrish, Nathalia Ramos, Skyler Shaye
tomatoConsensus: Full of mixed messages and dubious role-models, Bratz is too shallow even for its intended audience.

Title: You Kill Me
Actors: Ben Kingsley, Téa Leoni, Luke Wilson, Dennis Farina
tomatoConsensus: Featuring wonderful performances from Ben Kingsley and Tea Leoni, You Kill Me is a charming, funny take on the familiar inner-lives-of-hit-men premise.

Plot: Two co-dependent high school seniors are forced to deal with separation anxiety after their plan to stage a booze-soaked party goes awry.
Title: Superbad
Actors: Jonah Hill, Michael Cera, Christopher Mintz-Plasse, Bill Hader
tomatoConsensus: Deftly balancing vulgarity and sincerity while placing its protagonists in excessive situations, Superbad is an authentic take on friendship and the overarching awkwardness of the high school experience.

Plot: Two narratives -- the life cycle of a mother walrus and her calf, and the life of a polar bear and her cubs -- are used to illustrate the harsh realities of existence in the Arctic.
Title: Arctic Tale
Writer: Linda Woolverton (narration), Mose Richards (narration), Kristin Gore (narration)
Actors: Queen Latifah, Katrina Agate, Zain Ali, Preston Bailey
tomatoConsensus: Arctic Tale features breathtaking nature cinematography, but is undone by its over-cutesy narration.

Plot: The arrival of a newborn girl causes the gradual disintegration of the Cairn family; particularly for 9-year-old Joshua (Kogan), an eccentric boy whose proper upbringing and refined tastes both take a sinister turn.
Title: Joshua
Actors: Sam Rockwell, Vera Farmiga, Celia Weston, Dallas Roberts
tomatoConsensus: Though Joshua is ultimately too formulaic, its intelligence and suspenseful buildup heighten the overall creep factor.

Plot: The story of Washington D.C. radio personality Ralph "Petey" Greene, an ex-con who became a popular talk show host and community activist in the 1960s.
Title: Talk to Me
Writer: Michael Genet (screenplay), Rick Famuyiwa (screenplay), Michael Genet (story)
Actors: Don Cheadle, Chiwetel Ejiofor, Bruce McFee, Mike Epps
tomatoConsensus: A riveting look at the life of legendary DJ "Petey" Greene, Talk to Me goes beyond the typical biopic with explosive performances from Don Cheadle and Chiwetal Ejiofor.

Plot: Up-and-coming sports reporter rescues a homeless man ("Champ") only to discover that he is, in fact, a boxing legend believed to have passed away. What begins as an opportunity to resurrect Champ's story and escape the shadow of his father's success becomes a personal journey as the ambitious reporter reexamines his own life and his relationship with his family.
Title: Resurrecting the Champ
Writer: Michael Bortman (screenplay), Allison Burnett (screenplay), Michael Bortman (screen story), Allison Burnett (screen story), J.R. Moehringer (Los Angeles Times Magazine article)
Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Josh Hartnett, Kathryn Morris, Dakota Goyo
tomatoConsensus: While sluggish in spots, Resurrecting the Champ is a sports/newsroom drama elevated by high-caliber performances by Samuel Jackson, Josh Hartnet, and Alan Alda.

Plot: After an attempted assassination on Ambassador Han, Lee and Carter head to Paris to protect a French woman with knowledge of the Triads' secret leaders.
Title: Rush Hour 3
Actors: Chris Tucker, Jackie Chan, Max von Sydow, Hiroyuki Sanada
tomatoConsensus: Rush Hour 3 is a tired rehash of the earlier films, and a change of scenery can't hide a lack of new ideas.

Title: The Last Legion
Writer: Jez Butterworth (screenplay), Tom Butterworth (screenplay), Carlo Carlei (story), Peter Rader (story), Valerio Manfredi (story)
Actors: Colin Firth, Ben Kingsley, Aishwarya Rai Bachchan, Peter Mullan
tomatoConsensus: With miscast leads and unoriginal, uninspired dialogue, The Last Legion pales in comparison to the recent cinematic epics it invokes.

Plot: Down-and-out former professional ping-pong phenom, Randy Daytona, is sucked into a maelstrom when FBI Agent Ernie Rodriguez recruits him for a secret mission. Randy is determined to bounce back and win, and to smoke out his father's killer -- arch-fiend Feng.
Title: Balls of Fury
Actors: Dan Fogler, Christopher Walken, George Lopez, Maggie Q
tomatoConsensus: Tasteless, yet harmless, Balls of Fury nevertheless fails to generate enough laughs despite its lowbrow intentions.

Plot: A modern retelling of Snow White set against students in their freshman year of college in the greek system.
Title: Sydney White
Actors: Amanda Bynes, Sara Paxton, Matt Long, Jack Carpenter
tomatoConsensus: Amanda Bynes is charming, but Sydney White is a poorly adapted take on Snow White, relying on tired ethnic stereotypes laughs.

Plot: A team of U.S. government agents is sent to investigate the bombing of an American facility in the Middle East.
Title: The Kingdom
Actors: Jamie Foxx, Chris Cooper, Jennifer Garner, Jason Bateman
tomatoConsensus: While providing several top-notch action scenes, The Kingdom ultimately collapses under the weight of formula and muddled politics.

Plot: Looking for answers to life's big questions, a stuttering boy joins his high school debate team.
Title: Rocket Science
Actors: Nicholas D'Agosto, Anna Kendrick, Utkarsh Ambudkar, Candace Hammer
tomatoConsensus: Though Rocket Science appears to be a typically quirky indie, the well-rounded performances and director Jeffrey Blitz's clear affection for his characters gives the film its proper human spark.

Plot: Seeking to offer his son the satisfying summer camp experience that eluded him as a child, the operator of a neighborhood daycare center opens his own camp, only to face financial hardship and stiff competition from a rival camp.
Title: Daddy Day Camp
Writer: Geoff Rodkey (screenplay), J. David Stem (screenplay), David N. Weiss (screenplay), Geoff Rodkey (story), Joel Cohen (story), Alec Sokolow (story), Geoff Rodkey (characters)
Actors: Cuba Gooding Jr., Lochlyn Munro, Richard Gant, Tamala Jones
tomatoConsensus: A mirthless, fairly desperate family film, Daddy Day Camp relies too heavily on bodily functions for comedic effect, resulting in plenty of cheap gags but no laughs.

Plot: As a Washington psychiatrist unearths the origin of an alien epidemic, she also discovers her son might be the only way it can be stopped.
Title: The Invasion
Actors: Nicole Kidman, Daniel Craig, Jeremy Northam, Jackson Bond
tomatoConsensus: The Invasion is slickly made, but it lacks psychological insight and thrills.

Plot: When the thugs who killed his father come looking for him, a young Latino man and his mother flee from their home.
Title: Illegal Tender
Actors: Michael Philip Del Rio, Samuel Molina, Rick Sepulveda, Manny Perez
tomatoConsensus: Lackluster acting and a ridiculous plot make the over-the-top Illegal Tender an unrealistic bust.

Plot: After being committed for 17 years, Michael Myers, now a grown man and still very dangerous, escapes from the mental institution (where he was committed as a 10 year old) and he immediately returns to Haddonfield, where he wants to find his baby sister, Laurie. Anyone who crosses his path is in mortal danger.
Title: Halloween
Writer: Rob Zombie (screenplay), John Carpenter, Debra Hill
Actors: Malcolm McDowell, Brad Dourif, Tyler Mane, Daeg Faerch
tomatoConsensus: Rob Zombie doesn't bring many new ideas to the table in Halloween, making it another bloody disappointment for fans of the franchise.

Plot: Nick Hume is a mild-mannered executive with a perfect life, until one gruesome night he witnesses something that changes him forever. Transformed by grief, Hume eventually comes to the disturbing conclusion that no length is too great when protecting his family.
Title: Death Sentence
Actors: Kevin Bacon, Garrett Hedlund, Kelly Preston, Jordan Garrett
tomatoConsensus: A nonsensical plot and an absurd amount of violence make this revenge pic gratuitous and overwrought.

Plot: Marion and Jack try to rekindle their relationship with a visit to Paris, home of Marion's parents -- and several of her ex-boyfriends.
Title: 2 Days in Paris
Actors: Adam Goldberg, Julie Delpy, Daniel Brühl, Marie Pillet
tomatoConsensus: Delpy proves not only to be an adept actress, but makes her mark as a writer and director in this thought-provoking comedy that breaks the romantic comedy mold.

Plot: Die-hard gamers compete to break world records on classic arcade games.
Title: The King of Kong: A Fistful of Quarters
Actors: Steve Wiebe, Mark Alpiger, Adam Wood, Walter Day
tomatoConsensus: The King of Kong is funny and compelling with more than a few poignant insights into human behavior. Director Seth Gordon presents the dueling King Kong players in all their obsessive complexity and with perfectly al dente observations.

Plot: A pair of well-meaning, but socially inept brothers try to find their perfect mates in order to provide their dying father with a grandchild.
Title: The Brothers Solomon
Actors: Will Arnett, Will Forte, Chi McBride, Kristen Wiig
tomatoConsensus: Squandering its impressive cast with poorly-directed gags, The Brothers Solomon is a one-joke film stretched well beyond its limits.

Plot: A small-time rancher agrees to hold a captured outlaw who's awaiting a train to go to court in Yuma. A battle of wills ensues as the outlaw tries to psych out the rancher.
Title: 3:10 to Yuma
Writer: Halsted Welles (screenplay), Michael Brandt (screenplay), Derek Haas (screenplay), Elmore Leonard (short story)
Actors: Russell Crowe, Christian Bale, Logan Lerman, Dallas Roberts
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 30 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This remake of a classic Western improves on the original, thanks to fiery performances from Russell Crowe and Christian Bale as well as sharp direction from James Mangold.

Plot: A man named Mr. Smith delivers a woman's baby during a shootout, and is then called upon to protect the newborn from the army of gunmen.
Title: Shoot 'Em Up
Actors: Clive Owen, Paul Giamatti, Monica Bellucci, Stephen McHattie
tomatoConsensus: As preposterous and over-the-top as Shoot 'Em Up may be, its humor and non-stop action make for a very enjoyable film.

Plot: Ten stories, each inspired by one of the ten commandments.
Title: The Ten
Actors: Paul Rudd, Adam Brody, Jon Hamm, Winona Ryder
tomatoConsensus: Although a few of the sketches that make up The Ten are humorous, the uneven and random tone of the film cause it to fall apart.

Plot: Fledgling writer Briony Tallis, as a thirteen-year-old, irrevocably changes the course of several lives when she accuses her older sister's lover of a crime he did not commit.
Title: Atonement
Actors: Saoirse Ronan, Ailidh Mackay, Brenda Blethyn, Julia West
tomatoConsensus: Atonement features strong performances, brilliant cinematography, and a unique score. Featuring deft performances from James MacAvoy and Keira Knightley, it's a successful adaptation of Ian McEwan's novel.

Plot: A comprehensive look at the Bush Administration's conduct of the Iraq war and its occupation of the country.
Title: No End in Sight
Actors: Campbell Scott, Gerald Burke, Ali Fadhil, Omar Fekeiki
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 12 wins & 18 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Charles Ferguson's documentary provides a good summary of the decisions that led to the mess in post-war Iraq, and offers politically interested audiences something they'd been looking for: a lowdown on the decision making.

Plot: A woman struggles to recover from a brutal attack by setting out on a mission for revenge.
Title: The Brave One
Writer: Roderick Taylor (screenplay), Bruce A. Taylor (screenplay), Cynthia Mort (screenplay), Roderick Taylor (story), Bruce A. Taylor (story)
Actors: Jodie Foster, Terrence Howard, Nicky Katt, Naveen Andrews
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 6 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Magnetic by between Jodie Foster and Terrence Howard can't quite compensate for The Brave One's problematic and unconvincing eye-for-an-eye moral.

Plot: A retired military investigator works with a police detective to uncover the truth behind his son's disappearance following his return from a tour of duty in Iraq.
Title: In the Valley of Elah
Writer: Paul Haggis (screenplay), Mark Boal (story), Paul Haggis (story)
Actors: Tommy Lee Jones, Charlize Theron, Jason Patric, Susan Sarandon
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 17 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though some of Paul Haggis's themes are heavy-handed, In the Valley of Elah is otherwise an engrossing murder mystery and antiwar statement, featuring a mesmerizing performance from Tommy Lee Jones.

Plot: A young journalist, a seasoned cameraman and a discredited war correspondent embark on an unauthorized mission to find the No.1 war criminal in Bosnia. However, their extremely dangerous target decides to come after them.
Title: The Hunting Party
Actors: Terrence Howard, Richard Gere, Gordana Vukres, James Brolin
tomatoConsensus: The Hunting Party is tonally awkward: its shifts from dark satire to serious political thriller create an uneven film, despite best efforts from its game leads.

Plot: A Russian teenager living in London who dies during childbirth leaves clues to a midwife in her journal that could tie her child to a rape involving a violent Russian mob family.
Title: Eastern Promises
Actors: Josef Altin, Mina E. Mina, Aleksandar Mikic, Sarah-Jeanne Labrosse
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 28 wins & 69 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: David Cronenberg triumphs again, showcasing the Viggo Mortensen's onscreen prowess in a daring performance. Bearing the trademarks of psychological drama and gritty violence, Eastern Promises is a very compelling crime story.

Plot: Brooklyn, 1985. With the mob world as a backdrop, three life-long friends struggle with questions of love, loss and loyalty.
Title: Brooklyn Rules
Actors: Paulo Araujo, Daniel Tay, Ty Thomas Reed, Brian O'Neill
tomatoConsensus: Brooklyn Rules' premise is old hat now, but strong performances from Alec Baldwin and the supporting cast are reasons enough to watch.

Plot: The crew members of NASA's Apollo missions tell their story in their own words.
Title: In the Shadow of the Moon
Actors: Buzz Aldrin, Neil Armstrong, Stephen Armstrong, Viola Armstrong
tomatoConsensus: Director David Sington poetically interwove 20th Century's cosmonautic history with its effect on the public's view of their country, their heroes and their future.

Plot: After falling out with his editor, a fading political journalist is forced to interview America's most popular soap actress.
Title: Interview
Writer: David Schechter, Theo van Gogh (based on the film by), Theodor Holman (screenplay), Hans Teeuwen (idea), Steve Buscemi (screenplay)
Actors: Steve Buscemi, Sienna Miller, Michael Buscemi, Tara Elders
tomatoConsensus: Captivating performances from Steve Buscemi and Sienna Miller make a seemingly simple premise gripping and entertaining.

Plot: Survivors of the Raccoon City catastrophe travel across the Nevada desert, hoping to make it to Alaska. Alice joins the caravan and their fight against the evil Umbrella Corp.
Title: Resident Evil: Extinction
Actors: Milla Jovovich, Oded Fehr, Ali Larter, Iain Glen
tomatoConsensus: Resident Evil: Extinction is more of the same; its few impressive action sequences unable to compensate for the pedestrian plot.

Plot: Taken aback by his mother's wedding announcement, a young man returns home in an effort to stop her from marrying his old high school gym teacher, a man who made high school hell for generations of students.
Title: Mr. Woodcock
Actors: Billy Bob Thornton, Seann William Scott, Susan Sarandon, Amy Poehler
tomatoConsensus: Underutilizing a talented cast, Mr. Woodcock lacks the comic energy and timing to make the most of its intriguing premise.

Plot: In order to keep the woman of his dreams from falling for another guy, Charlie Logan has to break the curse that has made him wildly popular with single women: Sleep with Charlie once, and the next man you meet will be your true love.
Title: Good Luck Chuck
Actors: Connor Price, Troy Gentile, Mackenzie Mowat, Sasha Pieterse
tomatoConsensus: A shortage of laughs and an undercurrent of mean-spiritedness undermine Good Luck Chuck, squandering a decent premise on gross-out humor and shopworn slapstick.

Plot: After graduating from Emory University, top student and athlete Christopher McCandless abandons his possessions, gives his entire $24,000 savings account to charity and hitchhikes to Alaska to live in the wilderness. Along the way, Christopher encounters a series of characters that shape his life.
Title: Into the Wild
Actors: Emile Hirsch, Marcia Gay Harden, William Hurt, Jena Malone
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 23 wins & 99 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: With his sturdy cast and confident direction, Sean Penn has turned a complex work of non-fiction like Into the Wild into an accessible and poignant character study.

Plot: An NFL quarterback living the bachelor lifestyle discovers that he has an 8-year-old daughter from a previous relationship.
Title: The Game Plan
Writer: Nichole Millard (screenplay), Kathryn Price (screenplay), Nichole Millard (story), Kathryn Price (story), Audrey Wells (story)
Actors: Dwayne Johnson, Madison Pettis, Kyra Sedgwick, Roselyn Sanchez
tomatoConsensus: Despite The Rock's abundant charisma, The Game Plan is just another run-of-the-mill Disney comedy.

Plot: During World War II era, a young woman, Wang Jiazhi, gets swept up in a dangerous game of emotional intrigue with a powerful political figure, Mr. Yee.
Language: Mandarin, Japanese, English, Shanghainese, Hindi, Cantonese
Title: Lust, Caution
Writer: Eileen Chang (story), James Schamus (screenplay), Hui-Ling Wang (screenplay)
Actors: Tony Chiu Wai Leung, Wei Tang, Joan Chen, Leehom Wang
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 24 wins & 51 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Ang Lee's Lust, Caution is a tense, sensual and beautifully-shot espionage film.

Plot: A meditation on love and its various incarnations, set within a community of friends in Oregon. and is described as an exploration of the magical, mysterious and sometimes painful incarnations of love.
Title: Feast of Love
Actors: Morgan Freeman, Greg Kinnear, Radha Mitchell, Billy Burke
tomatoConsensus: Though beautifully photographed, Feast of Love offers little beyond a trite, melodramatic character drama.

Plot: A newly wed man who believes he's just gotten hitched to the perfect woman encounters another lady on his honeymoon.
Title: The Heartbreak Kid
Writer: Scot Armstrong (screenplay), Leslie Dixon (screenplay), Bobby Farrelly (screenplay), Peter Farrelly (screenplay), Kevin Barnett (screenplay), Bruce Jay Friedman (short story "A Change of Plan"), Neil Simon
Actors: Ben Stiller, Malin Akerman, Michelle Monaghan, Jerry Stiller
tomatoConsensus: Despite some amiable performances, The Heartbreak Kid is neither as daring nor as funny as the Farrelly Brothers' earlier films.

Plot: A year after their father's funeral, three brothers travel across India by train in an attempt to bond with each other.
Title: The Darjeeling Limited
Writer: Wes Anderson, Roman Coppola, Jason Schwartzman
Actors: Owen Wilson, Adrien Brody, Jason Schwartzman, Amara Karan
tomatoConsensus: With the requisite combination of humor, sorrow and outstanding visuals, The Darjeeling Limited will satisfy Wes Anderson fans.

Plot: A New York nightclub manager tries to save his brother and father from Russian mafia hit men.
Title: We Own the Night
Actors: Joaquin Phoenix, Eva Mendes, Danny Hoch, Alex Veadov
tomatoConsensus: Bland characters, clichéd dialogue and rickety plotting ensure We Own The Night never lives up to its potential.

Plot: A mature Queen Elizabeth endures multiple crises late in her reign including court intrigues, an assassination plot, the Spanish Armada, and romantic disappointments.
Title: The Golden Age
Actors: Jordi Mollà, Aimee King, Cate Blanchett, Laurence Fox
tomatoConsensus: This sequel is full of lavish costumes and elaborate sets, but lacks the heart and creativity of the original Elizabeth

Title: Michael Clayton
Actors: Tom Wilkinson, Michael O'Keefe, Sydney Pollack, Danielle Skraastad
tomatoConsensus: Michael Clayton is one of the most sharply scripted films of 2007, with an engrossing premise and faultless acting. Director Tony Gilroy succeeds not only in capturing the audience's attention, but holding it until the credits roll.

Plot: On his sprawling country estate, an aging writer matches wits with the struggling actor who has stolen his wife's heart.
Title: Sleuth
Actors: Michael Caine, Jude Law, Harold Pinter
tomatoConsensus: Sleuth is so obvious and coarse, rather than suspenseful and action-packed, that it does nothing to improve on the original version

Plot: A delusional young man strikes up an unconventional relationship with a doll he finds on the Internet.
Title: Lars and the Real Girl
Actors: Ryan Gosling, Emily Mortimer, Paul Schneider, R.D. Reid
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 32 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Lars and the Real Girl could've so easily been a one-joke movie. But the talented cast, a great script, and direction never condescends to its character or the audience.

Plot: After an Alaskan town is plunged into darkness for a month, it is attacked by a bloodthirsty gang of vampires.
Title: 30 Days of Night
Writer: Steve Niles (screenplay), Stuart Beattie (screenplay), Brian Nelson (screenplay), Steve Niles (comic), Ben Templesmith (comic)
Actors: Josh Hartnett, Melissa George, Danny Huston, Ben Foster
tomatoConsensus: While 30 Days of Night offers a few thrills, it ultimately succumbs to erratic execution.

Plot: A CIA analyst questions his assignment after witnessing an unorthodox interrogation at a secret detention facility outside the US.
Title: Rendition
Actors: Jake Gyllenhaal, Reese Witherspoon, Meryl Streep, Alan Arkin
tomatoConsensus: The impressive cast cannot rescue Rendition, which explores complex issues in woefully simplified terms.

Plot: A recent widow invites her husband's troubled best friend to live with her and her two children. As he gradually turns his life around, he helps the family cope and confront their loss.
Title: Things We Lost in the Fire
Actors: Halle Berry, Benicio Del Toro, David Duchovny, Alexis Llewellyn
tomatoConsensus: Things We Lost in the Fire is a well-acted, beautifully filmed reflection on love, loss, addiction and recovery from life's obstacles.

Plot: Two Boston area detectives investigate a little girl's kidnapping, which ultimately turns into a crisis both professionally and personally.
Title: Gone Baby Gone
Writer: Ben Affleck (screenplay), Aaron Stockard (screenplay), Dennis Lehane (novel)
Actors: Casey Affleck, Michelle Monaghan, Morgan Freeman, Ed Harris
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 34 wins & 28 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Ben Affleck proves his directing credentials in this gripping dramatic thriller, drawing strong performances from the excellent cast and bringing working-class Boston to the screen.

Plot: A comedy that spoofs the inspirational sports movies, The Comebacks tells the story of an out-of-luck coach, Lambeau Fields, who takes a rag-tag bunch of college misfits and drives them towards the football championships. In the process, this life-long loser discovers that he is a winner after all by redeeming himself, saving his relationship with his family and friends, and finding that there is...
Title: The Comebacks
Writer: Ed Yeager (screenplay), Joey Gutierrez (screenplay), John Aboud (story), Michael Colton (story), Adam Jay Epstein (story), Andrew Jacobson (story)
Actors: David Koechner, Carl Weathers, Melora Hardin, Matthew Lawrence
tomatoConsensus: Full of groin-centric humor and tired sports clichés, The Comebacks is poor even by parody movie standards.

Plot: Robert Ford, who's idolized Jesse James since childhood, tries hard to join the reforming gang of the Missouri outlaw, but gradually becomes resentful of the bandit leader.
Title: The Assassination of Jesse James by the Coward Robert Ford
Actors: Brad Pitt, Mary-Louise Parker, Brooklynn Proulx, Dustin Bollinger
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 25 wins & 64 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: On the strength of its two lead performances Assassination is an expertly crafted period piece, and an insightful look at one of the enduring figures of American lore.

Plot: Kent Stock disrupts his life to become coach of the Norway High School baseball team and try to lead them to victory.
Title: The Final Season
Writer: Art D'Alessandro (story), James Grayford (screenplay), Art D'Alessandro (screenplay)
Actors: Sean Astin, Jesse Henecke, Powers Boothe, Owen Patchen Evans
tomatoConsensus: The Final Season recycles clichés we've seen in countless other sports movies, making for an unoriginal and uninspiring addition to the genre.

Plot: A precocious and outspoken Iranian girl grows up during the Islamic Revolution.
Title: Persepolis
Actors: Chiara Mastroianni, Danielle Darrieux, Catherine Deneuve, Simon Abkarian
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 28 wins & 54 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Persepolis is an emotionally powerful, dramatically enthralling autobiographical gem, and the film's simple black-and-white images are effective and bold.

Plot: A profile of Ian Curtis, the enigmatic singer of Joy Division whose personal, professional, and romantic troubles led him to commit suicide at the age of 23.
Title: Control
Actors: Sam Riley, Samantha Morton, Alexandra Maria Lara, Joe Anderson
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 30 wins & 32 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Control is a work of art, thanks to its evocative black and white cinematography and sensational performances from Sam Riley and Samantha Morton. Even those not familiar with Joy Division can still appreciate the beauty of the film.

Plot: Six Californians start a club to discuss the works of Jane Austen, only to find their relationships -- both old and new -- begin to resemble 21st century versions of her novels.
Title: The Jane Austen Book Club
Actors: Maria Bello, Emily Blunt, Kathy Baker, Amy Brenneman
tomatoConsensus: Though at times formulaic and sentimental, Jane Austen Book Club succeeds on the strength of its likable ensemble cast. Even those not familiar with Jane Austen's work may find much to enjoy this lighthearted romance.

Plot: A child escapes from Poland during World War II and first heads to Greece before coming of age in Canada.
Title: Fugitive Pieces
Actors: Robbie Kay, Monika Schurmann, Nina Dobrev, Jordan Pettle
tomatoConsensus: Though the retelling is a bit too subtle, the moving story and solid performances lift Fugitive Pieces beyond standard holocaust tales.

Plot: The story of a married silkworm merchant-turned-smuggler in 19th century France traveling to Japan for his town's supply of silkworms after a disease wipes out their African supply. During his stay in Japan, he becomes obsessed with the concubine of a local baron.
Title: Silk
Writer: Alessandro Baricco (novel), François Girard (screenplay), Michael Golding (screenplay)
Actors: Sei Ashina, Michael Pitt, Tony Vogel, Toni Bertorelli
tomatoConsensus: Silk contains a simple love triangle story but director Francois Gerard goes to painstaking lengths to turn it into a protracted and wearisome art film.

Plot: A Turkish man travels to Istanbul to find the daughter of his father's former girlfriend.
Title: The Edge of Heaven
Actors: Baki Davrak, Gürsoy Gemec, Cengiz Daner, Tuncel Kurtiz
tomatoConsensus: Evocative and complex, this story of struggling immigrants in Germany will stay with you after you leave the theater.

Plot: The big screen adaptation of Perry's stage play about the trials of marriage, and what happens to one family when a sexy young temptress arrives on the scene.
Title: Why Did I Get Married?
Actors: Tyler Perry, Sharon Leal, Janet Jackson, Malik Yoba
tomatoConsensus: Despite some poignant observations on modern marriages, Why Did I Get Married? is too preachy and melodramatic.

Plot: Despite Jigsaw's death, and in order to save the lives of two of his colleagues, Lieutenant Rigg is forced to take part in a new game, which promises to test him to the limit.
Title: Saw IV
Writer: Patrick Melton (screenplay), Marcus Dunstan (screenplay), Patrick Melton (story), Marcus Dunstan (story), Thomas Fenton (story)
Actors: Tobin Bell, Costas Mandylor, Scott Patterson, Betsy Russell
tomatoConsensus: Saw IV is more disturbing than compelling, with material already seen in the prior installments.

Plot: A science-fiction writer, recently widowed, considers whether to adopt a hyper-imaginative 6-year-old abandoned and socially rejected boy who says he's really from Mars.
Title: Martian Child
Writer: Seth Bass (screenplay), Jonathan Tolins (screenplay), David Gerrold (novel)
Actors: John Cusack, Bobby Coleman, Amanda Peet, Sophie Okonedo
tomatoConsensus: Despite some charms, overt emotional manipulation and an inconsistent tone prevents Martian Child from being the heartfelt dramedy it aspires to be.

Plot: In 1970s America, a detective works to bring down the drug empire of Frank Lucas, a heroin kingpin from Manhattan, who is smuggling the drug into the country from the Far East.
Title: American Gangster
Actors: Denzel Washington, Russell Crowe, Chiwetel Ejiofor, Josh Brolin
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 12 wins & 34 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: American Gangster is a gritty and entertaining throwback to classic gangster films, with its lead performers firing on all cylinders.

Plot: Barry B. Benson, a bee just graduated from college, is disillusioned at his lone career choice: making honey. On a special trip outside the hive, Barry's life is saved by Vanessa, a florist in New York City. As their relationship blossoms, he discovers humans actually eat honey, and subsequently decides to sue them.
Title: Bee Movie
Writer: Jerry Seinfeld, Spike Feresten, Barry Marder, Andy Robin, Chuck Martin (additional screenplay material), Tom Papa (additional screenplay material)
Actors: Jerry Seinfeld, Renée Zellweger, Matthew Broderick, Patrick Warburton
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 14 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Bee Movie has humorous moments, but its awkward premise and tame delivery render it mostly forgettable.

Plot: When two brothers organize the robbery of their parents' jewelry store the job goes horribly wrong, triggering a series of events that sends them, their father and one brother's wife hurtling towards a shattering climax.
Title: Before the Devil Knows You're Dead
Actors: Philip Seymour Hoffman, Ethan Hawke, Albert Finney, Marisa Tomei
tomatoConsensus: A tense and effective thriller, Before the Devil Knows You're Dead marks a triumphant return to form for director Sidney Lumet.

Plot: Violence and mayhem ensue after a hunter stumbles upon a drug deal gone wrong and more than two million dollars in cash near the Rio Grande.
Title: No Country for Old Men
Writer: Joel Coen (screenplay), Ethan Coen (screenplay), Cormac McCarthy (novel)
Actors: Tommy Lee Jones, Javier Bardem, Josh Brolin, Woody Harrelson
tomatoConsensus: Bolstered by powerful lead performances from Javier Bardem, Josh Brolin, and Tommy Lee Jones, No Country for Old Men finds the Coen brothers spinning cinematic gold out of Cormac McCarthy's grim, darkly funny novel.

Plot: The bizarre true story of Linda Riss and Burt Pugach.
Title: Crazy Love
Actors: Bob Janoff, Burt Pugach, Linda Pugach, Sylvia Hoffman
tomatoConsensus: Crazy Love's subjects and story are so compelling that they overcome the doc's dry, talking heads format.

Plot: A drama with fairy tale elements, where an orphaned musical prodigy uses his gift as a clue to finding his birth parents.
Title: August Rush
Writer: Nick Castle (screenplay), James V. Hart (screenplay), Paul Castro (story), Nick Castle (story)
Actors: Freddie Highmore, Keri Russell, Jonathan Rhys Meyers, Terrence Howard
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 10 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though featuring a talented cast, August Rush cannot overcome the flimsy direction and schmaltzy plot.

Plot: Injuries sustained by two Army rangers behind enemy lines in Afghanistan set off a sequence of events involving a congressman, a journalist and a professor.
Title: Lions for Lambs
Actors: Robert Redford, Meryl Streep, Tom Cruise, Michael Peña
tomatoConsensus: Despite its powerhouse cast, Lions for Lambs feels like a disjointed series of lectures, rather than a sharp narrative, and ends up falling flat.

Plot: Fred Claus, Santa's bitter older brother, is forced to move to the North Pole.
Title: Fred Claus
Writer: Dan Fogelman (screenplay), Jessie Nelson (story), Dan Fogelman (story)
Actors: Vince Vaughn, Paul Giamatti, John Michael Higgins, Miranda Richardson
tomatoConsensus: A slew of talent is wasted in this contrived and overly sentimental Christmas film, which can't quite get the balance between slapstick humor and schmaltzy uplift.

Plot: The warrior Beowulf must fight and defeat the monster Grendel who is terrorizing Denmark, and later, Grendel's mother, who begins killing out of revenge.
Title: Beowulf
Writer: Neil Gaiman (screenplay), Roger Avary (screenplay), Anonymous (epic poem "Beowulf")
Actors: Robin Wright, Anthony Hopkins, Paul Baker, John Bilezikjian
tomatoConsensus: Featuring groundbreaking animation, stunning visuals, and a talented cast, Beowulf has in spades what more faithful book adaptations forget to bring: pure cinematic entertainment.

Plot: Molly Mahoney is the awkward and insecure manager of Mr. Magorium's Wonder Emporium, the strangest, most fantastic, most wonderful toy store in the world. But when Mr. Magorium, the 243-year-old eccentric who owns the store, bequeaths the store to her, a dark and ominous change begins to take over the once-remarkable Emporium.
Title: Mr. Magorium's Wonder Emporium
Actors: Ted Ludzik, Natalie Portman, Zach Mills, Dustin Hoffman
tomatoConsensus: Mr. Magorium's Wonder Emporium's title is much more fun that the film itself, as the colorful visuals and talented players can't make up for a bland story.

Plot: Florentino, rejected by the beautiful Fermina at a young age, devotes much of his adult life to carnal affairs as a desperate attempt to heal his broken heart.
Title: Love in the Time of Cholera
Actors: Benjamin Bratt, Gina Bernard Forbes, Giovanna Mezzogiorno, Javier Bardem
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though beautifully filmed, the makers of Love in the Time of Cholera fail to transfer the novel's magic to the screen.

Plot: An examination of the genocide in Sudan's western region of Darfur.
Title: Darfur Now
Actors: Ahmed Mahammed Abaka, Sheikh Ahmed Mohamad Abakar, Hawa Abaker, Hejewa Adam
tomatoConsensus: Although Darfur Now is not always engaging as cinema, the film succeeds in bringing attention to the crisis in Darfur.

Plot: A freak storm unleashes a species of blood-thirsty creatures on a small town, where a small band of citizens hole up in a supermarket and fight for their lives.
Title: The Mist
Actors: Thomas Jane, Marcia Gay Harden, Laurie Holden, Andre Braugher
tomatoConsensus: Frank Darabont's impressive camerawork and politically incisive script make The Mist a truly frightening experience.

Plot: A princess, who is prepared to be wed, is sent away to New York by an evil queen, where she falls in love with a lawyer.
Title: Enchanted
Actors: Amy Adams, Patrick Dempsey, James Marsden, Timothy Spall
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 11 wins & 47 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A smart re-imagining of fairy tale tropes that's sure to delight children and adults, Enchanted features witty dialogue, sharp animation, and a star turn by Amy Adams.

Plot: A Christmastime drama centered around the Whitfield family's first holiday together in four years.
Title: This Christmas
Actors: Delroy Lindo, Idris Elba, Loretta Devine, Chris Brown
tomatoConsensus: This Christmas features strong performances and a sharp portrayal of family dynamics, but relies too heavily on holiday movie clichés.

Plot: A businesswoman is pursued by a psychopath after being locked in a parking garage on Christmas Eve.
Title: P2
Writer: Alexandre Aja (story), Grégory Levasseur (story), Franck Khalfoun (screenplay), Alexandre Aja (screenplay), Grégory Levasseur (screenplay)
Actors: Wes Bentley, Rachel Nichols, Simon Reynolds, Philip Akin
tomatoConsensus: P2 is full of gore, but low on suspense, featuring a cat-and-mouse plot has been done many times before.

Plot: The story focuses on a man who suffers "anesthetic awareness" and finds himself awake and aware, but paralyzed, during heart surgery. His mother must wrestle with her own demons as a turn of events unfolds around them, while trying to unfold the story hidden behind her son's young wife.
Title: Awake
Actors: Hayden Christensen, Jessica Alba, Terrence Howard, Lena Olin
tomatoConsensus: Awake has an interesting premise but would have benefited from tighter performances and more efficient direction and editing.

Plot: In a parallel universe, young Lyra Belacqua journeys to the far North to save her best friend and other kidnapped children from terrible experiments by a mysterious organization.
Title: The Golden Compass
Actors: Nicole Kidman, Daniel Craig, Dakota Blue Richards, Ben Walker
tomatoConsensus: Without the bite or the controversy of the source material, The Golden Compass is reduced to impressive visuals overcompensating for lax storytelling.

Plot: Years after a plague kills most of humanity and transforms the rest into monsters, the sole survivor in New York City struggles valiantly to find a cure.
Title: I Am Legend
Writer: Mark Protosevich (screenplay), Akiva Goldsman (screenplay), Richard Matheson (novel), John William Corrington, Joyce Hooper Corrington
Actors: Will Smith, Alice Braga, Charlie Tahan, Salli Richardson-Whitfield
tomatoConsensus: I Am Legend overcomes questionable special effects and succeeds largely on the strength of Will Smith's mesmerizing performance.

Plot: A struggling songwriter named Dave Seville finds success when he comes across a trio of singing chipmunks: mischievous leader Alvin, brainy Simon, and chubby, impressionable Theodore.
Title: Alvin and the Chipmunks
Writer: Jon Vitti (screenplay), Will McRobb (screenplay), Chris Viscardi (screenplay), Jon Vitti (story), Ross Bagdasarian (characters Alvin and the Chipmunks)
Actors: Jason Lee, David Cross, Cameron Richardson, Jane Lynch
tomatoConsensus: Though cutely rendered, Alvin and the Chipmunks suffers from bland potty humor and a rehashed kids' movie formula.

Plot: Margot and her son Claude decide to visit her sister Pauline after she announces that she is marrying less-than-impressive Malcolm. In short order, the storm the sisters create leaves behind a mess of thrashed relationships and exposed family secrets.
Title: Margot at the Wedding
Actors: Zane Pais, Susan Blackwell, Nicole Kidman, Jack Black
tomatoConsensus: Despite a great cast, the characters in Margot at the Wedding are too unlikable to enthrall viewers.

Plot: Ruminations on the life of Bob Dylan, where six characters embody a different aspect of the musician's life and work.
Title: I'm Not There.
Writer: Todd Haynes (screenplay), Oren Moverman (screenplay), Todd Haynes (story)
Actors: Cate Blanchett, Ben Whishaw, Christian Bale, Richard Gere
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 26 wins & 45 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: I'm Not There's unique editing, visuals, and multiple talented actors portraying Bob Dylan make for a deliciously unconventional experience. Each segment brings a new and fresh take on Dylan's life.

Plot: A sister and brother face the realities of familial responsibility as they begin to care for their ailing father.
Title: The Savages
Actors: Laura Linney, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Philip Bosco, Peter Friedman
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 17 wins & 31 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Thanks to a tender, funny script from director Tamara Jenkins, and fine performances from Philip Seymour Hoffman and Laura Linney, this film delivers a nuanced, beautifully three-dimensional look at the struggles and comforts of family bonds.

Plot: Faced with an unplanned pregnancy, an offbeat young woman makes an unusual decision regarding her unborn child.
Title: Juno
Actors: Ellen Page, Michael Cera, Jennifer Garner, Jason Bateman
tomatoConsensus: One of the brightest, funniest comedies of the year, Juno's smart script and direction are matched by assured performances in a coming of age story with a 21st century twist.

Plot: A young woman takes a soul-searching journey across America to resolve her questions about love while encountering a series of offbeat characters along the way.
Title: My Blueberry Nights
Writer: Kar-Wai Wong (screenplay), Lawrence Block (screenplay), Kar-Wai Wong (story)
Actors: Jude Law, Norah Jones, Chad R. Davis, Katya Blumenberg
tomatoConsensus: Though well filmed, My Blueberry Nights is a mixed bag of dedicated performers working with thin material.

Plot: An ambitious graduate student convinces a writer that her thesis can resurrect his career.
Title: Starting Out in the Evening
Writer: Brian Morton (novel), Fred Parnes (screenplay), Andrew Wagner (screenplay)
Actors: Frank Langella, Lauren Ambrose, Patti Perkins, Lili Taylor
tomatoConsensus: Starting Out in the Evening features sharp dialogue and moving performances from the talented Frank Langella and Lili Taylor.

Plot: The devastating reconstruction of the rape and murder of a 15-year-old Iraqi girl by American soldiers in Samarra in 2006.
Title: Redacted
Actors: Izzy Diaz, Rob Devaney, Ty Jones, Anas Wellman
tomatoConsensus: Despite DePalma's obvious commitment to the material and passion for the issues at hand, Redacted suffers from stereotypical characters and a forced faux-doc style.

Plot: Two terminally ill men escape from a cancer ward and head off on a road trip with a wish list of to-dos before they die.
Title: The Bucket List
Actors: Jack Nicholson, Morgan Freeman, Sean Hayes, Beverly Todd
tomatoConsensus: Not even the earnest performances of the two leads can rescue The Bucket List from its schmaltzy script.

Plot: After spending years in California, Amir returns to his homeland in Afghanistan to help his old friend Hassan, whose son is in trouble.
Title: The Kite Runner
Actors: Khalid Abdalla, Atossa Leoni, Shaun Toub, Sayed Jafar Masihullah Gharibzada
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 22 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despite some fine performances, The Kite Runner is just shy of rendering the magic of the novel on to the big screen.

Plot: The infamous story of Benjamin Barker, AKA Sweeney Todd, who sets up a barber shop down in London which is the basis for a sinister partnership with his fellow tenant, Mrs. Lovett. Based on the hit Broadway musical.
Title: Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street
Writer: John Logan (screenplay), Hugh Wheeler (musical), Christopher Bond (musical adaptation)
Actors: Johnny Depp, Helena Bonham Carter, Alan Rickman, Timothy Spall
tomatoConsensus: Full of pith and Grand Guignol grossness, this macabre musical is perfectly helmed and highly entertaining. Tim Burton masterfully stages the musical in a way that will make you think he has done this many times before.

Plot: Benjamin Gates must follow a clue left in John Wilkes Booth's diary to prove his ancestor's innocence in the assassination of Abraham Lincoln.
Title: National Treasure: Book of Secrets
Writer: Marianne Wibberley (screenplay), Cormac Wibberley (screenplay), Gregory Poirier (story), Marianne Wibberley (story), Cormac Wibberley (story), Ted Elliott (story), Terry Rossio (story), Jim Kouf (characters), Oren Aviv (characters), Charles Segars (characters)
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Justin Bartha, Diane Kruger, Jon Voight
tomatoConsensus: A talented cast goes to waste in the improbable National Treasure: Book of Secrets, which is eerily similar to the first film.

Plot: A story of family, religion, hatred, oil and madness, focusing on a turn-of-the-century prospector in the early days of the business.
Title: There Will Be Blood
Actors: Daniel Day-Lewis, Martin Stringer, Matthew Braden Stringer, Jacob Stringer
tomatoConsensus: Widely touted as a masterpiece, this sparse and sprawling epic about the underhanded "heroes" of capitalism boasts incredible performances by leads Daniel Day-Lewis and Paul Dano, and is director Paul Thomas Anderson's best work to date.

Plot: A drama based on a Texas congressman Charlie Wilson's covert dealings in Afghanistan, where his efforts to assist rebels in their war with the Soviets have some unforeseen and long-reaching effects.
Language: English, Dari, Russian, Urdu, Hebrew, Arabic
Title: Charlie Wilson's War
Actors: Tom Hanks, Amy Adams, Julia Roberts, Philip Seymour Hoffman
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 22 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Charlie Wilson's War manages to entertain and inform audiences, thanks to its witty script and talented cast of power players.

Plot: Warring alien and predator races descend on a rural US town, where unsuspecting residents must band together for any chance of survival.
Title: Aliens vs. Predator: Requiem
Writer: Shane Salerno, Dan O'Bannon ("Alien" characters), Ronald Shusett ("Alien" characters), Jim Thomas ("Predator" characters), John Thomas ("Predator" characters)
Actors: Steven Pasquale, Reiko Aylesworth, John Ortiz, Johnny Lewis
tomatoConsensus: The increased gore and violence over the first Alien vs. Predator can't excuse Requiem's disorientating editing, excessively murky lighting, and lack of new ideas.

Plot: Singer Dewey Cox overcomes adversity to become a musical legend.
Title: Walk Hard: The Dewey Cox Story
Actors: Nat Faxon, John C. Reilly, Tim Meadows, Conner Rayburn
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A parody that pokes fun at rock stars and reductive biopics alike, this comedy sings in large part because of stellar performances and clever original music.

Plot: A young girl turns to a department store Santa in the hopes that he will help find a new husband for her divorced mother.
Title: The Perfect Holiday
Writer: Lance Rivera, Marc Calixte, Nat Mauldin, Jeff Stein
Actors: Morris Chestnut, Gabrielle Union, Faizon Love, Charlie Murphy
tomatoConsensus: The Perfect Holiday is the perfect example of Christmas movie clichés run amok.

Plot: Through readings of historical account by actors and the testimony of survivors, the events of the Nanjing Massacre are recounted.
Title: Nanking
Writer: Bill Guttentag (screenplay), Dan Sturman (screenplay), Elisabeth Bentley (screenplay), Bill Guttentag (story), Dan Sturman (story)
Actors: Hugo Armstrong, Rosalind Chao, Stephen Dorff, John Getz
tomatoConsensus: This powerful and horrific documentary brings the atrocities committed at Nanking to light without sugarcoating any of the brutality.

Plot: The tale of two brothers with serious financial woes. When a third party proposes they turn to crime, things go badly and the two become enemies.
Title: Cassandra's Dream
Actors: Ewan McGregor, Colin Farrell, Peter-Hugo Daly, John Benfield
tomatoConsensus: Colin Farrell and Tom Wilkinson act up a storm in Cassandra's Dream, but Woody Allen's heavy-handed symbolism and foreshadowing drains the plot of all tension.

Plot: Based on the Korean legend, unknown creatures will return and devastate the planet. Reporter Ethan Kendrick is called in to investigate the matter, and he arrives at the conclusion that a ...
Title: Dragon Wars: D-War
Actors: Jason Behr, Amanda Brooks, Robert Forster, Craig Robinson
tomatoConsensus: Dragon Wars' special effects can't make up for an unfocused script and stale acting.

Plot: A band comprised of members of the Egyptian police force head to Israel to play at the inaugural ceremony of an Arab arts center, only to find themselves lost in the wrong town.
Title: The Band's Visit
Actors: Sasson Gabai, Ronit Elkabetz, Saleh Bakri, Khalifa Natour
tomatoConsensus: The Band's Visit is both a clever, subtle slice-of-life comedy, and poignant cross-cultural exploration.

Plot: A man named Farmer sets out to rescue his kidnapped wife and avenge the death of his son -- two acts committed by the Krugs, a race of animal-warriors who are controlled by the evil Gallian.
Title: In the Name of the King: A Dungeon Siege Tale
Writer: Doug Taylor (screenplay), Jason Rappaport (story), Dan Stroncak (story), Doug Taylor (story), Chris Taylor (video game "Dungeon Siege")
Actors: Jason Statham, Leelee Sobieski, John Rhys-Davies, Ron Perlman
tomatoConsensus: Featuring mostly wooden performances, laughable dialogue, and shoddy production values, In the Name of the King fulfills all expectations of an Uwe Boll film.

Plot: Set in 1960 London, where a soon to retire caretaker convinces a glass-ceiling constrained American executive to help him steal a handful of diamonds from their employer, the London Diamond Corporation.
Title: Flawless
Actors: Demi Moore, Michael Caine, Lambert Wilson, Nathaniel Parker
tomatoConsensus: Michael Caine's excellent performance makes Flawless something more than an average heist movie.

Plot: Adriana is a 13-year-old girl from Mexico City whose kidnapping by sex traffickers sets in motion a desperate mission by her 17-year-old brother, Jorge, to save her. Trapped and terrified ...
Title: Trade
Writer: Jose Rivera (screenplay), Peter Landesman (story), Jose Rivera (story), Peter Landesman (article)

Actors: Mick Jagger, Keith Richards, Charlie Watts, Ronnie Wood
tomatoConsensus: It may offer little new for fans, but Martin Scorsese's document of the Rolling Stones' electrifying live show should provide satisfaction to audiences.

Plot: A young girl inhabits an isolated island with her scientist father and communicates with a reclusive author of the novel she's reading.
Title: Nim's Island
Writer: Joseph Kwong (screenplay), Paula Mazur (screenplay), Mark Levin (screenplay), Jennifer Flackett (screenplay), Wendy Orr (novel)
Actors: Abigail Breslin, Jodie Foster, Gerard Butler, Michael Carman
tomatoConsensus: Despite good intentions, Nim's Island flounders under an implausible storyline, simplistic stock characters, and distracting product placement.

Plot: A group of friends whose leisurely Mexican holiday takes a turn for the worse when they, along with a fellow tourist, embark on a remote archaeological dig in the jungle where something evil lives among the ruins.
Title: The Ruins
Writer: Scott B. Smith (screenplay), Scott B. Smith (novel)
Actors: Jonathan Tucker, Jena Malone, Laura Ramsey, Shawn Ashmore
tomatoConsensus: Despite a solid cast and truly frightening source material, The Ruins founders, thanks to a weak script and an excess of gore.

Plot: Devastated Peter takes a Hawaiian vacation in order to deal with the recent break-up with his TV star girlfriend, Sarah. Little does he know, Sarah's traveling to the same resort as her ex - and she's bringing along her new boyfriend.
Title: Forgetting Sarah Marshall
Actors: Jason Segel, Kristen Bell, Mila Kunis, Russell Brand
tomatoConsensus: With ample laughs and sharp performances, Forgetting Sarah Marshall finds just the right mix of romantic and raunchy comedy.

Plot: Orphaned high school student Rick Riker is bitten by a radioactive dragonfly, develops super powers (except for the ability to fly), and becomes a hero.
Title: Superhero Movie
Actors: Drake Bell, Sara Paxton, Christopher McDonald, Leslie Nielsen
