tomatoConsensus: Superhero Movie is not the worst of the spoof genre, but relies on tired gags and lame pop culture references all the same.

Plot: An undercover cop, disillusioned by the recent murder of his wife, is implicated in the murder of an officer and must struggle to clear himself.
Title: Street Kings
Writer: James Ellroy (screenplay), Kurt Wimmer (screenplay), Jamie Moss (screenplay), James Ellroy (story)
Actors: Keanu Reeves, Forest Whitaker, Hugh Laurie, Chris Evans
tomatoConsensus: Street Kings contains formulaic violence but no shred of intelligence.

Plot: After being mistaken for terrorists and thrown into Guantánamo Bay, stoners Harold and Kumar escape and return to the U.S., where they proceed to flee across the country with federal agents in hot pursuit.
Title: Harold & Kumar Escape from Guantanamo Bay
Writer: Jon Hurwitz, Hayden Schlossberg, Jon Hurwitz (characters), Hayden Schlossberg (characters)
Actors: John Cho, Kal Penn, Rob Corddry, Jack Conley
tomatoConsensus: It may not equal its predecessor, but Harold and Kumar Escape from Guantanamo Bay is still good for some laughs -- and food for thought.

Plot: A young driver, Speed Racer, aspires to be champion of the racing world with the help of his family and his high-tech Mach 5 automobile.
Title: Speed Racer
Writer: Lilly Wachowski, Lana Wachowski, Tatsuo Yoshida (animated series "Speed Racer")
Actors: Emile Hirsch, Nicholas Elia, Susan Sarandon, Melissa Holroyd
tomatoConsensus: The Wachowski Brothers have overloaded Speed Racer with headache-inducing special effects, and neglected to develop a coherent storyline.

Plot: Morgan Spurlock tours the Middle East to discuss the war on terror with Arabic people.
Title: Where in the World Is Osama Bin Laden?
Actors: Morgan Spurlock, George Bush, Dick Cheney, Daryl Isaacs
tomatoConsensus: Morgan Sprulock's doc offers occasional insights but gets bogged down by the director/subject's gimmicky schtick.

Plot: A look at a few chapters in the life of Poppy, a cheery, colorful, North London schoolteacher whose optimism tends to exasperate those around her.
Title: Happy-Go-Lucky
Actors: Sally Hawkins, Elliot Cowan, Alexis Zegerman, Andrea Riseborough
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 38 wins & 54 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Mike Leigh's latest partially-improvised film is a light-hearted comedy with moments that bite, and features a brilliant star turn by Sally Hawkins.

Plot: Bill Maher's take on the current state of world religion.
Title: Religulous
Actors: Bill Maher, Tal Bachman, Jonathan Boulden, Steve Burg
tomatoConsensus: Religulous is funny and offensive in equal measure, and aims less to change hearts and minds than to inspire conversation.

Plot: An accountant is introduced to a mysterious sex club known as The List by his lawyer friend. But in this new world, he soon becomes the prime suspect in a woman's disappearance and a multi-million dollar heist.
Title: Deception
Actors: Ewan McGregor, Hugh Jackman, Michelle Williams, Bruce Altman
tomatoConsensus: Deception is a middling, predictable potboiler with mediocre dialogue and ludicrous plot twists.

Plot: A successful, single businesswoman who dreams of having a baby discovers she is infertile and hires a working class woman to be her unlikely surrogate.
Title: Baby Mama
Actors: Amy Poehler, Tina Fey, Greg Kinnear, Dax Shepard
tomatoConsensus: Baby Mama is a lightweight, predictable comedy that ekes by on the strength of its performers.

Plot: Ben Stein examines the issue of academic freedom and decides that there is none when it comes to the debate over intelligent design.
Title: Expelled: No Intelligence Allowed
Actors: Ben Stein, Lili Asvar, Peter Atkins, Hector Avalos
tomatoConsensus: Full of patronizing, poorly structured arguments, Expelled is a cynical political stunt in the guise of a documentary.

Plot: Donna's senior prom is supposed to be the best night of her life, though a sadistic killer from her past has different plans for her and her friends.
Title: Prom Night
Actors: Brittany Snow, Scott Porter, Jessica Stroup, Dana Davis
tomatoConsensus: A dim and predictable remake of an already dull slasher film, this Prom Night fails to be memorable.

Plot: After being held captive in an Afghan cave, billionaire engineer Tony Stark creates a unique weaponized suit of armor to fight evil.
Title: Iron Man
Writer: Mark Fergus (screenplay), Hawk Ostby (screenplay), Art Marcum (screenplay), Matt Holloway (screenplay), Stan Lee (characters), Don Heck (characters), Larry Lieber (characters), Jack Kirby (characters)
Actors: Robert Downey Jr., Terrence Howard, Jeff Bridges, Gwyneth Paltrow
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 19 wins & 61 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Director Jon Favreau and star Robert Downey Jr. make this smart, high impact superhero movie one that even non-comics fans can enjoy.

Plot: A guy in love with an engaged woman tries to win her over after she asks him to be her maid of honor.
Title: Made of Honor
Writer: Adam Sztykiel (screenplay), Deborah Kaplan (screenplay), Harry Elfont (screenplay), Adam Sztykiel (story)
Actors: Patrick Dempsey, Michelle Monaghan, Kevin McKidd, Kadeem Hardison
tomatoConsensus: Sharp performances by Patrick Dempsey and Michelle Monaghan can't save this forgettable, formulaic chick flick from its comic failings.

Plot: A fateful event leads to a job in the film business for top mixed-martial arts instructor Mike Terry. Though he refuses to participate in prize bouts, circumstances conspire to force him to consider entering such a competition.
Title: Redbelt
Actors: Max Martini, Matt Cable, Chiwetel Ejiofor, Alice Braga
tomatoConsensus: Mamet's mixed marital arts morality play weaves between action and intellect but doesn't always hit its target.

Plot: A retired CIA agent travels across Europe and relies on his old skills to save his estranged daughter, who has been kidnapped while on a trip to Paris.
Title: Taken
Actors: Liam Neeson, Maggie Grace, Leland Orser, Jon Gries
tomatoConsensus: Taken is undeniably fun with slick action, but is largely a brainless exercise.

Plot: A man and a woman are compelled, for legal reasons, to live life as a couple for a limited period of time. At stake is a large amount of money.
Title: What Happens in Vegas
Actors: Cameron Diaz, Ashton Kutcher, Rob Corddry, Lake Bell
tomatoConsensus: What Happens in Vegas has a few laughs, but mostly settles for derivative romantic comedy conventions and receives little help from a pair of unlikable leads.

Plot: The Pevensie siblings return to Narnia, where they are enlisted to once again help ward off an evil king and restore the rightful heir to the land's throne, Prince Caspian.
Title: The Chronicles of Narnia: Prince Caspian
Writer: Andrew Adamson (screenplay), Christopher Markus (screenplay), Stephen McFeely (screenplay), C.S. Lewis (novel)
Actors: Ben Barnes, Georgie Henley, Skandar Keynes, William Moseley
tomatoConsensus: The Chronicles of Narnia: Prince Caspian is an entertaining family adventure worthy of the standard set by its predecessor.

Plot: A political satire set in Turaqistan, a country occupied by an American private corporation run by a former US Vice-President. In an effort to monopolize the opportunities the war-torn ...
Title: War, Inc.
Writer: Mark Leyner, Jeremy Pikser, John Cusack
Actors: John Cusack, Hilary Duff, Marisa Tomei, Joan Cusack
tomatoConsensus: War, Inc. attempts to satirize the military industrial complex, but more often than not it misses its target.

Plot: Famed archaeologist/adventurer Dr. Henry "Indiana" Jones is called back into action when he becomes entangled in a Soviet plot to uncover the secret behind mysterious artifacts known as the Crystal Skulls.
Title: Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull
Writer: David Koepp (screenplay), George Lucas (story), Jeff Nathanson (story), George Lucas (characters), Philip Kaufman (characters)
Actors: Harrison Ford, Cate Blanchett, Karen Allen, Shia LaBeouf
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 10 wins & 34 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though the plot elements are certainly familiar, Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull still delivers the thrills and Harrison Ford's return in the title role is more than welcome.

Plot: A newly married couple discovers disturbing, ghostly images in photographs they develop after a tragic accident. Fearing the manifestations may be connected, they investigate and learn that some mysteries are better left unsolved.
Title: Shutter
Actors: Joshua Jackson, Rachael Taylor, Megumi Okina, David Denman
tomatoConsensus: Being a remake of a Thai horror film instead of Japanese doesn't prevent Shutter from being another lame Asian horror remake.

Plot: A New York writer on sex and love is finally getting married to her Mr. Big. But her three best girlfriends must console her after one of them inadvertently leads Mr. Big to jilt her.
Title: Sex and the City
Writer: Michael Patrick King, Candace Bushnell (book), Darren Star (television series creator)
Actors: Sarah Jessica Parker, Kim Cattrall, Kristin Davis, Cynthia Nixon
tomatoConsensus: Sex and the City loses steam in the transition to the big screen, but will still thrill fans of the show.

Plot: A young couple staying in an isolated vacation home are terrorized by three unknown assailants.
Title: The Strangers
Actors: Alex Fisher, Peter Clayton-Luce, Scott Speedman, Liv Tyler
tomatoConsensus: The Strangers provides a few scares, but offers little else to distinguish itself from other slasher films.

Plot: An examination of America's win-at-all-cost culture from the perspective of bodybuilding and performance enhancing drugs, as it focuses on a pair of siblings chasing their dream.
Title: Bigger Stronger Faster*
Writer: Chris Bell, Alexander Buono, Tamsin Rawady
Actors: Chris Bell, Hank Aaron, Lyle Alzado, Joshua Amsden
tomatoConsensus: Bigger, Stronger, Faster* is a fascinating, informative, entertaining and especially introspective account of the American 'enhancement' culture.

Plot: The Dragon Warrior has to clash against the savage Tai Lung as China's fate hangs in the balance: However, the Dragon Warrior mantle is supposedly mistaken to be bestowed upon an obese panda who is a tyro in martial arts.
Title: Kung Fu Panda
Writer: Jonathan Aibel (screenplay), Glenn Berger (screenplay), Ethan Reiff (story), Cyrus Voris (story)
Actors: Jack Black, Dustin Hoffman, Angelina Jolie, Ian McShane
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 38 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Kung Fu Panda has a familiar message, but the pleasing mix of humor, swift martial arts action, and colorful animation makes for winning Summer entertainment.

Plot: An Israeli Special Forces Soldier fakes his death so he can re-emerge in New York City as a hair stylist.
Title: You Don't Mess with the Zohan
Writer: Adam Sandler, Robert Smigel, Judd Apatow
Actors: Adam Sandler, John Turturro, Emmanuelle Chriqui, Nick Swardson
tomatoConsensus: You Don't Mess With the Zohan features intermittent laughs, and will please Sandler diehards, but after awhile the leaky premise wears thin.

Plot: Two assistant managers of a corporate grocery store vie for a coveted promotion.
Title: The Promotion
Actors: Seann William Scott, Chris Conrad, Rick Gonzalez, Adrian Martinez
tomatoConsensus: With a workplace-related theme worthy of satire, The Promotion features some sharp witticisms but ultimately disappoints.

Plot: A science teacher, his wife, and a young girl struggle to survive a plague that causes those infected to commit suicide.
Title: The Happening
Actors: Mark Wahlberg, Zooey Deschanel, John Leguizamo, Ashlyn Sanchez
tomatoConsensus: The Happening begins with promise, but unfortunately descends into an incoherent and unconvincing trifle.

Plot: Bruce Banner, a scientist on the run from the U.S. Government, must find a cure for the monster he emerges whenever he loses his temper. However, Banner then must fight a soldier who unleashes himself as a threat stronger than he.
Title: The Incredible Hulk
Actors: Edward Norton, Liv Tyler, Tim Roth, William Hurt
tomatoConsensus: The Incredible Hulk may not be quite the smashing success that fans of Marvel's raging behemoth might hope for, but it offers more than enough big green action to make up for its occasionally puny narrative.

Plot: About young British journalist, George Hogg, who with the assistance of a courageous Australian nurse, saves a group of orphaned children during the Japanese occupation of China in 1937.
Title: The Children of Huang Shi
Actors: Jonathan Rhys Meyers, Radha Mitchell, Yun-Fat Chow, Michelle Yeoh
tomatoConsensus: This beautifully photographed but dramatically flat war drama recounts an important chapter in history with little cinematic freshness.

Plot: In the distant future, a small waste-collecting robot inadvertently embarks on a space journey that will ultimately decide the fate of mankind.
Title: WALL·E
Writer: Andrew Stanton (original story by), Pete Docter (original story by), Andrew Stanton (screenplay), Jim Reardon (screenplay)
Actors: Ben Burtt, Elissa Knight, Jeff Garlin, Fred Willard
tomatoConsensus: Wall-E's stellar visuals testify once again to Pixar's ingenuity, while its charming star will captivate younger viewers -- and its timely story offers thought-provoking subtext.

Plot: A frustrated office worker learns that he is the son of a professional assassin, and that he shares his father's superhuman killing abilities.
Title: Wanted
Writer: Michael Brandt (screenplay), Derek Haas (screenplay), Chris Morgan (screenplay), Michael Brandt (story), Derek Haas (story), Mark Millar (comic book series), J.G. Jones (comic book series)
Actors: James McAvoy, Morgan Freeman, Angelina Jolie, Terence Stamp
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 20 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Wanted is stylish, energetic popcorn fare with witty performances from Angelina Jolie (playing an expert assassin), James McAvoy, and Morgan Freeman that help to distract from its absurdly over-the-top plot.

Plot: Hancock is a superhero whose ill considered behavior regularly causes damage in the millions. He changes when one person he saves helps him improve his public image.
Title: Hancock
Actors: Will Smith, Charlize Theron, Jason Bateman, Jae Head
tomatoConsensus: Though it begins with promise, Hancock suffers from a flimsy narrative and poor execution.

Plot: A highly intellectual but socially awkward spy is tasked with preventing a terrorist attack from a Russian spy agency.
Title: Get Smart
Writer: Tom J. Astle, Matt Ember, Mel Brooks (characters), Buck Henry (characters)
Actors: Steve Carell, Anne Hathaway, Dwayne Johnson, Alan Arkin
tomatoConsensus: Get Smart rides Steve Carell's considerable charm for a few laughs, but in the end is a rather ordinary Summer comedy.

Plot: A television producer with a penchant for drinking and gambling is sent to Las Vegas to convince his troubled niece to enter rehab.
Title: Finding Amanda
Actors: Matthew Broderick, Brittany Snow, Maura Tierney, Peter Facinelli
tomatoConsensus: Despite a charming turn by Matthew Broderick, Finding Amanda is too flimsily executed to succeed as a dark comedy.

Plot: Set in Cincinnati at the height of the Great Depression, Kit Kittredge, a resourceful young girl, helps her mother run a boardinghouse after her father loses his job.
Title: Kit Kittredge: An American Girl
Writer: Ann Peacock, Valerie Tripp (Kit Kittredge stories)
Actors: Abigail Breslin, Julia Ormond, Chris O'Donnell, Jane Krakowski
tomatoConsensus: Refreshingly sweet and sincere, Kit's doll-and-book-inspired do-good mystery may be geared towards the tween girl but will please audiences of all ages.

Plot: A portrait of the late gonzo journalist Hunter S. Thompson.
Title: Gonzo: The Life and Work of Dr. Hunter S. Thompson
Actors: Hunter S. Thompson, Johnny Depp, Joe Cairo, David Carlo
tomatoConsensus: While not the comprehensive profile of the man that his die-hard fans might have hoped for, Gonzo remains an insightful introduction to the life of rebellious writer Hunter S. Thompson and his influences.

Plot: It's the summer of 1994, and the streets of New York are pulsing with hip-hop. Set against this backdrop, a lonely teenager named Luke Shapiro spends his last summer before university selling marijuana throughout New York City, trading it with his unorthodox psychotherapist for treatment, while having a crush on his stepdaughter.
Title: The Wackness
Actors: Ben Kingsley, Josh Peck, Famke Janssen, Olivia Thirlby
tomatoConsensus: Sympathetic characters and a clever script help The Wackness overcome a familiar plot to make for a charming coming-of-age comedy.

Plot: The story of a bride-to-be trying to find her real father told using hit songs by the popular '70s group ABBA.
Title: Mamma Mia!
Actors: Amanda Seyfried, Stellan Skarsgård, Pierce Brosnan, Nancy Baldwin
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 15 wins & 24 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This jukebox musical is full of fluffy fun but rough singing voices and a campy tone might not make you feel like "You Can Dance" the whole 90 minutes.

Plot: On a quest to find out what happened to his missing brother, a scientist, his nephew and their mountain guide discover a fantastic and dangerous lost world in the center of the earth.
Title: Journey to the Center of the Earth
Writer: Michael D. Weiss (screenplay), Jennifer Flackett (screenplay), Mark Levin (screenplay), Jules Verne (novel)
Actors: Brendan Fraser, Josh Hutcherson, Anita Briem, Seth Meyers
tomatoConsensus: Modern visuals and an old fasioned storyline make this family adventure/comedy a fast-paced, kitschy ride.

Plot: A crew of miniature aliens operate a spaceship that has a human form. While trying to save their planet, the aliens encounter a new problem, as their ship becomes smitten with an Earth woman.
Title: Meet Dave
Actors: Eddie Murphy, Elizabeth Banks, Gabrielle Union, Scott Caan
tomatoConsensus: Easy gags and slack direction drag this occasionally clever alien-out-of-planet comedy down to unimaginative lows.

Plot: A Trans-Siberian train journey from China to Moscow becomes a thrilling chase of deception and murder when an American couple encounters a mysterious pair of fellow travelers.
Title: Transsiberian
Actors: Woody Harrelson, Emily Mortimer, Ben Kingsley, Kate Mara
tomatoConsensus: Traditional in form yet effective in execution, this taut thriller updates the "danger on a train" scenario with atmospheric sense.

Plot: Ham III, the grandson of the first chimp astronaut, is blasted off into space by an opportunity-seeking senator. Soon, the fun-loving chimp has to get serious about the mission at hand; ...
Title: Space Chimps
Writer: Kirk De Micco (screenplay), Robert Moreland (screenplay), Kirk De Micco (story), Jason Mayland (additional screenplay material)
Actors: Andy Samberg, Cheryl Hines, Jeff Daniels, Patrick Warburton
tomatoConsensus: Space Chimps' cheap animation and overabundance of monkey puns feels especially dated in a post-Wall-E world.

Plot: Two aimless middle-aged losers still living at home are forced against their will to become roommates when their parents marry.
Title: Step Brothers
Writer: Will Ferrell (screenplay), Adam McKay (screenplay), Will Ferrell (story), Adam McKay (story), John C. Reilly (story)
Actors: Will Ferrell, John C. Reilly, Mary Steenburgen, Richard Jenkins
tomatoConsensus: The relentless immaturity of the humor is not a total handicap for this film, which features the consistently well-matched talents of Will Ferrell and John C. Reilly.

Plot: A poignant story of forbidden love and the loss of innocence set in England prior to the Second World War.
Title: Brideshead Revisited
Writer: Andrew Davies, Jeremy Brock, Evelyn Waugh (novel)
Actors: Matthew Goode, Thomas Morrison, David Barrass, Anna Madeley
tomatoConsensus: Suspenseful and beautifully mounted, Brideshead Revisited does an able job condensing Evelyn Waugh's novel.

Plot: Mulder and Scully are called back to duty by the FBI when a former priest claims to be receiving psychic visions pertaining to a kidnapped agent.
Title: The X Files: I Want to Believe
Writer: Frank Spotnitz, Chris Carter, Chris Carter (television series "The X-Files")
Actors: David Duchovny, Gillian Anderson, Amanda Peet, Billy Connolly
tomatoConsensus: The chemistry between leads David Duchovny and Gillian Anderson do live up to The X-Files' televised legacy, but the roving plot and droning routines make it hard to identify just what we're meant to believe in.

Plot: A documentary on seniors at a high school in a small Indiana town and their various cliques.
Title: American Teen
Actors: Jake Tusing, Megan Krizmanich, Colin Clemens, Mitch Reinholt
tomatoConsensus: American Teen skates some thin ice with its documentary ethics but, in the end, presents a charming and stylish (if packaged) tale.

Plot: A look at tightrope walker Philippe Petit's daring, but illegal, high-wire routine performed between New York City's World Trade Center's twin towers in 1974, what some consider, "the artistic crime of the century."
Title: Man on Wire
Actors: Philippe Petit, Jean François Heckel, Jean-Louis Blondeau, Annie Allix
tomatoConsensus: James Marsh's doc about artist Phililppe Petit's artful caper brings you every ounce of suspense that can be wrung from a man on a (suspended) wire.

Plot: The war in Iraq is the backdrop as the Crosby, Stills, Nash, and Young "Freedom of Speech Tour" crisscrosses North America. Echoes of Vietnam-era anti-war sentiment abound as the band connects with today's audiences.
Title: CSNY/Déjà Vu
Writer: Mike Cerre (documentary written by), Neil Young
Actors: David Crosby, Stephen Stills, Graham Nash, Neil Young
tomatoConsensus: Half concert doc, half political exposition, CSNY: DeJa Vu straddles the old and new slant on politics in music with diligence and not a little self-promotion.

Plot: In the Far East, Alex O'Connell, the son of famed mummy fighters Rick and Evy O'Connell, unearths the mummy of the first Emperor of Qin -- a shape-shifting entity cursed by a witch centuries ago.
Title: The Mummy: Tomb of the Dragon Emperor
Actors: Brendan Fraser, Jet Li, Maria Bello, John Hannah
tomatoConsensus: With middling CG effects and a distinct lack of fun, The Mummy: Tomb of the Dragon Emperor finds the series past its prime.

Plot: In a remarkable turn-of-events, the result of the presidential election comes down to one man's vote.
Title: Swing Vote
Actors: Kevin Costner, Madeline Carroll, Paula Patton, Kelsey Grammer
tomatoConsensus: Despite Kevin Costner providing his most charismatic performance in years, Swing Vote fails to find the right mix of political satire and heartfelt drama.

Plot: A photographer, Leon's obsessive pursuit of dark subject matter leads him into the path of a serial killer, Mahogany, the subway murderer who stalks late night commuters, ultimately butchering them in the most gruesome ways imaginable.
Title: The Midnight Meat Train
Writer: Jeff Buhler (screenplay), Clive Barker (short story "The Midnight Meat Train")
Actors: Bradley Cooper, Leslie Bibb, Brooke Shields, Vinnie Jones
tomatoConsensus: A creative and energetic adaptation of a Clive Barker short story, with enough scares and thrills to be a potential cult classic.

Plot: Takes place in the days before Christmas near a little-known border crossing on the Mohawk reservation between New York State and Quebec. Here, the lure of fast money from smuggling ...
Title: Frozen River
Actors: Melissa Leo, Misty Upham, Charlie McDermott, Michael O'Keefe
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 32 wins & 37 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Veteran character actress Melissa Leo delivers a stunning performance in this powerful -- if grim -- indie film.

Plot: The story of the early days of California wine making featuring the now infamous, blind Paris wine tasting of 1976 that has come to be known as "Judgment of Paris".
Title: Bottle Shock
Writer: Jody Savin (screenplay), Randall Miller (screenplay), Ross Schwartz (screenplay), Ross Schwartz (story), Lannette Pabon (story), Jody Savin (story), Randall Miller (story)
Actors: Chris Pine, Hal B. Klein, Alan Rickman, Jean-Michel Richaud
tomatoConsensus: Bottle Shock fails to properly utilize the inspiring true tale at its core, settling instead for an ordinary, plodding account.

Plot: Two girlfriends on a summer holiday in Spain become enamored with the same painter, unaware that his ex-wife, with whom he has a tempestuous relationship, is about to re-enter the picture.
Title: Vicky Cristina Barcelona
Actors: Rebecca Hall, Scarlett Johansson, Christopher Evan Welch, Chris Messina
tomatoConsensus: A beguiling tragicomedy, Vicky Cristina Barcelona charms with beautiful views of the Spanish city and a marvelously well-matched cast.

Plot: Carmen Lowell is working on the backstage of a play at Yale. When the lead actress, her friend Julia, invites her to Vermont with her to work on a play with a professional cast, she decides...
Title: The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants 2
Actors: Amber Tamblyn, Alexis Bledel, America Ferrera, Blake Lively
tomatoConsensus: The workable chemistry among the four leads combined with the enriching message make for a winning Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants 2.

Plot: Two rival bikers gangs, the Victors and the Six-Six-Six's, refuel their decades-old rivalry.
Title: Hell Ride
Actors: Julia Jones, Larry Bishop, Leonor Varela, Austin Galuppo
tomatoConsensus: Hell Ride misses out on the rusting zeitgeist of the biker genre, sucking the glee from a saucy premise.

Plot: Cultural critic David Kepesh finds his life -- which he indicates is a state of "emancipated manhood" -- thrown into tragic disarray by Consuela Castillo, a well-mannered student who awakens a sense of sexual possessiveness in her teacher.
Title: Elegy
Actors: Penélope Cruz, Ben Kingsley, Dennis Hopper, Patricia Clarkson
tomatoConsensus: An intelligent, adult, and provocative Philip Roth adaptation that features classy performances, Elegy is never quite the sum of its parts.

Plot: Through a series of freak occurrences, a group of actors shooting a big-budget war movie are forced to become the soldiers they are portraying.
Title: Tropic Thunder
Writer: Justin Theroux (screenplay), Ben Stiller (screenplay), Etan Cohen (screenplay), Ben Stiller (story), Justin Theroux (story)
Actors: Jeff Kahn, Robert Downey Jr., Anthony Ruivivar, Jack Black
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 39 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: With biting satire, plenty of subversive humor, and an unforgettable turn by Robert Downey, Jr., Tropic Thunder is a triumphant late Summer comedy.

Plot: Anakin Skywalker and Ahsoka Tano must rescue the kidnapped son of Jabba the Hutt, but political intrigue complicates their mission.
Title: Star Wars: The Clone Wars
Writer: Henry Gilroy, Steven Melching, Scott Murphy, George Lucas (characters and universe)
Actors: Matt Lanter, Ashley Eckstein, James Arnold Taylor, Dee Bradley Baker
tomatoConsensus: Mechanical animation and a less-than stellar script make The Clone Wars a pale shadow of George Lucas' once great franchise.

Plot: Henry Poole moves in to a house in his old neighborhood, to spend what he believes are his remaining days alone. The discovery of a "miracle" by a nosy neighbor ruptures his solitude and restores his faith in life.
Title: Henry Poole Is Here
Actors: Luke Wilson, Radha Mitchell, Adriana Barraza, George Lopez
tomatoConsensus: Full of Hallmark-truisms and pop songs presented with strained significance, this comic foible intends less to convert than to preach to the choir.

Plot: An Israeli film director interviews fellow veterans of the 1982 invasion of Lebanon to reconstruct his own memories of his term of service in that conflict.
Title: Waltz with Bashir
Country: Israel, France, Germany, USA, Finland, Switzerland, Belgium, Australia
Actors: Ari Folman, Ori Sivan, Ronny Dayag, Shmuel Frenkel
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 43 wins & 56 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A wholly innovative, original, and vital history lesson, with pioneering animation, Waltz With Bashir delivers its message about the Middle East in a mesmerizing fashion.

Plot: In this irreverent comedy, a failed actor-turned-worse-high-school-drama-teacher rallies his Tucson, AZ students as he conceives and stages politically incorrect musical sequel to Shakespeare's Hamlet.
Title: Hamlet 2
Actors: Steve Coogan, Catherine Keener, Joseph Julian Soria, Skylar Astin
tomatoConsensus: The script's biting premise and Steve Coogan's endearing, off-the-handle performance make Hamlet 2 an hysterical -- if slightly painful -- ride.

Plot: Ex-con Jensen Ames is forced by the warden of a notorious prison to compete in our post-industrial world's most popular sport: a car race in which inmates must brutalize and kill one another on the road to victory.
Title: Death Race
Writer: Paul W.S. Anderson (screenplay), Paul W.S. Anderson (screen story), Robert Thom, Charles B. Griffith, Ib Melchior
Actors: Jason Statham, Joan Allen, Ian McShane, Tyrese Gibson
tomatoConsensus: Mindless, violent, and lightning-paced, Death Race is little more than an empty action romp.

Plot: After Playboy bunny Shelley is kicked out of the playboy mansion, she finds a job as the house mother for a sorority full of socially awkward girls.
Title: The House Bunny
Actors: Anna Faris, Colin Hanks, Emma Stone, Kat Dennings
tomatoConsensus: Anna Faris is game, but she can't salvage this middling, formulaic comedy.

Plot: The true story of Jasmine Plummer who, at the age of eleven, became the first female to play in Pop Warner football tournament in its 56-year history.
Title: The Longshots
Actors: Ice Cube, Keke Palmer, Tasha Smith, Jill Marie Jones
tomatoConsensus: The Longshots means well, but it's a largely formulaic affair, rarely deviating from the inspirational sports movie playbook.

Plot: The Rocker tells the story of a failed drummer who is given a second chance at fame. Robert "Fish" Fishman is the extremely dedicated and astoundingly passionate drummer for the eighties ...
Title: The Rocker
Writer: Maya Forbes (screenplay), Wallace Wolodarsky (screenplay), Ryan Jaffe (story)
Actors: Rainn Wilson, Christina Applegate, Teddy Geiger, Josh Gad
tomatoConsensus: With a predictable and lightweight story, the earnest efforts of the cast are squandered by The Rocker's bland script.

Plot: Few are aware that America may be on the brink of a financial meltdown. I.O.U.S.A. explores the country's shocking current fiscal condition and ways to avoid a national economic disaster.
Title: I.O.U.S.A.
Writer: Patrick Creadon, Christine O'Malley, Addison Wiggin (story), Addison Wiggin, Kate Incontrera (story), William Bonner (book)
Actors: Robert Bixby, Humphrey Bogart, Warren Buffett, George Bush
tomatoConsensus: A potent and lithely constructed documentary about America's financial crisis, I.O.U.S.A grabs you with figures but holds you with irreverent wit.

Plot: An ex-cop and his family are the target of an evil force that is using mirrors as a gateway into their home.
Title: Mirrors
Writer: Alexandre Aja (screenplay), Grégory Levasseur (screenplay), Sung-ho Kim (Korean motion picture "Into the Mirror")
Actors: Kiefer Sutherland, Paula Patton, Cameron Boyce, Erica Gluck
tomatoConsensus: Inconsistency and listless plot make this K-horror remake a less-than-frightening time at the movies.

Plot: Three young houseflies stow away aboard the Apollo 11 flight to the moon.
Title: Fly Me to the Moon 3D
Actors: Christopher Lloyd, Kelly Ripa, Nicollette Sheridan, Tim Curry
tomatoConsensus: Flatly animated and indifferently scripted, Fly Me To the Moon offers little for audiences not comprised of very young children.

Plot: A disk containing the memoirs of a CIA agent ends up in the hands of two unscrupulous gym employees who attempt to sell it.
Title: Burn After Reading
Actors: George Clooney, Frances McDormand, Brad Pitt, John Malkovich
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 5 wins & 26 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: With Burn After Reading, the Coen Brothers have crafted another clever comedy/thriller with an outlandish plot and memorable characters.

Plot: Over the course of one evening, an unsuspecting group of twenty-somethings find themselves bombarded by a series of natural disasters and catastrophic events.
Title: Disaster Movie
Actors: Matt Lanter, Vanessa Lachey, Gary 'G. Thang' Johnson, Nicole Parker
tomatoConsensus: Returning to their seemingly bottomless well of flatulence humor, racial stereotypes, and stale pop culture gags, Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer have produced what is arguably their worst Movie yet.

Plot: Veteran-turned-mercenary Toorop takes the high-risk job of escorting a woman from Russia to America. Little does he know that she is host to an organism that a cult wants to harvest in order to produce a genetically modified Messiah.
Title: Babylon A.D.
Writer: Maurice G. Dantec (novel), Mathieu Kassovitz (screenplay), Éric Besnard (scenario and dialogue), Joseph Simas (screenplay)
Actors: Vin Diesel, Michelle Yeoh, Mélanie Thierry, Lambert Wilson
tomatoConsensus: A poorly constructed, derivative sci-fi stinker with a weak script and poor action sequences.

Plot: When straight arrow FBI agent Roy Clayton heads up the investigation into a dangerous international conspiracy, all clues seem to lead back to former U.S. Special Operations officer, Samir Horn.
Title: Traitor
Writer: Jeffrey Nachmanoff (screenplay), Steve Martin (story), Jeffrey Nachmanoff (story)
Actors: Don Cheadle, Guy Pearce, Saïd Taghmaoui, Neal McDonough
tomatoConsensus: Despite another reliable performance from Don Cheadle, Traitor suffers from too many cliches and an unfocused narrative.

Plot: A wild weekend is in store for three high school seniors who visit a local college campus as prospective freshmen.
Title: College
Actors: Drake Bell, Andrew Caldwell, Andree Moss, Carolyn Moss
tomatoConsensus: A pale imitation of the raunchy frat comedies of old, College aims low and misses.

Plot: A redemptive tale of an aspiring rap artist surviving failed levees and her own troubled past and seizing a chance for a new beginning.
Title: Trouble the Water
Actors: Michael Brown, George W. Bush, Julie Chen, Ray Nagin
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 13 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This incredible documentary displays the tragedy and mismanagement of Katrina along with the heroism of strangers and survivors.

Plot: A wealthy New Yorker wrestles with the decision to leave her cheating husband, as she and her friends discover that women really can have it all.
Title: The Women
Writer: Diane English (screenplay), Clare Boothe Luce (play), Anita Loos, Jane Murfin
Actors: Meg Ryan, Annette Bening, Eva Mendes, Debra Messing
tomatoConsensus: The Women is a toothless remake of the 1939 classic, lacking the charm, wit and compelling protagonists of the original.

Plot: Rookie cop Denny Colt returns from the beyond as The Spirit, a hero whose mission is to fight against the bad forces in Central City.
Title: The Spirit
Writer: Frank Miller (screenplay), Will Eisner (comic book series)
Actors: Jaime King, Gabriel Macht, Dan Gerrity, Arthur the Cat
tomatoConsensus: Though its visuals are unique, The Spirit's plot is almost incomprehensible, the dialogue is ludicrously mannered, and the characters are unmemorable.

Plot: A drama with a two-tiered storyline concerning a mother and daughter who try to form a bond after the young woman's difficult childhood.
Title: The Burning Plain
Actors: Charlize Theron, John Corbett, José María Yazpik, Robin Tunney
tomatoConsensus: This heavily symbolic, melodramatic multi-narrative drama lacks emotional resonance.

Plot: A hitman who's in Bangkok to pull off a series of jobs violates his personal code when he falls for a local woman and bonds with his errand boy.
Title: Bangkok Dangerous
Writer: Jason Richman (screenplay), Oxide Chun Pang, Danny Pang
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Shahkrit Yamnarm, Charlie Yeung, Panward Hemmanee
tomatoConsensus: With murky cinematography, a meandering pace, a dull storyline, and rather wooden performances, The Pang Brothers' Hollywood remake of Bangkok Dangerous is unsuccessful.

Plot: Two veteran New York City detectives work on a case of serial executions of criminals who escaped justice.
Title: Righteous Kill
Actors: Robert De Niro, Al Pacino, 50 Cent, Carla Gugino
tomatoConsensus: Al Pacino and Robert De Niro do their best to elevate this dowdy genre exercise, but even these two greats can't resuscitate the film's hackneyed script.

Plot: A LAPD officer will stop at nothing to force out the interracial couple who just moved in next door.
Title: Lakeview Terrace
Writer: David Loughery (screenplay), Howard Korder (screenplay), David Loughery (story)
Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Patrick Wilson, Kerry Washington, Ron Glass
tomatoConsensus: This thriller about a menacing cop wreaking havoc on his neighbors is tense enough but threatens absurdity when it enters into excessive potboiler territory.

Plot: Bertram Pincus is a man whose people skills leave much to be desired. When Pincus dies unexpectedly, but is miraculously revived after seven minutes, he wakes up to discover that he now has the annoying ability to see ghosts.
Title: Ghost Town
Actors: Greg Kinnear, Jordan Carlos, Dequina Moore, Joseph Badalucco Jr.
tomatoConsensus: Ricky Gervais' consistently sharp performance and beautifully dry execution transform this otherwise mainstream comedy into an endearing, funny, and altogether snappy romantic comedy. With ghosts.

Plot: Two friends hired to police a small town that is suffering under the rule of a rancher find their job complicated by the arrival of a young widow.
Title: Appaloosa
Writer: Robert Knott (screenplay), Ed Harris (screenplay), Robert B. Parker (novel)
Actors: Robert Jauregui, Jeremy Irons, Timothy V. Murphy, Luce Rains
tomatoConsensus: A traditional genre western, Appaloosa sets itself apart with smart psychology, an intriguing love triangle, and good chemistry between the leads.

Plot: Set in 1944 Italy, the story of four black American soldiers who get trapped in a Tuscan village during WWII.
Title: Miracle at St. Anna
Actors: Derek Luke, Michael Ealy, Laz Alonso, Omar Benson Miller
tomatoConsensus: Miracle at St. Anna is a well-intentioned but overlong, disjointed affair that hits few of the right notes.

Plot: Jerry and Rachel are two strangers thrown together by a mysterious phone call from a woman they have never met. Threatening their lives and family, she pushes Jerry and Rachel into a series of increasingly dangerous situations, using the technology of everyday life to track and control their every move.
Title: Eagle Eye
Writer: John Glenn (screenplay), Travis Wright (screenplay), Hillary Seitz (screenplay), Dan McDermott (screenplay), Dan McDermott (story)
Actors: Shia LaBeouf, Michelle Monaghan, Rosario Dawson, Michael Chiklis
tomatoConsensus: Eagle Eye is a preposterously plotted thriller that borrows heavily from other superior films.

Title: How to Lose Friends & Alienate People
Actors: Kelan Pannell, Janette Scott, Simon Pegg, Megan Fox
tomatoConsensus: A decent performance from Pegg in a disappointing film. Neither sharp nor satirical, Weide's adaptation relies too heavily on slapstick, and misses the point of the source material in the process.

Plot: A doctor who is traveling to see his estranged son sparks with an unhappily married woman at a North Carolina inn.
Title: Nights in Rodanthe
Writer: Ann Peacock (screenplay), John Romano (screenplay), Nicholas Sparks (novel)
Actors: Richard Gere, Diane Lane, Christopher Meloni, Viola Davis
tomatoConsensus: Derivative and schmaltzy, Nicholas Sparks' Nights in Rodanthe is strongly mottled by contrivances that even the charisma of stars Diane Lane and Richard Gere can't repair.

Plot: High school student Nick O'Leary, member of the Queercore band The Jerk Offs, meets college-bound Norah Silverberg when she asks him to be her boyfriend for five minutes.
Title: Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist
Writer: Lorene Scafaria (screenplay), Rachel Cohn (novel), David Levithan (novel)
Actors: Michael Cera, Kat Dennings, Aaron Yoo, Rafi Gavron
tomatoConsensus: Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist combines a pair of charming leads, the classic New York backdrop, and a sweet soundtrack.

Plot: A chronicle of the life of 18th century aristocrat Georgiana, Duchess of Devonshire, who was reviled for her extravagant political and personal life.
Title: The Duchess
Writer: Jeffrey Hatcher (screenplay), Anders Thomas Jensen (screenplay), Saul Dibb (screenplay), Amanda Foreman (book)
Actors: Keira Knightley, Ralph Fiennes, Charlotte Rampling, Dominic Cooper
tomatoConsensus: While The Duchess treads the now-familiar terrain of the corset-ripper, the costumes look great and Keira Knightley's performance is stellar in this subtly feminist, period drama.

Title: Rachel Getting Married
Actors: Sebastian Stan, Roslyn Ruff, Anne Hathaway, Bill Irwin
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 31 wins & 59 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Rachel Getting Married is an engrossing tale of family angst, highlighted by Anne Hathaway's powerful performance and director Jonathan Demme's return to form.

Plot: A CIA agent on the ground in Jordan hunts down a powerful terrorist leader while being caught between the unclear intentions of his American supervisors and Jordan Intelligence.
Title: Body of Lies
Actors: Leonardo DiCaprio, Russell Crowe, Mark Strong, Golshifteh Farahani
tomatoConsensus: Body of Lies relies on the performances of Russell Crowe and Leonardo DiCaprio to elevate it beyond the conventional espionage thriller.

Plot: For generations, the people of the City of Ember have flourished in an amazing world of glittering lights. But Ember's once powerful generator is failing ... and the great lamps that illuminate the city are starting to flicker.
Title: City of Ember
Actors: Saoirse Ronan, David Ryall, Harry Treadaway, Mary Kay Place
tomatoConsensus: City of Ember is visually arresting, and boasts a superb cast, but is sadly lacking in both action and adventure.

Plot: Coming together to solve a series of murders in New York City are a police detective whose family was slain as part of a conspiracy and an assassin out to avenge her sister's death. The duo will be hunted by the police, the mob, and a ruthless corporation.
Title: Max Payne
Writer: Beau Thorne (screenplay), Sam Lake (video game by Remedy Entertainment and 3-D Realms Entertainment)
Actors: Mark Wahlberg, Mila Kunis, Beau Bridges, Ludacris
tomatoConsensus: While it boasts some stylish action, Max Payne suffers severely from an illogical plot and overdirection.

Plot: Lifelong platonic friends Zack and Miri look to solve their respective cash-flow problems by making an adult film together. As the cameras roll, however, the duo begin to sense that they may have more feelings for each other than they previously thought.
Title: Zack and Miri Make a Porno
Actors: Elizabeth Banks, Seth Rogen, Craig Robinson, Gerry Bednob
tomatoConsensus: Zack and Miri Make a Porno is a modest success for Kevin Smith, due in large part to the charm of Seth Rogen and Elizabeth Banks.

Plot: A chronicle of the life and presidency of George W. Bush.
Title: W.
Country: USA, Australia, Hong Kong, Switzerland, China
Actors: Josh Brolin, Colin Hanks, Toby Jones, Dennis Boutsikaris
tomatoConsensus: A surprisingly sympathetic portrayal of the 43rd American president, W. is fascinating in spots, but merely rudimentary as a whole.

Plot: Tank faces the ultimate test of friendship when his best friend hires him to take his ex-girlfriend out on a lousy date in order to make her realize how great her former boyfriend is.
Title: My Best Friend's Girl
Actors: Dane Cook, Kate Hudson, Alec Baldwin, Jason Biggs
tomatoConsensus: My Best Friend's Girl spends too much time being vulgar and offensive, leaving little room for laughs.

Plot: A theatre director struggles with his work, and the women in his life, as he creates a life-size replica of New York City inside a warehouse as part of his new play.
Title: Synecdoche, New York
Actors: Philip Seymour Hoffman, Catherine Keener, Sadie Goldstein, Tom Noonan
tomatoConsensus: Charlie Kaufman's ambitious directorial debut occasionally strains to connect, but ultimately provides fascinating insight into a writer's mind.

Plot: Set in South Carolina in 1964, this is the tale of Lily Owens, a 14 year-old girl who is haunted by the memory of her late mother. To escape her lonely life and troubled relationship with ...
Title: The Secret Life of Bees
Actors: Dakota Fanning, Queen Latifah, Jennifer Hudson, Alicia Keys
tomatoConsensus: The Secret Life of Bees has moments of charm, but is largely too maudlin and sticky-sweet.

Plot: Robert Kearns takes on the Detroit automakers who he claims stole his idea for the intermittent windshield wiper.
Title: Flash of Genius
Actors: Greg Kinnear, Tim Eddis, Warren Belle, Karl Pruner
tomatoConsensus: The touching underdog story of a single guy against a massive corporation, Flash of Genius is a well-paced and well-written tale with a standout performance by star Greg Kinnear.

Plot: An anti-American filmmaker who's out to abolish the July Fourth holiday is visited by three ghosts who try to change his perception of the country.
Title: An American Carol
Writer: David Zucker, Myrna Sokoloff, Lewis Friedman
Actors: Trace Adkins, Brandon Alter, Chriss Anglin, Geoffrey Arend
tomatoConsensus: An American Carol suffers not so much from its perceived political bias, but from the fact that it simply is not very funny.

Plot: Two families from different walks of life learn to work together.
Title: The Family That Preys
Actors: Alfre Woodard, Sanaa Lathan, Rockmond Dunbar, KaDee Strickland
tomatoConsensus: Tyler Perry's The Family that Preys treads the filmmaker's established terrain of family loyalty and moral uprightness, though the occasionally predictable plot slides forward, aided by an excess of soapy melodrama.

Plot: A television reporter and her cameraman are trapped inside a building quarantined by the CDC, after the outbreak of a mysterious virus which turns humans into bloodthirsty killers.
Title: Quarantine
Writer: John Erick Dowdle (screenplay), Drew Dowdle (screenplay), Jaume Balagueró (motion picture "Rec"), Luiso Berdejo (motion picture "Rec"), Paco Plaza (motion picture "Rec")
Actors: Jennifer Carpenter, Steve Harris, Jay Hernandez, Johnathon Schaech
tomatoConsensus: Quarantine uses effective atmosphere and consistent scares to stand above the crop of recent horror films.

Plot: A family's moral codes are tested when Ray Tierney investigates a case that reveals an incendiary police corruption scandal involving his own brother-in-law. For Ray, the truth is revelatory, a Pandora's Box that threatens to upend not only the Tierney legacy but the entire NYPD.
Title: Pride and Glory
Writer: Joe Carnahan (screenplay), Gavin O'Connor (screenplay), Gavin O'Connor (story), Greg O'Connor (story), Robert Hopes (story)
Actors: Colin Farrell, Edward Norton, Jon Voight, Noah Emmerich
tomatoConsensus: Formulaic in its plotting and cliched in its dialogue, Pride and Glory does little to distinguish itself from other police procedurals.

Plot: A drama based on the life of college football hero Ernie Davis, the first African-American to win the Heisman Trophy.
Title: The Express
Actors: Rob Brown, Dennis Quaid, Darrin Dewitt Henson, Omar Benson Miller
tomatoConsensus: This inspirational sports biopic set in the the civil rights era is interesting even for non-football fans, and features a great performance by Dennis Quaid as tough-but-fair football coach.

Plot: In London, a real-estate scam puts millions of pounds up for grabs, attracting some of the city's scrappiest tough guys and its more established underworld types, all of whom are looking to get rich quick. While the city's seasoned criminals vie for the cash, an unexpected player -- a drugged out rock 'n' roller presumed to be dead but very much alive -- has a multi-million dollar prize fall into...
Title: RocknRolla
Actors: Gerard Butler, Tom Wilkinson, Thandie Newton, Mark Strong
tomatoConsensus: Mixed reviews for Guy Ritchie's return to his London-based cockney wideboy gangster movie roots, but most agree, it's a step in the right direction following two major turkeys.

Plot: As seniors in high school, Troy and Gabriella struggle with the idea of being separated from one another as college approaches. Along with the rest of the Wildcats, they stage a spring musical to address their experiences, hopes and fears about their future.
Title: High School Musical 3: Senior Year
Actors: Zac Efron, Vanessa Hudgens, Ashley Tisdale, Lucas Grabeel
tomatoConsensus: It won't win many converts, but High School Musical 3 is bright, energetic, and well-crafted.

Plot: The animals try to fly back to New York City, but crash-land on an African wildlife refuge, where Alex is reunited with his parents.
Title: Madagascar: Escape 2 Africa
Writer: Etan Cohen, Eric Darnell, Tom McGrath
Actors: Ben Stiller, Chris Rock, David Schwimmer, Jada Pinkett Smith
tomatoConsensus: Madagascar: Escape 2 Africa is an improvement on the original, with more fleshed-out characters, crisper animation and more consistent humor.

Plot: A city is ravaged by an epidemic of instant white blindness.
Title: Blindness
Actors: Yûsuke Iseya, Jason Bermingham, Eduardo Semerjian, Don McKellar
tomatoConsensus: This allegorical disaster film about society's reaction to mass blindness is mottled and self-satisfied; provocative but not as interesting as its premise implies.

Plot: A grief-stricken mother takes on the LAPD to her own detriment when it stubbornly tries to pass off an obvious impostor as her missing child, while also refusing to give up hope that she will find him one day.
Title: Changeling
Actors: Angelina Jolie, Gattlin Griffith, Michelle Gunn, Michael Kelly
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 13 wins & 47 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Beautifully shot and well-acted, Changeling is a compelling story that unfortunately gives in to convention too often.

Plot: A Mumbai teen reflects on his upbringing in the slums when he is accused of cheating on the Indian Version of "Who Wants to be a Millionaire?"
Title: Slumdog Millionaire
Actors: Dev Patel, Saurabh Shukla, Anil Kapoor, Rajendranath Zutshi
tomatoConsensus: Visually dazzling and emotionally resonant, Slumdog Millionaire is a film that's both entertaining and powerful.

Plot: James Bond descends into mystery as he tries to stop a mysterious organization from eliminating a country's most valuable resource. All the while, he still tries to seek revenge over the death of his love.
Language: English, Spanish, Italian, French, Swiss German, German
Title: Quantum of Solace
Writer: Paul Haggis, Neal Purvis, Robert Wade
Actors: Daniel Craig, Olga Kurylenko, Mathieu Amalric, Judi Dench
Awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 4 wins & 29 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Brutal and breathless, Quantum Of Solace delivers tender emotions along with frenetic action, but coming on the heels of Casino Royale, it's still a bit of a disappointment.

Plot: Wild behavior forces a pair of energy drink reps to enroll in a Big Brother program.
Title: Role Models
Writer: Timothy Dowling (story), W. Blake Herron (story), Paul Rudd (screenplay), David Wain (screenplay), Ken Marino (screenplay), Timothy Dowling (screenplay)
Actors: Seann William Scott, Paul Rudd, Christopher Mintz-Plasse, Bobb'e J. Thompson
tomatoConsensus: Role Models is a frequently crude, always funny comedy with the cast providing solid work throughout.

Plot: A cinematic triptych of three Tokyo-set stories.
Title: Tokyo!
Writer: Gabrielle Bell (graphic novel "Cecil and Jordan in New York"), Joon-ho Bong, Leos Carax, Michel Gondry
Director: Joon-ho Bong, Leos Carax, Michel Gondry
Actors: Ayako Fujitani, Ryô Kase, Ayumi Itô, Nao Ohmori
tomatoConsensus: An imaginative, if uneven, love letter to a city that signals a great creative enterprise by its three contributing directors.

Plot: Jean-Claude Van Damme gets involved in a bank robbery with hostages situation and reflects about his life during it.
Title: JCVD
Writer: Mabrouk El Mechri (scenario), Frédéric Benudis (in collaboration with), Mabrouk El Mechri (adaptation), Frédéric Taddeï (original idea), Vincent Ravalec (original idea), Christophe Turpin
Actors: Jean-Claude Van Damme, Valérie Bodson, Hervé Sogne, Rock Chen
tomatoConsensus: JCVD is a touching, fascinating piece, with Jean-Claude Van Damme confounding all with his heartfelt performance.

Plot: Following Jigsaw's grisly demise, Mark Hoffman is commended as a hero, but Agent Strahm is suspicious, and delves into Hoffman's past. Meanwhile, another group of strangers are put through a series of gruesome tests.
Title: Saw V
Actors: Tobin Bell, Costas Mandylor, Scott Patterson, Betsy Russell
tomatoConsensus: If its plot were as interesting as its torture devices, or its violence less painful than its performances, perhaps Saw V might not feel like it was running on fumes.

Plot: A high school senior drives cross-country with his best friends to hook up with a babe he met online.
Title: Sex Drive
Writer: Sean Anders (screenplay), John Morris (screenplay), Andy Behrens (book)
Actors: Josh Zuckerman, Amanda Crew, Clark Duke, James Marsden
tomatoConsensus: Sex Drive has some hilarious moments and is well made for a raunchy teen film, but will appeal to few beyond that demographic.

Plot: Though it's been some twenty years since they have spoken with one another, two estranged soul-singing legends agree to participate in a reunion performance at the Apollo Theater to honor their recently deceased band leader.
Title: Soul Men
Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Bernie Mac, Sharon Leal, Adam Herschman
tomatoConsensus: Soul Men features lively performances from Bernie Mac and Samuel L. Jackson and some hilarious moments, but ultimately suffers from an unoriginal script.

Plot: While on vacation in Mexico, Chloe, a ritzy Beverly Hills chihuahua, finds herself lost and in need of assistance in order to get back home.
Title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
Writer: Analisa LaBianco (screenplay), Jeffrey Bushell (screenplay), Jeffrey Bushell (story)
Actors: Piper Perabo, Manolo Cardona, Jamie Lee Curtis, José María Yazpik
tomatoConsensus: Despite hitting some sweet notes, Beverly Hills Chihuahua is little more than disposable family entertainment.

Plot: Set in northern Australia before World War II, an English aristocrat who inherits a sprawling ranch reluctantly pacts with a stock-man in order to protect her new property from a takeover plot. As the pair drive 2,000 head of cattle over unforgiving landscape, they experience the bombing of Darwin, Australia, by Japanese forces firsthand.
Title: Australia
Writer: Stuart Beattie (screenplay), Baz Luhrmann (screenplay), Ronald Harwood (screenplay), Richard Flanagan (screenplay), Baz Luhrmann (story)
Actors: Shea Adams, Eddie Baroo, Ray Barrett, Tony Barry
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 33 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Built on lavish vistas and impeccable production, Australia is unfortunately burdened with thinly drawn characters and a lack of originality.

Plot: The canine star of a fictional sci-fi/action show that believes his powers are real embarks on a cross country trek to save his co-star from a threat he believes is just as real.
Title: Bolt
Actors: John Travolta, Miley Cyrus, Susie Essman, Mark Walton
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 28 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Bolt is a pleasant animated comedy that overcomes the story's familiarity with strong visuals and likable characters.

Plot: The story of Harvey Milk, and his struggles as an American gay activist who fought for gay rights and became California's first openly gay elected official.
Title: Milk
Actors: Sean Penn, Emile Hirsch, Josh Brolin, Diego Luna
tomatoConsensus: Anchored by Sean Penn's powerhouse performance, Milk is a triumphant account of America's first openly gay man elected to public office.

Plot: A teenage girl risks everything when she falls in love with a vampire.
Title: Twilight
Actors: Kristen Stewart, Sarah Clarke, Matt Bushell, Billy Burke
tomatoConsensus: Having lost much of its bite transitioning to the big screen, Twilight will please its devoted fans, but do little for the uninitiated.

Plot: Frank Martin puts the driving gloves on to deliver Valentina, the kidnapped daughter of a Ukranian government official, from Marseilles to Odessa on the Black Sea. En route, he has to contend with thugs who want to intercept Valentina's safe delivery and not let his personal feelings get in the way of his dangerous objective.
Title: Transporter 3
Writer: Luc Besson, Robert Mark Kamen, Luc Besson (characters), Robert Mark Kamen (characters)
Actors: Jason Statham, Natalya Rudakova, François Berléand, Robert Knepper
tomatoConsensus: This middling installment in the Transporter franchise is a few steps down from its predecessors, featuring generic stunts and a lack of energy.

Plot: A couple struggles to visit all four of their divorced parents on Christmas.
Title: Four Christmases
Writer: Matt Allen (screenplay), Caleb Wilson (screenplay), Jon Lucas (screenplay), Scott Moore (screenplay), Matt Allen (story), Caleb Wilson (story)
Actors: Vince Vaughn, Reese Witherspoon, Robert Duvall, Sissy Spacek
tomatoConsensus: Despite a strong cast, this sour holiday comedy suffers from a hackneyed script.

Plot: Set during WWII, a story seen through the innocent eyes of Bruno, the eight-year-old son of the commandant at a German concentration camp, whose forbidden friendship with a Jewish boy on the other side of the camp fence has startling and unexpected consequences.
Title: The Boy in the Striped Pajamas
Actors: Asa Butterfield, Zac Mattoon O'Brien, Domonkos Németh, Henry Kingsmill
tomatoConsensus: A touching and haunting family film that deals with the Holocaust in an arresting and unusual manner, and packs a brutal final punch of a twist.

Plot: Animated fable about a cliché hunchbacked evil scientist's assistant who aspires to become a scientist himself, much to the displeasure of the rest of the evil science community.
Title: Igor
Writer: Chris McKenna, John Hoffman (additional screenplay), Anthony Leondis (additional screenplay), Dimitri Toscas (additional screenplay)
Actors: John Cusack, Myleene Klass, Robin Walsh, Matt McKenna
tomatoConsensus: With an animation style that apes Tim Burton, and a slew of cultural references that aren't clear enough to reach the crowds, Igor's patched together antics make it hard to see who the film is trying to please.

Plot: Chronicles the rise of Chess Records and its recording artists.
Title: Cadillac Records
Actors: Joshua Alscher, Tim Bellow, Tony Bentley, Tammy Blanchard
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 7 wins & 19 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: What Cadillac Records may lack in originality, it more than makes up for in strong performances and soul-stirring music.

Plot: After hunting down and killing hundreds of violent criminals, Frank Castle, aka The Punisher, faces his most deadly foe yet: Jigsaw.
Title: Punisher: War Zone
Writer: Nick Santora, Art Marcum, Matt Holloway
Actors: Ray Stevenson, Dominic West, Doug Hutchison, Colin Salmon
tomatoConsensus: Punisher: War Zone recalls the excessively violent, dialogue-challenged actioners of the 1980s, and coincidentally feels two decades out of date.

Plot: A remake of the 1951 classic sci-fi film about an alien visitor and his giant robot counterpart who visit Earth.
Title: The Day the Earth Stood Still
Actors: Keanu Reeves, Jennifer Connelly, Kathy Bates, Jaden Smith
tomatoConsensus: Heavy on special effects, but without a coherent story at its base, The Day the Earth Stood Still is subpar re-imagining of the 1951 science-fiction classic.

Plot: In 1956, Ernesto 'Che' Guevara and a band of Castro-led Cuban exiles mobilize an army to topple the regime of dictator Fulgencio Batista.
Title: Che: Part One
Writer: Peter Buchman (screenplay), Ernesto 'Che' Guevara (memoir "Reminiscences of the Cuban Revolutionary War")
Actors: Julia Ormond, Benicio Del Toro, Oscar Isaac, Pablo Guevara
tomatoConsensus: Though lengthy and at times plodding, Soderbergh's vision and Benicio Del Toro's understated performance ensure that Che always fascinates.

Plot: In 1967, Ernesto 'Che' Guevara leads a small partisan army to fight an ill-fated revolutionary guerrilla war in Bolivia, South America.
Title: Che: Part Two
Writer: Peter Buchman (screenplay), Benjamin A. van der Veen (screenplay), Ernesto 'Che' Guevara (Bolivian Diary)
Actors: Demián Bichir, Rodrigo Santoro, Benicio Del Toro, Catalina Sandino Moreno
tomatoConsensus: The second part of Soderbergh's biopic is a dark, hypnotic and sometimes frustrating portrait of a warrior in decline, with a terrific central performance from Del Toro.

Plot: A Puerto Rican family living in the area of Humboldt Park in west Chicago face what may be their last Christmas together.
Title: Nothing Like the Holidays
Writer: Alison Swan (screenplay), Rick Najera (screenplay), Robert Teitel (story), Rene M. Rigal (story)
Actors: Alfred Molina, Elizabeth Peña, Freddy Rodríguez, Luis Guzmán
tomatoConsensus: The performances are the strength of Nothing Like the Holidays, a rather ordinary holiday comedy with a latin twist.

Plot: A Catholic school principal questions a priest's ambiguous relationship with a troubled young student.
Title: Doubt
Writer: John Patrick Shanley (screenplay), John Patrick Shanley (play)
Actors: Meryl Streep, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Amy Adams, Viola Davis
Awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 26 wins & 88 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Doubt succeeds on the strength of its top-notch cast, who successfully guide the film through the occasional narrative lull.

Plot: Disgruntled Korean War veteran Walt Kowalski sets out to reform his neighbor, a Hmong teenager who tried to steal Kowalski's prized possession: a 1972 Gran Torino.
Title: Gran Torino
Writer: Nick Schenk (screenplay), Dave Johannson (story), Nick Schenk (story)
Actors: Clint Eastwood, Christopher Carley, Bee Vang, Ahney Her
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 20 wins & 17 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though a minor entry in Eastwood's body of work, Gran Torino is nevertheless a humorous, touching, and intriguing old-school parable.

Plot: A dramatic retelling of the post-Watergate television interviews between British talk-show host David Frost and former president Richard Nixon.
Title: Frost/Nixon
Actors: Frank Langella, Michael Sheen, Sam Rockwell, Kevin Bacon
Awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 21 wins & 72 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Frost/Nixon is weighty and eloquent; a cross between a boxing match and a ballet with Oscar worthy performances.

Plot: Post-WWII Germany: Nearly a decade after his affair with an older woman came to a mysterious end, law student Michael Berg re-encounters his former lover as she defends herself in a war-crime trial.
Title: The Reader
Actors: Ralph Fiennes, David Kross, Jeanette Hain, Kate Winslet
tomatoConsensus: Despite Kate Winslet's superb portrayal, The Reader suggests an emotionally distant, Oscar-baiting historical drama.

Plot: Delgo, an adventurous but naive teenager, must rally his group of friends to protect their world from conflict between the Lockni and Nohrin people.
Title: Delgo
Writer: Patrick J. Cowan (screenplay), Carl Dream (screenplay), Jennifer Jones-Mitchell (screenplay), Marc F. Adler (story), Scott Biear (story), Jason Maurer (story)
Actors: Freddie Prinze Jr., Chris Kattan, Jennifer Love Hewitt, Anne Bancroft
tomatoConsensus: Delgo features a blend of plot elements from earlier (and superior) fantasy films, with weaker animation and dull characters.

Plot: A woman struggles to interact with her family and find her place in society after spending fifteen years in prison.
Title: I've Loved You So Long
Actors: Kristin Scott Thomas, Elsa Zylberstein, Serge Hazanavicius, Laurent Grévill
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 14 wins & 27 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: I've Loved You So Long is a sublimely acted family drama as well as a noteworthy directorial debut from Phillipe Claudel.

Plot: A man with a fateful secret embarks on an extraordinary journey of redemption by forever changing the lives of seven strangers.
Title: Seven Pounds
Actors: Will Smith, Rosario Dawson, Woody Harrelson, Michael Ealy
tomatoConsensus: Grim and morose, Seven Pounds is also undone by an illogical plot.

Plot: A faded professional wrestler must retire, but finds his quest for a new life outside the ring a dispiriting struggle.
Title: The Wrestler
Actors: Mickey Rourke, Marisa Tomei, Evan Rachel Wood, Mark Margolis
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 56 wins & 83 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Mickey Rourke gives a performance for the ages in The Wrestler, a richly affecting, heart-wrenching yet ultimately rewarding drama.

Plot: Tells the story of Benjamin Button, a man who starts aging backwards with bizarre consequences.
Title: The Curious Case of Benjamin Button
Writer: Eric Roth (screenplay), Eric Roth (story), Robin Swicord (story), F. Scott Fitzgerald (short story)
Actors: Cate Blanchett, Brad Pitt, Julia Ormond, Faune Chambers Watkins
tomatoConsensus: Curious Case of Benjamin Button is an epic fantasy tale with rich storytelling backed by fantastic performances.

Plot: A guy challenges himself to say "yes" to everything for an entire year.
Title: Yes Man
Writer: Nicholas Stoller (screenplay), Jarrad Paul (screenplay), Andrew Mogel (screenplay), Danny Wallace (book)
Actors: Jim Carrey, Zooey Deschanel, Bradley Cooper, John Michael Higgins
tomatoConsensus: Jim Carrey's comic convulsions are the only bright spots in this otherwise dim and predictable comedy.

Plot: A dramatization of the 20 July assassination and political coup plot by desperate renegade German Army officers against Hitler during World War II.
Title: Valkyrie
Actors: Tom Cruise, Kenneth Branagh, Bill Nighy, Tom Wilkinson
tomatoConsensus: Given the subject matter, Valkyrie could have been an outstanding historical thriller, but settles for being a mildly entertaining, but disposable yarn.

Plot: A hotel handyman's life changes when the lavish bedtime stories he tells his niece and nephew start to magically come true.
Title: Bedtime Stories
Writer: Matt Lopez (screenplay), Tim Herlihy (screenplay), Matt Lopez (story)
Actors: Adam Sandler, Keri Russell, Guy Pearce, Russell Brand
tomatoConsensus: Though it may earns some chuckles from pre-teens, this kid-friendly Adam Sandler comedy is uneven, poorly paced, and lacks the requisite whimsy to truly work.

Plot: A sex-addicted con-man pays for his mother's hospital bills by playing on the sympathies of those who rescue him from choking to death.
Title: Choke
Actors: Kathryn Alexander, Teodorina Bello, Kate Blumberg, Jonah Bobo
tomatoConsensus: While bolstered by strong performances from Sam Rockwell and Anjelica Huston, Choke struggles to capture the tone of Chuck Palahniuk's novel.

Plot: A young couple living in a Connecticut suburb during the mid-1950s struggle to come to terms with their personal problems while trying to raise their two children.
Title: Revolutionary Road
Actors: Kate Winslet, Leonardo DiCaprio, Christopher Fitzgerald, Jonathan Roumie
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 19 wins & 62 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Brilliantly acted and emotionally powerful, Revolutionary Road is a handsome adaptation of Richard Yates' celebrated novel.

Plot: Jewish brothers in Nazi-occupied Eastern Europe escape into the Belarussian forests, where they join Russian resistance fighters and endeavor to build a village in order to protect themselves and about 1,000 Jewish non-combatants.
Title: Defiance
Writer: Clayton Frohman (screenplay), Edward Zwick (screenplay), Nechama Tec (book)
Actors: Daniel Craig, Liev Schreiber, Jamie Bell, Alexa Davalos
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Professionally made but artistically uninspired, Ed Zwick's story of Jews surviving WWII in the Belarus forest lacks the emotional punch of the actual history.

Plot: A family learns important life lessons from their adorable, but naughty and neurotic dog.
Title: Marley & Me
Writer: Scott Frank (screenplay), Don Roos (screenplay), John Grogan (book)
Actors: Owen Wilson, Jennifer Aniston, Eric Dane, Kathleen Turner
tomatoConsensus: Pet owners should love it, but Marley and Me is only sporadically successful in wringing drama and laughs from its scenario.

Plot: Over the summer, a series of unfortunate happening triggers a financial crisis for a young woman and she soon finds her life falling apart.
Title: Wendy and Lucy
Writer: Jonathan Raymond, Jonathan Raymond (story "Night Choir"), Kelly Reichardt
Actors: Michelle Williams, Lucy, David Koppell, Max Clement
tomatoConsensus: Michelle Williams gives a heartbreaking performance in Wendy and Lucy, a timely portrait of loneliness and struggle.

Plot: In London for his daughter's wedding, a rumpled man finds his romantic spirits lifted by a new woman in his life.
Title: Last Chance Harvey
Actors: Dustin Hoffman, Emma Thompson, Eileen Atkins, Kathy Baker
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.
tomatoConsensus: Last Chance Harvey is an above-average story that graduates to potent romantic drama based on the chemistry and charm of its top-notch performers.

Plot: When you are so small, even for a mouse, the world can be a dangerous place, but when your heart is brave, nothing can stand against your dreams.
Title: The Tale of Despereaux
Writer: Kate DiCamillo (book), Will McRobb (screen story), Gary Ross, Chris Viscardi (screen story)
Actors: Matthew Broderick, Dustin Hoffman, Emma Watson, Tracey Ullman
tomatoConsensus: Despite its striking visuals, The Tale of Despereaux as a story feels familiar and unimaginative.

Plot: The story of french gangster Jacques Mesrine, before he was called Public Enemy N°1.
Title: Mesrine Part 1: Killer Instinct
Writer: Jacques Mesrine (book), Abdel Raouf Dafri (scenario), Abdel Raouf Dafri (adaptation), Jean-François Richet (adaptation)
Actors: Vincent Cassel, Cécile De France, Gérard Depardieu, Gilles Lellouche
tomatoConsensus: It's undeniably uneven, but Vincent Cassel's electrifying performance makes Mesrine: Killer Instinct a gangster biopic worth seeking out.

Plot: A young girl discovers her father has an amazing talent to bring characters out of their books and must try to stop a freed villain from destroying them all, with the help of her father, her aunt, and a storybook's hero.
Title: Inkheart
Actors: Brendan Fraser, Sienna Guillory, Eliza Bennett, Richard Strange
tomatoConsensus: Heavy on cliches and light on charm, this kid-lit fantasy-adventure doesn't quite get off the ground.

Plot: During the reign of the Vikings, Kainan, a man from a far-off world, crash lands on Earth, bringing with him an alien predator known as the Moorwen. Though both man and monster are seeking revenge for violence committed against them, Kainan leads the alliance to kill the Moorwen by fusing his advanced technology with the Viking's Iron Age weaponry.
Title: Outlander
Actors: Jim Caviezel, Sophia Myles, Jack Huston, John Hurt
tomatoConsensus: Schizophrenic in subject and lackluster in execution, Outlander might have trouble finding the cult audience for which it was built.

Plot: A Brooklyn-set romantic drama about a bachelor torn between the family friend his parents wish he would marry and his beautiful but volatile new neighbor.
Title: Two Lovers
Actors: Joaquin Phoenix, Anne Joyce, Elliot Villar, Craig Walker
tomatoConsensus: Two Lovers is a complex, intriguing, richly-acted romantic drama

Plot: The Taylor family is devastated by an accident that takes place on the day their matriarch is due to graduate from college -- decades after leaving to raise her children.
Title: Fireflies in the Garden
Actors: Ryan Reynolds, Willem Dafoe, Emily Watson, Carrie-Anne Moss
tomatoConsensus: Despite boasting a stellar cast, Fireflies in the Garden is just tedious, dull and predictable melodrama. Instantly forgettable.

Plot: The story of Italian politician Giulio Andreotti, who has served as Prime Minister of Italy seven times since the restoration of democracy in 1946.
Title: Il Divo
Actors: Toni Servillo, Anna Bonaiuto, Giulio Bosetti, Flavio Bucci
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 30 wins & 36 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: While the web of corruption in this Italian political thriller can be hard for a non-native to follow, the visuals and the intrigue are compelling and thrilling in equal measure.

Plot: Dominican baseball star Miguel "Sugar" Santos is recruited to play in the U.S. minor-leagues.
Title: Sugar
Actors: Jose Rijo, Walki Cuevas, Algenis Perez Soto, Santo Silvestre
tomatoConsensus: Sugar is an exceptionally-crafted film -- part sports flick, part immigrant tale -- with touching and poignant drama highlighted by splendid performances.

Plot: In order to raise the tuition to send her young son to private school, a mom starts an unusual business -- a biohazard removal/crime scene clean-up service -- with her unreliable sister.
Title: Sunshine Cleaning
Actors: Amy Adams, Emily Blunt, Alan Arkin, Jason Spevack
tomatoConsensus: Despite a sometimes overly familiar plot, Sunshine Cleaning benefits from the lively performances of its two stars.

Plot: A look at Germany's terrorist group, The Red Army Faction (RAF), which organized bombings, robberies, kidnappings and assassinations in the late 1960s and '70s.
Title: The Baader Meinhof Complex
Writer: Bernd Eichinger (screenplay), Uli Edel (screenplay), Stefan Aust (book)
Actors: Martina Gedeck, Moritz Bleibtreu, Johanna Wokalek, Nadja Uhl
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 20 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Intricately researched and impressively authentic slice of modern German History, with a terrific cast, assured direction, and a cracking script.

Plot: A man's life begins to unravel when his mistress brings him a bag of cash.
Title: The Square
Writer: Joel Edgerton, Matthew Dabner, Joel Edgerton (original story)
Actors: David Roberts, Claire van der Boom, Peter Phelps, Bill Hunter
tomatoConsensus: The Square may not quite live up to the modern noir classics that inspired it, but with twists and tension to spare, it comes admirably close.

Plot: Since 1978, Anvil has become one of heavy metal's most influential yet commercially unsuccessful acts. In 2006, after a fledging European tour Anvil sets out to record their thirteenth album and continue to follow their dreams.
Title: Anvil: The Story of Anvil
Actors: Scott Ian, Lemmy, Malcolm Dome, Lars Ulrich
tomatoConsensus: A touching, uplifting and inspirational rockumentary about an aging metal band, both hilarious and heart-warming in equal measure.

Plot: The story revolves around three soldiers - Colee, TK and Cheever - who return from the war after suffering injuries and learn that life has moved on without them. They end up on an ...
Title: The Lucky Ones
Actors: Rachel McAdams, Tim Robbins, Michael Peña, Molly Hagan
tomatoConsensus: The Lucky Ones features heartfelt performances, but is undone by the plot's overwrought parade of coincidence and contrivance.

Plot: A young man, much to the chagrin of his father, becomes the new assistant to an illusionist in decline.
Title: The Great Buck Howard
Actors: John Malkovich, Colin Hanks, Emily Blunt, Ricky Jay
tomatoConsensus: By turns fluffy and biting, this show biz comedy is given girth by comic heavyweight John Malkovich and made all the more charming by Emily Blunt.

Plot: After Rudi's wife Trudi suddenly dies, he travels to Japan to fulfill her dream of being a Butoh dancer.
Title: Cherry Blossoms
Actors: Elmar Wepper, Hannelore Elsner, Aya Irizuki, Maximilian Brückner
tomatoConsensus: This mature and eloquent meditation on grief and loss sports measured performances and moments of humor.

Plot: A woman leaves an abusive relationship to begin a new life in a new city, where she forms an unlikely and ironic relationship with a suicidal hit man (unbeknownst to her). Enter a worn, ...
Title: The Merry Gentleman
Actors: Michael Keaton, Kelly Macdonald, Tom Bastounes, Kareem Bandealy
tomatoConsensus: Michael Keaton's directorial debut, The Merry Gentleman, is a slow character study aided greatly by the performances of Keaton and Kelly MacDonald.

Plot: A traveling art saleswoman tries to shake off a flaky motel manager who falls for her and won't leave her alone.
Title: Management
Actors: Jennifer Aniston, Steve Zahn, Margo Martindale, Fred Ward
tomatoConsensus: Clever and often beguiling performances by Steve Zahn and Jennifer Aniston can't revive this sweetly misguided stalker romance.

Plot: Follows the plight of real-life dancers as they struggle through auditions for the Broadway revival of "A Chorus Line". Also investigates the history of the show and the creative minds behind the original and current incarnations.
Title: Every Little Step
Director: Adam Del Deo, James D. Stern
Actors: German Alexander, Bob Avian, Justin Bellero, Michael Bennett
tomatoConsensus: Fascinating and insightful, Every Little Step is a thoroughly engrossing behind the scenes look at Broadway performers.

Plot: The Brothers Bloom are the best con men in the world, swindling millionaires with complex scenarios of lust and intrigue. Now they've decided to take on one last job - showing a beautiful and eccentric heiress the time of her life with a romantic adventure that takes them around the world.
Title: The Brothers Bloom
Actors: Rachel Weisz, Adrien Brody, Mark Ruffalo, Rinko Kikuchi
tomatoConsensus: Despite strong performances The Brothers Bloom ultimately does not fulfill its lofty ambitions.

Plot: A young Englishman marries a glamorous American. When he brings her home to meet the parents, she arrives like a blast from the future - blowing their entrenched British stuffiness out the window.
Title: Easy Virtue
Writer: Stephan Elliott, Sheridan Jobbins, Noël Coward (play)
Actors: Jessica Biel, Ben Barnes, Kristin Scott Thomas, Colin Firth
tomatoConsensus: A lightweight and pithy Noel Coward adaptation with plenty of sparkle and fizz.

Plot: Two brothers and a sister witness the disappearance of their childhood memories when they must relinquish the family belongings to ensure their deceased mother's succession.
Title: Summer Hours
Actors: Juliette Binoche, Charles Berling, Jérémie Renier, Edith Scob
tomatoConsensus: Olivier Assayas' contemplative family drama handles lofty ideas about art and culture with elegance and lightness.

Plot: A single mother struggles to clear her name after being wrongly accused and arrested for dealing drugs in an impoverished town in Texas.
Title: American Violet
Actors: Nicole Beharie, Tim Blake Nelson, Will Patton, Michael O'Keefe
tomatoConsensus: Though its politics are as obvious as its outcome, American Violet is an earnest docudrama about the justice system with a powerful performance from Nicole Behairie.

Title: The Stoning of Soraya M.
Writer: Betsy Giffen Nowrasteh (screenplay), Cyrus Nowrasteh (screenplay), Freidoune Sahebjam (book)
Actors: Shohreh Aghdashloo, Mozhan Marnò, Jim Caviezel, Navid Negahban
tomatoConsensus: The Stoning of Soraya M. nearly transcends its deficiencies through the sheer strength of its subject material, but ultimately drowns out its message with an inappropriately heavy-handed approach.

Title: Tyson
Actors: Mills Lane, Mike Tyson, Trevor Berbick, Cus D'Amato
