tomatoConsensus: A fascinating, emotional, and frank confessional from Iron Mike that sheds a sympathetic light on one of boxing's most controversial icons.

Plot: During the Iraq War, a Sergeant recently assigned to an army bomb squad is put at odds with his squad mates due to his maverick way of handling his work.
Title: The Hurt Locker
Actors: Jeremy Renner, Anthony Mackie, Brian Geraghty, Guy Pearce
tomatoConsensus: A well-acted, intensely shot, action filled war epic, Kathryn Bigelow's The Hurt Locker is thus far the best of the recent dramatizations of the Iraq War.

Plot: A single mom takes her family to Georgia for the funeral of her father -- a man she never met. There, her clan is introduced to the crass, fun-loving Brown family.
Title: Meet the Browns
Actors: Tyler Perry, David Mann, Tamela J. Mann, Angela Bassett
tomatoConsensus: Angela Bassett's considerable charms can't compensate for Meet the Browns' incessant melodrama and scattered narrative threads.

Plot: Molly Hartley looks to put her troubled past behind her with a fresh start at a new school, where she sparks with one of the most popular students. But can her secrets stay buried, ...
Title: The Haunting of Molly Hartley
Actors: Haley Bennett, Jake Weber, Chace Crawford, Shannon Woodward
tomatoConsensus: The Haunting of Molly Hartley is a rather lifeless horror endeavor, with a pedestrian plot and few scares.

Plot: For his French-class assignment, a high school student weaves his family history in a news story involving terrorism, and goes on to invite an Internet audience in on the resulting controversy.
Title: Adoration
Actors: Devon Bostick, Rachel Blanchard, Louca Tassone, Kenneth Welsh
tomatoConsensus: A complex and thought-provoking work, Atom Egoyan's Adoration works well as both mystery and engaging drama.

Plot: A young man who was sentenced to seven years in prison for robbing a post office ends up spending three decades in solitary confinement. During this time, his own personality is supplanted by his alter-ego, Charles Bronson.
Title: Bronson
Writer: Brock Norman Brock (screenplay), Nicolas Winding Refn (screenplay)
Actors: Tom Hardy, Kelly Adams, Luing Andrews, Katy Barker
tomatoConsensus: Undeniably gripping, Bronson forces the viewer to make some hard decisions about where the line between art and exploitation lies.

Plot: A documentary on the electric guitar from the point of view of three significant rock musicians: the Edge, Jimmy Page and Jack White.
Title: It Might Get Loud
Actors: Jimmy Page, The Edge, Jack White, Link Wray
tomatoConsensus: An affectionate tribute to rock's most distinctive instrument, It Might Get Loud is insightful and musically satisfying.

Plot: Two men form an unlikely friendship that will change both of their lives forever.
Title: Goodbye Solo
Actors: Souleymane Sy Savane, Red West, Diana Franco Galindo, Lane 'Roc' Williams
tomatoConsensus: An original and thoughtful human drama, Goodbye Solo looks at relationships and loneliness while proving director Ramin Bahrani's is an important American voice.

Plot: A look at the life of legendary fashion designer Valentino.
Title: Valentino: The Last Emperor
Actors: Valentino Garavani, Giancarlo Giammetti, Nati Abascal, Giorgio Armani
tomatoConsensus: Valentino: the Last Emperor utilizes its access to the fashion icon to the fullest, and the result is a glitzy, dishy, and insightful documentary.

Plot: An unflattering look inside America's corporate controlled food industry.
Title: Food, Inc.
Writer: Robert Kenner, Elise Pearlstein, Kim Roberts
Actors: Eric Schlosser, Richard Lobb, Vince Edwards, Carole Morison
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 19 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: An eye-opening expose of the modern food industry, Food, Inc. is both fascinating and terrifying, and essential viewing for any health-conscious citizen.

Plot: Several love stories set in one of the most loved cities of the world, New York.
Title: New York, I Love You
Writer: Hu Hong (segment), Yao Meng (segment), Israel Horovitz (adaptation), Suketu Mehta (segment), Shunji Iwai (segment), Israel Horovitz (adaptation), Olivier Lécot (segment), Jeff Nathanson (segment), Xan Cassavetes (segment), Stephen Winter (segment), Anthony Minghella (segment), Natalie Portman (segment), Fatih Akin (segment), Joshua Marston (segment), Hall Powell (transitions "Randy Balsmeyer"), Israel Horovitz (transitions "Randy Balsmeyer"), James C. Strouse (transitions "Randy Balsmeyer"), Emmanuel Benbihy (concept)
Director: Fatih Akin, Yvan Attal, Randall Balsmeyer, Allen Hughes, Shunji Iwai, Wen Jiang, Shekhar Kapur, Joshua Marston, Mira Nair, Natalie Portman, Brett Ratner
Actors: Hayden Christensen, Andy Garcia, Rachel Bilson, Natalie Portman
tomatoConsensus: Like many anthologies, New York, I Love You has problems of consistency, but it isn't without its moments.

Plot: Set in 1980s seaside England, this is the story of Edward, an unusual ten year old boy growing up in an old people's home run by his parents. Whilst his mother struggles to keep the family ...
Title: Is Anybody There?
Actors: Bill Milner, Anne-Marie Duff, Ralph Riach, Linzey Cocker
tomatoConsensus: Though Michael Caine gives an excellent performance, Is Anybody There? features a cliche-filled story that ultimately falters.

Plot: The story of a Palestinian widow who must defend her lemontree field when a new Israeli Defense Minister moves next to her and threatens to have her lemon grove torn down.
Title: Lemon Tree
Actors: Hiam Abbass, Rona Lipaz-Michael, Ali Suliman, Doron Tavory
tomatoConsensus: A positive and personal Israeli film that offers an understated and thought-provoking vision of the West Bank troubles.

Plot: The near future. Like tomorrow. In a world marked by closed borders, corporate warriors, and a global computer network, three strangers risk their lives to connect, break through the barriers of technology, and unseal their fates.
Title: Sleep Dealer
Writer: Alex Rivera (screenplay), David Riker (screenplay), Alex Rivera (story)
Actors: Luis Fernando Peña, Metztli Adamina, José Concepción Macías, Tenoch Huerta
tomatoConsensus: Sleep Dealer's depth and energy are almost enough to overcome a shaky screenplay and pedestrian acting.

Title: Me and Orson Welles
Writer: Robert Kaplow (based on the novel by), Holly Gent Palmo (screenplay), Vincent Palmo Jr. (screenplay)
Actors: Christian McKay, Zac Efron, Zoe Kazan, Megan Maczko
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 5 wins & 25 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Me and Orson Welles boasts a breakout performance by Christian McKay and an infectious love of the backstage drama that overcomes its sometimes fluffy tone.

Plot: This documentary follows NBA superstar LeBron James and four of his talented teammates through the trials and tribulations of high school basketball in Ohio and James' journey to fame.
Title: More Than a Game
Actors: LeBron James, Dru Joyce, Romeo Travis, Sian Cotton
tomatoConsensus: Though the film may not delve as deep as some would prefer, More Than a Game is an inspiring documentary featuring likable youngsters, a positive message, and some exciting in-game footage.

Plot: Based on Michael Chabon's novel, the film chronicles the defining summer of a recent college graduate who crosses his gangster father and explores love, sexuality, and the enigmas surrounding his life and his city.
Title: The Mysteries of Pittsburgh
Actors: Jon Foster, Peter Sarsgaard, Sienna Miller, Nick Nolte
tomatoConsensus: A listless interpretation of Michael Chabon's first novel, Mysteries of Pittsburgh features none of the source material's charm, but has coming-of-age film cliches in abundance.

Plot: About the young life and loves of artist Salvador Dalí, filmmaker Luis Buñuel and writer Federico García Lorca.
Title: Little Ashes
Actors: Javier Beltrán, Robert Pattinson, Matthew McNulty, Marina Gatell
tomatoConsensus: It has a beautiful cast, but Little Ashes suffers from an uneven tone and a surplus of unintentionally silly moments.

Plot: A road trip through Louisiana transforms three strangers who were originally brought together by their respective feelings of loneliness.
Title: The Yellow Handkerchief
Actors: William Hurt, Maria Bello, Kristen Stewart, Eddie Redmayne
tomatoConsensus: Small and intimate -- occasionally to a fault -- The Yellow Handkerchief rises above its overly familiar ingredients thanks to riveting performances from William Hurt and Kristen Stewart.

Plot: Two kids, Dylan and Kylie, run away from home at Christmas and spend a night of magic and terror on the streets of inner-city Dublin.
Title: Kisses
Actors: Kelly O'Neill, Shane Curry, Paul Roe, Roy Dempsey
tomatoConsensus: Although admittedly sleight, this gritty but tender coming-of-age Irish drama features some impressive work both in front, and behind the camera.

Plot: In the Nazi-occupied Netherlands, a teenage boy gets involved in the Dutch Resistance after coming to the aid of a wounded RAF pilot.
Title: Winter in Wartime
Writer: Mieke de Jong (screenplay), Martin Koolhoven (screenplay), Paul Jan Nelissen (screenplay), Jan Terlouw (novel)
Actors: Martijn Lakemeier, Yorick van Wageningen, Jamie Campbell Bower, Raymond Thiry
tomatoConsensus: A gripping, handsomely shot World War II melodrama with thriller elements successfully mixed in.

Plot: Film-maker Kate Churchill is determined to prove that yoga can transform anyone. Nick Rosen is skeptical but agrees to be her guinea pig. Kate immerses Nick in yoga, and follows him around ...
Title: Enlighten Up!
Actors: Norman Allen, Alan Finger, Sharon Gannon, B.K.S. Iyengar
tomatoConsensus: Enlighten Up! is a funny, warmhearted documentary that's uneven in spots, but thought-provoking nonetheless.

Plot: A celebration of the musical work of a group of session musicians known as "The Wrecking Crew", a band that provided back-up instrumentals to such legendary recording artists as Frank Sinatra, The Beach Boys and Bing Crosby.
Title: The Wrecking Crew!
Actors: Denny Tedesco, Brian Wilson, Dick Clark, Cher
tomatoConsensus: The Wrecking Crew may not achieve the greatness of the many classic songs its subjects helped bring to life, but it remains a heartfelt, overdue tribute to overshadowed brilliance.

Plot: In 1985 where former superheroes exist, the murder of a colleague sends active vigilante Rorschach into his own sprawling investigation, uncovering something that could completely change the course of history as we know it.
Title: Watchmen
Writer: David Hayter (screenplay), Alex Tse (screenplay), Dave Gibbons (graphic novel illustrator)
Actors: Malin Akerman, Billy Crudup, Matthew Goode, Jackie Earle Haley
tomatoConsensus: Gritty and visually striking, Watchmen is a faithful adaptation of Alan Moore's graphic novel, but its complex narrative structure may make it difficult for it to appeal to viewers not already familiar with the source material.

Plot: In a dangerous post-apocalyptic world, an ailing father defends his son as they slowly travel to the sea.
Title: The Road
Actors: Viggo Mortensen, Kodi Smit-McPhee, Robert Duvall, Guy Pearce
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 5 wins & 30 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Road's commitment to Cormac McCarthy's dark vision may prove too unyielding for some, but the film benefits from hauntingly powerful performances from Viggo Mortensen and Kodi McPhee.

Plot: Two best friends become rivals when they schedule their respective weddings on the same day.
Title: Bride Wars
Writer: Greg DePaul (screenplay), Casey Wilson (screenplay), June Diane Raphael (screenplay), Greg DePaul (story)
Actors: Kate Hudson, Anne Hathaway, Bryan Greenberg, Chris Pratt
tomatoConsensus: Bride Wars takes the already wearisome concept of battling bridezillas, and makes it thoroughly insufferable via a lazy script and wholly detestable characters.

Plot: Tom returns to his hometown on the tenth anniversary of the Valentine's night massacre that claimed the lives of 22 people. Instead of a homecoming, Tom finds himself suspected of committing the murders, and it seems like his old flame is the only one that believes he's innocent.
Title: My Bloody Valentine
Writer: Todd Farmer (screenplay), Zane Smith (screenplay), John Beaird, Stephen A. Miller
Actors: Jensen Ackles, Jaime King, Kerr Smith, Betsy Rue
tomatoConsensus: This gory, senses-assaulting slasher film is an unpretentious, effective mix of old-school horror stylings and modern 3D technology.

Plot: Two young Americans with special abilities must race to find a girl in Hong Kong before a shadowy government organization called Division does.

Plot: An Interpol agent attempts to expose a high-profile financial institution's role in an international arms dealing ring.

Plot: When seasoned comedian George Simmons learns of his terminal, inoperable health condition, his desire to form a genuine friendship causes him to take a relatively green performer under his wing as his opening act.

Plot: When a teenager, Chun-Li witnesses the kidnapping of her father by wealthy crime lord M. Bison. When she grows up, she goes into a quest for vengeance and becomes the famous crime-fighter of the Street Fighter universe.

Plot: Mischievous grandma Madea lands in jail, where she meets a variety of mixed-up characters.

Plot: Insp. Jacques Clouseau teams up with a squad of International detectives who are just as bumbling as he is. Their mission: Stop a globe-trotting thief who specializes in stealing historical artifacts.

Plot: M.I.T. professor John Koestler links a mysterious list of numbers from a time capsule to past and future disasters and sets out to prevent the ultimate catastrophe.

Plot: A journalist is aided in his search for a woman who has been missing -- or dead -- for forty years by a young female hacker.

Plot: A grieving couple retreat to their cabin in the woods, hoping to repair their broken hearts and troubled marriage. But nature takes its course and things go from bad to worse.

Plot: A pushy boss forces her young assistant to marry her in order to keep her visa status in the U.S. and avoid deportation to Canada.

Plot: The story of a mysterious loner, a stranger in the process of completing a criminal job.

Plot: A middle-aged, misanthropic divorcée from New York City surprisingly enters a fulfilling, Pygmalion-type relationship with a much younger, unsophisticated Southern girl.

Plot: Used-car liquidator Don Ready is hired by a flailing auto dealership to turn their Fourth of July sale into a majorly profitable event.

Plot: Adam, a lonely man with Asperger's Syndrome, develops a relationship with his upstairs neighbor, Beth.

Plot: A Chicago librarian has a gene that causes him to involuntarily time travel, creating complications in his marriage.
Title: The Time Traveler's Wife
Actors: Michelle Nolden, Alex Ferris, Arliss Howard, Eric Bana
tomatoConsensus: Though it may satisfy fans of the novel, The Time Traveler's Wife's plot contrivances and illogical narrative hamper its big screen effectiveness.

Plot: A new kid in town assembles a fledgling rock band -- together, they achieve their dreams and compete against the best in the biggest event of the year, a battle of the bands.

Plot: Bennie travels to Buenos Aires to find his long-missing older brother, a once-promising writer who is now a remnant of his former self. Bennie's discovery of his brother's near-finished play might hold the answer to understanding their shared past and renewing their bond.

Plot: A rag doll that awakens in a postapocalyptic future holds the key to humanity's salvation.

Plot: A reporter in Iraq might just have the story of a lifetime when he meets Lyn Cassady, a guy who claims to be a former member of the U.S. Army's New Earth Army, a unit that employs paranormal powers in their missions.

Plot: A drama centered on the trials and tribulations of a proud Palestinian Christian immigrant single mother and her teenage son in small town Indiana.

Plot: Larry Gopnik, a Midwestern physics teacher, watches his life unravel over multiple sudden incidents. Though seeking meaning and answers amidst his turmoils, he seems to keep sinking.

Plot: A documentary chronicling Vogue editor-in-chief Anna Wintour's preparations for the 2007 fall-fashion issue.

Plot: A group of sorority sisters try to cover up the death of their house-sister after a prank gone wrong, only to be stalked by a serial killer.

Plot: U.S. Marshal Carrie Stetko tracks a killer in Antarctica, as the sun is about to set for six months.

Plot: A coming-of-age story about a teenage girl in 1960s suburban London, and how her life changes with the arrival of a playboy nearly twice her age.

Plot: The story of Coco Chanel's rise from obscure beginnings to the heights of the fashion world.

tomatoConsensus: Though it doesn't quite capture the complexity of its subject's life, Coco Avant Chanel remains a fascinating, appropriately lovely tribute.

Plot: A comedy centered around four couples who settle into a tropical-island resort for a vacation. While one of the couples is there to work on the marriage, the others fail to realize that participation in the resort's therapy sessions is not optional.

Actors: Vince Vaughn, Jason Bateman, Faizon Love, Jon Favreau
tomatoConsensus: Despite a talented cast and some reliably pleasant interplay between Jon Favreau and Vince Vaughn, Couples Retreat leaves viewers stranded in an arid, mirthless comedy.

Plot: Convinced that a CCN cameraman is her true love, an eccentric crossword puzzler trails him as he travels all over the country, hoping to convince him that they belong together.

Plot: Yearning for escape and adventure, a young boy runs away from home and sails to an island filled with creatures that take him in as their king.

Plot: A young boy's discovery of a colorful, wish-granting rock causes chaos in the suburban town of Black Falls when jealous kids and scheming adults alike set out to get their hands on it.
Title: Shorts
Actors: Jimmy Bennett, Jake Short, Kat Dennings, Trevor Gagnon
tomatoConsensus: Shorts has imagination and energy, but most viewers beyond elementary school will likely tire of the kiddie humor and sensory overload.

Plot: A frustrated man decides to take justice into his own hands after a plea bargain sets one of his family's killers free. He targets not only the killer but also the district attorney and others involved in the deal.
Title: Law Abiding Citizen

tomatoConsensus: Unnecessarily violent and unflinchingly absurd, Law Abiding Citizen is plagued by subpar acting and a story that defies reason.

Plot: A look at the life of legendary American pilot Amelia Earhart, who disappeared while flying over the Pacific Ocean in 1937 in an attempt to make a flight around the world.
Title: Amelia

Actors: Hilary Swank, Richard Gere, Ewan McGregor, Christopher Eccleston
tomatoConsensus: Amelia takes the compelling raw materials of its subject's life and does little with them, conventionally ticking off Earhart's accomplishments without exploring the soul of the woman.

Plot: Michael returns home from military school to find his mother happily in love and living with her new boyfriend. As the two men get to know each other, he becomes more and more suspicious of the man who is always there with a helpful hand.
Title: The Stepfather
Writer: J.S. Cardone (screenplay), Donald E. Westlake (earlier screenplay), Carolyn Lefcourt (story), Brian Garfield (story), Donald E. Westlake (story)
Actors: Dylan Walsh, Sela Ward, Penn Badgley, Amber Heard
tomatoConsensus: This tepid remake of the 1987 cult classic lacks the tension and satirical undercurrents of the original.

Plot: A sex comedy centered on a serial womanizer and his jilted lover.
Title: Spread
Writer: Jason Hall (screenplay), Jason Hall (story), Paul Kolsby (story)
Actors: Ashton Kutcher, Anne Heche, Margarita Levieva, Sebastian Stan
tomatoConsensus: Despite occasional detours into surprisingly dark territory, Spread overall is an ineffectual celebration of vacuous Los Angeles high life rather than a deconstruction of it.

Plot: A sports writer becomes a single parent in tragic circumstances.
Title: The Boys Are Back
Actors: Clive Owen, Emma Booth, Laura Fraser, George MacKay
tomatoConsensus: Great performances by Clive Owen and The Boys save this melodrama from entering into the sappy territory it might have in less competent hands.

Plot: A romantic drama about a brief, unexpected love affair that catches two people completely off-guard.
Title: Cairo Time
Actors: Patricia Clarkson, Alexander Siddig, Elena Anaya, Amina Annabi
tomatoConsensus: Though potentially too slowly paced for some, Cairo Time lingers long after the closing credits, largely due to a wonderful performance by Patricia Clarkson.

Plot: With a job traveling around the country firing people, Ryan Bingham enjoys his life living out of a suitcase, but finds that lifestyle threatened by the presence of a new hire and a potential love interest.
Title: Up in the Air
Writer: Walter Kirn (novel), Jason Reitman (screenplay), Sheldon Turner (screenplay)
Actors: George Clooney, Vera Farmiga, Anna Kendrick, Jason Bateman
Awards: Nominated for 6 Oscars. Another 76 wins & 152 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Led by charismatic performances by its three leads, director Jason Reitman delivers a smart blend of humor and emotion with just enough edge for mainstream audiences.

Plot: Agent Strahm is dead, and FBI agent Erickson draws nearer to Hoffman. Meanwhile, a pair of insurance executives find themselves in another game set by jigsaw.
Title: Saw VI
Actors: Tobin Bell, Costas Mandylor, Mark Rolston, Betsy Russell
tomatoConsensus: It won't earn the franchise many new fans, but Saw VI is a surprising step up for what has become an intricately grisly annual tradition.

Plot: A compilation of interviews, rehearsals and backstage footage of Michael Jackson as he prepared for his series of sold-out shows in London.
Title: This Is It
Actors: Michael Jackson, Alex Al, Alexandra Apjarova, Nick Bass
tomatoConsensus: While it may not be the definitive concert film (or the insightful backstage look) some will hope for, Michael Jackson's This Is It packs more than enough entertainment value to live up to its ambitious title.

Plot: Teenager, Darren Shan, meets a mysterious man at a freak show who turns out to be a Vampire. After a series of events Darren must leave his normal life and go on the road with the Cirque Du Freak and become a Vampire.
Title: Cirque du Freak: The Vampire's Assistant
Writer: Paul Weitz (screenplay), Brian Helgeland (screenplay), Darren Shan (series of books)
Actors: John C. Reilly, Josh Hutcherson, Chris Massoglia, Jessica Carlson
tomatoConsensus: This overstuffed, scattershot vampire flick suffers from poor characterization and an unwieldy mix of scares and chuckles.

Plot: The MacManus brothers are living a quiet life in Ireland with their father, but when they learn that their beloved priest has been killed by mob forces, they go back to Boston to bring justice to those responsible and avenge the priest.
Title: The Boondock Saints II: All Saints Day
Writer: Troy Duffy (screenplay), Troy Duffy (story), Taylor Duffy (story)
Actors: Sean Patrick Flanery, Norman Reedus, Billy Connolly, Clifton Collins Jr.
tomatoConsensus: This sequel to the cult favorite The Boondock Saints is more of the same -- unoriginal, absurd, violent, over-the-top, and occasionally mean-spirited.

Plot: Chris Rock explores the wonders of African-American hairstyles.
Title: Good Hair
Writer: Lance Crouther, Paul Marchand (ghostwriter), Chris Rock, Chuck Sklar, Jeff Stilson
Actors: Tanya Crumel, Kevin Kirk, Jason Griggers, Maya Angelou
tomatoConsensus: Funny, informative, and occasionally sad, Good Hair is a provocative look at the complex relationship between African Americans and their hair.

Plot: Black Dynamite is the greatest African-American action star of the 1970s. When his only brother is killed by The Man it's up to him to find justice.
Title: Black Dynamite
Writer: Michael Jai White (screenplay), Byron Minns (screenplay), Scott Sanders (screenplay), Michael Jai White (story), Byron Minns (story)
Actors: Phyllis Applegate, Obba Babatundé, William Bassett, Troy Lindsey Brown
tomatoConsensus: A loving and meticulous send-up of 1970s blaxsploitation movies, Black Dynamite is funny enough for the frat house and clever enough for film buffs.

Plot: A hard-core New York Giants fan struggles to deal with the consequences when he is beaten up by his favorite player.
Title: Big Fan
Actors: Patton Oswalt, Kevin Corrigan, Michael Rapaport, Marcia Jean Kurtz
tomatoConsensus: Featuring Patton Oswalt's sympathetic portrayal, Big Fan humorously and effectively captures the dark and lonely world of a sports fanatic.

Plot: When an android replica of a boy is rejected by his aggrieved creator, he goes off to find his own identity in an adventure that would make him the greatest hero of his time.
Title: Astro Boy
Writer: Osamu Tezuka (manga), David Bowers (story), Timothy Harris, David Bowers
Actors: Charlize Theron, Freddie Highmore, Ryan Stiles, Eugene Levy
tomatoConsensus: While it isn't terribly original, and it seems to have a political agenda that may rankle some viewers, Astro Boy boasts enough visual thrills to please its target demographic.

Plot: An urbane fox cannot resist returning to his farm raiding ways and then must help his community survive the farmers' retaliation.
Title: Fantastic Mr. Fox
Writer: Roald Dahl (novel), Wes Anderson (screenplay), Noah Baumbach (screenplay)
Actors: George Clooney, Meryl Streep, Jason Schwartzman, Bill Murray
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 30 wins & 59 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Fantastic Mr. Fox is a delightfully funny feast for the eyes with multi-generational appeal -- and it shows Wes Anderson has a knack for animation.

Plot: Torn between faith and science, and suffering hallucinations, English naturalist Charles Darwin struggles to complete 'On the Origin of Species' and maintain his relationship with his wife.
Title: Creation
Writer: John Collee (screenplay), Jon Amiel (screen story), John Collee (screen story), Randal Keynes (book)
Actors: Paul Bettany, Ian Kelly, Guy Henry, Martha West
tomatoConsensus: This Charles Darwin biopic is curiously dispassionate, but Creation contains some of director Jon Amiel's best work, and Paul Bettany's performance is not to be missed.

Plot: Paris 1913. Coco Chanel is infatuated with the rich and handsome Boy Capel, but she is also compelled by her work. Igor Stravinsky's The Rite of Spring is about to be performed. The ...
Title: Coco Chanel & Igor Stravinsky
Writer: Chris Greenhalgh (screenplay), Chris Greenhalgh (novel), Carlo De Boutiny (adaptation), Jan Kounen (adaptation)
Actors: Mads Mikkelsen, Anna Mouglalis, Elena Morozova, Natacha Lindinger
tomatoConsensus: It's well-acted and beautifully filmed, but Jan Kounen's dramatization of the affair between his famous subjects is curiously short on passion.

Plot: A car accident and shifting affections test the bond between a married couple.
Title: Not Easily Broken
Actors: Morris Chestnut, Taraji P. Henson, Maeve Quinlan, Kevin Hart
tomatoConsensus: Though well-intentioned, Not Easily Broken is bogged down by melodramatic plotting and stereotypical characters.

Plot: An animated retelling of Charles Dickens' classic novel about a Victorian-era miser taken on a journey of self-redemption, courtesy of several mysterious Christmas apparitions.
Title: A Christmas Carol
Actors: Jim Carrey, Steve Valentine, Daryl Sabara, Sage Ryan
tomatoConsensus: Robert Zemeckis' 3-D animated take on the Dickens classic tries hard, but its dazzling special effects distract from an array of fine performances from Jim Carrey and Gary Oldman.

Plot: A frustrated writer struggles to keep his family alive when a series of global catastrophes threatens to annihilate mankind.
Language: English, French, Tibetan, Mandarin, Russian, Hindi, Portuguese, Latin, Italian
Actors: John Cusack, Amanda Peet, Chiwetel Ejiofor, Thandie Newton
tomatoConsensus: Roland Emmerich's 2012 provides plenty of visual thrills, but lacks a strong enough script to support its massive scope and inflated length.

Plot: A small wooden box arrives on the doorstep of a married couple, who know that opening it will grant them a million dollars and kill someone they don't know.
Title: The Box
Writer: Richard Kelly (screenplay), Richard Matheson (short story "Button,  Button")
Actors: Cameron Diaz, James Marsden, Frank Langella, James Rebhorn
tomatoConsensus: Imaginative but often preposterous, The Box features some thrills but largely feels too piecemeal.

Plot: Harry Caine, a blind writer, reaches this moment in time when he has to heal his wounds from 14 years back. He was then still known by his real name, Mateo Blanco, and directing his last movie.
Title: Broken Embraces
Actors: Penélope Cruz, Lluís Homar, Blanca Portillo, José Luis Gómez
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 9 wins & 38 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Pedro Almodovar's fourth film with Penélope Cruz isn't his finest work, but he brings his signature visual brilliance to this noirish tale, and the cast turns in some first-class performances.

Plot: A thriller involving an ongoing unsolved mystery in Alaska, where one town has seen an extraordinary number of unexplained disappearances during the past 40 years and there are accusations of a federal cover up.
Title: The Fourth Kind
Writer: Olatunde Osunsanmi (screenplay), Olatunde Osunsanmi (story), Terry Robbins (story)
Actors: Milla Jovovich, Will Patton, Hakeem Kae-Kazim, Corey Johnson
tomatoConsensus: While it boasts a handful of shocks, The Fourth Kind is hokey and clumsy and makes its close encounters seem eerily mundane.

Plot: In New York City's Harlem circa 1987, an overweight, abused, illiterate teen who is pregnant with her second child is invited to enroll in an alternative school in hopes that her life can head in a new direction.
Title: Precious
Actors: Gabourey Sidibe, Mo'Nique, Paula Patton, Mariah Carey
tomatoConsensus: Precious is a grim yet ultimately triumphant film about abuse and inner-city life, largely bolstered by exceptional performances from its cast.

Plot: Terence McDonagh is a drug- and gambling-addled detective in post-Katrina New Orleans investigating the killing of five Senegalese immigrants.
Title: Bad Lieutenant: Port of Call New Orleans
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Eva Mendes, Val Kilmer, Xzibit
tomatoConsensus: Befitting its unorthodox origins, this Bad Lieutenant benefits from Werner Herzog's typically fearless direction and a delightfully unhinged Nicolas Cage in the title role.

Plot: Edward leaves Bella after an attack that nearly claimed her life, and in her depression she falls into yet another paranormal relationship - this time with werewolf Jacob Black.
Title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
Actors: Kristen Stewart, Christina Jastrzembska, Robert Pattinson, Billy Burke
tomatoConsensus: The Twilight Saga's second installment may satisfy hardcore fans of the series, but outsiders are likely to be turned off by its slow pace, relentlessly downcast tone, and excessive length.

Plot: An American soldier struggles with an ethical dilemma when he becomes involved with a widow of a fallen officer.
Title: The Messenger
Actors: Ben Foster, Jena Malone, Eamonn Walker, Woody Harrelson
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 16 wins & 44 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A dark but timely subject is handled deftly by writer/directer Owen Moverman and superbly acted by Woody Harrleson and Ben Foster.

Plot: A young ninja turns his back on the orphanage that raised him, leading to a confrontation with a fellow ninja from the clan.
Title: Ninja Assassin
Writer: Matthew Sand (screenplay), J. Michael Straczynski (screenplay), Matthew Sand (story)
Actors: Rain, Joon Lee, Jonathan Chan-Pensley, Ill-Young Kim
tomatoConsensus: Overly serious and incomprehensibly edited, Ninja Assassin fails to live up to the promise of its title.

Plot: A young man comforts his older brother's wife and children after he goes missing in Afghanistan.
Title: Brothers
Writer: David Benioff (screenplay), Susanne Bier (motion picture "Brødre"), Anders Thomas Jensen (motion picture "Brødre")
Actors: Tobey Maguire, Jake Gyllenhaal, Natalie Portman, Sam Shepard
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 3 wins & 13 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It plays more like a traditional melodrama than the Susanne Bier film that inspired it, but Jim Sheridan's Brothers benefits from rock-solid performances by its three leads.

Plot: The story of Michael Oher, a homeless and traumatized boy who became an All American football player and first round NFL draft pick with the help of a caring woman and her family.
Title: The Blind Side
Actors: Sandra Bullock, Tim McGraw, Quinton Aaron, Jae Head
tomatoConsensus: It might strike some viewers as a little too pat, but The Blind Side has the benefit of strong source material and a strong performance from Sandra Bullock.

Plot: Unable to cope with a recent personal tragedy, LA's top celebrity shrink turns into a pothead with no concern for his appearance and a creeping sense of his inability to help his patients.
Title: Shrink
Actors: Kevin Spacey, Joe Nunez, Mark Webber, Keke Palmer
tomatoConsensus: Kevin Spacey's performance is almost sharp enough to save this Hollywood dramedy from itself, but in the end, he's dragged down by a cliched script and indifferent direction.

Plot: Two friends and business partners find their lives turned upside down when strange circumstances lead them to be the temporary guardians of seven year-old twins.
Title: Old Dogs
Actors: John Travolta, Robin Williams, Kelly Preston, Conner Rayburn
tomatoConsensus: Its cast tries hard, but Old Dogs is a predictable, nearly witless attempt at physical comedy and moral uplift that misses the mark on both counts.

Plot: An alien civilization is invaded by Astronaut Chuck Baker, who believes that the planet was uninhabited. Wanted by the military, Baker must get back to his ship before it goes into orbit without him.
Title: Planet 51
Writer: Javier Abad (original idea by), Jorge Blanco (original idea by), Marcos Martínez (original idea by), Ignacio Pérez Dolset (original idea by), Joe Stillman
Director: Jorge Blanco, Javier Abad, Marcos Martínez
Actors: Jessica Biel, John Cleese, Gary Oldman, Dwayne Johnson
tomatoConsensus: Planet 51 squanders an interesting premise with an overly familiar storyline, stock characters, and humor that alternates between curious and potentially offensive.

Plot: An English professor, one year after the sudden death of his boyfriend, is unable to cope with his typical days in 1960s Los Angeles.
Title: A Single Man
Writer: Christopher Isherwood (novel), Tom Ford (written for the screen by), David Scearce (written for the screen by)
Actors: Colin Firth, Julianne Moore, Nicholas Hoult, Matthew Goode
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 34 wins & 51 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though the costumes are beautiful and the art direction impeccable, what stands out most from this debut by fashion designer Tom Ford is the leading performance by Colin Firth.

Plot: Centers on a young girl who has been murdered and watches over her family - and her killer - from purgatory. She must weigh her desire for vengeance against her desire for her family to heal.
Title: The Lovely Bones
Writer: Fran Walsh (screenplay), Philippa Boyens (screenplay), Peter Jackson (screenplay), Alice Sebold (novel)
Actors: Mark Wahlberg, Rachel Weisz, Susan Sarandon, Stanley Tucci
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 43 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It's stuffed full of Peter Jackson's typically dazzling imagery, but The Lovely Bones suffers from abrupt shifts between horrific violence and cloying sentimentality.

Plot: Nelson Mandela, in his first term as the South African President, initiates a unique venture to unite the apartheid-torn land: enlist the national rugby team on a mission to win the 1995 Rugby World Cup.
Language: English, Afrikaans, Maori, Zulu, Xhosa, Southern Sotho
Title: Invictus
Actors: Morgan Freeman, Matt Damon, Tony Kgoroge, Patrick Mofokeng
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 33 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Delivered with typically stately precision from director Clint Eastwood, Invictus may not be rousing enough for some viewers, but Matt Damon and Morgan Freeman inhabit their real-life characters with admirable conviction.

Plot: A waitress, desperate to fulfill her dreams as a restaurant owner, is set on a journey to turn a frog prince back into a human being, but she has to face the same problem after she kisses him.
Title: The Princess and the Frog
Writer: Ron Clements (story by), John Musker (story by), Greg Erb (story by), Jason Oremland (story by), Ron Clements (screenplay), John Musker (screenplay), Rob Edwards (screenplay), E.D. Baker (story inspired in part by "The Frog Princess" by)
Actors: Anika Noni Rose, Bruno Campos, Keith David, Michael-Leon Wooley
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 12 wins & 39 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The warmth of traditional Disney animation makes this occasionally lightweight fairy-tale update a lively and captivating confection for the holidays.

Plot: A widower who realized his only connection to his family was through his wife sets off on an impromptu road trip to reunite with each of his grown children.
Title: Everybody's Fine
Writer: Kirk Jones, Giuseppe Tornatore (original screenplay), Tonino Guerra (original screenplay), Massimo De Rita (original screenplay)
Actors: Robert De Niro, Drew Barrymore, Kate Beckinsale, Sam Rockwell
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A calm, charismatic performance from Robert De Niro nearly saves the movie, but ultimately, Everybody's Fine has the look and feel of a stereotypical Christmas dramedy.

Plot: A newbie guard for an armored truck company is coerced by his veteran coworkers to steal a truck containing $42 million. But a wrinkle in their supposedly foolproof plan divides the group, leading to a potentially deadly resolution.
Title: Armored
Actors: Matt Dillon, Jean Reno, Laurence Fishburne, Amaury Nolasco
tomatoConsensus: This B-grade thriller has a good cast and director but is undone by plot holes and messy conclusion.

Plot: In New York City, an estranged couple who witness a murder are relocated to small-town Wyoming as part of a witness-protection program.
Title: Did You Hear About the Morgans?
Actors: Hugh Grant, Sarah Jessica Parker, Natalia Klimas, Vincenzo Amato
tomatoConsensus: It gets a certain amount of mileage out of the inherent likability of its stars, but with an unfunny script and a lack of onscreen chemistry, Did You Hear About the Morgans? falls flat.

Plot: A paraplegic marine dispatched to the moon Pandora on a unique mission becomes torn between following his orders and protecting the world he feels is his home.
Title: Avatar
Actors: Sam Worthington, Zoe Saldana, Sigourney Weaver, Stephen Lang
tomatoConsensus: It might be more impressive on a technical level than as a piece of storytelling, but Avatar reaffirms James Cameron's singular gift for imaginative, absorbing filmmaking.

Plot: Famous film director Guido Contini struggles to find harmony in his professional and personal lives, as he engages in dramatic relationships with his wife, his mistress, his muse, his agent, and his mother.
Title: Nine
Writer: Michael Tolkin (screenplay), Anthony Minghella (screenplay), Arthur Kopit (Broadway musical "Nine"), Maury Yeston (Broadway musical "Nine"), Mario Fratti (Broadway musical "Nine" Italian original)
Actors: Daniel Day-Lewis, Sandro Dori, Nicole Kidman, Marion Cotillard
Awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 8 wins & 56 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It has a game, great-looking cast, led by the always worthwhile Daniel Day-Lewis, but Rob Marshall's Nine is chaotic and curiously distant.

Plot: When attending their son's college graduation, a couple reignite the spark in their relationship. But the complicated fact is they're divorced and he's remarried.
Title: It's Complicated
Actors: Meryl Streep, Steve Martin, Alec Baldwin, John Krasinski
Awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 8 wins & 12 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despite fine work by an appealing cast, It's Complicated is predictable romantic comedy fare, going for broad laughs instead of subtlety and nuance.

Plot: Detective Sherlock Holmes and his stalwart partner Watson engage in a battle of wits and brawn with a nemesis whose plot is a threat to all of England.
Title: Sherlock Holmes
Writer: Michael Robert Johnson (screenplay), Anthony Peckham (screenplay), Simon Kinberg (screenplay), Lionel Wigram (screen story), Michael Robert Johnson (screen story), Arthur Conan Doyle (characters: Sherlock Holmes,  Dr. Watson)
Actors: Robert Downey Jr., Jude Law, Rachel McAdams, Mark Strong
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 25 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Guy Ritchie's directorial style might not be quite the best fit for an update on the legendary detective, but Sherlock Holmes benefits from the elementary appeal of a strong performance by Robert Downey, Jr.

Plot: A faded country music musician is forced to reassess his dysfunctional life during a doomed romance that also inspires him.
Title: Crazy Heart
Actors: Jeff Bridges, James Keane, Anna Felix, Paul Herman
tomatoConsensus: Thanks to a captivating performance from Jeff Bridges, Crazy Heart transcends its overly familiar origins and finds new meaning in an old story.

Plot: A historical drama that illustrates Russian author Leo Tolstoy's struggle to balance fame and wealth with his commitment to a life devoid of material things.
Title: The Last Station
Writer: Michael Hoffman (screenplay), Jay Parini (based on the novel by)
Actors: Helen Mirren, Christopher Plummer, Paul Giamatti, James McAvoy
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 15 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Michael Hoffman's script doesn't quite live up to its famous subject, but this Tolstoy biopic benefits from a spellbinding tour de force performance by Helen Mirren.

Plot: The world famous singing pre-teen chipmunk trio return to contend with the pressures of school, celebrity, and a rival female music group known as The Chipettes.
Title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel
Writer: Jon Vitti, Jonathan Aibel, Glenn Berger, Ross Bagdasarian (characters Alvin and the Chipmunks)
Actors: Zachary Levi, David Cross, Jason Lee, Justin Long
tomatoConsensus: This Squeakquel may entertain the kiddies, but it's low on energy and heavily reliant on slapstick humor.

Plot: While his trailer trash parents teeter on the edge of divorce, Nick Twisp sets his sights on dream girl Sheeni Saunders, hoping that she'll be the one to take away his virginity.
Title: Youth in Revolt
Actors: Michael Cera, Portia Doubleday, Jean Smart, Zach Galifianakis
tomatoConsensus: It may not entirely do its source material justice, but Miguel Arteta's Youth in Revolt is a fun, funny comic romp that lets Michael Cera stretch a little and introduces filmgoers to a major find in Portia Doubleday.

Plot: In the year 2019, a plague has transformed almost every human into vampires. Faced with a dwindling blood supply, the fractured dominant race plots their survival; meanwhile, a researcher works with a covert band of vamps on a way to save humankind.
Title: Daybreakers
Actors: Harriet Minto-Day, Jay Laga'aia, Damien Garvey, Sahaj Dumpleton
tomatoConsensus: Though it arrives during an unfortunate glut of vampire movies, Daybreakers offers enough dark sci-fi thrills -- and enough of a unique twist on the genre -- to satisfy filmgoers.

Plot: An unusual road trip movie about a mother driving her two sons from New York to Pittsburgh to St. Louis and eventually Hollywood in her quest to find a man to take care of them all.
Title: My One and Only
Actors: Renée Zellweger, Logan Lerman, Kevin Bacon, Troy Garity
tomatoConsensus: A breezy road movie with characters both glamorous and familiar, My One and Only is a colorful period look at the early life of actor George Hamilton.

Plot: A vampire named Saya, who is part of covert government agency that hunts and destroys demons in a post-WWII Japan, is inserted in a military school to discover which one of her classmates is a demon in disguise.
Title: Blood: The Last Vampire
Writer: Chris Chow (screenplay), Kenji Kamiyama (character), Katsuya Terada (character)
Actors: Ji-hyun Jun, Allison Miller, Liam Cunningham, JJ Feild
tomatoConsensus: Based on a classic anime series, Blood: The Last Vampire is a tedious, shoddily acted, amateurish picture that loses all charm in the transition to live-action.

Plot: A chronicle of John Lennon's first years, focused mainly in his adolescence and his relationship with his stern aunt Mimi, who raised him, and his absentee mother Julia, who re-entered his life at a crucial moment in his young life.
Title: Nowhere Boy
Actors: Aaron Taylor-Johnson, Kristin Scott Thomas, David Threlfall, Josh Bolt
Awards: Nominated for 3 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 6 wins & 18 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Don't expect any musical insights, but this look at John Lennon's early life benefits from its restrained, low-key approach and some fine acting from Aaron Johnson.

Plot: A cop turns con man once he comes out of the closet. Once imprisoned, he meets the second love of his life, whom he'll stop at nothing to be with.
Title: I Love You Phillip Morris
Writer: John Requa, Glenn Ficarra, Steve McVicker (book)
Actors: Jim Carrey, Ewan McGregor, Leslie Mann, Rodrigo Santoro
tomatoConsensus: This fact-based romantic comedy has its flaws, but they're mostly overcome by its consistently sweet, funny tone and one of the best performances of Jim Carrey's career.

Plot: Everything changes for 15-year-old Mia when her mum brings home a new boyfriend.
Title: Fish Tank
Actors: Katie Jarvis, Michael Fassbender, Kierston Wareing, Rebecca Griffiths
tomatoConsensus: Cannes Jury Prize-winner Fish Tank is gritty British realism at its very best, with flawless performances from newcomer Kate Jarvis, and Michael Fassbender.

Plot: An Irish fisherman discovers a woman in his fishing net whom his precocious daughter believes to be a selkie.
Title: Ondine
Actors: Colin Farrell, Alicja Bachleda, Dervla Kirwan, Alison Barry
tomatoConsensus: Flawed but charming, Ondine reaffirms writer-director Neil Jordan's gift for myth, magic, and wonder.

Plot: As computer hacker Lisbeth and journalist Mikael investigate a sex-trafficking ring, Lisbeth is accused of three murders, causing her to go on the run while Mikael works to clear her name.
Title: The Girl Who Played with Fire
Actors: Michael Nyqvist, Noomi Rapace, Lena Endre, Peter Andersson
tomatoConsensus: Noomi Rapace and Michael Nyqvist remain extraordinarily well-suited to their roles, but the second installment in Stieg Larsson's Millennium Trilogy doesn't pack quite as much punch as the first.

Plot: A young boy in a remote medieval outpost under siege from barbarian raids is beckoned to adventure when a celebrated master illuminator arrives with an ancient book, brimming with secret wisdom and powers.
Title: The Secret of Kells
Actors: Evan McGuire, Christen Mooney, Brendan Gleeson, Mick Lally
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Beautifully drawn and refreshingly calm, The Secret of Kells hearkens back to animation's golden age with an enchanting tale inspired by Irish mythology.

Title: I Hope They Serve Beer in Hell
Writer: Tucker Max (novel), Tucker Max (screenplay), Nils Parker (screenplay)
Actors: Tim Huck, Lex D. Geddings, Matt Czuchry, Yvette Yates
tomatoConsensus: I Hope They Serve Beer in Hell fails in its attempts at raunchy humor, and Tucker Max comes across so unlikable and outrageous that the film's inevitable story arc feels forced.

Plot: A historical drama set in Roman Egypt, concerning a slave who turns to the rising tide of Christianity in the hope of pursuing freedom while falling in love with his mistress, the famous philosophy and mathematics professor Hypatia of Alexandria.
Title: Agora
Actors: Rachel Weisz, Max Minghella, Oscar Isaac, Ashraf Barhom
tomatoConsensus: Noble goals and a gripping performance from Rachel Weisz can't save Agora from its muddled script, uneven acting, and choppy editing.

Plot: In Manhattan, a mother of two preparing for her daughter's sixth birthday party has no idea of the challenges she's about to face in order to pull off the event.
Title: Motherhood
Actors: Uma Thurman, Anthony Edwards, David Schallipp, Matthew Schallipp
tomatoConsensus: Despite Uma Thurman's comic skills, Motherhood's contrived set-ups and cliched jokes keep this comedy from delivering laughs -- or insights into modern parenting.

Plot: Three unconnected Brooklyn cops wind up at the same deadly location after enduring vastly different career paths.
Title: Brooklyn's Finest
Actors: Richard Gere, Don Cheadle, Ethan Hawke, Wesley Snipes
tomatoConsensus: It's appropriately gritty, and soaked in the kind of palpable tension Antoine Fuqua delivers so well, but Brooklyn's Finest suffers from the comparisons its cliched script provokes.

Plot: An elderly ex-serviceman and widower looks to avenge his best friend's murder by doling out his own form of justice.
Title: Harry Brown
Actors: Michael Caine, Emily Mortimer, Charlie Creed-Miles, David Bradley
tomatoConsensus: Its lurid violence may put off some viewers, but Harry Brown is a vigilante thriller that carries an emotional as well as a physical punch, thanks to a gripping performance from Michael Caine in the title role.

Plot: An Ivy League professor is lured back to his Oklahoma hometown, where his twin brother, a small-time pot grower, has concocted a scheme to take down a local drug lord.
Title: Leaves of Grass
Actors: Edward Norton, Lucy DeVito, Kent Jude Bernard, Amelia Campbell
tomatoConsensus: Edward Norton delivers one of his finest performances in Leaves of Grass, but he's overpowered by the movie's many jarring tonal shifts.

Plot: A social worker fights to save a girl from her abusive parents, only to discover that the situation is more dangerous than she ever expected.
Title: Case 39
Actors: Renée Zellweger, Jodelle Ferland, Ian McShane, Bradley Cooper
tomatoConsensus: Director Christian Alvert has a certain stylish flair, but it's wasted on Case 39's frightless, unoriginal plot.

Plot: An ecological drama/documentary, filmed throughout the globe. Part thriller, part meditation on the vanishing wonders of the sub-aquatic world.
Title: Oceans
Country: France, Switzerland, Spain, USA, United Arab Emirates
Writer: Christophe Cheysson, Jacques Cluzaud, Laurent Debas, Stéphane Durand, Laurent Gaudé, Jacques Perrin, François Sarano
Actors: Pierce Brosnan, Jacques Perrin, Pedro Armendáriz Jr., Aldo
tomatoConsensus: Oceans adds another visually stunning chapter to the Disney Nature library.

Plot: The owner of a Miami restaurant indebted to the mob institutes a contest to see what waiter can earn the most money in one night.
Title: The Slammin' Salmon
Writer: Jay Chandrasekhar, Kevin Heffernan, Steve Lemme, Paul Soter, Erik Stolhanske
Actors: Kevin Heffernan, Jeff Chase, Carla Gallo, Paul Soter
tomatoConsensus: Potty humor and juvenile antics keep this workplace comedy from being particularly funny or memorable.

Plot: A doctor hires an escort to seduce her husband, whom she suspects of cheating, though unforeseen events put the family in danger.
Title: Chloe
Writer: Erin Cressida Wilson (screenplay), Anne Fontaine (motion picture "Nathalie")
Actors: Julianne Moore, Liam Neeson, Amanda Seyfried, Max Thieriot
tomatoConsensus: Despite its promising pedigree and a titillating premise, Chloe ultimately fails to deliver the heat -- or the thrills -- expected of a sexual thriller.

Title: Waking Sleeping Beauty
Actors: Don Hahn, Ron Clements, Peter Schneider, Roy Edward Disney
tomatoConsensus: It doesn't probe as deep -- or tell as many hard truths -- as it could have, but Don Hahn's look at Disney's rebirth offers a fascinating and surprisingly candorous glimpse into the studio's past.

Plot: Emma left Russia to live with her husband in Italy. Now a member of a powerful industrial family, she is the respected mother of three, but feels unfulfilled. One day, Antonio, a talented chef and her son's friend, makes her senses kindle.
Title: I Am Love
Writer: Barbara Alberti (screenplay), Ivan Cotroneo (screenplay), Walter Fasano (screenplay), Luca Guadagnino (screenplay), Luca Guadagnino (story)
Actors: Tilda Swinton, Flavio Parenti, Edoardo Gabbriellini, Alba Rohrwacher
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 37 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It stumbles into melodrama, but I Am Love backs up its flamboyance with tremendous visual style and a marvelous central performance from Tilda Swinton.

Plot: During the First Lebanon War in 1982, a lone tank and a paratroopers platoon are dispatched to search a hostile town.
Title: Lebanon
Actors: Yoav Donat, Itay Tiran, Oshri Cohen, Michael Moshonov
tomatoConsensus: A powerful and personal account of war on the front line, writer-director Samuel Maoz takes the viewer inside an Israeli tank to deliver an exhausting, original film.

Plot: Genetic engineers Clive Nicoli and Elsa Kast hope to achieve fame by successfully splicing together the DNA of different animals to create new hybrid animals for medical use.
Title: Splice
Writer: Vincenzo Natali (screenplay), Antoinette Terry Bryant (screenplay), Doug Taylor (screenplay), Vincenzo Natali (story), Antoinette Terry Bryant (story)
Actors: Adrien Brody, Sarah Polley, Delphine Chanéac, Brandon McGibbon
tomatoConsensus: It doesn't take its terrific premise quite as far as it should, but Splice is a smart, well-acted treat for horror fans.

Plot: A car magnate watches his personal and professional life hit the skids because of his business and romantic indiscretions.
Title: Solitary Man
Actors: Michael Douglas, Susan Sarandon, Danny DeVito, Mary-Louise Parker
tomatoConsensus: Built around a singularly unpleasant main character, Solitary Man needed a flawless central performance to succeed -- and Michael Douglas delivers.

Plot: Ambitious young Manhattanite and urban conservationist Beth wants it all: a good job, good friends, and a good guy to share the city with. Of course that last one is often the trickiest of ...
Title: The Good Guy
Actors: Alexis Bledel, Anna Chlumsky, Christine Evangelista, Bryan Greenberg
tomatoConsensus: The Good Guy has an attractive cast, but they aren't done any favors by the film's cardboard characters and cliched plot.

Plot: Jack Rebney is the most famous man you've never heard of - after cursing his way through a Winnebago sales video, Rebney's outrageously funny outtakes became an underground sensation and ...
Title: Winnebago Man
Writer: Malcolm Pullinger, Ben Steinbauer, Louisa Hall (additional writing), Joel Heller (additional writing), Berndt Mader (additional writing), Natasha Rosow (additional writing)
Actors: Jack Rebney, Ben Steinbauer, Keith Gordon, Nick Prueher
tomatoConsensus: Though it doesn't quite answer all of the questions it raises, Winnebago Man is nevertheless a fascinating, hilarious, and surprisingly poignant look at a geniunely colorful internet celebrity.

Plot: A boy stands on a station platform as a train is about to leave. Should he go with his mother or stay with his father? Infinite possibilities arise from this decision. As long as he doesn't choose, anything is possible.
Title: Mr. Nobody
Actors: Jared Leto, Sarah Polley, Diane Kruger, Linh Dan Pham
tomatoConsensus: Mr. Nobody's narrative tangles may bedevil as much as they entertain, but its big ambitions and absorbing visuals make for an intriguing addition to director Jaco Van Dormael's filmography.

Plot: Friends, family, and lovers struggle to find love, forgiveness, and meaning in a war-torn world riddled with comedy and pathos.
Title: Life During Wartime
Actors: Shirley Henderson, Michael Kenneth Williams, Roslyn Ruff, Allison Janney
tomatoConsensus: With Life During Wartime, Todd Solondz delivers an unexpected semi-sequel to Happiness in typically uncompromising fashion.

Plot: A movie spun out of equal parts folk tale, fable and real-life legend about the mysterious, 1930s Tennessee hermit who famously threw his own rollicking funeral party... while he was still alive.
Title: Get Low
Writer: Chris Provenzano (screenplay), C. Gaby Mitchell (screenplay), Chris Provenzano (story), Scott Seeke (story)
Actors: Robert Duvall, Sissy Spacek, Bill Murray, Lucas Black
tomatoConsensus: Subtle to a fault, this perfectly cast ensemble drama is lifted by typically sharp performances from Robert Duvall and Bill Murray.

Plot: A seemingly perfect family moves into a suburban neighborhood, but when it comes to the truth as to why they're living there, they don't exactly come clean with their neighbors.
Title: The Joneses
Actors: David Duchovny, Demi Moore, Amber Heard, Benjamin Hollingsworth
tomatoConsensus: It doesn't pursue its subversive premise as far as it should, but The Joneses benefits from its timely satire of consumer culture -- as well as a pair of strong performances from David Duchovny and Demi Moore.

Plot: Chronicles Jack Harris, one of the pioneers of internet commerce, as he wrestles with his morals and struggles not to drown in a sea of conmen, mobsters, drug addicts, and pornstars.
Title: Middle Men
Actors: Luke Wilson, Giovanni Ribisi, Gabriel Macht, James Caan
tomatoConsensus: Middle Men benefits from a solid cast, particularly Luke Wilson, but its muddled script lets them down.

Plot: A Chelsea art gallerist falls for a brooding new music composer in this comic tale about the state of contemporary art.
Title: (Untitled)
Actors: Adam Goldberg, Marley Shelton, Eion Bailey, Lucy Punch
tomatoConsensus: This satire on the art world is at times both clever and shallow, but its top-notch cast generates plenty of goodwill.

Plot: An ex-gambler is lured back into the game by a veteran insurance-fraud investigator.
Title: Saint John of Las Vegas
Actors: Steve Buscemi, Romany Malco, Sarah Silverman, Peter Dinklage
tomatoConsensus: Writer-director Hue Rhodes' debut is a poorly-paced, forgettable comedy that wastes the quirky talents of stars Steve Buscemi and Sarah Silverman.

Plot: Suzanne is a well married mother, but her bourgeois lifestyle gets her down and she decides to go back to work as a physiotherapist by building an office in their backyard. Then Suzanne falls in love with the man hired to build the office.
Title: Leaving
Writer: Catherine Corsini (scenario), Gaëlle Macé (collaborator), Antoine Jaccoud (scenario consultant), Emmanuelle Bernheim (scenario consultant)
Actors: Kristin Scott Thomas, Sergi López, Yvan Attal, Bernard Blancan
tomatoConsensus: Laden with melodramatic clichés, Leaving needed a talented star to succeed -- and Kristin Scott Thomas delivers the goods with another superb performance.

Plot: In the Summer of 1969 a young man is filled with the life of the idyllic old pearling port Broome - fishing, hanging out with his mates and his girl. However his mother returns him to the ...
Title: Bran Nue Dae
Writer: Jimmy Chi (stage musical), Kuckles (stage musical), Patrick Duttoo Bin Amat (stage musical), Garry Gower (stage musical), Michael Manolis Mavromatis (stage musical), Stephen Pigram (stage musical), Reg Cribb (screenplay), Rachel Perkins (screenplay), Jimmy Chi (screenplay), Adrian Russell Wills
Actors: Rocky McKenzie, Jessica Mauboy, Ernie Dingo, Missy Higgins
tomatoConsensus: It's original and high-spirited, but Bran Nue Dae is also uneven and sometimes overly kitschy.

Plot: Documentary that follows the struggle for control of Dr. Albert C. Barnes' 25 billion dollar collection of modern and post-impressionist art.
Title: The Art of the Steal
Actors: Julian Bond, David D'Arcy, Richard Feigen, Richard H. Glanton
tomatoConsensus: Deeply esoteric and unapologetically one-sided, The Art of the Steal proves a documentary doesn't have to make an objective argument as long as it argues well.

Plot: A drama centered around three women: A 50-year-old woman, the daughter she gave up for adoption 35 years ago, and an African American woman looking to adopt a child of her own.
Title: Mother and Child
Actors: Alexandria M. Salling, Connor Kramme, Annette Bening, Eileen Ryan
tomatoConsensus: Though it occasionally veers into unnecessary melodrama, Mother and Child benefits from a stellar cast and writer-director Rodrigo Garcia's finely detailed, bravely unsentimental script.

Plot: In the summer of 2003, a group of shepherds took a herd of sheep one final time through the Beartooth Mountains of Montana, in the extreme north-west of the United States. It was a journey ...
Title: Sweetgrass
tomatoConsensus: At once tender and unsentimental, Sweetgrass gracefully captures the beauty and hardships of a dying way of life.

Plot: A look at the lives and relationships among girls at an elite boarding school.
Title: Cracks
Writer: Ben Court (screenplay), Caroline Ip (screenplay), Jordan Scott (screenplay), Sheila Kohler (novel)
Actors: Eva Green, Juno Temple, María Valverde, Imogen Poots
tomatoConsensus: Atomospheric but not much else, Cracks is a formless film in search of compelling drama.

Plot: Realizing the urban legend of their youth has actually come true; two filmmakers delve into the mystery surrounding five missing children and the real-life boogeyman linked to their disappearances.
Title: Cropsey
Actors: Joshua Zeman, Barbara Brancaccio, Bill Ellis, Dorothy D'Eletto
tomatoConsensus: Riveting and bone-chillingly creepy, Cropsey manages to be one of the best documentaries and one of the best horror movies of the year.

Plot: The story of lawsuit by tens of thousands of Ecuadorans against Chevron over contamination of the Ecuadorean Amazon.
Title: Crude
Actors: Dan Ashley, Pablo Fajardo, Kent Robertson, German Yanez
tomatoConsensus: Dynamic, tightly arranged, and deliberately provocative, Joe Berlinger's Crude is a sobering, enraging wake-up call.

Plot: 28-year-old Kansas University doctoral student Omar Razaghi wins a grant to write a biography of Latin American writer Jules Gund. Omar must get through to three people who were close to ...
Title: The City of Your Final Destination
Actors: Nicholas Blandullo, Sofía Viruboff, James Martin, Omar Metwally
tomatoConsensus: A stellar cast can't elevate this leaden adaptation that, while just as beautiful as anything director James Ivory's made before, comes off as dusty and dry.

Plot: Follows six extreme sports stars as they prepare for and then compete in the 2008 Summer X-Games in Los Angeles. Kyle Loza practices a new motocross trick, landing in a pit of foam. Can he ...
Title: X Games 3D: The Movie
Actors: Shaun White, Travis Pastrana, Ricky Carmichael, Danny Way
tomatoConsensus: Though fans of the event will likely enjoy X-Games 3D: The Movie, most will find it a poorly put together, skin deep, extended advertisement for the extreme sports competition.

Plot: Photo-animated feature documentary, uniquely narrated by the 10 people who knew Bill best.
Title: American: The Bill Hicks Story
Actors: Bill Hicks, Dwight Slade, Mary Hicks, Steve Hicks
tomatoConsensus: A treasure trove of archival material and interviews, American: The Bill Hicks Story is an exuberant celebration about a unique, sorely missed voice in comedy.

Plot: A true-story account of a German businessman who saved more than 200,000 Chinese during the Nanjing massacre in 1937-38.
Language: Cantonese, Mandarin, German, Japanese, English, Ukrainian
Title: City of War: The Story of John Rabe
Actors: Ulrich Tukur, Daniel Brühl, Steve Buscemi, Anne Consigny
tomatoConsensus: Though it strays into predictable melodrama, John Rabe is worth watching for the light it shines on a neglected corner of Chinese history.

Plot: A drama that details the story of a woman's difficult relationship with her stepson.
Title: Love and Other Impossible Pursuits
Actors: Natalie Portman, Scott Cohen, Lisa Kudrow, Charlie Tahan
tomatoConsensus: Natalie Portman and Lisa Kudrow deliver fine performances in The Other Woman, but they're muted by Don Roos' clumsy direction and cluttered, melodramatic script.

Plot: The story of the actress, writer, and broadcasting pioneer Gertrude Berg.
Title: Yoo-Hoo, Mrs. Goldberg
Actors: Gertrude Berg, Lewis Berg, Sara Chase, Ruth Bader Ginsburg
tomatoConsensus: Equal parts edification and entertainment, Kempner's tender tribute to a forgotten pioneer of American entertainment is both richly deserved and long overdue.

Plot: The true story of a Hawaiian princess' attempts to maintain the independence of the island against the threat of American colonization.
Title: Princess Kaiulani
Actors: Q'orianka Kilcher, Barry Pepper, Shaun Evans, Jimmy Yuill
tomatoConsensus: A middling biopic about an important figure in Hawaiian history, Princes Kaiulani looks and feels like a TV movie of the week and offers about as much insight.

Plot: An action-comedy about a simple cook from Chandni Chowk mistaken for the reincarnation of an ancient peasant warrior Liu Shengh by residents of an oppressed Chinese village.
Title: Chandni Chowk to China
Writer: Rajat Arora (dialogue), Bohemia (lyrics), Kailash Kher (lyrics), Shridhar Raghavan
Actors: Mithun Chakraborty, Akshay Kumar, Deepika Padukone, Ranvir Shorey
tomatoConsensus: A thin plot is disguised by high octane dancing and action in this Bollywood crossover comedy.

Plot: A young ladies' man teaches his dating tricks to his lonely, widowed grandfather, and plays his best mind games to meet the woman of his dreams.
Title: Play the Game
Actors: Paul Campbell, Andy Griffith, Doris Roberts, Marla Sokoloff
tomatoConsensus: Andy Griffith is his usually likable self, but he's stranded in a middling comedy that's surprisingly tasteless and poorly crafted.

Plot: Based on a true story, a group of boys from Monterrey, Mexico who become the first non-U.S. team to win the Little League World Series.
Title: The Perfect Game
Writer: W. William Winokur, W. William Winokur (book)
Actors: Jake T. Austin, Jansen Panettiere, Moises Arias, Ryan Ochoa
tomatoConsensus: It's bogged down with an unfocused script and countless sports movie cliches, but The Perfect Game still manages to charm with its unabashed sweetness and a stirring final act.

Plot: In the early 70s, Cathy Rush becomes the head basketball coach at a tiny, all-girls Catholic college. Though her team has no gym and no uniforms -- and the school itself is in danger of being sold -- Coach Rush looks to steer her girls to their first national championship.
Title: The Mighty Macs
Writer: Tim Chambers (screenplay), Tim Chambers (story), Anthony Gargano (story)
Actors: Carla Gugino, David Boreanaz, Ellen Burstyn, Marley Shelton
tomatoConsensus: Its heart is obviously in the right place, but The Mighty Macs is too blandly formulaic to transcend the genre's many clichés.

Plot: An intimate and moving account of one family's extraordinary courage in the face of overwhelming injustice and brutality.
Title: Mugabe and the White African
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 6 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: As much legal thriller as objective documentary, this account of a farmer's battle with Zimbabwe's regime serves as a powerful and emotional attack upon President Mugabe.

Plot: Anna Brady plans to travel to Dublin, Ireland to propose marriage to her boyfriend Jeremy on Leap Day, because, according to Irish tradition, a man who receives a marriage proposal on a leap day must accept it.
Title: Leap Year
Actors: Amy Adams, Matthew Goode, Adam Scott, John Lithgow
tomatoConsensus: Amy Adams is as appealing as ever, but her charms aren't enough to keep Leap Year from succumbing to an overabundance of clichés and an unfunny script.

Plot: A post-apocalyptic tale, in which a lone man fights his way across America in order to protect a sacred book that holds the secrets to saving humankind.
Title: The Book of Eli
Actors: Denzel Washington, Gary Oldman, Mila Kunis, Ray Stevenson
tomatoConsensus: It's certainly uneven, and many viewers will find that its reach exceeds its grasp, but The Book of Eli finds the Hughes brothers injecting some fresh stylish fun into the kind of post-apocalyptic wasteland filmgoers have seen more than enough of lately.

Plot: When a group of strangers at a dusty roadside diner come under attack by demonic forces, their only chance for survival lies with an archangel named Michael, who informs a pregnant waitress that her unborn child is humanity's last hope.
Title: Legion
Actors: Paul Bettany, Lucas Black, Tyrese Gibson, Adrianne Palicki
tomatoConsensus: Despite a solid cast and intermittent thrills, Legion suffers from a curiously languid pace, confused plot, and an excess of dialogue.

Plot: A drama centered on the efforts of John and Aileen Crowley to find a researcher who might have a cure for their two children's rare genetic disorder.
Title: Extraordinary Measures
Actors: Brendan Fraser, Harrison Ford, Keri Russell, Meredith Droeger
tomatoConsensus: Despite a timely topic and a pair of heavyweight leads, Extraordinary Measures never feels like much more than a made-for-TV tearjerker.

Plot: Beth is a young, ambitious New Yorker who is completely unlucky in love. However, on a whirlwind trip to Rome, she impulsively steals some coins from a reputed fountain of love, and is then aggressively pursued by a band of suitors.
Title: When in Rome
Actors: Kristen Bell, Josh Duhamel, Anjelica Huston, Danny DeVito
tomatoConsensus: A pair of young, attractive leads can't overcome When in Rome's reliance on unfunny gags and threadbare rom-com clichés.

Plot: As homicide detective Thomas Craven investigates the death of his activist daughter, he uncovers not only her secret life, but a corporate cover-up and government collusion that attracts an agent tasked with cleaning up the evidence.
Title: Edge of Darkness
Writer: William Monahan (screenplay), Andrew Bovell (screenplay), Troy Kennedy-Martin (television series)
Actors: Mel Gibson, Ray Winstone, Danny Huston, Bojana Novakovic
tomatoConsensus: For better and for worse, Edge of Darkness offers vintage Mel Gibson, working within the familiar framework of a bloody revenge thriller.

Plot: Intertwining couples and singles in Los Angeles break-up and make-up based on the pressures and expectations of Valentine's Day.
Title: Valentine's Day
Writer: Katherine Fugate (screenplay), Katherine Fugate (story), Abby Kohn (story), Marc Silverstein (story)
Actors: Jessica Alba, Kathy Bates, Jessica Biel, Bradley Cooper
tomatoConsensus: Eager to please and stuffed with stars, Valentine's Day squanders its promise with a frantic, episodic plot and an abundance of rom-com cliches.

Plot: Upon his return to his ancestral homeland, an American man is bitten, and subsequently cursed by, a werewolf.
Title: The Wolfman
Writer: Andrew Kevin Walker (screenplay), David Self (screenplay), Curt Siodmak
Actors: Simon Merrells, Gemma Whelan, Emily Blunt, Benicio Del Toro
tomatoConsensus: Suitably grand and special effects-laden, The Wolfman suffers from a suspense-deficient script and a surprising lack of genuine chills.

Plot: In 1954, a U.S. marshal investigates the disappearance of a murderess who escaped from a hospital for the criminally insane.
Title: Shutter Island
Actors: Leonardo DiCaprio, Mark Ruffalo, Ben Kingsley, Max von Sydow
tomatoConsensus: It may not rank with Scorsese's best work, but Shutter Island's gleefully unapologetic genre thrills represent the director at his most unrestrained.

Plot: Jimmy's rare baseball card is robbed. Since it's his only hope to pay for his daughter's upcoming wedding, he recruits his cop partner Paul to track down the robber, a memorabilia-obsessed gangster.
Title: Cop Out
Actors: Bruce Willis, Tracy Morgan, Juan Carlos Hernández, Cory Fernandez
tomatoConsensus: Cop Out is a cliched buddy action/comedy that suffers from stale gags and slack pacing.

Plot: A ghostwriter hired to complete the memoirs of a former British prime minister uncovers secrets that put his own life in jeopardy.
Title: The Ghost Writer
Writer: Robert Harris (screenplay), Roman Polanski (screenplay), Robert Harris (novel)
Actors: Ewan McGregor, Jon Bernthal, Tim Preece, Jim Belushi
tomatoConsensus: While it may lack the revelatory punch of Polanski's finest films, Ghost Writer benefits from stylish direction, a tense screenplay, and a strong central performance from Ewan McGregor.

Plot: Former CIA spy Bob Ho takes on his toughest assignment to date: looking after his girlfriend's three kids, who haven't exactly warmed to their mom's beau.
Title: The Spy Next Door
Writer: Jonathan Bernstein (screenplay), James Greer (screenplay), Gregory Poirier (screenplay), Jonathan Bernstein (story), James Greer (story)
Actors: Jackie Chan, Amber Valletta, Madeline Carroll, Will Shadley
tomatoConsensus: Lacking a script funny enough to cover up for Jackie Chan's fading physical gifts, The Spy Next Door fails on every conceivable level.

Plot: A drama based on the true story in which a black Vietnam-era veteran is allegedly murdered by a local white businessman who is later exonerated. The plot focuses on the role of a local high school teacher and the civil unrest that followed the acquittal.
Title: Blood Done Sign My Name
Actors: Nate Parker, Natalie Alyn Lind, Michael Rooker, Emily Alyn Lind
tomatoConsensus: Even among civil rights movies, Blood Done Sign My Name is remarkably earnest, but its big heart can't cover for the bland acting and TV-style melodrama that blunts the movie's impact.

Plot: About the inhabitants of a small Iowa town suddenly plagued by insanity and then death after a mysterious toxin contaminates their water supply.
Title: The Crazies
Writer: Scott Kosar (screenplay), Ray Wright (screenplay), George A. Romero
Actors: Timothy Olyphant, Radha Mitchell, Joe Anderson, Danielle Panabaker
tomatoConsensus: Tense, nicely shot, and uncommonly intelligent, The Crazies is a horror remake that, unusually, works.

Plot: A romantic drama about a soldier who falls for a conservative college student while he's home on leave.
Title: Dear John
Actors: Channing Tatum, Amanda Seyfried, Richard Jenkins, Henry Thomas
tomatoConsensus: Built from many of the same ingredients as other Nicholas Sparks tearjerkers, Dear John suffers from its cliched framework, as well as Lasse Hallstrom's curiously detached directing.

Plot: A bad deed on the part of a tough minor-league hockey player results in an unusual sentence: He must serve one week as a real-life tooth fairy.
Title: Tooth Fairy
Writer: Lowell Ganz (screenplay), Babaloo Mandel (screenplay), Joshua Sternin (screenplay), Jennifer Ventimilia (screenplay), Randi Mayem Singer (screenplay), Jim Piddock (story)
Actors: Dwayne Johnson, Ashley Judd, Stephen Merchant, Ryan Sheckler
tomatoConsensus: Dwayne Johnson brings the full force of his charm (and his appropriately pale chompers) to the title role, but flat direction and a committee-written script render The Tooth Fairy unacceptably dull.

Plot: Nineteen-year-old Alice returns to the magical world from her childhood adventure, where she reunites with her old friends and learns of her true destiny: to end the Red Queen's reign of terror.
Title: Alice in Wonderland
Actors: Johnny Depp, Mia Wasikowska, Helena Bonham Carter, Anne Hathaway
tomatoConsensus: Tim Burton's Alice sacrifices the book's minimal narrative coherence -- and much of its heart -- but it's an undeniable visual treat.

Plot: Discovering covert and faulty intelligence causes a U.S. Army officer to go rogue as he hunts for Weapons of Mass Destruction in an unstable region.
Title: Green Zone
Actors: Igal Naor, Said Faraj, Faycal Attougui, Aymen Hamdouchi
tomatoConsensus: Matt Damon and Paul Greengrass return to the propulsive action and visceral editing of the Bourne films -- but a cliched script and stock characters keep those methods from being as effective this time around.

Plot: In Paris, a young employee in the office of the US Ambassador hooks up with an American spy looking to stop a terrorist attack in the city.
Title: From Paris with Love
Actors: John Travolta, Jonathan Rhys Meyers, Kasia Smutniak, Richard Durden
tomatoConsensus: Thought not without its charms -- chief among them John Travolta's endearingly over-the-top performance -- From Paris with Love is too muddled and disjointed to satisfy.

Plot: A man from Los Angeles, who moved to New York years ago, returns to L.A. to figure out his life while he house-sits for his brother. He soon sparks with his brother's assistant.
Title: Greenberg
Writer: Jennifer Jason Leigh (story), Noah Baumbach (story), Noah Baumbach (screenplay)
Actors: Greta Gerwig, Koby Rouviere, Sydney Rouviere, Chris Messina
tomatoConsensus: Greenberg's title character is harder to like than most, but Ben Stiller's nuanced performance and a darkly funny script help take the misanthropic edge off.

Plot: An average Joe meets the perfect woman, but his lack of confidence and the influence of his friends and family begin to pick away at the relationship.
Title: She's Out of My League
Actors: Jay Baruchel, Alice Eve, T.J. Miller, Mike Vogel
tomatoConsensus: She's Out of My League has moments of humor and insight, but it's bogged down by excessive vulgarity and cartoonishness.

Plot: A romantic drama centered on two new lovers: Tyler, whose parents have split in the wake of his brother's suicide, and Ally, who lives each day to the fullest since witnessing her mother's murder.
Title: Remember Me
Actors: Caitlyn Rund, Moisés Acevedo, Noel Rodriguez, Kevin P. McCarthy
tomatoConsensus: Its leads are likeable, but Remember Me suffers from an overly maudlin script and a borderline offensive final twist.

Plot: Three skiers stranded on a chairlift are forced to make life-or-death choices which prove more perilous than staying put and freezing to death.
Title: Frozen
Actors: Emma Bell, Shawn Ashmore, Kevin Zegers, Ed Ackerman
tomatoConsensus: Writer/director Adam Green has the beginnings of an inventive, frightening yarn in Frozen, but neither the script nor the cast are quite strong enough to truly do it justice.

Plot: The weeks leading up to a young couple's wedding are comic and stressful, especially as their respective fathers try to lay their long standing feud to rest.
Title: Our Family Wedding
Writer: Wayne Conley (story), Wayne Conley (screenplay), Malcolm Spellman (screenplay), Rick Famuyiwa (screenplay)
Actors: Forest Whitaker, America Ferrera, Carlos Mencia, Regina King
tomatoConsensus: Our Family Wedding is a mirthless, contrived affair that does little with its promising premise and talented cast.

Plot: A bounty hunter learns that his next target is his ex-wife, a reporter working on a murder cover-up. Soon after their reunion, the always-at-odds duo find themselves on a run-for-their-lives adventure.
Title: The Bounty Hunter
Actors: Gerard Butler, Jennifer Aniston, Gio Perez, Joel Marsh Garland
tomatoConsensus: Gerard Butler and Jennifer Aniston remain as attractive as ever, but The Bounty Hunter's formula script doesn't know what to do with them -- or the audience's attention.

Plot: Set in the near future when artificial organs can be bought on credit, it revolves around a man who struggles to make the payments on a heart he has purchased. He must therefore go on the run before said ticker is repossessed.
Title: Repo Men
Writer: Eric Garcia (screenplay), Garrett Lerner (screenplay), Eric Garcia (novel)
Actors: Jude Law, Forest Whitaker, Alice Braga, Liev Schreiber
