tomatoConsensus: Repo Men has an intriguing premise, as well as a likable pair of leads, but they're wasted on a rote screenplay, indifferent direction, and mind-numbing gore.

Plot: A malfunctioning time machine at a ski resort takes a man back to 1986 with his two friends and nephew, where they must relive a fateful night and not change anything to make sure the nephew is born.
Title: Hot Tub Time Machine
Writer: Josh Heald (screenplay), Sean Anders (screenplay), John Morris (screenplay), Josh Heald (story)
Actors: John Cusack, Clark Duke, Craig Robinson, Rob Corddry
tomatoConsensus: Its flagrantly silly script -- and immensely likable cast -- make up for most of its flaws.

Plot: A hapless young Viking who aspires to hunt dragons becomes the unlikely friend of a young dragon himself, and learns there may be more to the creatures than he assumed.
Title: How to Train Your Dragon
Writer: William Davies (screenplay), Dean DeBlois (screenplay), Chris Sanders (screenplay), Cressida Cowell (book)
Actors: Jay Baruchel, Gerard Butler, Craig Ferguson, America Ferrera
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 25 wins & 58 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Boasting dazzling animation, a script with surprising dramatic depth, and thrilling 3-D sequences, How to Train Your Dragon soars.

Plot: Perseus demigod, son of Zeus, battles the minions of the underworld to stop them from conquering heaven and earth.
Title: Clash of the Titans
Writer: Travis Beacham (screenplay), Phil Hay (screenplay), Matt Manfredi (screenplay), Beverley Cross
Actors: Sam Worthington, Liam Neeson, Ralph Fiennes, Jason Flemyng
tomatoConsensus: An obviously affectionate remake of the 1981 original, Louis Leterrier's Clash of the Titans doesn't offer enough visual thrills to offset the deficiencies of its script.

Plot: Dave Lizewski is an unnoticed high school student and comic book fan who one day decides to become a superhero, even though he has no powers, training or meaningful reason to do so.
Title: Kick-Ass
Writer: Jane Goldman (screenplay), Matthew Vaughn (screenplay), Mark Millar (comic book), John Romita Jr. (comic book)
Actors: Aaron Taylor-Johnson, Garrett M. Brown, Evan Peters, Deborah Twiss
tomatoConsensus: Not for the faint of heart, Kick-Ass takes the comic adaptation genre to new levels of visual style, bloody violence, and gleeful profanity.

Plot: In New York City, a case of mistaken identity turns a bored married couple's attempt at a glamorous and romantic evening into something more thrilling and dangerous.
Title: Date Night
Actors: Steve Carell, Tina Fey, Mark Wahlberg, Taraji P. Henson
tomatoConsensus: An uneasy blend of action and comedy, Date Night doesn't quite live up to the talents of its two leads, but Steve Carell and Tina Fey still manage to shine through most of the movie's flaws.

Plot: A coming-of-age biographical film about the 1970s teenage all-girl rock band The Runaways. This film also explores the relationship between band members Joan Jett and Cherie Currie.
Title: The Runaways
Actors: Kristen Stewart, Dakota Fanning, Michael Shannon, Stella Maeve
tomatoConsensus: Viewers expecting an in-depth biopic will be disappointed, but The Runaways is as electric as the band's music, largely thanks to strong performances from Michael Shannon, Dakota Fanning, and Kristen Stewart.

Plot: A funeral ceremony turns into a debacle of exposed family secrets and misplaced bodies.
Title: Death at a Funeral
Actors: Keith David, Loretta Devine, Peter Dinklage, Ron Glass
tomatoConsensus: It's amusing and it assembles a talented cast, but Neil LaBute's surprisingly faithful remake of the 2007 Frank Oz dramedy ultimately falls short of the original.

Plot: The adventures of a teenager who is fresh out and in elementary, where he has to learn the consequences and responsibility to survive the year.
Title: Diary of a Wimpy Kid
Writer: Jackie Filgo (screenplay), Jeff Filgo (screenplay), Gabe Sachs (screenplay), Jeff Judah (screenplay), Jeff Kinney (book)
Actors: Zachary Gordon, Robert Capron, Rachael Harris, Steve Zahn
tomatoConsensus: Unlike its bestselling source material, Diary of a Wimpy Kid fails to place a likable protagonist at the center of its middle-school humor -- and its underlying message is drowned out as a result.

Plot: A CIA special forces team are betrayed and left for dead by their superiors, galvanizing them to mount an offensive on the CIA.
Title: The Losers
Writer: Peter Berg (screenplay), James Vanderbilt (screenplay), Andy Diggle (characters)
Actors: Jeffrey Dean Morgan, Zoe Saldana, Chris Evans, Idris Elba
tomatoConsensus: The Losers is loud, fast, and unrelentingly violent -- but it's also funny and well-acted, which will make all the difference for some action fans.

Plot: A rebellious girl is sent to a Southern beach town for the summer to stay with her father. Through their mutual love of music, the estranged duo learn to reconnect.
Title: The Last Song
Writer: Nicholas Sparks (screenplay), Jeff Van Wie (screenplay), Nicholas Sparks (book)
Actors: Miley Cyrus, Greg Kinnear, Bobby Coleman, Liam Hemsworth
tomatoConsensus: As shamelessly manipulative as any Nicholas Sparks production, The Last Song is done no favors by its miscast and overmatched star, Miley Cyrus.

Plot: John and Molly, a divorced middle aged man and a single mother meet at a friends party and start up a small relationship, all John has to do now is meet Molly's son... Cyrus
Title: Cyrus
Actors: John C. Reilly, Jonah Hill, Marisa Tomei, Catherine Keener
tomatoConsensus: While it may strike some viewers as slight, Cyrus is a successful hybrid of mainstream production values and the mumblecore ideals of directors Jay and Mark Duplass.

Plot: The story of how an eccentric French shop-keeper and amateur film-maker attempted to locate and befriend Banksy, only to have the artist turn the camera back on its owner. The film contains...
Title: Exit Through the Gift Shop
Actors: Banksy, Mr. Brainwash, Debora Guetta, Space Invader
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 24 wins & 28 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: An amusing, engrossing look at underground art, Exit Through the Gift Shop entertains as it deflates the myths and hype surrounding its subjects.

Plot: With the world now aware of his identity as Iron Man, Tony Stark must contend with both his declining health and a vengeful mad man with ties to his father's legacy.
Title: Iron Man 2
Writer: Justin Theroux (screenplay), Stan Lee (Marvel comic book), Don Heck (Marvel comic book), Larry Lieber (Marvel comic book), Jack Kirby (Marvel comic book)
Actors: Robert Downey Jr., Gwyneth Paltrow, Don Cheadle, Scarlett Johansson
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 40 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It isn't quite the breath of fresh air that Iron Man was, but this sequel comes close with solid performances and an action-packed plot.

Plot: A suburban family moves to a new neighborhood with their large yet lovable Great Dane, who has a tendency to wreak havoc in his own oblivious way.
Title: Marmaduke
Writer: Tim Rasmussen, Vince Di Meglio, Brad Anderson (comic), Phil Leeming (comic)
Actors: Owen Wilson, Emma Stone, George Lopez, Christopher Mintz-Plasse
tomatoConsensus: Dull and unfunny, Marmaduke offers family filmgoers little more than another round of talking animals and scatological humor.

Plot: Former special operative MacGruber is called back into action to take down his arch-enemy, Dieter Von Cunth, who's in possession of a nuclear warhead and bent on destroying Washington, D.C.
Title: MacGruber
Writer: Will Forte, John Solomon, Jorma Taccone
Actors: Will Forte, Kristen Wiig, Ryan Phillippe, Val Kilmer
tomatoConsensus: It too often mistakes shock value for real humor, but MacGruber is better than many SNL films -- and better than it probably should be.

Plot: The spectre of a dead child rapist haunts the children of the parents who murdered him, stalking and killing them in their dreams.
Title: A Nightmare on Elm Street
Writer: Wesley Strick (screenplay), Eric Heisserer (screenplay), Wesley Strick (story), Wes Craven (characters)
Actors: Jackie Earle Haley, Kyle Gallner, Rooney Mara, Katie Cassidy
tomatoConsensus: Visually faithful but lacking the depth and subversive twists that made the original so memorable, the Nightmare on Elm Street remake lives up to its title in the worst possible way.

Plot: Four incompetent British jihadists set out to train for and commit an act of terror.
Title: Four Lions
Writer: Christopher Morris, Sam Bain, Jesse Armstrong, Simon Blackwell (additional writing)
Actors: Riz Ahmed, Arsher Ali, Nigel Lindsay, Kayvan Novak
Awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 8 wins & 23 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Its premise suggests brazenly tasteless humor, but Four Lions is actually a smart, pitch-black comedy that carries the unmistakable ring of truth.

Plot: In 12th century England, Robin and his band of marauders confront corruption in a local village and lead an uprising against the crown that will forever alter the balance of world power.
Title: Robin Hood
Writer: Brian Helgeland (screenplay), Brian Helgeland (story), Ethan Reiff (story), Cyrus Voris (story)
Actors: Russell Crowe, Cate Blanchett, Max von Sydow, William Hurt
tomatoConsensus: Ridley Scott's revisionist take on this oft-told tale offers some fine acting and a few gripping action sequences, but it's missing the thrill of adventure that made Robin Hood a legend in the first place.

Plot: The relationship of a contemporary married couple, charting their evolution over a span of years by cross-cutting between time periods.
Title: Blue Valentine
Writer: Derek Cianfrance, Joey Curtis, Cami Delavigne
Actors: Ryan Gosling, Michelle Williams, Faith Wladyka, John Doman
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 50 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This emotionally gripping examination of a marriage on the rocks isn't always easy to watch, but Michelle Williams and Ryan Gosling give performances of unusual depth and power.

Plot: A vacationing woman meets her ideal man, leading to a swift marriage. Back at home, however, their idyllic life is upset when they discover their neighbors could be assassins who have been contracted to kill the couple.
Title: Killers
Writer: Bob DeRosa (screenplay), Ted Griffin (screenplay), Bob DeRosa (story)
Actors: Ashton Kutcher, Katherine Heigl, Tom Selleck, Catherine O'Hara
tomatoConsensus: Dull, formulaic, and chemistry-free, Killers is an action/comedy that's largely bereft of thrills or laughs.

Plot: Paul is a U.S. truck driver working in Iraq. After an attack by a group of Iraqis he wakes to find he is buried alive inside a coffin. With only a lighter and a cell phone it's a race against time to escape this claustrophobic death trap.
Title: Buried
Actors: Ryan Reynolds, José Luis García Pérez, Robert Paterson, Stephen Tobolowsky
tomatoConsensus: Wringing a seemingly impossible amount of gripping drama out of its claustrophobic premise, Buried is a nerve-wracking showcase for Ryan Reynolds' talent.

Plot: A young fugitive prince and princess must stop a villain who unknowingly threatens to destroy the world with a special dagger that enables the magic sand inside to reverse time.
Title: Prince of Persia: The Sands of Time
Writer: Boaz Yakin (screenplay), Doug Miro (screenplay), Carlo Bernard (screenplay), Jordan Mechner (screen story), Jordan Mechner (video game series "Prince of Persia")
Actors: Jake Gyllenhaal, Gemma Arterton, Ben Kingsley, Alfred Molina
tomatoConsensus: It doesn't offer much in the way of substance, but Prince of Persia is a suitably entertaining swashbuckler -- and a substantial improvement over most video game adaptations.

Plot: In New York City, a husband and wife butt heads with the granddaughters of the elderly woman who lives in the apartment the couple owns.
Title: Please Give
Actors: Rebecca Hall, Elizabeth Keener, Elise Ivy, Catherine Keener
tomatoConsensus: Nicole Holofcener's newest might seem slight in places, but its rendering of complex characters in a conflicted economic landscape is varied, natural, and touching all the same.

Plot: While wrestling with the pressures of life, love, and work in Manhattan, Carrie, Miranda, and Charlotte join Samantha for a trip to Abu Dhabi (United Arab Emirates), where Samantha's ex is filming a new movie.
Title: Sex and the City 2
Writer: Michael Patrick King, Candace Bushnell (characters from the book by), Darren Star (television series creator)
Actors: Sarah Jessica Parker, Kristin Davis, Cynthia Nixon, Kim Cattrall
tomatoConsensus: Straining under a thin plot stretched to its limit by a bloated running time, Sex and the City 2 adds an unfortunate coda to the long-running HBO series.

Plot: A record company intern is hired to accompany out-of-control British rock star Aldous Snow to a concert at L.A.'s Greek Theater.
Title: Get Him to the Greek
Actors: Russell Brand, Rose Byrne, Tyler McKinney, Zoe Salmon
tomatoConsensus: Thanks to a suitably raunchy script and a pair of winning performances from Jonah Hill and Russell Brand, Get Him to the Greek is one of the year's funniest comedies.

Plot: A woman conceives twins through artificial insemination, only to meet the man of her dreams on the very same day.
Title: The Back-up Plan
Actors: Jennifer Lopez, Alex O'Loughlin, Michaela Watkins, Eric Christian Olsen
tomatoConsensus: Jennifer Lopez is as appealing as ever, but The Back-Up Plan smothers its star with unrelatable characters and a predictable plot.

Plot: Sophie dreams of becoming a writer and travels to Verona, Italy where she meets the "Secretaries of Juliet".
Title: Letters to Juliet
Actors: Amanda Seyfried, Marcia DeBonis, Gael García Bernal, Giordano Formenti
tomatoConsensus: Letters to Juliet has a refreshingly earnest romantic charm, but it suffers from limp dialogue and an utter lack of surprises.

Plot: The U.S. military makes a scarred bounty hunter with warrants on his own head an offer he cannot refuse: in exchange for his freedom, he must stop a terrorist who is ready to unleash Hell on Earth.
Title: Jonah Hex
Writer: Mark Neveldine (screenplay), Brian Taylor (screenplay), William Farmer (story), Mark Neveldine (story), Brian Taylor (story), John Albano (characters appearing in magazines published by DC Comics), Tony DeZuniga (characters appearing in magazines published by DC Comics)
Actors: Josh Brolin, John Malkovich, Megan Fox, Michael Fassbender
tomatoConsensus: Josh Brolin gives it his best shot, but he can't keep the short, unfocused Jonah Hex from collapsing on the screen.

Plot: A group of Iraq War veterans looks to clear their name with the U.S. military, who suspect the four men of committing a crime for which they were framed.
Title: The A-Team
Writer: Joe Carnahan, Brian Bloom, Skip Woods, Frank Lupo (television series "The A-Team"), Stephen J. Cannell (television series "The A-Team")
Actors: Liam Neeson, Bradley Cooper, Jessica Biel, Quinton 'Rampage' Jackson
tomatoConsensus: For better and for worse, Joe Carnahan's big-screen version of The A-Team captures the superficial, noisy spirit of the TV series.

Plot: The toys are mistakenly delivered to a day-care center instead of the attic right before Andy leaves for college, and it's up to Woody to convince the other toys that they weren't abandoned and to return home.
Title: Toy Story 3
Writer: John Lasseter (story by), Andrew Stanton (story by), Lee Unkrich (story by), Michael Arndt (screenplay)
Actors: Tom Hanks, Tim Allen, Joan Cusack, Ned Beatty
tomatoConsensus: Deftly blending comedy, adventure, and honest emotion, Toy Story 3 is a rare second sequel that really works.

Plot: A documentary on the life and career of Joan Rivers, made as the comedienne turns 75 years old.
Title: Joan Rivers: A Piece of Work
Actors: Joan Rivers, Jocelyn Pickett, Bill Sammeth, Larry A. Thompson
tomatoConsensus: Penetrating Rivers' coarse image, this compelling documentary offers an honest, behind-the-scenes look at her career -- and at show business in general.

Plot: An unflinching Ozark Mountain girl hacks through dangerous social terrain as she hunts down her drug-dealing father while trying to keep her family intact.
Title: Winter's Bone
Writer: Debra Granik (screenplay), Anne Rosellini (screenplay), Daniel Woodrell (novel)
Actors: Jennifer Lawrence, Isaiah Stone, Ashlee Thompson, Valerie Richards
Awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 63 wins & 118 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Bleak, haunting, and yet still somehow hopeful, Winter's Bone is writer-director Debra Granik's best work yet -- and it boasts an incredible, starmaking performance from Jennifer Lawrence.

Plot: Rumpelstiltskin tricks a mid-life crisis burdened Shrek into allowing himself to be erased from existence and cast in a dark alternate timeline where Rumpel rules supreme.
Title: Shrek Forever After
Writer: William Steig (book), Josh Klausner, Darren Lemke
Actors: Mike Myers, Eddie Murphy, Cameron Diaz, Antonio Banderas
tomatoConsensus: While not without its moments, Shrek Forever After too often feels like a rote rehashing of the franchise's earlier entries.

Plot: A West Texas deputy sheriff is slowly unmasked as a psychotic killer.
Title: The Killer Inside Me
Actors: Casey Affleck, Kate Hudson, Jessica Alba, Ned Beatty
tomatoConsensus: The Killer Inside Me is stylish and beautifully shot, but Michael Winterbottom's distance from his characters robs this often brutally violent film of crucial emotional context.

Plot: As a string of mysterious killings grips Seattle, Bella, whose high school graduation is fast approaching, is forced to choose between her love for vampire Edward and her friendship with werewolf Jacob.
Title: The Twilight Saga: Eclipse
Actors: Xavier Samuel, Kristen Stewart, Robert Pattinson, Billy Burke
tomatoConsensus: Stuffed with characters and overly reliant on uninspired dialogue, Eclipse won't win The Twilight Saga many new converts, despite an improved blend of romance and action fantasy.

Plot: Follows the adventures of Aang, a young successor to a long line of Avatars, who must master all four elements and stop the Fire Nation from enslaving the Water Tribes and the Earth Kingdom.
Title: The Last Airbender
Actors: Noah Ringer, Dev Patel, Nicola Peltz, Jackson Rathbone
tomatoConsensus: The Last Airbender squanders its popular source material with incomprehensible plotting, horrible acting, and detached joyless direction.

Plot: A group of elite warriors parachute into an unfamiliar jungle and are hunted by members of a merciless alien race.
Title: Predators
Writer: Alex Litvak, Michael Finch, Jim Thomas (characters), John Thomas (characters)
Actors: Adrien Brody, Topher Grace, Alice Braga, Walton Goggins
tomatoConsensus: After a string of subpar sequels, this bloody, action-packed reboot takes the Predator franchise back to its testosterone-fueled roots.

Plot: When a criminal mastermind uses a trio of orphan girls as pawns for a grand scheme, he finds their love is profoundly changing him for the better.
Title: Despicable Me
Writer: Cinco Paul (screenplay), Ken Daurio (screenplay), Sergio Pablos (story)
Actors: Steve Carell, Jason Segel, Russell Brand, Julie Andrews
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 38 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Borrowing heavily (and intelligently) from Pixar and Looney Tunes, Despicable Me is a surprisingly thoughtful, family-friendly treat with a few surprises of its own.

Plot: After their high school basketball coach passes away, five good friends and former teammates reunite for a Fourth of July holiday weekend.
Title: Grown Ups
Actors: Adam Sandler, Kevin James, Chris Rock, David Spade
tomatoConsensus: Grown Ups' cast of comedy vets is amiable, but they're let down by flat direction and the scattershot, lowbrow humor of a stunted script.

Plot: Master sorcerer Balthazar Blake must find and train Merlin's descendant to defeat dark sorceress Morgana la Fée.
Title: The Sorcerer's Apprentice
Writer: Lawrence Konner (screen story), Mark Rosenthal (screen story), Matt Lopez (screen story), Matt Lopez (screenplay), Doug Miro (screenplay), Carlo Bernard (screenplay)
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Jay Baruchel, Alfred Molina, Teresa Palmer
tomatoConsensus: It has a likable cast and loads of CGI spectacle, but for all but the least demanding viewers, The Sorcerer's Apprentice will be less than spellbinding.

Plot: A young woman gets mixed up with a disgraced spy who is trying to clear his name.
Title: Knight and Day
Actors: Tom Cruise, Cameron Diaz, Peter Sarsgaard, Jordi Mollà
tomatoConsensus: It's pure formula, but thanks to its breezy pace and a pair of charming performances from Tom Cruise and Cameron Diaz, Knight and Day offers some agreeably middle-of-the-road summer action.

Plot: Work causes a single mother to move to China with her young son; in his new home, the boy embraces kung fu, taught to him by a master.
Title: The Karate Kid
Actors: Jaden Smith, Jackie Chan, Taraji P. Henson, Wenwen Han
tomatoConsensus: It may not be as powerful as the 1984 edition, but the 2010 Karate Kid delivers a surprisingly satisfying update on the original.

Plot: Two children conceived by artificial insemination bring their biological father into their non-traditional family life.
Title: The Kids Are All Right
Actors: Julianne Moore, Annette Bening, Mark Ruffalo, Mia Wasikowska
Awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 28 wins & 116 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Worthwhile as both a well-acted ensemble piece and as a smart, warm statement on family values, The Kids Are All Right is remarkable.

Plot: A CIA agent goes on the run after a defector accuses her of being a Russian spy.
Title: Salt
Actors: Angelina Jolie, Liev Schreiber, Chiwetel Ejiofor, Daniel Olbrychski
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 16 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Angelina Jolie gives it her all in the title role, and her seasoned performance is almost enough to save Salt from its predictable and ludicrous plot.

Plot: When he finds out that his work superiors host a dinner celebrating the idiocy of their guests, a rising executive questions it when he's invited, just as he befriends a man who would be the perfect guest.
Title: Dinner for Schmucks
Writer: David Guion (screenplay), Michael Handelman (screenplay), Francis Veber (film "Le Diner de Cons")
Actors: Steve Carell, Paul Rudd, Zach Galifianakis, Jemaine Clement
tomatoConsensus: It doesn't honor its source material -- or its immensely likable leads -- as well as it should, but Dinner for Schmucks offers fitfully nourishing comedy.

Plot: A scorching indictment of the Mormon Church's historic involvement in the promotion & passage of California's Proposition 8 and the Mormon religion's secretive, decades-long campaign against LGBT human rights.
Title: 8: The Mormon Proposition
Actors: Spencer Jones, Tyler Barrick, Dustin Lance Black, Linda Williams Stay
tomatoConsensus: It's unabashedly biased, but this look at the fight over gay marriage in California is impassioned and provocative.

Plot: Nanny McPhee arrives to help a harried young mother who is trying to run the family farm while her husband is away at war, though she uses her magic to teach the woman's children and their two spoiled cousins five new lessons.
Title: Nanny McPhee Returns
Actors: Maggie Gyllenhaal, Oscar Steer, Asa Butterfield, Lil Woods
tomatoConsensus: Emma Thompson's second labor of love with the Nanny McPhee character actually improves on the first, delivering charming family fare with an excellent cast.

Plot: An adventurous young girl uses her imagination to escape her reality, that is quickly spinning out of reach.
Title: Ramona and Beezus
Writer: Laurie Craig (screenplay), Nick Pustay (screenplay), Beverly Cleary (novels)
Actors: Joey King, Selena Gomez, John Corbett, Bridget Moynahan
tomatoConsensus: If Ramona and Beezus fails to capture the essence of its classic source material, it's sunny, sweet, and wholesome.

Plot: Charlie's brother, Sam, dies in a car crash that Charlie survives. Charlie is given the gift of seeing his dead brother, but when the girl he falls in love with's life is at risk, he must choose between his girlfriend and his brother.
Title: Charlie St. Cloud
Writer: Craig Pearce (screenplay), Lewis Colick (screenplay), Ben Sherwood (novel)
Actors: Zac Efron, Charlie Tahan, Amanda Crew, Augustus Prew
tomatoConsensus: Zac Efron gives it his all, but Charlie St. Cloud is too shallow and cloying to offer much more than eye candy for his fans.

Plot: Two mismatched New York City detectives seize an opportunity to step up like the city's top cops whom they idolize -- only things don't quite go as planned.
Title: The Other Guys
Actors: Will Ferrell, Derek Jeter, Mark Wahlberg, Eva Mendes
tomatoConsensus: A clever parody of cop-buddy action-comedies, The Other Guys delivers several impressive action set pieces and lots of big laughs, thanks to the assured comic chemistry between Will Ferrell and Mark Wahlberg.

Plot: A CIA operative hires a team of mercenaries to eliminate a Latin dictator and a renegade CIA agent.
Title: The Expendables
Writer: Dave Callaham (screenplay), Sylvester Stallone (screenplay), Dave Callaham (story)
Actors: Sylvester Stallone, Jason Statham, Jet Li, Dolph Lundgren
tomatoConsensus: It makes good on the old-school action it promises, but given all the talent on display, The Expendables should hit harder.

Plot: Scott Pilgrim must defeat his new girlfriend's seven evil exes in order to win her heart.
Title: Scott Pilgrim vs. the World
Writer: Michael Bacall (screenplay), Edgar Wright (screenplay), Bryan Lee O'Malley (Oni Press graphic novels)
Actors: Michael Cera, Alison Pill, Mark Webber, Johnny Simmons
tomatoConsensus: Its script may not be as dazzling as its eye-popping visuals, but Scott Pilgrim vs. the World is fast, funny, and inventive.

Plot: A seventeen year-old navigates his survival amongst an explosive criminal family and the detective who thinks he can save him.
Title: Animal Kingdom
Actors: James Frecheville, Bryce Lindemann, Paul Smits, Jacki Weaver
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 38 wins & 54 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: With confident pacing, a smart script, and a top-notch cast, Animal Kingdom represents the best the Australian film industry has to offer.

Plot: A splinter group of Roman soldiers fight for their lives behind enemy lines after their legion is decimated in a devastating guerrilla attack.
Title: Centurion
Actors: Michael Fassbender, Andreas Wisniewski, Dave Legeno, Axelle Carolyn
tomatoConsensus: It's a bloody geyser of Neil Marshall's typically stylish B-movie action, but Centurion is too focused on hacking and slashing to deliver original dialogue or interesting characters.

Plot: A look at one year in the life of four babies from around the world, from Mongolia to Namibia to San Francisco to Tokyo.
Title: Babies
Actors: Bayar, Hattie, Mari, Ponijao
tomatoConsensus: Babies is a joyous celebration of humankind that's loaded with adorable images, but it lacks insight and depth.

Plot: After a sudden underwater tremor sets free scores of the prehistoric man-eating fish, an unlikely group of strangers must band together to stop themselves from becoming fish food for the area's new razor-toothed residents.
Title: Piranha 3D
Actors: Richard Dreyfuss, Ving Rhames, Elisabeth Shue, Christopher Lloyd
tomatoConsensus: Playing exactly to expectations for a movie about killer fish run amok, Piranha 3-D dishes out gore, guffaws and gratuitous nudity with equal glee.

Plot: A glimpse at the life of French singer Serge Gainsbourg, from growing up in 1940s Nazi-occupied Paris through his successful song-writing years in the 1960s to his death in 1991 at the age of 62.
Title: Gainsbourg: A Heroic Life
Writer: Joann Sfar (graphic novel), Joann Sfar (screenplay), Declan May (dialogue)
Actors: Eric Elmosnino, Lucy Gordon, Laetitia Casta, Doug Jones
tomatoConsensus: It might be thinly written and messily made, but Gainsbourg: A Heroic Life is also appropriately glamorous and intense -- and powerfully led by a gripping performance from Erik Elmosnino.

Plot: A troubled evangelical minister agrees to let his last exorcism be filmed by a documentary crew.
Title: The Last Exorcism
Actors: Patrick Fabian, Ashley Bell, Iris Bahr, Louis Herthum
tomatoConsensus: It doesn't fully deliver on the chilly promise of its Blair Witch-style premise, but The Last Exorcism offers a surprising number of clever thrills.

Plot: An assassin hides out in Italy for one last assignment.
Title: The American
Actors: George Clooney, Irina Björklund, Lars Hjelm, Björn Granath
tomatoConsensus: As beautifully shot as it is emotionally restrained, The American is an unusually divisive spy thriller -- and one that rests on an unusually subdued performance from George Clooney.

Plot: Seven years after the fact, a man comes to the realization that he was the sperm donor for his best friend's boy.
Title: The Switch
Actors: Jason Bateman, Victor Pagan, Jennifer Aniston, Jeff Goldblum
tomatoConsensus: The Switch has an interesting premise and a charming cast; unfortunately, it also has a trite script that hews too close to tired rom-com formulas.

Plot: After being set-up and betrayed by the man who hired him to assassinate a Texas Senator, an ex-Federale launches a brutal rampage of revenge against his former boss.
Title: Machete
Actors: Danny Trejo, Robert De Niro, Jessica Alba, Steven Seagal
tomatoConsensus: Machete is messy, violent, shallow, and tasteless -- and that's precisely the point of one of the summer's most cartoonishly enjoyable films.

Plot: A tight-knit group of New York City street dancers find themselves pitted against the world's best hip hop dancers in a high-stakes showdown.
Title: Step Up 3D
Writer: Amy Andelson, Emily Meyer, Duane Adler (characters)
Actors: Rick Malambri, Adam G. Sevani, Sharni Vinson, Alyson Stoner
tomatoConsensus: It may not contain believable acting or a memorable plot, but Step Up 3-D delivers solid choreography and stunning visuals.

Plot: A romantic comedy centered on a guy and a gal who try to keep their love alive as they shuttle back and forth between New York and San Francisco to see one another.
Title: Going the Distance
Actors: Drew Barrymore, Justin Long, Charlie Day, Jason Sudeikis
tomatoConsensus: It's timelier and a little more honest than most romantic comedies, but Drew Barrymore and Justin Long's screen chemistry doesn't make up for Going the Distance's overall flatness.

Plot: A spoof of vampire-themed movies, where teenager Becca finds herself torn between two boys. As she and her friends wrestle with a number of different dramas, everything comes to a head at their prom.
Title: Vampires Suck
Actors: Jenn Proske, Matt Lanter, Diedrich Bader, Chris Riggi
tomatoConsensus: Witlessly broad and utterly devoid of laughs, Vampires Suck represents a slight step forward for the Friedberg-Seltzer team.

Plot: While still out to destroy the evil Umbrella Corporation, Alice joins a group of survivors living in a prison surrounded by the infected who also want to relocate to the mysterious but supposedly unharmed safe haven known only as Arcadia.
Title: Resident Evil: Afterlife
Actors: Milla Jovovich, Ali Larter, Kim Coates, Shawn Roberts
tomatoConsensus: As dim-witted and lifeless as its undead antagonists, Resident Evil: Afterlife is a wholly unnecessary addition to the franchise.

Plot: Harvard student Mark Zuckerberg creates the social networking site that would become known as Facebook, but is later sued by two brothers who claimed he stole their idea, and the co-founder who was later squeezed out of the business.
Title: The Social Network
Actors: Jesse Eisenberg, Rooney Mara, Bryan Barter, Dustin Fitzsimons
tomatoConsensus: Impeccably scripted, beautifully directed, and filled with fine performances, The Social Network is a riveting, ambitious example of modern filmmaking at its finest.

Plot: As he plans his next job, a longtime thief tries to balance his feelings for a bank manager connected to one of his earlier heists, as well as the FBI agent looking to bring him and his crew down.
Title: The Town
Writer: Peter Craig (screenplay), Ben Affleck (screenplay), Aaron Stockard (screenplay), Chuck Hogan (novel)
Actors: Ben Affleck, Rebecca Hall, Jon Hamm, Jeremy Renner
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 44 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Tense, smartly written, and wonderfully cast, The Town proves that Ben Affleck has rediscovered his muse -- and that he's a director to be reckoned with.

Plot: A clean-cut high school student relies on the school's rumor mill to advance her social and financial standing.
Title: Easy A
Actors: Emma Stone, Penn Badgley, Amanda Bynes, Dan Byrd
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 9 wins & 19 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It owes a huge debt to older (and better) teen comedies, but Easy A proves a smart, witty showcase for its irresistibly charming star, Emma Stone.

Plot: A married woman realizes how unhappy her marriage really is, and that her life needs to go in a different direction. After a painful divorce, she takes off on a round-the-world journey to "find herself".
Title: Eat Pray Love
Writer: Ryan Murphy (screenplay), Jennifer Salt (screenplay), Elizabeth Gilbert (book)
Actors: Julia Roberts, I. Gusti Ayu Puspawati, Hadi Subiyanto, Billy Crudup
tomatoConsensus: The scenery is nice to look at, and Julia Roberts is as luminous as ever, but without the spiritual and emotional weight of the book that inspired it, Eat Pray Love is too shallow to resonate.

Plot: As Allen Ginsberg talks about his life and art, his most famous poem is illustrated in animation while the obscenity trial of the work is dramatized.
Title: Howl
Writer: Rob Epstein (written for the screen by), Jeffrey Friedman (written for the screen by)
Actors: James Franco, Todd Rotondi, Jon Prescott, Aaron Tveit
tomatoConsensus: James Franco gives it his all as beat poet Allen Ginsberg, but Howl never develops enough of a focus to do his performance justice.

Plot: Documenting Joaquin Phoenix's transition from the acting world to a career as an aspiring rapper.
Title: I'm Still Here
Actors: Joaquin Phoenix, Antony Langdon, Carey Perloff, Larry McHale
tomatoConsensus: As unkempt and inscrutable as Joaquin Phoenix himself, I'm Still Here raises some interesting questions about its subject, as well as the nature of celebrity, but it fails to answer many of them convincingly.

Plot: Two eighth-graders start to have feelings for each other despite being total opposites.
Title: Flipped
Writer: Rob Reiner (screenplay), Andrew Scheinman (screenplay), Wendelin Van Draanen (novel)
Actors: Madeline Carroll, Callan McAuliffe, Rebecca De Mornay, Anthony Edwards
tomatoConsensus: While not without its nostalgic charms, Rob Reiner's sometimes awkward adaptation of Wendelin Van Draanen's childhood novel doesn't reach the heights of the director's earlier work like Stand By Me.

Plot: An IMAX 3D camera chronicles the effort of 7 astronauts aboard the Space Shuttle Atlantis to repair the Hubble Space Telescope.
Title: Hubble 3D
Writer: Toni Myers, Frank Summers, Graeme Ferguson
Actors: Leonardo DiCaprio, Scott D. Altman, Andrew J. Feustel, Michael T. Good
tomatoConsensus: Offering a stunning, expansive viewing experience, Hubble 3D takes advantage of IMAX and 3-D technology like no other film.

Plot: Now out of prison but still disgraced by his peers, Gordon Gekko works his future son-in-law, an idealistic stock broker, when he sees an opportunity to take down a Wall Street enemy and rebuild his empire.
Title: Wall Street: Money Never Sleeps
Writer: Allan Loeb, Stephen Schiff, Stanley Weiser (characters), Oliver Stone (characters)
Actors: Richard Stratton, Harry Kerrigan, Michael Douglas, Carey Mulligan
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It's more entertaining than many sequels, but with Oliver Stone directing, a terrific cast, and a timely storyline that picks up where the original left off, Wall Street: Money Never Sleeps should be better.

Plot: When a young owl is abducted by an evil Owl army, he must escape with new-found friends and seek the legendary Guardians to stop the menace.
Title: Legend of the Guardians: The Owls of Ga'Hoole
Writer: John Orloff (screenplay), Emil Stern (screenplay), Kathryn Lasky (novels)
Actors: Emily Barclay, Abbie Cornish, Essie Davis, Adrienne DeFaria
tomatoConsensus: Legend of the Guardians' dark tone and dazzling visuals are to be admired, even if they're ultimately let down by a story that never lives up to its full potential.

Plot: The ongoing war between the canine and feline species is put on hold when they join forces to thwart a rogue cat spy with her own sinister plans for conquest.
Title: Cats & Dogs: The Revenge of Kitty Galore
Writer: Ron J. Friedman, Steve Bencich, John Requa (characters), Glenn Ficarra (characters)
Actors: James Marsden, Nick Nolte, Christina Applegate, Katt Williams
tomatoConsensus: Dull and unfunny, this inexplicable sequel offers little more than the spectacle of digitally rendered talking animals with celebrity voices.

Plot: A clinically depressed teenager gets a new start after he checks himself into an adult psychiatric ward.
Title: It's Kind of a Funny Story
Writer: Anna Boden (screenplay), Ryan Fleck (screenplay), Ned Vizzini (novel)
Actors: Keir Gilchrist, Dana DeVestern, Lauren Graham, Jim Gaffigan
tomatoConsensus: It's amiable, and it does a surprisingly good job of sidestepping psych ward comedy cliches, but given its talented cast and directors, It's Kind of a Funny Story should be more than just mildly entertaining.

Plot: A bullied young boy befriends a young female vampire who lives in secrecy with her guardian.
Title: Let Me In
Writer: Matt Reeves (screenplay), John Ajvide Lindqvist (screenplay), John Ajvide Lindqvist (novel)
Actors: Kodi Smit-McPhee, Chloë Grace Moretz, Richard Jenkins, Cara Buono
tomatoConsensus: Similar to the original in all the right ways -- but with enough changes to stand on its own -- Let Me In is the rare Hollywood remake that doesn't add insult to inspiration.

Plot: Penny Chenery Tweedy and colleagues guide her long-shot but precocious stallion to set, in 1973, the unbeaten record for winning the Triple Crown.
Title: Secretariat
Actors: Diane Lane, John Malkovich, Dylan Walsh, Margo Martindale
tomatoConsensus: Rousing, heartwarming, and squarely traditional, Secretariat offers exactly what you'd expect from an inspirational Disney drama -- no more, and no less.

Plot: Two single adults become caregivers to an orphaned girl when their mutual best friends die in an accident.
Title: Life as We Know It
Actors: Katherine Heigl, Josh Duhamel, Josh Lucas, Alexis Clagett
tomatoConsensus: Katherine Heigl and Josh Duhamel make a charming couple with plenty of chemistry, but that isn't enough to make up for Life as We Know It's formulaic plot and poorly written script.

Plot: Young filmmakers document their colleague's budding online friendship with a young woman and her family which leads to an unexpected series of discoveries.
Title: Catfish
Actors: Yaniv Schulman, Ariel Schulman, Henry Joost, Angela Wesselman-Pierce
tomatoConsensus: Catfish may tread the line between real-life drama and crass exploitation a little too unsteadily for some viewers' tastes, but its timely premise and tightly wound mystery make for a gripping documentary.

Plot: Sally's parents' marriage breaks up when her father undergoes a mid-life crisis and impulsively weds a prostitute as Sally's own marriage also begins to disintegrate.
Title: You Will Meet a Tall Dark Stranger
Actors: Gemma Jones, Pauline Collins, Anthony Hopkins, Rupert Frazer
tomatoConsensus: It's sporadically amusing, and typically well-cast, but You Will Meet a Tall Dark Stranger isn't one of Woody Allen's more inspired late-period efforts.

Plot: A convicted arsonist looks to manipulate a parole officer into a plan to secure his parole by placing his beautiful wife in the lawman's path.
Title: Stone
Actors: Robert De Niro, Edward Norton, Milla Jovovich, Frances Conroy
tomatoConsensus: Stone boasts a cast that includes Robert De Niro, Edward Norton, and Milla Jovovich, and it features strong dialogue, but it's ultimately undone by its heavy-handed symbolism and overabundant plot twists.

Plot: Takes a closer look at what brought about the 2008 financial meltdown.
Title: Inside Job
Writer: Charles Ferguson, Chad Beck, Adam Bolt
Actors: Matt Damon, William Ackman, Daniel Alpert, Jonathan Alpert
tomatoConsensus: Disheartening but essential viewing, Charles Ferguson's documentary explores the 2008 Global Financial Crisis with exemplary rigor.

Plot: A working mother puts herself through law school in an effort to represent her brother, who has been wrongfully convicted of murder and has exhausted his chances to appeal his conviction through public defenders.
Title: Conviction
Actors: Hilary Swank, Sam Rockwell, Thomas D. Mahard, Owen Campbell
tomatoConsensus: Less compelling -- and more manipulative -- than it should be, Conviction benefits from its compelling true story and a pair of solid performances from Swank and Rockwell.

Plot: The lives of three friends, from their early school days into young adulthood.
Title: Never Let Me Go
Actors: Carey Mulligan, Andrew Garfield, Izzy Meikle-Small, Charlie Rowe
tomatoConsensus: With Never Let Me Go, Mark Romanek has delivered a graceful adaptation that captures the spirit of the Ishiguro novel -- which will be precisely the problem for some viewers.

Plot: A French illusionist finds himself out of work and travels to Scotland, where he meets a young woman. Their ensuing adventure changes both their lives forever.
Title: The Illusionist
Actors: Jean-Claude Donda, Eilidh Rankin, Duncan MacNeil, Raymond Mearns
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 29 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: An engrossing love letter to fans of adult animation, The Illusionist offers a fine antidote to garish mainstream fare.

Plot: A homicidal car tire, discovering it has destructive psionic power, sets its sights on a desert town once a mysterious woman becomes its obsession.
Title: Rubber
Actors: Stephen Spinella, Jack Plotnick, Wings Hauser, Roxane Mesquida
tomatoConsensus: A clever premise gets plenty of comic blood and violence, but its hampered by some questionable storytelling techniques from director Quentin Dupieux.

Plot: Johnny Knoxville and company return for the third installment of their TV show spin-off, where dangerous stunts and explicit public displays rule.
Title: Jackass 3D
Actors: Johnny Knoxville, Bam Margera, Ryan Dunn, Steve-O
tomatoConsensus: The Jackass gang might be running out of gross-out stunts, but this installment contains plenty of brilliantly brain-dead comedy -- and the 3-D adds a pungent new dimension.

Plot: A year with one platoon in the deadliest valley in Afghanistan.
Title: Restrepo
Actors: The Men of Battle Company 2nd of the 503rd Infantry Regiment 173rd Airborne Brigade Combat Team, Juan 'Doc Restrepo, Dan Kearney, LaMonta Caldwell
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 19 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Forsaking narrative structure for pure visceral power, Restrepo plunges viewers into the experiences of soldiers on the front lines of the Afghan War.

Title: Waiting for 'Superman'
Actors: Charles Adam, Charles Adams, Jonathan Alter, Robert Balfanz
tomatoConsensus: Gripping, heartbreaking, and ultimately hopeful, Waiting for Superman is an impassioned indictment of the American school system from An Inconvenient Truth director Davis Guggenheim.

Plot: When his peaceful life is threatened by a high-tech assassin, former black-ops agent Frank Moses reassembles his old team in a last ditch effort to survive and uncover his assailants.
Title: RED
Writer: Jon Hoeber (screenplay), Erich Hoeber (screenplay), Warren Ellis (graphic novel), Cully Hamner (graphic novel)
Actors: Bruce Willis, Mary-Louise Parker, Heidi von Palleske, Karl Urban
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 17 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It may not be the killer thrill ride you'd expect from an action movie with a cast of this caliber, but Red still thoroughly outshines most of its big-budget counterparts with its wit and style.

Plot: The lives of two Danish families cross each other, and an extraordinary but risky friendship comes into bud. But loneliness, frailty and sorrow lie in wait.
Title: In a Better World
Writer: Anders Thomas Jensen (screenplay), Susanne Bier (story), Anders Thomas Jensen (story), Per Nielsen (supervising writer)
Actors: Mikael Persbrandt, Wil Johnson, Eddy Kimani, Emily Mulaya
tomatoConsensus: In a Better World is a sumptuous melodrama that tackles some rather difficult existential and human themes.

Plot: A serial killer returns to his hometown to stalk seven children who share the same birthday as the date he was allegedly put to rest.
Title: My Soul to Take
Actors: Max Thieriot, John Magaro, Denzel Whitaker, Zena Grey
tomatoConsensus: Dull, joyless, and formulaic, My Soul to Take suggests writer/director Wes Craven ended his five-year filmmaking hiatus too soon.

Plot: Alex and his sister run a business designed to break up relationships. They are hired by a rich man to break up the wedding of his daughter. The only problem is that they only have one week to do so.
Language: French, English, Spanish, Japanese, Arabic, Mandarin
Title: Heartbreaker
Writer: Laurent Zeitoun (scenario), Jeremy Doner (scenario), Yoann Gromb (scenario), Laurent Zeitoun (original idea)
Actors: Romain Duris, Vanessa Paradis, Julie Ferrier, François Damiens
tomatoConsensus: While definitely on the fluffier side of French comedy, Heartbreaker benefits from never taking itself too seriously -- and from the performance of the ever-charming Romain Duris.

Plot: After experiencing what they think are a series of "break-ins", a family sets up security cameras around their home, only to realize that the events unfolding before them are more sinister than they seem.
Title: Paranormal Activity 2
Writer: Michael R. Perry (screenplay), Christopher Landon (screenplay), Tom Pabst (screenplay), Michael R. Perry (story), Oren Peli (film "Paranormal Activity")
Actors: David Bierend, Brian Boland, Molly Ephraim, Katie Featherston
tomatoConsensus: Paranormal Activity 2 doesn't cover any new ground, but its premise is still scary -- and in some respects, it's a better film than the original.

Plot: A drama centered on three people -- a blue-collar American, a French journalist and a London school boy -- who are touched by death in different ways.
Title: Hereafter
Actors: Cécile De France, Thierry Neuvic, Cyndi Mayo Davis, Lisa Griffiths
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 13 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despite a thought-provoking premise and Clint Eastwood's typical flair as director, Hereafter fails to generate much compelling drama, straddling the line between poignant sentimentality and hokey tedium.

Plot: Set during the time of the first outbreak of bubonic plague in England, a young monk is given the task of learning the truth about reports of people being brought back to life in a small village.
Title: Black Death
Actors: Sean Bean, Eddie Redmayne, John Lynch, Tim McInnerny
tomatoConsensus: Black Death delivers the fire and brimstone violence its subject matter warrants, while posing some interesting questions of faith and religion.

Plot: As a deadly battle rages over Jigsaw's brutal legacy, a group of Jigsaw survivors gathers to seek the support of self-help guru and fellow survivor Bobby Dagen, a man whose own dark secrets unleash a new wave of terror.
Title: Saw 3D: The Final Chapter
Actors: Tobin Bell, Costas Mandylor, Betsy Russell, Cary Elwes
tomatoConsensus: Sloppily filmed, poorly acted, and illogically plotted, Saw 3D leaves viewers trapped in the most lackluster installment of the series.

Plot: High-strung father-to-be Peter Highman is forced to hitch a ride with aspiring actor Ethan Tremblay on a road trip in order to make it to his child's birth on time.
Title: Due Date
Writer: Alan R. Cohen (screenplay), Alan Freedland (screenplay), Adam Sztykiel (screenplay), Todd Phillips (screenplay), Alan R. Cohen (story), Alan Freedland (story)
Actors: Robert Downey Jr., Zach Galifianakis, Michelle Monaghan, Jamie Foxx
tomatoConsensus: Shamelessly derivative and only sporadically funny, Due Date doesn't live up to the possibilities suggested by its talented director and marvelously mismatched stars.

Plot: An adventurous mountain climber becomes trapped under a boulder while canyoneering alone near Moab, Utah and resorts to desperate measures in order to survive.
Title: 127 Hours
Writer: Danny Boyle (screenplay), Simon Beaufoy (screenplay), Aron Ralston (book)
Actors: James Franco, Kate Mara, Amber Tamblyn, Sean Bott
Awards: Nominated for 6 Oscars. Another 23 wins & 138 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: As gut-wrenching as it is inspirational, 127 Hours unites one of Danny Boyle's most beautifully exuberant directorial efforts with a terrific performance from James Franco.

Plot: The supervillain Megamind finally defeats his nemesis, the superhero Metro Man. But without a hero, he loses all purpose and must find new meaning to his life.
Title: Megamind
Actors: Will Ferrell, Brad Pitt, Tina Fey, Jonah Hill
tomatoConsensus: It regurgitates plot points from earlier animated efforts, and isn't quite as funny as it should be, but a top-shelf voice cast and strong visuals help make Megamind a pleasant, if unspectacular, diversion.

Plot: A committed dancer wins the lead role in a production of Tchaikovsky's "Swan Lake" only to find herself struggling to maintain her sanity.
Title: Black Swan
Writer: Mark Heyman (screenplay), Andres Heinz (screenplay), John J. McLaughlin (screenplay), Andres Heinz (story)
Actors: Natalie Portman, Mila Kunis, Vincent Cassel, Barbara Hershey
tomatoConsensus: Bracingly intense, passionate, and wildly melodramatic, Black Swan glides on Darren Aronofsky's bold direction -- and a bravura performance from Natalie Portman.

Plot: A limo driver's blind date sparks a tale of love, betrayal, friendship, and grace centered around two working-class New York City couples.
Title: Jack Goes Boating
Actors: Philip Seymour Hoffman, John Ortiz, Richard Petrocelli, Tom McCarthy
tomatoConsensus: It's made the journey from stage to screen somewhat worse for wear, but Jack Goes Boating remains a sensitive, well-acted character study.

Plot: CIA operative Valerie Plame discovers her identity is allegedly leaked by the government as payback for an op-ed article her husband wrote criticizing the Bush administration.
Title: Fair Game
Writer: Jez Butterworth (screenplay), John-Henry Butterworth (screenplay), Joseph Wilson (book), Valerie Plame Wilson (book)
Actors: Naomi Watts, Sonya Davison, Vanessa Chong, Anand Tiwari
tomatoConsensus: It struggles with the balance between fact-based biopic and taut political thriller, but Fair Game brims with righteous anger -- and benefits from superb performances by Naomi Watts and Sean Penn.

Plot: With an unmanned, half-mile-long freight train barreling toward a city, a veteran engineer and a young conductor race against the clock to prevent a catastrophe.
Title: Unstoppable
Actors: Denzel Washington, Chris Pine, Rosario Dawson, Ethan Suplee
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 13 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: As fast, loud, and relentless as the train at the center of the story, Unstoppable is perfect popcorn entertainment -- and director Tony Scott's best movie in years.

Plot: An upstart television producer accepts the challenge of reviving a struggling morning show program with warring co-hosts.
Title: Morning Glory
Actors: Rachel McAdams, Noah Bean, Jack Davidson, Vanessa Aspillaga
tomatoConsensus: It's lifted by affable performances from its impeccable cast, and it's often charming -- but Morning Glory is also inconsistent and derivative.

Plot: In Tuscany to promote his latest book, a middle-aged British writer meets a French woman who leads him to the village of Lucignano. While there, a chance question reveals something deeper.
Title: Certified Copy
Writer: Caroline Eliacheff (collaborator on screenplay), Abbas Kiarostami
Actors: Juliette Binoche, William Shimell, Jean-Claude Carrière, Agathe Natanson
tomatoConsensus: The main stars are absolutely perfect in this absorbing, existential drama that dissects human relationships.

Plot: A married couple's life is turned upside down when the wife is accused of a murder.
Title: The Next Three Days
Writer: Paul Haggis (screenplay), Fred Cavayé (screenplay), Guillaume Lemans (screenplay)
Actors: Russell Crowe, Elizabeth Banks, Michael Buie, Moran Atias
tomatoConsensus: Russell Crowe and Elizabeth Banks give it their all, but their solid performances aren't quite enough to compensate for The Next Three Days' uneven pace and implausible plot.

Plot: After withdrawing to the Chateau Marmont, a passionless Hollywood actor reexamines his life when his eleven-year-old daughter surprises him with a visit.
Title: Somewhere
Actors: Stephen Dorff, Chris Pontius, Erin Wasson, Alexandra Williams
tomatoConsensus: It covers familiar territory for Sofia Coppola, but Somewhere remains a hypnotic, seductively pensive meditation on the nature of celebrity, anchored by charming performances from Stephen Dorff and Elle Fanning.

Plot: A hitman tries to retire but a beautiful thief may change his plans.
Title: Wild Target
Actors: Bill Nighy, Emily Blunt, Rupert Grint, Rupert Everett
tomatoConsensus: An ineptly staged farce that dishonors the original film and squanders the comedic potential of its fine actors.

Plot: As Harry races against time and evil to destroy the Horcruxes, he uncovers the existence of three most powerful objects in the wizarding world: the Deathly Hallows.
Title: Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 1
Actors: Bill Nighy, Emma Watson, Richard Griffiths, Harry Melling
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 51 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It can't help but feel like the prelude it is, but Deathly Hallows: Part I is a beautifully filmed, emotionally satisfying penultimate installment for the Harry Potter series.

Plot: The story of King George VI of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, his impromptu ascension to the throne and the speech therapist who helped the unsure monarch become worthy of it.
Title: The King's Speech
Actors: Colin Firth, Helena Bonham Carter, Derek Jacobi, Robert Portal
tomatoConsensus: Colin Firth gives a masterful performance in The King's Speech, a predictable but stylishly produced and rousing period drama.

Plot: The magically long-haired Rapunzel has spent her entire life in a tower, but now that a runaway thief has stumbled upon her, she is about to discover the world for the first time, and who she really is.
Title: Tangled
Writer: Dan Fogelman (screenplay), Jacob Grimm (based upon the fairy tale "Rapunzel" by), Wilhelm Grimm (based upon the fairy tale "Rapunzel" by)
Actors: Mandy Moore, Zachary Levi, Donna Murphy, Ron Perlman
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 39 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: While far from Disney's greatest film, Tangled is a visually stunning, thoroughly entertaining addition to the studio's classic animated canon.

Plot: A look at the early years of boxer "Irish" Micky Ward and his brother who helped train him before going pro in the mid 1980s.
Title: The Fighter
Writer: Scott Silver (screenplay), Paul Tamasy (screenplay), Eric Johnson (screenplay), Paul Tamasy (story), Eric Johnson (story), Keith Dorrington (story)
Actors: Mark Wahlberg, Christian Bale, Amy Adams, Melissa Leo
tomatoConsensus: Led by a trio of captivating performances from Mark Wahlberg, Christian Bale, and Amy Adams, The Fighter is a solidly entertaining, albeit predictable, entry in the boxing drama genre.

Plot: Pat Tillman never thought of himself as a hero. His choice to leave a multimillion-dollar football contract and join the military wasn't done for any reason other than he felt it was the ...
Title: The Tillman Story
Actors: Josh Brolin, Pat Tillman, Mary Tillman, Russell Baer
tomatoConsensus: Passionate, angry, and insightful, The Tillman Story offers a revealing portrait of its subject's inspiring life and untimely death.

Plot: A hot shot Washington DC lobbyist and his protégé go down hard as their schemes to peddle influence lead to corruption and murder.
Title: Casino Jack
Actors: Kevin Spacey, Ruth Marshall, Graham Greene, Hannah Endicott-Douglas
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.
tomatoConsensus: Kevin Spacey turns in one of his stronger performances, but Casino Jack is a disappointingly uneven fictionalized account of a fascinating true story.

Plot: An ex-con with a reputation tries to go straight by working as a handy man for a reclusive actress but this is unfortunately not the wish of London's underground crime lord.
Title: London Boulevard
Actors: Colin Farrell, Keira Knightley, David Thewlis, Anna Friel
tomatoConsensus: In spite of its spotless pedigree and a strong sense of visual style, London Boulevard stumbles over its frenetic pace and crowded, clichéd plot.

Plot: Strange lights descend on the city of Los Angeles, drawing people outside like moths to a flame where an extraterrestrial force threatens to swallow the entire human population off the face of the Earth.
Title: Skyline
Actors: Eric Balfour, Scottie Thompson, Brittany Daniel, Crystal Reed
tomatoConsensus: A middling sci-fi entry, Skyline offers proof that solid special effects alone cannot overcome a flat storyline filled with uninspired dialogue.

Plot: A young woman suffering from Parkinson's befriends a drug rep working for Pfizer in 1990s Pittsburgh.
Title: Love & Other Drugs
Writer: Charles Randolph (screenplay), Edward Zwick (screenplay), Marshall Herskovitz (screenplay), Jamie Reidy (book)
Actors: Jake Gyllenhaal, Anne Hathaway, Oliver Platt, Hank Azaria
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It's a pleasure to see Hollywood produce a romance this refreshingly adult, but Love and Other Drugs struggles to find a balance between its disparate plot elements.

Plot: Lucy and Edmund Pevensie return to Narnia with their cousin Eustace where they meet up with Prince Caspian for a trip across the sea aboard the royal ship The Dawn Treader. Along the way they encounter dragons, dwarves, merfolk, and a band of lost warriors before reaching the edge of the world.
Title: The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader
Writer: Christopher Markus (screenplay), Stephen McFeely (screenplay), Michael Petroni (screenplay), C.S. Lewis (novel)
Actors: Georgie Henley, Skandar Keynes, Ben Barnes, Will Poulter
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 16 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Its leisurely, businesslike pace won't win the franchise many new fans, but Voyage of the Dawn Treader restores some of the Narnia franchise's lost luster with strong performances and impressive special effects.

Plot: Revolves around Frank, an American tourist visiting Italy to mend a broken heart. Elise is an extraordinary woman who deliberately crosses his path.
Title: The Tourist
Writer: Florian Henckel von Donnersmarck (screenplay), Christopher McQuarrie (screenplay), Julian Fellowes (screenplay), Jérôme Salle (motion picture "Anthony Zimmer")
Actors: Johnny Depp, Angelina Jolie, Paul Bettany, Timothy Dalton
Awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The scenery and the stars are undeniably beautiful, but they can't make up for The Tourist's slow, muddled plot, or the lack of chemistry between Johnny Depp and Angelina Jolie.

Plot: In the depths of the Korvatunturi mountains, 486 metres deep, lies the closest ever guarded secret of Christmas. The time has come to dig it up! This Christmas everyone will believe in Santa Claus.
Title: Rare Exports: A Christmas Tale
Writer: Jalmari Helander, Jalmari Helander (based on the original idea by), Juuso Helander (based on the original idea by), Petri Jokiranta (dramaturge), Sami Parkkinen (dramaturge)
Actors: Onni Tommila, Jorma Tommila, Tommi Korpela, Rauno Juvonen
tomatoConsensus: Rare Exports is an unexpectedly delightful crossbreed of deadpan comedy and Christmas horror.

Plot: Marybeth escapes the clutches of the bayou-butcher Victor Crowley and returns to the swamp with an army of hunters and gunmen, determined to end Crowley's reign of horror once and for all.
Title: Hatchet II
Actors: Danielle Harris, Tony Todd, Kane Hodder, Parry Shen
tomatoConsensus: Funnier and more gleefully gory than most slasher sequels, Hatchet II aims for so-bad-it's-good territory, but can't quite hack it.

Plot: Mr. David Marks was suspected but never tried for killing his wife Katie who disappeared in 1982, but the truth is eventually revealed.
Title: All Good Things
Actors: Ryan Gosling, Kirsten Dunst, Frank Langella, Lily Rabe
tomatoConsensus: It's well-acted, and the true story that inspired it offers plenty of drama -- which is why it's so frustrating that All Good Things is so clichéd and frustratingly ambiguous.

Plot: In 1976, complex political and emotional forces are set in motion when a young man returns to the race-torn Philadelphia neighborhood where he came of age during the Black Power movement.
Title: Night Catches Us
Actors: Anthony Mackie, Jamara Griffin, Sadiq Afif, Shango Rich
tomatoConsensus: A bold, original debut, Night Catches Us personalizes a tumultuous period in American history thanks to strong performances from Anthony Mackie and Kerry Washington.

Plot: A tough U.S. Marshal helps a stubborn teenager track down her father's murderer.
Title: True Grit
Writer: Joel Coen (screenplay), Ethan Coen (screenplay), Charles Portis (novel)
Actors: Jeff Bridges, Hailee Steinfeld, Matt Damon, Josh Brolin
Awards: Nominated for 10 Oscars. Another 37 wins & 148 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Girded by strong performances from Jeff Bridges, Matt Damon, and newcomer Hailee Steinfeld, and lifted by some of the Coens' most finely tuned, unaffected work, True Grit is a worthy companion to the Charles Portis book.

Plot: The son of a virtual world designer goes looking for his father and ends up inside the digital world that his father designed. He meets his father's corrupted creation and a unique ally who was born inside the digital world.
Title: TRON: Legacy
Writer: Edward Kitsis (screenplay), Adam Horowitz (screenplay), Edward Kitsis (story), Adam Horowitz (story), Brian Klugman (story), Lee Sternthal (story), Steven Lisberger (characters), Bonnie MacBird (characters)
Actors: Jeff Bridges, Garrett Hedlund, Olivia Wilde, Bruce Boxleitner
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 48 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Tron Legacy boasts dazzling visuals, but its human characters and story get lost amidst its state-of-the-art production design.

Plot: A look at four seasons in the lives of a happily married couple and their relationships with their family and friends.
Title: Another Year
Actors: Jim Broadbent, Ruth Sheen, Lesley Manville, Oliver Maltman
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 20 wins & 52 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Characterized by strong performances and the director's trademark feel for the nuances of everyday life, Another Year marks another solid entry in Mike Leigh's career of kitchen-sink English drama.

Plot: After being cut from the USA softball team and feeling a bit past her prime, Lisa finds herself evaluating her life and in the middle of a love triangle, as a corporate guy in crisis competes with her current, baseball-playing beau.
Title: How Do You Know
Actors: Reese Witherspoon, Paul Rudd, Owen Wilson, Jack Nicholson
tomatoConsensus: How Do You Know boasts a quartet of likeable leads -- and they deserve better than this glib, overlong misfire from writer/director James L. Brooks.

Plot: The picaresque and touching story of the politically incorrect, fully lived life of the impulsive, irascible and fearlessly blunt Barney Panofsky.
Title: Barney's Version
Actors: Paul Giamatti, Macha Grenon, Paul Gross, Atom Egoyan
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 18 wins & 17 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: With a magnificent performance by Paul Giamatti, Barney's Version offers much comedy and insight to the complexities of modern romance.

Plot: The story centers on a year in the life of three men trying to survive a round of corporate downsizing at a major company - and how that affects them, their families, and their communities.
Title: The Company Men
Actors: Ben Affleck, Tommy Lee Jones, Chris Cooper, Suzanne Rico
tomatoConsensus: It might be hard for most viewers to identify with The Company Men's well-heeled protagonists, but writer/director John Wells uses their plight to make universally resonant points -- and gets the most out of his excellent cast.

Plot: An ex-con gets on a series of apparently unrelated killings. He gets tracked by a veteran cop with secrets of his own and an egocentric hit man.
Title: Faster
Actors: Dwayne Johnson, Mauricio Lopez, Jim Gaines, Tom Berenger
tomatoConsensus: It's good to see Dwayne Johnson back in full-throttle action mode, but Faster doesn't deliver enough of the high-octane thrills promised by its title.

Plot: Life for a happy couple is turned upside down after their young son dies in an accident.
Title: Rabbit Hole
Writer: David Lindsay-Abaire (screenplay), David Lindsay-Abaire (based on his play: "Rabbit Hole")
Actors: Nicole Kidman, Aaron Eckhart, Dianne Wiest, Miles Teller
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 40 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It's often painful to watch, but Rabbit Hole's finely written script and convincing performances make it worth the effort.

Plot: Family-patriarch Jack Byrnes wants to appoint a successor. Does his son-in-law, the male nurse Greg Focker, have what it takes?
Title: Little Fockers
Writer: John Hamburg, Larry Stuckey, Greg Glienna (characters), Mary Ruth Clarke (characters)
Actors: Robert De Niro, Ben Stiller, Owen Wilson, Dustin Hoffman
tomatoConsensus: As star-studded as it is heartbreakingly lazy, Little Fockers takes the top-grossing trilogy to embarrassing new lows.

Plot: Travel writer Lemuel Gulliver takes an assignment in Bermuda, but ends up on the island of Liliput, where he towers over its tiny citizens.
Title: Gulliver's Travels
Writer: Joe Stillman (screenplay), Nicholas Stoller (screenplay), Jonathan Swift (book)
Actors: Jack Black, Jason Segel, Emily Blunt, Amanda Peet
tomatoConsensus: Though Jack Black is back doing what he does best, Gulliver's Travels largely fails to do any justice to its source material, relying instead on juvenile humor and special effects.

Plot: A small-town girl ventures to Los Angeles and finds her place in a neo-burlesque club run by a former dancer.
Title: Burlesque
Actors: Cher, Christina Aguilera, Eric Dane, Cam Gigandet
Awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 17 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Campy and clichéd, Burlesque wastes its talented cast (including a better-than-expected Christina Aguilera) on a movie that wavers uncertainly between "bad" and "so bad it's good."

Plot: The Clock family are four-inch-tall people who live anonymously in another family's residence, borrowing simple items to make their home. Life changes for the Clocks when their daughter, Arrietty, is discovered.
Title: The Secret World of Arrietty
Writer: Mary Norton (novel), Hayao Miyazaki (screenplay), Keiko Niwa (screenplay)
Actors: Moises Arias, Bridgit Mendler, David Henrie, Will Arnett
tomatoConsensus: Visually lush, refreshingly free of family-friendly clatter, and anchored with soulful depth, The Secret World of Arrietty lives up to Studio Ghibli's reputation.

Plot: A documentary filmmaker travels to Jellystone Park to shoot a project and soon crosses paths with Yogi Bear, his sidekick Boo-Boo, and Ranger Smith.
Title: Yogi Bear
Writer: Jennifer Ventimilia, Joshua Sternin, Brad Copeland, Joseph Barbera (characters), William Hanna (characters)
Actors: Dan Aykroyd, Justin Timberlake, Anna Faris, Tom Cavanagh
tomatoConsensus: Yogi Bear's 3D effects and all-star voice cast are cold comfort for its aggressively mediocre screenplay.

Plot: On the outskirts of Rio de Janeiro is Jardim Gramacho, the world's largest landfill, where men and women sift through garbage for a living. Artist Vik Muniz produces portraits of the workers and learns about their lives.
Title: Waste Land
Director: Lucy Walker, Karen Harley, João Jardim
Actors: Vik Muniz
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 27 wins & 10 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Waste Land begins with an eco-friendly premise, but quickly transforms into an uplifting portrait of the power of art and the dignity of the human spirit.

Plot: The story follows a married couple, apart for a night while the husband takes a business trip with a colleague to whom he's attracted to. While he's resisting temptation, his wife encounters her past love.
Title: Last Night
Actors: Keira Knightley, Sam Worthington, Guillaume Canet, Eva Mendes
tomatoConsensus: Last Night doesn't opt for easy answers, but the framework and characters overall are too slight and plain to be compelling.

Plot: Siberian gulag escapees travel 4,000 miles by foot to freedom in India.
Title: The Way Back
Writer: Keith R. Clarke (screenplay), Slavomir Rawicz (novel), Peter Weir (screenplay)
Actors: Dragos Bucur, Colin Farrell, Ed Harris, Alexandru Potocean
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It isn't as emotionally involving as it should be, but this Peter Weir epic offers sweeping ambition and strong performances to go with its grand visual spectacle.

Plot: A warrior-assassin is forced to hide in a small town in the American Badlands after refusing a mission.
Title: The Warrior's Way
Actors: Dong-gun Jang, Kate Bosworth, Geoffrey Rush, Danny Huston
tomatoConsensus: Perfectly, thoroughly divisive, The Warrior's Way will either be delightful or unbearable, depending on your tolerance for surreal, shamelessly over the top collisions of eastern and western clichés.

Plot: A film about an unfinished film which portrays the people behind and before the camera in the Warsaw Ghetto, exposing the extent of the cinematic manipulation forever changing the way we look at historic images.
Title: A Film Unfinished
Actors: Hanna Avrutzki, Luba Gewisser, Jurek Plonski, Aliza Vitis-Shomron
tomatoConsensus: A heartbreaking, haunting historical document, A Film Unfinished excavates particularly horrible chapter of Holocaust history, and in doing so, the film provides a glimpse into the Nazi propaganda machine.

Plot: After a vicious attacks leaves him brain-damaged and broke, Mark Hogancamp seeks recovery in "Marwencol", a 1/6th scale World War II-era town he creates in his backyard.
Title: Marwencol
Actors: Mark Hogancamp, Emmanuel Nneji, Edda Hogancamp, Tom Neubauer
tomatoConsensus: Inspiring and fascinating, Marwencol depicts its subject with heartfelt tenderness, raising poignant questions about art and personal tragedy along the way.

Plot: A drama centered on a go-go dancer with multiple personality disorder who struggles to remain her true self and begins working with a psychotherapist to uncover the mystery of the inner ghosts that haunt her.
Title: Frankie & Alice
Writer: Cheryl Edwards (screenplay), Marko King (screenplay), Mary King (screenplay), Jonathan Watters (screenplay), Joe Shrapnel (screenplay), Anna Waterhouse (screenplay), Oscar Janiger (story), Philip Goldberg (story), Cheryl Edwards (story)
Actors: Halle Berry, Stellan Skarsgård, Phylicia Rashad, Chandra Wilson
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Halle Berry gives it her all (and then some), but Frankie & Alice is ultimately too narratively strained and clumsily assembled to do her performance justice.

Plot: Steve Coogan has been asked by The Observer to tour the country's finest restaurants, but after his girlfriend backs out on him he must take his best friend and source of eternal aggravation, Rob Brydon.
Title: The Trip
Actors: Steve Coogan, Rob Brydon, Paul Popplewell, Margo Stilley
tomatoConsensus: Amiable, funny and sometimes insightful, The Trip works as both a showcase for the enduring chemistry between stars Steve Coogan and Rob Brydon and an unexpected perusal of men entering mid-life crises.

Plot: On a business trip to New Orleans, a damaged man seeks salvation by caring for a wayward young woman.
Title: Welcome to the Rileys
Actors: James Gandolfini, Kristen Stewart, Melissa Leo, Joe Chrest
tomatoConsensus: Despite earnest performances, Welcome to the Rileys cannot escape its belabored over-sentimentality and sluggish delivery.

Plot: A look at the art of Spalding Gray who drew from real life experience to create a compelling and deeply personal series of monologues.
Title: And Everything Is Going Fine
Actors: Spalding Gray
tomatoConsensus: Even if And Everything Is Going Fine isn't one of Soderbergh's more commercial efforts, this collection of judiciously edited performance footage of the late monologist Spalding Gray gave the director a chance to show a rarely-seen side of his artistry.

Plot: Each of the women portray one of the characters represented in the collection of twenty poems, revealing different issues that impact women in general and women of color in particular.
Title: For Colored Girls
Actors: Kimberly Elise, Janet Jackson, Loretta Devine, Thandie Newton
tomatoConsensus: Tyler Perry has assembled a fine cast for this adaptation of the 1975 play, and his heart is obviously in the right place, but his fondness for melodrama cheapens a meaningful story.

Plot: A rising country-music songwriter works with a fallen star to work their way to fame, causing romantic complications along the way.
Title: Country Strong
Actors: Gwyneth Paltrow, Tim McGraw, Garrett Hedlund, Leighton Meester
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 6 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The cast gives it their all, and Paltrow handles her songs with aplomb, but Country Strong's cliched, disjointed screenplay hits too many bum notes.

Plot: Shakespeare's epic play is translated from page to screen, with the gender of the main character, Prospero, changed from male to female.
Title: The Tempest
Actors: Felicity Jones, Jude Akuwudike, Reeve Carney, David Strathairn
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Director Julie Taymor's gender-swapping of roles and some frenzied special effects can't quite disguise an otherwise stagey, uninspired take on Shakespeare's classic.

Plot: In Brooklyn, a youth from an Orthodox Jewish community is lured into becoming an Ecstasy dealer by his pal who has ties to an Israeli drug cartel.
Title: Holy Rollers
Actors: Jesse Eisenberg, Justin Bartha, Ari Graynor, Danny A. Abeckaser
tomatoConsensus: Despite a promising premise and a solid central performance from Jesse Eisenberg, Holy Rollers lacks the depth necessary to overcome its cliched script.

Plot: Werner Herzog gains exclusive access to film inside the Chauvet caves of Southern France and captures the oldest known pictorial creations of humanity.
Title: Cave of Forgotten Dreams
Actors: Werner Herzog, Jean Clottes, Julien Monney, Jean-Michel Geneste
tomatoConsensus: Hauntingly filmed and brimming with Herzog's infectious enthusiasm, Cave of Forgotten Dreams is a fascinating triumph.

Plot: After his wife falls under the influence of a drug dealer, an everyday guy transforms himself into Crimson Bolt, a superhero with the best intentions, but lacking in heroic skills.
Title: Super
Actors: Rainn Wilson, Ellen Page, Liv Tyler, Kevin Bacon
tomatoConsensus: Super's intriguing premise and talented cast are drowned in a blood-red sea of graphic violence, jarring tonal shifts, and thinly written characters.

Plot: A group of students investigates a series of mysterious bear killings, but learns that there are much more dangerous things going on. They start to follow a mysterious hunter, learning that he is actually a troll hunter.
Title: Trollhunter
Actors: Otto Jespersen, Glenn Erland Tosterud, Johanna Mørck, Tomas Alf Larsen
tomatoConsensus: Trollhunter is a mockumentary with an appropriate level of creeping dread, but one that also benefits from generous helpings of dry wit.

Plot: A documentary on Brazilian Formula One racing driver Ayrton Senna, who won the F1 world championship three times before his death at age 34.
Title: Senna
Actors: Ayrton Senna, Alain Prost, Frank Williams, Ron Dennis
Awards: Won 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 14 wins & 18 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Even for filmgoers who aren't racing fans, Senna offers heart-pounding thrills -- and heartbreaking emotion.

Plot: A family looks to prevent evil spirits from trapping their comatose child in a realm called The Further.
Title: Insidious
Actors: Patrick Wilson, Rose Byrne, Ty Simpkins, Lin Shaye
tomatoConsensus: Aside from a shaky final act, Insidious is a very scary and very fun haunted house thrill ride.

Plot: Settlers traveling through the Oregon desert in 1845 find themselves stranded in harsh conditions.
Title: Meek's Cutoff
Actors: Michelle Williams, Bruce Greenwood, Will Patton, Zoe Kazan
tomatoConsensus: Moving at a contemplative speed unseen in most westerns, Meek's Cutoff is an effective, intense journey of terror and survival in the untamed frontier.

Plot: Set on the east coast of New Zealand in 1984, Boy, an 11-year-old kid and devout Michael Jackson fan, gets a chance to know his father, who has returned to find a bag of money he buried years ago.
Title: Boy
Actors: James Rolleston, Te Aho Eketone-Whitu, Taika Waititi, Moerangi Tihore
tomatoConsensus: Boy possesses the offbeat charm associated with New Zealand film but is also fully capable of drawing the viewer in emotionally.

Plot: Released from prison for a crime he didn't commit, an ex-con targets the same bank he was sent away for robbing.
Title: Henry's Crime
Writer: Sacha Gervasi (screenplay), David N. White (screenplay), Stephen Hamel (story), Sacha Gervasi (story)
Actors: Keanu Reeves, Judy Greer, Fisher Stevens, Danny Hoch
tomatoConsensus: Supporting actors Vera Farmiga and James Caan give the movie a little heft, but Henry's Crime is an otherwise predictable heist/comedy with slow pacing.

Plot: Portrayal of the late Bradford playwright Andrea Dunbar.
Title: The Arbor
Actors: Manjinder Virk, Christine Bottomley, Natalie Gavin, Parvani Lingiah
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 7 wins & 24 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Smart and inventive, The Arbor offers some intensely memorable twists on tired documentary tropes.

Plot: A guy who moves back to Portland, Oregon becomes involved in the mystery of his ex-girlfriend's disappearance.
Title: Cold Weather
Writer: Aaron Katz (story), Brendan McFadden (story), Ben Stambler (story), Aaron Katz
Actors: Cris Lankenau, Trieste Kelly Dunn, Raúl Castillo, Robyn Rikoon
tomatoConsensus: For viewers who manage to stay invested in its occasionally aimless story, Cold Weather proves a surprisingly sophisticated blend of mumblecore and indie noir.

Plot: Twins journey to the Middle East to discover their family history, and fulfill their mother's last wishes.
Title: Incendies
Writer: Denis Villeneuve (scenario), Wajdi Mouawad (play), Valérie Beaugrand-Champagne (collaboration), Denis Villeneuve (dialogue)
Actors: Mustafa Kamel, Hussein Sami, Rémy Girard, Mélissa Désormeaux-Poulin
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 39 wins & 15 nominations.
