tomatoConsensus: It's messy, overlong, and a touch melodramatic, but those flaws pale before Incendies' impressive acting and devastating emotional impact.

Plot: A teenage girl is targeted by an online sexual predator.
Title: Trust
Actors: Clive Owen, Catherine Keener, Liana Liberato, Jason Clarke
tomatoConsensus: Director David Schwimmer gets some gut-wrenching performances out of his actors but he still lacks the chops to fully ratchet up story tension.

Plot: A father heads overseas to recover the body of his estranged son who died while traveling the "El camino de Santiago," and decides to take the pilgrimage himself.
Title: The Way
Writer: Emilio Estevez (written for the screen by), Jack Hitt (book)
Actors: Martin Sheen, Emilio Estevez, Deborah Kara Unger, Yorick van Wageningen
tomatoConsensus: It may be a little too deliberately paced for more impatient viewers, but The Way is a worthy effort from writer/director Emilio Estevez, balancing heartfelt emotion with clear-eyed drama that resists cheap sentiment.

Plot: 15-year-old Oliver Tate has two objectives: To lose his virginity before his next birthday, and to extinguish the flame between his mother and an ex-lover who has resurfaced in her life.
Title: Submarine
Actors: Noah Taylor, Paddy Considine, Craig Roberts, Yasmin Paige
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 6 wins & 13 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Funny, stylish, and ringing with adolescent truth, Submarine marks Richard Ayoade as a talent to watch.

Plot: When an alcoholic relapses, causing him to lose his wife and his job, he holds a yard sale on his front lawn in an attempt to start over. A new neighbor might be the key to his return to form.
Title: Everything Must Go
Writer: Dan Rush, Raymond Carver (short story "Why Don't You Dance")
Actors: Will Ferrell, Christopher Jordan Wallace, Rebecca Hall, Michael Peña
tomatoConsensus: It may not improve on the Raymond Carver short story that inspired it, but Everything Must Go resists cliche and boasts a pair of magnetic performances from the perfectly cast Ferrell and Wallace.

Plot: A young man is rocked by two announcements from his elderly father: that he has terminal cancer, and that he has a young male lover.
Title: Beginners
Actors: Ewan McGregor, Christopher Plummer, Mélanie Laurent, Goran Visnjic
tomatoConsensus: Wearing its twee heart on its sleeve, Beginners explores the depths of modern, multi-generational romance with wit and depth.

Plot: Kevin Carson is a young man living in the projects who has to survive a three-day weekend after his opportunistic neighbors find out he's holding a winning lottery ticket worth $370 million.
Title: Lottery Ticket
Writer: Abdul Williams (screenplay), Erik White (story), Abdul Williams (story)
Actors: Shad Moss, Brandon T. Jackson, Naturi Naughton, Loretta Devine
tomatoConsensus: There's a worthwhile message at the heart of Lottery Ticket, but it's buried under stale humor, tired stereotypes, and obvious clichés.

Plot: Four couples find themselves struggling to save their marriages once again on their annual marriage retreat, while each of them battle through financial, physical, mental, and emotional issues.
Title: Why Did I Get Married Too?
Actors: Tyler Perry, Janet Jackson, Jill Scott, Sharon Leal
tomatoConsensus: It's bolstered by a strong performance from Janet Jackson, but ultimately, Tyler Perry's Why Did I Get Married Too? doesn't add anything new to Perry's melodramatic formula.

Plot: A group of bank robbers find their multi-million dollar plan interrupted by a hard-boiled detective.
Title: Takers
Writer: Peter Allen, Gabriel Casseus, John Luessenhop, Avery Duff
Actors: Chris Brown, Hayden Christensen, Matt Dillon, Michael Ealy
tomatoConsensus: Takers boasts some gripping set pieces and keeps things moving quickly, but its two-dimensional characters, clichéd script, and brazenly derivative plot make it hard to recommend.

Plot: Ruthless executive Christine brings on Isabelle as her assistant, and she takes delight in toying with the young woman's innocence. But when the protégé's ideas become tempting enough for ...
Title: Love Crime
Writer: Alain Corneau (scenario,  adaptation and dialogue), Natalie Carter (scenario,  adaptation and dialogue)
Actors: Ludivine Sagnier, Kristin Scott Thomas, Patrick Mille, Guillaume Marquet
tomatoConsensus: Director Corneau's swan song, Love Crime is smart and typically well-directed, but too thin and formulaic to overcome its melodramatic trappings.

Plot: Two young wolves at opposite ends of their pack's social order are thrown together into a foreign land and need each other to return home, but love complicates everything.
Title: Alpha and Omega
Writer: Chris Denk (screenplay), Ben Gluck (additional screenplay), Ben Gluck (original story), Steve Moore (original screenplay and story)
Actors: Justin Long, Hayden Panettiere, Dennis Hopper, Danny Glover
tomatoConsensus: With bland visuals and a dull, predictable plot, Alpha and Omega is a runt in 2010's animated litter.

Plot: Mary Surratt is the lone female charged as a co-conspirator in the assassination trial of Abraham Lincoln. As the whole nation turns against her, she is forced to rely on her reluctant lawyer to uncover the truth and save her life.
Title: The Conspirator
Writer: James D. Solomon, James D. Solomon (story), Gregory Bernstein (story)
Actors: James McAvoy, Robin Wright, Kevin Kline, Evan Rachel Wood
tomatoConsensus: The Conspirator is well cast and tells a worthy story, but many viewers will lack the patience for Redford's deliberate, stagebound approach.

Plot: A young girl sent to live with her father and his new girlfriend believes that she has released creatures from a sealed ash pit in the basement of her new home.
Title: Don't Be Afraid of the Dark
Writer: Guillermo del Toro (screenplay), Matthew Robbins (screenplay), Nigel McKeand
Actors: Katie Holmes, Guy Pearce, Bailee Madison, Jack Thompson
tomatoConsensus: While it's pleasantly atmospheric and initially quite scary, Don't Be Afraid of the Dark ultimately fails to deliver the skin-crawling chills of the original.

Plot: A young boy has lost his mother and is losing touch with his father and the world around him. Then he meets Hesher who manages to make his life even more chaotic.
Title: Hesher
Writer: Spencer Susser, David Michôd, Brian Charles Frank (story)
Actors: Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Devin Brochu, Rainn Wilson, Piper Laurie
tomatoConsensus: It has a dark sense of humor and a refreshing lack of sentimentality, but like its title character, Hesher isn't really interested in going anywhere.

Plot: Martin was a normal teenage boy before the country collapsed in an empty pit of economic and political disaster. A vampire epidemic has swept across what is left of the nation's abandoned ...
Title: Stake Land
Actors: Connor Paolo, Gregory Jones, Traci Hovel, Nick Damici
tomatoConsensus: Though the genre is well worn at this point, director Jim Mickle focuses on strong characterization and eerie atmosphere to craft an effective apocalyptic vampire chiller that also manages to pack a mean punch.

Plot: In 1965, three Mossad agents cross into East Berlin to apprehend a notorious Nazi war criminal. Thirty years later, the secrets the agents share come back to haunt them.
Title: The Debt
Writer: Matthew Vaughn (screenplay), Jane Goldman (screenplay), Peter Straughan (screenplay), Assaf Bernstein (film "Ha-Hov"), Ido Rosenblum (film "Ha-Hov")
Actors: Helen Mirren, Tom Wilkinson, Ciarán Hinds, Romi Aboulafia
tomatoConsensus: Its time-shifting narrative creates distracting casting problems, but ultimately, The Debt is a smart, well-acted entry in a genre that could use more like it.

Plot: A profile of the noted and extraordinarily cheerful veteran New York City fashion photographer.
Title: Bill Cunningham New York
Actors: Bill Cunningham, Editta Sherman, Patrick McDonald, Howard Koda
tomatoConsensus: Suffused with happiness and modest charm, Bill Cunningham New York offers a touching, gently humorous portrait of its subject without invading his jealously guarded privacy.

Plot: A drama centered around a married couple who opened the first legal brothel in Nevada.
Title: Love Ranch
Actors: Helen Mirren, Joe Pesci, Sergio Peris-Mencheta, Gina Gershon
tomatoConsensus: Despite its saucy setup and the always marvelous Helen Mirren, Love Ranch is disappointingly flaccid.

Plot: A documentary on a former Miss Wyoming who is charged with abducting and imprisoning a young Mormon Missionary.
Title: Tabloid
Actors: Joyce McKinney, Peter Tory, Troy Williams, Jackson Shaw
tomatoConsensus: It's far from his most thought-provoking work, but Tabloid finds Errol Morris as smart, spirited, and engaging as ever.

Plot: A '40s period piece which revolves around an American expat who returns to Shanghai in the months before Pearl Harbor due to the death of his friend.
Title: Shanghai
Actors: John Cusack, Li Gong, Yun-Fat Chow, David Morse
tomatoConsensus: Shanghai is crippled by a weak story and fatally undermined by clunky direction, making for a period political drama that lacks all of its key components.

Plot: In modern-day Paris, a journalist finds her life becoming entwined with a young girl whose family was torn apart during the notorious Vel' d'Hiv Roundup in 1942.
Title: Sarah's Key
Writer: Tatiana De Rosnay (novel), Serge Joncour (screenplay), Gilles Paquet-Brenner (screenplay)
Actors: Kristin Scott Thomas, Mélusine Mayance, Niels Arestrup, Frédéric Pierrot
tomatoConsensus: Sarah's Key is an absorbing, impeccably-acted Holocaust drama with minor plot issues.

Plot: After the death of her father, an 8-year-old girl becomes convinced that he is whispering to her through the leaves of the gargantuan tree that towers over her house.
Title: The Tree
Writer: Judy Pascoe (novel), Julie Bertuccelli, Elizabeth J. Mars (first screenplay)
Actors: Charlotte Gainsbourg, Morgana Davies, Marton Csokas, Christian Byers
tomatoConsensus: Though it leans rather heavily on its central metaphor, The Tree is a moving and ultimately hopeful meditation on grief with shades of magical realism.

Plot: A drama based on the experiences of Kathryn Bolkovac, a Nebraska cop who served as a peacekeeper in post-war Bosnia and outed the U.N. for covering up a sex scandal.
Title: The Whistleblower
Actors: Rachel Weisz, Vanessa Redgrave, Monica Bellucci, David Strathairn
tomatoConsensus: Rachel Weisz puts on a compelling smoldering act though the film suffers from a literal-minded approach to the material.

Plot: A young police officer must survive his first day's duty in a small country town.
Title: Red Hill
Actors: Ryan Kwanten, Steve Bisley, Tommy Lewis, Claire van der Boom
tomatoConsensus: Though its attempts to rework genre conventions may fall flat with some, Red Hill is a beautifully shot, tightly paced thriller that marks a strong debut for director Patrick Hughes.

Plot: Through intimate interviews, provocative art, and rare, historical film and video footage, this feature documentary reveals how art addressing political consequences of discrimination and ...
Title: !Women Art Revolution
Actors: Lynn Hershman-Leeson
tomatoConsensus: Though a tad messy in spots, !Women Art Revolution is a worthy chronicle of an influential art movement seldom explored or documented.

Plot: A sheriff sees his state senate bid slide out onto the ice when his daughter begins to date the son of a charming but psychologically disturbed woman with whom the sheriff has engaged in a two-decade-long affair.
Title: Virginia
Actors: Jennifer Connelly, Ed Harris, Carrie Preston, Barry Shabaka Henley
tomatoConsensus: Brave, autobiographical, but also completely off the mark, Virginia is a frantic drama that fails to pull the viewer in.

Plot: An exploration of the clothes, the glamour and the decadence of iconic fashion designer Halston.
Title: Ultrasuede: In Search of Halston
Actors: Patricia Altschul, Phillip Bloch, Thom Browne, Stephen Burrows
tomatoConsensus: Its subject is fascinating, but Ultrasuede: In Search of Halston is a rambling and unfocused profile.

Plot: A physical therapist falls for the basketball player she is helping recover from a career-threatening injury.
Title: Just Wright
Actors: Queen Latifah, Common, Paula Patton, James Pickens Jr.
tomatoConsensus: Well-intentioned but formulaic, Just Wright has winning leads but can't overcome its preponderance of cliches.

Plot: In 1920s Vienna, a young girl receives a magical doll on Christmas Eve.
Title: The Nutcracker in 3D
Actors: Richard Philipps, Fernanda Dorogi, Kriszta Dorogi, Dániel Mogács
tomatoConsensus: Misguided, misconceived, and misbegotten on every level, The Nutcracker in 3D is a stunning exercise in astonishing cinematic wrong-headedness.

Plot: A wounded man searches for his sweetheart in the Mexican desert while on the run from the police, bounty hunters, and others.
Title: Kites
Writer: Anurag Basu (screenplay), Robin Bhatt (screenplay), Sanjeev Dutta (dialogue), Akarsh Khurana (additional English dialogue), Akarsh Khurana (screenplay), Rakesh Roshan (story)
Actors: Hrithik Roshan, Bárbara Mori, Kangana Ranaut, Steven Michael Quezada
tomatoConsensus: Thoroughly overwrought in true Bollywood fashion, Kites is deeply flawed -- and too effervescently charming to resist.

Plot: A book-smart teenager joins his school's wrestling team as a way to reunite his surviving family members, who split apart after the death of his father, a college wrestling legend, 10 years ago.
Title: Legendary
Actors: Patricia Clarkson, Devon Graye, John Cena, Madeleine Martin
tomatoConsensus: Maudlin, predictable, and clichéd, Legendary pins its talented cast under a heavy layer of formulaic schmaltz.

Plot: A modern-day take on the "Beauty and the Beast" tale where a New York teen is transformed into a hideous monster in order to find true love.
Title: Beastly
Actors: Alex Pettyfer, Justin Bradley, Mary-Kate Olsen, Dakota Johnson
tomatoConsensus: Fundamentally misguided, poorly written, and badly acted, Beastly adds little to the legacy of its timeless source material.

Plot: Following the death of his father, Britt Reid, heir to his father's large company, teams up with his late dad's assistant Kato to become a masked crime fighting team.
Title: The Green Hornet
Writer: Seth Rogen, Evan Goldberg, George W. Trendle (radio series "The Green Hornet")
Actors: Seth Rogen, Jay Chou, Cameron Diaz, Tom Wilkinson
tomatoConsensus: It's sporadically entertaining, but The Green Hornet never approaches the surreal heights suggested by a Michel Gondry/Seth Rogen collaboration.

Plot: 14th-century knights transport a suspected witch to a monastery, where monks deduce her powers could be the source of the Black Plague.
Title: Season of the Witch
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Ron Perlman, Stephen Campbell Moore, Stephen Graham
tomatoConsensus: Slow, cheap-looking, and dull, Season of the Witch fails even as unintentional comedy.

Plot: A spaceship arrives in Arizona, 1873, to take over the Earth, starting with the Wild West region. A posse of cowboys and natives are all that stand in their way.
Title: Cowboys & Aliens
Writer: Roberto Orci (screenplay), Alex Kurtzman (screenplay), Damon Lindelof (screenplay), Mark Fergus (screenplay), Hawk Ostby (screenplay), Mark Fergus (screen story), Hawk Ostby (screen story), Steve Oedekerk (screen story), Scott Mitchell Rosenberg (Platinum Studios comic book)
Actors: Daniel Craig, Abigail Spencer, Buck Taylor, Matthew Taylor
tomatoConsensus: Daniel Craig and Harrison Ford are as dependably appealing as ever, but they're let down by director Jon Favreau's inability to smooth Cowboys & Aliens' jarring tonal shifts.

Plot: A man discovers that his best friend's wife is having an affair.
Title: The Dilemma
Actors: Vince Vaughn, Kevin James, Jennifer Connelly, Winona Ryder
tomatoConsensus: It boasts a likable cast and an interesting premise, but The Dilemma can't decide what to do with them; the result is an uneven blend of cheesy slapstick and surprisingly dark comedy.

Plot: With the help of a mysterious pill that enables the user to access 100 percent of his brain abilities, a struggling writer becomes a financial wizard, but it also puts him in a new world with lots of dangers.
Title: Limitless
Actors: Bradley Cooper, Robert De Niro, Abbie Cornish, Andrew Howard
tomatoConsensus: Although its script is uneven, Neil Burger directs Limitless with plenty of visual panache, and Bradley Cooper makes for a charismatic star.

Plot: A guy and girl try to keep their relationship strictly physical, but it's not long before they learn that they want something more.
Title: No Strings Attached
Writer: Elizabeth Meriwether (screenplay), Michael Samonek (story), Elizabeth Meriwether (story)
Actors: Natalie Portman, Ashton Kutcher, Kevin Kline, Cary Elwes
tomatoConsensus: It benefits from the presence of Natalie Portman and director Ivan Reitman's steady hand, but No Strings Attached doesn't have the courage or conviction to follow through on its ribald premise.

Plot: Mick Haller is a defense lawyer who works out of his Lincoln. When a wealthy Realtor is accused of assaulting a prostitute, Haller is asked to defend him. The man claims that the woman is ...
Title: The Lincoln Lawyer
Actors: Matthew McConaughey, Marisa Tomei, Ryan Phillippe, William H. Macy
tomatoConsensus: It doesn't offer any twists on the predictable courtroom thriller formula, but with a charming Matthew McConaughey leading its solid cast, The Lincoln Lawyer offers briskly enjoyable entertainment.

Plot: An American seminary student travels to Italy to take an exorcism course.
Language: English, Welsh, Italian, Latin, Russian, Hungarian
Title: The Rite
Actors: Anthony Hopkins, Colin O'Donoghue, Alice Braga, Ciarán Hinds
tomatoConsensus: Anthony Hopkins is as excellent as ever, but he's no match for The Rite's dawdling pace and lack of chills -- or Colin O'Donoghue's tentative performance in the leading role.

Plot: A man awakens from a coma, only to discover that someone has taken on his identity and that no one, (not even his wife), believes him. With the help of a young woman, he sets out to prove who he is.
Title: Unknown
Writer: Oliver Butcher (screenplay), Stephen Cornwell (screenplay), Didier Van Cauwelaert (novel)
Actors: Liam Neeson, Diane Kruger, January Jones, Aidan Quinn
tomatoConsensus: Liam Neeson elevates the proceedings considerably, but Unknown is ultimately too derivative -- and implausible -- to take advantage of its intriguing premise.

Plot: An underwater cave diving team experiences a life-threatening crisis during an expedition to the unexplored and least accessible cave system in the world.
Title: Sanctum
Writer: John Garvin, Andrew Wight, Andrew Wight (story)
Actors: Richard Roxburgh, Ioan Gruffudd, Rhys Wakefield, Alice Parkinson
tomatoConsensus: Sanctum is beautifully photographed, and it makes better use of 3-D technology than most, but that doesn't make up for its ham-handed script and lifeless cast.

Plot: Tim Lippe has no idea what he's in for when he's sent to Cedar Rapids, Iowa to represent his company at an annual insurance convention, where he soon finds himself under the "guidance" of three convention veterans.
Title: Cedar Rapids
Actors: Ed Helms, John C. Reilly, Anne Heche, Isiah Whitlock Jr.
tomatoConsensus: It's as conventional as its Midwestern setting, but Cedar Rapids boasts a terrific cast and a script that deftly blends R-rated raunch and endearing sweetness.

Plot: The neighboring gardens of Montague and Capulet are at war, but the gnomes, Gnomeo and Juliet, are in love.
Title: Gnomeo & Juliet
Writer: Rob Sprackling (story), John R. Smith (story), Andy Riley (story), Kevin Cecil (story), Kelly Asbury (story), Steve Hamilton Shaw (story), Andy Riley (screenplay), Kevin Cecil (screenplay), Mark Burton (screenplay), Emily Cook (screenplay), Kathy Greenberg (screenplay), Steve Hamilton Shaw (screenplay), Kelly Asbury (screenplay), Rob Sprackling (original screenplay), John R. Smith (original screenplay), William Shakespeare (play)
Actors: James McAvoy, Emily Blunt, Ashley Jensen, Michael Caine
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 10 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: While it has moments of inspiration, Gnomeo and Juliet is often too self-referential for its own good.

Plot: Two British comic-book geeks traveling across the U.S. encounter an alien outside Area 51.
Title: Paul
Actors: Mia Stallard, Simon Pegg, Nick Frost, Jeremy Owen
tomatoConsensus: It doesn't measure up to Pegg and Frost's best work, but Paul is an amiably entertaining -- albeit uneven -- road trip comedy with an intergalactic twist.

Plot: A vengeful father escapes from hell and chases after the men who killed his daughter and kidnapped his granddaughter.
Title: Drive Angry
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Amber Heard, William Fichtner, Billy Burke
tomatoConsensus: It may deliver the over-the-top action pieces, but Drive Angry prefers to work safely within grindhouse formula than do something truly unique.

Plot: Rango is an ordinary chameleon who accidentally winds up in the town of Dirt, a lawless outpost in the Wild West in desperate need of a new sheriff.
Title: Rango
Writer: John Logan, John Logan (story), Gore Verbinski (story), James Ward Byrkit (story)
Actors: Johnny Depp, Isla Fisher, Abigail Breslin, Ned Beatty
tomatoConsensus: Rango is a smart, giddily creative burst of beautifully animated entertainment, and Johnny Depp gives a colorful vocal performance as a household pet in an unfamiliar world.

Plot: Four years after graduation, an awkward high school genius uses his sister's boyfriend's Labor Day party as the perfect opportunity to make his move on his high school crush.
Title: Take Me Home Tonight
Writer: Jackie Filgo (screenplay), Jeff Filgo (screenplay), Topher Grace (story), Gordon Kaywin (story)
Actors: Topher Grace, Anna Faris, Dan Fogler, Teresa Palmer
tomatoConsensus: It has a charming sweetness about it, but Take Me Home Tonight is neither funny nor original enough to live up to the comedies it evokes.

Plot: The affair between a politician and a contemporary dancer is affected by mysterious forces keeping the lovers apart.
Title: The Adjustment Bureau
Writer: George Nolfi (screenplay), Philip K. Dick (short story "Adjustment Team")
Actors: Matt Damon, Emily Blunt, Lisa Thoreson, Florence Kastriner
tomatoConsensus: First-time writer/director George Nolfi struggles to maintain a consistent tone, but The Adjustment Bureau rises on the strong, believable chemistry of its stars.

Plot: Follows an elite hit man as he teaches his trade to an apprentice who has a connection to one of his previous victims.
Title: The Mechanic
Writer: Richard Wenk (screenplay), Lewis John Carlino (screenplay), Lewis John Carlino (story)
Actors: Jason Statham, Ben Foster, Tony Goldwyn, Donald Sutherland
tomatoConsensus: Jason Statham and Ben Foster turn in enjoyable performances, but this superficial remake betrays them with mind-numbing violence and action thriller cliches.

Plot: Rick and Fred, two husbands who are having difficulty in their marriages, are given a Hall Pass by their wives: for one week, they can do whatever they want.
Title: Hall Pass
Writer: Pete Jones (screenplay), Peter Farrelly (screenplay), Kevin Barnett (screenplay), Bobby Farrelly (screenplay), Pete Jones (story)
Actors: Owen Wilson, Jason Sudeikis, Jenna Fischer, Christina Applegate
tomatoConsensus: Some filmgoers may be surprised by the Farrellys' defense of traditional domestic values in Hall Pass -- unfortunately, they'll probably also be dismayed by the absence of laughs.

Title: The Eagle
Actors: Channing Tatum, István Göz, Bence Gerö, Denis O'Hare
tomatoConsensus: The Eagle has a pleasantly traditional action-adventure appeal, but it's drowned out by Kevin Macdonald's stolid direction and Channing Tatum's uninspired work in the central role.

Plot: Aliens and their Guardians are hiding on Earth from intergalactic bounty hunters. They can only be killed in numerical order, and Number Four is next on the list. This is his story.
Title: I Am Number Four
Writer: Alfred Gough (screenplay), Miles Millar (screenplay), Marti Noxon (screenplay), Jobie Hughes (novel), James Frey (novel)
Actors: Alex Pettyfer, Timothy Olyphant, Teresa Palmer, Dianna Agron
tomatoConsensus: It's positioned as the start of a franchise, but I Am Number Four's familiar plot and unconvincing performances add up to one noisy, derivative, and ultimately forgettable sci-fi thriller.

Plot: A squadron of U.S. Marines becomes the last line of defense against a global invasion.
Title: Battle Los Angeles
Actors: Aaron Eckhart, Ramon Rodriguez, Will Rothhaar, Cory Hardrict
tomatoConsensus: Overlong and overly burdened with war movie clichés, Battle: Los Angeles will entertain only the most ardent action junkies.

Plot: A young boy named Milo gains a deeper appreciation for his mom after Martians come to Earth to take her away.
Title: Mars Needs Moms
Writer: Simon Wells (screenplay), Wendy Wells (screenplay), Berkeley Breathed (book)
Actors: Seth Green, Dan Fogler, Joan Cusack, Elisabeth Harnois
tomatoConsensus: The cast is solid and it's visually well-crafted, but Mars Needs Moms suffers from a lack of imagination and heart.

Plot: On a weekend trip to Hawaii, a plastic surgeon convinces his loyal assistant to pose as his soon-to-be-divorced wife in order to cover up a careless lie he told to his much-younger girlfriend.
Title: Just Go with It
Writer: Allan Loeb (screenplay), Timothy Dowling (screenplay), I.A.L. Diamond (screenplay), Abe Burrows (stage play), Pierre Barillet (French play), Jean-Pierre Grédy (French play)
Actors: Adam Sandler, Jennifer Aniston, Nicole Kidman, Nick Swardson
tomatoConsensus: Just Go With It may be slightly better than some entries in the recently dire rom-com genre, but that's far from a recommendation.

Plot: Set in a medieval village that is haunted by a werewolf, a young girl falls for an orphaned woodcutter, much to her family's displeasure.
Title: Red Riding Hood
Actors: Amanda Seyfried, Gary Oldman, Billy Burke, Shiloh Fernandez
tomatoConsensus: Amanda Seyfried is magnetic in Red Riding Hood's starring role, but she's let down by her uninspired leading men and a painfully cliched script.

Plot: Malcolm Turner and his stepson Trent go undercover at an all-girls school to flush out a killer.
Title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
Writer: Matt Fogel (screenplay), Don Rhymer (story), Matt Fogel (story), Darryl Quarles (characters)
Actors: Martin Lawrence, Brandon T. Jackson, Jessica Lucas, Michelle Ang
tomatoConsensus: Unnecessary, unfunny, and generally unwelcome, Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son offers more of the same for fans of Martin Lawrence's perplexingly popular series.

Plot: A soldier wakes up in someone else's body and discovers he's part of an experimental government program to find the bomber of a commuter train. A mission he has only 8 minutes to complete.
Title: Source Code
Actors: Jake Gyllenhaal, Michelle Monaghan, Vera Farmiga, Jeffrey Wright
tomatoConsensus: Finding the human story amidst the action, director Duncan Jones and charming Jake Gyllenhaal craft a smart, satisfying sci-fi thriller.

Plot: A young girl is institutionalized by her abusive stepfather. Retreating to an alternative reality as a coping strategy, she envisions a plan which will help her escape from the mental facility.
Title: Sucker Punch
Writer: Zack Snyder (screenplay), Steve Shibuya (screenplay), Zack Snyder (story)
Actors: Emily Browning, Abbie Cornish, Jena Malone, Vanessa Hudgens
tomatoConsensus: It's technically impressive and loaded with eye-catching images, but without characters or a plot to support them, all of Sucker Punch's visual thrills are for naught.

Plot: Former skateboard champion Kim wants to make more money after her mother's tragic death. She joins the elite posh servicing company, which sends her off to Austria.
Title: Chalet Girl
Actors: Miquita Oliver, Rick Edwards, Felicity Jones, Bill Bailey
tomatoConsensus: Chalet Girl is light comedic fun geared for teenage girls, featuring a charming performance from Felicity Jones.

Plot: A struggling lawyer and volunteer wrestling coach's chicanery comes back to haunt him when the teenage grandson of the client he has double-crossed comes into his life.
Title: Win Win
Writer: Tom McCarthy (screenplay), Tom McCarthy (story), Joe Tiboni (story)
Actors: Paul Giamatti, Amy Ryan, Bobby Cannavale, Jeffrey Tambor
tomatoConsensus: Rich, wonderful characters and strong performances populate Win Win, with writer/director Thomas McCarthy continuing to emerge as a great American humanist.

Plot: Back in middle school after summer vacation, Greg Heffley and his older brother Rodrick must deal with their parents' misguided attempts to have them bond.
Title: Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Rodrick Rules
Writer: Gabe Sachs (screenplay), Jeff Judah (screenplay), Jeff Kinney (book)
Actors: Zachary Gordon, Devon Bostick, Rachael Harris, Robert Capron
tomatoConsensus: Moderately witty and acceptably acted, Diary of a Wimpy Kid 2 isn't much worse than the first installment.

Plot: E.B., the Easter Bunny's teenage son, heads to Hollywood, determined to become a drummer in a rock 'n' roll band. In LA, he's taken in by Fred after the out-of-work slacker hits E.B. with his car.
Title: Hop
Writer: Cinco Paul (screenplay), Ken Daurio (screenplay), Brian Lynch (screenplay), Cinco Paul (story), Ken Daurio (story)
Actors: James Marsden, Russell Brand, Kaley Cuoco, Hank Azaria
tomatoConsensus: It's impressively animated, but Hop's script is so uninspired that not even James Marsden's frantic mugging can give it any bounce.

Plot: A sixteen-year-old girl who was raised by her father to be the perfect assassin is dispatched on a mission across Europe, tracked by a ruthless intelligence agent and her operatives.
Language: English, French, German, Italian, Arabic, Spanish
Title: Hanna
Writer: Seth Lochhead (screenplay), David Farr (screenplay), Seth Lochhead (story)
Actors: Saoirse Ronan, Eric Bana, Vicky Krieps, Cate Blanchett
tomatoConsensus: Fantastic acting and crisply choreographed action sequences propel this unique, cool take on the revenge thriller.

Plot: A drunken playboy stands to lose a wealthy inheritance when he falls for a woman his family doesn't like.
Title: Arthur
Actors: Russell Brand, Helen Mirren, Greta Gerwig, Jennifer Garner
tomatoConsensus: An irritating, unnecessary remake that demonstrates the libertine charm Russell Brand exudes in supporting roles turn against him when he's star of the show.

Plot: Ten years have passed, and Sidney Prescott, who has put herself back together thanks in part to her writing, is visited by the Ghostface Killer.
Title: Scream 4
Actors: Lucy Hale, Roger Jackson, Shenae Grimes-Beech, Dane Farwell
tomatoConsensus: The franchise is showing its age, but Scream 4 is undeniably an improvement over its predecessor, with just enough meta humor and clever kills.

Plot: When Blu, a domesticated macaw from small-town Minnesota, meets the fiercely independent Jewel, he takes off on an adventure to Rio de Janeiro with the bird of his dreams.
Title: Rio
Writer: Carlos Saldanha (story), Earl Richey Jones (story), Todd R. Jones (story), Don Rhymer (screenplay), Joshua Sternin (screenplay), Jennifer Ventimilia (screenplay), Sam Harper (screenplay)
Actors: Karen Disher, Jason Fricchione, Sofia Scarpa Saldanha, Leslie Mann
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 28 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: This straightforward movie reaches great heights thanks to its colorful visual palette, catchy music, and funny vocal performances.

Plot: Two sisters find their already strained relationship challenged as a mysterious new planet threatens to collide with Earth.
Title: Melancholia
Actors: Kirsten Dunst, Charlotte Gainsbourg, Alexander Skarsgård, Brady Corbet
tomatoConsensus: Melancholia's dramatic tricks are more obvious than they should be, but this is otherwise a showcase for Kirsten Dunst's acting and for Lars von Trier's profound, visceral vision of depression and destruction.

Plot: The powerful but arrogant god Thor is cast out of Asgard to live amongst humans in Midgard (Earth), where he soon becomes one of their finest defenders.
Title: Thor
Writer: Ashley Miller (screenplay), Zack Stentz (screenplay), Don Payne (screenplay), J. Michael Straczynski (story), Mark Protosevich (story), Stan Lee (comic book), Larry Lieber (comic book), Jack Kirby (comic book)
Actors: Chris Hemsworth, Natalie Portman, Tom Hiddleston, Anthony Hopkins
tomatoConsensus: A dazzling blockbuster that tempers its sweeping scope with wit, humor, and human drama, Thor is mighty Marvel entertainment.

Plot: Railroad executive Dagny Taggart and steel mogul Henry Rearden form an alliance to fight the increasingly authoritarian government of the United States.
Title: Atlas Shrugged: Part I
Writer: Brian Patrick O'Toole (screenplay), John Aglialoro (screenplay), Ayn Rand (novel)
Actors: Taylor Schilling, Grant Bowler, Matthew Marsden, Edi Gathegi
tomatoConsensus: Passionate ideologues may find it compelling, but most filmgoers will find this low-budget adaptation of the Ayn Rand bestseller decidedly lacking.

Plot: Set in the 1930s, a former veterinary student takes a job in a traveling circus and falls in love with the ringmaster's wife.
Title: Water for Elephants
Actors: Reese Witherspoon, Robert Pattinson, Christoph Waltz, Paul Schneider
tomatoConsensus: It's a tale tastefully told and beautifully filmed, but Water for Elephants suffers from a pronounced lack of chemistry between its leads.

Plot: A nature documentary centered on two cat families and how they teach their cubs the ways of the wild.
Title: African Cats
Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Patrick Stewart, Mara
tomatoConsensus: It isn't quite as majestic as its subjects, but African Cats boasts enough astounding footage -- and a big enough heart -- to keep things entertaining.

Plot: Dominic Toretto and his crew of street racers plan a massive heist to buy their freedom while in the sights of a powerful Brazilian drug lord and a dangerous federal agent.
Title: Fast Five
Actors: Vin Diesel, Paul Walker, Jordana Brewster, Tyrese Gibson
tomatoConsensus: Sleek, loud, and over the top, Fast Five proudly embraces its brainless action thrills and injects new life into the franchise.

Plot: Teenage surfer Bethany Hamilton overcomes the odds and her own fears of returning to the water after losing her left arm in a shark attack.
Title: Soul Surfer
Writer: Sean McNamara (screenplay), Deborah Schwartz (screenplay), Douglas Schwartz (screenplay), Michael Berk (screenplay), Sean McNamara (screen story), Deborah Schwartz (screen story), Douglas Schwartz (screen story), Michael Berk (screen story), Matt Allen (screen story), Caleb Wilson (screen story), Brad Gann (screen story), Bethany Hamilton (book), Sheryl Berk (book), Rick Bundschuh (book)
Actors: AnnaSophia Robb, Helen Hunt, Dennis Quaid, Carrie Underwood
tomatoConsensus: There's an amazing true story at the heart of Soul Surfer -- and unfortunately, it's drowned by waves of Hollywood cheese.

Plot: Friendships are tested and secrets come to the surface when terminally single Rachel falls for Dex, her best friend Darcy's fiancé.
Title: Something Borrowed
Actors: Ginnifer Goodwin, Kate Hudson, Colin Egglesfield, John Krasinski
tomatoConsensus: In spite of solid performances from Kate Hudson and John Krasinski, Something Borrowed is an unpleasant misfire that lives down to its title.

Plot: Competition between the maid of honor and a bridesmaid, over who is the bride's best friend, threatens to upend the life of an out-of-work pastry chef.
Title: Bridesmaids
Actors: Kristen Wiig, Terry Crews, Maya Rudolph, Tom Yi
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 25 wins & 67 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A marriage of genuine characters, gross out gags, and pathos, Bridesmaids is a female-driven comedy that refuses to be boxed in as Kristen Wiig emerges as a real star.

Plot: A priest disobeys church law to track down the vampires who kidnapped his niece.
Title: Priest
Writer: Cory Goodman, Min-Woo Hyung (graphic novel series "Priest")
Actors: Paul Bettany, Karl Urban, Cam Gigandet, Maggie Q
tomatoConsensus: Sleek and stylish, but those qualities are wasted on a dull, derivative blend of sci-fi, action, and horror.

Plot: A troubled husband and executive adopts a beaver hand-puppet as his sole means of communicating.
Title: The Beaver
Actors: Mel Gibson, Cherry Jones, Jodie Foster, Anton Yelchin
tomatoConsensus: Jodie Foster's visual instincts and Mel Gibson's all-in performance sell this earnest, straightforward movie.

Plot: Jack Sparrow and Barbossa embark on a quest to find the elusive fountain of youth, only to discover that Blackbeard and his daughter are after it too.
Title: Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides
Writer: Ted Elliott (screenplay), Terry Rossio (screenplay), Ted Elliott (screen story), Terry Rossio (screen story), Ted Elliott (characters), Terry Rossio (characters), Stuart Beattie (characters), Jay Wolpert (characters), Tim Powers (novel)
Actors: Johnny Depp, Penélope Cruz, Geoffrey Rush, Ian McShane
tomatoConsensus: It's shorter and leaner than the previous sequel, but this Pirates runs aground on a disjointed plot and a non-stop barrage of noisy action sequences.

Plot: While on a trip to Paris with his fiancée's family, a nostalgic screenwriter finds himself mysteriously going back to the 1920s everyday at midnight.
Title: Midnight in Paris
Actors: Owen Wilson, Rachel McAdams, Kurt Fuller, Mimi Kennedy
tomatoConsensus: It may not boast the depth of his classic films, but the sweetly sentimental Midnight in Paris is funny and charming enough to satisfy Woody Allen fans.

Plot: The story of a family in Waco, Texas in 1956. The eldest son witnesses the loss of innocence and struggles with his parents' conflicting teachings.
Title: The Tree of Life
Actors: Brad Pitt, Sean Penn, Jessica Chastain, Hunter McCracken
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 105 wins & 111 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Terrence Malick's singularly deliberate style may prove unrewarding for some, but for patient viewers, Tree of Life is an emotional as well as visual treat.

Plot: Two years after the bachelor party in Las Vegas, Phil, Stu, Alan, and Doug jet to Thailand for Stu's wedding. Stu's plan for a subdued pre-wedding brunch, however, goes seriously awry.
Title: The Hangover Part II
Writer: Craig Mazin, Scot Armstrong, Todd Phillips, Jon Lucas (characters), Scott Moore (characters)
Actors: Bradley Cooper, Ed Helms, Zach Galifianakis, Justin Bartha
tomatoConsensus: A crueler, darker, raunchier carbon copy of the first installment, The Hangover Part II lacks the element of surprise -- and most of the joy -- that helped make the original a hit.

Plot: A tribute to the late German choreographer, Pina Bausch, as her dancers perform her most famous creations.
Language: German, French, English, Spanish, Croatian, Italian, Portuguese, Russian, Korean
Title: Pina
Actors: Regina Advento, Malou Airaudo, Ruth Amarante, Jorge Puerta
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 23 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Pina is an immersive, gorgeously shot tribute to the people who express life through movement.

Plot: When college freshman Sara arrives on campus for the first time, she befriends her roommate, Rebecca, unaware that the girl is becoming dangerously obsessed with her.
Title: The Roommate
Actors: Leighton Meester, Minka Kelly, Cam Gigandet, Aly Michalka
tomatoConsensus: Devoid of chills, thrills, or even cheap titillation, The Roommate isn't even bad enough to be good.

Plot: A teen gang in South London defend their block from an alien invasion.
Title: Attack the Block
Actors: Jodie Whittaker, John Boyega, Alex Esmail, Leeon Jones
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 18 wins & 35 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Effortlessly mixing scares, laughs, and social commentary, Attack the Block is a thrilling, brisky-paced sci-fi yarn with a distinctly British flavor.

Plot: Po and his friends fight to stop a peacock villain from conquering China with a deadly new weapon, but first the Dragon Warrior must come to terms with his past.
Title: Kung Fu Panda 2
Actors: Jack Black, Angelina Jolie, Dustin Hoffman, Gary Oldman
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 44 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The storyline arc may seem a tad familiar to fans of the original, but Kung Fu Panda 2 offers enough action, comedy, and visual sparkle to compensate.

Plot: In 1962, the United States government enlists the help of Mutants with superhuman abilities to stop a malicious dictator who is determined to start World War III.
Title: X-Men: First Class
Writer: Ashley Miller (screenplay), Zack Stentz (screenplay), Jane Goldman (screenplay), Matthew Vaughn (screenplay), Sheldon Turner (story), Bryan Singer (story)
Actors: James McAvoy, Laurence Belcher, Michael Fassbender, Bill Milner
tomatoConsensus: With a strong script, stylish direction, and powerful performances from its well-rounded cast, X-Men: First Class is a welcome return to form for the franchise.

Plot: During the summer of 1979, a group of friends witness a train crash and investigate subsequent unexplained events in their small town.
Title: Super 8
Actors: Joel Courtney, Jessica Tuck, Joel McKinnon Miller, Ryan Lee
tomatoConsensus: It may evoke memories of classic summer blockbusters a little too eagerly for some, but Super 8 has thrills, visual dazzle, and emotional depth to spare.

Plot: Reckless test pilot Hal Jordan is granted an alien ring that bestows him with otherworldly powers that inducts him into an intergalactic police force, the Green Lantern Corps.
Title: Green Lantern
Writer: Greg Berlanti (screenplay), Michael Green (screenplay), Marc Guggenheim (screenplay), Michael Goldenberg (screenplay), Greg Berlanti (screen story), Michael Green (screen story), Marc Guggenheim (screen story)
Actors: Ryan Reynolds, Blake Lively, Peter Sarsgaard, Mark Strong
tomatoConsensus: Noisy, overproduced, and thinly written, Green Lantern squanders an impressive budget and decades of comics mythology.

Plot: The life of a businessman begins to change after he inherits six penguins, and as he transforms his apartment into a winter wonderland, his professional side starts to unravel.
Title: Mr. Popper's Penguins
Writer: Sean Anders (screenplay), John Morris (screenplay), Jared Stern (screenplay), Richard Atwater (novel), Florence Atwater (novel)
Actors: Jim Carrey, Carla Gugino, Angela Lansbury, Ophelia Lovibond
tomatoConsensus: Blandly inoffensive and thoroughly predictable, Mr. Popper's Penguins could have been worse -- but it should have been better.

Plot: A lazy, incompetent middle school teacher who hates her job, her students, and her co-workers is forced to return to teaching to make enough money for breast implants after her wealthy fiancé dumps her.
Title: Bad Teacher
Actors: Cameron Diaz, Lucy Punch, Jason Segel, Justin Timberlake
tomatoConsensus: In spite of a promising concept and a charmingly brazen performance from Cameron Diaz, Bad Teacher is never as funny as it should be.

Plot: The Autobots learn of a Cybertronian spacecraft hidden on the moon, and race against the Decepticons to reach it and to learn its secrets.
Title: Transformers: Dark of the Moon
Actors: Shia LaBeouf, Rosie Huntington-Whiteley, Josh Duhamel, John Turturro
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 40 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Its special effects -- and 3D shots -- are undeniably impressive, but they aren't enough to fill up its loud, bloated running time, or mask its thin, indifferent script.

Plot: After losing his job, a middle-aged man reinvents himself by going back to college.
Title: Larry Crowne
Actors: Tom Hanks, Sarah Mahoney, Roxana Ortega, Randall Park
tomatoConsensus: Despite the relaxed, easy chemistry of stars Tom Hanks and Julia Roberts, Larry Crowne is surprisingly bland and conventional.

Plot: When Prince Fabious's bride is kidnapped, he goes on a quest to rescue her... accompanied by his lazy useless brother Thadeous.
Title: Your Highness
Actors: Danny McBride, James Franco, Rasmus Hardiker, Natalie Portman
tomatoConsensus: Big budgets and costumes in service of scatalogical jokes may seem funny on paper, but in execution this is a highly monotonous romp that registers only occasional laughs.

Plot: Third grader Judy Moody sets out to have the most thrilling summer of her life.
Title: Judy Moody and the Not Bummer Summer
Writer: Kathy Waugh (screenplay), Megan McDonald (screenplay), Megan McDonald ("Judy Moody" book series)
Actors: Jordana Beatty, Parris Mosteller, Janet Varney, Kristoffer Ryan Winters
tomatoConsensus: Entertaining for some very young viewers, but for those with normal attention spans, Judy Moody is loud hyperactive overload.

Plot: A group of zoo animals decide to break their code of silence in order to help their lovable zoo keeper find love -- without opting to leave his current job for something more illustrious.
Title: Zookeeper
Writer: Nick Bakay (screenplay), Rock Reuben (screenplay), Kevin James (screenplay), Jay Scherick (screenplay), David Ronn (screenplay), Jay Scherick (story), David Ronn (story)
Actors: Kevin James, Rosario Dawson, Leslie Bibb, Ken Jeong
tomatoConsensus: Zookeeper smothers Kevin James's with a sodden script and a surfeit of jokes inappropriate for the young viewers who would be intrigued by its juvenile storyline.

Plot: Three friends conspire to murder their awful bosses when they realize they are standing in the way of their happiness.
Title: Horrible Bosses
Writer: Michael Markowitz (screenplay), John Francis Daley (screenplay), Jonathan Goldstein (screenplay), Michael Markowitz (story)
Actors: Jason Bateman, Steve Wiebe, Kevin Spacey, Charlie Day
tomatoConsensus: It's nasty, uneven, and far from original, but thanks to a smartly assembled cast that makes the most of a solid premise, Horrible Bosses works.

Plot: Star race car Lightning McQueen and his pal Mater head overseas to compete in the World Grand Prix race. But the road to the championship becomes rocky as Mater gets caught up in an intriguing adventure of his own: international espionage.
Title: Cars 2
Writer: John Lasseter (original story by), Brad Lewis (original story by), Dan Fogelman (original story by), Ben Queen (screenplay)
Actors: Larry the Cable Guy, Owen Wilson, Michael Caine, Emily Mortimer
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 16 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Cars 2 is as visually appealing as any other Pixar production, but all that dazzle can't disguise the rusty storytelling under the hood.

Plot: Three young women vacationing in Paris find themselves whisked away to Monte Carlo after one of the girls is mistaken for a British heiress.
Title: Monte Carlo
Writer: Thomas Bezucha (screenplay), April Blair (screenplay), Maria Maggenti (screenplay), Kelly Bowe (screen story), Jules Bass (novel)
Actors: Selena Gomez, Katie Cassidy, Leighton Meester, Cory Monteith
tomatoConsensus: Although it has its charming moments, Monte Carlo is mostly silly, predictable stuff that never pushes beyond the boundaries of formula.

Plot: Harry, Ron and Hermione search for Voldemort's remaining Horcruxes in their effort to destroy the Dark Lord as the final battle rages on at Hogwarts.
Title: Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 2
Actors: Ralph Fiennes, Michael Gambon, Alan Rickman, Daniel Radcliffe
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 46 wins & 87 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Thrilling, powerfully acted, and visually dazzling, Deathly Hallows Part II brings the Harry Potter franchise to a satisfying -- and suitably magical -- conclusion.

Plot: A mysterious Hollywood stuntman and mechanic moonlights as a getaway driver and finds himself in trouble when he helps out his neighbor.
Title: Drive
Actors: Ryan Gosling, Carey Mulligan, Bryan Cranston, Albert Brooks
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 74 wins & 162 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: With its hyper-stylized blend of violence, music, and striking imagery, Drive represents a fully realized vision of arthouse action.

Plot: Steve Rogers, a rejected military soldier transforms into Captain America after taking a dose of a "Super-Soldier serum". But being Captain America comes at a price as he attempts to take down a war monger and a terrorist organization.
Title: Captain America: The First Avenger
Writer: Christopher Markus (screenplay), Stephen McFeely (screenplay), Joe Simon (comic books), Jack Kirby (comic books)
Actors: Chris Evans, Hayley Atwell, Sebastian Stan, Tommy Lee Jones
tomatoConsensus: With plenty of pulpy action, a pleasantly retro vibe, and a handful of fine performances, Captain America is solidly old-fashioned blockbuster entertainment.

Plot: A middle-aged husband's life changes dramatically when his wife asks him for a divorce. He seeks to rediscover his manhood with the help of a newfound friend, Jacob, learning to pick up girls at bars.
Title: Crazy, Stupid, Love.
Actors: Steve Carell, Ryan Gosling, Julianne Moore, Emma Stone
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 20 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It never lives up to the first part of its title, but Crazy, Stupid, Love's unabashed sweetness -- and its terrifically talented cast -- more than make up for its flaws.

Plot: After spending the night together on the night of their college graduation Dexter and Em are shown each year on the same date to see where they are in their lives. They are sometimes together, sometimes not, on that day.
Title: One Day
Actors: Anne Hathaway, Jim Sturgess, Tom Mison, Jodie Whittaker
tomatoConsensus: Despite some fresh narrative twists, One Day lacks the emotion, depth, or insight of its bestselling source material.

Plot: An unorthodox Irish policeman with a confrontational personality is partnered with an up-tight F.B.I. agent to investigate an international drug-smuggling ring.
Title: The Guard
Actors: Ronan Collins, Paraic Nialand, John Patrick Beirne, Liam O'Conghaile
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 14 wins & 25 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A violent, crackerjack comedy with a strong Irish flavor and an emminently likable Brendan Gleeson in the main role.

Plot: During an ordinary day in Hundred Acre Wood, Winnie the Pooh sets out to find some honey. Misinterpreting a note from Christopher Robin, Owl convinces Tigger, Rabbit, Piglet, Pooh, Kanga, ...
Title: Winnie the Pooh
Writer: Stephen J. Anderson (story by), Clio Chiang (story by), Don Dougherty (story by), Don Hall (story by), Kendelle Hoyer (story by), Brian Kesinger (story by), Nicole Mitchell (story by), Jeremy Spears (story by), A.A. Milne (based upon the works of), Ernest Shepard (based upon the works of)
Actors: John Cleese, Jim Cummings, Bud Luckey, Craig Ferguson
tomatoConsensus: Short, nostalgic, and gently whimsical, Winnie the Pooh offers young audiences -- and their parents -- a sweetly traditional family treat.

Plot: When the evil wizard Gargamel chases the tiny blue Smurfs out of their village, they tumble from their magical world into New York City.
Title: The Smurfs
Writer: J. David Stem (screenplay), David N. Weiss (screenplay), Jay Scherick (screenplay), David Ronn (screenplay), J. David Stem (story), David N. Weiss (story), Peyo (characters)
Actors: Hank Azaria, Neil Patrick Harris, Jayma Mays, Sofía Vergara
tomatoConsensus: The Smurfs assembles an undeniably talented cast of voice actors and live-action stars -- then crushes them beneath a blue mound of lowest-common-denominator kiddie fare.

Plot: A young man and woman decide to take their friendship to the next level without becoming a couple, but soon discover that adding sex only leads to complications.
Title: Friends with Benefits
Writer: Keith Merryman (screenplay), David A. Newman (screenplay), Will Gluck (screenplay), Harley Peyton (story), Keith Merryman (story), David A. Newman (story)
Actors: Justin Timberlake, Mila Kunis, Patricia Clarkson, Jenna Elfman
tomatoConsensus: Friends with Benefits adds nothing new to its well-worn rom-com formula, but the chemistry between Justin Timberlake and Mila Kunis is almost enough to carry the movie by itself.

Plot: A comedy centered on an idealist who barges into the lives of his three sisters.
Title: Our Idiot Brother
Writer: Jesse Peretz (story), Evgenia Peretz (story), David Schisgall (story), Evgenia Peretz (screenplay), David Schisgall (screenplay)
Actors: Paul Rudd, Nick Sullivan, Francesca Papalia, Bob Stephenson
tomatoConsensus: It's decidedly uneven, but like Paul Rudd's performance in the title role, Our Idiot Brother is too charming to resist.

Plot: Michael Rapaport documents the inner workings and behind the scenes drama that follows this innovative and influential band to this day.
Title: Beats, Rhymes & Life: The Travels of a Tribe Called Quest
Actors: Phife Dawg, Ali Shaheed Muhammad, Q-Tip, Jarobi White
tomatoConsensus: This documentary focuses less on the music and more on the personality clashes and in-group tensions to great, compelling effect.

Plot: A substance, designed to help the brain repair itself, gives rise to a super-intelligent chimp who leads an ape uprising.
Title: Rise of the Planet of the Apes
Writer: Rick Jaffa, Amanda Silver, Pierre Boulle (novel)
Actors: Andy Serkis, Karin Konoval, Terry Notary, Richard Ridings
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 20 wins & 41 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Led by Rupert Wyatt's stylish direction, some impressive special effects, and a mesmerizing performance by Andy Serkis, Rise of the Planet of the Apes breathes unlikely new life into a long-running franchise.

Plot: Dave is a married man with three kids and a loving wife, and Mitch is a single man who is at the prime of his sexual life. One fateful night while Mitch and Dave are peeing in a fountain, lightning strikes and they switch bodies.
Title: The Change-Up
Actors: Ryan Reynolds, Jason Bateman, Leslie Mann, Olivia Wilde
tomatoConsensus: There's a certain amount of fun to be had from watching Bateman and Reynolds play against type, but it isn't enough to carry The Change-Up through its crude humor and formulaic plot.

Plot: An aspiring author during the civil rights movement of the 1960s decides to write a book detailing the African American maids' point of view on the white families for which they work, and the hardships they go through on a daily basis.
Title: The Help
Actors: Emma Stone, Viola Davis, Bryce Dallas Howard, Octavia Spencer
tomatoConsensus: Though arguably guilty of glossing over its racial themes, The Help rises on the strength of its cast -- particularly Viola Davis, whose performance is powerful enough to carry the film on its own.

Plot: Two fledgling criminals kidnap a pizza delivery guy, strap a bomb to his chest, and inform him that he has mere hours to rob a bank or else...
Title: 30 Minutes or Less
Writer: Michael Diliberti (screenplay), Michael Diliberti (story), Matthew Sullivan (story)
Actors: Jesse Eisenberg, Danny McBride, Aziz Ansari, Nick Swardson
tomatoConsensus: It's sporadically funny and it benefits from a talented cast, but 30 Minutes or Less suffers from a disjointed narrative, and too often mistakes crude gags for true lowbrow humor.

Plot: A concert documentary shot during the Glee Live! In Concert! summer 2011 tour, featuring song performances and Glee fans' life stories and how the show influenced them.
Title: Glee: The 3D Concert Movie
Actors: Dianna Agron, Chris Colfer, Darren Criss, Kevin McHale
tomatoConsensus: The unconverted will remain just as perplexed as ever, but for gleeful Gleeks, The 3D Concert Movie delivers exactly what it promises.

Plot: Survivors of a suspension-bridge collapse learn there's no way you can cheat Death.
Title: Final Destination 5
Actors: Nicholas D'Agosto, Emma Bell, Miles Fisher, Ellen Wroe
tomatoConsensus: It's still only for the gore-thirsty faithful, but Final Destination 5 represents a surprising return to form for the franchise.

Plot: Six years after their Guantanamo Bay adventure, stoner buds Harold Lee and Kumar Patel cause a holiday fracas by inadvertently burning down Harold's father-in-law's prize Christmas tree.
Title: A Very Harold & Kumar 3D Christmas
Writer: Jon Hurwitz, Hayden Schlossberg, Jon Hurwitz (characters), Hayden Schlossberg (characters)
Actors: Patton Oswalt, Isabella Gielniak, Kal Penn, Austin Bickel
tomatoConsensus: Still raunchy, still irreverent, and still hit-and-miss, this Harold & Kumar outing also has a Christmas miracle: The audience gets to see the sweeter side of the duo.

Plot: A retired spy is called back into action, and to bond with her new step-children, she invites them along for the adventure to stop the evil Timekeeper from taking over the world.
Title: Spy Kids: All the Time in the World in 4D
Actors: Jessica Alba, Joel McHale, Rowan Blanchard, Mason Cook
tomatoConsensus: Burdened by a rote plot and unfunny scatological humor, All the Time in the World suggests that the Spy Kids franchise has run its course.

Plot: After a new neighbor moved into the house next door, Charley discovers that he is an ancient vampire and goes in search for the help of Peter Vincent, a famous "vampire killer" to save his neighborhood from the creature.
Title: Fright Night
Writer: Marti Noxon (screenplay), Tom Holland (story), Tom Holland (film "Fright Night")
Actors: Anton Yelchin, Colin Farrell, Toni Collette, David Tennant
tomatoConsensus: It may not have been necessary to remake the 1985 cult classic, but the new Fright Night benefits from terrific performances by Colin Farrell and David Tennant -- and it's smart, funny, and stylishly gory to boot.

Plot: A documentary about branding, advertising and product placement that is financed and made possible by brands, advertising and product placement.
Title: The Greatest Movie Ever Sold
Actors: J.J. Abrams, Peter Berg, Paul Brennan, Noam Chomsky
tomatoConsensus: The Greatest Movie Ever Sold plays smartly to Spurlock's strengths, and the result is a breezy, albeit not particularly enlightening documentary.

Plot: A young woman, after witnessing her parents' murder as a child in Bogota, grows up to be a stone-cold assassin.
Title: Colombiana
Actors: Zoe Saldana, Jordi Mollà, Lennie James, Amandla Stenberg
tomatoConsensus: Zoe Saldana has the chops but she's taken out by erratic and sloppy filmmaking.

Plot: A vengeful barbarian warrior sets off to get his revenge on the evil warlord who attacked his village and murdered his father when he was a boy.
Title: Conan the Barbarian
Writer: Thomas Dean Donnelly, Joshua Oppenheimer, Sean Hood, Robert E. Howard (character of Conan)
Actors: Jason Momoa, Stephen Lang, Rachel Nichols, Ron Perlman
tomatoConsensus: While its relentless, gory violence is more faithful to the Robert E. Howard books, Conan the Barbarian forsakes three-dimensional characters, dialogue, and acting in favor of unnecessary 3D effects.

Plot: A group of teenagers get ready for their high school prom.
Title: Prom
Actors: Aimee Teegarden, Thomas McDonell, DeVaughn Nixon, Danielle Campbell
tomatoConsensus: Given its flatly descriptive title and live-action Disney pedigree, Prom is more nuanced and less cynical -- but also just as corny and cliched -- as you might expect.

Plot: A freewheeling portrait of Ken Kesey and the Merry Pranksters' fabled road trip across America.
Title: Magic Trip: Ken Kesey's Search for a Kool Place
Writer: Alex Gibney (screenplay), Alex Gibney, Alison Ellwood (screenplay), Ken Kesey (words and recordings), Ken Kesey (based on the works of)
Actors: Stanley Tucci, Jim Meskimen, Veronica Taylor, Timothy Leary
tomatoConsensus: Magic Trip is overall unenlightening, though there's an inherent novelty and joy in seeing the unearthed footage of Ken Kesey and his band of Merry Pranksters.

Plot: Tells the story of a chimpanzee taken from its mother at birth and raised like a human child by a family in a brownstone on the upper West Side in the 1970s.
Title: Project Nim
Actors: Nim Chimpsky, Stephanie LaFarge, Herbert Terrace, Wer LaFarge
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 15 wins & 26 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Equal parts hilarious, poignant, and heartbreaking, Project Nim not only tells a compelling story masterfully, but also raises the flag on the darker side of human nature.

Plot: A year in the life of a city grappling with urban violence.
Title: The Interrupters
Writer: Alex Kotlowitz (New York Times magazine article)
Actors: Tio Hardiman, Ameena Matthews, Toya Batey, Cobe Williams
tomatoConsensus: Impeccably crafted and edited, The Interrupters is a tough and honest documentary about street violence that truly has the power to inspire change.

Plot: Set in Middle America, a group of teens receive an online invitation for sex, though they soon encounter fundamentalists with a much more sinister agenda.
Title: Red State
Actors: Michael Angarano, Deborah Aquila, Nicholas Braun, Ronnie Connell
tomatoConsensus: Red State is an audacious and brash affair that ultimately fails to provide competent scares or thrills.

Plot: A documentary on the band Pearl Jam that marks their 20th anniversary in the year 2011.
Title: Pearl Jam Twenty
Actors: Cameron Crowe, Jeff Ament, Matt Cameron, Stone Gossard
tomatoConsensus: Cameron Crowe's fawning documentary is a true boon for Pearl Jam fans, but the band's insistent resistance to fame comes off hollow.

Plot: A comedy centered on the life of Kate Reddy, a finance executive who is the breadwinner for her husband and two kids.
Title: I Don't Know How She Does It
Actors: Sarah Jessica Parker, Pierce Brosnan, Greg Kinnear, Christina Hendricks
tomatoConsensus: A limp comedy with a hopelessly outdated viewpoint on gender, featuring Sarah Jessica Parker in rote Carrie-mode.

Plot: A weekend at a lake house in the Louisiana Gulf turns into a nightmare for seven vacationers as they are subjected to shark attacks.
Title: Shark Night 3D
Actors: Sara Paxton, Dustin Milligan, Chris Carmack, Katharine McPhee
tomatoConsensus: A joyless excursion into the water that doesn't even produce good gore or nudity thanks to the neutered PG-13 rating.

Plot: Healthcare professionals, government officials and everyday people find themselves in the midst of a worldwide epidemic as the CDC works to find a cure.
Title: Contagion
Actors: Gwyneth Paltrow, Tien You Chui, Josie Ho, Daria Strokous
tomatoConsensus: Tense, tightly plotted, and bolstered by a stellar cast, Contagion is an exceptionally smart -- and scary -- disaster movie.

Plot: L.A. screenwriter David Sumner relocates with his wife to her hometown in the deep South. There, while tensions build between them, a brewing conflict with locals becomes a threat to them both.
Title: Straw Dogs
Writer: Rod Lurie (screenplay), David Zelag Goodman (earlier screenplay), Sam Peckinpah (earlier screenplay), Gordon Williams (novel)
Actors: James Marsden, Kate Bosworth, Alexander Skarsgård, James Woods
tomatoConsensus: This remakes streamlines the plot but ultimately makes a fatal mistake: It celebrates violence.

Plot: Oakland A's general manager Billy Beane's successful attempt to assemble a baseball team on a lean budget by employing computer-generated analysis to acquire new players.
Title: Moneyball
Writer: Steven Zaillian (screenplay), Aaron Sorkin (screenplay), Stan Chervin (story), Michael Lewis (book)
Actors: Brad Pitt, Jonah Hill, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Robin Wright
Awards: Nominated for 6 Oscars. Another 29 wins & 74 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Director Bennett Miller, along with Brad Pitt and Jonah Hill, take a niche subject and turn it into a sharp, funny, and touching portrait worthy of baseball lore.

Plot: The story of a terminally ill teenage girl who falls for a boy who likes to attend funerals and their encounters with the ghost of a Japanese kamikaze pilot from WWII.
Title: Restless
Actors: Henry Hopper, Mia Wasikowska, Ryô Kase, Schuyler Fisk
tomatoConsensus: Mia Wasikowska puts in a nuanced performance but nobody else, actors and directors included, are capable of finding a compelling angle beneath the twee veneer.

Plot: In the bleak days of the Cold War, espionage veteran George Smiley is forced from semi-retirement to uncover a Soviet agent within MI6.
Title: Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy
Writer: Bridget O'Connor (screenplay), Peter Straughan (screenplay), John le Carré (novel)
Actors: Mark Strong, John Hurt, Zoltán Mucsi, Péter Kálloy Molnár
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 34 wins & 88 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy is a dense puzzle of anxiety, paranoia, and espionage that director Tomas Alfredson pieces together with utmost skill.

Plot: A look at how the intense relationship between Carl Jung and Sigmund Freud gives birth to psychoanalysis.
Title: A Dangerous Method
Writer: Christopher Hampton (screenplay), Christopher Hampton (play), John Kerr (book)
Actors: Keira Knightley, Viggo Mortensen, Michael Fassbender, Vincent Cassel
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 18 wins & 26 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A provocative historical fiction about the early days of psychoanalysis, A Dangerous Method is buoyed by terrific performances by Michael Fassbender, Keira Knightley, and Viggo Mortensen.

Plot: The youngest son of an alcoholic former boxer returns home, where he's trained by his father for competition in a mixed martial arts tournament - a path that puts the fighter on a collision course with his estranged, older brother.
Title: Warrior
Writer: Gavin O'Connor (screenplay), Anthony Tambakis (screenplay), Cliff Dorfman (screenplay), Gavin O'Connor (story), Cliff Dorfman (story)
Actors: Joel Edgerton, Tom Hardy, Nick Nolte, Jennifer Morrison
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 20 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Warrior relies on many of the clichés that critics of the genre love to mock -- and it transcends them with gripping action, powerful acting, and heart.

Plot: An idealistic staffer for a new presidential candidate gets a crash course on dirty politics during his stint on the campaign trail.
Title: The Ides of March
Writer: George Clooney (screenplay), Grant Heslov (screenplay), Beau Willimon (screenplay), Beau Willimon (play)
Actors: Ryan Gosling, George Clooney, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Paul Giamatti
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 34 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: While not exactly exposing revelatory truths, The Ides of March is supremely well-acted drama that moves at a measured, confident clip.

Plot: Nearly a year after a botched job, a hitman takes a new assignment with the promise of a big payoff for three killings. What starts off as an easy task soon unravels, sending the killer into the heart of darkness.
Title: Kill List
Actors: Neil Maskell, MyAnna Buring, Harry Simpson, Michael Smiley
tomatoConsensus: Kill List is an expertly executed slow-burn crime thriller that thrives on tension before morphing into visceral horror.

Plot: When his mentor is taken captive by a disgraced Arab sheik, a killer-for-hire is forced into action. His mission: kill three members of Britain's elite Special Air Service responsible for the death of his sons.
Title: Killer Elite
Actors: Jason Statham, Clive Owen, Robert De Niro, Dominic Purcell
tomatoConsensus: A rote, utterly disposable Jason Statham vehicle that just happens to have Clive Owen and Robert De Niro in it.

Plot: Two friends spend all their free time building flame-throwers and weapons of mass destruction in hopes that a global apocalypse will occur and clear the runway for their imaginary gang "Mother Medusa".
Title: Bellflower
Actors: Evan Glodell, Jessie Wiseman, Tyler Dawson, Rebekah Brandes
tomatoConsensus: This fevered, stylish vision of the end of the world stitches multiple genres together and marks writer/director/star Evan Glodell as a true talent to watch.

Plot: Inspired by a true story, a comedy centered on a 27-year-old guy who learns of his cancer diagnosis, and his subsequent struggle to beat the disease.
Actors: Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Seth Rogen, Anna Kendrick, Bryce Dallas Howard
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 12 wins & 26 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A good-hearted film about a difficult topic, 50/50 maneuvers between jokes and drama with surprising finesse.

Plot: A silent movie star meets a young dancer, but the arrival of talking pictures sends their careers in opposite directions.
Title: The Artist
Actors: Jean Dujardin, Bérénice Bejo, John Goodman, James Cromwell
tomatoConsensus: A crowd-pleasing tribute to the magic of silent cinema, The Artist is a clever, joyous film with delightful performances and visual style to spare.

Plot: A wealthy Iranian family struggles to contain a teenager's growing sexual rebellion and her brother's dangerous obsession.
Title: Circumstance
Actors: Nikohl Boosheri, Sarah Kazemy, Reza Sixo Safai, Soheil Parsa
tomatoConsensus: A thought-provoking, insightful look into Iranian youth culture.

Plot: Plagued by a series of apocalyptic visions, a young husband and father questions whether to shelter his family from a coming storm, or from himself.
Title: Take Shelter
Actors: Michael Shannon, Jessica Chastain, Tova Stewart, Shea Whigham
tomatoConsensus: Michael Shannon gives a powerhouse performance and the purposefully subtle filmmaking creates a perfect blend of drama, terror, and dread.

Plot: Tale of a father who struggles to bond with his estranged son Gabriel, after Gabriel suffers from a brain tumor that prevents him from forming new memories. With Gabriel unable to shed the ...
Title: The Music Never Stopped
Writer: Gwyn Lurie (screenplay), Gary Marks (screenplay), Oliver Sacks (essay "The Last Hippie")
Actors: J.K. Simmons, Cara Seymour, Lou Taylor Pucci, Scott Adsit
tomatoConsensus: An involving, if sentimental and predictable family drama elevated by J.K. Simmons' sympathetic lead performance.

Plot: In the near future, robot boxing is a top sport. A struggling promoter feels he's found a champion in a discarded robot.
Title: Real Steel
Writer: John Gatins (screenplay), Dan Gilroy (story), Jeremy Leven (story), Richard Matheson (short story "Steel")
Actors: Hugh Jackman, Dakota Goyo, Evangeline Lilly, Anthony Mackie
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Silly premise notwithstanding, this is a well-made Hollywood movie: Thrilling and exciting action with just enough characterization.

Plot: City teenager Ren MacCormack moves to a small town where rock music and dancing have been banned, and his rebellious spirit shakes up the populace.
Title: Footloose
Writer: Dean Pitchford (screenplay), Craig Brewer (screenplay), Dean Pitchford (story)
Actors: Kenny Wormald, Julianne Hough, Dennis Quaid, Andie MacDowell
tomatoConsensus: While it hews closely to the 1984 original, Craig Brewer infuses his Footloose remake with toe-tapping energy and manages to keep the story fresh for a new generation.

Plot: At an Antarctica research site, the discovery of an alien craft leads to a confrontation between graduate student Kate Lloyd and scientist Dr. Sander Halvorson.
Title: The Thing
Writer: Eric Heisserer, John W. Campbell Jr. (short story "Who Goes There?")
Actors: Mary Elizabeth Winstead, Joel Edgerton, Ulrich Thomsen, Eric Christian Olsen
tomatoConsensus: It serves the bare serviceable minimum for a horror flick, but The Thing is all boo-scares and a slave to the far superior John Carpenter version.

Plot: Joseph, a man plagued by violence and a rage that is driving him to self-destruction, earns a chance of redemption that appears in the form of Hannah, a Christian charity shop worker.
Title: Tyrannosaur
Actors: Peter Mullan, Archie Lal, Jag Sanghera, Mike Fearnley
Awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 20 wins & 22 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Tyrannosaur is a brutal, frank, and ultimately rewarding story of violent men seeking far-off redemption.

Plot: Haunted by painful memories and increasing paranoia, a damaged woman struggles to re-assimilate with her family after fleeing an abusive cult.
Title: Martha Marcy May Marlene
Actors: Elizabeth Olsen, Christopher Abbott, Brady Corbet, Hugh Dancy
tomatoConsensus: Led by a mesmerizing debut performance from Elizabeth Olsen, Martha Marcy May Marlene is a distinctive, haunting psychological drama.

Plot: Kevin's mother struggles to love her strange child, despite the increasingly vicious things he says and does as he grows up. But Kevin is just getting started, and his final act will be beyond anything anyone imagined.
Title: We Need to Talk About Kevin
Writer: Lynne Ramsay (screenplay), Rory Stewart Kinnear (screenplay), Lionel Shriver (novel)
Actors: Tilda Swinton, John C. Reilly, Ezra Miller, Jasper Newell
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 27 wins & 61 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: We Need to Talk About Kevin is a masterful blend of drama and horror, with fantastic performances across the board (Tilda Swinton especially, delivering one of her very best).

Plot: The hot-headed young D'Artagnan along with three former legendary but now down on their luck Musketeers must unite and defeat a beautiful double agent and her villainous employer from seizing the French throne and engulfing Europe in war.
Title: The Three Musketeers
Writer: Alex Litvak (screenplay), Andrew Davies (screenplay), Alexandre Dumas père (novel)
Actors: Matthew Macfadyen, Milla Jovovich, Helen George, Christian Oliver
tomatoConsensus: It plays admirably fast and loose with Alexandre Dumas' classic tale, but in every other respect, The Three Musketeers offers nothing to recommend -- or to set it apart from the many other film adaptations.

Plot: In a future where people stop aging at 25, but are engineered to live only one more year, having the means to buy your way out of the situation is a shot at immortal youth. Here, Will Salas finds himself accused of murder and on the run with a hostage - a connection that becomes an important part of the way against the system.
Title: In Time
Actors: Justin Timberlake, Olivia Wilde, Shyloh Oostwald, Johnny Galecki
tomatoConsensus: In Time's intriguing premise and appealing cast are easily overpowered by the blunt, heavy-handed storytelling.

Plot: A young woman witnesses a bus accident, and is caught up in the aftermath, where the question of whether or not it was intentional affects many people's lives.
Title: Margaret
Actors: Anna Paquin, J. Smith-Cameron, Mark Ruffalo, Jeannie Berlin
tomatoConsensus: A surfeit of ideas contributes to Margaret's excessive run time, but Anna Paquin does a admirable job of guiding viewers through emotional hell.

Plot: Two pairs of parents hold a cordial meeting after their sons are involved in a fight, though as their time together progresses, increasingly childish behavior throws the discussion into chaos.
Title: Carnage
Writer: Yasmina Reza (play), Yasmina Reza (screenplay), Roman Polanski (screenplay), Michael Katims (translation)
Actors: Jodie Foster, Kate Winslet, Christoph Waltz, John C. Reilly
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 7 wins & 19 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It isn't as compelling on the screen as it was on the stage, but Carnage makes up for its flaws with Polanski's smooth direction and assured performances from Winslet and Foster.

Plot: Follows the key people at an investment bank, over a 24-hour period, during the early stages of the 2008 financial crisis.
Title: Margin Call
Actors: Kevin Spacey, Paul Bettany, Jeremy Irons, Zachary Quinto
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 23 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Smart, tightly wound, and solidly acted, Margin Call turns the convoluted financial meltdown of '08 into gripping, thought-provoking drama.

Title: Paranormal Activity 3
Actors: Lauren Bittner, Christopher Nicholas Smith, Chloe Csengery, Jessica Tyler Brown
tomatoConsensus: While the jolts and thrills are undeniably subject to the diminishing returns that plague most horror sequels, Paranormal Activity 3 is a surprisingly spine-tingling treat.

Plot: A David and Goliath law drama about a drug-addicted lawyer who takes on a health supply corporation while battling his own personal demons.
Title: Puncture
Writer: Paul Danziger (story), Chris Lopata, Ela Thier (story)
Actors: Chris Evans, Mark Kassen, Marshall Bell, Brett Cullen
tomatoConsensus: There's a compelling story at the heart of Puncture but viewers will have to pierce through the formulaic storytelling to find it.

Plot: Johnny English goes up against international assassins hunting down the Chinese premier.
Language: English, Mandarin, Swiss German, Cantonese, Russian
Title: Johnny English Reborn
Writer: Hamish McColl (screenplay), William Davies (story), Neal Purvis (characters), Robert Wade (characters)
Actors: Roger Barclay, Eric Carte, Rowan Atkinson, Togo Igawa
tomatoConsensus: Arguably a marginal improvement on its mostly-forgotten predecessor, Johnny English Reborn nonetheless remains mired in broad, tired spy spoofing that wastes Rowan Atkinson's once considerable comedic talent.

Plot: A thriller centered on a young man who sets out to uncover the truth about his life after finding his baby photo on a missing persons website.
Title: Abduction
Actors: Jake Andolina, Oriah Acima Andrews, Ken Arnold, Maria Bello
tomatoConsensus: A soulless and incompetent action/thriller not even a veteran lead actor could save, let alone Taylor Lautner.

Plot: A woman looks back at the past nineteen men she's had relationships with in her life and wonders if one of them might be her one true love.
Title: What's Your Number?
Writer: Gabrielle Allan (screenplay), Jennifer Crittenden (screenplay), Karyn Bosnak (novel)
Actors: Anna Faris, Chris Evans, Ari Graynor, Blythe Danner
tomatoConsensus: The comic timing of Anna Faris is sharp as always, but it's wasted away in this predictable, boilerplate comedy.

Plot: Soon after moving into their seemingly idyllic new home, a family learns of a brutal crime committed against former residents of the dwelling.
Title: Dream House
Actors: Daniel Craig, Naomi Watts, Rachel Weisz, Elias Koteas
tomatoConsensus: Dream House is punishingly slow, stuffy, and way too obvious to be scary.

Plot: Sam Childers is a former drug-dealing biker tough guy who found God and became a crusader for hundreds of Sudanese children who've been forced to become soldiers.
Title: Machine Gun Preacher
Actors: Gerard Butler, Michelle Monaghan, Kathy Baker, Michael Shannon
tomatoConsensus: There's a complex man at the center of Machine Gun Preacher but the movie is too shapeless and emotionally vacant to bring his story to life.

Plot: The theory that it was in fact Edward De Vere, Earl of Oxford, who penned Shakespeare's plays. Set against the backdrop of the succession of Queen Elizabeth I and the Essex rebellion against her.
Title: Anonymous
Actors: Rhys Ifans, Vanessa Redgrave, Sebastian Armesto, Rafe Spall
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 8 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Roland Emmerich delivers his trademark visual and emotional bombast, but the more Anonymous stops and tries to convince the audience of its half-baked theory, the less convincing it becomes.

Plot: An outlaw cat, his childhood egg-friend and a seductive thief kitty set out in search for the eggs of the fabled Golden Goose to clear his name, restore his lost honor and regain the trust of his mother and town.
Title: Puss in Boots
Writer: Charles Perrault (character), Tom Wheeler (screenplay), Brian Lynch (story), William Davies (story), Tom Wheeler (story)
Actors: Antonio Banderas, Salma Hayek, Zach Galifianakis, Billy Bob Thornton
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 42 nominations.
