tomatoConsensus: It isn't deep or groundbreaking, but what it lacks in profundity, Puss in Boots more than makes up for with an abundance of wit, visual sparkle, and effervescent charm.

Title: Tower Heist
Writer: Adam Cooper (story), Bill Collage (story), Ted Griffin (story), Ted Griffin (screenplay), Jeff Nathanson (screenplay)
Actors: Ben Stiller, Eddie Murphy, Casey Affleck, Alan Alda
tomatoConsensus: Tower Heist is a true Brett Ratner joint: little brains to this caper, but it's fun fluff, exciting to watch, and showcases a welcome return to form for Eddie Murphy.

Plot: J. Edgar Hoover, powerful head of the F.B.I. for nearly 50 years, looks back on his professional and personal life.
Title: J. Edgar
Actors: Leonardo DiCaprio, Josh Hamilton, Geoff Pierson, Cheryl Lawson
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 16 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Leonardo DiCaprio gives a predictably powerhouse performance, but J. Edgar stumbles in all other departments with cheesy makeup, poor lighting, confusing narrative, and humdrum storytelling.

Plot: Intrepid reporter Tintin and Captain Haddock set off on a treasure hunt for a sunken ship commanded by Haddock's ancestor.
Title: The Adventures of Tintin
Writer: Hergé (comic book series "The Adventures of Tintin"), Steven Moffat (screenplay), Edgar Wright (screenplay), Joe Cornish (screenplay)
Actors: Jamie Bell, Andy Serkis, Daniel Craig, Nick Frost
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 22 wins & 59 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Drawing deep from the classic Raiders of the Lost Ark playbook, Steven Spielberg has crafted another spirited, thrilling adventure in the form of Tintin.

Plot: A young cop is assigned to a precinct in the working class neighborhood where he grew up, and an old secret threatens to destroy his life and his family.
Title: The Son of No One
Actors: Al Pacino, Channing Tatum, James Ransone, Ray Liotta
tomatoConsensus: Needless stylistic flourishes and wholly illogical storytelling make The Son of No One a grisly, repugnant journey.

Plot: Set in 1930s Paris, an orphan who lives in the walls of a train station is wrapped up in a mystery involving his late father and an automaton.
Title: Hugo
Actors: Ben Kingsley, Sacha Baron Cohen, Asa Butterfield, Chloë Grace Moretz
tomatoConsensus: Hugo is an extravagant, elegant fantasy with an innocence lacking in many modern kids' movies, and one that emanates an unabashed love for the magic of cinema.

Plot: A chronicle of one woman's lifelong struggle with her faith.
Title: Higher Ground
Writer: Carolyn S. Briggs (screenplay), Tim Metcalfe (screenplay), Carolyn S. Briggs (memoir "This Dark World")
Actors: Joshua Leonard, Norbert Leo Butz, Michael Chernus, Vera Farmiga
tomatoConsensus: With Higher Ground, star and debuting director Vera Farmiga takes viewers on a challenging spiritual journey whose missteps are easily overcome by its many rich rewards.

Plot: As they're held for ransom, a husband and wife's predicament grows more dire amid the discovery of betrayal and deception.
Title: Trespass
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Nicole Kidman, Ben Mendelsohn, Liana Liberato
tomatoConsensus: Another claustrophobic thriller that Joel Schumacher can churn out in his sleep, Trespass is nasty and aggressive, more unpleasant than entertaining.

Plot: Theseus is a mortal man chosen by Zeus to lead the fight against the ruthless King Hyperion, who is on a rampage across Greece to obtain a weapon that can destroy humanity.
Title: Immortals
Actors: Henry Cavill, Mickey Rourke, Stephen Dorff, Freida Pinto
tomatoConsensus: The melding of real sets, CG work, and Tarsem's signature style produces fireworks, though the same can't be said for Immortals slack, boring storytelling.

Plot: Family guy Jack Sadelstein prepares for the annual event he dreads: the Thanksgiving visit of his twin sister, the needy and passive-aggressive Jill, who then refuses to leave.
Title: Jack and Jill
Writer: Steve Koren (screenplay), Adam Sandler (screenplay), Ben Zook (story)
Actors: Adam Sandler, Al Pacino, Katie Holmes, Elodie Tougne
tomatoConsensus: Although it features an inexplicably committed performance from Al Pacino, Jack and Jill is impossible to recommend on any level whatsoever.

Plot: The wife of a British Judge is caught in a self-destructive love affair with a Royal Air Force pilot.
Title: The Deep Blue Sea
Actors: Ann Mitchell, Jolyon Coy, Karl Johnson, Rachel Weisz
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 12 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Featuring an outstanding performance by Rachel Weisz, The Deep Blue Sea is a visually stunning, melancholy tale of subsumed passion.

Plot: Conversations with death row inmate Michael Perry and those affected by his crime serve as an examination of why people - and the state - kill.
Title: Into the Abyss
Actors: Werner Herzog, Richard Lopez, Michael Perry, Damon Hall
tomatoConsensus: Another probing, insightful look at an interesting subject, Werner Herzog explores the American prison system with passion and not politics.

Plot: A land baron tries to reconnect with his two daughters after his wife is seriously injured in a boating accident.
Title: The Descendants
Writer: Alexander Payne (screenplay), Nat Faxon (screenplay), Jim Rash (screenplay), Kaui Hart Hemmings (novel)
Actors: George Clooney, Shailene Woodley, Amara Miller, Nick Krause
tomatoConsensus: Funny, moving, and beautifully acted, The Descendants captures the unpredictable messiness of life with eloquence and uncommon grace.

Plot: A British college student falls for an American student, only to be separated from him when she's banned from the U.S. after overstaying her visa.
Title: Like Crazy
Actors: Anton Yelchin, Felicity Jones, Jennifer Lawrence, Charlie Bewley
tomatoConsensus: It has the schmaltzy trappings of my romantic films, but Like Crazy allows its characters to express themselves beyond dialogue, crafting a true, intimate study.

Plot: A Muppet fanatic with some help from his two human compatriots must regroup the Muppet gang to stop an avaricious oil mogul from taking down one of their precious life-longing treasures.
Title: The Muppets
Writer: Jason Segel, Nicholas Stoller, Jim Henson (based on)
Actors: Jason Segel, Amy Adams, Chris Cooper, Rashida Jones
tomatoConsensus: Clever, charming, and heartfelt, The Muppets is a welcome big screen return for Jim Henson's lovable creations that will both win new fans and delight longtime devotees.

Plot: The Quileutes close in on expecting parents Edward and Bella, whose unborn child poses a threat to the Wolf Pack and the towns people of Forks.
Title: The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn - Part 1
Actors: Taylor Lautner, Gil Birmingham, Billy Burke, Sarah Clarke
tomatoConsensus: Slow, joyless, and loaded with unintentionally humorous moments, Breaking Dawn Part 1 may satisfy the Twilight faithful, but it's strictly for fans of the franchise.

Plot: Young Albert enlists to serve in World War I after his beloved horse is sold to the cavalry. Albert's hopeful journey takes him out of England and to the front lines as the war rages on.
Title: War Horse
Writer: Lee Hall (screenplay), Richard Curtis (screenplay), Michael Morpurgo (novel), Nick Stafford (stage play)
Actors: Jeremy Irvine, Peter Mullan, Emily Watson, Niels Arestrup
Awards: Nominated for 6 Oscars. Another 16 wins & 70 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Technically superb, proudly sentimental, and unabashedly old-fashioned, War Horse is an emotional drama that tugs the heartstrings with Spielberg's customary flair.

Plot: American journalist Paul Kemp takes on a freelance job in Puerto Rico for a local newspaper during the 1960s and struggles to find a balance between island culture and the expatriates who live there.
Title: The Rum Diary
Actors: Johnny Depp, Aaron Eckhart, Michael Rispoli, Amber Heard
tomatoConsensus: It's colorful and amiable enough, and Depp's heart is clearly in the right place, but The Rum Diary fails to add sufficient focus to its rambling source material.

Plot: Colin Clark, an employee of Sir Laurence Olivier's, documents the tense interaction between Olivier and Marilyn Monroe during the production of The Prince and the Showgirl (1957).
Title: My Week with Marilyn
Actors: Michelle Williams, Eddie Redmayne, Julia Ormond, Kenneth Branagh
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 19 wins & 59 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Michelle Williams shines in My Week with Marilyn, capturing the magnetism and vulnerability of Marilyn Monroe.

Plot: A college student on suspension is coaxed into babysitting the kids next door, though he is fully unprepared for the wild night ahead of him.
Title: The Sitter
Actors: Jonah Hill, Max Records, Ari Graynor, J.B. Smoove
tomatoConsensus: With its recycled plot, misguided gags, and formula performance from Jonah Hill, The Sitter adds up to another disappointing entry from director David Gordon Green.

Plot: A nine-year-old amateur inventor, Francophile, and pacifist searches New York City for the lock that matches a mysterious key left behind by his father, who died in the World Trade Center on September 11, 2001.
Title: Extremely Loud & Incredibly Close
Actors: Tom Hanks, Thomas Horn, Sandra Bullock, Zoe Caldwell
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 8 wins & 24 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Extremely Loud & Incredibly Close has a story worth telling, but it deserves better than the treacly and pretentious treatment director Stephen Daldry gives it.

Plot: Set in 1999 Los Angeles, veteran police officer Dave Brown, the last of the renegade cops, works to take care of his family, and struggles for his own survival.
Title: Rampart
Actors: Woody Harrelson, Jon Bernthal, Stella Schnabel, Jon Foster
tomatoConsensus: Rampart sends viewers plummeting into a nihilistic hell of its protagonist's creation, yet Woody Harrelson's performance in the central role is too magnetic to dismiss.

Plot: Mumble's son, Erik, is struggling to realize his talents in the Emperor Penguin world. Meanwhile, Mumble and his family and friends discover a new threat their home -- one that will take everyone working together to save them.
Title: Happy Feet 2
Writer: George Miller, Gary Eck, Warren Coleman, Paul Livingston
Director: George Miller, Gary Eck, David Peers
Actors: Carlos Alazraqui, Lombardo Boyar, Jeffrey Garcia, Johnny A. Sanchez
tomatoConsensus: The animation is as eye-popping as ever, but Happy Feet Two's narrative is too noisily incoherent to recapture the Oscar-winning charm of its predecessor.

Plot: Santa's clumsy son Arthur gets put on a mission with St. Nick's father to give out a present they misplaced to a young girl in less than 2 hours.
Title: Arthur Christmas
Actors: James McAvoy, Hugh Laurie, Bill Nighy, Jim Broadbent
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 21 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Aardman Animations broadens their humor a bit for Arthur Christmas, a clever and earnest holiday film with surprising emotional strength.

Plot: Sherlock Holmes and his sidekick Dr. Watson join forces to outwit and bring down their fiercest adversary, Professor Moriarty.
Title: Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows
Writer: Michele Mulroney, Kieran Mulroney, Arthur Conan Doyle (characters: Sherlock Holmes,  Dr. Watson)
Actors: Robert Downey Jr., Jude Law, Noomi Rapace, Rachel McAdams
tomatoConsensus: Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows is a good yarn thanks to its well-matched leading men but overall stumbles duplicating the well-oiled thrills of the original.

Plot: Soon after her divorce, a fiction writer returns to her home in small-town Minnesota, looking to rekindle a romance with her ex-boyfriend, who is now happily married and has a newborn daughter.
Title: Young Adult
Actors: Charlize Theron, Patton Oswalt, Patrick Wilson, Elizabeth Reaser
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 29 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despite its somewhat dour approach, Young Adult is a funny and ultimately powerful no-holds-barred examination of prolonged adolescence, thanks largely to a convincing performance by Charlize Theron.

Plot: The lives of several couples and singles in New York intertwine over the course of New Year's Eve.
Title: New Year's Eve
Actors: Michelle Pfeiffer, Zac Efron, Charlotte Marshall-Fricker, Fiona Choi
tomatoConsensus: Shallow, sappy, and dull, New Year's Eve assembles a star-studded cast for no discernible purpose.

Title: Mission: Impossible - Ghost Protocol
Country: USA, United Arab Emirates, Czech Republic
Writer: Bruce Geller (television series "Mission: Impossible"), Josh Appelbaum, André Nemec
Actors: Tom Cruise, Paula Patton, Simon Pegg, Jeremy Renner
tomatoConsensus: Stylish, fast-paced, and loaded with gripping set pieces, the fourth Mission: Impossible is big-budget popcorn entertainment that really works.

Plot: Set in Southern California, a father moves his young family to the countryside to renovate and re-open a struggling zoo.
Title: We Bought a Zoo
Writer: Aline Brosh McKenna (screenplay), Cameron Crowe (screenplay), Benjamin Mee (book)
Actors: Matt Damon, Scarlett Johansson, Thomas Haden Church, Colin Ford
tomatoConsensus: We Bought a Zoo is a transparently cloying effort by director Cameron Crowe, but Matt Damon makes for a sympathetic central character.

Plot: Journalist Mikael Blomkvist is aided in his search for a woman who has been missing for forty years by Lisbeth Salander, a young computer hacker.
Title: The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo
Actors: Daniel Craig, Rooney Mara, Christopher Plummer, Stellan Skarsgård
tomatoConsensus: Brutal yet captivating, The Girl With the Dragon Tattoo is the result of David Fincher working at his lurid best with total role commitment from star Rooney Mara.

Plot: Playing around while aboard a cruise ship, the Chipmunks and Chipettes accidentally go overboard and end up marooned in a tropical paradise. They discover their new turf is not as deserted as it seems.
Title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked
Writer: Jonathan Aibel, Glenn Berger, Ross Bagdasarian (characters), Janice Karman (characters)
Actors: Jason Lee, David Cross, Jenny Slate, Justin Long
tomatoConsensus: Lazy, rote, and grating, Chipwrecked is lowest-common-denominator family entertainment that's strictly for the very, very, very young at heart.

Plot: Two best friends decide to have a child together while keeping their relationship platonic, so they can avoid the toll kids can take on romantic relationships.
Title: Friends with Kids
Actors: Adam Scott, Jennifer Westfeldt, Maya Rudolph, Chris O'Dowd
tomatoConsensus: Sharp, shrewd, and funny, Friends with Kids features excellent performances that help smooth over some of the story's more conventional elements.

Plot: Two children living in different countries are visited nightly by a faceless being who wants to take possession of them.
Title: Intruders
Actors: Clive Owen, Carice van Houten, Daniel Brühl, Pilar López de Ayala
tomatoConsensus: Intruders has a fantastic first act but then settles into a bland plot and scare tactics that aren't all too scary.

Plot: A Brooklyn teenager juggles conflicting identities and risks friendship, heartbreak, and family in a desperate search for sexual expression.
Title: Pariah
Actors: Adepero Oduye, Pernell Walker, Aasha Davis, Charles Parnell
tomatoConsensus: Pulsing with authenticity and led by a stirring lead performance from Adepero Oduye, Pariah is a powerful coming out/coming-of-age film that signals the arrival of a fresh new talent in writer/director Dee Rees.

Title: Dolphin Tale
Actors: Harry Connick Jr., Ashley Judd, Nathan Gamble, Kris Kristofferson
tomatoConsensus: Wisely dialing down the schmaltz, Dolphin Tale is earnest, sweet, and well-told, a rare family film that both kids and parents can enjoy.

Plot: An elderly Margaret Thatcher talks to the imagined presence of her recently deceased husband as she struggles to come to terms with his death while scenes from her past life, from girlhood to British prime minister, intervene.
Title: The Iron Lady
Actors: Meryl Streep, Jim Broadbent, Susan Brown, Alice da Cunha
tomatoConsensus: Meryl Streep's performance as The Iron Lady is reliably perfect, but it's mired in bland, self-important storytelling.

Plot: After their plane crashes in Alaska, six oil workers are led by a skilled huntsman to survival, but a pack of merciless wolves haunts their every step.
Title: The Grey
Writer: Joe Carnahan (screenplay), Ian Mackenzie Jeffers (screenplay), Ian Mackenzie Jeffers (short story "Ghost Walker")
Actors: Liam Neeson, Frank Grillo, Dermot Mulroney, Dallas Roberts
tomatoConsensus: The Grey is an exciting tale of survival, populated with fleshed-out characters and a surprising philosophical agenda.

Plot: A black ops super soldier seeks payback after she is betrayed and set up during a mission.
Title: Haywire
Actors: Gina Carano, Michael Angarano, Channing Tatum, Debby Lynn Ross
tomatoConsensus: MMA star and first-time actress Gina Carano displays ample action-movie chops in Haywire, a fast-paced thriller with a top-notch cast and outstanding direction from Steven Soderbergh.

Plot: Inspired by the fictional Dr. Heiter, disturbed loner Martin dreams of creating a 12-person centipede and sets out to realize his sick fantasy.
Title: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence)
Actors: Laurence R. Harvey, Ashlynn Yennie, Maddi Black, Kandace Caine
tomatoConsensus: The Human Centipede II (Full Sequence) attempts to weave in social commentary but as the movie wears on, it loses its ability to repulse and shock and ends up obnoxious and annoying.

Plot: An engaged couple's backpacking trip in the Caucasus Mountains is derailed by a single misstep that threatens to undo everything the pair believed about each other and about themselves.
Title: The Loneliest Planet
Writer: Tom Bissell (short story "Expensive Trips Nowhere" from the collection 'God Lives In St. Petersburg'), Mikhail Lermontov (excerpt from 'A Hero Of Our Time'), Julia Loktev
Actors: Hani Furstenberg, Gael García Bernal, Bidzina Gujabidze, Tali Pitakhelauri
tomatoConsensus: The source material that inspired The Loneliest Planet may be brief, but this adaptation of a Tom Bissell short story compensates with studious, finely detailed filmmaking, haunting visuals, and thought-provoking subtext.

Plot: Decades-old found footage from NASA's abandoned Apollo 18 mission, where two American astronauts were sent on a secret expedition, reveals the reason the U.S. has never returned to the moon.
Title: Apollo 18
Actors: Warren Christie, Lloyd Owen, Ryan Robbins, Michael Kopsa
tomatoConsensus: A boring, suspense-free Paranormal Activity rip-off that feels long even at just 90 minutes.

Plot: After his wife is assaulted, a husband enlists the services of a vigilante group to help him settle the score. Then he discovers they want a 'favor' from him in return.
Title: Seeking Justice
Writer: Todd Hickey (story), Robert Tannen (screenplay), Robert Tannen (story)
Actors: Nicolas Cage, January Jones, Guy Pearce, Harold Perrineau
tomatoConsensus: Seeking Justice is nothing more than a typical potboiler with another phoned-in performance by Nicolas Cage.

Plot: After he becomes a quadriplegic from a paragliding accident, an aristocrat hires a young man from the projects to be his caregiver.
Title: The Intouchables
Actors: François Cluzet, Omar Sy, Anne Le Ny, Audrey Fleurot
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 33 wins & 39 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It handles its potentially prickly subject matter with kid gloves, but Intouchables gets by thanks to its strong cast and some remarkably sensitive direction.

Plot: During the final days at the Yankee Pedlar Inn, two employees determined to reveal the hotel's haunted past begin to experience disturbing events as old guests check in for a stay.
Title: The Innkeepers
Actors: Sara Paxton, Pat Healy, Alison Bartlett, Jake Ryan
tomatoConsensus: It doesn't break any rules of the genre, but The Innkeepers serves as additional proof that Ti West is a young director that discriminating horror fans can trust.

Plot: George, a lonely and fatalistic teen who has made it all the way to his senior year without ever having done a real day of work, is befriended by Sally, a popular but complicated girl who recognizes in him a kindred spirit.
Title: The Art of Getting By
Actors: Freddie Highmore, Emma Roberts, Sasha Spielberg, Marcus Carl Franklin
tomatoConsensus: A sitcom-level twee mess that bakes in the typical manic pixie dream girl and boring, withdrawn boy hero.

Plot: A kid from the Midwest moves out to Hollywood in order to follow in his parents footsteps -- and become a porn star.
Title: Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star
Writer: Adam Sandler, Allen Covert, Nick Swardson
Actors: Nick Swardson, Christina Ricci, Don Johnson, Stephen Dorff
tomatoConsensus: A severely misguided and inept comedy incapable of even telling its single joke properly.

Plot: At a Montréal public grade school, an Algerian immigrant is hired to replace a popular teacher who committed suicide in her classroom. While helping his students deal with their grief, his own recent loss is revealed.
Title: Monsieur Lazhar
Writer: Philippe Falardeau (screenplay), Evelyne de la Chenelière (play)
Actors: Mohamed Fellag, Sophie Nélisse, Émilien Néron, Marie-Ève Beauregard
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 30 wins & 12 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Monsieur Lahzar is a tender and thoughtful portrait of a man with hidden grief and also a compelling exploration of the teacher-student dynamic.

Plot: An epic 12-year journey into the brutal and secretive world of Irish Traveler bare-knuckle fighting. This film follows a history of violent feuding between rival clans.
Title: Knuckle
Actors: James Quinn McDonagh, Michael Quinn McDonagh, Paddy Quinn McDonagh, Ian Palmer
tomatoConsensus: A gritty documentary that captures the brutality and banality of bare-knuckle fights among Irish Travellers.

Plot: Martin, a mercenary, is sent from Europe by a mysterious biotech company to the Tasmanian wilderness on a hunt for the last Tasmanian tiger.
Title: The Hunter
Writer: Alice Addison (screenplay), Wain Fimeri (original adaptation), Daniel Nettheim (original adaptation), Julia Leigh (based on the novel by)
Actors: Willem Dafoe, Frances O'Connor, Sam Neill, Morgana Davies
tomatoConsensus: The Hunter occasionally suffers from predictability, but Willem Dafoe gives a terrific performance as an obsessive hunter on the trail of a mysterious beast.

Plot: As Johnny Blaze hides out in Eastern Europe, he is called upon to stop the devil, who is trying to take human form.
Title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
Writer: Scott M. Gimple (screenplay), Seth Hoffman (screenplay), David S. Goyer (screenplay), David S. Goyer (story)
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Violante Placido, Ciarán Hinds, Idris Elba
tomatoConsensus: With a weak script, uneven CG work, and a Nic Cage performance so predictably loony it's no longer amusing, Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance aims to be trashy fun but ends up as plain trash.

Plot: When a tragedy strikes close to home, four police officers struggle with their faith and their roles as husbands and fathers; together they make a decision that will change all of their lives.
Title: Courageous
Actors: Ken Bevel, Alex Kendrick, Kevin Downes, Renee Jewell
tomatoConsensus: While the filmmaking is fairly competent, Courageous is overall worthless to anybody who doesn't subscribe to its dogmatic agenda.

Plot: Two bird enthusiasts try to defeat the cocky, cutthroat world record holder in a year-long bird-spotting competition.
Title: The Big Year
Actors: John Cleese, Jack Black, Zahf Paroo, Stacey Scowley
tomatoConsensus: Though made with care and affection for its characters, The Big Year plods along, rarely reaching any comedic heights.

Plot: Chronicles three underprivileged students from inner-city Memphis and their volunteer coach who tries to help them beat the odds on and off the field.
Title: Undefeated
Actors: Montrail 'Money' Brown, O.C. Brown, Bill Courtney, Chavis Daniels
tomatoConsensus: It covers familiar sports documentary territory, but Undefeated proves there are still powerful stories to be told on the high school gridiron.

Plot: In 1921, England is overwhelmed by the loss and grief of World War I. Hoax exposer Florence Cathcart visits a boarding school to explain sightings of a child ghost. Everything she believes unravels as the 'missing' begin to show themselves.
Title: The Awakening
Actors: Rebecca Hall, Dominic West, Imelda Staunton, Isaac Hempstead Wright
tomatoConsensus: The Awakening never quite quickens the pulse the way it should, yet it remains a well-acted and handsomely assembled example of an old-fashioned supernatural thriller.

Plot: Dispatched from his basement room on an errand for his widowed mother, slacker Jeff might discover his destiny (finally) when he spends the day with his unhappily married brother as he tracks his possibly adulterous wife.
Title: Jeff, Who Lives at Home
Actors: Jason Segel, Ed Helms, Susan Sarandon, Judy Greer
tomatoConsensus: Sweet, funny, and flawed, Jeff, Who Lives at Home finds the Duplass brothers moving into the mainstream with their signature quirky charm intact.

Plot: A trio of girls set out to change the male-dominated environment of the Seven Oaks college campus, and to rescue their fellow students from depression, grunge and low standards of every kind.
Title: Damsels in Distress
Actors: Greta Gerwig, Carrie MacLemore, Megalyn Echikunwoke, Analeigh Tipton
tomatoConsensus: Damsels in Distress can sometimes feel mannered and outlandish, but it's redeemed by director Whit Stillman's oddball cleverness and Greta Gerwig's dryly funny performance.

Plot: A fisheries expert is approached by a consultant to help realize a sheik's vision of bringing the sport of fly-fishing to the desert and embarks on an upstream journey of faith and fish to prove the impossible possible.
Title: Salmon Fishing in the Yemen
Actors: Amr Waked, Emily Blunt, Catherine Steadman, Tom Mison
Awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 3 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Quirky and a little reserved, Salmon Fishing in the Yemen is nonetheless a charming little romantic drama sold by some strong central performances.

Plot: British retirees travel to India to take up residence in what they believe is a newly restored hotel. Less luxurious than advertised, the Marigold Hotel nevertheless slowly begins to charm in unexpected ways.
Title: The Best Exotic Marigold Hotel
Actors: Judi Dench, Tom Wilkinson, Patrick Pearson, Hugh Dickson
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 4 wins & 19 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Best Exotic Marigold Hotel isn't groundbreaking storytelling, but it's a sweet story about the senior set featuring a top-notch cast of veteran actors.

Plot: A documentary on peer-to-peer bullying in schools across America.
Title: Bully
Actors: Ja'Meya Jackson, Kelby Johnson, Lona Johnson, Bob Johnson
tomatoConsensus: Hard-hitting and gracefully filmed, Bully powerfully delivers an essential message to an audience that may not be able to see it.

Plot: The truth of how Mortimer Granville devised the invention of the first vibrator in the name of medical science.
Title: Hysteria
Writer: Stephen Dyer (story), Jonah Lisa Dyer (story), Stephen Dyer (screenplay), Jonah Lisa Dyer (screenplay), Howard Gensler (original story)
Actors: Hugh Dancy, Maggie Gyllenhaal, Jonathan Pryce, Felicity Jones
tomatoConsensus: Hysteria has an amusing subject but its winking, vaguely sarcastic tone doesn't do the movie any favors.

Plot: Two very different families converge on Martha's Vineyard one weekend for a wedding.
Title: Jumping the Broom
Writer: Elizabeth Hunter (screenplay), Arlene Gibbs (screenplay), Elizabeth Hunter (story)
Actors: Angela Bassett, Paula Patton, Laz Alonso, Loretta Devine
tomatoConsensus: Its heart is in the right place -- and so is its appealing cast -- but Jumping the Broom is ultimately too cliched and thinly written to recommend.

Plot: After bringing democracy to his country, President Mohamed Nasheed of the Maldives, the lowest-lying country in the world, takes up the fight to keep his homeland from disappearing under the sea.
Title: The Island President
Actors: Mohamed Nasheed
tomatoConsensus: An eye-opening and appealing documentary about an earnest politician up against the closed door drama of climate change.

Plot: Since his beloved violin was broken, Nasser Ali Khan, one of the most renowned musicians of his day, has lost all taste for life. Finding no instrument worthy of replacing it, he decides to confine himself to bed to await death.
Title: Chicken with Plums
Writer: Marjane Satrapi, Vincent Paronnaud, Marjane Satrapi (comic book)
Actors: Mathieu Amalric, Edouard Baer, Maria de Medeiros, Golshifteh Farahani
tomatoConsensus: Whimsical and melancholy, Chicken with Plums is visually striking and dreamily compelling despite its occasional narrative missteps.

Title: Bernie
Writer: Skip Hollandsworth (based on the article in Texas Monthly by), Richard Linklater (screenplay), Skip Hollandsworth (screenplay)
Actors: Jack Black, Shirley MacLaine, Matthew McConaughey, Brady Coleman
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 10 wins & 18 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Richard Linklater's Bernie is a gently told and unexpectedly amusing true-crime comedy that benefits from an impressive performance by Jack Black.

Plot: A happily married woman falls for the artist who lives across the street.
Title: Take This Waltz
Actors: Michelle Williams, Seth Rogen, Luke Kirby, Sarah Silverman
tomatoConsensus: Featuring excellent work from an outstanding cast, the bittersweet drama Waltz proves that in the right hands, a familiar tale can still ring true.

Plot: In the Texas bayous, a local homicide detective teams up with a cop from New York City to investigate a series of unsolved murders.
Title: Texas Killing Fields
Actors: Sam Worthington, Jeffrey Dean Morgan, Jessica Chastain, Chloë Grace Moretz
tomatoConsensus: Texas Killing Fields is a competent boilerplate crime thriller, brewing up characters and plots used in better films.

Title: First Position
Actors: Aran Bell, Rebecca Houseknecht, Joan Sebastian Zamora, Miko Fogarty
tomatoConsensus: An upbeat and visually dramatic documentary of children's ballet, First Position displays the potential of the human spirit when fostered at a young age.

Plot: When a debt puts a young man's life in danger, he turns to putting a hit out on his evil mother in order to collect the insurance.
Title: Killer Joe
Actors: Matthew McConaughey, Emile Hirsch, Juno Temple, Thomas Haden Church
tomatoConsensus: Violent, darkly comic, and full of strong performances, Killer Joe proves William Friedkin hasn't lost his touch, even if the plot may be too lurid for some.

Plot: Romance blooms between two thirty-somethings in arrested development: an avid toy collector who is the dark horse of his family and a depressed woman on the rebound.
Title: Dark Horse
Actors: Melisa Young, Jordan Gelber, Selma Blair, Mia Farrow
tomatoConsensus: Typically misanthropic yet curiously satisfying and incisive, Dark Horse is a movie that preaches to the cynical converted.

Plot: A group of 30-year-olds who have been friends since high school attempt to throw an end-of-summer orgy.
Title: A Good Old Fashioned Orgy
Actors: Jason Sudeikis, Leslie Bibb, Lake Bell, Michelle Borth
tomatoConsensus: Its titillating title promises ribald laughs, but the lazily written, indifferently acted, and only sporadically funny A Good Old Fashioned Orgy fails to consummate.

Plot: In Iowa, an adopted girl discovers her talent for butter carving and finds herself pitted against an ambitious local woman in their town's annual contest.
Title: Butter
Actors: Jennifer Garner, Ty Burrell, Garrett Schenck, Kristen Schaal
tomatoConsensus: Despite its talented cast and a few funny moments, Butter's satirical aims are largely undone by a lack of subtlety and air of smugness.

Plot: Red Riding Hood is training in the group of Sister Hoods, when she and the Wolf are called to examine the sudden mysterious disappearance of Hansel and Gretel.
Title: Hoodwinked Too! Hood vs. Evil
Writer: Cory Edwards (story), Todd Edwards (story), Tony Leech (story), Cory Edwards (screenplay), Todd Edwards (screenplay), Tony Leech (screenplay), Mike Disa (screenplay), Michael Ludy (punch-up/sketches)
Actors: Hayden Panettiere, Glenn Close, Patrick Warburton, Joan Cusack
tomatoConsensus: It may add 3D to the original, but Hoodwinked Too! is missing the first installment's wit and refreshingly low-budget charm.

Plot: The night before their high school reunion, a group of friends realize they still haven't quite grown up in some ways.
Title: 10 Years
Actors: Channing Tatum, Jenna Dewan Tatum, Justin Long, Max Minghella
tomatoConsensus: A sweet ensemble comedy about a high school reunion, 10 Years is well cast but unfortunately predictable and short on three dimensional characters.

Plot: An uptight NYC lawyer takes her two teenagers to her hippie mother's farmhouse upstate for a family vacation.
Title: Peace, Love, & Misunderstanding
Actors: Kyle MacLachlan, Catherine Keener, Joseph Dunn, Ann Osmond
tomatoConsensus: Peace, Love, & Misunderstanding produces many unintentional laughs with its absurdly contrived plot and cheery insistence that everything is just super.

Plot: This heartwarming film documents orphaned orangutans and elephants and the extraordinary people who rescue and raise them-saving endangered species one life at a time.
Title: Born to Be Wild
Actors: Morgan Freeman, Birute Galdikas, Daphne Sheldrick
tomatoConsensus: The human story of Born To Be Wild is captivating and the accompanying nature footage is utterly cute and charming.

Plot: In January 1942 US forces engaged an unidentified flying object above Los Angeles. Now almost 70 years later, the alien invaders have returned.
Title: Battle of Los Angeles
Actors: Nia Peeples, Kel Mitchell, Dylan Vox, Theresa June-Tao
tomatoConsensus: Overlong and overly burdened with war movie clichés, Battle: Los Angeles will entertain only the most ardent action junkies.

Plot: Two top baseball prospects in the Dominican Republic face fierce competition and corruption as they chase their big league dreams.
Title: Ballplayer: Pelotero
Director: Ross Finkel, Trevor Martin, Jonathan Paley
Actors: Jean Carlos Batista, John Leguizamo, Miguel Angel Sano
tomatoConsensus: Gripping and surprisingly nuanced, Ballplayer: Pelotero is a frank exploration of the nature of corruption in baseball recruitment.

Plot: Follows Justin Bieber with some footage of performances from his 2010 concert tour.
Title: Justin Bieber: Never Say Never
Actors: Justin Bieber, Boyz II Men, Miley Cyrus, Sean Kingston
tomatoConsensus: As a tour documentary, it's rather uninspired -- but as a 3D glimpse of a building pop culture phenomenon, Never Say Never is undeniably entertaining.

Plot: Earth's mightiest heroes must come together and learn to fight as a team if they are to stop the mischievous Loki and his alien army from enslaving humanity.
Title: The Avengers
Writer: Joss Whedon (screenplay), Zak Penn (story), Joss Whedon (story)
Actors: Robert Downey Jr., Chris Evans, Mark Ruffalo, Chris Hemsworth
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 34 wins & 75 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Thanks to a script that emphasizes its heroes' humanity and a wealth of superpowered set pieces, The Avengers lives up to its hype and raises the bar for Marvel at the movies.

Plot: After watching their respective partners die, a New Orleans hitman and a Washington D.C. detective form an alliance in order to bring down their common enemy.
Title: Bullet to the Head
Writer: Alessandro Camon (screenplay), Alexis Nolent (based on the graphic novel "Du plomb dans la tête" by), Colin Wilson (based on the graphic novel "Du plomb dans la tête" illustrated by)
Actors: Sylvester Stallone, Sung Kang, Sarah Shahi, Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje
tomatoConsensus: Bullet to the Head's unapologetically trashy thrills evoke memories of its star and director's proud cinematic pasts -- but sadly, those memories are just about all it has to offer.

Plot: Mr. Church reunites the Expendables for what should be an easy paycheck, but when one of their men is murdered on the job, their quest for revenge puts them deep in enemy territory and up against an unexpected threat.
Title: The Expendables 2
Writer: Richard Wenk (screenplay), Sylvester Stallone (screenplay), Ken Kaufman (story), David Agosto (story), Richard Wenk (story), Dave Callaham (characters)
Actors: Sylvester Stallone, Jason Statham, Jet Li, Dolph Lundgren
tomatoConsensus: Taut, violent, and suitably self-deprecating, The Expendables 2 gives classic action fans everything they can reasonably expect from a star-studded shoot-'em-up -- for better and for worse.

Plot: Katniss Everdeen voluntarily takes her younger sister's place in the Hunger Games, a televised competition in which two teenagers from each of the twelve Districts of Panem are chosen at random to fight to the death.
Title: The Hunger Games
Writer: Gary Ross (screenplay), Suzanne Collins (screenplay), Billy Ray (screenplay), Suzanne Collins (novel)
Actors: Stanley Tucci, Wes Bentley, Jennifer Lawrence, Willow Shields
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 33 wins & 42 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Thrilling and superbly acted, The Hunger Games captures the dramatic violence, raw emotion, and ambitious scope of its source novel.

Plot: Eight years after the Joker's reign of anarchy, the Dark Knight, with the help of the enigmatic Selina, is forced from his imposed exile to save Gotham City, now on the edge of total annihilation, from the brutal guerrilla terrorist Bane.
Title: The Dark Knight Rises
Writer: Jonathan Nolan (screenplay), Christopher Nolan (screenplay), Christopher Nolan (story), David S. Goyer (story), Bob Kane (characters)
Actors: Christian Bale, Gary Oldman, Tom Hardy, Joseph Gordon-Levitt
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 38 wins & 96 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Dark Knight Rises is an ambitious, thoughtful, and potent action film that concludes Christopher Nolan's franchise in spectacular fashion.

Plot: An expansion of the universe from Robert Ludlum's novels, centered on a new hero whose stakes have been triggered by the events of the previous three films.
Title: The Bourne Legacy
Writer: Tony Gilroy (screenplay), Dan Gilroy (screenplay), Tony Gilroy (story), Robert Ludlum (inspired by "The Bourne Series" created by)
Actors: Jeremy Renner, Scott Glenn, Stacy Keach, Edward Norton
tomatoConsensus: It isn't quite as compelling as the earlier trilogy, but The Bourne Legacy proves the franchise has stories left to tell -- and benefits from Jeremy Renner's magnetic work in the starring role.

Plot: In Italy, a woman becomes involved in a series of unauthorized exorcisms during her mission to discover what happened to her mother, who allegedly murdered three people during her own exorcism.
Title: The Devil Inside
Actors: Fernanda Andrade, Simon Quarterman, Evan Helmuth, Ionut Grama
tomatoConsensus: The Devil Inside is a cheap, choppy unscary mess, featuring one of the worst endings in recent memory.

Plot: To protect his brother-in-law from a drug lord, a former smuggler heads to Panama to score millions of dollars in counterfeit bills.
Title: Contraband
Writer: Aaron Guzikowski (screenplay), Arnaldur Indriðason (film "Reykjavik-Rotterdam"), Óskar Jónasson (film "Reykjavik-Rotterdam")
Actors: Robert Wahlberg, Caleb Landry Jones, Jason Mitchell, Paul LeBlanc
tomatoConsensus: It's more entertaining than your average January action thriller, but that isn't enough to excuse Contraband's lack of originality and unnecessarily convoluted plot.

Plot: G.G. Sparrow faces off with her choir's newly appointed director, Vi Rose Hill, over the group's direction as they head into a national competition.
Title: Joyful Noise
Actors: Queen Latifah, Dolly Parton, Keke Palmer, Jeremy Jordan
tomatoConsensus: Joyful Noise's musical numbers are solidly entertaining, and it benefits from Queen Latifah and Dolly Parton's sizable chemistry; unfortunately, they aren't enough to make up for the rest of the film.

Plot: When human forces discover the existence of the Vampire and Lycan clans, a war to eradicate both species commences. The vampire warrior Selene leads the battle against humankind.
Title: Underworld: Awakening
Writer: Len Wiseman (screenplay), John Hlavin (screenplay), J. Michael Straczynski (screenplay), Allison Burnett (screenplay), Len Wiseman (story), John Hlavin (story), Kevin Grevioux (characters), Len Wiseman (characters), Danny McBride (characters)
Actors: Kate Beckinsale, Stephen Rea, Michael Ealy, Theo James
tomatoConsensus: There's more vapid action and less story in Underworld Awakening than previous installments, making the whole affair feel inconsequential.

Plot: As a police psychologist works to talk down an ex-con who is threatening to jump from a Manhattan hotel rooftop, the biggest diamond heist ever committed is in motion.
Title: Man on a Ledge
Actors: Sam Worthington, Mandy Gonzalez, William Sadler, Barbara Marineau
tomatoConsensus: Uninspired acting and preposterous plotlines defuse Man on a Ledge's mildly intriguing premise.

Plot: A crew of African American pilots in the Tuskegee training program, having faced segregation while kept mostly on the ground during World War II, are called into duty under the guidance of Col. A.J. Bullard.
Title: Red Tails
Writer: John Ridley (story), John Ridley (screenplay), Aaron McGruder (screenplay), John B. Holway (book)
Actors: Terrence Howard, Cuba Gooding Jr., Nate Parker, David Oyelowo
tomatoConsensus: Despite a worthy fact-based story and obvious good intentions, Red Tails suffers from one-dimensional characters, corny dialogue, and heaps of clichés.

Plot: Unemployed and newly-divorced Stephanie Plum lands a job at her cousin's bail-bond business, where her first assignment puts her on the trail of a wanted local cop from her romantic past.
Title: One for the Money
Writer: Stacy Sherman (screenplay), Karen Ray (screenplay), Liz Brixius (screenplay), Janet Evanovich (novel)
Actors: Katherine Heigl, Jason O'Mara, Daniel Sunjata, John Leguizamo
tomatoConsensus: Dull and unfunny, One For the Money wastes Katherine Heigl's talents on a stunningly generic comic thriller.

Plot: In small town Alaska, a news reporter recruits his ex-girlfriend - a Greenpeace volunteer - on a campaign to save a family of gray whales trapped by rapidly forming ice in the Arctic Circle.
Title: Big Miracle
Writer: Jack Amiel (screenplay), Michael Begler (screenplay), Thomas Rose (book)
Actors: John Pingayak, Ahmaogak Sweeney, John Chase, Ishmael Angalook Hope
tomatoConsensus: Big Miracle uses real-life events as the basis for a surprisingly satisfying family drama.

Plot: Whilst attending a party, three high school friends gain superpowers after making an incredible discovery underground. Soon, though, they find their lives spinning out of control and their bond tested as they embrace their darker sides.
Title: Chronicle
Writer: Max Landis (screenplay), Max Landis (story), Josh Trank (story)
Actors: Dane DeHaan, Alex Russell, Michael B. Jordan, Michael Kelly
tomatoConsensus: Chronicle transcends its found-footage gimmick with a smart script, fast-paced direction, and engaging performances from the young cast.

Plot: A young lawyer travels to a remote village where he discovers the vengeful ghost of a scorned woman is terrorizing the locals.
Title: The Woman in Black
Actors: Emma Shorey, Molly Harmon, Ellisa Walker-Reid, Sophie Stuckey
tomatoConsensus: Traditional to a fault, The Woman in Black foregoes gore for chills -- although it may not provide enough of them for viewers attuned to more modern, high-stakes horror.

Plot: A young CIA agent is tasked with looking after a fugitive in a safe house. But when the safe house is attacked, he finds himself on the run with his charge.
Title: Safe House
Actors: Denzel Washington, Ryan Reynolds, Vera Farmiga, Brendan Gleeson
tomatoConsensus: Safe House stars Washington and Reynolds are let down by a thin script and choppily edited action sequences.

Plot: A car accident puts Paige in a coma, and when she wakes up with severe memory loss, her husband Leo works to win her heart again.
Title: The Vow
Country: USA, France, Australia, UK, Germany, Canada
Writer: Abby Kohn (screenplay), Marc Silverstein (screenplay), Jason Katims (screenplay), Stuart Sender (story)
Actors: Rachel McAdams, Channing Tatum, Jessica Lange, Sam Neill
tomatoConsensus: Channing Tatum and Rachel McAdams do their best with what they're given, but The Vow is too shallow and familiar to satisfy the discriminating date-night filmgoer.

Plot: Former college frenemies Lauren and Katie move into a fabulous Gramercy Park apartment, and in order to make ends meet, the unlikely pair start a phone sex line together.
Title: For a Good Time, Call...
Actors: Lauren Miller, James Wolk, Ari Graynor, Justin Long
tomatoConsensus: Brisk, funny, and sweetly raunchy, For a Good Time, Call... adds to the recent string of R-rated female comedies while serving as an overdue coming out party for the charming Ari Graynor.

Plot: Sean Anderson partners with his mom's husband on a mission to find his grandfather, who is thought to be missing on a mythical island.
Title: Journey 2: The Mysterious Island
Writer: Brian Gunn (screenplay), Mark Gunn (screenplay), Richard Outten (story), Brian Gunn (story), Mark Gunn (story), Jules Verne (novel)
Actors: Dwayne Johnson, Michael Caine, Josh Hutcherson, Luis Guzmán
tomatoConsensus: Aggressively unambitious, Journey 2 might thrill tween viewers, but most others will find it too intense for young audiences and too cartoonishly dull for adults.

Plot: 3 high school seniors throw a birthday party to make a name for themselves. As the night progresses, things spiral out of control as word of the party spreads.
Title: Project X
Writer: Matt Drake (screenplay), Michael Bacall (screenplay), Michael Bacall (story)
Actors: Thomas Mann, Oliver Cooper, Jonathan Daniel Brown, Dax Flame
tomatoConsensus: Unoriginal, unfunny, and all-around unattractive, Project X mines the depths of the teen movie and found-footage genres for 87 minutes of predictably mean-spirited debauchery.

Plot: A 12-year-old boy searches for the one thing that will enable him to win the affection of the girl of his dreams. To find it he must discover the story of the Lorax, the grumpy yet charming creature who fights to protect his world.
Title: The Lorax
Writer: Dr. Seuss (based on the book by), Cinco Paul (screenplay), Ken Daurio (screenplay)
Actors: Danny DeVito, Ed Helms, Zac Efron, Taylor Swift
tomatoConsensus: Dr. Seuss' The Lorax is cute and funny enough but the moral simplicity of the book gets lost with the zany Hollywood production values.

Plot: An elite team of Navy SEALs embark on a covert mission to recover a kidnapped CIA agent.
Title: Act of Valor
Actors: Rorke Denver, Dave, Sonny, Weimy
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 6 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It's undeniably reverent of the real-life heroes in its cast, but Act of Valor lets them down with a clichéd script, stilted acting, and a jingoistic attitude that ignores the complexities of war.

Plot: Two top CIA operatives wage an epic battle against one another after they discover they are dating the same woman.
Title: This Means War
Writer: Timothy Dowling (screenplay), Simon Kinberg (screenplay), Timothy Dowling (story), Marcus Gautesen (story)
Actors: Reese Witherspoon, Chris Pine, Tom Hardy, Til Schweiger
tomatoConsensus: A career lowlight for all three of its likable stars, This Means War is loud, clumsily edited, and neither romantic nor funny.

Plot: Transported to Barsoom, a Civil War vet discovers a barren planet seemingly inhabited by 12-foot tall barbarians. Finding himself prisoner of these creatures, he escapes, only to encounter Woola and a princess in desperate need of a savior.
Title: John Carter
Writer: Andrew Stanton (screenplay), Mark Andrews (screenplay), Michael Chabon (screenplay), Edgar Rice Burroughs (based on the story "A Princess of Mars" by)
Actors: Taylor Kitsch, Lynn Collins, Samantha Morton, Willem Dafoe
tomatoConsensus: While John Carter looks terrific and delivers its share of pulpy thrills, it also suffers from uneven pacing and occasionally incomprehensible plotting and characterization.

Plot: A pair of underachieving cops are sent back to a local high school to blend in and bring down a synthetic drug ring.
Title: 21 Jump Street
Writer: Michael Bacall (screenplay), Michael Bacall (story), Jonah Hill (story), Patrick Hasburgh (television series), Stephen J. Cannell (television series)
Actors: Jonah Hill, Channing Tatum, Brie Larson, Dave Franco
tomatoConsensus: A smart, affectionate satire of '80s nostalgia and teen movie tropes, 21 Jump Street offers rowdy mainstream comedy with a surprisingly satisfying bite.

Plot: A man wrongly convicted of conspiracy to commit espionage against the U.S. is offered his freedom if he can rescue the president's daughter from an outer space prison taken over by violent inmates.
Title: Lockout
Writer: Stephen St. Leger (screenplay), James Mather (screenplay), Luc Besson (screenplay), Luc Besson (original idea)
Actors: Guy Pearce, Maggie Grace, Vincent Regan, Joseph Gilgun
tomatoConsensus: Guy Pearce does the best he can with what he's given, but Lockout is ultimately too derivative and shallow to build on the many sci-fi thrillers it borrows from.

Plot: Scheming on a way to save their father's ranch, the Alvarez brothers find themselves in a war with Mexico's most feared drug lord.
Title: Casa de mi Padre
Writer: Andrew Steele, Eva Maria Peters (dubbing dialogue)
Actors: Will Ferrell, Diego Luna, Pedro Armendáriz Jr., Genesis Rodriguez
tomatoConsensus: Thinly written and not as funny as it needs to be, Casa de mi Padre would have worked better as a fake trailer or short film; stretched to feature length, it wears out its welcome far too quickly.

Plot: Perseus braves the treacherous underworld to rescue his father, Zeus, captured by his son, Ares, and brother Hades who unleash the ancient Titans upon the world.
Title: Wrath of the Titans
Writer: Dan Mazeau (screenplay), David Leslie Johnson (screenplay), Greg Berlanti (story), David Leslie Johnson (story), Dan Mazeau (story), Beverley Cross
Actors: Sam Worthington, Liam Neeson, Ralph Fiennes, Edgar Ramírez
tomatoConsensus: Its 3D effects are an improvement over its predecessor's, but in nearly every other respect, Wrath of the Titans fails to improve upon the stilted acting, wooden dialogue, and chaos-driven plot of the franchise's first installment.

Plot: Jim, Michelle, Stifler, and their friends reunite in East Great Falls, Michigan for their high school reunion.
Title: American Reunion
Writer: Jon Hurwitz (screenplay), Hayden Schlossberg (screenplay), Adam Herz (characters)
Actors: Jason Biggs, Alyson Hannigan, Chris Klein, Thomas Ian Nicholas
tomatoConsensus: It'll provide sweetly nostalgic comfort food for fans of the franchise, but American Reunion fails to do anything truly new or interesting -- or even very funny -- with the characters.

Plot: Five friends go for a break at a remote cabin in the woods, where they get more than they bargained for. Together, they must discover the truth behind the cabin in the woods.
Title: The Cabin in the Woods
Actors: Kristen Connolly, Chris Hemsworth, Anna Hutchison, Fran Kranz
tomatoConsensus: The Cabin in the Woods is an astonishing meta-feat, capable of being funny, strange, and scary -- frequently all at the same time.

Plot: While trying to save their childhood orphanage, Moe, Larry and Curly inadvertently stumble into a murder plot and wind up starring in a reality television show.
Title: The Three Stooges
Writer: Mike Cerrone, Bobby Farrelly, Peter Farrelly
Actors: Sean Hayes, Will Sasso, Chris Diamantopoulos, Jane Lynch
tomatoConsensus: While nowhere near as painful as it could have been, The Three Stooges fails to add fresh laughs to the Stooges' inestimable cinematic legacy.

Plot: When a madman begins committing horrific murders inspired by Edgar Allan Poe's works, a young Baltimore detective joins forces with Poe to stop him from making his stories a reality.
Title: The Raven
Actors: John Cusack, Luke Evans, Alice Eve, Brendan Gleeson
tomatoConsensus: Thinly scripted, unevenly acted, and overall preposterous, The Raven disgraces the legacy of Edgar Allen Poe with a rote murder mystery that's more silly than scary.

Plot: An evil queen steals control of a kingdom and an exiled princess enlists the help of seven resourceful rebels to win back her birthright.
Title: Mirror Mirror
Writer: Marc Klein (screenplay), Jason Keller (screenplay), Melisa Wallack (screen story)
Actors: Julia Roberts, Lily Collins, Armie Hammer, Nathan Lane
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 8 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Like most of Tarsem Singh's films, Mirror Mirror is undeniably beautiful -- but its treatment of the age-old Snow White fable lacks enough depth or originality to set it apart from the countless other adaptations of the tale.

Plot: A fleet of ships is forced to do battle with an armada of unknown origins in order to discover and thwart their destructive goals.
Title: Battleship
Actors: Taylor Kitsch, Alexander Skarsgård, Rihanna, Brooklyn Decker
tomatoConsensus: It may offer energetic escapism for less demanding filmgoers, but Battleship is too loud, poorly written, and formulaic to justify its expense -- and a lot less fun than its source material.

Plot: One year after meeting, Tom proposes to his girlfriend, Violet, but unexpected events keep tripping them up as they look to walk down the aisle together.
Title: The Five-Year Engagement
Actors: Jason Segel, Emily Blunt, Chris Pratt, Alison Brie
tomatoConsensus: While certainly overlong, The Five-Year Engagement benefits from the easy chemistry of its leads and a funny, romantic script with surprising depth and intelligence.

Plot: Four friends conspire to turn the tables on their women when they discover the ladies have been using Steve Harvey's relationship advice against them.
Title: Think Like a Man
Writer: Keith Merryman (screenplay), David A. Newman (screenplay), Steve Harvey (book)
Actors: Michael Ealy, Jerry Ferrara, Meagan Good, Regina Hall
tomatoConsensus: In Think Like a Man, an otherwise standard rom-com is partially elevated by a committed -- and attractive -- cast, resulting in a funny take on modern romance.

Plot: A Marine travels to Louisiana after serving three tours in Iraq and searches for the unknown woman he believes was his good luck charm during the war.
Title: The Lucky One
Actors: Zac Efron, Taylor Schilling, Blythe Danner, Riley Thomas Stewart
tomatoConsensus: While it provides the requisite amount of escapist melodrama, The Lucky One ultimately relies on too many schmaltzy clichés to appeal to anyone not already familiar with the Nicholas Sparks formula.

Plot: Mei, a young girl whose memory holds a priceless numerical code, finds herself pursued by the Triads, the Russian mob, and corrupt NYC cops. Coming to her aid is an ex-cage fighter whose life was destroyed by the gangsters on Mei's trail.
Title: Safe
Actors: Jason Statham, Catherine Chan, Robert John Burke, James Hong
tomatoConsensus: While hard-hitting and violently inventive, Safe ultimately proves too formulaic to set itself apart from the action thriller pack -- including some of its star's better films.

Plot: An imprisoned vampire, Barnabas Collins, is set free and returns to his ancestral home, where his dysfunctional descendants are in need of his protection.
Title: Dark Shadows
Writer: Seth Grahame-Smith (screenplay), John August (story), Seth Grahame-Smith (story), Dan Curtis (television series)
Actors: Johnny Depp, Michelle Pfeiffer, Helena Bonham Carter, Eva Green
tomatoConsensus: The visuals are top notch but Tim Burton never finds a consistent rhythm, mixing campy jokes and gothic spookiness with less success than other Johnny Depp collaborations.

Plot: The heroic story of a dictator who risked his life to ensure that democracy would never come to the country he so lovingly oppressed.
Title: The Dictator
Writer: Sacha Baron Cohen, Alec Berg, David Mandel, Jeff Schaffer
Actors: Sacha Baron Cohen, Sayed Badreya, Rocky Citron, Liam Campora
tomatoConsensus: Wildly uneven but consistently provocative, The Dictator is a decent entry in the poli-slapstick comedy genre.

Plot: Agent J travels in time to M.I.B.'s early days in 1969 to stop an alien from assassinating his friend Agent K and changing history.
Title: Men in Black 3
Writer: Etan Cohen, Lowell Cunningham (based on the Malibu comic by)
Actors: Will Smith, Tommy Lee Jones, Josh Brolin, Jemaine Clement
tomatoConsensus: It isn't exactly a persuasive argument for the continuation of the franchise, but Men in Black III is better than its predecessor and manages to exceed expectations.

Plot: In a twist to the fairy tale, the Huntsman ordered to take Snow White into the woods to be killed winds up becoming her protector and mentor in a quest to vanquish the Evil Queen.
Title: Snow White and the Huntsman
Writer: Evan Daugherty (screenplay), John Lee Hancock (screenplay), Hossein Amini (screenplay), Evan Daugherty (screen story)
Actors: Kristen Stewart, Chris Hemsworth, Charlize Theron, Sam Claflin
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 13 wins & 31 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: While it offers an appropriately dark take on the fairy tale that inspired it, Snow White and the Huntsman is undone by uneven acting, problematic pacing, and a confused script.

Plot: Six tourists hire an extreme tour guide who takes them to the abandoned city Pripyat, the former home to the workers of the Chernobyl nuclear reactor. During their exploration, they soon discover they are not alone.
Title: Chernobyl Diaries
Writer: Oren Peli (screenplay), Carey Van Dyke (screenplay), Shane Van Dyke (screenplay), Oren Peli (story)
Actors: Ingrid Bolsø Berdal, Dimitri Diatchenko, Olivia Taylor Dudley, Devin Kelley
tomatoConsensus: Despite an interesting premise and spooky atmospherics, Chernobyl Diaries is mostly short on suspense and originality.

Plot: Pirate Captain sets out on a mission to defeat his rivals Black Bellamy and Cutlass Liz for the Pirate of the year Award. The quest takes Captain and his crew from the shores of Blood Island to the foggy streets of Victorian London.
Title: The Pirates! Band of Misfits
Actors: Hugh Grant, Martin Freeman, Imelda Staunton, David Tennant
tomatoConsensus: It may not quite scale Aardman's customary delirious heights, but The Pirates! still represents some of the smartest, most skillfully animated fare that modern cinema has to offer.

Plot: Following clues to the origin of mankind a team journey across the universe and find a structure on a distant moon containing a monolithic statue of a humanoid head and stone cylinders of alien blood but they soon find they are not alone.
Title: Prometheus
Writer: Jon Spaihts, Damon Lindelof, Dan O'Bannon (elements), Ronald Shusett (elements)
Actors: Noomi Rapace, Michael Fassbender, Charlize Theron, Idris Elba
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 43 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Ridley Scott's ambitious quasi-prequel to Alien may not answer all of its big questions, but it's redeemed by its haunting visual grandeur and compelling performances -- particularly Michael Fassbender as a fastidious android.

Plot: Rattled by sudden unemployment, a Manhattan couple surveys alternative living options, ultimately deciding to experiment with living on a rural commune where free love rules.
Title: Wanderlust
Actors: Paul Rudd, Jennifer Aniston, Justin Theroux, Alan Alda
tomatoConsensus: It isn't always as funny as it should be, but Wanderlust benefits from an extremely talented cast and some of David Wain's most confident, assured work behind the camera.

Plot: A pair of young lovers flee their New England town, which causes a local search party to fan out to find them.
Title: Moonrise Kingdom
Actors: Bruce Willis, Edward Norton, Bill Murray, Frances McDormand
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 37 wins & 117 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Warm, whimsical, and poignant, the immaculately framed and beautifully acted Moonrise Kingdom presents writer/director Wes Anderson at his idiosyncratic best.

Plot: Riding across Manhattan in a stretch limo in order to get a haircut, a 28-year-old billionaire asset manager's day devolves into an odyssey with a cast of characters that start to tear his world apart.
Title: Cosmopolis
Actors: Robert Pattinson, Sarah Gadon, Paul Giamatti, Kevin Durand
tomatoConsensus: Though some may find it cold and didactic, Cosmopolis benefits from David Cronenberg's precise direction, resulting in a psychologically complex adaptation of Don DeLillo's novel.

Plot: After stretching the truth on a deal with a spiritual guru, literary agent Jack McCall finds a Bodhi tree on his property. Its appearance holds a valuable lesson on the consequences of every word he speaks.
Title: A Thousand Words
Actors: Eddie Murphy, Kerry Washington, Emanuel Ragsdale, Jill Basey
tomatoConsensus: Dated jokes (A Thousand Words was shot in 2008) and removing Eddie Murphy's voice -- his greatest comedic asset -- dooms this painful mess from the start.

Plot: A 3-months-old chimpanzee is separated from his troop and is then adopted by a fully-grown male.
Title: Chimpanzee
Writer: Alastair Fothergill (original concept), Mark Linfield (original concept), Mark Linfield, Alastair Fothergill, Don Hahn
Actors: Tim Allen
tomatoConsensus: Chimpanzee often anthropomorphizes its subjects, but it's a beautifully filmed, remarkably intimate look at the lives of a family of primates.

Plot: Three magazine employees head out on an assignment to interview a guy who placed a classified advertisement seeking a companion for time travel.
Title: Safety Not Guaranteed
Actors: Aubrey Plaza, Lauren Carlos, Basil Harris, Mary Lynn Rajskub
tomatoConsensus: Safety Not Guaranteed's ostensibly modest ambitions are outmatched by the movie's strong performances, beguiling charm, and heartfelt story.

Plot: Alex, Marty, Gloria and Melman are still fighting to get home to their beloved Big Apple. Their journey takes them through Europe where they find the perfect cover: a traveling circus, which they reinvent - Madagascar style.
Title: Madagascar 3: Europe's Most Wanted
Director: Eric Darnell, Tom McGrath, Conrad Vernon
Actors: Ben Stiller, Chris Rock, David Schwimmer, Jada Pinkett Smith
tomatoConsensus: Dazzlingly colorful and frenetic, Madagascar 3 is silly enough for young kids, but boasts enough surprising smarts to engage parents along the way.

Plot: Determined to make her own path in life, Princess Merida defies a custom that brings chaos to her kingdom. Granted one wish, Merida must rely on her bravery and her archery skills to undo a beastly curse.
Title: Brave
Writer: Brenda Chapman (story by), Mark Andrews (screenplay), Steve Purcell (screenplay), Brenda Chapman (screenplay), Irene Mecchi (screenplay)
Director: Mark Andrews, Brenda Chapman, Steve Purcell
Actors: Kelly Macdonald, Billy Connolly, Emma Thompson, Julie Walters
tomatoConsensus: Brave offers young audiences and fairy tale fans a rousing, funny fantasy adventure with a distaff twist and surprising depth.

Plot: Follows the lives of five interconnected couples as they experience the thrills and surprises of having a baby, and realize that no matter what you plan for, life does not always deliver what is expected.
Title: What to Expect When You're Expecting
Writer: Shauna Cross (screenplay), Heather Hach (screenplay), Heidi Murkoff (books)
Actors: Cameron Diaz, Jennifer Lopez, Elizabeth Banks, Chace Crawford
tomatoConsensus: The cast is stocked with likable performers, but What to Expect When You're Expecting is too disjointed -- and too reliant on stock rom-com cliches -- to live up to its distinguished literary namesake.

Plot: The lives of some visitors and residents of Rome and the romances, adventures and predicaments they get into.
Title: To Rome with Love
Actors: Judy Davis, Flavio Parenti, Roberto Benigni, Alison Pill
tomatoConsensus: To Rome With Love sees Woody Allen cobbling together an Italian postcard of farce, fantasy, and comedy with only middling success.

Plot: Abraham Lincoln, the 16th President of the United States, discovers vampires are planning to take over the United States. He makes it his mission to eliminate them.
Title: Abraham Lincoln: Vampire Hunter
Writer: Seth Grahame-Smith (screenplay), Seth Grahame-Smith (based on the novel by)
Actors: Benjamin Walker, Dominic Cooper, Anthony Mackie, Mary Elizabeth Winstead
tomatoConsensus: Abraham Lincoln: Vampire Hunter has visual style to spare, but its overly serious tone doesn't jibe with its decidedly silly central premise, leaving filmgoers with an unfulfilling blend of clashing ingredients.

Plot: A chronicle of the Cristeros War (1926-1929); a war by the people of Mexico against the atheistic Mexican government.
Title: For Greater Glory: The True Story of Cristiada
Actors: Mauricio Kuri, Adrian Alonso, Rubén Blades, Catalina Sandino Moreno
tomatoConsensus: It has laudable aspirations, but For Greater Glory ultimately fails to fulfill its goals due to an overstuffed script, thinly written characters, and an overly simplified dramatization of historical events.

Plot: A small town girl and a city boy meet on the Sunset Strip, while pursuing their Hollywood dreams.
Title: Rock of Ages
Writer: Justin Theroux (screenplay), Chris D'Arienzo (screenplay), Allan Loeb (screenplay), Chris D'Arienzo (musical book)
Actors: Julianne Hough, Dakota Sage Grant, Matthew Rush Sullivan, Diego Boneta
tomatoConsensus: Its exuberant silliness is almost enough to make up for its utter inconsequentiality, but Rock of Ages is ultimately too bland and overlong to justify its trip to the big screen.

Plot: As an asteroid nears Earth, a man finds himself alone after his wife leaves in a panic. He decides to take a road trip to reunite with his high school sweetheart. Accompanying him is a neighbor who inadvertently puts a wrench in his plan.
Title: Seeking a Friend for the End of the World
Actors: Brad Morris, Steve Carell, Nancy Carell, Mark Moses
tomatoConsensus: Tender, charming, and well-acted, Seeking a Friend for the End of the World is unfortunately hamstrung by jarring tonal shifts and a disappointing final act.

Plot: John Bennett, a man whose childhood wish of bringing his teddy bear to life came true, now must decide between keeping the relationship with the bear or his girlfriend, Lori.
Title: Ted
Writer: Seth MacFarlane (screenplay), Alec Sulkin (screenplay), Wellesley Wild (screenplay), Seth MacFarlane (story by)
Actors: Mark Wahlberg, Mila Kunis, Seth MacFarlane, Joel McHale
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 13 wins & 26 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Ted's "romance versus bromance" plot is familiar, but the film's held aloft by the high-concept central premise and a very funny (albeit inconsistent) script.

Plot: A male stripper teaches a younger performer how to party, pick up women, and make easy money.
Title: Magic Mike
Actors: Matthew McConaughey, Channing Tatum, Olivia Munn, Alex Pettyfer
tomatoConsensus: Magic Mike's sensitive direction, smart screenplay, and strong performances allow audiences to have their beefcake and eat it too.

Plot: After Peter Parker is bitten by a genetically altered spider, he gains newfound, spider-like powers and ventures out to solve the mystery of his parent's mysterious death.
Title: The Amazing Spider-Man
Writer: James Vanderbilt (screenplay), Alvin Sargent (screenplay), Steve Kloves (screenplay), James Vanderbilt (story), Stan Lee (based on the Marvel comic book by), Steve Ditko (based on the Marvel comic book by)
Actors: Andrew Garfield, Emma Stone, Rhys Ifans, Denis Leary
tomatoConsensus: A well-chosen cast and sure-handed direction allow The Amazing Spider-Man to thrill, despite revisiting many of the same plot points from 2002's Spider-Man.

Plot: Manny, Diego, and Sid embark upon another adventure after their continent is set adrift. Using an iceberg as a ship, they encounter sea creatures and battle pirates as they explore a new world.
Title: Ice Age: Continental Drift
Writer: Michael Berg (screenplay), Jason Fuchs (screenplay), Michael Berg (story), Lori Forte (story)
Actors: Aziz Ansari, Joy Behar, Christopher Campbell, Alain Chabat
tomatoConsensus: Ice Age: Continental Drift 3D has moments of charm and witty slapstick, but it often seems content to recycle ideas from the previous films.

Plot: Faced with both her hot-tempered father's fading health and melting ice-caps that flood her ramshackle bayou community and unleash ancient aurochs, six-year-old Hushpuppy must learn the ways of courage and love.
Title: Beasts of the Southern Wild
Writer: Lucy Alibar (screenplay), Benh Zeitlin (screenplay), Lucy Alibar (stage play "Juicy and Delicious")
Actors: Quvenzhané Wallis, Dwight Henry, Levy Easterly, Lowell Landes
Awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 92 wins & 123 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Beasts of the Southern Wild is a fantastical, emotionally powerful journey and a strong case of filmmaking that values imagination over money.

Plot: While settling his recently deceased father's estate, a salesman discovers he has a sister whom he never knew about, leading both siblings to re-examine their perceptions about family and life choices.
Title: People Like Us
Writer: Alex Kurtzman, Roberto Orci, Jody Lambert
Actors: Chris Pine, Elizabeth Banks, Michael Hall D'Addario, Michelle Pfeiffer
tomatoConsensus: Though calculated and melodramatic, People Like Us benefits from a pair of solid leads and its rare screenplay that caters to adult filmgoers.

Plot: Pot growers Ben and Chon face off against the Mexican drug cartel who kidnapped their shared girlfriend.
Title: Savages
Writer: Shane Salerno (screenplay), Don Winslow (screenplay), Oliver Stone (screenplay), Don Winslow (novel)
Actors: Blake Lively, Taylor Kitsch, Aaron Taylor-Johnson, Jana Banker
tomatoConsensus: It's undeniably messy, but Savages finds Oliver Stone returning to dark, fearlessly lurid form.

Plot: Four men who form a neighborhood watch group as a way to get out of their day-to-day family routines find themselves defending the Earth from an alien invasion.
Title: The Watch
Writer: Jared Stern, Seth Rogen, Evan Goldberg
Actors: Ben Stiller, Vince Vaughn, Jonah Hill, Richard Ayoade
tomatoConsensus: The Watch uneasily mixes sci-fi elements with gross-out gags and strands its talented cast with a script that favors vulgarity over wit at nearly every turn.

Plot: Working in a Boston homeless shelter, Nick Flynn re-encounters his father, a con man and self-proclaimed poet. Sensing trouble in his own life, Nick wrestles with the notion of reaching out yet again to his dad.
Title: Being Flynn
Actors: Robert De Niro, Paul Dano, Julianne Moore, Olivia Thirlby
tomatoConsensus: Robert De Niro gives a sincere, gripping performance, but Being Flynn is an uneasy mix of drama and comedy that fails to emotionally resonate as a whole.

Plot: A novelist struggling with writer's block finds romance in a most unusual way: by creating a female character he thinks will love him, then willing her into existence.
Title: Ruby Sparks
Actors: Paul Dano, Zoe Kazan, Chris Messina, Annette Bening
tomatoConsensus: Cleverly written and wonderfully acted, Ruby Sparks overcomes its occasional lags in pace with an abundance of charm and wit.

Plot: A factory worker, Douglas Quaid, begins to suspect that he is a spy after visiting Rekall - a company that provides its clients with implanted fake memories of a life they would like to have led - goes wrong and he finds himself on the run.
Title: Total Recall
Writer: Kurt Wimmer (screenplay), Mark Bomback (screenplay), Ronald Shusett (screen story by), Dan O'Bannon (screen story by), Jon Povill (screen story by), Kurt Wimmer (screen story by), Ronald Shusett (based on the motion picture "Total Recall",  screenplay by), Dan O'Bannon (based on the motion picture "Total Recall",  screenplay by), Gary Goldman (based on the motion picture "Total Recall",  screenplay by), Ronald Shusett (based on the motion picture "Total Recall",  screen story by), Dan O'Bannon (based on the motion picture "Total Recall",  screen story by), Jon Povill (based on the motion picture "Total Recall",  screen story by)
Actors: Colin Farrell, Kate Beckinsale, Jessica Biel, Bryan Cranston
tomatoConsensus: While it boasts some impressive action sequences, Total Recall lacks the intricate plotting, wry humor, and fleshed out characters that made the original a sci-fi classic.

Plot: Bond's loyalty to M is tested when her past comes back to haunt her. Whilst MI6 comes under attack, 007 must track down and destroy the threat, no matter how personal the cost.
Title: Skyfall
Writer: Neal Purvis, Robert Wade, John Logan
Actors: Daniel Craig, Judi Dench, Javier Bardem, Ralph Fiennes
tomatoConsensus: Sam Mendes brings Bond surging back with a smart, sexy, riveting action thriller that qualifies as one of the best 007 films to date.

Plot: An incumbent congressman embroiled in personal scandal faces a no-holds-barred challenge from a naive newcomer funded by two unscrupulous billionaire lobbyist brothers.
Title: The Campaign
Writer: Chris Henchy (screenplay), Shawn Harwell (screenplay), Adam McKay (story), Chris Henchy (story), Shawn Harwell (story)
Actors: Will Ferrell, Zach Galifianakis, Jason Sudeikis, Dylan McDermott
tomatoConsensus: Its crude brand of political satire isn't quite as smart or sharp as one might hope in an election year, but The Campaign manages to generate a sufficient number of laughs thanks to its well-matched leads.

Plot: After thirty years of marriage, a middle-aged couple attends an intense, week-long counseling session to work on their relationship.
Title: Hope Springs
Actors: Meryl Streep, Tommy Lee Jones, Steve Carell, Jean Smart
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Led by a pair of mesmerizing performances from Meryl Streep and Tommy Lee Jones, Hope Springs offers filmgoers some grown-up laughs -- and a thoughtful look at mature relationships.

Plot: A documentary that follows a billionaire couple as they begin construction on a mansion inspired by Versailles. During the next two years, their empire, fueled by the real estate bubble and cheap money, falters due to the economic crisis.
Title: The Queen of Versailles
Actors: Alyse Barker, Lorraine Barrett, June Downs, Phillip Froehlich
tomatoConsensus: The Queen of Versailles is a timely, engaging, and richly drawn portrait of the American Dream improbably composed of equal parts compassion and schadenfreude.

Plot: A misunderstood boy takes on ghosts, zombies and grown-ups to save his town from a centuries-old curse.
Title: ParaNorman
Actors: Kodi Smit-McPhee, Tucker Albrizzi, Anna Kendrick, Casey Affleck
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 19 wins & 44 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Beautifully animated and solidly scripted, ParaNorman will entertain (and frighten) older children while providing surprisingly thoughtful fare for their parents.

Plot: School's out. Summer vacation is on. However, Greg may not have the best summer vacation ever. What could go wrong?
Title: Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Dog Days
Writer: Maya Forbes (screenplay), Wallace Wolodarsky (screenplay), Jeff Kinney (based upon the book by)
Actors: Zachary Gordon, Steve Zahn, Robert Capron, Devon Bostick
tomatoConsensus: Overly familiar and a bit too reliant on slapstick, the sitcom-like Dog Days fails to improve upon previous installments and will likely appeal to few outside its target audience.

Plot: A divorcing couple tries to maintain their friendship while they both pursue other people.
Title: Celeste & Jesse Forever
Actors: Rashida Jones, Andy Samberg, Ari Graynor, Eric Christian Olsen
tomatoConsensus: While it doesn't subvert the genre as incisively as it thinks it does, Celeste and Jesse Forever is a shrewd rom-com that benefits from its likable cast and trumpets the arrival of Rashida Jones as a bona fide big screen talent.

Plot: Former getaway driver Charlie Bronson jeopardizes his Witness Protection Plan identity in order to help his girlfriend get to Los Angeles. The feds and Charlie's former gang chase them on the road.
Title: Hit and Run
Actors: Kristen Bell, Dax Shepard, Tom Arnold, Kristin Chenoweth
tomatoConsensus: Though Hit & Run has some surprisingly oft-kilter filmmaking, the action doesn't add to much and the writing's a bit smug.

Plot: In Manhattan, a bike messenger picks up an envelope that attracts the interest of a dirty cop, who pursues the cyclist throughout the city.
Title: Premium Rush
Actors: Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Dania Ramirez, Sean Kennedy, Kym Perfetto
tomatoConsensus: It's built out of familiar parts, but no matter how formulaic Premium Rush's storyline might seem, it's elevated by high-octane action and enjoyable performances.

Plot: A childless couple bury a box in their backyard, containing all of their wishes for an infant. Soon, a child is born, though Timothy Green is not all that he appears.
Title: The Odd Life of Timothy Green
Actors: Jennifer Garner, Joel Edgerton, CJ Adams, Odeya Rush
tomatoConsensus: It means well, but The Odd Life of Timothy Green is ultimately too cloyingly sentimental -- and thinly scripted -- to satisfy all but the least demanding viewers.

Plot: Set in Depression-era Franklin County, Virginia, a trio of bootlegging brothers are threatened by a new special deputy and other authorities angling for a cut of their profits.
Title: Lawless
Actors: Shia LaBeouf, Tom Hardy, Jason Clarke, Guy Pearce
tomatoConsensus: Grim, bloody, and utterly flawed, Lawless doesn't quite achieve the epic status it strains for, but it's too beautifully filmed and powerfully acted to dismiss.

Plot: After the events at Lake Victoria, the pre-historic school of blood-thirsty piranhas make their way into a newly opened waterpark.
Title: Piranha 3DD
Writer: Patrick Melton, Marcus Dunstan, Joel Soisson, Pete Goldfinger (characters), Josh Stolberg (characters)
Actors: Danielle Panabaker, Matt Bush, Katrina Bowden, Jean-Luc Bilodeau
tomatoConsensus: It strains to up the gore and self-awareness of it predecessor, and -- despite some game celebrity cameos -- the result is a dispiriting echo of 2010's horror-comedy.

Plot: A burgeoning stand-up comedian struggles with the stress of a stalled career, a stale relationship, and the wild spurts of severe sleepwalking he is desperate to ignore.
Title: Sleepwalk with Me
Writer: Mike Birbiglia (screenplay), Ira Glass (screenplay), Joe Birbiglia (screenplay), Seth Barrish (screenplay), Mike Birbiglia (based on the play "Sleepwalk With Me" by)
Actors: Mike Birbiglia, Lauren Ambrose, James Rebhorn, Carol Kane
tomatoConsensus: Laugh-out-loud funny and endearingly messy, Sleepwalk with Me overcomes its tonal inconsistencies to deliver a sweetly melancholic, amiably reassuring indie crowd-pleaser.

Plot: Two South Africans set out to discover what happened to their unlikely musical hero, the mysterious 1970s rock n roller, Rodriguez.
Title: Searching for Sugar Man
Writer: Malik Bendjelloul, Stephen 'Sugar' Segerman (article), Craig Bartholomew Strydom (article)
Actors: Stephen 'Sugar' Segerman, Dennis Coffey, Mike Theodore, Dan DiMaggio
tomatoConsensus: A fascinating portrait of a forgotten musical pioneer, Searching for Sugar Man is by turns informative and mysterious.
