Plot: A young girl buys an antique box at a yard sale, unaware that inside the collectible lives a malicious ancient spirit. The girl's father teams with his ex-wife to find a way to end the curse upon their child.
Title: The Possession
Writer: Juliet Snowden, Stiles White, Leslie Gornstein (article)
Actors: Jeffrey Dean Morgan, Kyra Sedgwick, Natasha Calis, Madison Davenport
tomatoConsensus: It may be based on a true story, but that doesn't excuse the way The Possession repeatedly falls back on hoary ghost movie clichés -- or the uninentional laughs it provides.

Plot: A couple is haunted by a supernatural presence that is unleashed during a college experiment.
Title: The Apparition
Actors: Ashley Greene, Sebastian Stan, Tom Felton, Julianna Guill
tomatoConsensus: The Apparition fails to offer anything original, isn't particularly scary, and offers so little in the way of dramatic momentum that it's more likely to put you to sleep than thrill you.

Plot: Three friends are asked to be bridesmaids at a wedding of a woman they used to ridicule back in high school.
Title: Bachelorette
Writer: Leslye Headland (screenplay), Leslye Headland (based on the play by)
Actors: Kirsten Dunst, Rebel Wilson, Lizzy Caplan, Paul Corning
tomatoConsensus: It has its moments, but Bachelorette ultimately plays it too safe with its trio of unlikable leads, betraying them with a predictably sentimental final act that undermines the bracingly honest humor preceding it.

Plot: A writer at the peak of his literary success discovers the steep price he must pay for stealing another man's work.
Title: The Words
Actors: Dennis Quaid, John Hannah, Jeremy Irons, Bradley Cooper
tomatoConsensus: Neither as clever nor as interesting as it appears to think it is, The Words maroons its talented stars in an overly complex, dramatically inert literary thriller that's ultimately a poor substitute for a good book.

Plot: Beca, a freshman at Barden University, is cajoled into joining The Bellas, her school's all-girls singing group. Injecting some much needed energy into their repertoire, The Bellas take on their male rivals in a campus competition.
Title: Pitch Perfect
Writer: Kay Cannon (screenplay), Mickey Rapkin (based on the book by)
Actors: Anna Kendrick, Skylar Astin, Ben Platt, Brittany Snow
tomatoConsensus: Pitch Perfect's plot is formulaic, but the performances are excellent and the musical numbers are toe-tapping as well.

Plot: Circumstances force a young divorcée to move back in with her parents in suburban Connecticut, where an affair with a younger guy rejuvenates her passion for life
Title: Hello I Must Be Going
Actors: Melanie Lynskey, Blythe Danner, John Rubinstein, Sara Chase
tomatoConsensus: Hello I Must Be Going offers an offbeat twist to the romance genre, a solid character study for fans of grown-up drama, and a career-making breakout vehicle for Melanie Lynskey.

Plot: In 2074, when the mob wants to get rid of someone, the target is sent into the past, where a hired gun awaits - someone like Joe - who one day learns the mob wants to 'close the loop' by sending back Joe's future self for assassination.
Title: Looper
Actors: Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Bruce Willis, Emily Blunt, Paul Dano
tomatoConsensus: As thought-provoking as it is thrilling, Looper delivers an uncommonly smart, bravely original blend of futuristic sci-fi and good old-fashioned action.

Plot: A normal Friday service at a fast food restaurant becomes interrupted by a police officer who claims an employee stole from a customer, but something more sinister is going on.
Title: Compliance
Actors: Ann Dowd, Matt Servitto, Dreama Walker, Pat Healy
tomatoConsensus: Anchored by smart, sensitive direction and strong performances, Complicance is a ripped-from-the-headlines thriller that's equal parts gripping and disturbing.

Plot: While in his teens, Donny fathered a son, Todd, and raised him as a single parent up until Todd's 18th birthday. Now, after not seeing each other for years, Todd's world comes crashing down when Donny resurfaces just before Todd's wedding.
Title: That's My Boy
Actors: Adam Sandler, Andy Samberg, Leighton Meester, Vanilla Ice
tomatoConsensus: While it does represent a new foray into raunch for the normally PG-13 Sandler, That's My Boy finds him repeating himself to diminishing effect - and dragging Andy Samberg down with him.

Plot: Set in the near future, an ex-jewel thief receives a gift from his son: a robot butler programmed to look after him. But soon the two companions try their luck as a heist team.
Title: Robot & Frank
Actors: Frank Langella, James Marsden, Liv Tyler, Peter Sarsgaard
tomatoConsensus: Led by a brilliant performance from star Frank Langella, Robot & Frank works as both a quirky indie drama and as a smart, thoughtful meditation on aging.

Plot: Alice fights alongside a resistance movement to regain her freedom from an Umbrella Corporation testing facility.
Title: Resident Evil: Retribution
Actors: Milla Jovovich, Sienna Guillory, Michelle Rodriguez, Aryana Engineer
tomatoConsensus: Resident Evil: Retribution offers everything one might reasonably expect from the fifth installment in a heavily action-dependent franchise -- which means very little beyond stylishly hollow CGI-enhanced set pieces.

Plot: A daughter tries to remedy her dysfunctional relationship with her ailing father, a decorated baseball scout by helping him in a recruiting trip which could be his last.
Title: Trouble with the Curve
Actors: Clint Eastwood, Chelcie Ross, Raymond Anthony Thomas, Ed Lauter
tomatoConsensus: Though predictable and somewhat dramatically underwhelming, Trouble with the Curve benefits from Clint Eastwood's grizzled charisma and his easy chemistry with a charming Amy Adams.

Plot: Dumped by her boyfriend just three weeks before their wedding, Lola enlists her close friends for a series of adventures she hopes will help her come to terms with approaching 30 as a single woman.
Title: Lola Versus
Actors: Greta Gerwig, Joel Kinnaman, Zoe Lister-Jones, Hamish Linklater
tomatoConsensus: It's fun to see Greta Gerwig mature her acting career but Lola Versus -- with its unpleasant characters and completely familiar script -- does not succeed as her first major leading role.

Plot: A Naval veteran arrives home from war unsettled and uncertain of his future - until he is tantalized by The Cause and its charismatic leader.
Title: The Master
Actors: Joaquin Phoenix, Price Carson, Mike Howard, Sarah Shoshana David
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 76 wins & 179 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Smart and solidly engrossing, The Master extends Paul Thomas Anderson's winning streak of challenging films for serious audiences.

Plot: In a violent, futuristic city where the police have the authority to act as judge, jury and executioner, a cop teams with a trainee to take down a gang that deals the reality-altering drug, SLO-MO.
Title: Dredd
Writer: John Wagner (characters), Carlos Ezquerra (characters), Alex Garland (screenplay)
Actors: Karl Urban, Rachel Wood, Andile Mngadi, Porteus Xandau
tomatoConsensus: Fueled by bombastic violence and impressive special effects, rooted in self-satire and deadpan humor, Dredd 3D does a remarkable job of capturing its source material's gritty spirit.

Plot: A troubled hedge fund magnate desperate to complete the sale of his trading empire makes an error that forces him to turn to an unlikely person for help.
Title: Arbitrage
Actors: Richard Gere, Susan Sarandon, Tim Roth, Brit Marling
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Arbitrage is both a tense thriller and a penetrating character study, elevated by the strength of a typically assured performance from Richard Gere.

Plot: Shot documentary-style, this film follows the daily grind of two young police officers in LA who are partners and friends, and what happens when they meet criminal forces greater than themselves.
Title: End of Watch
Actors: Jake Gyllenhaal, Michael Peña, Natalie Martinez, Anna Kendrick
tomatoConsensus: End of Watch has the energy, devotion to characters, and charismatic performances to overcome the familiar pitfalls of its genre and handheld format.

Plot: An introvert freshman is taken under the wings of two seniors who welcome him to the real world.
Title: The Perks of Being a Wallflower
Actors: Logan Lerman, Dylan McDermott, Kate Walsh, Patrick de Ledebur
tomatoConsensus: The Perks of Being a Wallflower is a heartfelt and sincere adaptation that's bolstered by strong lead performances.

Plot: A teacher lives a lonely life, all the while struggling over his son's custody. His life slowly gets better as he finds love and receives good news from his son, but his new luck is about to be brutally shattered by an innocent little lie.
Title: The Hunt
Actors: Mads Mikkelsen, Thomas Bo Larsen, Annika Wedderkopp, Lasse Fogelstrøm
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 35 wins & 64 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Anchored by Mads Mikkelsen's sympathetic performance, The Hunt asks difficult questions with the courage to pursue answers head on.

Plot: From dawn to dusk, a few hours in the shadowy life of a mystic man named Monsieur Oscar.
Title: Holy Motors
Actors: Denis Lavant, Edith Scob, Eva Mendes, Kylie Minogue
tomatoConsensus: Mesmerizingly strange and willfully perverse, Holy Motors offers an unforgettable visual feast alongside a spellbinding -- albeit unapologetically challenging -- narrative.

Plot: In the 1960s, three sisters form a girl group and soon become local sensations with major label interest, but fame becomes a challenge as the close-knit family begins to fall apart.
Title: Sparkle
Writer: Mara Brock Akil (screenplay), Joel Schumacher (story), Howard Rosenman (story)
Actors: Jordin Sparks, Whitney Houston, Derek Luke, Mike Epps
tomatoConsensus: While undeniably melodramatic and old-fashioned, Sparkle transcends its formulaic trappings thanks to Salim Akil's empathetic direction and strong performances from a committed cast.

Plot: In Istanbul, retired CIA operative Bryan Mills and his wife are taken hostage by the father of a kidnapper Mills killed while rescuing his daughter.
Title: Taken 2
Writer: Luc Besson, Robert Mark Kamen, Luc Besson (based on characters created by), Robert Mark Kamen (based on characters created by)
Actors: Liam Neeson, Maggie Grace, Famke Janssen, Leland Orser
tomatoConsensus: Taken 2 is largely bereft of the kinetic thrills -- and surprises -- that made the original a hit.

Plot: A reporter returns to his Florida home-town to investigate a case involving a death row inmate.
Title: The Paperboy
Writer: Peter Dexter (screenplay), Lee Daniels (screenplay), Peter Dexter (based on the novel by)
Actors: Zac Efron, Matthew McConaughey, Nicole Kidman, John Cusack
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 11 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Trashy and melodramatic, The Paperboy is enlivened by a strong cast and a steamy, sordid plot, but it's uneven and often veers into camp.

Plot: A young queen, who is married to an insane king, falls secretly in love with her physician - and together they start a revolution that changes a nation forever.
Title: A Royal Affair
Writer: Bodil Steensen-Leth (novel), Rasmus Heisterberg (screenplay), Nikolaj Arcel (screenplay)
Actors: Alicia Vikander, Mads Mikkelsen, Mikkel Boe Følsgaard, Trine Dyrholm
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 21 wins & 36 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A Royal Affair is a lavish and sumptuous costume drama with a juicy story to back it up.

Plot: After moving with her mother to a small town, a teenager finds that an accident happened in the house at the end of the street. Things get more complicated when she befriends a boy who was the only survivor of the accident.
Title: House at the End of the Street
Actors: Jennifer Lawrence, Max Thieriot, Elisabeth Shue, Gil Bellows
tomatoConsensus: Poorly conceived, clumsily executed, and almost completely bereft of scares, House at the End of the Street strands its talented star in a film as bland as its title.

Plot: It's 1968, and four young, talented Australian Aboriginal girls learn about love, friendship and war when their all-girl group The Sapphires entertain the US troops in Vietnam.
Title: The Sapphires
Writer: Tony Briggs (adapted from the stage play by), Tony Briggs, Keith Thompson
Actors: Tanika Lonesborough, Nioka Brennan, Lynette Narkle, Kylie Belling
tomatoConsensus: While it's plenty predictable and sentimental, The Sapphires also has an irresistible feel-good vibe, winning music and charming performances to spare.

Plot: Put in charge of his young son, Alain leaves Belgium for Antibes to live with his sister and her husband as a family. Alain's bond with Stephanie, a killer whale trainer, grows deeper after Stephanie suffers a horrible accident.
Title: Rust and Bone
Writer: Jacques Audiard (screenplay), Thomas Bidegain (screenplay), Craig Davidson (story)
Actors: Marion Cotillard, Matthias Schoenaerts, Armand Verdure, Céline Sallette
Awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 32 wins & 68 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Surging on strong performances from Marion Cotillard and Matthias Schoenaerts, Rust and Bone is as vibrant and messily unpredictable as life itself.

Plot: Legendary explorer Thor Heyerdal's epic 4,300-mile crossing of the Pacific on a balsawood raft in 1947, in an effort to prove that it was possible for South Americans to settle in Polynesia in pre-Columbian times.
Title: Kon-Tiki
Actors: Pål Sverre Hagen, Anders Baasmo Christiansen, Tobias Santelmann, Gustaf Skarsgård
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 12 wins & 13 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A well-crafted retelling of an epic true story, Kon Tiki is a throwback to old-school adventure filmmaking that's exciting and entertaining in spite of its by-the-book plotting.

Plot: The life, career and music of singer Katy Perry as we follow her on the California Dreams World Tour.
Title: Katy Perry: Part of Me
Actors: Katy Perry, Adam Marcello, Casey Hooper, Patrick Matera
tomatoConsensus: Katy Perry: Part of Me succeeds on the strengths of the pop star's genuine likability, inspiring work ethic, and dazzling stage show, even if it plays somewhat like a PR puff piece at times.

Plot: A documentary on the life, music, and legacy of Bob Marley.
Title: Marley
Actors: Bob Marley, Ziggy Marley, Jimmy Cliff, Rita Marley
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 7 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Kevin Macdonald's exhaustive, evenhanded portrait of Bob Marley offers electrifying concert footage and fascinating insights into reggae's greatest star.

Plot: Young Victor conducts a science experiment to bring his beloved dog Sparky back to life, only to face unintended, sometimes monstrous, consequences.
Title: Frankenweenie
Writer: Leonard Ripps, Tim Burton (original idea), John August (screenplay)
Actors: Catherine O'Hara, Martin Short, Martin Landau, Charlie Tahan
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 47 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Frankenweenie is an energetic stop-motion horror movie spoof with lovingly crafted visuals and a heartfelt, oddball story.

Plot: Washed-up true-crime writer Ellison Oswalt finds a box of super 8 home movies that suggest the murder he is currently researching is the work of a serial killer whose work dates back to the 1960s.
Title: Sinister
Actors: Ethan Hawke, Juliet Rylance, Fred Dalton Thompson, James Ransone
tomatoConsensus: Its plot hinges on typically implausible horror-movie behavior and recycles countless genre cliches, but Sinister delivers a surprising number of fresh, diabolical twists.

Plot: Dracula, who operates a high-end resort away from the human world, goes into overprotective mode when a boy discovers the resort and falls for the count's teen-aged daughter.
Title: Hotel Transylvania
Writer: Peter Baynham (screenplay), Robert Smigel (screenplay), Todd Durham (story), Dan Hageman (story), Kevin Hageman (story)
Actors: Adam Sandler, Andy Samberg, Selena Gomez, Kevin James
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 14 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Hotel Transylvania's buoyant, giddy tone may please children, but it might be a little too loud and thinly-scripted for older audiences.

Plot: Acting under the cover of a Hollywood producer scouting a location for a science fiction film, a CIA agent launches a dangerous operation to rescue six Americans in Tehran during the U.S. hostage crisis in Iran in 1980.
Title: Argo
Writer: Chris Terrio (screenplay), Tony Mendez (based on a selection from "The Master of Disguise" by), Joshuah Bearman (based on the Wired Magazine article "The Great Escape" by)
Actors: Ben Affleck, Bryan Cranston, Alan Arkin, John Goodman
tomatoConsensus: Tense, exciting, and often darkly comic, Argo recreates a historical event with vivid attention to detail and finely wrought characters.

Plot: A struggling screenwriter inadvertently becomes entangled in the Los Angeles criminal underworld after his oddball friends kidnap a gangster's beloved Shih Tzu.
Title: Seven Psychopaths
Actors: Michael Pitt, Michael Stuhlbarg, Sam Rockwell, Colin Farrell
tomatoConsensus: Seven Psychopaths delivers sly cinematic commentary while serving up a heaping helping of sharp dialogue and gleeful violence.

Plot: When 30-something Jesse returns to his alma mater for a professor's retirement party, he falls for Zibby, a college student, and is faced with a powerful attraction that springs up between them.
Title: Liberal Arts
Actors: Josh Radnor, Elizabeth Olsen, Richard Jenkins, Allison Janney
tomatoConsensus: While it's hard not to wish it had a little more bite, Liberal Arts ultimately succeeds as a good-natured -- and surprisingly clever -- look at the addictive pull of nostalgia for our youth.

Plot: An examination of a failure of justice in the case against the West Memphis Three.
Title: West of Memphis
Actors: Michael Baden, Jason Baldwin, Holly Ballard, Jamie Clark Ballard
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 9 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Both a sobering look at a true crime story and a scathing indictment of the American justice system, West of Memphis is a real-life horror story told with fury and compassion.

Plot: The story of two coalitions -- ACT UP and TAG (Treatment Action Group) -- whose activism and innovation turned AIDS from a death sentence into a manageable condition.
Title: How to Survive a Plague
Writer: David France, Woody Richman, Tyler H. Walk
Actors: Ed Koch, David Barr, Bob Rafsky, Jim Eigo
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 13 wins & 18 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Angry, powerful, and stirring, How to Survive a Plague is a brilliantly constructed documentary about the activists who pushed for action to combat the AIDS epidemic.

Plot: As single mom Grace juggles work, bills, and her affair with a married doctor, her daughter, Ansiedad, plots a shortcut to adulthood after finding inspiration in the coming-of-age stories she's reading for school.
Title: Girl in Progress
Actors: Eva Mendes, Matthew Modine, Cierra Ramirez, Patricia Arquette
tomatoConsensus: Despite a well-intentioned and novel premise, Girl in Progress is plagued by jarring tonal shifts and does little to break its characters out of cliché.

Plot: Director Michael Apted revisits the same group of British-born adults after a 7 year wait. The subjects are interviewed as to the changes that have occurred in their lives during the last seven years.
Title: 56 Up
Actors: Michael Apted, Bruce Balden, Jacqueline Bassett, Symon Basterfield
tomatoConsensus: Director Michael Apted continues to utilize cinema as a window into the lives of everyday people, and in the reflection of this documentary we can glimpse our own aging humanity.

Plot: It has been five years since the disappearance of Katie and Hunter, and a suburban family witness strange events in their neighborhood when a woman and a mysterious child move in.
Title: Paranormal Activity 4
Writer: Christopher Landon (screenplay), Chad Feehan (story), Oren Peli (film "Paranormal Activity")
Actors: Katie Featherston, Kathryn Newton, Matt Shively, Aiden Lovekamp
tomatoConsensus: While it does manage to wring a few more screams out of the franchise's surprisingly durable premise, Paranormal Activity 4 provides fans of the series with dismayingly diminishing returns.

Plot: After failing to get his wife pregnant, a guy (Schneider) recruits his pals to steal the deposit he left at a sperm bank years ago.
Title: The Babymakers
Actors: Paul Schneider, Olivia Munn, Michael Yurchak, Wood Harris
tomatoConsensus: The Babymakers mistakes raunch for humor and, despite a few sporadic laughs, wastes its otherwise capable cast on gross-out gags and misfired one-liners.

Plot: A homicide detective is pushed to the brink of his moral and physical limits as he tangles with a ferociously skilled hired killer who specializes in torture and pain.
Title: Alex Cross
Writer: Marc Moss (screenplay), Kerry Williamson (screenplay), James Patterson (based on the novel "Cross" by)
Actors: Tyler Perry, Edward Burns, Matthew Fox, Jean Reno
tomatoConsensus: Tyler Perry and Matthew Fox do their best, but they're trampled by Rob Cohen's frustrating direction and a tasteless, lazily written screenplay.

Plot: An exploration of how the actions of individual lives impact one another in the past, present and future, as one soul is shaped from a killer into a hero, and an act of kindness ripples across centuries to inspire a revolution.
Title: Cloud Atlas
Writer: David Mitchell (novel), Lana Wachowski (written for the screen by), Tom Tykwer (written for the screen by), Lilly Wachowski (written for the screen by)
Director: Tom Tykwer, Lana Wachowski, Lilly Wachowski
Actors: Tom Hanks, Halle Berry, Jim Broadbent, Hugo Weaving
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 16 wins & 72 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Its sprawling, ambitious blend of thought-provoking narrative and eye-catching visuals will prove too unwieldy for some, but the sheer size and scope of Cloud Atlas are all but impossible to ignore.

Plot: When her adoptive father disappears, Sharon Da Silva is drawn into a strange and terrifying alternate reality that holds answers to the horrific nightmares that have plagued her since childhood.
Title: Silent Hill: Revelation 3D
Actors: Adelaide Clemens, Kit Harington, Carrie-Anne Moss, Sean Bean
tomatoConsensus: Mediocre effort even by the standards of video game adaptations, Silent Hill: Revelation 3D features weak characters and an incomprehensible plot with a shortage of scares.

Plot: When young Jay Moriarity discovers that the mythic Mavericks surf break, one of the biggest waves on Earth, exists just miles from his Santa Cruz home, he enlists the help of local legend Frosty Hesson to train him to survive it.
Title: Chasing Mavericks
Writer: Kario Salem (screenplay), Jim Meenaghan (story), Brandon Hooper (story)
Actors: Gerard Butler, Jonny Weston, Elisabeth Shue, Abigail Spencer
tomatoConsensus: It's sweet, gentle, and affably modest, but Chasing Mavericks is ultimately pulled under by an unconvincing script and a puzzling lack of energy.

Plot: A high school biology teacher looks to become a successful mixed-martial arts fighter in an effort to raise money to prevent extra-curricular activities from being axed at his cash-strapped school.
Title: Here Comes the Boom
Actors: Kevin James, Salma Hayek, Henry Winkler, Greg Germann
tomatoConsensus: Here Comes the Boom benefits from Kevin James's genial presence but the film doesn't deliver enough laughs to live up to its title -- or enough satisfying plot to make up the difference.

Plot: Jackie Cogan is an enforcer hired to restore order after three dumb guys rob a Mob protected card game, causing the local criminal economy to collapse.
Title: Killing Them Softly
Writer: Andrew Dominik (screenplay), George V. Higgins (based on the novel "Cogan's Trade" by)
Actors: Brad Pitt, Scoot McNairy, Ben Mendelsohn, James Gandolfini
tomatoConsensus: Killing Them Softly is a darkly comic, visceral thriller that doubles as a cautionary tale on capitalism, whose message is delivered with sledgehammer force.

Plot: A documentary centered on a young man in Spain who claims to a grieving Texas family that he is their 16-year-old son who has been missing for 3 years.
Title: The Imposter
Actors: Nicholas Barclay, Carey Gibson, Bryan Gibson, Beverly Dollarhide
Awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 11 wins & 29 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despite its true-crime trappings, The Imposter is an utterly gripping and sometimes heartbreaking documentary thriller cleverly told with narrative flair.

Plot: A man in an iron lung who wishes to lose his virginity contacts a professional sex surrogate with the help of his therapist and priest.
Title: The Sessions
Writer: Ben Lewin (written for the screen by), Mark O'Brien (article)
Actors: John Hawkes, Helen Hunt, William H. Macy, Moon Bloodgood
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 18 wins & 63 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Tender, funny, and touching, The Sessions provides an acting showcase for its talented stars and proves it's possible for Hollywood to produce a grown-up movie about sex.

Plot: A video game villain wants to be a hero and sets out to fulfill his dream, but his quest brings havoc to the whole arcade where he lives.
Title: Wreck-It Ralph
Writer: Rich Moore (story by), Phil Johnston (story by), Jim Reardon (story by), Phil Johnston (screenplay), Jennifer Lee (screenplay), John C. Reilly (additional story material by), Sam Levine (additional story material by), Jared Stern (additional story material by)
Actors: John C. Reilly, Sarah Silverman, Jack McBrayer, Jane Lynch
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 33 wins & 40 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Equally entertaining for both kids and parents old enough to catch the references, Wreck-It Ralph is a clever, colorful adventure built on familiar themes and joyful nostalgia.

Plot: After a stint in a mental institution, former teacher Pat Solitano moves back in with his parents and tries to reconcile with his ex-wife. Things get more challenging when Pat meets Tiffany, a mysterious girl with problems of her own.
Title: Silver Linings Playbook
Actors: Bradley Cooper, Jennifer Lawrence, Robert De Niro, Jacki Weaver
tomatoConsensus: Silver Linings Playbook walks a tricky thematic tightrope, but David O. Russell's sensitive direction and some sharp work from a talented cast gives it true balance.

Plot: An airline pilot saves almost all his passengers on his malfunctioning airliner which eventually crashed, but an investigation into the accident reveals something troubling.
Title: Flight
Actors: Nadine Velazquez, Denzel Washington, Carter Cabassa, Adam C. Edwards
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 16 wins & 41 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Robert Zemeckis makes a triumphant return to live-action cinema with Flight, a thoughtful and provocative character study propelled by a compelling performance from Denzel Washington.

Plot: In late-19th-century Russian high society, St. Petersburg aristocrat Anna Karenina enters into a life-changing affair with the dashing Count Alexei Vronsky.
Title: Anna Karenina
Actors: Matthew Macfadyen, Eric MacLennan, Kelly Macdonald, Theo Morrissey
tomatoConsensus: Joe Wright's energetic adaptation of Tolstoy's classic romance is a bold, visually stylized work -- for both better and worse.

Plot: A young man who survives a disaster at sea is hurtled into an epic journey of adventure and discovery. While cast away, he forms an unexpected connection with another survivor: a fearsome Bengal tiger.
Language: English, Tamil, French, Japanese, Hindi, Chinese
Title: Life of Pi
Actors: Suraj Sharma, Irrfan Khan, Ayush Tandon, Gautam Belur
tomatoConsensus: A 3D adaptation of a supposedly "unfilmable" book, Ang Lee's Life of Pi achieves the near impossible -- it's an astonishing technical achievement that's also emotionally rewarding.

Plot: On the hunt for a fabled treasure of gold, a band of warriors, assassins, and a rogue British soldier descend upon a village in feudal China, where a humble blacksmith looks to defend himself and his fellow villagers.
Title: The Man with the Iron Fists
Actors: RZA, Rick Yune, Russell Crowe, Lucy Liu
tomatoConsensus: Messy kung-fu homage The Man with the Iron Fists demonstrates a slavish affection for the genre it mimics, for better or worse.

Plot: Two determined mothers­, one a teacher, look to transform their children's failing inner city school. Facing a powerful and entrenched bureaucracy, they risk everything to make a difference in the education and future of their children.
Title: Won't Back Down
Actors: Maggie Gyllenhaal, Viola Davis, Oscar Isaac, Holly Hunter
tomatoConsensus: Despite the best efforts of its talented leads, Won't Back Down fails to lend sufficient dramatic heft or sophistication to the hot-button issue of education reform.

Plot: Chaos breaks out in a small Maryland town after an ecological disaster occurs.
Title: The Bay
Writer: Michael Wallach (screenplay), Barry Levinson (story by), Michael Wallach (story by)
Actors: Nansi Aluka, Christopher Denham, Stephen Kunken, Frank Deal
tomatoConsensus: Barry Levinson's eco-horror flick cleverly utilizes familiar found-footage methods in service of a gruesome yet atmospheric chiller.

Plot: Members of a world-renowned string quartet struggle to stay together in the face of death, competing egos and insuppressible lust.
Title: A Late Quartet
Writer: Seth Grossman (screenplay), Yaron Zilberman (screenplay), Yaron Zilberman (story)
Actors: Catherine Keener, Christopher Walken, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Mark Ivanir
tomatoConsensus: An outstanding ensemble cast lends weight and depth to A Late Quartet's melodramatic script, and the result is insightful and emotionally satisfying.

Plot: Georges and Anne are an octogenarian couple. They are cultivated, retired music teachers. Their daughter, also a musician, lives in Britain with her family. One day, Anne has a stroke, and the couple's bond of love is severely tested.
Title: Amour
Actors: Jean-Louis Trintignant, Emmanuelle Riva, Isabelle Huppert, Alexandre Tharaud
tomatoConsensus: With towering performances and an unflinching script from Michael Haneke, Amour represents an honest, heartwrenching depiction of deep love and responsibility.

Plot: Amidst financial crises and unprecedented public school budget cuts, Brooklyn Castle takes an intimate look at the challenges and triumphs facing members of a junior high school's champion chess team.
Title: Brooklyn Castle
Actors: Je'Daiah Ballantyne, Michelle Ballantyne, Rochelle Ballantyne, Pamela Ballard
tomatoConsensus: Brooklyn Castle is a warm, engaging, and even uplifting documentary about chess-playing whiz kids.

Plot: An investigative documentary about the epidemic of rape of soldiers within the US military.
Title: The Invisible War
Writer: Kirby Dick, Amy Ziering (additional writer), Douglas Blush (additional writer)
Actors: Amy Ziering, Kirby Dick, Kori Cioca, Jessica Hinves
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 13 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Invisible War is a vital and frank expose on sexual assault in the U.S. military, shot by master filmmaker Kirby Dick (This Film is Not Yet Rated).

Plot: After the birth of Renesmee, the Cullens gather other vampire clans in order to protect the child from a false allegation that puts the family in front of the Volturi.
Title: The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn - Part 2
Actors: Kristen Stewart, Robert Pattinson, Taylor Lautner, Peter Facinelli
tomatoConsensus: It's the most entertaining Twilight, but that's not enough to make Breaking Dawn Part 2 worth watching for filmgoers who don't already count themselves among the franchise converts.

Plot: A group of teenagers look to save their town from an invasion of North Korean soldiers.
Title: Red Dawn
Writer: Carl Ellsworth (screenplay), Jeremy Passmore (screenplay), Kevin Reynolds, John Milius, Kevin Reynolds (story)
Actors: Chris Hemsworth, Josh Peck, Josh Hutcherson, Adrianne Palicki
tomatoConsensus: The rebooted Red Dawn lacks the original's topicality, but at least pays tribute in delivering the same short shrift to character development and general logic.

Plot: When the evil spirit Pitch launches an assault on Earth, the Immortal Guardians team up to protect the innocence of children all around the world.
Title: Rise of the Guardians
Actors: Chris Pine, Alec Baldwin, Jude Law, Isla Fisher
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 14 wins & 30 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A sort of Avengers for the elementary school set, Rise of the Guardians is wonderfully animated and briskly paced, but it's only so-so in the storytelling department.

Plot: Residents of a coastal town learn, with deathly consequences, the secret shared by the two mysterious women who have sought shelter at a local resort.
Title: Byzantium
Actors: Saoirse Ronan, Barry Cassin, Gemma Arterton, David Heap
tomatoConsensus: Director Neil Jordan remains as expert as ever when it comes to setting a chilling mood, but Byzantium struggles to match its creepily alluring atmosphere with a suitably compelling story.

Plot: Emily arrives in Miami with aspirations to become a professional dancer. She sparks with Sean, the leader of a dance crew whose neighborhood is threatened by Emily's father's development plans.
Title: Step Up Revolution
Actors: Cleopatra Coleman, Ryan Guzman, Misha Gabriel Hamilton, Michael 'Xeno' Langebeck
tomatoConsensus: Step Up Revolution treads familiar territory by surrounding its lively and kinetic dance sequences with a predictably generic story.

Plot: The relationship between Alfred Hitchcock and his wife Alma Reville during the filming of Psycho (1960) in 1959 is explored.
Title: Hitchcock
Actors: Anthony Hopkins, Helen Mirren, Scarlett Johansson, Danny Huston
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 27 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though it suffers from tonal inconsistency and a lack of truly insightful retrospection, Hitchcock is elevated by inspired performances from its two distinguished leads.

Plot: A reluctant hobbit, Bilbo Baggins, sets out to the Lonely Mountain with a spirited group of dwarves to reclaim their mountain home - and the gold within it - from the dragon Smaug.
Title: The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey
Writer: Fran Walsh (screenplay), Philippa Boyens (screenplay), Peter Jackson (screenplay), Guillermo del Toro (screenplay), J.R.R. Tolkien (novel)
Actors: Ian McKellen, Martin Freeman, Richard Armitage, Ken Stott
Awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 70 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Peter Jackson's return to Middle-earth is an earnest, visually resplendent trip, but the film's deliberate pace robs the material of some of its majesty.

Plot: The story of the love affair between FDR and his distant cousin Margaret "Daisy" Suckley, centered around the weekend in 1939 when the King and Queen of the United Kingdom visited upstate New York.
Title: Hyde Park on Hudson
Actors: Bill Murray, Laura Linney, Samuel West, Olivia Colman
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Though bolstered by a thoroughly charming performance by Bill Murray in the central role, Hyde Park on Hudson is an FDR biopic that lets down both its audience and its subject.

Plot: A chronicle of the decade-long hunt for al-Qaeda terrorist leader Osama bin Laden after the September 2001 attacks, and his death at the hands of the Navy S.E.A.L.s Team 6 in May 2011.
Title: Zero Dark Thirty
Actors: Jason Clarke, Reda Kateb, Jessica Chastain, Kyle Chandler
tomatoConsensus: Gripping, suspenseful, and brilliantly crafted, Zero Dark Thirty dramatizes the hunt for Osama bin Laden with intelligence and an eye for detail.

Plot: A former sports star who's fallen on hard times starts coaching his son's soccer team as a way to get his life together. His attempts to become an adult are met with challenges from the attractive soccer moms who pursue him at every turn.
Title: Playing for Keeps
Actors: Gerard Butler, Jessica Biel, Noah Lomax, Dennis Quaid
tomatoConsensus: Witless, unfocused, and arguably misogynistic, Playing for Keeps is a dispiriting, lowest-common-denominator Hollywood rom-com.

Plot: As inventor Andy Brewster is about to embark on the road trip of a lifetime, a quick stop at his mom's house turns into an unexpected cross-country voyage with her along for the ride.
Title: The Guilt Trip
Actors: Barbra Streisand, Seth Rogen, Julene Renee, Zabryna Guevara
tomatoConsensus: Seth Rogen and Barbra Streisand have enough chemistry to drive a solidly assembled comedy; unfortunately, The Guilt Trip has a lemon of a script and is perilously low on comedic fuel.

Plot: A homicide investigator digs deeper into a case involving a trained military sniper who shot five random victims.
Title: Jack Reacher
Writer: Lee Child (based on the book "One Shot" by), Christopher McQuarrie (written for the screen by)
Actors: Tom Cruise, Rosamund Pike, Richard Jenkins, David Oyelowo
tomatoConsensus: Jack Reacher is an above-average crime thriller with a smoothly charismatic performance from Tom Cruise.

Plot: With the help of a German bounty hunter, a freed slave sets out to rescue his wife from a brutal Mississippi plantation owner.
Title: Django Unchained
Actors: Jamie Foxx, Christoph Waltz, Leonardo DiCaprio, Kerry Washington
tomatoConsensus: Bold, bloody, and stylistically daring, Django Unchained is another incendiary masterpiece from Quentin Tarantino.

Plot: Pete and Debbie are both about to turn 40, their kids hate each other, both of their businesses are failing, they're on the verge of losing their house, and their relationship is threatening to fall apart.
Title: This Is 40
Writer: Judd Apatow, Judd Apatow (based on characters created by)
Actors: Paul Rudd, Leslie Mann, Maude Apatow, Iris Apatow
tomatoConsensus: Judd Apatow definitely delivers funny and perceptive scenes in This is 40, even if they are buried in aimless self-indulgence.

Plot: The story of a tourist family in Thailand caught in the destruction and chaotic aftermath of the 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami.
Title: The Impossible
Actors: Naomi Watts, Ewan McGregor, Tom Holland, Samuel Joslin
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 27 wins & 65 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The screenplay isn't quite as powerful as the direction or the acting, but with such an astonishing real-life story at its center, The Impossible is never less than compelling.

Plot: In 19th-century France, Jean Valjean, who for decades has been hunted by the ruthless policeman Javert after breaking parole, agrees to care for a factory worker's daughter. The decision changes their lives forever.
Title: Les Misérables
Writer: William Nicholson (screenplay), Alain Boublil (screenplay), Claude-Michel Schönberg (screenplay), Herbert Kretzmer (screenplay), Alain Boublil (stage musical "Les Misérables"), Claude-Michel Schönberg (stage musical "Les Misérables"), Victor Hugo (novel)
Actors: Hugh Jackman, Russell Crowe, Anne Hathaway, Amanda Seyfried
tomatoConsensus: Impeccably mounted but occasionally bombastic, Les Misérables largely succeeds thanks to bravura performances from its distinguished cast.

Plot: Set in suburban New Jersey the 1960s, a group of friends form a rock band and try to make it big.
Title: Not Fade Away
Actors: John Magaro, Jack Huston, Will Brill, Brahm Vaccarella
tomatoConsensus: Exuberant and bittersweet, Not Fade Away is a coming-of-age story set to a British Invasion beat that occasionally meanders but mostly charms.

Plot: At a home for retired musicians, the annual concert to celebrate Verdi's birthday is disrupted by the arrival of Jean, an eternal diva and the former wife of one of the residents.
Title: Quartet
Actors: Maggie Smith, Tom Courtenay, Billy Connolly, Pauline Collins
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 4 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It's sweet, gentle, and predictable to a fault, but Dustin Hoffman's affectionate direction and the talented cast's amiable charm make Quartet too difficult to resist.

Plot: Artie and Diane agree to look after their three grandkids when their type-A helicopter parents need to leave town for work. Problems arise when the kids' 21st-century behavior collides with Artie and Diane's old-school methods.
Title: Parental Guidance
Actors: Billy Crystal, Bette Midler, Marisa Tomei, Tom Everett Scott
tomatoConsensus: Parental Guidance is sweet but milquetoast, an inoffensive trifle that's blandly predictable.

Plot: A new street drug that sends its users across time and dimensions has one drawback: some people return as no longer human. Can two college dropouts save humankind from this silent, otherworldly invasion?
Title: John Dies at the End
Writer: Don Coscarelli (written for the screen by), David Wong (based on the story by)
Actors: Chase Williamson, Rob Mayes, Paul Giamatti, Clancy Brown
tomatoConsensus: Some will find the darkly funny, genre-bending incoherence of John Dies at the End charming; some will feel its zany antics and gore lead to an unsatisfying payoff.

Plot: A man who escapes from the vicious grips of the serial killer known as "The Collector" is blackmailed to rescue an innocent girl from the killer's booby-trapped warehouse.
Title: The Collection
Writer: Patrick Melton, Marcus Dunstan, Patrick Melton (characters), Marcus Dunstan (characters)
Actors: Josh Stewart, Emma Fitzpatrick, Christopher McDonald, Lee Tergesen
tomatoConsensus: The Collection offers more grisly thrills and twisted humor than its predecessor; in other words, fun for genre fans, but unpleasant for anyone else.

Plot: A documentary that explores the question: In the age of manscaping, metrosexuals, and grooming products galore - what does it mean to be a man?
Title: Mansome
Actors: Jason Bateman, Will Arnett, Isaiah Mustafa, Brett McKay
tomatoConsensus: Mansome is a threadbare documentary with little insight into modern male maintenance, with useless celebrity interviews padding an already slim runtime.

Plot: A salesman for a natural gas company experiences life-changing events after arriving in a small town, where his corporation wants to tap into the available resources.
Title: Promised Land
Writer: John Krasinski (screenplay), Matt Damon (screenplay), Dave Eggers (story)
Actors: Matt Damon, Benjamin Sheeler, Terry Kinney, Carla Bianco
tomatoConsensus: The earnest and well-intentioned Promised Land sports a likable cast, but it also suffers from oversimplified characterizations and a frustrating final act.

Plot: A hardened detective in the Flying Squad of London's Metropolitan police. Based on the '70s UK TV show.
Title: The Sweeney
Writer: Nick Love, John Hodge, Ian Kennedy Martin (source material)
Actors: Ray Winstone, Plan B, Hayley Atwell, Steven Mackintosh
tomatoConsensus: Ray Winstone exudes tough-guy bravado, but this cop thriller otherwise feels thoroughly generic.

Plot: A former Weather Underground activist goes on the run from a journalist who has discovered his identity.
Title: The Company You Keep
Writer: Lem Dobbs (screenplay), Neil Gordon (based on the novel by)
Actors: Robert Redford, Shia LaBeouf, Julie Christie, Susan Sarandon
tomatoConsensus: The Company You Keep is a (frustratingly) slow-burning thriller about very contemporary issues.

Plot: After twenty years in prison, Foley is finished with the grifter's life. When he meets an elusive young woman named Iris, the possibility of a new start looks real. But his past is proving to be a stubborn companion.
Title: The Samaritan
Actors: Samuel L. Jackson, Luke Kirby, Ruth Negga, A.C. Peterson
tomatoConsensus: The Samaritan is a ludicrous neo-noir starring a seemingly bored Samuel L. Jackson.

Plot: The story of Richard Kuklinski, the notorious contract killer and family man. When finally arrested in 1986, neither his wife nor daughters have any clue about his real profession.
Title: The Iceman
Writer: Morgan Land (screenplay), Ariel Vromen (screenplay), Anthony Bruno (book), Jim Thebaut (documentary "The Iceman Tapes: Conversations with a Killer")
Actors: Michael Shannon, Winona Ryder, Chris Evans, Ray Liotta
tomatoConsensus: While it deserved stronger direction and a more fully realized script, Michael Shannon's riveting performance in the title role is more than enough to make The Iceman recommended viewing.

Plot: A look at the lives of two teenage girls - inseparable friends Ginger and Rosa -- growing up in 1960s London as the Cuban Missile Crisis looms, and the pivotal event that comes to redefine their relationship.
Title: Ginger & Rosa
Actors: Christina Hendricks, Jodhi May, Alessandro Nivola, Luke Cloud
tomatoConsensus: Elle Fanning gives a terrific performance in this powerful coming-of-age tale about a pair of teenage girls whose friendship is unnerved by the threat of nuclear war.

Plot: Set in 1990s Belfast, an active member of the IRA becomes an informant for MI5 in order to protect her son's welfare.
Title: Shadow Dancer
Writer: Tom Bradby (screenplay), Tom Bradby (based on the novel by)
Actors: Barry Barnes, Maria Laird, Ben Smyth, Brid Brennan
tomatoConsensus: A tense, thought-provoking thriller, Shadow Dancer is bolstered by sensitive direction from James Marsh and a terrific performance from Andrea Riseborough.

Plot: Four couples meet for Sunday brunch only to discover they are stuck in a house together as the world may be about to end.
Title: It's a Disaster
Actors: Rachel Boston, Kevin M. Brennan, David Cross, America Ferrera
tomatoConsensus: A clever black comedy, It's a Disaster is sometimes uneven but the sharp writing and stellar ensemble cast keeps the film on track.

Plot: In Manhattan, film-maker Erik bonds with closeted lawyer Paul after a fling. As their relationship becomes one fueled by highs, lows, and dysfunctional patterns, Erik struggles to negotiate his own boundaries while being true to himself.
Title: Keep the Lights On
Actors: Thure Lindhardt, Zachary Booth, Marilyn Neimark, Paprika Steen
tomatoConsensus: Keep the Lights On is a mysterious, sexy journey deep into the love affair of two men that always manages to stay true to life.

Plot: A pair of aging stickup men try to get the old gang back together for one last hurrah before one of the guys takes his last assignment - to kill his comrade.
Title: Stand Up Guys
Actors: Al Pacino, Christopher Walken, Alan Arkin, Julianna Margulies
tomatoConsensus: Stand Up Guys largely wastes its talented cast in a resolutely mediocre comedy hampered by messy direction and a perfunctory script.

Plot: In Uganda, a new bill threatens to make homosexuality punishable by death. David Kato - Uganda's first openly gay man - and his fellow activists work against the clock to defeat the ...
Title: Call Me Kuchu
Actors: David Kato, Christopher Senyonjo
tomatoConsensus: Alternately horrific and uplifting, Call Me Kuchu exposes heinous systematic brutality with a clear eye and admirable precision.

Plot: A documentary featuring interviews with all surviving former heads of Shin Bet, the Israeli security agency whose activities and membership are closely held state secrets.
Title: The Gatekeepers
Actors: Ami Ayalon, Avi Dichter, Yuval Diskin, Carmi Gillon
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 10 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Strikingly stark, brutally honest, and rivetingly assembled, The Gatekeepers offers essential perspective on a seemingly intractable war from some of the men who fought it.

Plot: As the Japanese surrender at the end of WWII, Gen. Fellers is tasked with deciding if Emperor Hirohito will be hanged as a war criminal. Influencing his ruling is his quest to find Aya, an exchange student he met years earlier in the U.S.
Title: Emperor
Writer: Vera Blasi (screenplay), David Klass (screenplay), Shiro Okamoto (book)
Actors: Matthew Fox, Tommy Lee Jones, Eriko Hatsune, Toshiyuki Nishida
tomatoConsensus: Despite a typically strong performance from Tommy Lee Jones, Emperor does little with its fascinating historical palate, and is instead bogged down in a cliched romantic subplot.

Plot: A documentary shot in the North Atlantic and focused on the commercial fishing industry.
Title: Leviathan
Actors: Brian Jannelle, Adrian Guillette, Arthur Smith, Asterias Vulgaris
tomatoConsensus: It moves to its own inscrutable rhythm, but for filmgoers willing to immerse themselves, Leviathan proves a one-of-a-kind viewing experience.

Plot: Four college girls hold up a restaurant in order to fund their spring break vacation. While partying, drinking, and taking drugs, they are arrested, only to be bailed out by a drug and arms dealer.
Title: Spring Breakers
Actors: James Franco, Selena Gomez, Vanessa Hudgens, Ashley Benson
tomatoConsensus: Spring Breakers blends stinging social commentary with bikini cheesecake and a bravura James Franco performance.

Plot: Two teenage brothers must face their own prejudices head on if they are to survive the perils of being British Arabs growing up on the streets of gangland London.
Title: My Brother the Devil
Actors: James Floyd, Fady Elsayed, Anthony Welsh, Amira Ghazalla
tomatoConsensus: A tough, tender tale of familial angst with careful attention to detail, My Brother the Devil is a strong debut from director Sally El Hosaini.

Plot: A motorcycle stunt rider turns to robbing banks as a way to provide for his lover and their newborn child, a decision that puts him on a collision course with an ambitious rookie cop navigating a department ruled by a corrupt detective.
Title: The Place Beyond the Pines
Writer: Derek Cianfrance (story), Ben Coccio (story), Derek Cianfrance (screenplay), Ben Coccio (screenplay), Darius Marder (screenplay)
Actors: Ryan Gosling, Craig Van Hook, Eva Mendes, Olga Merediz
tomatoConsensus: Ambitious to a fault, The Place Beyond the Pines finds writer/director Derek Cianfrance reaching for -- and often grasping -- thorny themes of family, fatherhood, and fate.

Plot: After falling in love in Paris, Marina and Neil come to Oklahoma, where problems arise. Their church's Spanish-born pastor struggles with his faith, while Neil encounters a woman from his childhood.
Language: English, French, Spanish, Italian, Sign Languages, Russian
Title: To the Wonder
Actors: Ben Affleck, Olga Kurylenko, Rachel McAdams, Javier Bardem
tomatoConsensus: To the Wonder demonstrates Terrence Malick's gift for beautiful images, but its narrative is overly somber and emotionally unsatisfying.

Plot: A hairdresser who has lost her hair to cancer finds out her husband is having an affair, travels to Italy for her daughter's wedding and meets a widower who still blames the world for the loss of his wife.
Title: Love Is All You Need
Writer: Anders Thomas Jensen (screenplay), Susanne Bier (story), Anders Thomas Jensen (story)
Actors: Trine Dyrholm, Stina Ekblad, Sebastian Jessen, Molly Blixt Egelind
tomatoConsensus: Undeniably slight and fluffy, Love Is All You Need is redeemed by its picturesque setting and warm performances by Pierce Brosnan and Trine Dyrholm.

Plot: A drama centered on a group of people searching for human connections in today's wired world.
Title: Disconnect
Actors: Jason Bateman, Hope Davis, Frank Grillo, Michael Nyqvist
tomatoConsensus: It's didactic in spots and melodramatic in others, but Disconnect's strong cast helps make it a timely, effective exploration of modern society's technological overload.

Plot: A documentary on the 1970s punk trio Death, and their new-found popularity decades after they disbanded.
Title: A Band Called Death
Actors: Dannis Hackney, Bobby Hackney, David Hackney, Robbie Duncan
tomatoConsensus: A Band Called Death is not only a fascinating portrait of a pioneering rock group, but also a tribute to family ties and perseverance in the face of hardship.

Plot: Two young boys encounter a fugitive and form a pact to help him evade the vigilantes that are on his trail and to reunite him with his true love.
Title: Mud
Actors: Matthew McConaughey, Reese Witherspoon, Tye Sheridan, Jacob Lofland
tomatoConsensus: Bolstered by a strong performance from Matthew McConaughey in the title role, Mud offers an engaging Southern drama that manages to stay sweet and heartwarming without being sappy.

Plot: A film that excavates layers of myth and memory to find the elusive truth at the core of a family of storytellers.
Title: Stories We Tell
Actors: Michael Polley, Harry Gulkin, Susy Buchan, John Buchan
tomatoConsensus: In Stories We Tell, Sarah Polley plays with the documentary format to explore the nature of memory and storytelling, crafting a thoughtful, compelling narrative that unfolds like a mystery.

Plot: A story that follows a New York woman (who doesn't really have an apartment), apprentices for a dance company (though she's not really a dancer), and throws herself headlong into her dreams, even as their possibility dwindles.
Title: Frances Ha
Actors: Greta Gerwig, Mickey Sumner, Michael Esper, Adam Driver
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 43 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Audiences will need to tolerate a certain amount of narrative drift, but thanks to sensitive direction from Noah Baumbach and an endearing performance from Greta Gerwig, Frances Ha makes it easy to forgive.

Plot: Heidi, a radio DJ, is sent a box containing a record - a "gift from the Lords". The sounds within the grooves trigger flashbacks of her town's violent past. Is Heidi going mad, or are the Lords back to take revenge on Salem, Massachusetts?
Title: The Lords of Salem
Actors: Sheri Moon Zombie, Bruce Davison, Jeff Daniel Phillips, Judy Geeson
tomatoConsensus: The Lords of Salem has lots of atmospheric portent, but it's unfortunately short on scares.

Plot: A sound engineer's work for an Italian horror studio becomes a terrifying case of life imitating art.
Title: Berberian Sound Studio
Actors: Toby Jones, Cosimo Fusco, Antonio Mancino, Fatma Mohamed
tomatoConsensus: Its reach may exceed its grasp, but with Berberian Sound Studio, director Peter Strickland assembles a suitably twisted, creepy tribute to the Italian Giallo horror movies of the '70s that benefits from a strong central performance by Toby Jones.

Plot: A modern retelling of Shakespeare's classic comedy about two pairs of lovers with different takes on romance and a way with words.
Title: Much Ado About Nothing
Writer: Joss Whedon (written for the screen by), William Shakespeare (play)
Actors: Amy Acker, Alexis Denisof, Nathan Fillion, Clark Gregg
tomatoConsensus: Lighthearted to a fault, Much Ado About Nothing's giddy energy and intimate charm make for an entertaining romantic comedy -- and a Shakespearean adaptation that's hard to resist.

Plot: An elderly couple fight against local authorities in rural New Brunswick to build their final home.
Title: Still Mine
Actors: James Cromwell, Chuck Shamata, Geneviève Bujold, Ronan Rees
tomatoConsensus: James Cromwell and Geneviève Bujold are outstanding in this tender, affecting, insightful drama about the bonds and sacrifices of marriage.

Plot: A young Pakistani man is chasing corporate success on Wall Street. He finds himself embroiled in a conflict between his American Dream, a hostage crisis, and the enduring call of his family's homeland.
Title: The Reluctant Fundamentalist
Writer: Javed Akhtar (eulogy in urdu), Ami Boghani (screen story), Mohsin Hamid (novel), Mohsin Hamid (screen story), William Wheeler (screenplay)
Actors: Riz Ahmed, Kate Hudson, Liev Schreiber, Kiefer Sutherland
tomatoConsensus: The Reluctant Fundamentalist is technically proficient, with solid acting and cinematography, but its message is so ambitious and heavy-handed that some of its power is robbed.

Plot: A documentary that investigates incidents of hunger experienced by millions of Americans, and proposed solutions to the problem.
Title: A Place at the Table
Actors: Adam Appelhanz, David Beckmann, Joel Berg, William Booker
tomatoConsensus: A Place at the Table is a well-reported documentary that raises important questions about the state of hunger in America culture.

Plot: As he helps a young artist with her upcoming exhibition, the owner of a mannequin shop's deadly, suppressed desires come to the surface.
Title: Maniac
Writer: Alexandre Aja (screenplay), Grégory Levasseur (screenplay), Joe Spinell (original screenplay)
Actors: Nora Arnezeder, Brian Ames, America Olivo, Genevieve Alexandra
tomatoConsensus: Shocking and bloody. Maniac is smarter than your average psychological slasher, but it's often undermined by its excessive gore.

Plot: In New York City, a young girl is caught in the middle of her parents' bitter custody battle.
Title: What Maisie Knew
Writer: Nancy Doyne (screenplay), Carroll Cartwright (screenplay), Henry James (based on the novel by)
Actors: Julianne Moore, Steve Coogan, Alexander Skarsgård, Joanna Vanderham
tomatoConsensus: It's undeniably difficult to watch at times, but What Maisie Knew ultimately rises on the strength of its solidly sourced script, powerful performances, and empathetic direction.

Plot: An acclaimed writer, his ex-wife, and their teenaged children come to terms with the complexities of love in all its forms over the course of one tumultuous year.
Title: Stuck in Love
Actors: Greg Kinnear, Jennifer Connelly, Lily Collins, Nat Wolff
tomatoConsensus: It struggles to enliven its uneven script, but Stuck in Love boasts enough winning performances from its solid veteran cast to offer an appealing diversion for rom-com enthusiasts.

Plot: When a Vienna museum guard befriends an enigmatic visitor, the grand Kunsthistorisches Art Museum becomes a mysterious crossroads that sparks explorations of their lives, the city, and the ways in which works of art reflect and shape the world.
Title: Museum Hours
Writer: Jem Cohen, Natalie Lettner, Mary Margaret O'Hara (additional dialogue), Bobby Sommer (additional dialogue)
Actors: Mary Margaret O'Hara, Bobby Sommer, Ela Piplits, Marcus O'Hara
tomatoConsensus: Its languid pace may frustrate some viewers, but for patient filmgoers, Museum Hours offers a carefully observed portrait of the human condition.

Plot: A recent college graduate flees to Paris after a break-up, where his involvement with a prostitute begins to reveal a potentially dark recent past.
Title: Simon Killer
Writer: Antonio Campos, Antonio Campos (story), Brady Corbet (story), Mati Diop (story)
Actors: Brady Corbet, Nicolas Ronchi, Constance Rousseau, Lila Salet
tomatoConsensus: Though its bleak themes may be off-putting for some, Simon Killer is an engrossing, effective character study of a brutal, enigmatic figure.

Plot: Asia Argento stars in horror legend Dario Argento's sexy spin on the classic tale about the sharp-toothed count who craves human blood.
Title: Dracula 3D
Writer: Dario Argento (screenplay), Enrique Cerezo (screenplay), Stefano Piani (screenplay), Bram Stoker (book), Antonio Tentori (screenplay)
Actors: Thomas Kretschmann, Marta Gastini, Asia Argento, Unax Ugalde
tomatoConsensus: Schlocky and gross but far from bad enough to be good, Argento's Dracula 3D bites and sucks in all the wrong ways.

Title: The History of Future Folk
Actors: Nils d'Aulaire, Jay Klaitz, Julie Ann Emery, April L. Hernandez
tomatoConsensus: High on quirky smarts and low on splashy special effects, The History of Future Folk is an unusual -- and unusually fun -- slice of sci-fi.

Plot: A farming family's business is threatened by an unexpected crisis, further testing the relationship between a father and his rebellious son.
Title: At Any Price
Actors: Dennis Quaid, Kim Dickens, Aaron B. Oduber, Jacob R. Oduber
tomatoConsensus: At Any Price features a terrific performance from Dennis Quaid, and it offers further evidence of Ramin Bahrani's unique eye for detail, but film is weighted down by an overly melodramatic story.

Plot: A failed New York playwright awkwardly navigates the transition from Next Big Thing to Last Year's News.
Title: Girl Most Likely
Actors: Kristen Wiig, Annette Bening, Matt Dillon, Darren Criss
tomatoConsensus: Largely witless and disappointingly dull, Girl Most Likely strands the gifted Kristen Wiig in a blandly hollow foray into scattershot sitcom territory.

Plot: A humble orphan suddenly becomes a gentleman with the help of an unknown benefactor.
Title: Great Expectations
Actors: Toby Irvine, Ralph Fiennes, Jason Flemyng, Sally Hawkins
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 6 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Not the best version of the oft-filmed Dickens classic but far from the worst, Mike Newell's Great Expectations breathes just enough life into the source material to justify yet another adaptation.

Plot: Wren's Halloween plans go awry when she's made to babysit her brother, who disappears into a sea of trick-or-treaters. With her best friend and two nerds at her side, she needs to find her brother before her mom finds out he's missing.
Title: Fun Size
Actors: Victoria Justice, Jackson Nicoll, Chelsea Handler, Josh Pence
tomatoConsensus: It occasionally shows surprising flashes of wit, but Fun Size is too safe and formulaic -- not to mention unfunny -- to survive comparisons to the '80s teen movies it eagerly imitates.

Plot: A documentary on Arnel Pineda, who was plucked from YouTube to become the new singer for the rock & roll band, Journey.
Title: Don't Stop Believin': Everyman's Journey
Actors: Arnel Pineda, Jonathan Cain, Neal Schon, Deen Castronovo
tomatoConsensus: An energetic but thin portrait of the venerable rock band Journey, Don't Stop Believin' gets a boost from new singer Arnel Pineda's charming personality.

Plot: Alabama; 1969: The death of a clan's estranged wife and mother brings together two very different families. Do the scars of the past hide differences that will tear them apart, or expose truths that could lead to unexpected collisions?
Title: Jayne Mansfield's Car
Actors: Robert Duvall, John Hurt, Billy Bob Thornton, Kevin Bacon
tomatoConsensus: Jayne Mansfield's Car assembles an impressive number of talented actors, but the screenplay -- co-written by director and star Billy Bob Thornton -- never gives them much of anything to do.

Plot: Johnny Depp pays a visit to Ralph Steadman, the renown artist and the last of the original Gonzo visionaries who worked alongside Hunter S. Thompson.
Title: For No Good Reason
Actors: Ralph Steadman, Johnny Depp, Hunter S. Thompson, Terry Gilliam
tomatoConsensus: For No Good Reason is a solid but surface-level look at gonzo artist Ralph Steadman's artistry and eccentricities.

Plot: When their latest work is buffed by a rival crew, two determined graffiti writers embark on an elaborate plan to bomb the ultimate location: the New York Mets' Home Run Apple.
Title: Gimme the Loot
Actors: Tashiana Washington, Ty Hickson, Meeko, Sam Soghor
tomatoConsensus: Thanks to energetic performances from its young leads, Gimme The Loot captures a slice of city life with warmth and exuberance.

Plot: After a highly unusual zombie saves a still-living girl from an attack, the two form a relationship that sets in motion events that might transform the entire lifeless world.
Title: Warm Bodies
Actors: Nicholas Hoult, Teresa Palmer, Analeigh Tipton, Rob Corddry
tomatoConsensus: Warm Bodies offers a sweet, well-acted spin on a genre that all too often lives down to its brain-dead protagonists.

Plot: A young woman travels to Texas to collect an inheritance; little does she know that an encounter with a chainsaw-wielding killer is part of the reward.
Title: Texas Chainsaw 3D
Writer: Adam Marcus (screenplay), Debra Sullivan (screenplay), Kirsten McCallion (screenplay), Stephen Susco (story), Adam Marcus (story), Debra Sullivan (story), Kim Henkel (characters), Tobe Hooper (characters)
Actors: Alexandra Daddario, Dan Yeager, Trey Songz, Scott Eastwood
tomatoConsensus: As an ugly and cynical attempt to rebrand Leatherface as horror anti-hero, Texas Chainsaw 3D is a bold move for the franchise.

Plot: It's 1949 Los Angeles, the city is run by gangsters and a malicious mobster, Mickey Cohen. Determined to end the corruption, John O'Mara assembles a team of cops, ready to take down the ruthless leader and restore peace to the city.
Title: Gangster Squad
Actors: Sean Penn, Holt McCallany, Wade Williams, James Landry Hébert
tomatoConsensus: Though it's stylish and features a talented cast, Gangster Squad suffers from lackluster writing, underdeveloped characters, and an excessive amount of violence.

Plot: The leader of a drug cartel busts out of a courthouse and speeds to the Mexican border, where the only thing in his path is a sheriff and his inexperienced staff.
Title: The Last Stand
Actors: Arron Shiver, Arnold Schwarzenegger, Titos Menchaca, Richard Dillard
tomatoConsensus: There's nothing particularly distinguished about it, but for Schwarzenegger fans The Last Stand provides perfectly undemanding entertainment.

Plot: A young couple take in their two nieces only to suspect that a foreboding evil has latched itself to their family.
Title: Mama
Writer: Andrés Muschietti (story), Barbara Muschietti (story), Neil Cross (screenplay), Andrés Muschietti (screenplay), Barbara Muschietti (screenplay)
Actors: Jessica Chastain, Nikolaj Coster-Waldau, Megan Charpentier, Isabelle Nélisse
tomatoConsensus: If you're into old-school scares over cheap gore, you'll be able to get over Mama's confusing script and contrived plot devices.

Plot: A man and woman are drawn together, entangled in the life cycle of an ageless organism. Identity becomes an illusion as they struggle to assemble the loose fragments of wrecked lives.
Title: Upstream Color
Actors: Amy Seimetz, Shane Carruth, Andrew Sensenig, Thiago Martins
tomatoConsensus: As technically brilliant as it is narratively abstract, Upstream Color represents experimental American cinema at its finest -- and reaffirms Shane Carruth as a talent to watch.

Plot: In a city rife with injustice, ex-cop Billy Taggart seeks redemption and revenge after being double-crossed and then framed by its most powerful figure: Mayor Nicholas Hostetler.
Title: Broken City
Actors: Mark Wahlberg, Russell Crowe, Catherine Zeta-Jones, Jeffrey Wright
tomatoConsensus: Broken City's thinly sketched, formulaic script offers meager rewards for all but the least demanding noir aficionados.

Plot: A series of interconnected short films follows a washed-up producer as he pitches insane story lines featuring some of the biggest stars in Hollywood.
Title: Movie 43
Writer: Rocky Russo, Jeremy Sosenko, Ricky Blitt, Rocky Russo (screenplay), Jeremy Sosenko (screenplay), Bill O'Malley (story), Will Graham, Jack Kukoda, Rocky Russo, Jeremy Sosenko, Matt Portenoy, Rocky Russo (screenplay), Jeremy Sosenko (screenplay), Claes Kjellstrom (story), Jonas Wittenmark (story), Tobias Carlson (story), Will Carlough, Jonathan van Tulleken, Elizabeth Shapiro, Patrik Forsberg, Olle Sarri, Jacob Fleisher, Greg Pritikin, Rocky Russo, Jeremy Sosenko, James Gunn
Director: Elizabeth Banks, Steven Brill, Steve Carr, Rusty Cundieff, James Duffy, Griffin Dunne, Peter Farrelly, Patrik Forsberg, Will Graham, James Gunn, Brett Ratner, Jonathan van Tulleken, Bob Odenkirk
Actors: Dennis Quaid, Greg Kinnear, Common, Charlie Saxton
tomatoConsensus: A star-studded turkey, Movie 43 is loaded with gleefully offensive and often scatological gags, but it's largely bereft of laughs.

Plot: A thief with a unique code of professional ethics is double-crossed by his crew and left for dead. Assuming a new disguise and forming an unlikely alliance with a woman on the inside, he looks to hijack the score of the crew's latest heist.
Title: Parker
Writer: John J. McLaughlin (screenplay), Donald E. Westlake (novel)
Actors: Jason Statham, Jennifer Lopez, Michael Chiklis, Wendell Pierce
tomatoConsensus: Jason Statham is game as usual, but Parker is a thoroughly generic and convoluted heist movie.

Plot: Hansel & Gretel are bounty hunters who track and kill witches all over the world. As the fabled Blood Moon approaches, the siblings encounter a new form of evil that might hold a secret to their past.
Title: Hansel & Gretel: Witch Hunters
Actors: Jeremy Renner, Gemma Arterton, Famke Janssen, Pihla Viitala
tomatoConsensus: Alternately bloody and silly, Hansel and Gretel: Witch Hunters fails as both a fantasy adventure and as a parody of same.

Plot: An operative for an elite private intelligence firm finds her priorities changing dramatically after she is tasked with infiltrating an anarchist group known for executing covert attacks upon major corporations.
Title: The East
Actors: Brit Marling, Alexander Skarsgård, Ellen Page, Toby Kebbell
tomatoConsensus: Tense, thoughtful, and deftly paced, The East is a political thriller that never loses sight of the human element.

Plot: A young woman's world unravels when a drug prescribed by her psychiatrist has unexpected side effects.
Title: Side Effects
Actors: Rooney Mara, Carmen Pelaez, Marin Ireland, Channing Tatum
tomatoConsensus: A smart, clever thriller with plenty of disquieting twists, Side Effects is yet another assured effort from director Steven Soderbergh.

Plot: Mild mannered businessman Sandy Patterson travels from Denver to Florida to confront the deceptively harmless looking woman who has been living it up after stealing Sandy's identity.
Title: Identity Thief
Writer: Craig Mazin (screenplay), Jerry Eeten (story), Craig Mazin (story)
Actors: Jason Bateman, Melissa McCarthy, Jon Favreau, Amanda Peet
tomatoConsensus: Identity Thief's few laughs are attributable to Melissa McCarthy and Jason Bateman, who labor mightily to create a framework for the movie's undisciplined plotline.

Plot: Ethan longs to escape his small Southern town. He meets a mysterious new girl, Lena. Together, they uncover dark secrets about their respective families, their history and their town.
Title: Beautiful Creatures
Writer: Richard LaGravenese (screenplay), Kami Garcia (based on the novel "Beautiful Creatures" by), Margaret Stohl (based on the novel "Beautiful Creatures" by)
Actors: Alden Ehrenreich, Alice Englert, Jeremy Irons, Viola Davis
tomatoConsensus: Charming romantic leads and esteemed supporting cast aside, Beautiful Creatures is a plodding YA novel adaptation that feels watered down for the Twilight set.

Plot: John McClane travels to Russia to help out his seemingly wayward son, Jack, only to discover that Jack is a CIA operative working undercover, causing the father and son to team up against underworld forces.
Title: A Good Day to Die Hard
Writer: Skip Woods, Roderick Thorp (certain original characters by)
Actors: Bruce Willis, Jai Courtney, Sebastian Koch, Mary Elizabeth Winstead
tomatoConsensus: A Good Day to Die Hard is the weakest entry in a storied franchise, and not even Bruce Willis' smirking demeanor can enliven a cliched, uninspired script.

Plot: The night before his big medical school interview, a promising student celebrates his 21st birthday with his two best friends.
Title: 21 & Over
Actors: Miles Teller, Skylar Astin, Justin Chon, Sarah Wright
tomatoConsensus: Though it strives to mimic The Hangover, 21 and Over is too predictable, too unabashedly profane, and too inconsistently funny to carry the torch.

Plot: A young woman with a mysterious past lands in Southport, North Carolina where her bond with a widower forces her to confront the dark secret that haunts her.
Title: Safe Haven
Writer: Dana Stevens (screenplay), Gage Lansky (screenplay), Nicholas Sparks (based upon the novel by)
Actors: Julianne Hough, Irene Ziegler, Jon Kohler, Tim Parati
tomatoConsensus: Schmaltzy, predictable, and melodramatic, Safe Haven also suffers from a ludicrous plot twist, making for a particularly ignominious Nicholas Sparks adaptation.

Plot: We meet Jesse and Celine nine years on in Greece. Almost two decades have passed since their first meeting on that train bound for Vienna.
Title: Before Midnight
Writer: Richard Linklater, Julie Delpy, Ethan Hawke, Richard Linklater (characters), Kim Krizan (characters)
Actors: Ethan Hawke, Julie Delpy, Seamus Davey-Fitzpatrick, Jennifer Prior
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 20 wins & 57 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Building on the first two installments in Richard Linklater's well-crafted Before trilogy, Before Midnight offers intelligent, powerfully acted perspectives on love, marriage, and long-term commitment.

Plot: A father goes undercover for the DEA in order to free his son, who was imprisoned after being set up in drug deal.
Title: Snitch
Actors: Dwayne Johnson, Barry Pepper, Jon Bernthal, Susan Sarandon
tomatoConsensus: Though it features one of Dwayne Johnson's more thoughtful performances, the presentation of Snitch's underlying message is muddled by lackluster storytelling and some tonal inconsistencies.

Plot: As the Barret family's peaceful suburban life is rocked by an escalating series of disturbing events, they come to learn that a terrifying and deadly force is after them.
Title: Dark Skies
Actors: Keri Russell, Josh Hamilton, Dakota Goyo, Kadan Rockett
tomatoConsensus: Dark Skies writer director Scott Stewart has a solid cast, an interesting premise, and some admirable ambitions, but he can't figure out what to do with any of them, and the result is a dull, muddled effort that will bore all but the most devoted horror buffs.

Plot: The ancient war between humans and a race of giants is reignited when Jack, a young farmhand fighting for a kingdom and the love of a princess, opens a gateway between the two worlds.
Title: Jack the Giant Slayer
Writer: Darren Lemke (screenplay), Christopher McQuarrie (screenplay), Dan Studney (screenplay), Darren Lemke (story), David Dobkin (story)
Actors: Nicholas Hoult, Eleanor Tomlinson, Ewan McGregor, Stanley Tucci
tomatoConsensus: It's enthusiastically acted and reasonably fun, but Jack the Giant Slayer is also overwhelmed by digital effects and a bland, impersonal story.

Plot: The G.I. Joes are not only fighting their mortal enemy Cobra; they are forced to contend with threats from within the government that jeopardize their very existence.
Title: G.I. Joe: Retaliation
Actors: Dwayne Johnson, Jonathan Pryce, Byung-hun Lee, Elodie Yung
tomatoConsensus: Though arguably superior to its predecessor, G.I. Joe: Retaliation is overwhelmed by its nonstop action and too nonsensical and vapid to leave a lasting impression.

Plot: After India's father dies, her Uncle Charlie, who she never knew existed, comes to live with her and her unstable mother. She comes to suspect this mysterious, charming man has ulterior motives and becomes increasingly infatuated with him.
Title: Stoker
Actors: Mia Wasikowska, Nicole Kidman, David Alford, Matthew Goode
tomatoConsensus: Its script doesn't quite carry the dramatic heft of his earlier work, but Park Chan-wook's Stoker showcases his eye for sumptuous imagery and his affection for dark, atmospheric narratives populated by mysterious characters.

Plot: The haunted Captain of a Soviet submarine holds the fate of the world in his hands. Forced to leave his family behind, he is charged with leading a covert mission cloaked in mystery.
Title: Phantom
Actors: Ed Harris, David Duchovny, William Fichtner, Lance Henriksen
tomatoConsensus: A cast of solid actors do what they can to elevate the material, but Phantom's script is too clunky and devoid of tension to bear comparison to its thematic predecessors.

Plot: A documentary on the fabled recording studio that was located in Van Nuys, California.
Title: Sound City
Actors: Vinny Appice, Joe Barresi, Brian Bell, Frank Black
tomatoConsensus: Smart, affectionate, and unabashedly sincere, Sound City pairs a great soundtrack with a well-argued ode to one of rock 'n' roll's most fondly remembered bygone eras.

Plot: A small-time magician is swept away to an enchanted land and is forced into a power struggle between three witches.
Title: Oz the Great and Powerful
Writer: Mitchell Kapner (screenplay), David Lindsay-Abaire (screenplay), Mitchell Kapner (screen story), L. Frank Baum ("Oz" works)
Actors: James Franco, Mila Kunis, Rachel Weisz, Michelle Williams
tomatoConsensus: It suffers from some tonal inconsistency and a deflated sense of wonder, but Oz the Great and Powerful still packs enough visual dazzle and clever wit to be entertaining in its own right.

Plot: In New York City, a crime lord's right-hand man is helped by a woman seeking retribution.
Title: Dead Man Down
Actors: Colin Farrell, Noomi Rapace, Terrence Howard, Dominic Cooper
tomatoConsensus: While the fine cast keeps Dead Man Down watchable throughout, the film is weighted down by absurd plot twists and a slack pace.

Plot: After their cave is destroyed, a caveman family must trek through an unfamiliar fantastical world with the help of an inventive boy.
Title: The Croods
Writer: Chris Sanders (screenplay), Kirk De Micco (screenplay), John Cleese (story), Kirk De Micco (story), Chris Sanders (story)
Actors: Nicolas Cage, Emma Stone, Ryan Reynolds, Catherine Keener
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 41 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: While it may not be as (ahem) evolved as the best modern animated fare, The Croods will prove solidly entertaining for families seeking a fast-paced, funny cartoon adventure.

Plot: A veteran Vegas magician tries to revive his career after his longtime partner quits, he gets fired from his casino act, and an edgy new "street magician" steals his thunder.
Title: The Incredible Burt Wonderstone
Writer: Jonathan Goldstein (screenplay), John Francis Daley (screenplay), Chad Kultgen (story), Tyler Mitchell (story), Jonathan Goldstein (story), John Francis Daley (story)
Actors: Steve Carell, Steve Buscemi, Olivia Wilde, Jim Carrey
tomatoConsensus: The Incredible Burt Wonderstone serves up some goofy laughs, but given its outrageous conceit, it's surprisingly safe and predictable.

Plot: Disgraced Secret Service agent (and former presidential guard) Mike Banning finds himself trapped inside the White House in the wake of a terrorist attack; using his inside knowledge, Banning works with national security to rescue the President from his kidnappers.
Title: Olympus Has Fallen
Actors: Gerard Butler, Aaron Eckhart, Finley Jacobsen, Dylan McDermott
tomatoConsensus: It's far from original, but Olympus Has Fallen benefits from Antoine Fuqua's tense direction and a strong performance from Gerard Butler -- which might just be enough for action junkies.

Plot: When an unseen enemy threatens mankind by taking over their bodies and erasing their memories, Melanie will risk everything to protect the people she cares most about, proving that love can conquer all in a dangerous new world.
Title: The Host
Actors: Rachel Roberts, Shyaam Karra, Brent Wendell Williams, Jhil McEntyre
tomatoConsensus: Poorly scripted and dramatically ineffective, The Host is mostly stale and tedious, with moments of unintentional hilarity.

Plot: A Princeton admissions officer who is up for a major promotion takes a professional risk after she meets a college-bound alternative school kid who just might be the son she gave up years ago in a secret adoption.
Title: Admission
Writer: Karen Croner (screenplay), Jean Hanff Korelitz (based on the novel by)
Actors: Tina Fey, Ann Harada, Ben Levin, Dan Levy
tomatoConsensus: Admission has a pair of immensely likable leads in Tina Fey and Paul Rudd, but it wastes them on a contrived (and clumsily directed) screenplay.

Plot: An abandoned boy is lured to America and drawn into the shadow of a dangerous father figure. Inspired by the real life events that led to the 2002 Beltway sniper attacks.
Title: Blue Caprice
Writer: Alexandre Moors (story), R.F.I. Porto (screenplay), R.F.I. Porto (story)
