Actors: Henry Cavill, Amy Adams, Michael Shannon, Diane Lane
tomatoConsensus: Man of Steel's exhilarating action and spectacle can't fully overcome its detours into generic blockbuster territory.

Plot: Three teenage friends, in the ultimate act of independence, decide to spend their summer building a house in the woods and living off the land.
Title: The Kings of Summer
Actors: Nick Robinson, Gabriel Basso, Moises Arias, Nick Offerman
tomatoConsensus: Thanks to charming performances and endearingly off-kilter spirit, The Kings of Summer proves to be a slight, sweet entry in the crowded coming-of-age genre.

Plot: A long-divorced couple fakes being married as their family unites for a wedding.
Title: The Big Wedding
Writer: Justin Zackham (screenplay), Jean-Stéphane Bron (motion picture "Mon frère se marie"), Karine Sudan (motion picture "Mon frère se marie")
Actors: Robert De Niro, Katherine Heigl, Diane Keaton, Amanda Seyfried
tomatoConsensus: The Big Wedding's all-star cast is stranded in a contrived, strained plot that features broad stabs at humor but few laughs.

Plot: In the future, a wealthy family is held hostage for harboring the target of a murderous syndicate during the Purge, a 12-hour period in which any and all crime is legalized.
Title: The Purge
Actors: Ethan Hawke, Lena Headey, Max Burkholder, Adelaide Kane
tomatoConsensus: Half social allegory, half home-invasion thriller, The Purge attempts to make an intelligent point, but ultimately devolves into numbing violence and tired clichés.

Plot: Inspired by actual events, a group of fame-obsessed teenagers use the internet to track celebrities' whereabouts in order to rob their homes.
Title: The Bling Ring
Writer: Sofia Coppola, Nancy Jo Sales (based on the Vanity Fair article "The Suspect Wore Louboutins" by)
Actors: Katie Chang, Israel Broussard, Emma Watson, Claire Julien
tomatoConsensus: While it's certainly timely and beautifully filmed, The Bling Ring suffers from director Sofia Coppola's failure to delve beneath the surface of its shallow protagonists' real-life crimes.

Plot: A look at the relationship between Mike and Sulley during their days at Monsters University -- when they weren't necessarily the best of friends.
Title: Monsters University
Writer: Dan Scanlon (story by), Daniel Gerson (story by), Robert L. Baird (story by), Daniel Gerson (screenplay), Robert L. Baird (screenplay), Dan Scanlon (screenplay)
Actors: Billy Crystal, John Goodman, Steve Buscemi, Helen Mirren
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 9 wins & 54 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Offering Monsters, Inc. fans a return visit with beloved characters, Monsters University delivers funny and thoughtful family entertainment for viewers of any age.

Plot: As a war between humankind and monstrous sea creatures wages on, a former pilot and a trainee are paired up to drive a seemingly obsolete special weapon in a desperate effort to save the world from the apocalypse.
Title: Pacific Rim
Writer: Travis Beacham (screenplay), Guillermo del Toro (screenplay), Travis Beacham (story)
Actors: Charlie Hunnam, Diego Klattenhoff, Idris Elba, Rinko Kikuchi
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 5 wins & 42 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: It may sport more style than substance, but Pacific Rim is a solid modern creature feature bolstered by fantastical imagery and an irresistible sense of fun.

Plot: Former United Nations employee Gerry Lane traverses the world in a race against time to stop the Zombie pandemic that is toppling armies and governments, and threatening to destroy humanity itself.
Title: World War Z
Writer: Matthew Michael Carnahan (screenplay), Drew Goddard (screenplay), Damon Lindelof (screenplay), Matthew Michael Carnahan (screen story), J. Michael Straczynski (screen story), Max Brooks (based on the novel by)
Actors: Brad Pitt, Mireille Enos, Daniella Kertesz, James Badge Dale
tomatoConsensus: It's uneven and diverges from the source book, but World War Z still brings smart, fast-moving thrills and a solid performance from Brad Pitt to the zombie genre.

Plot: In the year 2154, the very wealthy live on a man-made space station while the rest of the population resides on a ruined Earth. A man takes on a mission that could bring equality to the polarized worlds.
Title: Elysium
Actors: Matt Damon, Jodie Foster, Sharlto Copley, Alice Braga
tomatoConsensus: After the heady sci-fi thrills of District 9, Elysium is a bit of a comedown for director Neill Blomkamp, but on its own terms, it delivers just often enough to satisfy.

Plot: Investigative journalist Jeremy Scahill is pulled into an unexpected journey as he chases down the hidden truth behind America's expanding covert wars.
Title: Dirty Wars
Actors: Nasser Al Aulaqi, Saleha Al Aulaqi, Muqbal Al Kazemi, Abdul Rahman Barman
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Some viewers may find fault with director Rick Rowley's filmmaking methods, but they aren't distracting enough to keep Dirty Wars from serving as a terribly compelling argument against elements of American foreign policy.

Plot: A documentary that details the creation of Julian Assange's controversial website, which facilitated the largest security breach in U.S. history.
Title: We Steal Secrets: The Story of WikiLeaks
Actors: John 'FuzzFace' McMahon, Alex Gibney, Julian Assange, Robert Manne
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 3 wins & 8 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: As fascinating as it is provocative, We Steal Secrets: The Story of Wikileaks presents another documentary triumph for director Alex Gibney, as well as a troubling look at one of the more meaningful issues of our time.

Plot: An international crew of astronauts undertakes a privately funded mission to search for life on Jupiter's fourth largest moon.
Title: Europa Report
Actors: Daniel Wu, Sharlto Copley, Christian Camargo, Karolina Wydra
tomatoConsensus: Claustrophobic and stylish, Europa Report is a slow-burning thriller that puts the science back into science fiction.

Plot: When Gru, the world's most super-bad turned super-dad has been recruited by a team of officials to stop lethal muscle and a host of Gru's own, He has to fight back with new gadgetry, cars, and more minion madness.
Title: Despicable Me 2
Actors: Steve Carell, Kristen Wiig, Benjamin Bratt, Miranda Cosgrove
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 12 wins & 63 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Despicable Me 2 offers plenty of eye-popping visual inventiveness and a number of big laughs.

Plot: While on a tour of the White House with his young daughter, a Capitol policeman springs into action to save his child and protect the president from a heavily armed group of paramilitary invaders.
Title: White House Down
Actors: Channing Tatum, Jamie Foxx, Maggie Gyllenhaal, Jason Clarke
tomatoConsensus: White House Down benefits from the leads' chemistry, but director Roland Emmerich smothers the film with narrative clichés and choppily edited action.

Plot: An uptight FBI Special Agent is paired with a foul-mouthed Boston cop to take down a ruthless drug lord.
Title: The Heat
Actors: Sandra Bullock, Melissa McCarthy, Demián Bichir, Marlon Wayans
tomatoConsensus: The Heat is predictable, but Melissa McCarthy is reliably funny and Sandra Bullock proves a capable foil.

Plot: Native American warrior Tonto recounts the untold tales that transformed John Reid, a man of the law, into a legend of justice.
Title: The Lone Ranger
Writer: Justin Haythe (screenplay), Ted Elliott (screenplay), Terry Rossio (screenplay), Ted Elliott (screen story), Terry Rossio (screen story), Justin Haythe (screen story)
Actors: Johnny Depp, Armie Hammer, William Fichtner, Tom Wilkinson
Awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 17 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Armie Hammer and Johnny Depp make for an appealing pair of leads, but they're not enough to make up for The Lone Ranger's bland script, bloated length, and blaring action overkill.

Plot: A recently slain cop joins a team of undead police officers working for the Rest in Peace Department and tries to find the man who murdered him.
Title: R.I.P.D.
Writer: Phil Hay (screenplay), Matt Manfredi (screenplay), David Dobkin (story), Phil Hay (story), Matt Manfredi (story), Peter M. Lenkov (Dark Horse comic)
Actors: Jeff Bridges, Ryan Reynolds, Kevin Bacon, Mary-Louise Parker
tomatoConsensus: It has its moments -- most of them courtesy of Jeff Bridges' rootin' tootin' performance as an undead Wild West sheriff -- but R.I.P.D. is ultimately too dim-witted and formulaic to satisfy.

Plot: Amid the Civil War in 17th-century England, a group of deserters flee from battle through an overgrown field. Captured by an alchemist, the men are forced to help him search to find a hidden treasure that he believes is buried in the field.
Title: A Field in England
Actors: Julian Barratt, Peter Ferdinando, Richard Glover, Ryan Pope
tomatoConsensus: Recklessly assembled and occasionally compelling in spite of itself, A Field in England showcases a singularly brilliant voice in British cinema.

Plot: Paranormal investigators Ed and Lorraine Warren work to help a family terrorized by a dark presence in their farmhouse.
Title: The Conjuring
Actors: Vera Farmiga, Patrick Wilson, Lili Taylor, Ron Livingston
tomatoConsensus: Well-crafted and gleefully creepy, The Conjuring ratchets up dread through a series of effective old-school scares.

Plot: A freak accident might just help an everyday garden snail achieve his biggest dream: winning the Indy 500.
Title: Turbo
Writer: Darren Lemke (screenplay), Robert D. Siegel (screenplay), David Soren (screenplay), David Soren (story)
Actors: Ryan Reynolds, Paul Giamatti, Michael Peña, Samuel L. Jackson
tomatoConsensus: It's nowhere near as inventive as its off-the-wall premise might suggest, but Turbo boasts just enough colorful visual thrills and sharp voice acting to recommend as undemanding family-friendly fare.

Plot: When Wolverine is summoned to Japan by an old acquaintance, he is embroiled in a conflict that forces him to confront his own demons.
Title: The Wolverine
Actors: Hugh Jackman, Tao Okamoto, Rila Fukushima, Hiroyuki Sanada
tomatoConsensus: Although its final act succumbs to the usual cartoonish antics, The Wolverine is one superhero movie that manages to stay true to the comics while keeping casual viewers entertained.

Plot: Luke and Kate are coworkers at a brewery who spend their nights drinking and flirting heavily. One weekend away together with their significant others proves who really belongs together and who doesn't.
Title: Drinking Buddies
Actors: Olivia Wilde, Jake Johnson, Anna Kendrick, Ron Livingston
tomatoConsensus: Smart, funny, and powered by fine performances from Olivia Wilde and Jake Johnson, Drinking Buddies offers a bittersweet slice of observational comedy.

Plot: Retired C.I.A. agent Frank Moses reunites his unlikely team of elite operatives for a global quest to track down a missing portable nuclear device.
Title: RED 2
Writer: Jon Hoeber, Erich Hoeber, Warren Ellis (characters), Cully Hamner (characters)
Actors: Bruce Willis, John Malkovich, Mary-Louise Parker, Helen Mirren
tomatoConsensus: While it's still hard to argue with its impeccable cast or the fun they often seem to be having, Red 2 replaces much of the goofy fun of its predecessor with empty, over-the-top bombast.

Plot: Two hardened criminals get into trouble with the US border patrol after meeting with a Mexican drug lord, and then revelations start to unfold.
Title: 2 Guns
Writer: Blake Masters (screenplay), Steven Grant (based on the Boom! Studios graphic novels by)
Actors: Denzel Washington, Mark Wahlberg, Paula Patton, Edward James Olmos
tomatoConsensus: Formulaic and often jarringly violent, 2 Guns rests its old-school appeal on the interplay between its charismatic, well-matched stars.

Plot: In order to restore their dying safe haven, the son of Poseidon and his friends embark on a quest to the Sea of Monsters to find the mythical Golden Fleece while trying to stop an ancient evil from rising.
Title: Percy Jackson: Sea of Monsters
Writer: Marc Guggenheim (screenplay), Rick Riordan (based upon the novel "Percy Jackson and the Olympians: The Sea of Monsters" written by)
Actors: Logan Lerman, Alexandra Daddario, Douglas Smith, Leven Rambin
tomatoConsensus: It's pretty and packed with action; unfortunately, Percy Jackson: Sea of Monsters is also waterlogged with characters and plots that can't help but feel derivative.

Plot: The Smurfs team up with their human friends to rescue Smurfette, who has been kidnapped by Gargamel since she knows a secret spell that can turn the evil sorcerer's newest creation - creatures called the Naughties - into real Smurfs.
Title: The Smurfs 2
Writer: J. David Stem (screenplay), David N. Weiss (screenplay), Jay Scherick (screenplay), David Ronn (screenplay), Karey Kirkpatrick (screenplay), J. David Stem (story), David N. Weiss (story), Jay Scherick (story), David Ronn (story), Peyo (characters and works)
Actors: Hank Azaria, Neil Patrick Harris, Brendan Gleeson, Jayma Mays
tomatoConsensus: Like its predecessor, Smurfs 2 may amuse small children, but it's largely an unambitious, charm-free collection of slapstick gags and one-liners.

Plot: When famous DJ Alan Partridge's radio station is taken over by a new media conglomerate, it sets in motion a chain of events which see Alan having to work with the police to defuse a potentially violent siege.
Title: Alan Partridge
Writer: Peter Baynham (based upon characters created by), Peter Baynham (screenplay), Steve Coogan (based upon characters created by), Steve Coogan (screenplay), Neil Gibbons (screenplay), Rob Gibbons (screenplay), Armando Iannucci (based upon characters created by), Armando Iannucci (screenplay), Patrick Marber (based upon characters created by)
Actors: Colm Meaney, Steve Coogan, Tim Key, Karl Theobald
tomatoConsensus: The Alan Partridge movie ditches the TV series' nuanced humor for something broader, and succeeds in presenting the character on a global scale.

Plot: A 1980s-set story centered around a man vs. machine chess tournament.
Title: Computer Chess
Actors: Kriss Schludermann, Tom Fletcher, Wiley Wiggins, Patrick Riester
tomatoConsensus: With its delightfully retro production design, Computer Chess is an inventive, intelligent, and humorous comedy that celebrates the eccentricity and uniqueness of its subject.

Plot: Two highway road workers spend the summer of 1988 away from their city lives. The isolated landscape becomes a place of misadventure as the men find themselves at odds with each other and the women they left behind.
Title: Prince Avalanche
Writer: David Gordon Green, Hafsteinn Gunnar Sigurðsson (based on the film "Either Way")
Actors: Paul Rudd, Emile Hirsch, Lance LeGault, Joyce Payne
tomatoConsensus: A step back in the right direction for director David Gordon Green, Prince Avalanche shambles amiably along with a pair of artfully low-key performances from Paul Rudd and Emile Hirsch.

Plot: A veteran pot dealer creates a fake family as part of his plan to move a huge shipment of weed into the U.S. from Mexico.
Title: We're the Millers
Writer: Bob Fisher (screenplay), Steve Faber (screenplay), Sean Anders (screenplay), John Morris (screenplay), Bob Fisher (story), Steve Faber (story)
Actors: Jennifer Aniston, Jason Sudeikis, Emma Roberts, Will Poulter
tomatoConsensus: We're the Millers squanders its potential with an uneven, lazily assembled story..

Plot: After moving his family back to his hometown to be with his friends and their kids, Lenny finds out that between old bullies, new bullies, schizo bus drivers, drunk cops on skis, and 400 costumed party crashers sometimes crazy follows you.
Title: Grown Ups 2
Writer: Fred Wolf, Adam Sandler, Tim Herlihy, Adam Sandler (based on characters created by), Fred Wolf (based on characters created by)
Actors: Adam Sandler, Kevin James, Chris Rock, David Spade
tomatoConsensus: While it's almost certainly the movie event of the year for filmgoers passionate about deer urine humor, Grown Ups 2 will bore, annoy, and disgust audiences of nearly every other persuasion.

Plot: Following Kick-Ass' heroics, other citizens are inspired to become masked crusaders. But the Red Mist leads his own group of evil supervillains to kill Kick-Ass and destroy everything for which he stands.
Title: Kick-Ass 2
Writer: Jeff Wadlow (screenplay), Mark Millar (comic book), John Romita Jr. (comic book)
Actors: Aaron Taylor-Johnson, Chloë Grace Moretz, Morris Chestnut, Claudia Lee
tomatoConsensus: Kick-Ass 2 falls short in its attempt to emulate the original's unique blend of ultra-violence and ironic humor.

Plot: The story of Steve Jobs' ascension from college dropout into one of the most revered creative entrepreneurs of the 20th century.
Title: Jobs
Actors: Ashton Kutcher, Dermot Mulroney, Josh Gad, Lukas Haas
tomatoConsensus: An ambitious but skin-deep portrait of an influential, complex figure, Jobs often has the feel of an over-sentimentalized made-for-TV biopic.

Plot: When her mother disappears, Clary Fray learns that she descends from a line of warriors who protect our world from demons. She joins forces with others like her and heads into a dangerous alternate New York called the Shadow World.
Title: The Mortal Instruments: City of Bones
Writer: Jessica Postigo (screenplay), Cassandra Clare (based on the novel by)
Actors: Lily Collins, Jamie Campbell Bower, Kevin Zegers, Jemima West
tomatoConsensus: The Mortal Instruments: City of Bones borrows ingredients from seemingly every fantasy franchise of the last 30 years -- but can't seem to figure out what to do with them.

Plot: A massage therapist is unable to do her job when stricken with a mysterious and sudden aversion to bodily contact. Meanwhile, her uptight brother's floundering dental practice receives new life when clients seek out his healing touch.
Title: Touchy Feely
Actors: Rosemarie DeWitt, Amber Wolfe Wollam, Josh Pais, Ellen Page
tomatoConsensus: Well-acted but overly quirky, Touchy Feely is a tonally uneven dramedy with some interesting ideas but a lack of follow-through.

Plot: As Cecil Gaines serves eight presidents during his tenure as a butler at the White House, the civil rights movement, Vietnam, and other major events affect this man's life, family, and American society.
Title: Lee Daniels' The Butler
Actors: Forest Whitaker, David Banner, Michael Rainey Jr., LaJessie Smith
Awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 18 wins & 50 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Gut-wrenching and emotionally affecting,  Lee Daniels' The Butler overcomes an uneven narrative thanks to strong performances from an all-star cast.

Plot: The tale of an outlaw who escapes from prison and sets out across the Texas hills to reunite with his wife and the daughter he has never met.
Title: Ain't Them Bodies Saints
Actors: Rooney Mara, Casey Affleck, Ben Foster, Keith Carradine
tomatoConsensus: While conventional in plot, Ain't Them Bodies Saints is a visually poetic film that pays homage to the New Hollywood directors of the 1970s and promises big things from director David Lowery.

Plot: A pair of childhood friends and neighbors fall for each other's sons.
Title: Adore
Writer: Anne Fontaine (screenplay), Christopher Hampton (story), Anne Fontaine (story), Doris Lessing (book)
Actors: Naomi Watts, Robin Wright, Xavier Samuel, James Frecheville
tomatoConsensus: Naomi Watts and Robin Wright give it their all, but they can't quite make Adore's trashy, absurd plot believable.

Plot: A look at Niall, Zayn, Liam, Louis, and Harry's meteoric rise to fame, from their humble hometown beginnings and competing on the X-Factor, to conquering the world and performing at London's famed O2 Arena.
Title: One Direction: This Is Us
Actors: Niall Horan, Zayn Malik, Liam Payne, Harry Styles
tomatoConsensus: It's mostly for the converted, but One Direction: This Is Us will be fun for fans -- and it offers just enough slickly edited concert footage to entertain the casual viewer.

Plot: To save his kidnapped wife, Brent Magna must drive at the orders of a mysterious man.
Title: Getaway
Actors: Ethan Hawke, Selena Gomez, Jon Voight, Rebecca Budig
tomatoConsensus: Monotonously fast-paced to the point of exhaustion, Getaway offers a reminder of the dangers in attempting to speed past coherent editing, character development, sensible dialogue, and an interesting plot.

Plot: A medical engineer and an astronaut work together to survive after an accident leaves them adrift in space.
Title: Gravity
Actors: Sandra Bullock, George Clooney, Ed Harris, Orto Ignatiussen
tomatoConsensus: Alfonso Cuarón's Gravity is an eerie, tense sci-fi thriller that's masterfully directed and visually stunning.

Plot: When Keller Dover's daughter and her friend go missing, he takes matters into his own hands as the police pursue multiple leads and the pressure mounts. But just how far will this desperate father go to protect his family?
Title: Prisoners
Actors: Hugh Jackman, Jake Gyllenhaal, Viola Davis, Maria Bello
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 34 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Prisoners has an emotional complexity and a sense of dread that makes for absorbing (and disturbing) viewing.

Plot: Obsessed with Pride and Prejudice (1995), a woman travels to a Jane Austen theme park in search for her perfect gentleman.
Title: Austenland
Writer: Jerusha Hess (screenplay), Shannon Hale (screenplay), Shannon Hale (based on the novel by)
Actors: Keri Russell, JJ Feild, Bret McKenzie, Jennifer Coolidge
tomatoConsensus: Despite an intriguing premise and fine performances from a talented cast, Austenland succumbs to outworn romcom cliches and slapstick gags.

Plot: The Manzoni family, a notorious mafia clan, is relocated to Normandy, France under the witness protection program, where fitting in soon becomes challenging as their old habits die hard.
Title: The Family
Writer: Luc Besson (screenplay), Michael Caleo (screenplay), Tonino Benacquista (based on the book by)
Actors: Robert De Niro, Michelle Pfeiffer, Dianna Agron, John D'Leo
tomatoConsensus: Luc Besson's The Family suffers from an overly familiar setup and a number of jarring tonal shifts.

Plot: An unprecedented look inside the private world of J.D. Salinger, the reclusive author of The Catcher in the Rye.
Title: Salinger
Actors: Philip Seymour Hoffman, Edward Norton, John Cusack, Martin Sheen
tomatoConsensus: A so-so documentary about a fascinating personality, Salinger has moments of insight but is too often bogged down by reenactments and a lack of attention to the man's actual writings.

Plot: Feeling pressured to become more sexually experienced before she goes to college, Brandy Klark makes a list of things to accomplish before hitting campus in the fall.
Title: The To Do List
Actors: Aubrey Plaza, Johnny Simmons, Bill Hader, Alia Shawkat
tomatoConsensus: The To Do List may play things disappointingly safe given its rather daring premise, but writer-director Maggie Carey's sure hand -- and Aubrey Plaza's performance -- keep the laughs coming.

Plot: Battle of the Year attracts all the best teams from around the world, but the Americans haven't won in fifteen years. Dante enlists Blake to assemble a team of the best dancers and bring the Trophy back to America where it started.
Title: Battle of the Year
Writer: Brin Hill, Chris Parker, Benson Lee (based upon the documentary "Planet B-Boy" by)
Actors: Josh Holloway, Laz Alonso, Josh Peck, Caity Lotz
tomatoConsensus: With a hopelessly hokey plot and unintentionally hilarious dialogue, Battle of the Year is flimsy even by the standards of the dance movie genre.

Plot: A documentary on the Manhattan department store with interviews from an array of fashion designers, style icons, and celebrities.
Title: Scatter My Ashes at Bergdorf's
Actors: Mary-Kate Olsen, Ashley Olsen, William Fichtner, Candice Bergen
tomatoConsensus: Scatter My Ashes At Bergdorf's is a fun documentary which ultimately doubles as an infomercial for the Manhattan store.

Plot: As Jamie travels in Chile, he invites an eccentric woman to join his group's quest to score a fabled hallucinogen, a move that finds him at odds with his new companion, until they drink the magic brew on a beach at the edge of the desert.
Title: Crystal Fairy & the Magical Cactus
Actors: Michael Cera, Gaby Hoffmann, Juan Andrés Silva, Agustín Silva
tomatoConsensus: Slight and unpolished, The Crystal Fairy is held together with Sebastian Silva's assured direction and a pair of strong, committed performances from Michael Cera and Gaby Hoffman.

Plot: When a poor college student who cracks an online poker game goes bust, he arranges a face-to-face with the man he thinks cheated him, a sly offshore entrepreneur.
Title: Runner Runner
Actors: Justin Timberlake, Ben Affleck, Gemma Arterton, Anthony Mackie
tomatoConsensus: It has an impressive cast and an intriguing premise, but Runner Runner wastes them on a bland, haphazardly assembled thriller with very little payoff.

Plot: Adèle's life is changed when she meets Emma, a young woman with blue hair, who will allow her to discover desire and to assert herself as a woman and as an adult. In front of others, Adèle grows, seeks herself, loses herself, and ultimately finds herself through love and loss.
Title: Blue Is the Warmest Color
Writer: Abdellatif Kechiche (scenario,  adaptation and dialogue), Ghalia Lacroix (scenario,  adaptation and dialogue), Julie Maroh (adapted from: the comic book "Le Bleu est une couleur chaude" by)
Actors: Léa Seydoux, Adèle Exarchopoulos, Salim Kechiouche, Aurélien Recoing
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 84 wins & 93 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Raw, honest, powerfully acted, and deliciously intense, Blue Is the Warmest Color offers some of modern cinema's most elegantly composed, emotionally absorbing drama.

Plot: A recounting of the chaotic events that occurred at Dallas' Parkland Hospital on the day U.S. President John F. Kennedy was assassinated.
Title: Parkland
Actors: Marcia Gay Harden, Matt Barr, Zac Efron, Mallory Moye
tomatoConsensus: Although its decision to look at John F. Kennedy's assassination through uncommon perspectives is refreshing, Parkland never achieves the narrative cohesion its subject deserves.

Plot: A documentary that follows former U.S. Labor Secretary Robert Reich as he looks to raise awareness of the country's widening economic gap.
Title: Inequality for All
Actors: Hillary Clinton, Sharon Gless, Candice Bergen, Lily Tomlin
tomatoConsensus: While it arrives in a glut of similarly themed documentaries, Inequality for All distinguishes itself with a compelling presentation of an important message, as well as much-needed splashes of wit.

Plot: Flint Lockwood now works at The Live Corp Company for his idol Chester V. But he's forced to leave his post when he learns that his most infamous machine is still operational and is churning out menacing food-animal hybrids.
Title: Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs 2
Writer: Erica Rivinoja (screenplay), John Francis Daley (screenplay), Jonathan Goldstein (screenplay), Phil Lord (story), Christopher Miller (story), Erica Rivinoja (story), Judi Barrett (characters), Ron Barrett (characters)
Actors: Bill Hader, Anna Faris, James Caan, Will Forte
tomatoConsensus: While not as clever or inventive as its predecessor, Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs 2 compensates with enough dazzling visuals to keep younger viewers entertained.

Plot: The true story of Captain Richard Phillips and the 2009 hijacking by Somali pirates of the US-flagged MV Maersk Alabama, the first American cargo ship to be hijacked in two hundred years.
Title: Captain Phillips
Writer: Billy Ray (screenplay), Richard Phillips (based upon the book "A Captain's Duty: Somali Pirates,  Navy SEALS,  and Dangerous Days at Sea" by), Stephan Talty (based upon the book "A Captain's Duty: Somali Pirates,  Navy SEALS,  and Dangerous Days at Sea" by)
Actors: Tom Hanks, Catherine Keener, Barkhad Abdi, Barkhad Abdirahman
Awards: Nominated for 6 Oscars. Another 16 wins & 138 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Smart, powerfully acted, and incredibly intense, Captain Phillips offers filmgoers a Hollywood biopic done right -- and offers Tom Hanks a showcase for yet another brilliant performance.

Plot: Romeo and Juliet secretly wed despite the sworn contempt their families hold for each other. It is not long, however, before a chain of fateful events changes the lives of both families forever.
Title: Romeo & Juliet
Actors: Damian Lewis, Laura Morante, Tomas Arana, Kodi Smit-McPhee
tomatoConsensus: Shakespeare's classic romance gets a so-so adaptation that's short on passion and energy.

Plot: A dramatic thriller based on real events that reveals the quest to expose the deceptions and corruptions of power that turned an Internet upstart into the 21st century's most fiercely debated organization.
Title: The Fifth Estate
Writer: Daniel Domscheit-Berg (book), David Leigh (book), Luke Harding (book), Josh Singer (screenplay)
Actors: Peter Capaldi, David Thewlis, Anatole Taubman, Alexander Beyer
tomatoConsensus: Heavy on detail and melodrama but missing the spark from its remarkable real-life inspiration, The Fifth Estate mostly serves as a middling showcase for Benedict Cumberbatch's remarkable talent.

Plot: In a world of fake castles and anthropomorphic rodents, an epic battle begins when an unemployed father's sanity is challenged by a chance encounter with two underage girls on holiday.
Title: Escape from Tomorrow
Actors: Roy Abramsohn, Elena Schuber, Katelynn Rodriguez, Jack Dalton
tomatoConsensus: Conceptually audacious but only intermittently successful in execution, Escape From Tomorrow is nonetheless visually inventive and darkly surreal.

Plot: Young Ender Wiggin is recruited by the International Military to lead the fight against the Formics, a genocidal alien race which nearly annihilated the human race in a previous invasion.
Title: Ender's Game
Writer: Gavin Hood (screenplay), Orson Scott Card (based on the book Ender's Game by)
Actors: Asa Butterfield, Harrison Ford, Hailee Steinfeld, Abigail Breslin
tomatoConsensus: If it isn't quite as thought-provoking as the book, Ender's Game still manages to offer a commendable number of well-acted, solidly written sci-fi thrills.

Plot: When Dr. Jane Foster gets cursed with a powerful entity known as the Aether, Thor is heralded of the cosmic event known as the Convergence and the genocidal Dark Elves.
Title: Thor: The Dark World
Writer: Christopher Yost (screenplay), Christopher Markus (screenplay), Stephen McFeely (screenplay), Don Payne (story by), Robert Rodat (story by), Stan Lee (based on the Marvel comics by), Larry Lieber (based on the Marvel comics by), Jack Kirby (based on the Marvel comics by)
Actors: Chris Hemsworth, Natalie Portman, Tom Hiddleston, Anthony Hopkins
tomatoConsensus: It may not be the finest film to come from the Marvel Universe, but Thor: The Dark World still offers plenty of the humor and high-stakes action that fans have come to expect.

Plot: Two thirteen year-old working-class friends in Bradford seek fortune by getting involved with a local scrap dealer and criminal.
Title: The Selfish Giant
Writer: Clio Barnard, Oscar Wilde (inspired by 'The Selfish Giant')
Actors: Conner Chapman, Shaun Thomas, Ralph Ineson, Ian Burfield
tomatoConsensus: Starkly emotional and beautifully directed, The Selfish Giant uses a lovely script and some powerful performances to present some of the best that modern British cinema has to offer.

Plot: A documentary that celebrates Rick Hall, the founder of FAME Studios in Muscle Shoals, Alabama, and the signature sound he developed in songs such as "I'll Take You There", "Brown Sugar", and "When a Man Loves a Woman".
Title: Muscle Shoals
Actors: Stephen Badger, Rick Hall, Aretha Franklin, Jerry Carrigan
tomatoConsensus: Essential for soul fans and entertaining for novices, Muscle Shoals offers a compelling, warts-and-all glimpse at one of the most fascinating stories in modern American music.

Plot: An affable underachiever finds out he's fathered 533 children through anonymous donations to a fertility clinic 20 years ago. Now he must decide whether or not to come forward when 142 of them file a lawsuit to reveal his identity.
Title: Delivery Man
Writer: Ken Scott (written for the screen by), Ken Scott (original screenplay "Starbuck"), Martin Petit (original screenplay "Starbuck")
Actors: Vince Vaughn, Chris Pratt, Cobie Smulders, Andrzej Blumenfeld
tomatoConsensus: It has an undeniably sweet charm, and Vince Vaughn is eminently likable in the lead role, but The Delivery Man suffers in comparison to Starbuck, the hit Canadian comedy that inspired it.

Plot: When the newly crowned Queen Elsa accidentally uses her power to turn things into ice to curse her home in infinite winter, her sister, Anna, teams up with a mountain man, his playful reindeer, and a snowman to change the weather condition.
Title: Frozen
Writer: Jennifer Lee (screenplay), Hans Christian Andersen (story inspired by "The Snow Queen" by), Chris Buck (story by), Jennifer Lee (story by), Shane Morris (story by)
Actors: Kristen Bell, Idina Menzel, Jonathan Groff, Josh Gad
tomatoConsensus: Beautifully animated, smartly written, and stocked with singalong songs, Frozen adds another worthy entry to the Disney canon.

Plot: While out on parole, Dennis reluctantly takes a job selling Christmas trees with his old buddy Rene in order to make enough money to buy his estranged daughter the piano she's always wanted.
Title: All Is Bright
Actors: Paul Giamatti, Paul Rudd, Sally Hawkins, Amy Landecker
tomatoConsensus: Well-acted but uneven, All Is Bright strands a pair of strong performances from Paul Giamatti and Paul Rudd in a meandering script.

Plot: Inventor Tim Jenison seeks to understand the painting techniques used by Dutch Master Johannes Vermeer.
Title: Tim's Vermeer
Actors: Tim Jenison, Penn Jillette, Martin Mull, Philip Steadman
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Entertaining and profound in equal measure, Tim's Vermeer uses its seemingly esoteric subject to pose fascinating questions about art and obsession.

Plot: After the assassination of Dr. George Tiller in Kansas in 2009, there are a limited number of doctors left in the country who provide third-trimester abortions for women. AFTER TILLER moves...
Title: After Tiller
Writer: Greg O'Toole, Martha Shane, Lana Wilson
Actors: George Tiller, Warren Hern, Leroy Carhart, Susan Robinson
tomatoConsensus: After Tiller applies empathy, honesty, and graceful understatement to a discussion that all too often lacks them all.

Plot: A look at the life of activist, musician, and cultural icon Kathleen Hanna, who formed the punk band Bikini Kill and pioneered the "riot grrrl" movement of the 1990s.
Title: The Punk Singer
Actors: Kathleen Hanna, Tammy Rae Carland, Kathryn Wilcox, Tobi Vail
tomatoConsensus: It verges on hagiography, but given the deeply compelling nature of its subject's story, The Punk Singer can be forgiven its lack of objectivity.

Plot: A documentary chronicling sports legend Lance Armstrong's improbable rise and ultimate fall from grace.
Title: The Armstrong Lie
Actors: Reed Albergotti, Betsy Andreu, Frankie Andreu, Lance Armstrong
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 7 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Smartly constructed and scathingly sharp, The Armstrong Lie presents an effective indictment of its unscrupulous subject -- as well as the sports culture that spawned him.

Plot: How Divine, aka Harris Glenn Milstead, became John Waters' cinematic muse and an international drag icon.
Title: I Am Divine
Actors: Divine, Michael Musto, Mark Payne, Greg Gorman
tomatoConsensus: With warmth and affection, I Am Divine offers an engaging portrait of the complex personality behind a trailblazing cinematic figure.

Plot: A mistaken delivery in Mumbai's famously efficient lunchbox delivery system connects a young housewife to an older man in the dusk of his life as they build a fantasy world together through notes in the lunchbox.
Title: The Lunchbox
Writer: Ritesh Batra (screenplay), Vasan Bala (hindi dialogue consultant)
Actors: Irrfan Khan, Nimrat Kaur, Nawazuddin Siddiqui, Lillete Dubey
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 28 wins & 35 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Warm, affectionate, and sweet but not cloying, The Lunchbox is a clever crowd-pleaser from first-time director Ritesh Batra.

Plot: This candid New York love story explores the chaotic 40-year marriage of famed boxing painter Ushio Shinohara and his wife, Noriko. Anxious to shed her role as her overbearing husband's assistant, Noriko finds an identity of her own.
Title: Cutie and the Boxer
Actors: Noriko Shinohara, Ushio Shinohara, Alex Shinohara, Ethan Cohen
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 12 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: A beautifully-made documentary that explores the challenges and richness of both marriage and art through the lens of a fascinating and complex couple.

Plot: The University of California at Berkeley, the oldest and most prestigious member of a ten campus public education system, is also one of the finest research and teaching facilities in the ...
Title: At Berkeley
tomatoConsensus: Its generous running time will test less forbearing viewers' patience, but for filmgoers seeking more of director Frederick Wiseman's observant brand of documentary, At Berkeley satisfies.

Title: The Square
Actors: Ahmed Hassan, Khalid Abdalla, Magdy Ashour, Ramy Essam
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 16 wins & 13 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: The Square offers an electrifying -- and edifying -- ground-level glimpse of life inside a real-life political revolution.

Plot: Adenike and Ayodele, a Nigerian couple living in Brooklyn, are having trouble conceiving a child - a problem that defies cultural expectations and leads Adenike to make a shocking decision that could either save or destroy her family.
Title: Mother of George
Actors: Danai Gurira, Isaach De Bankolé, Anthony Okungbowa, Bukky Ajayi
tomatoConsensus: Director Andrew Dosunmu's style takes some getting used to, but Mother of George compensates with powerful acting, a thoughtful script, and gorgeous visuals.

Plot: Depressed single mom Adele and her son Henry offer a wounded, fearsome man a ride. As police search town for the escaped convict, the mother and son gradually learn his true story as their options become increasingly limited.
Title: Labor Day
Writer: Jason Reitman (screenplay), Joyce Maynard (based on the novel by)
Actors: Kate Winslet, Josh Brolin, Gattlin Griffith, Tobey Maguire
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Kate Winslet and Josh Brolin make for an undeniably compelling pair, but they can't quite rescue Labor Day from the pallid melodrama of its exceedingly ill-advised plot.

Plot: The legal battles of the great American boxer against being conscripted into the US military during the Vietnam War.
Title: The Trials of Muhammad Ali
Actors: Eamonn Andrews, Muhammad Ali, David Susskind, George W. Bush
tomatoConsensus: Director Bill Siegel doesn't explore any new boundaries of the documentary with The Trials of Muhammad Ali, but his subject is so inherently fascinating that the movie proves gripping in spite of its familiar beats.

Title: Gerontophilia
Writer: Bruce La Bruce (original story), Bruce La Bruce (screenplay), Daniel Allen Cox (screenplay)
Actors: Pier-Gabriel Lajoie, Walter Borden, Katie Boland, Yardly Kavanagh
tomatoConsensus: Gerontophilia's handful of intriguing ideas are let down by tame execution and unconvincing acting that make the movie's premise feel creepy rather than original.

Plot: As the Large Hadron Collider is about to be launched for the first time, physicists are on the cusp of the greatest scientific discovery of all time -- or perhaps their greatest failure.
Title: Particle Fever
Actors: Martin Aleksa, Nima Arkani-Hamed, Savas Dimopoulos, Monica Dunford
tomatoConsensus: The concepts behind its heady subject matter may fly over the heads of most viewers, but Particle Fever presents it in such a way that even the least science-inclined viewers will find themselves enraptured.

Plot: Two best friends see their trip of a lifetime take a dark turn when one of them is struck by a mysterious affliction. Now, in a foreign land, they race to uncover the source before it consumes him completely.
Title: Afflicted
Actors: Derek Lee, Clif Prowse, Michael Gill, Baya Rehaz
tomatoConsensus: It isn't without its share of clichés, but Afflicted proves there's still life in the found-footage horror genre.

Plot: To a growing number of Mexicans and Latinos in the Americas, narco traffickers have become iconic outlaws and the new models of fame and success. They represent a pathway out of the ghetto ...
Title: Narco Cultura
tomatoConsensus: Disturbing, thought-provoking, and timely, Narco Cultura sheds some crucial light on an important -- and underserved -- subject.

Plot: The uncompromising Tony and Emmy Award-winner is showcased both on and off stage via rare archival footage and intimate cinema vérité.
Title: Elaine Stritch: Shoot Me
Actors: Alec Baldwin, Rob Bowman, Tina Fey, James Gandolfini
tomatoConsensus: Brutally honest and utterly compelling, Elaine Stritch: Shoot Me offers a riveting, vanity-free portrait of its legendary subject while offering a few essential truths about the human condition.

Title: Let the Fire Burn
Actors: Birdie Africa, Ramona Africa, Wilson Goode, William Brown III
tomatoConsensus: Smartly edited and heartbreakingly compelling, Let the Fire Burn uses archival footage to uncover a troubling -- and still deeply resonant -- chapter in American history.

Plot: Fontayne is enlisted by Bernice - her estranged old friend and current parole officer - along with a disgraced cop to search for Bernice's son, who went missing on the Mexican border.
Title: Go for Sisters
Actors: LisaGay Hamilton, Edward James Olmos, Yolonda Ross, Hilary Barraford
tomatoConsensus: Meandering and diffuse, Go for Sisters proves a letdown for all but the most ardent John Sayles enthusiasts.

Plot: A cocky young man travels to Oregon to work on an apple farm. Out of his element, he finds his lifestyle and notions being picked apart by everyone who crosses his path.
Title: C.O.G.
Actors: Jonathan Groff, Tyra Richards, Beth Furumasu, Keiko Green
tomatoConsensus: C.O.G.'s plot is a bit meandering, but the characters are always compelling and the ending is richly rewarding.

Plot: A documentary portrait of the late John Wojtowicz, whose attempted robbery of a Brooklyn bank to finance his male lover's sex-reassignment surgery was the real-life inspiration for Dog Day Afternoon (1975).
Title: The Dog
Actors: John Wojtowicz, Carmen Bifulco, Jeremy Bowker, Liz Debbie Eden
tomatoConsensus: Fascinating, evocative, and as unconventional as its subject, The Dog offers a colorful window into the real-life story behind a classic film.

Plot: Two common criminals get more than they bargained for after kidnapping the wife of a corrupt real-estate developer who shows no interest in paying the $1 million dollar ransom for her safe return.
Title: Life of Crime
Writer: Daniel Schechter (written for the screen by), Elmore Leonard (based on the book "The Switch" written by)
Actors: Jennifer Aniston, Yasiin Bey, Isla Fisher, Will Forte
tomatoConsensus: It may not stand shoulder-to-shoulder with the best Elmore Leonard adaptations, but Life of Crime has enough ambling charm -- and a sharp enough cast -- to get by.

Plot: About a series of unsolved disappearances on the Galapagos Island of Floreana in the 1930s.
Title: The Galapagos Affair: Satan Came to Eden
Writer: Dayna Goldfine, Daniel Geller, Celeste Schaefer Snyder, Dore Strauch (from the books,  journals,  articles and letters of), Margret Wittmer (from the books,  journals,  articles and letters of), Friedrich Ritter (from the books,  journals,  articles and letters of), Hinz Wittmer (from the books,  journals,  articles and letters of), John Garth (from the books,  journals,  articles and letters of)
Actors: Cate Blanchett, Sebastian Koch, Thomas Kretschmann, Diane Kruger
tomatoConsensus: It doesn't quite live up to its marvelously lurid premise, but The Galapagos Affair is still stranger than fiction in a very entertaining way.

Plot: Teenagers did not always exist. In this living collage of rare archival material, filmed portraits, and voices lifted from early 20th Century diary entries, a struggle erupts between adults and adolescents to define a new idea of youth.
Title: Teenage
Writer: Jon Savage (based on the book 'Teenage: The Creation of Youth Culture,  1875-1945'), Jon Savage, Matt Wolf
Actors: Jena Malone, Ben Whishaw, Julia Hummer, Jessie T. Usher
tomatoConsensus: Using a smartly assembled blend of archival footage and well-made re-enactments, Teenage surveys the rise of adolescent culture with tenderness and wit.

Plot: Madea dispenses her unique form of holiday spirit on rural town when she's coaxed into helping a friend pay her daughter a surprise visit in the country for Christmas.
Title: A Madea Christmas
Writer: Tyler Perry (screenplay), Tyler Perry (based on the stage play "A Madea Christmas" written by)
Actors: Tyler Perry, Anna Maria Horsford, Tika Sumpter, Eric Lively
tomatoConsensus: It boasts a few laughs, but overall, Tyler Perry's A Madea Christmas ranks among Perry's least entertaining or substantive works.

Plot: Rebecca is one of the world's top war photographers. She must weather a major emotional storm when her husband refuses to put up with her dangerous life any longer. He and their young ...
Title: 1,000 Times Good Night
Writer: Erik Poppe, Harald Rosenløw-Eeg, Kirsten Sheridan (additional material by)
Actors: Nikolaj Coster-Waldau, Juliette Binoche, Maria Doyle Kennedy, Chloë Annett
tomatoConsensus: Beautifully filmed and powerfully acted, 1,000 Times Good Night achieves absorbing fact-based drama without overindulging in Hollywood contrivances.

Plot: A pregnant teenager flees her abusive mother in search of her father, only to be rejected by her stepmother and forced to survive on the streets until a compassionate stranger offers a hopeful alternative.
Title: Gimme Shelter
Actors: Rosario Dawson, Emily Meade, Brendan Fraser, Vanessa Hudgens
tomatoConsensus: In spite of its obvious good intentions -- and the compelling true story that inspired it -- the heavy-handed Gimme Shelter can't overcome its cliche-riddled script.

Plot: Filmed at a sold-out performance at Madison Square Garden, comedian Kevin Hart delivers material from his 2012 "Let Me Explain" concert tour.
Title: Kevin Hart: Let Me Explain
Actors: Kevin Hart, Harry Ratchford, Will 'Spank' Horton, Joey Wells
tomatoConsensus: It's ironically rather short on standup from Mr. Hart himself, but structural problems aside, Kevin Hart: Let Me Explain offers another example of why he's achieved mainstream success on his own terms.

Plot: Sisters Olanna and Kainene return home to 1960s Nigeria, where they soon diverge on different paths. As civil war breaks out, political events loom larger than their differences as they join the fight to establish an independent republic.
Title: Half of a Yellow Sun
Actors: Thandie Newton, Chiwetel Ejiofor, Anika Noni Rose, Joseph Mawle
tomatoConsensus: While it doesn't quite do justice to the source material, Half of a Yellow Sun adapts Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie's novel with committed performances and narrative nuance.

Plot: Kids For Cash is a riveting look behind the notorious judicial scandal that rocked the nation. Beyond the millions paid and high stakes corruption, Kids For Cash exposes a shocking American...
Title: Kids for Cash
Actors: Charlie Balasavage, Joanne Balasavage, Justin Bodnar, Lisa Griffiths
tomatoConsensus: Dispassionately presented yet frequently enraging, Kids for Cash uses the fallout from one horrific scandal to offer a thought-provoking critique of the justice system in general.

Plot: A man is chosen by his world's creator to undertake a momentous mission before an apocalyptic flood cleanses the world.
Title: Noah
Actors: Russell Crowe, Jennifer Connelly, Ray Winstone, Anthony Hopkins
Awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 16 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: With sweeping visuals grounded by strong performances in service of a timeless tale told on a human scale, Darren Aronofsky's Noah brings the Bible epic into the 21st century.

Plot: The life and career of the renowned stage magician turned scientific skeptic of the paranormal, James Randi.
Title: An Honest Liar
Writer: Tyler Measom, Greg O'Toole, Justin Weinstein
Actors: James Randi, Deyvi Peña, Penn Jillette, Teller
tomatoConsensus: A thoughtful and surprisingly layered documentary enlivened by its subject, An Honest Liar serves as a well-deserved tribute to a fascinating life.

Plot: A documentary that follows an Alaskan bear family as its young cubs are taught life's most important lessons.
Title: Bears
Writer: Alastair Fothergill, Adam Chapman, Pamela Ribon (narration consultant)
Director: Alastair Fothergill, Keith Scholey, Adam Chapman
Actors: John C. Reilly
tomatoConsensus: Sweet, beautifully filmed, and admirably short on sugarcoating, Bears continues Disneynature's winning streak.

Plot: A scientist's drive for artificial intelligence, takes on dangerous implications when his consciousness is uploaded into one such program.
Title: Transcendence
Actors: Johnny Depp, Rebecca Hall, Paul Bettany, Cillian Murphy
tomatoConsensus: In his directorial debut, ace cinematographer Wally Pfister remains a distinctive visual stylist, but Transcendence's thought-provoking themes exceed the movie's narrative grasp.

Plot: A fun weekend turns into madness and horror for a bunch of groupies looking for fun in a beaver infested swamp.
Title: Zombeavers
Writer: Al Kaplan (screenplay), Jordan Rubin (screenplay), Jon Kaplan (screenplay)
Actors: Rachel Melvin, Cortney Palm, Lexi Atkins, Hutch Dano
tomatoConsensus: Zombeavers obviously isn't high art, but it delivers just enough of the gory insanity promised by the title to earn a recommendation for genre fans.

Plot: The story of programming prodigy and information activist Aaron Swartz, who took his own life at the age of 26.
Title: The Internet's Own Boy: The Story of Aaron Swartz
Actors: Tim Berners-Lee, Cindy Cohn, Gabriella Coleman, Cory Doctorow
tomatoConsensus: Informative and enraging in equal measure, The Internet's Own Boy: The Story of Aaron Swartz uses its subject's tragic tale to deliver an impassioned call to action.

Plot: When Dusty learns that his engine is damaged and he may never race again, he joins a forest fire and rescue unit to be trained as a firefighter, or else his air strip will be shut down.
Title: Planes: Fire & Rescue
Writer: Roberts Gannaway (story and screenplay by), Jeffrey M. Howard (story and screenplay by)
Actors: Dane Cook, Ed Harris, Julie Bowen, Curtis Armstrong
tomatoConsensus: Although it's too flat and formulaic to measure up against the best family-friendly fare, Planes: Fire and Rescue is a passable diversion for much younger viewers.

Plot: The life and career of the renowned film critic and social commentator, Roger Ebert.
Title: Life Itself
Actors: Martin Scorsese, Werner Herzog, Ava DuVernay, Roger Ebert
tomatoConsensus: Rich in detail and warmly affectionate, Life Itself offers a joyful yet poignant tribute to a critical cinematic legacy.

Plot: The honorable citizen Nils ploughs snow in the wild winter mountains of Norway, when his son is mistakenly murdered, Nils takes action, which ignites a war between the vegan gangster "the Count" and the Serbian mafia boss Papa.
Language: Norwegian, Swedish, Danish, English, Serbian, German
Title: In Order of Disappearance
Actors: Kåre Conradi, Huyen Huynh, Anders Baasmo Christiansen, Adil Halitaj
tomatoConsensus: In Order of Disappearance's black comedy doesn't always hit its targets, but on the whole, it still adds up to a sly, entertaining revenge thriller.

Plot: A Queens couple who specialize in robbing mafia social clubs stumble upon a score bigger than they could ever imagine, becoming targets of both the mob and the FBI in the process.
Title: Rob the Mob
Actors: Michael Pitt, Nina Arianda, Andy Garcia, Ray Romano
tomatoConsensus: Bolstered by a pair of likable leads and suffused in a warmly nostalgic glow, Rob the Mob is an uneven crime caper that mostly works.

Plot: An archaeological team attempts to unlock the secrets of a lost pyramid only to find themselves hunted by an insidious creature.
Title: The Pyramid
Actors: Ashley Grace, Denis O'Hare, James Buckley, Christa Nicola
tomatoConsensus: Poorly lit and thinly writ, The Pyramid houses little more than clunky dialogue, amateurish acting, and dusty found-footage scares.

Plot: A troubled couple vacate to a beautiful getaway, but bizarre circumstances further complicate their situation.
Title: The One I Love
Actors: Mark Duplass, Elisabeth Moss, Ted Danson, Kiana Cason
tomatoConsensus: The One I Love doesn't take its intriguing premise quite as far as it could, but it still adds up to an ambitious, well-acted look at love and marriage.

Plot: A look at the many roles played by eclectic 77-year-old actor/activist George Takei, whose wit, humor and grace have helped him to become an internationally beloved figure and Internet phenomenon with 7-million Facebook fans and counting.
Title: To Be Takei
Actors: George Takei, Brad Takei, Walter Koenig, William Shatner
tomatoConsensus: To Be Takei rests almost entirely on its subject's inherent likability -- and, for the most part, that's more than enough.

Plot: A newlywed couple finds their lake-country honeymoon descend into chaos after Paul finds Bea wandering and disoriented in the middle of the night.
Title: Honeymoon
Actors: Rose Leslie, Harry Treadaway, Ben Huber, Hanna Brown
tomatoConsensus: Smart, stylish, and nail-bitingly tense, Honeymoon packs more slow-building horror than many bigger-budget productions.

Plot: A soldier assigned to Guantanamo Bay befriends a man who has been imprisoned there.
Title: Camp X-Ray
Actors: Nawal Bengholam, Peyman Moaadi, Lane Garrison, Joseph Julian Soria
tomatoConsensus: Camp X-Ray's treatment of its subject verges on the shallow, but benefits greatly from a pair of impressive performances from Kristen Stewart and Peyman Moaadi.

Plot: A biography of the civil-rights activist and labor organizer Cesar Chavez.
Title: Cesar Chavez
Actors: Kerry Adra, Maynor Alvarado, Yancey Arias, Wes Bentley
tomatoConsensus: Too in awe of its subject's great works to present him as a human being, Cesar Chávez settles for trite hagiography.

Plot: Broken, desperate men chase their dreams and run from their demons in the North Dakota oil fields. A local Pastor risks everything to help them.
Title: The Overnighters
Actors: Keegan Edwards, Jay Reinke
tomatoConsensus: Hard-hitting, absorbing, and painfully relevant, The Overnighters offers an urgent and compassionate picture of life in 21st century America.

Plot: One couple's story as they try to reclaim the life and love they once knew and pick up the pieces of a past that may be too far gone.
Title: The Disappearance of Eleanor Rigby: Them
Actors: James McAvoy, Jessica Chastain, Nina Arianda, Viola Davis
tomatoConsensus: Led by strong performances from Jessica Chastain and James McAvoy, The Disappearance of Eleanor Rigby is a hauntingly original rumination on love and loss.

Plot: A pair of former brothers-in-law embark on a road trip through Iceland.
Title: Land Ho!
Actors: Earl Lynn Nelson, Paul Eenhoorn, Daníel Gylfason, Þrúður Kristjánsdóttir
tomatoConsensus: Gently amusing and agreeably modest in scale, Land Ho! uses its stars' warm chemistry to impart its poignant, quietly effective message.

Plot: Set in 1974, an authentic and uplifting tale of two friends whose horizons are opened up by the discovery of black American soul music.
Title: Northern Soul
Actors: Steve Coogan, Antonia Thomas, Ricky Tomlinson, James Lance
Awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 nomination.
tomatoConsensus: Northern Soul overcomes its spotty narrative with a likable cast, rich period atmosphere, and a killer soundtrack that perfectly captures the time.

Plot: Sasha and Paige's co-dependent friendship is tested as Paige gets serious with a guy for the first time.
Title: Life Partners
Actors: Leighton Meester, Gillian Jacobs, Gabourey Sidibe, Beth Dover
tomatoConsensus: With two appealing leads adrift in a sitcom-worthy plot, Life Partners doesn't do quite enough to earn viewers' commitment.

Plot: Advanced Style examines the lives of seven unique New Yorkers whose eclectic personal style and vital spirit have guided their approach to aging.
Title: Advanced Style
Actors: Joyce Carpati, Ari Cohen, Lynn Dell, Zelda Kaplan
tomatoConsensus: Colorful, witty, and uplifting, Advanced Style celebrates life and pays tribute to those who flout convention.

Plot: A grieving father in a downward spiral stumbles across a box of his recently deceased son's demo tapes and lyrics. Shocked by the discovery of this unknown talent, he forms a band in the hope of finding some catharsis.
Title: Rudderless
Writer: Casey Twenter, Jeff Robison, William H. Macy
Actors: Miles Heizer, Alexandra Lovelace, Billy Crudup, Casey Twenter
tomatoConsensus: Rudderless asks its cast to carry an awful lot of weight for its occasionally manipulative story; fortunately, this talented bunch -- led by Billy Crudup -- is often more than up to the task.

Plot: An examination of America's obesity epidemic and the food industry's role in aggravating it.
Title: Fed Up
Actors: Bill Clinton, Katie Couric, Michael Bloomberg, Gary Taubes
tomatoConsensus: Compelling and troubling in equal measure, Fed Up is an advocacy documentary that earns its outrage.

Plot: A look at the relationship between the famous physicist Stephen Hawking and his wife.
Title: The Theory of Everything
Actors: Eddie Redmayne, Felicity Jones, Tom Prior, Sophie Perry
tomatoConsensus: Part biopic, part love story, The Theory of Everything rises on James Marsh's polished direction and the strength of its two leads.

Plot: An army veteran's unlikely romance with an Iraqi immigrant is put to the test when she is faced with the prospect of deportation.
Title: Amira & Sam
Actors: Martin Starr, Dina Shihabi, Paul Wesley, Laith Nakli
tomatoConsensus: Amira & Sam doesn't quite live up to its premise -- or the chemistry of its stars -- but its flaws are overcome by its sweet, subversive charm.

Plot: The pressures of fame have superstar singer Noni on the edge, until she meets Kaz, a young cop who works to help her find the courage to develop her own voice and break free to become the artist she was meant to be.
Title: Beyond the Lights
Actors: Gugu Mbatha-Raw, Nate Parker, Minnie Driver, Machine Gun Kelly
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 22 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: Thanks to smart direction and a powerhouse performance from Gugu Mbatha-Raw, Beyond the Lights transcends its formulaic storyline to deliver thoroughly entertaining drama.

Plot: Dan Cohen, founder of the nonprofit organization Music & Memory, fights against a broken healthcare system to demonstrate music's ability to combat memory loss and restore a deep sense of self to those suffering from it.
Title: Alive Inside
Actors: Dan Cohen, Louise Dueno, Nell Hardie, Norman Hardie
tomatoConsensus: It's somewhat clumsily expressed, but Alive Inside offers such an uplifting message that it's ultimately hard to resist.

Plot: Based on the True story of Journalist Gary Webb. The film takes place in the mid 1990s, when Webb uncovered the CIA's past role in importing huge amounts of cocaine into the U.S. that was ...
Title: Kill the Messenger
Writer: Peter Landesman, Gary Webb (book), Nick Schou (book)
Actors: Jeremy Renner, Robert Patrick, Jena Sims, Robert Pralgo
tomatoConsensus: Kill the Messenger's potent fury over the tale of its real-life subject overrides its factual inaccuracies and occasional narrative stumbles.

Plot: A story that questions the shaming of the US through revisionist history, lies and omissions by educational institutions, political organizations, Alinsky, Barack Obama, Hillary Clinton and other progressives to destroy America.
Title: America: Imagine the World Without Her
Writer: Dinesh D'Souza, John Sullivan, Bruce Schooley
Actors: Dinesh D'Souza, Barack Obama, Josh Bonzie, Rich Bentz
tomatoConsensus: Passionate but poorly constructed, America preaches to the choir.

Plot: When five struggling single moms put aside their differences to form a support group, they find inspiration and laughter in their new sisterhood, and help each other overcome the obstacles that stand in their way.
Title: The Single Moms Club
Actors: Nia Long, Wendi McLendon-Covey, Amy Smart, Zulay Henao
tomatoConsensus: The Single Moms' Club finds Tyler Perry avoiding some of the pitfalls of his earlier work, but continuing to rely on heavy-handed melodrama at the expense of sensible characters or absorbing storylines.

Plot: Twin brothers are unknowingly separated at birth; one of them becomes an iconic rock 'n' roll star, while the other struggles to balance his love for music and pleasing his father.
Title: The Identical
Actors: Ray Liotta, Ashley Judd, Seth Green, Joe Pantoliano
tomatoConsensus: With nearly every element ringing as hollow as the ersatz Elvis at the story's core, The Identical looks destined for a bright future on the ironic viewing circuit.

Plot: Time Is Illmatic is a feature length documentary film that delves deep into the making of Nas' 1994 debut album, Illmatic, and the social conditions that influenced its creation. Twenty ...
Title: Nas: Time Is Illmatic
Actors: Mrs. Braconi, Fab 5 Freddy, Alicia Keys, Nas
tomatoConsensus: Comprehensive yet brisk, Nas: Time Is Illmatic offers an absorbing look at a hip-hop classic and the life of the artist who made it.

Plot: A documentary that questions the cost -- and value -- of higher education in the United States.
Title: Ivory Tower
Actors: Elizabeth Armstrong, Richard Arum, Jamshed Bharucha, David Boone
tomatoConsensus: Although Ivory Tower makes it clear that there isn't enough room in a 90-minute film to tackle spiraling student loan debt, it also serves as a compelling call for deeper investigation.

Plot: When one of the most prolific art forgers in US history is finally exposed, he must confront the legacy of his 30-year con.
Title: Art and Craft
Director: Sam Cullman, Jennifer Grausman, Mark Becker
Actors: Mark A. Landis
tomatoConsensus: The spotlight it shines on an apparently troubled mind may strike some viewers as exploitative, but Art and Craft remains a thoroughly gripping glimpse into the life of a legendary art forger.

Plot: During the chaotic final weeks of the Vietnam War, the North Vietnamese Army closes in on Saigon as the panicked South Vietnamese people desperately attempt to escape. On the ground, ...
Title: Last Days in Vietnam
Actors: Richard Nixon, Henry Kissinger, Stuart Herrington, Juan Valdez
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 9 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: As gripping as it is inspiring, Last Days in Vietnam offers a surprisingly fresh -- and heart-wrenching -- perspective on the end of the Vietnam War.

Plot: In a small American town still living in the shadow of a terrible coal mine accident, the disappearance of a teenage boy draws together a surviving miner, the lonely wife of a mine executive, and a local boy in a web of secrets.
Title: Little Accidents
Actors: Elizabeth Banks, Boyd Holbrook, Jacob Lofland, Josh Lucas
tomatoConsensus: Little Accidents has good intentions -- and a talented cast, led by Elizabeth Banks -- but it drowns them under dour melodrama.

Plot: During the early years of Nazi occupation of France in World War II, romance blooms between Lucile Angellier (Michelle Williams), a French villager, and Bruno von Falk (Matthias Schoenaerts), a German soldier.
Title: Suite Française
Writer: Saul Dibb (screenplay), Matt Charman (screenplay), Irène Némirovsky (based on the novel by)
Actors: Michelle Williams, Kristin Scott Thomas, Margot Robbie, Eric Godon
tomatoConsensus: Suite Française takes an understated approach to its period romance, which -- along with strong performances from a talented cast -- pays absorbing dividends.

Plot: A recounting of a New England whaling ship's sinking by a giant whale in 1820, an experience that later inspired the great novel Moby-Dick.
Title: In the Heart of the Sea
Writer: Charles Leavitt (screenplay), Charles Leavitt (story), Rick Jaffa (story), Amanda Silver (story), Nathaniel Philbrick (book)
Actors: Chris Hemsworth, Benjamin Walker, Cillian Murphy, Brendan Gleeson
tomatoConsensus: The admirably old-fashioned In the Heart of the Sea boasts thoughtful storytelling to match its visual panache, even if it can't claim the depth or epic sweep to which it so clearly aspires.

Plot: Literature student Anastasia Steele's life changes forever when she meets handsome, yet tormented, billionaire Christian Grey.
Title: Fifty Shades of Grey
Actors: Dakota Johnson, Jamie Dornan, Jennifer Ehle, Eloise Mumford
Awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 18 nominations.
tomatoConsensus: While creatively better endowed than its print counterpart, Fifty Shades of Grey is a less than satisfying experience on the screen.

Plot: The discovery of a bone and a gun send a husband and wife on separate adventures over the course of a weekend.
Title: Digging for Fire
Actors: Jake Johnson, Rosemarie DeWitt, Orlando Bloom, Brie Larson
tomatoConsensus: Digging for Fire finds director/co-writer Joe Swanberg working from a familiar palette, but in ways that suggest he's taking new and exciting strides as a filmmaker.

Plot: In 1961, famed social psychologist Stanley Milgram conducted a series of radical behavior experiments that tested ordinary humans' willingness to obey authority.
Title: Experimenter
Actors: John Palladino, Anthony Edwards, Jim Gaffigan, Peter Sarsgaard
tomatoConsensus: Led by a gripping performance from Peter Sarsgaard, Experimenter uses a fact-based story to pose thought-provoking questions about human nature.

Plot: Down on his luck and facing financial hardship, Gerry teams up with younger charismatic poker player, Curtis, in an attempt to change his luck. The two set off on a road trip through the South with visions of winning back what's been lost.
Title: Mississippi Grind
Actors: Ben Mendelsohn, Yvonne Landry, Anthony Howard, Ryan Reynolds
tomatoConsensus: Well-acted and steeped in Southern atmosphere, Mississippi Grind is a road movie and addiction drama that transcends each of its well-worn genres.

Plot: A look at the history of the American comedy publication and production company, National Lampoon, from its beginning in the 1970s to 2010, featuring rare and never-before-seen footage.
Title: DRUNK STONED BRILLIANT DEAD: The Story of the National Lampoon
Actors: Danny Abelson, Judd Apatow, Kevin Bacon, Henry Beard
tomatoConsensus: Drunk Stoned Brilliant Dead might not be the definitive doc National Lampoon fans are waiting for, but it's still almost as transgressively funny as the magazine in its heyday.

Plot: When Warren Jeffs rose to Prophet of the Fundamentalist Church of Latter Day Saints, he took control of a religion with a history of polygamous and underage marriage. In a short time, ...
Title: Prophet's Prey
Writer: Amy Berg, Sam Brower (based on: the book "Prophet's Prey" by), Nick Cave (narration by)
Actors: Elaine Anderson, Sam Brower, Nick Cave, Andrew Chatwin
tomatoConsensus: Prophet's Prey finds documentarian Amy Berg striking again at evil masquerading as righteousness -- and, as she did with  Deliver Us from Evil, hitting her targets with impressive precision.

Plot: A foul-mouthed former gymnastics bronze medalist with local celebrity status reluctantly trains a rising Olympics aspirant.
Title: The Bronze
Actors: Melissa Rauch, Gary Cole, Thomas Middleditch, Sebastian Stan
tomatoConsensus: Enthusiastically unpleasant and mostly unfunny, The Bronze fails to stick the landing -- or much else along the way.

Plot: Laney Brooks does bad things. Married with kids, she takes the drugs she wants, sleeps with the men she wants, disappears when she wants. Now, with the destruction of her family looming, ...
Title: I Smile Back
Writer: Paige Dylan, Paige Dylan, Amy Koppelman, Amy Koppelman
Actors: Josh Charles, Skylar Gaertner, Shayne Coleman, Sarah Silverman
tomatoConsensus: I Smile Back serves as a powerful showcase for Sarah Silverman's dramatic range, but fails to surround her committed performance with a movie worthy of its depth.

Plot: Alex, Emily, and their son, RJ, are new to Los Angeles. A chance meeting at the park introduces them to the mysterious Kurt, Charlotte, and Max. A family "playdate" becomes increasingly interesting as the night goes on.
Title: The Overnight
Actors: Adam Scott, Taylor Schilling, RJ Hermes, Kyle Field
tomatoConsensus: Witty and unpredictable, The Overnight benefits from writer-director Patrick Brice's sure-handed touch and strong performances from a talented cast.

Plot: Will Henry is a newly single graphic novelist balancing parenting his young twin daughters and a classroom full of students while exploring and navigating the rich complexities of new love and letting go of the woman who left him.
Title: People Places Things
Actors: Jemaine Clement, Aundrea Gadsby, Gia Gadsby, Nancy Eng
tomatoConsensus: People Places Things finds writer-director Jim Strouse in peak form -- and makes the most of talented stars who help breathe fresh life into familiar narrative territory.

Plot: A never-before-seen woodsman mysteriously appears aboard a submarine that's been trapped deep under water for months with an unstable cargo. As the terrified crew make their way through the...
Title: The Forbidden Room
Writer: Guy Maddin, Evan Johnson, Robert Kotyk, John Ashbery (additional writer), Kim Morgan (additional writer), Kim Morgan (story editor)
Actors: Roy Dupuis, Clara Furey, Louis Negin, Udo Kier
tomatoConsensus: The Forbidden Room may frustrate viewers looking for a linear experience, but those seeking a challenge -- or already familiar with director Guy Maddin's work -- will be rewarded.
